<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN PRIMARY SOFT MONEY FUND-RAISERS ORCHESTRATING HARD MONEY
FOR LAZIO 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREECE, N.Y. _ When Sen. John McCain lost the New York
Republican presidential primary last spring, he placed a large part
of the blame on what he asserted was an illegal $2.5 million
advertising campaign that attacked his environmental record
financed by two wealthy Texas brothers with close ties to Gov.
George W. Bush, McCain's opponent.
</P>
<P>
   One of those two brothers, Charles Wyly, resurfaced on the New
York political scene Tuesday. This time, he was allied with Rep.
Rick Lazio, who McCain has energetically promoted in television
advertisements and appearances in the congressman's Senate race
against Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Lazio acknowledged in this Rochester suburb that
Wyly is a sponsor of one of three out-of-state fund-raisers Lazio
is attending on Wednesday, this one in Dallas. Wyly is one of nine
signatories to a letter asking Texans to attend the fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people believe that Mrs. Clinton is the driving force
behind some of the most radical ideas put forth by the Clinton
administration,'' the letter said. It went on to solicit
contributions of $2,000 for individuals and $4,000 for couples.
</P>
<P>
   Wyly and his brother Sam are longtime associates of Bush. Using
a loophole in federal election laws, they financed television
advertisements in several states that attacked McCain's
environmental record. The advertisements were placed by an
independent committee, ``Republicans for Clean Air,'' and were
widely criticized as inaccurately portraying the environmental
records of Bush and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   McCain filed a complaint about the advertisements with the
Federal Election Commission. McCain, as a candidate for president _
and while campaigning with Lazio _ has championed curbing what he
describes as campaign finance abuses.
</P>
<P>
   Through a spokesman, the McCain said he had no comment on Wyly's
role in Lazio's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the fund-raiser, Karen Dunn, a spokeswoman for
Clinton, urged Lazio to cancel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rick Lazio wins hypocrite of the year award, soft money
division,'' Dunn said. ``In New York, he's running an ad promoting
campaign finance reform. But in Texas, behind closed doors, he's
raising money from one of the worst abusers of campaign finance
laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio, here to promote his tax cut plan, noted the money being
collected was not soft money because it will be raised to finance
an individual campaign, and as such is regulated by the Federal
Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has attacked Clinton for raising soft money, largely
unregulated campaign funds raised by political committees, to
promote her candidacy indirectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you about that is that this is all clean, hard
donors,'' he said before flying to Mobile, Ala., for the first of
the fund-raisers. ``These are all disclosed dollars. These are
dollars that are protected under campaign finance reform.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
