<HEADER>
A2648 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROW--AGARDEN-SFCHRON     09-06 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROW--AGARDEN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAIR OF BOOKS CAN HELP MAKE DUMMIES WISE  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Books for Dummies gang at IDG Books Worldwide in Foster City
keeps rolling out new titles for entrepreneurs who want instant
insights.
</P>
<P>
   Two on this summer's reading list are ``Franchising for
Dummies'' by Wendy's chief executive and chief pitchman Dave Thomas
and franchise consultant Michael Seid, and ``Marketing Kit for
Dummies'' by Alexander Hiam, a consulting and training-firm CEO
with an MBA from the University of California at Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Both books are filled with checklists, cheat sheets and useful
lists of do's and don'ts for business beginners.
</P>
<P>
   One might wonder if it's wise to listen to the founder of
Wendy's, whose stock has lost about 35 percent of its value during
the past year. But Thomas' 5 percent share is still worth about
$105 million, and the guy does &UR;  &LR; know how to flip ideas as well as
burgers.
</P>
<P>
   So does co-author Seid, who I caught by cell phone while he was
fly fishing in Canada. Getting a good franchise, it seems, takes as
much skill as catching a rainbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``The misconception is that owning a franchise is easy, that
it's a victory every time,'' says Seid. ``The survival rate is
better than independent businesses, but in some franchises, the
death rate can be 15 percent a year.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few of his and Thomas' tips:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Avoid franchise brokers.  &LR; They are typically paid by
franchisors to find franchisees and close the deal. Seid has
reservations about that and also questions franchise brokers'
``psychological testing'' techniques and the merits of using a
third party to find someone you intend to spend the next 10 or 20
years of your life with.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; If you are the first franchisee of a new chain, negotiate a &LR; 
 &UR; walk-away clause in your franchise agreement.  &LR; This will be
beneficial if the franchisor can't grow the franchise system.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Check out Small Business Administration loans.  &LR; The SBA
provides about 12,000 loans to franchisees in nearly 1,200
franchise systems. Check out &LR;  www.franchiseregistry.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Consider ``emerging markets.''  &LR; Many downtown areas are still
underdeveloped for branded quality goods and services. &UR;  &LR; They may
also qualify for tax credits on equipment and employee salaries.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Senior citizens are the fastest-growing segment of the &LR; 
 &UR; population.  &LR; With the recent easing of rules affecting the Social
Security earnings cap, this pool of potential workers is ripe for
hiring.
</P>
<P>
   Seid also advises prospective franchisees to check whether the
franchisor is well positioned against the competition, including
non-franchisors.
</P>
<P>
   Does the product or service have legs? He notes that ``auto
aftermarket'' franchises looked good in the 1980s, but that changed
after &UR;  &LR; new cars no longer required a tuneup every 15,000 miles.
</P>
<P>
   Also, find out whether the franchisor is spending money on
research and development, new products, service and field staff.
Beware if most of the resources are going to add franchises or
expand geographically.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Franchising for Dummies,'' ``Marketing Kit for Dummies''
quickly covers a lot of terrain, such as preparing a newsletter,
using testimonials, planning ad and publicity campaigns, and tips
on closing a sale.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the book reads like a lecture, but color often
accompanies the advice. For example:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Remember what your customers like.  &LR; Ritz-Carlton hotels keep
records on customer preferences and might serve a complimentary
glass of Kendall-Jackson Chardonnay to a guest who ordered a bottle
on a previous visit.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reward large customers.  &LR; Toys R Us gave away free Tickle Me
Elmo dolls to customers who purchased more than $100 worth of
Christmas gifts. (Hiam suggests offering an incentive to customers
who buy more than 1.5 times the business' average sale amount.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Make it easy for customers to reach you.  &LR; At Motorola, key
customers receive pager numbers for executives.
</P>
<P>
   Author Hiam, who is based in Massachusetts but is setting up a
consulting and employee training branch office in San Francisco,
also has praise for several local businesses. He mentions Sidney's
hair salon in San Francisco for ``high-end service,'' saying it
shuns walk-in traffic but keeps detailed records for regular
customers and often provides food for evening clients.
</P>
<P>
   Hiam also commends CalFed for its 50+ Interest Checking account,
which offers anyone older than 50 unlimited check writing with no
monthly service charges and pays interest (albeit a modest 0.5
percent, currently).
</P>
<P>
   ``The bulk of the wealth in this country is held by people in
this category,'' Hiam notes. ``No doubt CalFed has attracted some
large and very stable accounts.''
</P>
