<SLUG> BC-DATA--STORAGE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MATERIALS PROMISE BIG BOOST IN DATA STORAGE  &HT;     BY HENRY NORR
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ New materials described in a scientific journal
this week could help boost the data-storage capacity of PC hard
disks as much as seventy-fivefold in three to five years, making it
possible to store whole libraries of digital movies and music on a
single drive.
<P>
   With other expected advances in storage technology, the new
materials could increase the capacity of the magnetic platters
spinning inside a hard drive to 1,000 gigabits, or 1 terabit, of
information per square inch. Today's top PC drives store about 14
gigabits per square inch.
</P>
<P>
   In a report in the current issue of the journal Science,
scientists at the NEC Research Institute in Princeton, N.J.,
described new composites that exhibit a property they call
``extraordinary magnetoresistance,'' or EMR. Current drive
technology is based on a phenomenon called ``giant
magnetoresistance,'' or GMR; other scientists have recently
developed materials exhibiting ``colossal magnetoresistance,'' or
CMR.
</P>
<P>
   The magnetoresistance of a material refers to the percentage
change of its electrical resistance in the presence of a magnetic
field. The higher the magnetoresistance of a material, the smaller
the magnetic field it can distinguish.
</P>
<P>
   When materials with higher levels of magnetoresistance are
incorporated into future drives' ``read heads'' _ the components
that float just above the spinning platters and react to magnetic
polarities on their surface _ they can determine the magnetic state
of smaller areas, thus making possible huge increases in the
data-storage capacity of a given surface area.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of NEC06 (82840 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The resistance of most materials changes only very slightly when
they are exposed to a magnetic field _ even the latest GMR
materials change by no more than 20 percent at room temperatures.
CMR materials show much greater sensitivity, but only at very low
temperatures that aren't practical in hard drives, according to
Stuart Solin, head of the NEC Research team.
</P>
<P>
   The resistance of EMR materials at room temperature, however,
varies by 100 to 1 million percent, depending on the strength of
the magnetic field, according to the NEC report.
</P>
<P>
   Heads incorporating EMR materials would be not only more
sensitive, but also far easier to manufacture and therefore cheaper
than current equivalents, according to Solin. But he acknowledged
that the technology's adoption in the data-storage industry is not
a sure thing. ``No matter how good our solution is,'' he said, ``it
won't be adopted unless conventional technologies hit the wall, or
at least get close to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he said, ``just about everyone'' believes current
technologies will reach their technical limits well below a density
of 1,000 gigabits per square inch _ probably at or below 200
gigabits per square inch. To take full advantage of the potential
of EMR, he said, the industry will also need to develop new
materials for the disks that store the data inside a drive, but he
said advances in this area are expected.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of NEC06 (82840 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Jim Porter, president of Disk/Trend, a Mountain View
market-research company that focuses on the storage industry,
agreed that the outlook for densities beyond 100 gigabits per
square inch has been uncertain. But, he noted, ``scientists have
been discussing the effective limit on areal density for years, and
all the past forecasts have been eclipsed.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to the NEC technology's prospects in data storage, he
said, is whether it is adopted by the companies that have led the
way in boosting hard-disk density _ IBM, Seagate, Hitachi and
Fujitsu.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens in the storage arena, Solin said, his group's
discovery is certain to find a market. It has applications in the
booming cell phone business and in automobile engines and brakes.
In fact, he said, one company has already licensed the technology
from NEC for use in the automotive field.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; id  &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr &LR; (AT) &LR; sfchronicle.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
