r f BC-ROBERTSON--IPO-SFCHRO     09-06 0682
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERTSON--IPO-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVESTMENT BANK AIMS TO TAKES ITSELF PUBLIC  &HT;     BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The investment bank Robertson Stephens has taken
hundreds of companies public during the last few years. Now, the
San Francisco firm may come to market with its own initial public
offering.
<P>
   Fleet Boston Financial Corp., the giant New England bank that
owns Robertson Stephens, is weighing a spin-off of a minority stake
in the firm to the public, sources familiar with the matter said.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of discussions during the past six months,
executives of Robertson Stephens and Fleet Boston have agreed on
the merits of a transaction, but haven't begun the tough bargaining
on terms, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   That means a public offering of Robertson Stephens would not
happen for six months or more. And it's also possible Fleet and
Robertson won't be able to agree on terms, preventing an IPO from
taking place, one source said. A Robertson Stephens spokeswoman
declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   A sale of a stake in Robertson Stephens to the public would
allow Fleet to capitalize on the high values investment banks are
commanding without giving up control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ideal time to do a public offering,'' said Gary
Craft, a San Francisco e-commerce analyst for the investment bank
Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown. ``There are so few independent,
technology-driven investment banks left.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, for Roberston Stephens, an IPO would let it award
stock and options to employees, a powerful weapon in the cutthroat
competition for star investment bankers and stock analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1969, Robertson Stephens specializes in taking
high-tech and health care-services companies public. The firm is
the nation's No. 12 investment bank as measured by the dollars it
has raised for clients in public stock offerings this year.
</P>
<P>
   If Robertson Stephens were to sell shares to the public, the
firm would probably be valued at several billion dollars, analysts
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet's predecessor bought the firm for $800 million two years
ago. Since then, Robertson Stephens' revenue has quadrupled to
about $2 billion annually as the firm has ridden the wave of the
public's insatiable demand for technology stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Around the world, a series of takeovers at hefty prices is
shaking up the investment banking industry. Last month, in one of
the biggest recent deals, Credit Suisse First Boston agreed to buy
rival Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette for more than $13 billion,
creating one of the industry's dominant firms.
</P>
<P>
   In the Bay Area, a Robertson Stephens IPO would mark the latest
twist in what has been a tumultuous investment banking scene during
the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   Just about all San Francisco's big, home-grown investment banks
_ Montgomery Securities and Hambrecht &AMP; Quist as well as Robertson
Stephens _ were bought out by big commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a flock of startups, many rooted in Internet
technology, have opened shop. And the largest U.S. investment
banks, including Goldman Sachs and Credit Suisse First Boston, have
all beefed up their operations in the area to take advantage of the
IPO and merger boom.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that could hold up a Robertson Stephens public
offering is the difficulty of reaching an agreement with Fleet on
how large a stake to spin off to the public, sources familiar with
the matter noted. Fleet wants to keep as large a position as it
can, while officials of the investment bank want to sell as much
stock as possible, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Such differences are typical in spin-offs, industry watchers
noted. For Fleet, `retaining more shares would have a greater
impact'' on the value of the bank's own stock, said Scott Schubert,
an investment banker with the firm Putnam Lovell Securities.
</P>
<P>
   But ``the public markets prefer to see more liquidity than
less,'' Schubert said. ``It would attach a better valuation if
Fleet were to sell more.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman &LR; (AT) &LR; sfchronicle.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
