<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODWIN HAS FUTURE IN L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The rap on Tom Goodwin's offense is he strikes out
too much for a leadoff hitter. However, the rest of his offense is
fine and, coupled with his defense, enough for the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   When Goodwin was acquired in a non-waiver-trading-deadline deal
with Colorado, there were questions about whether the Los Angeles
Dodgers were committed to him long-term. He has two years remaining
on his contract and it appears those years will be with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said he's excited about
Goodwin's future. Malone was asked if that future was with the
Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it is,'' Malone said. ``I've studied it. I've done the
research. Guys like him don't exist, a leadoff-center fielder. I've
seen enough to know he can be. We'd like him to improve in center
areas, but everyone can improve. I think he has the potential to be
exactly what we need.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin extended his hitting streak to a season-high seven games
with a first-inning single Tuesday against Pittsburgh. He entered
batting .255 since joining the Dodgers on Aug. 1. His on-base
percentage was .339 and he scored 15 runs.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodwin, who scored 65 runs in 91 games with Colorado, has a
propensity to strike out. He had 28 hits in 32 games with the
Dodgers but also 28 strikeouts. In 505 plate appearances this
season, Goodwin has walked 64 times and struck out 104 times. He
has 45 stolen bases but only six with the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key with this guy is he's a run-scorer,'' Malone said.
``He's going to work on a higher on-base percentage and he needs to
cut down on his strikeouts, but the guy is an exciting player. He
brings a dimension to this club that we definitely need.''
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers have plans for Goodwin, their offseason
approach to Devon White is different. White is guaranteed another
$5.9 million. The Dodgers will try to trade him in the offseason,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Hundley heads home: Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley was in the
starting lineup but with a heavy heart. His mother, Betty Oneada
Hundley, died Monday night in Chicago after a long bout with
cancer. She was 58.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley will fly to Chicago today and rejoin the team Saturday
in Colorado, though the club wasn't sure if he would make it to
Denver in time for the 12:05 p.m. game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Todd feels blessed that she was no longer suffering and feels
she's in a much better place now, but he loved his mom a lot, as I
think everyone knows,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said.
``He's hurting right now. I think it's been bothering him since we
went to Chicago (in late August). . . . I told him to take as much
time as he needs. If he wants to come back in Arizona on Monday,
that's fine.''
</P>
<P>
   During off days in the past two months, Hundley would often fly
to Chicago to be with his mother and father, Randy Hundley. ``It's
been a rough night for him, not much sleep,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Odds and ends: The Dodgers activated shortstop Kevin Elster
from the 15-day disabled list, but Johnson said Elster wasn't 100
percent. . . . Former Brooklyn Dodgers player, manager and scout
Clyde Sukeforth died Sunday at the age of 98 at his Waldoboro,
Maine. He was the oldest living former Dodgers player. Sukeforth
caught for the Dodgers from 1932-34 and again in 1945. He managed
the Dodgers on an interim basis in 1947 and scouted from 1936-51.
He is credited with signing Don Newcombe, Roy Campanella and
Roberto Clemente and was dispatched by Branch Rickey to scout
Jackie Robinson.
</P>
</TEXT>
