<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0011 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2656 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-BUSINESS--ART-SFCHRON     09-06 1575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSINESS--ART-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOOMING ECONOMY DRIVES UP DEMAND FOR MURALS  &HT;     BY PETER SINTON
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ The Bay Area is more than a leader in computer
chips, the Internet and multimedia. It's also a major center for
mural artists.
<P>
   From San Jose to Sebastopol, San Francisco to Pleasanton, 47
mural businesses are listed in local phone books compared with 43
around New York City and 37 each in the Los Angeles and Chicago
metropolitan areas.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco has been a mecca for muralists since the Public
Works Administration commissioned Diego Rivera, Gottardo Piazzoni
and other artists during the 1930s Depression to paint social
scenes and pastoral panels in public buildings, including Coit
Tower and the old San Francisco Library.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there is a renaissance of mural painting thanks to the
booming economy and the desire of wealthy individuals and companies
to dress up their homes and places of business to make a statement
and attract attention.
</P>
<P>
   Il Fornaio America Corp. installed Italian-style murals designed
and painted by San Francisco's Evans &AMP; Brown in its first
restaurant at Levi's Plaza 12 years ago. It was a big success, and
Il Fornaio has placed at least $25,000 worth of faux frescoes in
each of its 23 restaurants around California and the country.
</P>
<P>
   Il Fornaio Chairman Larry Mindel said the murals are important
to him and his patrons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The art makes people feel as though they are in Italy,'' he
said. ``The trick of Evans &AMP; Brown murals is that they capture that
Old World feeling and look like the real deal without being
contrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Creating an actual fresco is labor intensive and generally
requires that the art be created at the final site rather than the
artist's studio.
</P>
<P>
   To mimic the antique plaster surface of a real fresco, Evans &AMP;
Brown and others have devised a technique involving coating muslin
with a thin paste of marble dust, polymer and other materials..
</P>
<P>
   Mark Evans, who previously ran a photo studio for Emporium owner
Carter Hawley Hale, teamed up with painter Charley Brown in 1984.
After visits to Europe, they were inspired to create their own
murals for commercial and residential projects.
</P>
<P>
   Although the firm specializes in Tiepolo and other Italianate
scenes, it has a broad artistic range. It recently installed two
54-by-16-foot surrealistic murals of huge floating mineral-like
spheres through space in the old Fashion Center at 650 Townsend St.
that now houses Sega and other media and Internet companies. The
project took more than two months and cost more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Evans &AMP; Brown's work is displayed on the 36-foot diameter
ceiling of the James Hormel Gay and Lesbian room at the San
Francisco Public Library, the lobby of the Bellagio Hotel in Las
Vegas and Sony Entertainment in Culver City (Los Angeles County).
</P>
<P>
   ``We sailed through the recession (in the early '90s),'' said
Evans, whose firm is not limited to local contracts.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; International Business
</P>
<P>
   The company produced an ``Age of Exploration'' mural for the
recently expanded Disneyland near Tokyo and installed a
10-by-60-foot California Wine Country scene in the Eureka
Restaurant in Tokyo's Imperial Hotel. It produced three large 19
century-style French Academic scenes of the education of Bacchus
for the casino of Deauville, Normandy, and created Pompeian-style
frescoes for the U.S. Embassy in Cypress.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the two partners have 14 employees in San Francisco and a
business that generates close to $2 million a year in revenue.
About 70 percent of the work is commercial; the balance is for
individual residences.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Evans &AMP; Brown created a Turkish motif for Ann and
Gordon Getty in their Pacific Heights residence.
</P>
<P>
   The mural business is not all peaches and cream. Last month,
Alabama artist Garth Benton sued the Gettys for painting over
another wall mural they commissioned him to paint. Citing an
obscure 1980 California law that that holds defacing art to be
``detrimental to the artist's reputation,'' Benton sued the Gettys
for $327,000 plus damages. The Gettys subsequently have hired art
experts to restore the mural.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Made to Order
</P>
<P>
   Muralists are generally more open to what clients want them to
paint than most so-called fine artists. But they have their limits.
Evans &AMP; Brown, for instance, refuse requests to paint images of the
Golden Gate Bridge or cable cars.
</P>
<P>
   The wife-and-husband mural team of Jennifer Ewing and Leo
Germano like to paint Italian scenes like many other muralists. But
the couple, which operate as the firm Ewing Germano, were happy to
paint eight 20-foot panels depicting San Francisco football history
for former 49er Len Rohde's Burger King restaurant in Mountain
View.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's distinctive,'' said Rohde, who operates nine Burger Kings
and two Applebee restaurants in the South Bay.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, Ewing and Germano don't like to render sporting
events, but back in 1995, Germano said, ``We didn't look down our
noses at work.''
</P>
<P>
   Although both Ewing and Germano studied art in college, they
didn't start out as muralists. They met at Woodward Clyde
Consultants, an Oakland engineering firm where both did drafting
and prepared site maps in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of it was black and white and we were starved for
color,'' Ewing recalled.
</P>
<P>
   On a five-month honeymoon to Europe in 1988, Ewing drew water
colors that she later showed to window display managers at Neiman
Marcus, Nordstrom, Gump's and other stores. Her drawings won her
some mural contracts, including a commission to create five
elaborate Renaissance palace displays for Neiman Marcus' Union
Square Christmas windows in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   While Ewing painted full time in a $600-a-month live-work space
in San Francisco's South of Market area that was once used for cold
storage, Germano kept his hand in geologic mapping until their
mural business became self-sustaining. He also took courses at the
Renaissance Entrepreneurship Center to learn about writing a
business plan, preparing spreadsheets and marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned what we need to charge to survive,'' said Germano.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of most murals runs from $20 to $200 a square foot
depending on size, complexity of design, level of detail and
installation requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing and Germano typically charge about $900 a day for both of
their time. That might translate into $3,600 for a simple
4-by-12-foot landscape that takes the duo four days to complete to
$23,500 for a complex 16-foot by 80-foot mural that takes 25 days
to research and render.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing and Germano have installed a 23-by-23-foot canvas of
Rome's Spanish Steps in ItalFoods' showroom in South San Francisco,
and numerous other Italian countryside and cuisine scenes for
hotels, restaurants and wineries, including the San Francisco
Marriott Hotel and Robert Mondavi's La Famiglia Winery.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Other clients include Levi Strauss, Peet's Coffee and private
residences. For example, Ewing Germano painted a Paris street scene
for Schwab co-CEO David Pottruck.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Staying Busy
</P>
<P>
   Most mural businesses like that of Ewing and Germano are
mom-and-pop shops. But there are a few with more than a dozen
employees such as San Francisco's Mural Arts.
</P>
<P>
   Started in 1978 by Les and Brenda Cole Seymour, who were both
trained in fine arts and commercial design, the firm hires from
seven to 15 employees, depending on the workload, and grosses
between &QL; 
$1 million and $2 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Seymours have created Italianate murals for clients such as
the Limited stores and Hotel Villa Florence in San Francisco. They
also have created 20,000 square feet of jungle scene murals for the
Lost City Resort in South Africa, faux tapestries for a Tokyo Hyatt
and a 1920s Hollywood Art Deco theme for the MGM Grand in Las
Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is a bigger mural center than most American
cities,'' said Les Seymour. ``Hotels, restaurants, office
buildings, banks and high-end residences from Hillsborough to Lake
Tahoe are buying our murals.''
</P>
<P>
   But more interest and orders are not necessarily good things.
``We're maxed out,'' said Brown of Evans &AMP; Brown. ``I don't have a
dot-commer's energy to work 100 hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not interesting for us to be administrators,'' added
Evans. ``Charley needs to be a painter, and I need design work.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the partners have a plan to build revenues without
overtaxing their creativity or time. After seeing their handmade
designs getting copied commercially, Evans and Brown accepted an
offer to create an upscale line of vinyl wall coverings for the
Koroseal division of RJF International Corp. in Ohio (formerly a
unit of BFGoodrich).
</P>
<P>
   ``To keep from getting knocked off, we decided to knock
ourselves off,'' said Evans. ``We're taking a humble material
considered cheap and tacky for a long time and making it opulent
and elegant.
</P>
<P>
   Products range from large mural scenes to textured vinyl wall
coverings that look like folded linen or draped silk.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the faux fabric is commercially available, the
Fairmont Hotel has ordered the draped silk pattern for its
remodeled ballroom in San Francisco. The price per square yard
could be $16 or less depending on the quantity _ a small fraction
of the cost of the hand-painted equivalent.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Peter Sinton at  &LR; psinton &LR; (AT) &LR; sfchronicle.com. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service Clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
