<HEADLINE>
HACKETT WANTS NO LETDOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Signs are everywhere that USC coach Paul Hackett
is worried this week, starting with the one attached to the door at
Howard Jones Field announcing that football practices are closed to
the public.
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't think the Trojans were ranked 11th in the nation
Tuesday, as Hackett halted practice twice to chew out the team
while it prepared for 0-1 Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human nature kicks in when you win a big game and think you're
pretty good,'' Hackett said. ``No, we're not pretty good. We won
one game.''
</P>
<P>
   The mood has become reminiscent of previous years when the
Trojans played big games against Florida State, Oregon or UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned going into this game,'' Hackett said. ``They're
mad as hornets because they lost a game and we're just trying to
get into a routine. I think byes are lousy. Your routine is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   So who is to blame? After thinking about it, Hackett admitted
that last week's bye was created when he opted to play Penn State
in the Kickoff Classic. Originally, Colorado was supposed to be
USC's season-opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I shouldn't be too upset about it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Circle the date: USC assistant coach Kennedy Pola has looked
forward to this week's game for some time, and for a while it was
from the other side of the matchup.
</P>
<P>
   Pola, a former USC fullback, coached at Colorado in 1997 and
'98.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've kind of had this game mapped,'' Pola said. ``I've always
waited for this moment. When I was recruiting against USC, I would
tell people 'Hey, we'll play them in two years.' At that time, I
didn't see myself on the USC sideline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been hard to hear the fight song and not put my
fingers up in the air.''
</P>
<P>
   Pola coached many of the prime players in Colorado's offense,
including tailback Cortlen Johnson and wide receivers Javon Green
and John Minardi.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hard thing is seeing kids you coached and realizing, 'Wait
a minute, I don't coach them,' '' Pola said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Goodson ailing: Freshman defensive lineman Nate Goodson
suffered an asthma attack during practice and paramedics
administered oxygen before taking him to California Hospital in Los
Angeles. He returned to campus by early evening.
</P>
<P>
   The news is not so good for strong safety Matt Grootegoed, who
will not practice this week and is believed to have mononucleosis.
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Petros Papadakis also missed practice after displaying
flu-like symptoms.
</P>
<P>
   __ Acosta quits: Center Carlos Acosta of Moorpark College has
decided to leave the team and will probably transfer to another
college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears his head was not in it,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Acosta had left the team in August because he was homesick and
rejoined the Trojans when school started last week.
</P>
<P>
   __ Game captains: Hackett said fullback Charlie Landrigan and
offensive tackle Faaesea Mailo will be offensive captains, and
defensive back Kris Richard and defensive end Lonnie Ford will be
defensive captains against Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans will have different captains every game until
midseason, when they vote for permanent captains.
</P>
</TEXT>
