<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 00:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2663 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-USOPEN-MEN-NYT &LR;      09-06 1026
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-USOPEN-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KIEFER AND SAFIN WIN, BUT WHO IS WATCHING?
</HEADLINE>
   (Story skedded as TEN-USOPEN is now two stories TEN-USOPEN-MEN and
TEN-USOPEN-WOMEN) 
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In one hermetically sealed pocket of Manhattan,
Nicolas Kiefer spent an unsettling Sunday night in a hotel where
guards were eyeing everything but the floor tiles, where security
alerts were shaking his sense of safety, and where the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, had taken up residence for the U.N.
Millennium Summit.
</P>
<P>
   How was Kiefer supposed to sleep?
</P>
<P>
   In a cozy corner of the National Tennis Center, Magnus Norman
spent the same steamy Sunday night inside a crammed Grandstand
stadium, where he kept shaking out his cramping legs as if they
were rumpled bed sheets, where he nearly expired in the fourth hour
of his intense third-round match, and where he finally escaped the
wingspan of Max Mirnyi to exit intact.
</P>
<P>
   How was Norman supposed to recover?
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, both players arrived for their Round of 16 match on Day
9 of the U.S. Open in varying states of decay. The 14th-seeded
Kiefer was sleep deprived, while the third-seeded Norman was
battling fatigue and a sore throat.
</P>
<P>
   Somehow, there is always something standing in the way of
consistency on the men's tour. Instead of stamping himself as a
certified star in yet another Grand Slam opportunity to make a
bigger name for himself, Norman became another victim of top-seeded
extinction at the U.S. Open once a more aggressive Kiefer put him
away, 6-2, 6-7 (3), 6-1, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   In an instant, Norman joined the No. 1-seeded Andre Agassi and
the No. 2-seeded Gustavo Kuerten in his premature exit. This is the
first time since the beginning of the Open Era (1968) that the top
three seeded men have failed to outlast the fourth round. And with
the quarterfinals set to begin Wednesday, only two of the top eight
seeded men remain: fourth-seeded Pete Sampras and sixth-seeded
Marat Safin. Safin, the affable young Russian, was a 6-1, 6-2, 6-2
winner Tuesday over Juan Carlos Ferrero, but only a few spectators
were there to witness it in a nearly vacant Arthur Ashe Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd was only another sign of apathy toward a men's tour
struggling to conjure up the star power that has propelled the
women's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the spectators, they have some other things to do,''
said Safin, who arrived on the court after Venus Williams exited
with a victory and took the fans with her. ``I think if they're not
here, they have to be somewhere, no?''
</P>
<P>
   They weren't around for Norman's struggle, either. He was in
trouble from the beginning of his match against Kiefer. Out of
sorts, Norman could not keep his ground strokes down in a swirling
wind and failed to put a good punch on his volleys. By the time he
trailed, 4-1, in the first set, Norman had committed 10 unforced
errors, while an under-control Kiefer had just two.
</P>
<P>
   Only a questionable line call in the second-set tiebreaker gave
Norman hope. He was down by 3-1 when an apparent ace by Kiefer was
overruled. Visibly upset, Kiefer lost a string of six straight
points to hand the tiebreaker to Norman. That was the last moment
of relief for Norman. For the rest of the match, he was unable to
control his wild swipes at his forehands, even crushing one short
ball against the back wall of the court on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   Out of answers by the middle of the fourth set, Norman even went
to his duffel bag for some psychological help. He pulled out the
same Lifesaver-red shirt he wore when he came back from two sets
down to beat the mighty Mirnyi late Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like I'm more on fire when I'm playing with that
shirt,'' said Norman, perhaps taking his cue from Tiger Woods'
tradition of wearing red on the final day of a tournament. ``Makes
me hot, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it did not work. After 59 unforced errors, Norman
became just another top man ushered out of the tournament. He had
hoped for much more. So had the marketing department of the men's
tour. Officials were looking to launch their photogenic young
phenoms (about a dozen of them, it seemed) into the American
consciousness during the U.S. Open. But only Safin and ninth-seeded
Lleyton Hewitt remain. Unseeded Arnaud Clement and Thomas
Johansson, who also won his fourth-round match Tuesday, are also in
the quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   During this shakeout of the top, Sampras remains as the one
steady name at the top of an increasingly homogeneous group trying
to string together two good months in a row. At times, Sampras,
long removed from making a No. 1 ranking his top priority, has
wondered if the up-and-coming players have the attention spans to
be consistent.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, no one has stepped forward to dominate. While Norman
has occupied the No. 1 ranking at times, and won five tour titles
last year, he has yet to become a household name by winning a
major.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, it will be a great help,'' Norman said. ``You know,
I'm a little tired of answering that question about my status.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Norman was weary on the court, as well. He admitted he
had enough energy even after battling Mirnyi, but the sore throat
that began creeping up on him Monday night did not help. He said he
had trouble with the wind and chill, but his mind was not as
focused as it could have been during the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today my rhythm wasn't there,'' Norman said. ``My head wasn't
really there. My body wasn't really there. But he didn't make it
easy for me either.''
</P>
<P>
   A livelier Kiefer fought through his fatigue. He was the one
with the crisper ground strokes and snappier footwork. On this
occasion, he was able to handle his ordeal a little better than
Norman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a bad night,'' said Kiefer, who switched hotels Monday
morning. ``It was only stress for me. I couldn't relax one
minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is ever easy in the men's draw. Thus far, none of the
women have complained about the various locations of their
accommodations. In fact, when Williams was told of Kiefer's
tribulations in the neighborhood of the United Nations, she sighed
and said, ``That's a bad choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 0027EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
