<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2694 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-DEBATES-ANALYSIS-SFCH     09-06 0989
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES-ANALYSIS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DEBATE OVER DEBATES MAY CARRY FAR PAST THE ELECTION  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's a fiery debate over the state of the presidential
debates this week.
</P>
<P>
   Will the candidates square off on ``Larry King Live'' or at the
University of Massachusetts? Will they do 90 minutes in prime time
before 90 million viewers or 60 minutes on a talk show with just a
fraction of that audience?
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the rhetoric, the bottom line is that some important
precedents are involved in the debate over the debates.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, the debates have been overseen by the nonpartisan
Presidential Commission on Debates, which was established by
agreement of the Democratic and Republican parties to make sure the
events are fair, impartial and best serve the voters.
</P>
<P>
   And it could be the voters who lose out if candidates opt
instead for a more free-for-all approach to setting up the debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Debates are for the people and belong to the people; they do
not belong to the campaign,'' said Alan Schroeder, author of
``Presidential Debates: Forty Years of High-Risk TV,'' a book
published this week by Columbia University Press. ``The commission
is as close as the citizenry has to having some kind of voice in
them ... and they ought not to be tampered with, because they do
serve the public in so many ways.''
</P>
<P>
   If Republican nominee George W. Bush succeeds in rejecting the
debate schedule proposed by the presidential commission, the Texas
governor may establish ``a dangerous historical precedent'' that
would reshape the way such events are held in the future, Schroeder
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   `'It means, in 2004, hundreds of sponsors trying to cut deals,
and the campaigns shopping among them'' for the best one, Schroeder
said. ``The interests of the citizens will not be well served.''
</P>
<P>
   It was precisely to avoid that scenario that both major parties
set up the commission, which has maintained ``an untarnished track
record of sponsorship'' of all 10 presidential and vice
presidential debates since its founding, Schroeder noted.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the commission has proposed three 90-minute
prime-time debates, in regional locations chosen for their ability
to handle the events and the media that accompany them: Oct. 3 in
Boston, Oct. 11 in Winston-Salem, N.C., and Oct. 17 in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has agreed to participate in the Oct. 17 event, but not the
other two. Instead, the Texas governor, in what Schroeder termed an
``unusual tactic,'' proposed different sponsors and his own
hand-picked alternatives. Bush proposed a Sept. 12 debate on a
prime-time broadcast of NBC's ``Meet the Press'' and an Oct. 3
matchup on CNN's ``Larry King Live.''
</P>
<P>
   Competing major networks have said they will not carry those
shows _ both one hour long.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, a three-time Emmy Award winning broadcaster and
current professor at Northeastern University in Boston, said he has
no doubt what both Bush and Gore should do:
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidates, however painful it may be, should bite the bullet
and do what's best for the interest of the citizens,'' Schroeder
said. ``That means (debates) in front of the largest possible
audiences, with the fewest format constraints _ and in a length
that allows for examination of the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's camp argues that there's one reason Bush is avoiding the
full prime-time dialogue: the size of the audience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not using the commission's recommendation literally cuts
millions of voters out of the process,'' said Peter Ragone, Gore's
California press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Ragone notes that 90 million people watched the last official
presidential debate on network television, but ``Larry King Live''
_ even during the primary debates between Bush and Arizona Sen.
John McCain _ drew just a fraction of that audience, roughly 3
million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of Americans don't get cable television, and millions
more don't get CNN, Ragone added, and ``we've said again and again,
once Bush accepts the commission's debates, we'll participate in
many other formats.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gerry Parsky, Bush's California campaign chairman, said the
issue is Gore's own promise _ made on both ``Larry King Live'' and
``Meet the Press'' _ to debate Bush ``any time, any place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't believe Gore on what he says on this, how can you
believe him on other issues?'' Parsky asked. He said Bush wants ``a
better range of locations and formats'' that will best serve
Americans, and that the governor isn't the first to question a
schedule proposed by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton decided that the presidential debates
wouldn't be adhered to totally'' in 1996, he said. ``That's not
something Gov. Bush started.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton did question the commission, but ``at no time
did Clinton ever refuse to deal with the commission as a sponsor,''
Schroeder said. With a big lead against Bob Dole, ``he tried, and
successfully did, reduce the number of debates he participated
in,'' from three to two.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also veered from the traditional format where a panel of
reporters questions candidates to agree to a ``town hall'' event
where voters ask questions, he said. That's why Bush's suggestion
that formats be expanded, Schroeder said, could indeed be valuable
for Americans trying to make a choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``What seems to work best for voters is a variety of formats,''
he said. ``Because each kind of format elicits variations from the
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Commission members have said they'll meet with Gore's camp this
week, and they have invited Bush's people to attend as well. So the
tug of war goes on, but it the bottom line remains the same: that
debates serve such an important purpose.
</P>
<P>
   ``As live events, they're the only time in the campaign where
the candidates have to perform, theoretically, without a script,''
he said. ``It's a pure dialogue between people seeking office and
the voters.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
