<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2695 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SCOOTERS-ACCIDENTS-SF     09-06 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCOOTERS-ACCIDENTS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 AS SCOOTERS BECOME MORE POPULAR ACCIDENTS TO RIDERS INCREASING  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're sleek, they're swift, they're way cool. And _ what do
you know _ they're dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   In August alone, the ubiquitous silver scooters favored by kids,
teens and dot-com dweebs caused more than 4,000 visits to emergency
rooms nationwide, the Consumer Product Safety Commission in
Washington, D.C., reported Tuesday. Kids aged 15 and younger
accounted for about 90 percent of the more than 9,400 reported
incidents so far this year, according to the first major study on
scooter safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``These scooters are the in thing with kids heading back to
school,'' said Commission Chairwoman Ann Brown. ``Unfortunately,
many kids are ending up in hospital emergency rooms instead of
classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Most reported scooter injuries were scrapes and bruises.
However, almost a third involved broken or dislocated bones, mostly
in the arms and hands.
</P>
<P>
   To date, there have been no scooter-related fatalities,
according to the report.
</P>
<P>
   While no specific scooter statistics have yet been compiled by
Bay Area emergency rooms, local doctors say they aren't surprised
that more and more kids are getting hurt on the contraptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things are every bit as dangerous as skateboards,'' said
Dr. Carol Miller, director of the pediatric clinic at the
University of California at San Francisco Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of time before they started causing
injuries,'' she said, adding that all riders should wear helmets
and pads.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 5 million scooters are expected to be sold this year
_ up from just about zero last year, when scooters were still
typically thought of as a get-around vehicle for the likes of
Dennis the Menace.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of SCOOTER0 (86159 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Today, lightweight scooters with in-line wheels, typically
selling for about $100, are the transportation of choice for the
tech-set and a must-have item for trendy youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   Major retailers like Toys ``R'' Us and Kmart expect scooters to
be among their hottest sellers this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Those ringing cash registers are music to the ears of Taiwan's
J.D. Corp., maker of the popular Razor, which dominates scooter
sales. The company expects to see its revenues double to more than
$80 million this year.
</P>
<P>
   Wendy Elkin, director of public affairs for the San Francisco
Unified School District, said no district-wide scooter policy
exists ``because they're so new.''
</P>
<P>
   While some schools already ban scooters on an informal basis,
she said an official, applies-to-all scooter policy should be in
place by next year, pretty much along the same lines as the
district's skateboard policy.
</P>
<P>
   Official school skateboard policy: No skateboards on campus.
Period.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Deignan, a spokesman for the San Francisco Police
Department, said helmets are required by law for scooter riders,
even though few seem to be aware of this fact.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, it's illegal to ride a scooter on city sidewalks,
which, again, doesn't seem to be a fact foremost in riders' minds.
</P>
<P>
   Scooters can be ridden legally on city streets, but only if the
posted speed limit is 25 mph or less.
</P>
<P>
   Laws pertaining to push scooters are a hodgepodge of bicycle and
skateboard statutes, reflecting the still-uncertain status of the
gizmos. And not even the police seem to know exactly what they are.
</P>
<P>
   One traffic cop said his best guess about where a scooter can be
ridden legally was that ``in a business district, you can't, but in
a residential district, you can.''
</P>
<P>
   This much seems clear: If you can't ride a bike or skateboard in
a certain area _ down a crowded sidewalk, say _ chances are the
same goes for scooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're real easy to fall on,'' said Jason Cook, 26, product
manager at the San Francisco office of HotBot, an Internet search
engine. ``All it takes is one or two misjudgements.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of SCOOTER0 (86159 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Cook, who gets to and from work on a scooter, said his worst
mishap came when he tried to jump off a curb. ``I narrowly avoided
breaking my wrist,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A little common sense, Cook insisted, will go a long way toward
keeping most scooter riders safe. Don't go for jumps, he said, and
watch out for cracks in the pavement.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, Cook stressed, don't ride the things downhill.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Dayneko, 23, a Web designer at San Francisco's Guru.com, an
online employment service, said the only problem he's had with his
scooter has been running into pedestrians when taking sharp turns
at street corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be careful and very aware of everyone else,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Menlo Park, Leah Shimabuku said her daughter, Camille, 7, is
not allowed to cross any streets on her scooter unless she is
accompanied by a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's not very fast,'' Shimabuku said. ``But some of those
older kids can really zip around on those things.''
</P>
<P>
   Jane Burks said she bought her son, Kevin, a scooter for his
ninth birthday in June. So far, she said, Kevin has been using his
new set of wheels responsibly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure if they jump and do tricks, they could be
dangerous,'' Burks said. ``And they do go pretty fast. But scooters
have been around forever. We had them when we were kids.''
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle staff writer Julie N. Lynem contributed to this
report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
