u a BC-MIAMI-MAYOR-NYT &LR;      09-06 0642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-MAYOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIAMI-DADE MAYOR WINS BULK OF VOTES BUT MAY FACE RUNOFF
</HEADLINE>
  By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Seeking re-election as mayor of Miami-Dade County, Alex
Penelas Tuesday won the bulk of votes in an open primary contest
against nine opponents. But hours after the polls closed, it was
still unclear whether he had the 50 percent needed to win a second
term without a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   With 62 percent of the precincts reporting, Penelas had 51
percent of the vote, compared with 21 percent for Miguel Diaz de la
Portilla, a county commissioner who had been expected to offer the
strongest challenge, and 20 percent for Jay Love, a Miami
businessman. The other contenders ran far behind.
</P>
<P>
   Political experts here said that even if Penelas did not win
outright, he would handily win a second term if the race went on to
an Oct. 3 runoff.
</P>
<P>
   Penelas, who is 38 and who at one time had been mentioned as a
possible running mate for Vice President Al Gore, seemed destined
for the national political stage as late as March.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with television cameras from around the country and the
world trained on him, he said he would not allow his police
department to aid any effort by the federal authorities to remove a
6-year-old Cuban boy, Elian Gonzalez, from the home where Miami
relatives kept him in defiance of a federal order to return him to
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor ``played for the moment,'' J.P. Monroe, a professor of
political science at the University of Miami, said. ``It pushed him
off the stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Political experts here say Penelas had to decide between defying
the federal government and defying the wishes of a majority of
Cuban-American voters. More than 44 percent of registered voters in
Miami-Dade County are Cuban-American, according to statistics from
the county supervisor of elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``It inoculated him'' against Election Day revenge by
Cuban-Americans, Monroe said.
</P>
<P>
   At the polls, Cuban-Americans said they recognized his
sacrifice, and rewarded him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Perhaps he did risk his political future on a national level,
but here he is our hero,'' said Liliana Morales, 59, a
Cuban-American who has lived in Miami since 1974. ``This just shows
you what this community means to him. He is willing to risk his
political future to stand up for his people.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not be liked among other groups, but here the
majority is Hispanic and we think he did the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Political experts said Penelas was in some ways in an impossible
situation. If he had sided against the emotional tide that was
running through Miami, he would have lost his office and his power
base.
</P>
<P>
   As anger against the federal government washed through parts of
the county during and after the Elian standoff, many people here,
especially blacks and Anglos, said they felt pushed aside by
Penelas.
</P>
<P>
   They promised to get even at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am mainly voting against Penelas because of how he handled
the Elian debacle,'' said Jamin O'Brien, a 32-year-old filmmaker
who lives in Coconut Grove. ``That left egg on the face of the
entire community.''
</P>
<P>
   But such a backlash cannot really harm Penelas, Monroe said,
adding: ``There's not enough to worry about. It's not just the
sheer numbers, but their discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban-Americans, especially older ones, are a reliable voting
bloc. Penelas courted them, strongly.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has run no more than a token campaign in English,'' said
Kevin Hill, an associate professor of political science at Florida
International University.
</P>
<P>
   ``People thought that whites and blacks would never forgive him,
but they tend not to vote'' when they are angry, Hill said.
</P>
<P>
   But Love, who entered the race in part because of that division
in the community, ran surprisingly well, even edging ahead of Diaz
de la Portilla as the early returns came in.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
