<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEINSTEIN-SURGERY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEINSTEIN BREAKS LEG, REQUIRES SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  WASHINGTON _ Sen. Dianne Feinstein slipped on the stairs of her
Colorado vacation home and will require surgery to repair a
compound fracture of her left leg, aides said Tuesday.
<P>
   The accident occurred Friday night as Feinstein and her husband
relaxed in their Aspen house on the final weekend of the Senate's
summer recess. Aides said Feinstein sustained a compound fracture
of her left tibia, more commonly known as the shinbone.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the accident were sketchy, though aides described the
accident as painful, and said she sustained damage to her tendons.
</P>
<P>
   After returning to Washington on Monday wearing a removable
cast, the 67-year-old California Democrat met with a Capitol
physician, an orthopedic surgeon, and Senate Minority Leader Tom
Daschle, D-S.D., to determine the best time for surgery.
</P>
<P>
   No decision was announced.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is some leeway in terms of when (surgery) is done,''
said Feinstein's Washington spokesman Howard Gantman. ``She's
spoken to Daschle to make sure she's here for the crucial votes.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides said they were not certain of the timetable for her
recovery. But they said it would not significantly affect her
ability to participate in the Senate's final push before
adjournment in early October, or her plans to campaign for
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein had planned to spend most of September in Washington
and return to California for the final weeks of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``This shouldn't have any effect on the campaign,'' said Kam
Kuwata, who is managing her re-election. ``The best way to ask the
voters to rehire you is to do a great job as Senator. She'll be (in
Washington) and plan to make every important vote.''
</P>
<P>
   South Bay Rep. Tom Campbell, Feinstein's opponent in the Senate
race, offered his support.
</P>
<P>
   ``A compound fracture is a painful and difficult injury,'' said
Campbell spokesman Sean Walsh. ``We wish Senator Feinstein a speedy
recovery and look forward to seeing her out on the campaign trail
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate faces several key votes in the coming weeks on trade
relations with China, a patient's bill of rights and health care
spending. It may not be evident whether Feinstein's presence is
needed on the Senate floor until hours before the votes.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, then-California Sen. Pete Wilson was rushed into the
Senate chambers in a wheelchair to cast a pivotal vote on a budget
package, days after undergoing an emergency appendectomy.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first broken bone Feinstein has suffered during
her political career. In 1979, as M &LR; mayor of San Francisco,
Feinstein fell and broke an elbow as she left a White House visit
with Vice President Walter Mondale.
</P>
<P>
   Five years later, she fell and broke the same elbow again in the
ancient city of Xian during a visit to China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0021 </DOCNO>
