r a BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON     09-06 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE BIG ROLLERS WIN AT JACK'S  &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ They're lined up like dominoes, and with a flick
of a finger, down they go.
</P>
<P>
   Next to fall: Jack's Restaurant, on Sacramento in the Financial
District. Jack's was born in 1864 and will pass away quietly two
days before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Cause of death: Cash strangulation.
</P>
<P>
   Owner John Konstin remodeled the place three years ago, and
while Jack's never quite re-attained its old status as the
epicenter of San Francisco political and financial
wheeling/dealing, business has been brisk.
</P>
<P>
   But the real estate guys made Konstin an unsolicited offer he
couldn't refuse for the old three-story building: $5 mil.
</P>
<P>
   ALSO OUTTAHERE: In Shape At Andres (no apostrophe), the city's
last (so they say) exercise studio that is strictly no-membership,
all-classes.
</P>
<P>
   Cause of death: Rent just doubled. In Shape is on Hayes near
Gough, and they've been buffing you up and sleeking you down since
'82.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soon,'' sighs In Shape boss Cheryl Rohsik, ``every corner in
the city will be Starbucks, Walgreens, Gap and 24 Hour Nautilus.''
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, Cheryl! On some corners, 24 Hour Nautilus will be muscled
out by Rite Aid.
</P>
<P>
   HEY, MOM! Back-to-school reminder: For the kiddies, pack lunch,
not heat!
</P>
<P>
   At Ross School (``A California Distinguished School''), they're
redefining old standards. In the school handbook, the following
rules (italics mine):
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Leave unsafe  &UR; toys  &LR; at home (fireworks, knives, guns,
hardballs, etc.).
</P>
<P>
   -- ``No ... personal  &UR; athletic equipment  &LR; (game boys (sic),
Walkman, remote control cars, balls) ...''
</P>
<P>
   But what if your child is a star on the varsity Nintendo team?
</P>
<P>
   And what if his/her Uzi has a trigger lock?
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR LEAGUE doofus: Adam Clymer, New York Times political
reporter.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of OSTLER06 (102559 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  I'm sure Clymer is an excellent newsguy and all that. But he
misconstrued a conversation between George W. Bush and Dick Cheney,
overheard when Shrub &AMP; Sidekick didn't realize Bush's mike was
live.
</P>
<P>
   Bush: ``There's Adam Clymer, major-league a_ from the New York
Times.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheney: ``Oh, yeah he is. Big time.''
</P>
<P>
   Clymer said he was ``disappointed.'' Apparently he didn't
realize Bush and Cheney were paying him a compliment.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing for Bush and Cheney that it wasn't some hot babe
walking into the room.
</P>
<P>
   DOG SCOOP: Monday's column on the lady in Mission Terrace whose
lawn is being assaulted by dogs with nonscooping owners brought an
avalanche of suggested solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The practical: A motion sensor hooked to a sprinkler.
</P>
<P>
   The kind-hearted: A small trash can, plastic baggies and a box
of cookies with a smiley-face on the box and a thank-you sign.
(Thanks, Ellie Bush. Say hi to Santa Claus for me).
</P>
<P>
   The cruel but possibly effective: Sprinkle pepper and/or cayenne
powder on the lawn and on droppings ... Hide in bushes and nail 'em
with high powered water gun or paintball gun ... Toss some
hot-pepper-stuffed meatballs around the lawn ... Rent an elephant,
follow the bad humans back to their house and reciprocate ...
Dribble bacon grease on previously-deposited piles, watch as dog
owners recoil in terror at Fido's feast.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, I endorse only the cruelty-lite solutions:
Sprinklers, elephant, bacon grease.
</P>
<P>
   WHERE'S LOTFI? The season-preview issue of the San Francisco
Opera News Magazine notes that Lotfi Mansouri is coming to the end
of his 49-year association with the Opera, 12 of those seasons as
general director.
</P>
<P>
   He did a heck of a job. Maybe that's why the 34-page magazine
has 17 photos of Lotfi.
</P>
<P>
   BIG NATE no ingrate: The city is considering naming the
basketball courts in the Golden Gate Park Panhandle after Nate
Thurmond, former great Warriors center.
</P>
<P>
   And Nate sez: ``I'm not Joe DiMaggio.``
</P>
<P>
   Translation: I would accept the honor with dignity and humility.
</P>
<P>
   I'm pretty sure Nate didn't mean that as a shot at the late
Yankee Clipper. But it's sad when a local legend's name is
synonymous with ingratitude.
</P>
<P>
   Here's my revised take on the city's plan to name North Beach
Playground after Joe: Hell no.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer who is suing the city to stop the renaming of the
playground was DiMaggio's dear friend, Joe said so in his will. We
have to assume the lawyer knows more than we do about what Joe
woulda wanted.
</P>
<P>
   So forget it. Name the playground after Dom DiMaggio, Joe's
brother and also a former star center fielder, plus a gentleman who
says he has fond memories of the playground.
</P>
<P>
   If Joe's attorney wants a bridge or an airport named after Joe,
let the attorney build a bridge or an airport.
</P>
</TEXT>
