<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROIC-DISPATHER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
911 OPERATER MEETS LITTLE GIRL HE HELPED SAVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SIMI VALLEY, Calif. _ Moments after a 2-year-old girl nearly
drowned in a Van Nuys spa, 911 dispatcher Edward Martin calmly gave
directions that helped revive her.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, a day after the incident, Martin saw the tot,
Cheyenne Padilla, whose scream heard by telephone had sounded
marvelous to him. And her parents, her sister Jasmine, 6, and her
grandmother met Martin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an angel,'' said the grandmother, Beverly Howerton, 54.
``The man was totally in control and helped me know where to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, a Los Angeles Fire Department dispatcher in the 911
center for 14 years, was humble about his role in saving the child.
</P>
<P>
   He praised Howerton for keeping her composure in a crisis and
calmly relaying his instructions to her son-in-law, Darrick
Padilla, who performed cardiopulmonary resuscitation on his little
daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``With her demeanor, I didn't think we had an emergency. I'm
here more to pay tribute to you folks,'' Martin said on a visit to
the Padilla family's home in Simi Valley on Tuesday, which also
happened to be Martin's 49th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting 2-year-old Cheyenne, released from a hospital Monday
night in good condition, made his birthday complete, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hardly wait to see the child. We can actually see a
beginning and an end,'' said Martin, who handles about 1,100
emergency calls daily from his base in downtown Los Angeles but
seldom meets those who benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Martin formally shook hands with the tot, who decided to pull
out and use her play camera while adult photographers surrounded
her.
</P>
<P>
   The fire dispatcher reflected on his joy during the 911 call
when he heard Cheyenne let out a loud cry in the background,
signaling she was breathing again.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a great scream,'' Martin told the family. ``I'm a
father, too, so I know what you were going through. I was very
happy to hear her scream. I almost wanted to laugh. It was a very
clear scream that sounded great.''
</P>
<P>
   The terrifying ordeal began shortly before 3 p.m. Monday when
the family was gathered at Howerton's home in Van Nuys, Calif., for
a swim and lunch on Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   The father was in the pool with his daughters. Cheyenne vanished
when his attention momentarily was distracted from her.
</P>
<P>
   His mother-in-law had gone into her home to answer the phone,
and he followed to see if Cheyenne was there. Then Jasmine spotted
her sister at the bottom of the spa and ran for her dad, who
quickly pulled out the child.
</P>
<P>
   The father, certified in infant and child CPR, found his
daughter had a pulse but was not breathing. He gave her
mouth-to-mouth resuscitation while his mother-in-law called 911.
The father was grateful for a CPR partner via phone.
</P>
<P>
   The dispatcher ``reclarified whether we were doing the right
thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through the grandmother, Martin passed along crucial
instructions, including turning the child face-up and tilting her
on her side, checking for a heartbeat and calming down the mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fortunately, we were on the same page,'' the father said.
``You did a good job,'' he told Martin.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the fire dispatcher played the 911 tape to the media
and family, quickly drawing tears from Cheyenne's mother, Kristine
Padilla.
</P>
<P>
   Before giving a hug to the child's mother, Martin told the
family, ``You guys did a good job.''
</P>
<P>
   x x x
</P>
