u a BC-LEE-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITE     09-06 1122
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEE-TRIAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE'S SEALED ORDER TO GRANT LOS ALAMOS SCIENTIST BAIL MADE
PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for rewriting thruout)  
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Lawyers for the former Los Alamos scientist Wen Ho
Lee filed a brief Tuesday with the 10th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals in Denver urging that it reject as disingenuous government
arguments against granting bail to Lee, because prosecutors had
shaped many of the terms of his proposed home detention.
</P>
<P>
   In an earlier motion, prosecutors had said the conditions for
granting bail were inadequate, since they still would not prevent
him from using his wife to spirit nuclear secrets to a hostile
power. Under those conditions she would be allowed to come and go,
with permission, from their house.
</P>
<P>
   In its motion Tuesday, the defense argued that since the
government itself had proposed some of the more stringent terms of
Lee's home detention, like the placement of video cameras in his
garden, it could not now say those terms were inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge handling the case, James Parker of U.S. District
Court in Albuquerque, issued an order on Aug. 24, saying he had
decided that Lee, who is charged with illegally downloading a large
number of nuclear weapons secrets while at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory, should be released to a strict form of home detention
on $1 million bail. Parker's order reversed his ruling of last
December, when he agreed with the government that Lee posed such a
threat to national security that he had to be jailed until his
trial, scheduled for November.
</P>
<P>
   But in a confusing twist, the judge raised questions about
whether his written decision granting bail had been improperly made
public. Last Thursday, Parker wrote a new 17-page opinion, stating
why he had changed his mind, and it was filed with the court that
day. But it was placed under seal so government officials could
determine if it contained classified information.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend the new opinion became public when it was
included with a motion filed by the U.S. attorney in Albuquerque
seeking an appeal of the bail decision. Once prosecutors filed
their appeal, they handed the order to defense attorneys and said
it was now public, and it was distributed.
</P>
<P>
   In describing his order's becoming public, Parker said Tuesday
that he did not believe anyone intended to violate his order but
added that he was concerned because his written opinion had slipped
out in a way that seemed contrary to his aim of distributing his
orders more straightforwardly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there were bad intentions on anyone's part,'' he
said. But, he added, ``I honestly don't know the status of it
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Classifiers at the Department of Energy apparently reviewed the
document, deleted a few details and gave it to the U.S. attorney on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney then attached the opinion, which pokes
numerous holes in the government's case, to its emergency appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Lee remains in prison pending the appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The judge's decision has still not been posted on the federal
court's official Web site or released at the courthouse. Patricia
Chavez, the spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney, said the office
would have no comment.
</P>
<P>
   The opinion is important in part because it casts deep doubts
about many of the government's assertions about Lee's supposed
deceptiveness and the value of the secrets he is accused of
downloading, issues at the heart of the prosecution's case.
</P>
<P>
   ``The totality of the information of which I now have knowledge
presents a tableau different from that described by the government
last December,'' the judge wrote. ``Instead of being confined, as
it was then, to an umbral area of pitch-black darkness, the
relevant information has shifted to a penumbral region that is a
somewhat mottled shade of gray.''
</P>
<P>
   Originally, government witnesses had testified that Lee had
downloaded the ``crown jewels'' of the U.S. weapons program, but in
his order Parker said that new information presented at the latest
bail hearing demonstrated that the information ``no longer is so
clearly deserving of that label.'' He pointedly quoted a defense
expert who called the government's assertions ``unbridled
exaggeration.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge said he was still concerned about some of Lee's
actions, particularly a meeting in a Beijing hotel room in 1988
with two senior Chinese nuclear weapons scientists that was not
fully disclosed to the government for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   But Parker said he now either had dismissed many of the
government's other claims about Lee's alleged deceptions or had
grave doubts about them. For instance, he said, he had been most
influenced by an FBI agent's testimony in December that Lee had
lied to a colleague to gain access to a computer he needed to
download the secret data. That agent, Robert Messemer, admitted in
court several weeks ago that Lee had not lied.
</P>
<P>
   Parker also noted that Messemer had testified earlier that he
anticipated that there would be a sharp increase in efforts by
enemy agents to find seven missing computer tapes on which Lee had
placed much of data he improperly downloaded. In the latest
hearing, Messemer conceded that no such activity had materialized.
</P>
<P>
   The judge also wrote that he had changed his mind about granting
bail because of the government's new charge that Lee had committed
the acts not because he was spying but in an effort to help him get
a job at some foreign scientific institutes, most in countries like
Australia, Singapore and Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Enhancing one's resume,'' Parker wrote, ``is less sinister
than the treacherous motive the government, at least by
implication, ascribed to Dr. Lee at the end of last year.''
</P>
<P>
   He also wrote that Lee had not only done little to conceal his
downloading, and also knew full well that there were monitoring
systems that would detect what he was doing. At one point when he
was trying to erase some files, however, Lee called an open help
line at the laboratory to seek assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``This suggests that Dr. Lee's actions may not have been as
surreptitious, clandestine, and secretive as the government
originally indicated,'' Parker wrote.
</P>
<P>
   And in a long footnote, he expressed anger that the government
``seems to have procrastinated in removing unduly onerous
conditions of confinement'' that he had asked be eased at the
beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
   Parker described some of the conditions as ``demeaning.''
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that, more than eight months later, the
conditions have been improved, and he assured the government that
his dismay over the slow response had not colored his decision to
free Lee on bail.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
