r s BC-TEN-OPEN-LEDE-TEX     09-06 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENUS PASSES FIRST REAL TEST; HINGIS NEXT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLUSHING MEADOWS, N.Y. _ Venus Williams grimly walked to her
chair during a changeover, went to sit down _ and missed.
</P>
<P>
   A gasp went up from the spectators, then a few nervous laughs as
Williams quickly got up, greatly embarrassed but otherwise unhurt.
</P>
<P>
   The incident served as a symbolic snapshot of Williams' day.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Open favorites aren't supposed to fall out of their chairs,
and neither are they supposed to struggle in the quarterfinals. But
Williams did both.
</P>
<P>
   She lost her first set of the tournament before subduing No. 8
Nathalie Tauziat, 6-4, 1-6, 6-1, Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't play up to par,'' Williams said. ``There's no excuse.
I just didn't play.''
</P>
<P>
   Her next opponent did.
</P>
<P>
   Martina Hingis dispatched Monica Seles in the other women's
quarterfinal, 6-0, 7-5, to advance to a rematch of last year's
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   That one was won by Hingis in three sets. This one was supposed
to belong to Williams, even though at No. 3 she's seeded two spots
behind her rival.
</P>
<P>
   Williams entered with the favorite's mantle after winning her
past four tournaments, but Tauziat sounded the alarm both on the
court and in the post-match debriefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she wins the tournament, she needs to improve her level,''
Tauziat said. ``I think she's not going to win if she plays like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hingis clearly is playing her best tennis. The No. 1 seed has
dropped just 15 games in winning five matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm playing better and better each match, picking it
up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She dominated the first set so thoroughly that she won all but
six points. A resurgent Seles broke Hingis twice in the second set
and was serving to send it into a tiebreaker, but Hingis broke for
the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just happy to close it out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also has played her best tennis for most of the
tournament, getting to the quarterfinals without dropping a set.
</P>
<P>
   Against Tauziat, though, she appeared vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a while since I've played a match like that, but I
can't accept these types of things,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of it was Tauziat's style. She's one of the few
serve-and-volleyers left on tour. She doesn't have the power of
some of the big hitters like Williams, but her relentless,
attacking style can pose problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was rushing sometimes,'' Williams said. ``You think your
time is taken away from you a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   She needed a late service break to win the first set, then was
routed in the shocking second set.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the first set I was very, very frustrated,''
Tauziat said. ``I broke her in the beginning of the second set, and
that gave me confidence and I played better.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams became so frustrated with what she called the worst set
she's played during her 24-match winning streak that she almost
lost her customary cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get upset when I'm playing, but today it was very
strange,'' she said. ``I was trying hard not to stomp my feet,
swing my racket around. I'm not used to that. Some players show a
lot of emotion, but usually I don't. That was maybe the main battle
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   She regrouped in the third set, winning it and the match
handily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't do anything much better, I just made some more shots
and was more determined,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But even the final set wasn't without a tense moment or two.
Williams was up two breaks and serving at 4-0, but double-faulted
three times and dropped her serve.
</P>
<P>
   It was after that game that she missed her chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really missed,'' she said. ``I was just angry, and I
couldn't see.''
</P>
<P>
   At least, though, she could talk about a subpar match _ and the
embarrassment of missing the chair _ after a victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel I had my best performance, to say the least,''
Williams said. ``But in the end, the win is on the record and I
moved forward.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep moving forward, she knows she can't afford another match
like this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I'll have to play a little better,'' she said. ``I'll
serve better. I always play better when it comes to a big match.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
