<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-FRANCI     09-06 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-TECH-FRANCIS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCIS' RECORD-SETTING EFFORT AWED MANY, BUT TEXAS TECH SAW IT
COMING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK _ Carlos Francis' record-setting 234-yard game as a
receiver in Texas Tech's victory against Utah State on Saturday
drew eye-opening appraisal from around the Big 12, gaining him
Offensive Player of the Week honors.
</P>
<P>
   Teammates and coaches, however, reacted with a relative yawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos showed everyone in Lubbock and whoever else was
watching what he could do,'' said Kevin Curtis, Tech's
all-conference safety. ``But he shows that every day in practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Kliff Kingsbury agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been doing things like that against our defense all
summer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew Carlos was capable of doing that,'' head coach Mike
Leach said. ``It was not really a surprise.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis, too, seemed singularly unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things just clicked,'' Francis said, matter-of-factly.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes a matter of fact, however, that the redshirt freshman
speedster from Southwest High School has added another dimension to
Leach's passing-game offense, which is predicated on spreading the
defense horizontally and then finding the open spaces. Francis is
the type of wide receiver who has the ability to stretch that
envelope vertically.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have a guy like Carlos _ with his speed in this offense _
is huge,'' Kingsbury said.
</P>
<P>
   Included among his seven receptions against Utah State was a
45-yard touchdown and a 67-yard catch.
</P>
<P>
   ``People don't really see that this is a ball-control offense,''
Red Raiders receivers coach Sonny Dykes said. ``Our deal is to
complete passes. But you have to have that guy who can stretch the
defense \Rdownfield\S so you can throw underneath. One aspect feeds
off the other, and then you take what the defense gives you.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis gives defenses something else to ponder.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more they have to worry about,'' Leach said, ``the better
off we are.''
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: In the opener, New Mexico concentrated on
taking away Tech's outside receivers, so the Raiders threw short _
slip-screens, slants and curls. Francis caught one pass for 3
yards. Utah State focused on stopping that aspect of Tech's game,
so the Raiders looked deep, which was part of the game plan anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back at the end of spring training, we sat down and looked and
Carlos had caught more balls \Rin scrimmages\S than anybody,''
Dykes said. ``So after our first ballgame, we decided we needed to
get this guy the ball more and we made a conscious effort to do
that. He responded.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis has been timed running the 40-yard dash in less than 4.3
seconds. But he is more than just a former track star who can run
fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos is still learning how to play and how to adjust to his
role in this offense,'' Dykes said. ``But for him to have as big a
game as he did this early is a credit to how hard he works. The
physical part of his game is there. The mental is still coming.''
</P>
<P>
   ``God blesses everyone with some kind of ability,'' Francis
said. ``It is up to you to take that ability to another level. I
have good speed, and people respect that. But will they respect the
curl route? Will they respect the out route?
</P>
<P>
   ``People can put you in a zone and shut down your speed. So you
have to be an all-around receiver. That's what I'm trying to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Francis is a solid 5-foot-9, 188 pounds. In addition to his
speed, he has other attributes that help make him a good receiver,
some you might not expect.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make fun of me because I have big hands and big feet,''
he said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   Francis wears size 121/2 shoes. His fingers are longer than
those of the average person of the same height. Long fingers
translate into the term ``good hands.''
</P>
<P>
   He has also emerged nicely from two knee problems. He suffered
cartilage damage at the district track meet his junior year at
Southwest. He partially tore ligaments in his left knee in
preseason workouts a year ago or would have been in Tech's receiver
rotation last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was faster my senior year in high school than I was as a
junior,'' Francis said. ``I'm faster now than I was a year ago. So
the knee problems haven't bothered me.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach said Francis is also surprisingly tough. He recalled an
August practice when Francis had twisted an ankle and had a sore
neck. A member of the training staff told Leach that Francis was
out for the rest of practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos discovered that and said, `No, I'm not out.' He runs
back out there and starts practicing,'' Leach said. ``And he had a
great practice.''
</P>
<P>
   His former coach at Southwest, Bill Hall, doesn't sound
surprised at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was unique in the sense that he always seemed to know what
he wanted to do,'' Hall said. ``He avoided a lot of the things that
were detrimental that we saw capture a lot of other kids along the
way and end their careers even before they got started. He told me,
`Coach, I've seen guys that came through here \RSouthwest\S who
could have been good but made some bad choices. I don't want that
to be me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Francis is yet another example of a player from the Spike Dykes
era who wasn't highly recruited but blossomed into a major-college
player. Tech was the only Division-I school to offer him a
scholarship. He understands why other recruiters didn't call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respected that,'' Francis said. ``I was coming off knee
surgery as a junior, a player who didn't play on a good team
\R2-8\S at a school that has never been a powerhouse in football.
But I knew that if I could get into a D-I college anywhere, I was
going to make an impact.''
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there, either.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Francis
</P>
<P>
   Position: Wide receiver
</P>
<P>
   Height: 5-foot-9
</P>
<P>
   Weight: 188
</P>
<P>
   Class: Sophomore
</P>
<P>
   College career: Set single-game school record with 234 receiving
yards Saturday against Utah State. ... Good spring practice earned
him playing time this season. Had kickoff returns of 100 and 56
yards in spring game. ... Fastest player on the team, having run
4.3 seconds in the 40-yard dash. ... Redshirted in 1999 season
after early-season knee injury. ... Sprinter on the Tech indoor and
outdoor track teams, competing in the 100, 200 and 4x100 relay.
</P>
<P>
   High school: Earned all-district honors as a cornerback and
receiver at Southwest High School. Also returned punts and kicks
and played some running back. ...Excelled as sprinter.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
