<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SYDOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARRYL SYDOR MIGHT NOT BE READY FOR OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Stars were hoping to have defenseman Darryl
Sydor ready for the season opener Oct. 4, but they might have to
wait a little longer.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor, who tore ligaments in his left ankle in Game 6 of the
Stanley Cup Finals in June, was at Dr Pepper StarCenter on Tuesday
for treatment but said there is progress to be made before he's
ready to move from the ice bags to the ice rink.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is still pain. That's how we know it's just not right,''
Sydor said. ``There is pain you can play with, but there is still
certain things I can't do that I need to be able to do them.''
</P>
<P>
   The first step is to get Sydor skating, which he hasn't done
since injuring the ankle. Stars trainer Dave Surprenant said he's
optimistic that will happen while the Stars are in Vail, Colo., for
training camp next week. If not sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get him in skates real soon,'' Surprenant
said. ``Whether or not he gets in a pair of skates before Vail, who
knows. But he'll definitely skate in Vail. Then, we'll go from
there.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to giving a definite yea or nay on Sydor's
availability for the opener, though, Surprenant skips
``definitely'' and retreats to ``hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Stars learned with winger Jere Lehtinen last season, an
ankle injury can be one of the most difficult injuries for which to
pinpoint a return date because skating puts pressure on the ankle,
slowing the healing process.
</P>
<P>
   Lehtinen missed 75 of the Stars' 105 games last season after
fracturing his ankle. Many of his comebacks from the injury were
aborted because of pain.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor neither fractured his ankle nor required surgery as
Lehtinen did, but Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said caution will be
used.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this type of injury, we won't play him until he's
ready,'' Hitchcock said. ``And our experience has been there is a
certain measuring stick. It's a toe drag. When the toe drag can be
made without pain, he's good. He can't do that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   That's not so good.
</P>
<P>
   Sydor is one of the reasons the Stars' top four on defense are
considered the best in the league. It's hard to find a better or
more complementary set than Sydor, Sergei Zubov, Richard Matvichuk
and Derian Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   But, unlike last season, the Stars don't have a veteran
defenseman anchoring their third defensive pair. Shawn Chambers,
who played that role in camp last season, retired this summer after
three doctors told him that the knee injury that sidelined him for
all but five games in 1999-2000 wasn't getting any better.
</P>
<P>
   The two veteran defenseman the Stars traded for during the
stretch run last season, Sylvain Cote and Dave Manson, are also
gone after signing with other teams in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   So the Stars will break in two young defensemen in the third
defensive pair, Brad Lukowich and Richard Jackman, with further
youth and inexperience backing up that pair.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like everybody in the league. If we received a long-term
injury to one of those top four guys, they'd be hard to replace,''
Hitchcock said. ``I'm not concerned, though. Even if \RSydor\S
misses the first couple of games, he wouldn't miss much more.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors initially said Sydor's ankle would heal in eight to 12
weeks, which would put his return near the third week of September.
So if Sydor is indeed going to be ready for the Oct. 4 opener
against Colorado, it will be with only seven or eight practices
under his belt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just going to take some time,'' Sydor said.
``There is nothing you can do. You can't speed it up. You just have
to let them heal the way they are going to heal.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
