u p BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-     09-06 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S ECONOMIC PLAN? HE COULD WRITE A BOOK ON IT, AND DOES
</HEADLINE>
 (SUBS for rewriting thruout; ADDS 200 words)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The Gore campaign Wednesday released a detailed
economic blueprint for the next decade, including a new proposal
for a $300 billion hedge against overly optimistic budget
projections.
</P>
<P>
   The document also reiterates the vice president's commitment to
eliminate the national debt and lists a broad variety of
socioeconomic goals _ like increasing home ownership, reducing
poverty and narrowing the pay gap between men and women _ that he
hopes to achieve through proposals he previously announced.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's idea for a $300 billion reserve fund _ money that would
not be spent from the federal budget surplus _ is intended to be a
cushion against shortfalls in projections by the Congressional
Budget Office, which estimates a surplus of $1.8 trillion over the
next decade, exclusive of the surplus reaped by the Social Security
system.
</P>
<P>
   While the Gore and Bush campaigns both assume the $1.8 trillion
projected by the CBO, the Clinton administration uses the more
conservative estimate of the White House Office of Management and
Budget: $1.4 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``If more conservative OMB projections are met,'' the Gore
blueprint says, ``this will allow an additional $300 billion of
debt reduction. If unexpected costs materialize, this surplus
resource will prevent us from going back to the days of big
deficits, high taxes and deep spending cuts.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's plan otherwise synthesizes proposals that he has made
over the last several months into a variety of national goals. He
is to discuss it in a speech here on Wednesday, and details are
being published in a 200-page book, unique in modern presidential
campaigns in that it is essentially a budget proposal that will
serve as an economic and political manifesto.
</P>
<P>
   The number-heavy and footnoted book, which was made available to
The New York Times, underscores Gore's determination to supply
specifics in his policy proposals. In that regard, it is intended
to serve as a counterweight to the campaign of Gov. George W. Bush,
which the Gore camp regards as feather-thin on policy and based
largely on personality.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, which Gore advisers denied was timed to offset Bush's
proposal today to overhaul Medicare, was drafted for months with
help from Clinton administration experts like Robert Rubin, former
treasury secretary; Laura Tyson, former chairwoman of the Council
of Economic Advisers; and Gene Sperling, Clinton's top economic
adviser. Rubin is to join Gore for the presentation here on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign said its blueprint was the road to continued
economic expansion. And realization of the goals that the vice
president laid out, like reducing the poverty level to below 10
percent for the first time in history, and increasing the college
graduation rate to 75 percent of high school graduates from the
current level of 66 percent, depends on that continued prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The sum of Gore's spending initiatives, as presented by his
campaign, is about $1.4 trillion, although Republicans said it
appeared to them that his proposals would mean new spending that
totaled more than the surplus of $1.8 trillion envisioned by the
Congressional Budget Office. An analysis prepared by the Senate
Budget Committee, headed by Senator Pete Domenici, R-N.M., said
Gore had proposed such extensive spending that he would have to dip
into Social Security to pay for his programs.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign has also proposed targeted tax cuts that it
says amount to $500 billion over 10 years. But Republicans say
these are illusory and so complicated that no one can be sure how
much anyone would save.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign said that its plan was sound and would
eliminate the publicly held federal debt by 2012, while Bush's, it
said, would leave the government $2.8 trillion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the centerpiece of the Gore plan is to eliminate the
debt, through use of Gore's proposed reserve fund and the Social
Security and Medicare surpluses. Gore would protect those surpluses
by barring their use for any other purpose.
</P>
<P>
   One of the plan's socioeconomic goals is to double the number of
families, to 65 million from 32 million, that have at least $50,000
in savings.
</P>
<P>
   Other goals include lowering the income tax burden on the
typical family to the lowest level in 50 years, reducing the
poverty level to below 10 percent, raising the number of families
who own homes to more than 70 percent, reducing the gap between
what men and women earn by 50 percent and creating 10 million
high-technology jobs.
</P>
<P>
   To achieve those goals, the plan offers numerous tax credits and
tax deductions for expenses like college, day care and long-term
care, and to encourage savings.
</P>
<P>
   The plan says that through increased productivity, a Gore
administration could raise family incomes by one-third over the
next decade. It estimates productivity growth at 2.8 percent a
year, by paying down the debt, investing in biomedical research and
computer technology, and opening more markets abroad.
</P>
<P>
   His plan says Gore would reduce the poverty rate to below 10
percent by 2004 from its current level above 12 percent. He would
achieve this by raising the minimum wage, expanding the
earned-income tax credit and creating more welfare-to-work
programs.
</P>
<P>
   The plan also sets a goal of cutting the gap between pay for men
and women.
</P>
<P>
   Women now earn 73 cents for every dollar earned by men,
according to the Council of Economic Advisers. The Gore plan would
cut that gap of 27 cents by almost half, to 14 cents, through
various plans that provide training programs to move women into
higher-paying, high-tech jobs and more loans to help women start
their own businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0029 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2740 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FIRESTONE-RECALL-1STL     09-06 1178
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRESTONE-RECALL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-1000&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD SAYS TIRE-DEFECT-RELATED EXPLORER CRASHES TOO INFREQUENT TO
DETECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS for updating thruout, story is now 200 words longer)  
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) By MATTHEW L. WALD and KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Bridgestone/Firestone tire defect now blamed
for 88 deaths, mainly from crashes of Ford Explorers, eluded
detection for so long because it occurred infrequently, even though
it proved deadlier than many problems that occur more often in
vehicles, Ford Motor and congressional investigators said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The deadliness of the tire problems, combined with a low rate of
warranty claims for poor quality tires, is focusing attention on
whether the design of the Explorer makes it especially vulnerable,
the investigators said. The high death rate associated with a
fairly small number of tire failures is striking because the
nation's last big tire recall, in 1978, involved Firestone tires
that failed frequently but were linked to less than half as many
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The investigators, who portray Ford and Firestone as both
culpable in the crash deaths, also distributed copies Tuesday of an
internal Ford memorandum from March 1999 that showed that Firestone
opposed a tire recall in Saudi Arabia for fear that the tire maker
would have to report it to U.S. regulators.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said it decided to recall Explorers in Saudi Arabia anyway,
at its expense, to replace the tires. But Ford also said it did not
tell U.S. regulators about the decision after Firestone assured it
that the rate of accident claims on identical tires in the United
States was average.
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate committees will conduct hearings on Wednesday
to examine what Firestone, Ford and federal regulators knew about
the tire problems, when they knew it, and how they reacted.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional investigators and Ford disagreed Tuesday about the
significance of the fact that Firestone customers turned in few of
the millions of tires for replacement under warranty, yet Firestone
received a high number of claims of property damage, personal
injury and death.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, the Louisiana Republican who is chairman of
one of the subcommittees holding hearings scheduled on Wednesday,
said that the problem was ``a lethal combination of a somewhat
unstable vehicle'' with tires prone to shed their treads at high
speed. His own Ford Explorer, a green 1992 model, has been sitting
in his garage for a month, he said, because he cannot find
replacement tires for it.
</P>
<P>
   In 1978, Firestone replaced 17 percent of the 23 million tires
in dispute to settle warranty claims even before that recall.
Though Ford and Firestone have not provided warranty figures for
the current recall, they have said that the figures are not
markedly different from other tires, which typically are replaced
under warranty at rates of one-tenth of 1 percent or less.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ford denied that a low rate of warranty complaints,
coupled with numerous crash claims, implied that anything was wrong
with the Explorer. Jon Harmon, a Ford spokesman, said that many of
the crashes involved tires on which the warranty had expired, so
that warranty data would not have provided a clue about the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that Explorers equipped with Goodyear tires from
1995 to 1997 have had virtually no problems. Even with the tire
problems, Explorers have a lower death rate in rollovers per
million vehicles on the road than other midsized sport utility
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Harmon also noted that the current dispute has drawn national
attention for only a month and warranty claims might rise; in 1978,
the recall took place after 18 months of disagreement between
Firestone and regulators, but that disagreement attracted much less
attention than now.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Petrauskas, Ford's vice president for environment and
safety issues, said that the warranty data was not always
appropriate for spotting safety problems because it included a lot
of ``chaff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People will complain, `I don't like the way the white
lettering is,' or `it's noisy,''' Petrauskas said. ``If you have
property and injury claims, chances are you've captured the more
serious thing that has happened with the tires.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin also complained that Ford had replaced tires for
customers in Saudi Arabia, Venezuela and Malaysia, among other
places, without telling the U.S. Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Petrauskas said in a briefing with reporters that Ford
voluntarily informs American regulators of recalls abroad ``if
there's reason to believe that there's a safety defect in the
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   But the company accepted Firestone's assurances that the
problems in those countries were not relevant to conditions in the
United States, after Firestone engineers dissected sample tires
shipped back to Akron, Ohio, Petrauskas said. Citing Firestone
analyses that failures in Saudi Arabia, in particular, were caused
by improper repairs and severe underinflation, she said she was
still not persuaded that tire problems overseas were relevant to
problems in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Firestone still refuse to recall in the United States
the 16-inch Wilderness tires that were recalled in Saudi Arabia,
saying that they have a low rate of crash claims here. Plaintiffs'
lawyers dispute this.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ford released a documents intended to show that it
carefully examined tires when foreign customers complained about
them, but it failed to spot a pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone, which is owned by Bridgestone Corp. of Japan,
repeatedly said that the problem was improper repairs or extended
operation at extremely low tire pressures, or both, Petrauskas
said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford said that rollovers had occurred in 85 of the 1,424
American tread separation cases involving tires now being recalled,
which are 15-inch ATX and ATX II tires of the P235/75R15 size, plus
Wilderness tires of the same size that were made in Decatur, Ill.
Most of the deaths, however, occurred in rollovers.
</P>
<P>
   Firestone, which will probably face criminal charges in
Venezuela, had no comment before the hearings..
</P>
<P>
   Ford and Bridgestone are both liable for damages resulting from
crashes, Tauzin said Tuesday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A Bridgestone/Firestone presentation at the International Tire
Exhibition and Conference two years ago in Akron reviewed the tire
maker's experiments with a Ford Explorer equipped with the kind of
tire that was recalled last month. A tire company engineer
concluded that if the tread separated, the result was ``well within
the range of a driver's ability to control a vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   Ford provided a copy of the document, but plaintiffs' lawyers,
and even some Ford officials, say that the bang that accompanies
the tire failure could startle a motorist into swerving or braking
sharply, either one of which could lead to a fatal crash.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
