<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEREZ TAKES HIS LUMPS AS DODGERS FLOUNDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ At some point, lefty Carlos Perez will run out of
time and chances with the Los Angeles Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, a bundle of a those moments have already passed, but
there are millions upon millions of reasons (i.e., dollars) why he
continues to get opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   But another lousy performance, and questionable health, might
finally put an end to Perez's chances _ at least for this season
after Pittsburgh embarrassed the Dodgers 8-0 Tuesday in front of a
season-low 22,780 at Dodger Stadium. In the first two games of the
series, the Dodgers have been outscored by the Pirates 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   They've also been shut down by two pitchers who had similar
numbers to Perez. Jimmy Anderson pitched a complete game Monday,
and right-hander Jose Silva (9-9) further frustrated the Dodgers on
Tuesday. Silva was 1-5 with a 13.50 ERA in August and allowed eight
runs in 3 innings in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers managed just five hits in seven innings against
Silva, who pitched at least six innings for the first time since
July 26. After Tom Goodwin led off the bottom of the first with a
single, Silva retired the next 11 batters and 14 of 15.
</P>
<P>
   Perez was smacked around again, this time by Pittsburgh. In the
end, Perez exited with a strained left rotator cuff and an enormous
deficit. He allowed six runs on 10 hits in 3 innings before
suffering .
</P>
<P>
   The initial diagnosis is a mild strain of the left rotator cuff,
but he will be re-examined today. His status for his next start,
art, because of his health. But the same questions that led to his
being sent to the minors last July still exist.
</P>
<P>
   And though Perez (5-8) has more than doubled his win total from
last season, that's of little consequence since he has one win
since May 20.
</P>
<P>
   If the injury didn't knock Perez out, the Pirates would likely
have done so shortly thereafter. Perez, who's ERA is 5.56, was
touched for three runs in the first inning and allowed eight hits
before he recorded his fourth out.
</P>
<P>
   Though Perez threw well in non-pressure situations out of the
bullpen, his return to the rotation has been anything but glorious.
He earned the win Aug. 25 against Chicago, but was lambasted for
six runs in two-plus innings last Thursday in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Davey Johnson said he was staying with Perez because
they were facing teams that had trouble against left-handers. The
Pirates, who were batting .266 against left-handers and .264
against right-handers, seemed to fall in the line of opponents
having little problem against Perez.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates took a 3-0 lead in the first, with the final two
runs coming on Keith Osik's single to left. Pat Meares led off the
second with a homer and Pittsburgh extended its lead to 6-0 in the
fourth. Jason Kendall had an RBI double against Perez, who came out
of the game while facing Giles, the next hitter. Matt Herges
relieved and allowed an RBI double to Alex Ramirez.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's exit marked the seventh time in 22 starts he's failed to
pitch at least five innings. In his past five starts, Perez had
made it into the fifth inning once. During that time he's 1-4 with
an 11.37 ERA. In his past two starts he has a 15.88 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Perez, who was 2-10 with a 7.43 ERA last season, continues
to get opportunities because of his contract situation. Perez has
another season left on a three-year, $15.6 million contract he
signed after the 1998 season.
</P>
</TEXT>
