<SLUG> BC-BERENSON-INTERVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORKER DESCRIBES HARSH IMPRISONMENT IN PERU
</HEADLINE>
  By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In her only interview from a Peruvian jail, Lori Berenson
describes the harsh conditions of her confinement and tells how her
captors have mistreated her fellow prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The interview was conducted in March 1999 by Pacifica Radio, and
was made public only Tuesday. The Peruvian government decided last
week to grant Berenson a new trial and void her life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But in the interview, to be broadcast at 9 a.m. Wednesday,
Berenson said that a new trial would be a delaying tactic for the
Peruvian government, which has faced criticism from the U.S.
government and the Organization of American States about the case.
Berenson, a New Yorker, was convicted of treason in January 1996 by
a military tribunal in which judges wore ski masks and her lawyers
were not allowed to cross-examine witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``With such publicity that I've had, such negative publicity
that I've had in Peru, I would never get a fair trial,'' she said,
according to a transcript of the interview provided by Pacifica.
She added that no evidence had been presented at her first trial.
</P>
<P>
   The interview was conducted in the Socabaya jail in Peru by Amy
Goodman, the host of the Pacifica program ``Democracy Now,'' but
was not broadcast immediately out of concern that Berenson would
suffer repercussions, Goodman said Tuesday. But last week, Berenson
was moved to Lima, out of the reach of Socabaya prison officials.
</P>
<P>
   According to the transcript, Berenson said that in December 1995
she spent 11 or 12 days in a cell with a woman who had five bullet
wounds. ``They had left her on a dirty mattress, naked,'' Berenson
said. ``A filthy mattress with five open wounds, which is pretty
horrendous. I mean, there were rats in my bed and things like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Berenson, 30, has had health problems from the high altitude of
Yanamayo, the Andean prison where she was held for the first three
years of her imprisonment. But she told Goodman she was not moved
to Socabaya until the day before the OAS Human Rights Commission
was scheduled to hear her case.
</P>
<P>
   Berenson criticized the United States for what she said was its
cozy relationship with President Alberto Fujimori of Peru.
``There's been some pressure at certain times, but not heavy
pressure, not heavy enough pressure, because I'm still here,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 0152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 01:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2758 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-KILLER-DOCTOR-NYT &LR;      09-06 0864
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KILLER-DOCTOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-DOCTOR TO ADMIT TO MURDERING 3 PATIENTS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio., Ill, W. Va., Iowa, Colo.)  By CHARLIE LeDUFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GARDEN CITY, N.Y. _ A former physician who the authorities say
poisoned patients from Ohio to Zimbabwe but continued to find
medical jobs will plead guilty in federal court Wednesday to
charges that he killed three patients at a Long Island hospital in
1993, prosecutors said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The former doctor, Michael J. Swango, will admit that he
murdered the three men with poison while working at the Northport
Veterans Affairs Medical Center on Long Island, according to Gary
R. Brown, the assistant U. S. attorney who is prosecuting the case.
Beyond that, Brown would offer no particulars about the plea
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   But an official familiar with the negotiations between
prosecutors and lawyers for Swango, 45, said that by accepting the
deal he would avoid the death penalty in New York and extradition
to Zimbabwe, where the authorities have issued a warrant for
Swango's arrest on charges that he poisoned seven patients, five of
them fatally, when he worked there from November 1994 to July 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The official said that the former doctor would also plead guilty
Wednesday before Judge Jacob Mishler of U.S. District Court to mail
and wire fraud charges. Within the description of those charges,
Swango is accused of assaulting two patients in Africa, another
elderly patient at the Veterans Hospital and a patient at Ohio
State University Hospitals, all of whom died in his care, the
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Chavis, a lawyer for Swango, would not comment on the plea
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   With the agreement, prosecutors say they will close the book on
one of the most bizarre and unsettling stories in modern medicine.
It seemed that no matter where Swango went, allegations, suspicion
and death followed. According to the book ``Blind Eye: The
Terrifying Story of a Doctor Who Got Away With Murder'' (Simon &AMP;
Schuster, 1999), by James B. Stewart, questions about Swango began
to surface as early 1982, when he was a medical student at Southern
Illinois University. After an inordinate number of his patients
died, classmates called him Double-0 Swango, joking that he had a
license to kill.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors believe that while working as an intern the next
year at Ohio State University Hospitals, Swango murdered or tried
to murder a number of patients by injecting them with poison. In
his plea, it is expected that Swango will also acknowledge that he
lied to the hospital investigators in connection with the death of
the Ohio State Hospitals patient, Cynthia McGee, 19, in January
1984. Prosecutors said that Swango murdered her by giving her a
potassium injection that caused her heart to stop.
</P>
<P>
   After several mysterious deaths, but no hard evidence, the Ohio
State University Hospitals &UR;  &LR; ended Swango's neurosurgery residency.
He then returned home to Illinois, where he got a job as a
emergency medical technician with the Adams County Ambulance
Service. While working there, he got into a dispute with co-workers
and laced their doughnuts and coffee with ant killer. Five people
became ill but no one died. Swango served two years of a five-year
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   When released from prison, Swango applied to residency programs
in West Virginia and Iowa, but administrators noticed his falsified
records, and his applications were rejected. He tried a third time
in 1993 at the Veterans hospital in Northport, N.Y., and was
accepted. The day after he was hired, his first patient, Dominic
Buffalino, fell into a coma and died.
</P>
<P>
   Three more patients died of lethal injections delivered by
Swango, prosecutors said: Thomas Sammarco, 73; George Siano, 60;
and Aldo Serini, all of Long Island. Swango will plead guilty to
their murders on Wednesday, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials charged Swango with the three murders in July, just as
he was about to be released from prison in Colorado, where he was
serving a three-and-a-half-year term for lying his way into the
Northport hospital. After exhuming the men's bodies, forensic
experts determined that they had indeed been poisoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard the news this afternoon'' Siano's stepdaughter,
Roselinda Conroy, said today about the plea agreement. She said she
had always assumed that her father had died from natural causes.
``I'm absorbing it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Buffalino said that they were happy that a serial
killer would be removed from society, but would remain dissatisfied
until the cause of his death was properly identified. ``I'm glad he
can't kill anymore, but I would like to see some answers in terms
of my brother,'' said Andrew Buffalino, 70, of Huntington. ``My
interest now is one thing. I want to see an autopsy report.''
</P>
<P>
   After Northport officials learned of Swango's criminal record,
they fired him. He became a physician at Mnene Mission Hospital in
Bulawayo, Zimbabwe, using forged documents form the Federation of
State Medical Boards. He is still wanted in that country.
</P>
<P>
   Swango was eventually arrested in 1997 in Chicago while waiting
for a flight to Saudi Arabia, where he had a new job as a doctor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 0159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
