<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLAM DUNK _ RED SOX COAST 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-A'S-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A Red Sox player who is awaiting a hearing on whether
he is juiced hit the first grand slam of his career Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night
off an Oakland pitcher who complained that the baseball was
``greasy.''
</P>
<P>
   This could be the first playoff race decided on the basis of DNA
evidence and fingerprint samples.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Alexander, the reserve Sox infielder who was to have been
in Dorchester District Court Wednesday for a hearing on whose
illegal steroids were found in the glove compartment of the
Mercedes he loaned to a team batboy more than two months ago, took
A's pitcher Kevin Appier deep with the bases loaded, the unexpected
climax of a seven-run first inning that propelled the Sox to a 10-3
win over Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, who must answer to an application for a criminal
complaint but has not been charged, won't be in court Wednesday.
His hearing was postponed until Oct. 18, with another continuance
almost certain if the Sox make it to the postseason for a third
straight year for the first time in their 100-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who scored in double figures for the first time in 44
games (July 20, the same day Pete Schourek last pitched), remained
two games behind the Cleveland Indians in the AL wild-card race and
six games behind the Yankees in the AL East with 27 to play. The
A's, who had won four in a row, fell three games behind the Indians
in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander, a.k.a. Friend of Sammy, said he was expecting a phone
call and perhaps a bottle of champagne from Cubs slugger Sammy
Sosa, his longtime amigo and countryman from the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know he's going to call me _ I call him when he hits one,''
said Alexander, who presumably sets aside considerably more pesos
for his phone bill than Sammy does his.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's grand slam, which landed just inside the left-field
foul pole, was his third home run this season. Sosa has 45.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think so,'' winning pitcher Schourek said when asked
whether he'd ever given up a home run to Alexander when both were
in the National League. ``He may have hit a deep fly ball off me. I
gave up a lot of home runs to the Cubs there, but I don't think he
was one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But Schourek, who is pitching on borrowed time _ he expects to
have postseason surgery on his left elbow and shoulder _ may never
have faced Alexander while laboring under the handicap claimed
Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night by Appier.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran righthander, who faced 11 hitters in a first inning
in which the Sox did not score until after Carl Everett hit into a
double play, complained bitterly that the baseballs, which normally
are rubbed with a secret mud before each game, felt more like
they'd been dipped in Brylcreem.
</P>
<P>
   ``They felt greasy,'' said Appier, who got to wash his hands in
the third inning, when doubles by Donnie Sadler and Trot Nixon made
it 8-0 and sent him to the dugout to contemplate his shortest start
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Appier tossed a ball into the A's dugout. ``Look
at the ball,'' he shouted to manager Art Howe and pitching coach
Rick Peterson.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson gave credence to Appier's lament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It almost felt like there was lotion on the ball,'' Peterson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Howe brought Appier's complaint to the attention of plate umpire
Randy Marsh, who offered the not unreasonable opinion that the
baseballs didn't seem to be bothering Schourek. Very little did.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, who was battered in four July starts (0-3, 11.57)
before admitting that his arm was close to disintegrating,
postponed surgery while checking to see whether he could continue
to pitch with bone chips in his elbow and a frayed rotator cuff in
his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by two rehab starts in the minors and a three-inning
simulated game, Schourek was activated four days ago and given Jeff
Fassero's spot in the rotation. He didn't allow a hit until Jason
Giambi's homer over the Sox bullpen with one out in the fourth, and
gave up just two hits before leaving with one out in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a long time coming,'' Schourek said of his first win
since May 15. ``I'm proud of myself for the way I worked, the
attitude I had to try and come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to sit at home and watch the guys play the rest
of the season. I wanted to give it a shot.''
</P>
<P>
   His job was made easier by the Sox' biggest inning since they
scored seven in the third against the Twins on July 5.
</P>
<P>
   After Everett rolled into a double play, Nomar Garciaparra
singled home Trot Nixon _ the first of seven successive hitters to
reach. Troy O'Leary walked, Dante Bichette singled to load the
bases, and Scott Hatteberg's broken-bat single scored two more runs
to make it 3-0. Sadler walked to bring up Alexander, whose home run
settled in the net, just inside the foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon had three hits. Garciaparra, who went 15 games without
driving in a run, knocked in three with a double and single, giving
him four RBIs in two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was really great for Pete,'' said Bichette, who had two
singles. ``I faced him a lot in the past. He showed some of the
same stuff. He freezes you with that big breaking curveball and
works off the corners with his fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   Call it the dry look.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
