<P>
   DISPUTE-MANAGEMENT (Undated) _ For years, accusations from
Postal Service workers of racial discrimination, sexual harassment
and other management abuses had poured into Equal Employment
Opportunity Commission. The backlog of informal complaints had
built up to an incredible 30,000 filings a year, more than from any
other single employer. Some of the complaints escalated into costly
litigation, while others festered, undermining morale. But in 1994
as part of a settlement of a class-action lawsuit, lawyers at the
Postal Service, the nation's largest employer, started an ambitious
experiment in dispute resolution. They created a program settle
disputes using outside neutral mediators. The lawyers estimate that
the program has saved the agency millions of dollars in legal costs
and improved productivity. Now, two of the Postal Service's lawyers
have left for private practice and are taking a similar program on
a road show.
</P>
