<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SUKEFORTH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLYDE SUKEFORTH, 98, IS DEAD; STEERED ROBINSON TO MAJORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clyde Sukeforth, the Brooklyn Dodger scout and manager who
accompanied Jackie Robinson through two of the Hall of Fame
player's milestones as the first African-American in modern
baseball, died on Sunday at his home in Waldoboro, Maine He was 98.
</P>
<P>
   In 1945, when the major league teams had an unwritten policy to
ignore black players, Sukeforth was assigned by Branch Rickey, the
Dodgers' president, to scout Robinson, then the Kansas City
Monarchs' shortstop, at a Negro Leagues game in Chicago before
bringing him back for what would be a historic meeting in the
Dodger offices in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Jack came out on the field,'' Sukeforth often said of
that game, ``I called him over and introduced myself and told him
who sent me. He was amazed. He said, `Why is Mr. Rickey interested
in me?' I told him, `I just work here. I have no authority to
answer that question, but I can assure you there's a lot of
interest in you in Brooklyn.'''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Rickey was forming a Brooklyn Brown Dodgers team to
play in a new black league, but on the morning of Aug. 28,
Sukeforth ushered Robinson into Rickey's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``We walked, in,'' Sukeforth recalled, ``and I said, `Mr.
Rickey, here is Jack Roosevelt Robinson,' and Rickey said, `Jack,
all my life I've been looking for a great colored ballplayer and I
have reason to believe you might be that man.' That's when Jack
realized Rickey was talking about the Dodgers, not the Brown
Dodgers.''
</P>
<P>
   Sukeforth was the only other person at that meeting as Rickey
told of his plan for Robinson to play in 1946 for the Dodgers' top
farm team in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Rickey told him: `You must be more than a great
ballplayer. I need a man who can accept the worst possible abuse
and take it day after day, a man with the courage not to fight
back.' Jack told him: `Mr. Rickey, I think I can play in Montreal
and I think I can play in Brooklyn. I'll accept your judgment on
that. But if you want to take this gamble, I promise you there will
be no incidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, Robinson signed a Montreal contract, becoming
the first black player in what was known as organized baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Six days before the 1947 season opener, the Dodger manager, Leo
Durocher, was suddenly suspended for the entire season by
Commissioner Happy Chandler for controversial off-field incidents.
Rickey named Sukeforth the interim manager. The next day, the
Dodgers purchased Robinson's contract from Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   Durocher's ban ``took the heat,'' as Sukeforth said, off
Robinson's debut. ``I didn't tell Jack anything special,''
Sukeforth said. ``Jack had enough to think about.''
</P>
<P>
   After two regular-season games that the Dodgers won, Rickey
hired Burt Shotton as manager. Sukeforth remained a Dodger coach
through 1951 when he was involved in another historic moment. In
the ninth inning of the decisive third game in the National League
pennant playoff at the Polo Grounds, the Giants were rallying
against Don Newcombe.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Dressen, the Dodger manager, phoned Sukeforth in the
bullpen where Ralph Branca and Carl Erskine were warming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always leaned toward Branca,'' Sukeforth said years later.
``Branca had won 21 games in 1947 when he was 21.'' So Branca was
summoned.
</P>
<P>
   On Branca's second pitch, Bobby Thomson hit the ``shot heard
'round the world,'' a three-run homer for a 5-4 victory and the NL
pennant.
</P>
<P>
   Sukeforth later scouted for the Pittsburgh and Atlanta
franchises; he had been a major league catcher with Cincinnati and
the Dodgers from 1926 to 1934 and again early in the 1945 season.
</P>
<P>
   Sukeforth's first wife, Helen, died in 1938. His second wife,
Grethel, died last year. According to The Associated Press, his
survivors include his daughter, Helen Zimmerman of Dallas, and four
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
