<HEADLINE>
ANGELS SIGN 16-YEAR-OLD DOMINICAN PITCHER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Anaheim Angels announced on Tuesday they have
signed 16-year-old pitcher Johan Quezada Santana from the Dominican
Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Santana, who is 6-foot-2, 150 pounds, worked out at Edison Field
in recent weeks and was an option for the club if it could not sign
pitcher Chris Bootcheck, a first-round draft pick in June.
</P>
<P>
   Bootcheck's agent, Scott Boras, and the Angels have not been
able to agree on a signing bonus. The Angels offer was believed to
be raised to $1.7 million recently but not accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Signing Santana to a substantial contract, approximately
$600,000 to $700,000, seems to indicate the Angels have gone in
another direction with Bootcheck, leaving him to remain in college
for his senio Bootcheck was the 20th overall pick in the draft, but
the Angels' second selection behind 17-year-old pitcher Joe Torres,
who was taken with the 10th overall pick and received a $2.1
million signing __ Back at you: The Angels didn't want
knuckleballer Steve Sparks after last season. Now pitching for the
Tigers, Sparks was named the American League pitcher of the month
for August. Sparks, who will start tonight against the Angels, has
won six in a row, includ record with a 1.69 ERA in August.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks says he has no bitter feelings toward the Angels. After
all, he went 5-11 with 5.42 ERA last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understood the situation, they had (Brian) Cooper, (Jarrod)
Washburn, (Ramon) Ortiz and (Matt) Wise. They were bringing back
Tim Belcher and Ken Hill. I read the writing on the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Erstad in the outfield: Darin Erstad started in left field
for the first time since Aug. 19. He had been limited to the DH
spot because of a strained muscle in his rib cage.
</P>
<P>
   He had two hits Tuesday to extend his hitting streak to 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   __ Health check: Pitchers Seth Etherton and Washburn each threw
three innings of a simulated game Tuesday, but there is for them to
return.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we are not ruling out them pitching again this year,
the chances are remote because of the time left,'' Scioscia said.
``In no way are we going to let the needs of a team in the pennant
race jeopardize the health of these two young arms.''
</P>
