<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOUNG ANGELS ARMS HIT THE SKIDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT Anaheim Angels manager Mike Scioscia hasn't wavered in
showing confidence in his young starting pitchers since the first
day of spring training. They lived up to his expectations and
exceeded those of others most of the season. But now, at the most
critical point of the season, they have hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   And the rest of the team is going down right along with them.
The Angels lost their season-worst sixth consecutive game 7-5
Tuesday night to the Detroit Tigers at Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   They fell seven games behind the first-place Seattle Mariners in
the American League West with 24 games remaining. They also fell 7
games behind the Cleveland Indians in the wild-card race.
</P>
<P>
   The recent slump has been the result of poor starting pitching.
No Angels starter has won since Matt Wise beat the Indians on Aug.
25, a stretch of 10 games. In those games, the starters are 0-6
with an 11.10 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday was Wise's turn and he had what he called his worst
performance of the season, including his first four months at
Triple-A Edmonton. Wise (3-3) gave up seven runs and seven hits and
2 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are some growing pains,'' Scioscia said. ``You have to
look at it as having growing pains at an inopportune time. But
these guys are the best we have to offer right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Tony Clark hit a two-run homer in the second inning off Wise,
who allowed five more runs in the third without making it out of
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The relievers _ Juan Alvarez, Lou Pote, Bryan Ward, Ben Weber
and Mark Petkovsek _ pitched well go give the Angels a chance. They
combined to throw 5 scoreless innings, giving up only three hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got an RBI single from Tim Salmon in the first and a
two-run triple from Scott Spiezio in the sixth off Tigers starter
Brian Moehler (12-7), but it wasn't enough to offset another large
deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew coming into the situation our pitching staff was going
to take us as far as we could go,'' said Angels first baseman Mo
Vaughn, who went 0 for 5 with four strikeouts. ``Even though they
are young, that's the way it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew what we got into from the beginning, you learn on the
job whether you're young or a guy like me, when you have a night
like I did tonight. You only get better with failing.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn emphasized he wasn't blaming the starters for the Angels'
plight. ``I am not pointing any fingers for any situation,'' Vaughn
said. ``We are a team.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the losing streak, Scioscia says there is no point in
shaking things up. ``If I didn't see the effort, or heart, or
passion to play the game, you'd see some lockers turned over right
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (coaching) staff would not put up with that, but we
haven't seen that. They are playing with a passion every day. They
live and die with every pitch. In my mind, the solution isn't
anything but having patience and getting productive starting
pitching.''
</P>
<P>
   Wise put together four good starts when he first joined the
rotation, but he has struggled in his past two.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not from a lack of confidence or focus,'' Wise said.
``It's just a lack of execution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
