<SLUG> BC-BBA-A'S-STANLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN STANLEY SHOWS VALUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Stanley went a career-best 5 for 5 _ a home run, a
double, three singles _ with 5 RBIs Monday in Oakland's 10-0 rout
of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   That's just two hits fewer than the struggling Red Sox had in
their 5-1 Labor Day win over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Why can't the Sox get a player like that?
</P>
<P>
   Things are good these days for Stanley, who finds himself again
in the thick of a playoff hunt just a little more than a month
after the Red Sox gave him his walking papers.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley returned to Fenway Park Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, in the starting
lineup at first base, and batting cleanup. His return attracted a
horde of media, eager to hear his thoughts on his past with the Sox
and his future with the Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first questions, of course, was whether the Red Sox
did the right thing in letting him go. Then he was asked about
being placed on the disabled list and his ex-teammates coming to
his support, Jeff Frye in particular.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``the (Red Sox) have a lot of players
here. Maybe they're better off without Mike Stanley. It's hard to
say. I'm not here to judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The disabled list? It was frustrating, because when I finally
signed with this team, it was, I think, a month and two or three
days since my last at-bat. It was tough, but at the time I
understood why Jimy (Williams) wanted to do what he wanted to do.
It just came down to a time when I felt like I needed to be
released and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   When Stanley finally was let go, more than one of his mates were
candid in their criticism of the organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``It felt great to know I had that kind of respect in the
clubhouse with teammates,'' said Stanley. ``That's ultimately the
family, a group of players. It's not necessarily the front office
or even the coaches. The players have such a unique bond.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice that some of those guys stepped up. Some of the
bigger names. Nomar (Garciaparra) said some nice things. It just
made me feel good to know that I had that respect from the players
I played with.''
</P>
<P>
   Most outspoken was Frye, who just days after his tirade was
traded to Colorado. Stanley said he has talked with Frye several
times since then. He joked, ``It's hard to say Jeff was punished in
any way. He went to one of the best hitting places in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Since signing with Oakland Aug. 4, Stanley is 25 for 86 (.291)
with three homers and 16 RBIs in 26 games. Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, he
provided a sixth-inning RBI double, a rare Oakland highlight in a
10-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't think I could still do the job, I wouldn't have
signed,'' said Stanley. ``I was having a great time with my kids.
It was a great period of time during the summer. But I felt I still
had something to offer the game and hopefully offer a team that was
in contention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way (Oakland) looks at it, we're very much in contention
in the West. We're actually in better position there than we are in
the wild card. That's what we focus our attention on, just as I'm
sure the (Red Sox) are focusing their attention on New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanley brings to the Oakland clubhouse the same kind of
influence he had in Boston. He was greeted there with open arms.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran second baseman Randy Velarde called Stanley a huge
addition to the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a veteran, a righthanded bat, and balances our lineup,''
said Velarde. ``He gives a little protection to Jason Giambi. To
get a quality addition like Stano is big for us. He brings playoff
experience and that's invaluable. I just can't say enough good
things about the guy. He's a presence in this clubhouse, especially
with all the youngsters we have on this team.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those youngsters is 24-year-old right fielder Adam Piatt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has seen just about everything at one time or another,''
said Piatt. ``He's a swell guy to have in the locker room. He's a
guy you can go up to and ask advice and know you're going to get a
quality answer and he's going to be genuine with you. He fit right
in. We're glad he's here. I know he's going to help us out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
