<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHOUREK PITCHES IN FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-SCHOUREK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN VELLANTE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Pete Schourek knows the elbow surgery is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder? Perhaps, but not definite.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, the Red Sox lefthander intends to take his turn
on the mound every fifth day and hope for the best. The pain will
return, doctors have told him, but Schourek hopes it's not until
November.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, saying that ``things are better, but not 100
percent,'' gave the Red Sox a huge boost Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night at Fenway
Park, where he pitched a strong 5 1/3 innings of two-hit ball in a
10-3 win over Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   It was his first appearance since coming off the 15-day disabled
list Saturday and ended a string of 12 starts without a win (0-6,
six no-decisions). It was a far cry from his last start July 20 at
Baltimore: 2 1/3 innings, 5 hits, 5 runs, 5 walks.
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, who threw 74 pitches, 48 for strikes, conceded he
could have packed it in for the season, knowing what lies ahead,
but he was reluctant to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a mixed decision,'' said Schourek (3-9, 5.05
ERA). ``I'm going to have to have surgery eventually this year.
Talking to the doctors, they said that I would be able to rehab it
and be ready for spring training if I was able to finish out the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of what kind of stuff I could come back
with. I'm happy with my stuff today and I'm just going to take it .
. . start to start and see how it goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change anything on the mound. I'm going to
throw as hard as I can for as long as I can during the game. If I
can't do it anymore, if I'm not effective anymore, than maybe it's
time to take care of it. But until that time, I'm going to try to
do what I did tonight every fifth day.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Giambi was the biggest thorn in Schourek's side. The
Oakland designated hitter reached on an error in the first inning,
then in the fourth drilled a one-out home run to right, the first
hit off Schourek. He also singled off Schourek in the sixth,
bringing Jimy Williams out of the dugout and reliever Hipolito
Pichardo into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really pitched good,'' said Williams of Schourek. ``He had
a good breaking ball and was on the plate. He really gave us a big
boost with that kind of performance out there. He really did.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek, whose winless streak was the longest for a Boston
pitcher since Mike Gardiner's dirty dozen in 1992, got the jump on
most of the 21 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's key for me, getting ahead,'' he said. ``I don't throw
real hard so I have to get ahead and get the count in my favor so I
can manipulate the strike zone the way I need to.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek said he loves pitching in September, when every outing
means something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to have more chips on the line,'' he said. ``I would
love to be able to do that throughout the whole season one time.
It's just when the weather gets cool, there's a little more bounce
in your step when there's a playoff race and the intensity level is
higher.''
</P>
<P>
   Schourek acknowledged that Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night's effort surprised him
somewhat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, kind of,'' he said. ``I was pretty down after that last
start in Baltimore. I didn't think I'd be able to get back to
having this kind of stuff right now. I was just working hard and
maybe the rest helped out some more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor told me it's just a matter of time before (the
pain) all comes back. I just hopes it's in early November.''
</P>
<P>
   So, too, do the Red Sox, who right now can use all the pitching
help they can get.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
