u s BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT &LR;      09-06 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONE HURT IN YANKS WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ After a doctor struggled to shove David
Cone's left, nonthrowing shoulder back into place Tuesday night,
Cone stifled the inevitable sadness over his latest setback and
mustered some levity. ``I guess this makes your decision about the
post-season roster a lot easier,'' he joked to Yankees manager Joe
Torre, while sitting on the trainer's table.
</P>
<P>
   Despite dislocating his shoulder while making a diving catch in
the third inning, there is a chance that Cone could come back in
the last two weeks of the season. He could start a game or two and
make a last bid to participate in the playoffs, at the end of his
sixth and perhaps final year with the Yankees. If that does not
happen, Cone will feel as if this is a fitting end to a horrible
season.
</P>
<P>
   When Cone was helped off the field in agony, the gate to the
visitors' bullpen in left field swung open and Dwight Gooden jogged
across the outfield here to relieve his longtime teammate, to help
his own chances of being on the post-season roster. Gooden threw 5
1/3 innings and collected his 194th career victory as the Yankees
dumped Kansas City, 10-5. Clay Bellinger, David Justice and Scott
Brosius each slugged home runs among 17 hits for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Cone walked into the clubhouse after the game shirtless, without
any wrapping whatsoever on his left shoulder. But as he pulled on
an olive-colored shirt, the trainer Gene Monahan stepped through a
throng of reporters. ``Let me put this on first,'' Monahan said,
holding a sling.
</P>
<P>
   Cone raised both hands to his chest as Monahan eased the sling
over his left elbow, then buttoned his shirt. Cone, who will have
an MRI exam Wednesday morning, spoke hopefully of a return this
season, reporting what he was told, that there does not seem to be
any additional damage. He keeps his hands below his shoulders in
his pitching motion; maybe it would just be a question of how much
pain he could stand, or whether he could raise his left arm quickly
enough to protect himself.
</P>
<P>
   Cone also mentioned other possibilities, that he would not pitch
again this year. ``I definitely do not want my career to end this
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitching in the third inning against his former team, in his
hometown, Cone rushed off the mound in pursuit of a bunt popped up
by the Kansas City shortstop Rey Sanchez; moving toward third base,
Cone extended his left-handed glove and dove, parallel to the
ground. He caught the ball in midair _ and landed heavily on his
left elbow. Cone immediately rolled over in pain, writhing, his
left arm prone at his side, panicked, realizing his shoulder was
out of its socket, yelling at Monahan to not touch him. ``It felt
like my shoulder was in my neck,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cone's body slumped toward his left side, in the direction of
the damaged shoulder, as Monahan quickly helped him to his feet and
off the field, Cone's body slumped toward his left side. Royals
fans, who cheered for Cone when he broke into the majors in 1986,
and again in 1993 and 1994 after he signed with Kansas City as a
free agent, clapped in support of Cone as he departed. His father
and mother, Ed and Joan Cone, watched from the stands before
heading for the Yankees' clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Joyce, the Royals' team doctor, worked for 15 minutes to
maneuver Cone's shoulder back into place; Joyce was having so much
trouble that at one point, there was talk of moving Cone to the
hospital for the procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Cone was eventually taken to a local hospital for X-rays, which
revealed no fractures, and his teammates were surprised to see him
moving his left hand and arm after the game. ``I feel like I dodged
a bullet,'' Cone said. ``Judging by how I feel now, I feel pretty
lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury comes at a time when the 37-year-old Cone seemed to
be rebounding, in the last weeks of what has been a frustrating
year. Cone,4-11 with a 6.16 earned run average overall, had no
victories for more than three months, his record 1-10 after the
Minnesota Twins pounded him for nine hits and eight runs in five
innings on July 27. Cone went to the Yankees' minor league facility
in Tampa, Fla., on the orders of the Yankees' owner George
Steinbrenner, worked on his mechanics and regained some confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Cone ended his streak without a victory Aug. 10, and in his five
outings leading up to tonight's game against the Royals last night,
Cone was 3-1 with a 3.86 ERA, contributing to the Yankees' recent
surge in the American League East standings.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees closing in on their third consecutive division
title and their sixth straight appearance in the post-season, it
appears as if Cone will not be part of the post-season rotation,
regardless of the condition of his shoulder and how it impacts what
he does. Roger Clemens, Andy Pettitte, Orlando Hernandez and Denny
Neagle are likely to make up the Yankees' rotation in October.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
