<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALEXANDER'S SHOT A TOUGH ONE TO CALL 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ALEXANDER-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As it usually is when they talk, the next conversation
between great friends Manny Alexander and Sammy Sosa will revolve
around home runs. This time, however, they will be discussing
Alexander's first career grand slam, a first-inning shot
Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night that pretty much settled matters early between the
Red Sox and Athletics.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could be a one-sided phone call because Sosa could
be left speechless by the shock of the news. So stunning was
Alexander's blast into the net that staked Pete Schourek to a 7-0
lead en route to a 10-3 win that the hero himself couldn't hide a
smile that had a shade of embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, I'm not a home run hitter,'' said the utility
infielder who manned third base in place of the injured Lou
Merloni. ``But (Sosa) better call me, because I do it all the time
when he does it.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the home run came from the most unlikely of
candidates. Alexander is, after all, the guy who back on July 4
ended a homerless streak of 371 at-bats _ fourth longest for
non-pitchers among active players _ with his first home run of the
season. He hit another in August, so he's now got three homers in
three months _ and 14 in 1,178 major league at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander's slugging percentage (.298) could never have forecast
what was in store as he came up in the first inning, the ninth
hitter to face beleaguered Oakland starter Kevin Appier. The
righthander had already yielded four hits and three walks, but with
Alexander up, there seemingly was no cause for alarm, so the
bullpen was silent.
</P>
<P>
   Two pitches later, Fenway was anything but, Alexander having
delivered an 0-and-1 pitch just inside the foul pole down the
left-field line to put the A's down by a touchdown and an extra
point.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pitch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A good pitch? Alexander was told that Appier had described it as
hanging slider that he didn't have a good grip on.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander smiled. The pitcher had his definition of what a good
pitch looks like, Alexander has his. And that hanging slider that
moved out over the the middle of the plate sure looked good to a
guy unaccustomed to the power role.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a power hitter,'' said Alexander, who has fewer hits
(36) this year than Sosa has home runs (45). ``But sometimes you
hit the ball in the real good part of the bat and you have a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he wasn't sure it would clear the wall, ``but I made
good contact and you have to be happy when you do things like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Most important, said Alexander, was the fact that the power
surge came in a crucial game in a September pennant race. It would
send him to the phones happy, for calls to his wife (she just
returned to the Dominican) and to his mother (visiting his younger
brother Enrique, who plays high school ball in New York).
</P>
<P>
   From a personal standpoint, it was also nice that first base
coach Tommy Harper somehow managed to retrieve the ball and deliver
it to Alexander, who said he'd like Appier to autograph it.
</P>
<P>
   Does he think the guy whose pitching line included nine hits and
eight runs in just 2 2/3 innings would actually want to do such a
thing?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I do,'' said Alexander. ``He's a nice guy. I think he'll
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he will. But Appier will probably still wonder how it ever
happened.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
