<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NUDODGERS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANOTHER DODGERS FIASCO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Erratic and mostly abysmal performances couldn't
keep lefty Carlos Perez out of the Los Angeles Dodgers starting
rotation. His health, though, might end his season.
</P>
<P>
   Perez, given a multitude of opportunities the past two seasons
for millions upon millions of reasons (i.e., dollars), was bashed
around by Pittsburgh before leaving his start Tuesday with a
shoulder injury.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's outing was the low point of an embarrassing 8-0,
three-error loss to Pittsburgh in front of a season-low 22,780 at
Dodger Stadium. In the first two games of the series, the Dodgers
have been outscored by the Pirates 20-1.
</P>
<P>
   They've also been shut down by two pitchers who had similar
numbers to Perez. Jimmy Anderson pitched a complete game Monday and
right-hander Jose Silva (9-9) further frustrated the Dodgers on
Tuesday. Silva was 1-5 with a 13.50 ERA in August and allowed eight
runs in 3 innings in his last start.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers managed just five hits in seven innings against
Silva, who pitched at least six innings for the first time since
July 26. After Tom Goodwin led off the bottom of the first with a
single, Silva retired the next 11 batters and 14 of 15.
</P>
<P>
   The issue, though, is Perez's shoulder. He had trouble with it
in his start in Milwaukee, during which he failed to record an out
in the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of the game, it was kind of stiff,'' said
Perez, who's guaranteed $7.5 million next season. ``The last pitch
I threw I felt something pop in the back of my shoulder. I was
trying to push myself and stay in the rotation. I want to help my
team, like always. Right now, my arm doesn't feel so good.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough pitching when you feel pain in your arm.''
</P>
<P>
   The initial diagnosis is mild strain of the left rotator cuff.
His status for his next start, which was slated for Monday in
Arizona, was uncertain. In part, because of his health. But the
same questions that led to his being sent to the minors last July
still exist.
</P>
<P>
   Perez will be re-examined today, but Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said it's unlikely he'd make his next start. Instead, the
Dodgers might turn to either Luke Prokopec of recall right-hander
Eric Gagne from Albuquerque, which is in the Triple-A playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's out indefinitely,'' Johnson said. ``He felt it pretty bad
in the game so we'll have to see. I'm sure he's going to have an
MRI. I'm sure he's not going to be able to start in five or six
days.''
</P>
<P>
   Perez exited with an injury and an enormous deficit. He allowed
six runs on 10 hits in 3 innings before suffering the injury on a
two-out pitch to Brian Giles in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   If injury didn't knock Perez out, the Pirates would likely have
done so shortly thereafter. Perez, whose ERA is 5.56, was touched
for three runs in the first inning and allowed eight hits before he
recorded his fourth out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just kills you,'' Johnson said. ``They had eight hits in
the first two innings. You escape with just four runs. It's
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Perez threw well in nonpressure situations out of the
bullpen, his return to the rotation has been anything but glorious.
He earned the win Aug. 25 against Chicago but was lambasted for six
runs in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Perez's exit marked the seventh time in 22 starts he's failed to
pitch at least five innings. In his past five starts, Perez had
made it into the fifth inning once. During that time, he's 1-4 with
an 11.37 ERA. In his past two starts he has a 15.88 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't playing well,'' Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros
said. ``The last two nights we haven't done much offensively, if
anything. We've just really struggled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
