<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HINGIS, VENUS WILLIAMS GAIN SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
 OPEN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALLEN LESSELS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was deja vu all over again. All over the place.
</P>
<P>
   First, Martina Hingis and Venus Williams won their quarterfinal
matches to set up a Friday rematch of last year's US Open
semifinal.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis roared out to a quick start and held off a Monica Seles
comeback for a 6-0, 7-5 win Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night. Earlier in the day,
Williams had all kinds of problems in outlasting Nathalie Tauziat,
6-4, 1-6, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Todd Martin, expressive and excited, did the women one
better.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Martin lost the first two sets of his fourth-round
match against Greg Rusedski and turned it around, winning the match
and then going all the way to the final, where he lost to Andre
Agassi.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, Martin squandered chances early and lost a pair
of 66-minute tiebreaker sets to get Carlos Moya right where he
wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   Martin, unseeded here after a tough season, battled back to beat
Moya, 6-7 (7-3), 6-7 (9-7), 6-1, 7-6 (8-6), 6-2, in a match that
took 4 hours 15 minutes and ended at 1:19 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fine, I feel great,'' a breathless Martin told a
television audience before he left the court. ``I feel terrible,
but I feel great. It was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin broke Moya early to run away with the third set. Then he
put on a show in the fourth. He had a couple of break points to win
the set but let them slip away, and it went to another tiebreaker.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was up, 5-3, in the tiebreaker. Moya won three straight
points to get to match point on his serve at 6-5. Martin got out of
that one with a volley to set up an overhead. A service winner and
crosscourt forehand winner and they were headed to a fifth set.
</P>
<P>
   Again Martin broke Moya twice early and then, the guy who has
been known to have trouble closing out matches, closed it out.
</P>
<P>
   Moya's last forehand popped wide and Martin turned to watch it,
smashing his racket on the court and celebrating with the fans who
had stayed.
</P>
<P>
   Martin meets Thomas Johansson, ranked No. 91 in the world.
Johansson ousted qualifier Wayne Arthurs, 6-4, 6-7 (9-7), 6-3, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   No. 3 seed Magnus Norman, who barely survived his previous
match, was ousted by No. 14 seed Nicolas Kiefer, 6-2, 6-7 (7-3),
6-1, 6-3. Kiefer plays No. 6 Marat Safin, who routed Juan Carlos
Ferrero, 6-1, 6-2, 6-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis won last year's semifinal match over Venus Williams in
three sets, but then lost to Serena Williams in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Hingis was all over Seles in the first set Tuesday, getting 24
of the 30 points in the set and putting it away in 13 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really started off the match sluggishly,'' Seles said. ``I
tried to get back in it, but it was way too late. Maybe I panicked
a little and against Martina, you're not going to get any free
points.''
</P>
<P>
   Seles had her serve broken and was down, 3-1, in the second set,
but then climbed back into the match. Hingis served for the match
at 5-4 and held off five break points before Seles evened it up at
5-5.
</P>
<P>
   Seles served at 6-5 to force a tiebreaker, but Hingis broke for
the match.
</P>
<P>
   Now she'll get ready for Venus Williams, who beat Hingis in
three sets at Wimbledon on the way to the title.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams even had problems finding a seat against Tauziat.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was broken in the third set and Tauziat had a little
life at 1-4. Williams headed to the side of the court for the
changeover, went to sit down . . . and missed her chair. Bottomed
out.
</P>
<P>
   It was that kind of day on the court for Williams. Even after
putting Tauziat away for a spot in the semis for the third year in
a row, Williams had a hard time feeling good about the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had quit playing tennis like that,'' Williams
said. ``But once again . . . It's been a little while since I
played a match like that. I can't accept these type of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Can't accept the 10 double faults and the 31 unforced errors (to
2 and 21 of Tauziat). Can't accept the inconsistency. Can't accept
the lost second set when Tauziat broke her the first two times she
served, by far the worst set she's played in some time, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the fact that she won her 24th consecutive match took
a little of the sting out of the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never get upset when I'm playing,'' Williams said. ``But
today I was. It was very strange.''
</P>
<P>
   And the chair episode?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just angry,'' she said. ``I just couldn't see.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying hard not to stomp my feet, swing my racquet
around,'' Williams said. ``Some players show a lot of emotion, but
usually I don't. I'm pretty calm and collected, moving on to the
next point. That was maybe the main battle for me, why I didn't
play well also. I was too busy thinking about the points before,
not focusing ahead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
