<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0052 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 10:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3623 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-PIRACY-VICTIMS-BOS &LR;      09-06 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRACY-VICTIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH, POOR TARGETED BY MODERN BUCCANEERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PATALON, Philippines _ Joel Quino knows what it's like to walk
the plank.
</P>
<P>
   It was a sunny March afternoon, and he was fishing in a small
dinghy, a mile and half offshore from this village in the southern
Philippines. Suddenly, two masked men wielding M-1 rifles sped up
alongside in a motorized canoe and shouted, ``Ambak pare!''_ ``Jump
overboard, pal!''
</P>
<P>
   He obeyed, and in a matter of seconds, the pirates stole his
entire life savings and his means of livelihood _ a tiny boat with
an outboard engine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I going to drown,'' said Quino, 34, who was rescued
by a passing fisherman. But his problems had just begun.
</P>
<P>
   In this village of 200 subsistence fishermen and their families,
he is one of 50 victims who have lost their boats or engines to
small-time but heavily armed pirates. Every penny of the
fishermen's earnings had gone into their tiny boats, and with an
average income of $77 a month, not one believes he will ever save
$700 to buy a new boat, engine, and nets. They now borrow dinghies
from their luckier neighbors and split the catch with them 50-50.
</P>
<P>
   Victims of modern piracy come in all stripes _ from poor
fishermen who lose their livelihoods, to shipping tycoons who have
to write off multimillion-dollar tankers, to yachtsmen whose
vacations turn into nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy-eight seafarers were killed by pirates in 1998, most
of them in Asian waters,'' said Corey Bousen, publisher of Lloyd's
List Maritime Asia, a trade journal. ``If 78 Americans were
murdered on a bus in downtown Boston, you'd hear about it for 10
years. But because these killings are at sea, and most victims are
from third-world countries, nobody takes notice.''
</P>
<P>
   The maritime industry has started to mobilize, however.
Shipowners are debating the merits of hiring former soldiers to
escort or recover their ships, and some have installed hidden
tracking devices to monitor vessels if they are seajacked. Crews
are urged to keep fire hoses ready to ward off attackers, and post
sailors on round-the-clock watches on floodlit decks.
</P>
<P>
   Some captains now avoid the most dangerous waters of Indonesia
and Malaysia and the coasts of Bangladesh and Somalia. Yachtsmen
have begun to sail in convoys and skip some deserted ``paradise
isles.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Severns, a Maui-based underwater photographer and biologist
who used to lead yacht trips to remote islands, still feels a chill
when he recalls a horrifying Indonesian holiday two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He and six friends had anchored their 90-foot ironwood boat off
the island of Salajar, by the southern tip of western Sulawesi.
``We had just finished dinner,'' Severns recounted, ``and before we
knew what happened, we turned around, and instead of the crew, we
saw 12 men with handguns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the horror of piracy. You're in the middle of nowhere,
no one knows where you are, and there's no place to run. They could
have shot us, ransacked the boat and sunk it, and no one would have
known.''
</P>
<P>
   Severns talked his way out of the situation, addressing the men
as if they were maritime police conducting a search, and telling
them he worked for the national airline's flight magazine, which
seemed to impress them. ``I guess they figured robbing us could
bring a problem, and we weren't worth their while.'' But that was
far from the end of his adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, off the northern tip of Babar Island, 200
miles east of East Timor, he and five friends were doing a night
scuba dive when they were surrounded by canoes filled with
screaming attackers. Severns, the divers' guide, and the captain of
their boat were taken ashore, where the guide and the captain were
beaten nearly unconscious, while the others escaped back to the
boat.
</P>
<P>
   The attackers had heard that ``tourists are rich, and they
thought we'd have thousands of dollars lying around on deck,''
Severns said.
</P>
<P>
   Although his jaw was broken, the captain managed to escape and
swimback to the yacht. ``The last thing he saw was mobs attacking
us, and he gave the order to cut the anchor line and go to sea.
They heard cheering like a rugby match, and they thought we were
dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The yacht's mayday signal was picked up by a woman who relayed
their call for help.
</P>
<P>
   Ashore, Severns and his guide were being held by the village
chief, who wanted a ransom of 220 pounds of rice and 110 pounds of
pork. A few hours later, soldiers burst into the village hall and
rescued them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Asian economic crisis has made people desperate,'' Severns
said. ``After my two experiences, I'm pretty much trying to stick
to main islands.''
</P>
<P>
   Alternate routes aren't an option, though, for coastal fishermen
on whom piracy has taken its greatest toll. Most attacks are never
reported, out of ignorance or fear of revenge by pirates they will
see again.
</P>
<P>
   Shipmaster Rudy Gabayron, 45, has worked aboard mid-sized
Philippine fishing trawlers for 20 years, and says he cannot count
the number of times his boats have been fired upon by men in
motorized canoes demanding fish.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Navy started arming civilian guards to ride on coastal
trawlers in 1989, attacks have decreased, Gabayron said.
</P>
<P>
   But around 11 one night last October, while their guard was on
leave, five motorboats carrying 20 men surrounded the May I off
Lanhill Island, southeast of Zamboanga City, and fired shots as two
pirates jumped aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Gabayron and four others were shot in the chaos, and the pirates
carted off the ship's sonar, its radio, and crew belongings _
$11,000 worth of goods.
</P>
<P>
   In the half-light of a fluorescent bulb in the dingy,
hospital-green cabin, he lifted his shirt to reveal his bullet
wounds, and admitted he was traumatized: ``My family told me not to
keep fishing, but I have no choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
