<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 10:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3626 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-PIRACY-ASIA-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE     09-06 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRACY-ASIA-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 NEAR SACOL ISLAND, PHILIPPINES: ... seaweed farmer.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although Bungalos says he and his gang would give up piracy if
they could, these uneducated men, none of whom finished elementary
school, have little prospect of landing a good job. Bungalos, 41,
spent 15 years as a rebel fighting for autonomy for Muslims in the
largely Catholic Philippines. He attributes the poor economic
prospects here to the government's disdain for Muslims, and to
multinational and Manila-based fishing companies that ``suck all
our fish out of the ocean,'' leaving nothing for locals.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he feels remorse. He wrote a letter to the kidnapped girl's
parents asking their forgiveness, and is putting his children
through school ``so they don't follow in my footsteps.'' His wife
and their nine surviving children live in a two-room wooden shack
on stilts, with tin roof and without furniture or electricity, in a
coastal village east of Zamboanga City. Bungalos visits a couple of
times a month, when he can slip away from his outlaws' island
hideaway.
</P>
<P>
   Five members of his gang have been killed in encounters with
authorities, and his wife says she would rather have him at home
and go without food than live off pirate's loot. Bungalos says he
would endanger the whole village if he returned to society; he's a
wanted man.
</P>
<P>
   Catching him _ or any other pirate _ is harder than one might
think.
</P>
<P>
   On patrol aboard the Filipino Flojo PG-386, a US-made 78-foot
gunboat, Navy Commander H. Robert Balanon Jr. pointed out the
``Eleven Islands,'' a circle of isles that are sanctuaries for sea
bandits.
</P>
<P>
   Pirates dart from one to another, hiding among the palms as
patrols pass. In the Philippines, as in other archipelago nations
like Indonesia or Malaysia, there are simply too many islands to
monitor around the clock. The terrain confounds strangers, and
pirates often are protected by corrupt local authorities.
</P>
<P>
   A long-running Muslim uprising in the Southern Philippines has
also fed piracy, as rebels have turned to crime at sea to fund
their rebellion.
</P>
<P>
   More than four months ago, the Abu Sayyaf group used speedboats
to kidnap 21 people from a Malaysian resort; it has made millions
by ransoming them. Last week, the group seized a 24-year-old
American and held him in a hideout on Jolo Island, where they
reportedly demanded $10 million for his release.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they see the Navy, they act like good guys. When the Navy
isn't here, they're bad guys,'' Lieutenant Bonifacio Manicap said,
aiming his binoculars at rows of laundry flapping from lines on one
of the hundreds of islands on the gunboat's patrol route, and at a
handful of people on a nearly deserted beach who stared back
suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   Balanon, the commander, pointed to a tangle of brush along the
coast of Pilas Island that looked much like any other _ until a
squint of the eye revealed a tiny gap just large enough for a
canoe, opening into a hidden lagoon.
</P>
<P>
   Getting off a gunboat to pursue fleeing suspects into shallow
waters means abandoning the ship's formidable weaponry. Clambering
into an inflatable raft armed with just a .45-caliber handgun,
Manicap was understandably nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``These pirates have machine guns left over from World War II
that could sink a boat,'' he said. ``They have antitank guns. We'd
be helpless in this rubber boat if we encountered pirates now.''
</P>
<P>
   There are hundreds of ``pirate islands'' across Asia that are
simply outside the reach of the law. Balanon's gunboat is fitted
with daunting armaments _ four .50-caliber machine guns, two 7.62mm
machine guns, and a 25mm automatic cannon. But for the safety of
his crew, he refused to disembark at Siasi, known as ``Texas
Island'' because every inhabitant is reputed to carry a gun.
</P>
<P>
   Last November, two officers from a sister gunboat, PG-387,
hopped ashore to buy cigarettes and were shot 30 yards away by
bandits who then fled with their guns. It was daylight, so their
mates assumed that the noise was from firecrackers. One man died on
the spot. The other staggered back to the ship, and the crew cast
off immediately rather than risk taking him to the local clinic. He
died before they reached the nearest island with a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   A weather-beaten metal sign over Siasi's single paved road
offers a ``Welcome,'' but residents don't seem to echo the
sentiment. Idle youths scowled at the Navy ship. A young boy
fiddled with a 9mm pistol. The dusty, two-story wooden facades that
lined the port seemed straight out of a hardscrabble frontier town
in the American West. The only color breaking the monotony of brown
peeling paint was a bilious yellow adorning the local ferry and the
minarets of the mosque.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of a gunboat didn't cow several groups of armed men
who strutted under the noon sun with M-14 and M-16 assault rifles
slung across their chests. Balanon and his men stayed aboard,
conscious that they could do nothing. This was the sea bandits'
turf.
</P>
<P>
   After years of denial, Asian authorities are acknowledging that
they have a problem. Some have launched joint patrols on the most
dangerous waterways, such as the Strait of Malacca, at 500 miles
the world's longest strait, which links the Indian Ocean to the
South China Sea. Indonesia announced recently that it would
establish a center to monitor ships entering it. The maritime
industry, meanwhile, is calling for governments to adopt tougher
laws and sign international conventions against sea crime.
</P>
<P>
   Sensing a niche, security companies have cropped up in Britain,
the United States, Hong Kong, and Australia, providing former
soldiers to defend ships and to search for, and perhaps recover,
missing vessels. The services are controversial because of fears
that having armed mercenaries aboard could escalate the violence.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Maritime Bureau's Piracy Reporting Center in Malaysia has
set up a 24-hour hot line to track missing vessels, with some
success.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, it guided authorities to Global Mars, a Japanese
tanker loaded with palm oil that had been hijacked in Malaysian
waters in February, its crew set adrift. Tips gleaned by the center
indicated that the ship had been repainted and was operating near
Hong Kong as a phantom ship named Bulawan. China sent an aircraft
to investigate, and police boarded it in late May, arresting 11
Filipinos and nine Burmese. The ship was towed to the Chinese port
of Zhuhai, where the suspected pirates are awaiting prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippines is one of the first countries to try to respond
creatively to modern piracy, training and arming civilians to ride
aboard coastal fishing vessels. There are 176 such guards now, and
authorities began training more last month. Fishing captains say
the guards are a deterrent, but some vessels have been attacked
despite them. Three guards were killed in a pirate attack last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks have declined since the Philippine Navy and coast guard
boosted patrols. But actually catching any of the 22 known pirate
gangs is more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The Philippine Navy operates a decoy vessel disguised as an old
fishing trawler (armed with five machine guns) to fool pirates into
attacking. On a recent night, the boat cast off after sunset with a
team of six Philippine Navy SEAL commandos aboard, hoping to
provoke an attack near Sibago Island. But the undercover boat has
been around since the early '90s, so pirates have come to recognize
and avoid it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a cat-and-mouse game,'' said Petty Officer 3d class Rocky
Galolo. And authorities cannot easily recognize the mouse; pirates
don't look like Blackbeard with a hoop earring. ``These pirates are
ordinary people like us. We can't identify them by looking at their
faces.''
</P>
<P>
   From the safety of his mangrove-covered cove, Bungalos sees Navy
patrols at a distance almost every day. But if he has his way, they
will never see him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
