<SLUG> BC-TEN-GERIATRICS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAME, SET, MATCHLESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID ARNOLD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ They are a bionic lot, the three dozen men
who have come to the Longwood Cricket Club with titanium joints
(mostly new hips and knees) and rock-steady hearts (thanks to
pacemakers).
</P>
<P>
   Off the tennis courts, they are models of gentility and
sweetness, as great-grandfathers should be.
</P>
<P>
   But once the first ball is served, they become connoisseurs of
slow-motion torture.
</P>
<P>
   Their shots and cross-court vollies can make an opponent lunge
and stumble _ and a spectator wince at the prospect of witnessing a
heart attack on a baseline.
</P>
<P>
   This is survival of the fittest time at Longwood, otherwise
known as the annual National Grass Court Championships for men
almost a century old, vying for titles in the 85- and 90-and-older
age groups. The handouts say ``WELCOME!'' but the orthopedic
doctors who remade many of these men _ literally _ may want them to
stay away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come, now _ you'd be amazed what you can do if you put your
mind to it,'' said Paul DeCamp of New Orleans, 85, who was
diagnosed with rheumatic fever in 1940 and given a year or two to
live.
</P>
<P>
   Now a retired physician, DeCamp holds his age group's national
tennis doubles title for indoor and hard court play _ and Tuesday,
prior to a match, he was holding the left hand of Lacy, his bride
of one year. Both their first marriages had ended with the deaths
of spouses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figure I've added 10, maybe 20 years to my life playing
super senior tennis,'' added Ed Baumer of Coronado, Calif. He
picked up the sport at age 65 because he wanted a game he could
play during lunch on business trips; at the time, golf clubs didn't
fit in the airplane overhead bins.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, more than half the seniors vying for trophies at the
week-long, United States Tennis Association-sanctioned event that
began Sunday apparently never played before they were 60. Notable
exceptions include Gardnar Mulloy, 86, of Miami, America's
top-ranked player in 1952.
</P>
<P>
   But others, such as Kenneth Beer, a former pilot who is just shy
of his 97th birthday, first picked up a racquet in 1963 _ after he
retired from the former Pan American Airlines to live in
Hillsborough, Calif. Incidently, Beer first flew for the airline in
1928 _ one year after Charles Lindbergh crossed the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   Beer has been riding the leading edge of tournament play as
increasing demand from seniors has created ever-older age groups.
Longwood hosted the first Senior 70 tournament in 1973. And then
the club started adding more: the Senior 75 tournament in 1975, the
Senior 80s in 1980, the Senior 85 in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the first Senior 90s tournament began.
</P>
<P>
   Before his 11 a.m. match Tuesday, Beer began by warming up on
the backboard, hitting the ball 20 times in a minute without
letting it bounce.
</P>
<P>
   Six minutes _ and 120 errorless hits later _ he took five steps
back to start another exercise that allowed the ball to bounce just
once between hits. He took few steps, and everything else moved
slowly _ but with pinpoint accuracy and no wasted motion.
</P>
<P>
   Players say that at this age, tennis footwork is basically
reduced to a shuffle. The best shot is an unreachable one _ the
drop shot, the lob over a competitor's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ball control, not foot control,'' said one player. ``Let's cut
to the quick here. We don't have any foot control left.''
</P>
<P>
   Beer, one of six men in the tournament who are 90 years or
older, lost his 11 a.m. match to Bob Lawrence, 90, of Santa
Barbara, Calif. Lawrence, a retired business executive, climbs
mountains in Nepal and Switzerland when he is not playing tennis _
a game he picked up at age 69.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my first tournament,'' Lawrence said somewhat shyly
after his victory. ``I'm wired _ seriously. My pacemaker did
great.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
