<HEADER>
A3634 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-06 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASIC ERRORS MARRED MONDAY NIGHT OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the hype surrounding the shiny new additions to
``Monday Night Football,'' you would think the basics would be
covered.
</P>
<P>
   You know, the little stuff, like covering the game.
</P>
<P>
   Take the 86-yard punt return by Az-Zahir Hakim in Monday's
season opener between the Rams and Broncos. Instead of showing a
replay immediately, ABC showed people dancing at the refurbished
Union Station in St. Louis, then went to commercial.
</P>
<P>
   The first replay appeared shortly after the break and showed
only Hakim running downfield _ not the key blocks that created a
lane for him. Viewers had to wait longer for that, and when ABC
finally did show the replay from a different angle, viewers still
didn't get a good shot of the blocking.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did viewers get much clarity on Terrell Davis's injury. At
first, new color analyst Dan Fouts said Davis injured his right
ankle, and given that Davis had injured his right knee last year,
that was significant.
</P>
<P>
   Fouts's reporting, however, didn't match up with that of
sideline ace Melissa Stark, the former ESPN reporter, who told
viewers that Davis injured his left ankle, then followed up with
definitive word that Davis would miss the remainder of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Left, right? Who cares? Fouts tried to shrug it off by joking
that the Broncos were taping both ankles as a decoy. Who knew Fouts
was the real comedian in the booth?
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that the Patriots play the New York Jets in
next week's Monday night game. Let's see what the ABC crew does if
the game is not as exciting as the Rams-Broncos thriller. The game
received a 10.6 rating and 20 share in Boston. It peaked around 10
p.m. with a 13.7 rating and 22 share.
</P>
<P>
   Boston viewers will need more than the obvious. Viewers here
already know the Patriots don't have much of an offensive line. We
already know the running game is virtually nonexistent. And we
certainly know about the rivalry between the Jets and Patriots
since Bill Parcells left in a huff.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see how much leeway Dennis Miller has
during the broadcast, given the fact that Patriots owner Bob Kraft
is a member of the NFL's powerful broadcast committee. Let's see
how many stadium-finance jokes Miller tells. Let's see if Boston's
unique brand of politics is ripe for some of Miller's satire.
</P>
<P>
   Miller improved from his practice sessions during three
preseason games, largely because he simply shut up. Miller, the
supposed savior of the showcase game, limited his rants during
Rams-Broncos but still managed to get off a few good lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were worried that I was going to use a lot of
profanity,'' Miller said. ``But the only f-word I'm going to use is
`Faulk.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the ABC crew was helped by having an exciting
game. Play-by-play man Al Michaels is still able to define a
situation with very few wasted words. He hit the nail on the head
when he described the Rams' attack as ``speed, speed, and more
speed.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing Michaels is still in the booth. Consider the
following observation during the first quarter. Rams quarterback
Kurt Warner had thrown an interception to end a drive near the goal
line _ the pass bounced off the tight end and into the hands of
linebacker Al Wilson. Fouts opined, ``Warner threw five
interceptions in the red zone last year, and this one is not his
fault.''
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. Everyone watching the game could see that.
</P>
<P>
   Pity Michaels. He has to come through for three straight hours
with little help from his new pals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
