</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLD THE TUNA, ADD SOME SPICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ It wouldn't surprise me if they spent parts
of spring and summer practicing their answers for this week. Maybe
they stood in front of the bathroom mirror, speaking to an
imaginary press corps on how Jets-Patriots was ``just another game
on the schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe wives and children were involved. ``Sweetheart? Kids?
Could you come in here for a second? Daddy wants you to listen to
something: `Look, you guys are trying to sell papers and I
understand that. It's your job. My job is to win games. If a win
happens to come against New England, so be it. All division games
are important, and . . . Hey! What's with the snickers? I'm not
finished.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This morning, Jets coach Al Groh and Patriots coach Kevin Spacey
(a.k.a. his identical twin, Bill Belichick) will hold press
conferences in different cities, for different audiences, at
slightly different times. But they will be saying the same things.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, their teams will meet in Giants Stadium in an
event that used to be known as the Tuna Bowl. Since the Tuna, Bill
Parcells, is no longer coaching, we should call this game by its
rightful name: the Alimony Bowl. Cleaned-out divorcees cringe every
time these teams play. When Parcells and Curtis Martin divorced the
Patriots and went to the Jets, it practically cost the New Yorkers
the house. When Belichick finally divorced the Jets, the Patriots
had to part with some property _ a first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this acrimonious game has been passed on to a new
generation of leaders. Gone are Tuna and Mr. P.C., Pete Carroll. In
are Groh and Belichick, both former Parcells assistants. The new
guys may tell you that times have changed and that this game
doesn't have the same amount of venom as ones in the past. You know
what? They're right.
</P>
<P>
   What this game has is more venom than the others. By far. There
is more ill will now than in the previous six games combined.
</P>
<P>
   When the Patriots hired Belichick, Parcells said, ``The border
war is over.'' But the reality is that the border war has been
replaced with psychological warfare. It is ruthless and petty.
There is a lot of gossiping involved. There is a lot of whispering
involved. There is a lot of Deep Throat dime-dropping involved. And
there are more angry people involved than before. It used to be a
basic Parcells vs. Robert and Jonathan Kraft rift. Now that there
has been a split of the Parcells coaching family, the rift has
deepened.
</P>
<P>
   It is not a coincidence that we suddenly are seeing a videotape
of Parcells forgetting the score at the end of last season's
Patriots-Jets opener. There was the Tuna in the fourth quarter,
walking on the field, looking like the NFL's Rip Van Winkle. It was
obvious that he didn't know the score. He looked confused, which is
exactly what the anti-Parcells camp wanted people to see; that, you
know, Parcells is not infallible.
</P>
<P>
   Smart people with NFL experience should know better. There have
been more significant errors in more significant games. Mike
Holmgren lost track of the downs late in Green Bay's Super Bowl
XXXII loss to Denver. It happens.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, that's not to say Parcells is a martyr. In his book,
written with the Globe's Will McDonough, he suggested that
Belichick had a deal with the Patriots even though he was under
contract with the Jets. Parcells said he couldn't prove it, but
that was his feeling. Let's just say that the Tuna probably should
have left that section out of the book.
</P>
<P>
   If Belichick indeed had a side deal with New England while under
contract, he certainly wasn't the first to do something like that.
There are strong indications that Parcells had a deal in place with
the Jets while he was contractually bound to the Patriots in 1997.
When contacted at his office Tuesday, Parcells said he was going to
``respectfully decline to comment.'' He is expected to speak with
the New York media later this week.
</P>
<P>
   As you might imagine, both camps are downplaying their
frostiness. And there's a lot to downplay. Patriots offensive
coordinator Charlie Weis had some of his play-calling duties taken
from him by Parcells last season. Think he doesn't want to prove
something to the big guy for disrespecting him like that? Groh was
given the job by default, so he will always struggle to be visible
during the Jets' Tuna Eclipse. Belichick was head coach of the Jets
_ twice _ without ever coaching a game. He was portrayed as a nut
when he left New York, and there still isn't a good relationship
with Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Patriots, the ones who actually will be
playing in the Alimony Bowl, this has very little to do with the
game. Hard feelings or not, they still have to figure out a way to
protect their quarterback. They still have to find a running game.
They still have to overcome some of their quirks, such as a center
who goes Knoblauch on you whenever a shotgun snap is required.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots cornerback Otis Smith was asked how he thought
Belichick would approach this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll probably work the (expletive) out of us,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The coach would do that even if next week's opponent were
Minnesota or Buffalo. But that's where the similarities stop.
Patriots-Jets another division game? No extra emotion? No
pathology? Come on. I've heard that joke before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Michael Holley is a Globe columnist. He can be reached by e-mail at
holley(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
