<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 10:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3652 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-ART-DUTCH-BOS &LR;      09-06 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-DUTCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOVERING VIVID IMAGES FROM HOLLAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRISTINE TEMIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The title ``Van Gogh to Mondrian'' is slightly
misleading. With very few exceptions _ Kees van Dongen is about the
only other one _ the artists in this show at the Museum of Fine
Arts won't be familiar to the average survivor of Art History 101.
That's part of the show's charm _ discoveries to be made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Van Gogh to Mondrian: Dutch Works on Paper'' originally was
organized by Peter Schatborn for the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam,
where it was called ``Rond 1900.'' For the MFA presentation,
curator Clifford Ackley has made judicious additions from the
Boston museum's collections.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of many shows _ including ``1900: Art at the
Crossroads'' at the Guggenheim Museum in New York, and
``ModernStarts,'' which appeared earlier this year at New York's
Museum of Modern Art _ to look at what was going on at the turn of
the last century.
</P>
<P>
   Plenty was. ``Van Gogh to Mondrian'' is more focused than either
of those blockbusters, covering only works on paper from only one
country from a span of only 30 years. Still, its variety
astonishes: everything from the dark realism that automatically
says ``Dutch'' to vivid versions of Art Nouveau that don't, to
posters that prefigure the De Stijl movement.
</P>
<P>
   In his fine catalog essay, Carel Blotkamp argues that while
Dutch graphic work around 1900 looked a lot like other European
art, its uniqueness lay in its ``strong tendency to impose upon the
image a rigorous geometric order.'' The British strain of Art
Nouveau was, however, just as geometric: Liberty of London designs
will spring to the minds of many as they look at Gerrit Willem
Dijsselhof's 1898 ``Wallpaper with fava bean motif.''
</P>
<P>
   Blotkamp also points out that French Impressionism never
established much of a foothold in Holland, leaving the door open to
new styles, and that there was an emphasis on
``Gemeenschapskunst,'' or ``public art,'' which was less a matter
of personal expression and more geared toward wide dissemination of
images in monumental wall paintings, posters, and book design.
Another characteristic of Dutch art of the era was its borrowing
from ``exotic'' sources. Japanese prints had influenced European
art for decades; Dutch art, because of Holland's long trade
association with Indonesia, added that country's imagery to the
mix. Patterns reminiscent of batiks and figures that look like
shadow puppets crop up often in the MFA show.
</P>
<P>
   Except for works by artists the caliber of Van Gogh, Mondrian,
Van Dongen, and Jan Toorop, the decorative and commercial designs
outweigh the ``fine'' arts in the show. Toorop moved between both
worlds. His poster for ``Delftsche Slaolie,'' a salad oil, became
so famous that Dutch Art Nouveau was dubbed the ``salad oil
style.'' Aubrey Beardsley's influence is evident in Toorop's
swirling line that threatens to camouflage the actual subject.
You're so engulfed by the endless whiplash curves that describe the
hair and billowing dresses of the two women in the work that you
hardly notice that one of them is indeed tossing a salad, and that
the peanuts from which the oil is made appear in a heraldic square
in the upper left.
</P>
<P>
   Toorop had a Symbolist side as well, in compositions such as the
1892 ``O Grave, Where Is Thy Victory?'' in which two attenuated
angels untie the brambles _ i.e. the earthly cares _ of a corpse
about to be laid to rest, as nasty monsters try in vain to claw at
the lifeless figure.
</P>
<P>
   Johan Thorn Prikker's drawing of ``Three Figures (Singing
Trees),'' a trio of ethereal and elongated women, and Matthew
Maris's black chalk ``Peace,'' a pair of misty figures on the verge
of evaporating, are further examples of the mystical strain in
Dutch art. So is Edzard Willem Koning's ``Virgin and Child Seated
in a Landscape,'' ensconced in a garden of sunflowers and
hollyhocks. Simple, sincere, and symmetrical, the work owes much to
Gauguin and the School of Pont Aven.
</P>
<P>
   On the more commercial side are illustrated calendars, posters
for entertainments, and book and magazine covers, which use some of
the same design tactics to a very different end. Johann Georg van
Caspel's poster advertising the first issue of the journal ``De
Hollandsche Revue'' is a rhythmic row of seated men, all bent over
the same publication; more copies lie in a reading rack in front of
them, just in case. Theodoor van Hoytema's 1893 version of Hans
Christian Andersen's ``The Ugly Duckling'' is densely illustrated
and has a Japanese feel, with the ducks' feathers all subdued into
scallops. Dutch art has been enamored of flora and fauna for
centuries, and that interest only intensified around 1900. Samuel
Jessurun de Mesquita's 1913 woodcut ``Egret'' is an eye-fooling
play of lines that remind you that Mesquita was the teacher of M.C.
Escher.
</P>
<P>
   The most beautiful flower in the show is Mondrian's 1909-'10
watercolor ``Golden-Rayed Lily,'' which is shown twice: once in the
prime of its life, petals flaring, stamens jabbing; then as limp as
a used tissue. Both are suspended in an aquatic, blue-dappled,
pointillist atmosphere. It's a trio of Mondrian tree pieces,
though, hung together, that is the show's high point. The three go
from a luscious watercolor of foliage reflected in water to a 1911
black chalk ``Tree'' that edges toward abstraction. Structure
reigns supreme in both, with branches expanding to fill the page,
as if they wanted to rule as much space as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The small number of van Gogh works in the show is something of a
disappointment. (The reason the Dutch drawing show is in the MFA in
the first place is to accompany ``Van Gogh: Face to Face,''
thepainting show upstairs.) The drawing show pieces range from the
straggly backyard of the 1882 ``Nursery Garden, The Hague'' to the
vertiginous ``Landscape With Houses Behind Trees,'' an Auvers
drawing from 1890, the year the artist died.
</P>
<P>
   Van Dongen was born near Rotterdam but spent most of his working
life in Paris, and his Fauve style looks like nothing else in this
show. ``Belly Dancer'' is an exercise in hedonism, the exuberantly
half-nude figure stretching her arms sideways and tossing her head
to one side, basking in a shadowy halo of pink.
</P>
<P>
   Scenes of urban life by George Hendrik Breitner and Isaac
Lazarus Israels are dark and pedestrian, outmoded in comparison to
the rest of the show. Their work carries little indication that the
40 Dutch artists in the exhibition lived at a time of sea changes
in art, some constituting brave manifestos. Toorop, for instance,
created a visual call to arms in his 1893 colored chalk drawing
``Pattern of lines. Rise of the new art, meeting resistance.'' But
for some reason he kept it mum, not exhibiting the work during his
lifetime, then leaving it to his widow. (It's now in the collection
of the Gemeentemuseum in The Hague.) Its complex imagery is typical
of Toorop. A four-legged creature, with four female torsos blowing
trumpets, tramples on the prone figure of the old, traditional art.
One of the most fascinating aspects of the picture, in addition to
its bizarre fairy-tale invention, is that it continues right onto
its carved wooden frame, as if Toorop were continuing one of the
main movements of the time _ the union of art and craft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
