<HEADER>
A3653 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-STAGE-GOREY-BOS &LR;      09-06 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAGE-GOREY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASTER OF THE WEIRD, ARTIST EDWARD GOREY IS MISSED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
By ELLEN BARRY 
c.2000 The Boston Globe 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COTUIT, Mass. _ The black canvas backdrop of the Dismal Swamp
has rolled silently out, a thumbtack has been stuck into the hammer
of each piano key for a creepy, off-kilter sound, the tiny
white-faced puppet is being stalked across the stage by a looming
character named Ooze, but Edward Gorey is not in the house.
</P>
<P>
   When Gorey, Cape Cod's most famous eccentric artist, died
suddenly in April at the age of 75, he left a few clues about his
intentions with regard to ``The White Canoe,'' the 13-act puppet
opera now playing at Freedom Hall.
</P>
<P>
   There was, for instance, the small triangular stone that he
mailed to the composer in Frankfurt, with the one-line instruction,
``The more attention given this stone, the more likely it is to
turn back into a frog.''
</P>
<P>
   There were cryptic notations on scraps of paper found among his
things, with messages like ``Spirits of the swamp: insects: Loie
Fuller sleeves,'' and, on one, ``Alligators have tails.''
</P>
<P>
   As opening night approached, director Carol Verburg threw up her
hands at guessing what Gorey would have wanted, even though she had
worked alongside him in staging his plays on the Cape for the last
12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Recalling her efforts to decode ``Loie Fuller sleeves'' _ her
research revealed that Fuller was a turn-of-the-century dancer
renowned for her diaphanous costumes and not much else _ Verburg
looked down at her teacup as if for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, I'm the director,'' said Verburg. ``What do I do with
this?''
</P>
<P>
   After 40 years' worth of verse and drawings won him a reputation
for intriguing obscurity, Gorey's theatrical productions on the
Cape marked a sharp turn in the direction of pure bafflement.
</P>
<P>
   Having reached his widest audience with his illustrations for
the opening credits to PBS's ``Mystery!'' series, Gorey spent his
last years like a semi-retiree, free to follow his impulses with
little regard for what the public thought, said Andreas Brown of
New York's Gotham Book Mart, an executor of Gorey's estate.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every summer for a decade, vacation theatergoers primed
for ``Brigadoon'' might find themselves faced with a dramatic
reading of Isaac Newton's Latin exercise book or a full-length
performance of Oscar Wilde's ``Salome'' featuring a muscular man in
the role of the Biblical temptress. When Gorey transferred his
attention to the nearly featureless three-fingered puppets he
called Le Theatricule Stoique, the conventions of plot and
character development went out the window. So much so that even
Brown sometimes pleaded with Gorey to be just a little less
cryptic.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, Gorey's actors stopped being surprised when half
the audience left during intermission. The motley crew of amateurs
who stuck with him _ a letter carrier, a nursery-school teacher and
a former soap opera actress, among others _ stopped minding. But
this summer, as the actors? performers strain on tiptoe behind the
puppet theater, the absence of the man who was both creator and
single essential audience member has left them that much more in
the dark.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us were in service to Edward's vision,'' said Jane
MacDonald, 49, who began working with Gorey eight years ago when
she and her husband bought a motel on Route 6A. ``We knew a lot of
people walked away saying `What was that about?' Sometimes it
didn't add up to anything on an emotional curve or any other kind
of curve. I mean, it didn't have a beginning, a middle and an end.
But we knew what Edward wanted. Whether or not they got it, it was
like, `Oh, well, he's here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For the 25 years he spent in Yarmouthport, in a 200-year-old
house piled with books and metal tools, Gorey proved fairly
effective at ignoring his fame, politely whisking away admirers.
His talents were focused locally, on such low-profile projects as a
poem in honor of a neighbor's amputated toe. (``Alack! Alas!/It's
come to pass/His left big toe/Has had to go,'' it read in part, and
was illustrated with a toe that had sprouted angel's wings.)
</P>
<P>
   When his puppet troupe traveled to Los Angeles for its first
out-of-town tour two summers ago, Gorey shuddered at the thought of
leaving Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
   But in the months since his death, overseas newspaper homages
and new translations have made it clear that interest in Gorey is
far from local and far from abating. For now, enough written work
exists to satisfy that hunger, Brown said; buried in his nest of
papers, executors have found between 75 and 100 unillustrated texts
and six complete books.
</P>
<P>
   High on the list of works that may have depended on Gorey's
presence, though, are the strange little plays, which seemed to
develop spontaneously: a New Orleans-style funeral procession of
puppets carrying peacock feathers, hatpins or surgical instruments;
a white-on-white puppet kabuki show that ``just put you into a
trance,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Richards, 49, a broad, bearded nursery-school teacher who
became one of Gorey's favorite amateur actors, recalled one puppet
show cast entirely with painted clothespins, and how Gorey rebuked
the puppeteers for just moving them ``up and down and side to
side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Edward, they're clothespins!'' they protested. But before long
the clothespins did seem to bend.
</P>
<P>
   Others recalled how words that came up by chance would find
their way into scripts, so that an ingredient in a Nantucket
Nectars drink would suddenly resurface as a dog named ``Citrus
Cloud Emulsion.'' Eventually, said Richards, Gorey's actors learned
not to memorize their lines too early.
</P>
<P>
   That process may be possible without him, Brown said, or it may
not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carol's very brave to step into the breach and make this into
a reality without any guidance from Edward,'' said Brown. ``They're
all going to be trying to second-guess. I'm just hopeful that it's
going to work.''
</P>
<P>
   A dress rehearsal for ``The White Canoe'' featured a clutter of
disembodied heads, egg-beater props and one singer napping with a
tiny proscenium arch over her head. The show itself, with its
ballet-dancing alligators and doomed, swamp-bound lovers (``Did
you, my dearest, hear a sound?/I think it came from underground'')
could not be mistaken for another man's work.
</P>
<P>
   And only the performers miss Gorey's sardonic ``No, dear,'' or
``Less, please,'' or, echoing his idol, the choreographer George
Balanchine, ``I want as less as possible.'' Perhaps most noticeably
missing is his gasping laugh, their only gauge of success, although
the puppeteers, jostling each other in a pool of light behind the
stage, still listen for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``What strikes me, and what's been striking to me all along, is
that everything we do points to his absence,'' said Eric Edwards, a
tall, craggy man of 53 who works a rural mail route in Mashpee.
``The show should be wonderful and funny. Nobody should be able to
discern the difference between Edward having directed it and not,
but for the people involved, I can speak about what I feel, and
what I feel is the absence of Edward.''
</P>
<P>
   Already, this production of ``The White Canoe'' runs the risks
of a sentimentality that Gorey might have kept at a distance. The
lush backdrop was painted by veteran set designers Herbert Senn and
Helen Pond, Yarmouthport neighbors who were fully aware, Senn said,
that Gorey himself would have stuck with the three dessicated
desiccated wooden doors he usually used for a stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We miss him acutely,'' the program notes read, and many in the
opening night audience seemed to know they were attending an elegy.
, packed with worshipful friends and fans, came prepared for an
elegy.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to make you miss the days when the audience walked
out, said Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a kind of cool thing about being this avant-garde and
not-very-much-watched and not-very-much-paid-attention-to thing.
You know what we got out of it? We got 11, 12 years of Edward,''
said Edwards. ``All that time spent with a freaking genius.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, smiling: ``And not just an ordinary genius.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1040EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
