<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3656 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-PIRACY-CHINA-BOS &LR;      09-06 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PIRACY-CHINA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CRITICISM, CHINA CRACKS DOWN ON PIRATES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SHANWEI, China _ There was no SOS signal, no storm, no sighting
of a sinking ship. A 14,000-ton freighter just vanished into thin
air.
</P>
<P>
   On Nov. 16, 1998, the Cheung Son, a Hong Kong-owned cargo ship
loaded with furnace slag, lost contact with its owners en route
from Shanghai to Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, a horrified fisherman near this southern
Chinese port pulled up his net to find a bound corpse, its mouth
taped shut and lashed to a 175-pound metal bar. It was the first of
10 bodies found tangled in nets in the following weeks, all later
determined to be among the 23 members of the Cheung Son's crew. The
ship itself was never seen or heard from again.
</P>
<P>
   A long coastline, a booming and increasingly deregulated
economy, and powerful organized crime networks have made southern
China a hub for the most serious form of modern piracy: the
hijacking of entire cargo ships, which are repainted, renamed, and
used to troll for fresh victims at sea. With the crew disposed of
and the ship under a new flag, the pirates advertise these ghost
vessels as legitimate cargo carriers and then disappear with the
cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1999, China has cracked down, devoting hundreds of
police officers in dozens of cities to solving six of the most
serious cases of modern piracy. Chinese courts have dealt harshly
with the perpetrators.
</P>
<P>
   After the capture of scores of Chinese, Indonesian, Burmese, and
Filipino suspects _ and the well-publicized execution this year of
14 of them _ robberies in the South China Sea have nosedived, and
murders during high seas attacks have dropped off to nearly zero,
according to international figures.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese crackdown has begun to quiet earlier accusations
that Beijing was soft on crime at sea or even colluding with the
perpetrators. The charges were leveled following a series of
hijackings by pirates wearing Chinese law enforcement uniforms and
a case in which Chinese authorities seized a ghost ship but later
released its crew.
</P>
<P>
   One outspoken critic _ Captain Pottengal Mukundan, director of
the International Maritime Bureau _ now praises Chinese authorities
for sending ``a clear signal to these gangs that they shouldn't
bring their cargo to China.''
</P>
<P>
   In the only interviews granted to foreign media on the subject,
Chinese police sketched the dramatic trail that led to those
responsible for the disappearance of the ship Cheung Son, the most
brutal case of piracy in modern Chinese history.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 2, 1998, the ship's owners reported that they had lost
contact with the ship two weeks earlier, when it was off the coast
of Kaohsiung, Taiwan. Authorities issued an international
all-points bulletin and called the ship's phone and fax repeatedly.
Someone answered, but kept hanging up.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clubbed and bound bodies began turning up near
Shanwei, a port at nearly the same longitude as Kaohsiung. Police
hit the docks and learned that a local man ``went to sea and came
back with a lot of money and a dented boat,'' said Ni Baodui,
deputy director of the Shanwei Public Security Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Police combed nearby ports for suspicious craft and hit pay dirt
in Dongshan, in the neighboring province of Fujian. Authorities
secretly boarded a boat and found a 30-foot-long scratch with paint
from another vessel. A lab test confirmed that it matched the paint
of the Cheung Son.
</P>
<P>
   In early January 1999, police tracked down the owner of the
dented boat, who was hiding in a fishing village not far from
Shanwei. He admitted he had lent his vessel to two other men and
said they could be found in Shenzhen, a seedy, freewheeling area
next to Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Three hundred police officers raided a karaoke bar where gang
members were celebrating and surrounded the two ringleaders,
tackling one in a football-style pileup when he tried to buy a
train ticket to escape.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian leader of the gang told authorities he was paid
$350,000 for the ship and cargo by his boss, an Indonesian named
Roger who worked for a Singapore shipping company. He couldn't say
where the freighter was, and police were unable to track down
Roger. Li said Indonesian authorities ignored numerous requests for
help from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of interrogation, authorities learned that the
Cheung Son gang members or their alleged kingpin had been involved
in at least three other high-profile pirate attacks, a break that
led to the arrest of 22 suspects in the Sept. 9, 1998, attack on
the Luisa, a Singapore-based palm oil tanker.
</P>
<P>
   Li Xiaoping, head of the organized crime task force for
Guangdong province _ a bureau that devoted all of last year to
piracy investigations _ said police discovered that the pirates had
disguised themselves as officials to get onto ships for bogus
inspections. A celebratory photograph taken by the Cheung Son
culprits showed them wearing fatigues.
</P>
<P>
   Li said the crackdown does not mean that China will flout the
law to prosecute pirates. He cited the case of the Tenyu _ a ship
carrying aluminum ingots that was hijacked in Indonesia and found
off southern China, renamed Sanei I. The Indonesian crew was
released last June after six months of investigation, Li said,
because they insisted they had been hired legitimately and had no
idea that Sanei I or its cargo had been stolen. Police could not
prove them wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't have enough evidence, we can't just hold people,''
Li said. Authorities now believe that the pirates hired the crew to
sail the ghost ship and that the mastermind was the same man who
plotted the seizure of the Cheung Son. Tenyu's original crew of 15
has never been found and are assumed dead.
</P>
<P>
   In January, 12 men convicted of murdering the Cheung Son's crew
and the owner of the boat they hired to carry out the crime were
sentenced to death in a heavily publicized trial in Shanwei.
Nineteen others received prison terms, and six were acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre scene shown across China, the convicted murderers
staggered drunkenly before the firing squad singing, ``Go, go, go!
Ale, Ale, Ale!'' _ the refrain from Ricky Martin's World Cup theme
song.
</P>
<P>
   Li said the tough sentences were intended to send a message.
``With the open economy, there is more and more shipping through
China, and those waters should be safe,'' he said. ``It is not just
our duty; we want to crack down on piracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
