u f BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS &LR;      09-06 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE INVESTMENT PLAN WORKS, BUT NEEDS TO BE MORE SYSTEMATIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I feel I have not made a very wise decision. In October, I
invested $1,000 in a mutual fund to help with my grandson's
education. I contributed $250 more through random investments of
$50 each. The latest statement shows 63 shares, no dividends, and
capital gains distributions of $7.18. I'll continue the $50
contributions for as long as possible. Should I stay with my plan?
</P>
<P>
   S.C., San Diego
</P>
<P>
   A. I don't think you made a mistake at all. Even though this
year hasn't been a terrific one for stock funds, the current value
of your investment is $1,363 and change. If you had put $1,000 into
a CD account paying 5 percent 10 months ago, and added $25 a month
(for the same total investment of $1,250), the balance would be
$1,296.
</P>
<P>
   It is reasonable to expect that over the next 14 years the stock
market will have spurts, both positive and negative, and will do
what it has been doing for most of this year, which is go nowhere,
by and large. But it is also reasonable to expect that in the long
run you will get returns of about 10 percent. If that happens, and
if you continue adding at the current rate, which I calculate at
about $300 a year, the account would grow to $14,591 by the time
your grandson is 17 _ a handsome start toward paying for college.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing I suggest you change is the pattern of your
contributions. When you say they have been random, it suggests to
me that you have been adding when the fund seems to be doing
better, and probably holding back when it's been in the doldrums.
That's only human, but the inevitable result is that you're missing
the chance to buy the cheapest shares. Set a schedule for
contributions, and stick to it _ regardless of the state of the
market. In your case, this might work out to a plan to send $50 on
the first day of every month. The odds are strong that this
discipline would return better results than investing at random.
</P>
<P>
   You chose a solid fund, rated above-average by Morningstar
Mutual Funds. Its year-to-date return of 5.29 percent compares
favorably to the 4.9 percent return for the median fund in the same
investment category _ holding the stocks of large companies that
represent a blend of growth and value orientation. I suggest you
stick with the plan.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I had to retire in 1985, with heart problems and cancer, and
liquidate my business. All I wanted to do was provide for a
dignified lifestyle for my wife, who was unsophisticated in
financial matters and came from a very long-lived family. I put
everything into Treasury bills and annuities _ about $2.5 million
worth at that time. Everything would have worked out fine _ except
I didn't die! We lived comfortably on an income of about $100,000
and even distributed money to our grandchildren for college
expenses from time to time. My problem is that the pile is
shrinking. Interest rates on Treasuries no longer support our
lifestyle, inflation is growing, and increasingly we are cutting
into the fully taxable annuities, creating higher tax bills and
shrinking the pile even faster. We have started to cut back on
expenses, but my concerns for the dignified lifestyle for my wife
are growing again. What would you suggest I do with the $485,000 in
cash?
</P>
<P>
   A.L., Onset, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. My suggestion would be to look at alternatives not only for
the $485,000 now in money markets, but for all of your savings.
Inflation has dug severely into the buying power of your money.
From 1985 until last year _ the latest for which statistics are
available _ inflation raised the price of $100,000 worth of goods
and services to $154,800. Estimating the average yield of your
current holdings at 5 percent, you are generating a yield of
$80,500, putting you $74,300 in the hole each year.
</P>
<P>
   If your savings were earning the current highest rate for
five-year jumbo CDs, 7.71 percent, your yield would be $124,131,
meaning you would be dipping into your capital at only $30,669 a
year. If you maintained withdrawals at that $154,800 annual rate,
the pool would last you or your wife 21 years.
</P>
<P>
   But you're going to have to do some work to get close to that
yield, establishing many CD accounts, and most of them at
institutions you've probably never heard of. Nonetheless, these
relatively new banking institutions do enjoy the protection of FDIC
insurance up to $100,000 for an individual account.
</P>
<P>
   The best tool for tracking them down is the computer. If you
have not gotten into the world of computers, find a friend who has
and ask him to go to one of the many Web sites that list the
highest current interest rates and the institutions' toll-free
phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   I use bankrate.com. As this is written, it lists the highest
rates ranging from that 7.71 percent at the leading institution to
7.22 percent at the 16th highest. (The full list of the top 30
rates finished with five institutions offering a flat 7 percent
yield.) These rates contrast to a national average of 6.34 percent
for five-year jumbos, so it is well worth doing the work to get the
top rates, especially with sums as large as yours.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
