<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0063 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3660 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-RAYTHEON-UNION-BOS &LR;      09-06 1703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-UNION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THANKS TO THE BOOMING US ECONOMY, IT'S LABOR'S DAY AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Passing around cups of water as the sun pounded the picket
line outside Raytheon Co.'s Lexington, Mass. headquarters last
week, workers complained bitterly of shifting job assignments,
layoffs, and shrinking paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bruno, whose grandmother started working for the company in
1946, said she felt betrayed by a $4 hourly wage cut after his old
job, as a plater, moved to Austin, Texas, and he began assembling
radar and missile components for Raytheon.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Minasian, who once built and tested circuits, was bumped
down to a job providing few challenges and paying $150 a week less.
And Sharon McNulty, who has transferred among a half-dozen Raytheon
plants in Massachusetts during 22 years with the company, frets
about paying $76 each month to test her pacemaker battery since
Raytheon terminated health benefits for strikers three days after
they walked out.
</P>
<P>
   The angry voices of Local 1505 of the International Brotherhood
of Electrical Workers sing discordant notes as the economy
continues to hum along. But this summer has seen several
well-publicized strikes, as workers seek to use the leverage of a
tight labor market to wring concessions from companies after years
of declines in both union membership and clout.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't escaped Raytheon workers that friends who had been
laid off by the company in recent years were snapped up by other
employers like Amtrak or M/A-Com and Alpha Industries, both growing
wireless communication companies.
</P>
<P>
   As striking Raytheon veteran Cathy Stanton says: ``Everything is
so good out there, and we're going backward.''
</P>
<P>
   The Raytheon walkout is the first against the defense contractor
since 1966. The company has offered a 14.7 percent pay increase
over the life of a four-year contract. But members of Local 1505,
which has declined from 10,000 workers in 1990 to 2,700 today, say
they are holding out for greater job security at the defense
contractor's manufacturing operation.
</P>
<P>
   With the economy helping them, other workers around the country
are scoring successes. Some unions are negotiating favorable
contracts with employers, such as Verizon Communications and
General Motors Corp., which fear work stoppages while US sales are
strong and global competition is fierce. In other successes, nurses
who went out on strike in Massachusetts put limits on mandatory
overtime. Food processors in the South won full health benefits
under newly negotiated contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Organizing drives in recent years have brought a union to
janitors in California, hotel employees in Las Vegas, and doctors
and service workers nationwide. Organized labor has even cut a path
into Arkansas-based Wal-Mart Stores Inc., a bastion of
antiunionism: Twelve meatcutters in a Texas store joined the United
Food and Commercial Workers International in February.
</P>
<P>
   Union membership in the private sector surged in 1999 by 96,000,
to nearly 9.4 million. It was the second year in the past decade
that union representation in the private sector has risen after
years of decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hemorraghing has stopped,'' said Tom Juravich, director of
the Labor Relations and Research Center at the University of
Massachusetts at Amherst. ``We're not seeing the long, drawn-out
defeats that we saw for labor in the 1980s. Unions are taking a
much more strategic approach to bargaining and organizing.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be a stretch to declare labor will prevail over
corporate America, where union membership has plunged from 36
percent of all private-sector employees in 1953 to just 9 percent
today. Labor's gains have been incremental, even with a
labor-friendly administration in the White House. A new worry for
labor leaders is a fast-growing sector of the economy _ high
technology _ that is nearly devoid of union influences.
</P>
<P>
   But in industries tied to union labor, employers seem eager to
reach faster, more favorable settlements and ensure that assembly
lines keep running.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors, which is reporting record sales of trucks and
sport utility vehicles, did not stop at a 3 percent wage increase
for auto workers in a contract with the United Auto Workers last
year. The company also agreed to cost-of-living adjustments and
equal pay for members employed at a parts unit that had been spun
off by the company.
</P>
<P>
   The union also won strong guarantees that GM would not close or
spin off plants employing UAW members. The company even agreed to
beef up pay for laid-off workers, said Douglas Fraser, who was the
UAW's president from 1977 to 1983.
</P>
<P>
   ``The auto workers probably have more bargaining power than they
ever had. You have bargaining power when you have the ability to
shut a company down and keep them down,'' Fraser said. Global
competition has made auto makers even more vulnerable, he added,
``so the balance of power has shifted a bit in favor of the
union.''
</P>
<P>
   This summer, workers at Verizon (formerly Bell Atlantic)
capitalized on the company's fears that a strike would disrupt
customer service or allow competitors to move in. A contract was
negotiated in just two weeks, after 85,000 telephone workers from
Maine to Virginia walked off the job Aug. 6 due to the expiration
of a two-year pact.
</P>
<P>
   In a contract that workers called ``path-blazing,'' members of
IBEW and the Communications Workers of America won new rights to
organize workers in the company's expanding wireless division,
which grew out of Bell's merger with GTE. In a watershed provision,
the contract allows wireless workers on the East Coast to become
part of the union if 55 percent sign union application cards. These
card checks, prevalent during the 1930s, are extremely unpopular
with corporate management because they are an easier route to
organizing than a full-blown union vote, which can be challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ``The union came out on top with Verizon. They won the big
issues. They reduced the company's opposition to the organization
of the wireless workers,'' said Paul Osterman, a professor in the
Sloan School of Management at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology.
</P>
<P>
   The short strike was a hardship for Verizon workers, who
received only $200 from the union's strike fund. But Kathy
McGreevey, a mother of two and treasurer for CWA Local 1400 in
Portsmouth, N.H., the primary representative for telephone service
representatives in New England, said it was easier to hold out
knowing that, ``in this market, we can get jobs. We can wait for
the contract to be up to our standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Such bold attitudes are in stark contrast to labor's dog days in
the 1980s when President Reagan fired striking air traffic
controllers (1981) and George A. Hormel &AMP; Co. declared war on
striking workers in a small Minnesota town (1985) and hired
permanent replacements. Unlike Hormel's strikers, today's workers
have ``less fear of the employer resorting to the use of permanent
strike replacements,'' said Steve Early, a national representative
for CWA International.
</P>
<P>
   The longer the US economy continues to expand, said Leo Troy,
labor expert at Rutgers University in Newark, the more workers will
``feel they have a good future and need not worry about economic
dislocations, including what would happen in the event of a strike.
This should benefit unions in one sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Troy, nevertheless, believes unions will fail to reverse their
shrinking presence in corporate America even if the boom continues.
For example, a strong economy, in another way, works against union
organizing efforts, he said, because nonunion workers have
``confidence that they don't need a union. That's the other side of
the coin people forget to look at.''
</P>
<P>
   As unions deteriorated, so did their ability to preserve wages.
According to new data from the Economic Policy Institute, a liberal
Washington think tank, in 1978 blue-collar workers' wages were
nearly 27 percent above nonunion workers' pay. Today, that premium
has fallen to 22 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Haynes, president of the AFL-CIO in Massachusetts, said
that's why the Verizon strike was significant for all workers.
``The labor movement finally figured out we've got to get these new
workers and new technologies.''
</P>
<P>
   In the South, the United Food and Commercial Workers has
campaigned successfully on behalf of low-paid workers in the
grocery and food industries. In a drive to improve members' health
benefits, the union staged several strikes against grocery store
operators during the late 1990s. In another victory, UFCW secured
health benefits for the first time for members in the South,
including catfish processors in Mississippi and nursing home
workers in Alabama, said union spokesman Greg Denier. Bucking the
overall trend in corporate America, Denier said his union's
membership has grown steadily, from about 1.3 million in 1990 to
1.42 million currently.
</P>
<P>
   The food industry, in Denier's view, has a strong ally in the
tight labor market. Employers, particularly grocery stores, often
thwart labor's efforts to organize by ``churning'' workers, pushing
older workers out and hiring young ones. ``As labor markets
tighten, you see employers begin to realize that if they turn over
employees, there'll be no one else to hire for the job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For striking Raytheon workers, whose average age is 45, the
benefits of a tight labor market go only so far.
</P>
<P>
   Local 1505 members have skills _ they do precision work
involving wafers and circuit boards _ in heavy demand by, for
example, the booming telecommunications industry in New England.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a tinge of bravado in their claims they could find
work elsewhere. In truth, many are insecure that they would need
additional education or training. None wants to sacrifice hard-won
seniority, vacations, and pay that averages between $30,000 and
$40,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   So a decision to strike was difficult for Mark Bruno, a divorced
father whose two children were covered under his health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But ``that's where we're at,'' he said. ``We've made the
decision to go out and get other jobs if we have to.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
