<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-OUTSOURCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYTHEON WORKERS DRAW A LINE OVER SUBCONTRACTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
  Raytheon Co. says it doesn't understand why manufacturing
employees walked off their jobs last week. Union officials are
trying to explain their concerns by picketing in front of the
company's old plant in Quincy, Mass.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once it produced microelectronic parts at the plant for radar
systems and commercial goods. Raytheon still needs the parts, but
now it buys them from a New York-based company, Imrex LLC, which
acquired Raytheon's production machines last year and moved them
away from the unionized work force.
</P>
<P>
   The deal eventually will eliminate nearly 300 jobs, just one
round of cuts as Raytheon turns over manufacturing work to a
growing network of mostly nonunion subcontractors. These companies
generally pay employees less than $40,000 a year, the average wage
of members of the striking union, Local 1505 of the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers.
</P>
<P>
   The union represents most of the company's blue-collar work
force in Massachusetts, and a decade ago it had around 10,000
members. Today it has just 2,700 as Raytheon follows the lead of
other companies, such as Lucent Technologies and Cisco Systems.
Both have sent their stock values soaring by turning over the heavy
lifting to so-called ``contract manufacturers'' such as Jabil
Circuit Inc. of St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Last year Jabil moved in to an abandoned Raytheon factory in
Billerica, Mass., where it now employs 500 people. ``Companies are
now discovering that it's cheaper for us to manufacture their
goods,'' said spokeswoman Lisa Allison.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon executives won't discuss their outsourcing strategy,
except to call it ``a function of being competitive.'' But in past
interviews chief executive Daniel Burnham and others have made it
clear the company wants to emphasize its white-collar projects, to
keep up with growing military demands for advanced software and
computer chips.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said it fell 1,000 people short of its hiring goals for
technical specialists last year, contributing to a decline in
earnings forecasts and a resulting drop in its stock price to
roughly a third of the high it reached last year.
</P>
<P>
   Striking workers, meanwhile, point to nearly a dozen examples of
manufacturing and assembly work sent away, they say to avoid union
pay scales.
</P>
<P>
   On its Web site, Local 1505 cites circuit-card assembly work
done by Group Technologies Corp. in Tampa, Fla., and sheet-metal
work by Pneumafil Corp. in Charlotte, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In Quincy, striker Norman Eldeb described recent visits by
executives from a Kentucky company, Lexel Imaging Systems,
interested in buying equipment that Eldeb operates to make
cathode-ray tubes. The components are still sold as spare parts for
aging computer systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``They must think we're going to teach them how to operate this
equipment, so they can take away some of our last jobs,'' said
Eldeb. The visit, he said, helped convince him to vote to strike.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance the job action might seem reckless, since Local
1505's strike fund amounts to just $59 a member.
</P>
<P>
   On the central issue of job security, Raytheon says the strikers
can't realistically demand more than the company's offer of a
four-year contract, including pay raises averaging 3.5 percent and
guarantees that at least four missile and radar programs will
remain in Massachusetts during that period. Raytheon says it pays
the workers 25 percent more than the average local wage, and that
voluntary attrition is less than 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The only guarantees over the long run, Raytheon says, come from
satisfying customers such as the Pentagon. Besides, said spokesman
David Polk, ``The profile of manufacturing has changed dramatically
in this region.''
</P>
<P>
   But many union members are convinced their jobs are doomed
eventually unless they extract firmer commitments now.
</P>
<P>
   With many members due to receive pensions in five to seven
years, the strike seems rational even though the company's specific
offer ``wasn't the worst thing in the world,'' said striker Ed
Staats, a technician at Raytheon's big plant in Andover.
</P>
<P>
   But subcontracting worries him, he said. ``Basically why we're
standing here is to bring this to a head, rather than get kicked
out one at a time,'' said Staats, 56, a Raytheon employee for 34
years.
</P>
<P>
   A Group Technologies representative confirmed that the company
does work for Raytheon, but declined to elaborate, citing a
confidentiality agreement between the companies. Executives from
Pneumafil and Lexel didn't return telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Imrex president Harry Armon said he didn't want to discuss the
equipment purchased from Raytheon or the new locations of the gear.
``I've very hesitant to say much, given that Raytheon's on
strike,'' he said. ``I don't want to get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   By sending its work out, Raytheon saves about $3 an hour per
worker, estimates the Associated Industries of Massachusetts, a
trade group. The group says lower costs also have helped to attract
other manufacturers to the state, such as Solectron Corp., which
employs about 1,200 workers in Westborough. Charlie Richardson,
director of a labor extension program at the University of
Massachusetts at Lowell, says that companies can save as much as $5
an hour by avoiding unions.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson also notes that big manufacturing unions have done
little to organize new members in recent years. Only this year did
Local 1505 hire an organizer to leaflet companies such as Jabil.
</P>
<P>
   Quietly, the right to organize these facilities also has become
a key issue in the strike. Union leaders want Raytheon to remain
neutral during organizing drives at outside plants, while the
company fears that could lead to higher costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some employers say the Raytheon workers have waited too long
before trying force their employer's hand. Carol Shibles, owner of
Central Metal Finishing Inc. in North Andover, Mass., said orders
from Raytheon have increased in recent years even as it has moved
to cut costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider myself to be a small business, and we have to be
more productive and more competitive than we would be within the
walls of a big company,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Central Metal, which did about $5 million in revenue last year,
is a nonunion shop with 70 employees who are paid an average of $10
to $12 a hour. Since the strike began, several Local 1505 members
have applied for jobs at Central Metal, seeking to be paid around
$20 an hour as inspectors. Shibles said she might pay $15 to $17 an
hour and expects the union members might accept. Currently, she
said, ``They're at a premium.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1048EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
