   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAT-DNA (San Francisco) _ Impressed by cases in which cat hair
has helped solve crimes, the federal government is bankrolling a
two-year, $265,000 project to develop a national database of
genetic information from cats. Scientists and the U.S. Department
of Justice are asking volunteers to send samples of their cats' DNA
to a federal laboratory near Washington. By KEAY DAVIDSON.
</P>
<P>
   DENTIST-ADS (San Francisco) _ If you're a dentist who advertises
that your rates are low, your quality is high and your
sterilization methods are state-of-the-art, the California Dental
Association says you may not be ethical enough to be a member. By
BOB EGELKO.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-GAYS (San Francisco)_ Gay-Straight Alliances are booming
in Northern California schools, formed by students who have learned
they can't depend on adults to save them and their friends from
rampant homophobia in classrooms and hallways. By CAROL NESS.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-GM-SUVS (San Antonio) _ General Motors is rolling out three
new sport utility vehicles _ the all-new 2002 Cadillac Escalade,
2001 GMC Yukon Denali and 2001 GMC Yukon Denali XL (better known as
the Suburban). All three of these high-end vehicles are expected to
do well in Texas, where General Motors' Suburban has been a
best-seller for decades. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-ACURA-SUV (Undated) _ After several years of selling a
rebadged version of the Isuzu Trooper as the Acura SLX
sport-utility vehicle, Honda's luxury-car division has decided to
produce its own premium SUV, designed from the ground up as an
Acura. By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-BRIEFS (Undated) _ The 2001 Honda Accord sedan and coupe
will feature ``freshened styling,'' a longer list of standard
features and enhanced safety, the company says. The changes are
designed to broaden the appeal of the car and perhaps help Honda
regain the lead in the all-important midsize sedan market. By G.
CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III.
</P>
<P>
   OREGON-REALTY (Florence, Ore.) _ ``Rent for a year, through the
winter, before you decide to buy a home here,'' advises Alan Burns,
the mayor of this seaside town. Andy Johnson, head of the oldest
and largest real estate brokerage on this section of the Oregon
coast, echoes the mayor. ``We find a lot of people who buy have
been here for vacation during the summer. I try and tell them to
spend a winter here first.'' By RICHARD PAOLI.
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I realize how warped this might
sound, but bear with me: Labor unions can learn a lot from watching
the National Rifle Association. This is about political strategy,
not ideology. The NRA and organized labor might well be at opposite
ends of the ideological spectrum, but that doesn't mean they can't
learn from each other. By DAVE MURPHY.
</P>
