``The Bear and the Dragon,'' is a work in progress _ for the
reader, who has to plow through more than 1,000 pages and subplot
upon subplot. However, the book is a real bargain at only $28.95.
By BOBBIE HESS.
</P>
<P>
   TV-COLUMN (Undated) _ Get the hell back, we've got the cranky
pants on. The Let's Debate Every Utterance of Dennis Miller goon
squad should be disbanded. Get out of his bathroom. Move off the
lawn. Debug the phone lines. He's just a stand-up comic making a
little yah-yah with football. It shouldn't be a national security
issue. By TIM GOODMAN.
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CARROTS (Undated) _ Cut into circles and boiled until soft,
carrots are about as appealing as a root canal. Shaped into little
cubes and combined with some mealy peas to be canned or frozen,
they're even worse. And that's a shame because carrots are
healthful, versatile and, if not boiled into mush, a sweet treat.
With the resurgence of farmers markets and small farms, colorful
carrots are making a comeback. By RUTH FANTASIA.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (San Francisco) _ Jeff Garcia is shivering in the
long, dark shadow cast by Steve Young and Joe Montana. No matter
what he does, if he doesn't win, the comparisons to these two will
cast him in an ugly light. Take Sunday's loss in Atlanta. Garcia
completed 23 passes, threw for three touchdowns, and guided the
team on four scoring drives. He compiled a quarterback rating of
100.8, fourth-highest of any quarterback on Sunday. Yet there were
grousings about Garcia's performance. By KEVIN LYNCH.
</P>
