<HEADER>
A3753 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN07-COX     09-06 0611
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Doc's life made full by listening
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wilford Chaney's first surgery was performed on a ``patient'' _
a pig _ after his father ordered him, ``Take the pig over this hill
and shoot it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pig had a hernia that dragged the ground when he walked. It
was the 1930s, and Chaney was taking pre-med courses at Ohio
University while working full time as a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpening his pen knife, Chaney performed the surgery, buying a
temporary reprieve for the doomed pig.
</P>
<P>
   The anecdote is one of hundreds in Chaney's recently
self-published book, The Making of a Family Physician, which is
one-half autobiography and one-half advice book for ``embryo
doctors,'' as he likes to call them.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney, 90, is retired from a long career as a family
practitioner in Oakwood, Ohio, and, later, an associate professor
at the Wright State University College of Medicine. He lives with
his wife of 67 years, Dorothy, in an Otterbein Lebanon Retirement
Living Community cottage that is filled with his original oil
paintings _ a hobby he took up at 80.
</P>
<P>
   Chaney wants to be something more than a Norman Rockwell
portrait of the Doctor Who Makes House Calls. He believes he has a
vital message to present-day doctors who are too well-versed in
technology and too little versed in human nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``I listened to my patients,'' Chaney said. ``I used to let them
tell me what was the matter.''
</P>
<P>
   When he once took an informal survey of fellow retirees, the top
complaint against doctors was, ``They don't listen to me.'' (''They
charge too much'' came in a distant third.)
</P>
<P>
   Although Chaney complains of being slowed by Parkinson's
disease, he smoked through the 100-page autobiography. ``And it was
so good, and everything fell right in line,'' Dorothy said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   Being raised on a farm in Ohio's Meigs County proved the perfect
early training for a young doctor. Chaney wrote: ``My pets and farm
animals taught me responsibility and compassion, which I needed
later in life.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1939, having saved $800 during eight years of teaching, he
entered Ohio State University as a medical student. By the March
1943 graduation day, he had three young daughters to support.
</P>
<P>
   By 1946, Chaney charged $5 for a house call. ``That got up to $7
in 1975,'' he said apologetically, ``and $10 after midnight.''
</P>
<P>
   House calls, meanwhile, are as extinct as the dodo. Chaney said
that's a shame _ for the doctor: ``I learned more about the patient
from one house call than from 10 hours in the office.''
</P>
<P>
   When teaching at WSU Medical College in the early '80s, Chaney
warned his students of the dangers of overmedication. At least one
of those students, television medical reporter Dr. Sherry Wheaton,
never forgot the message, or the professor.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell that he loved what he did, and you could tell
that patients loved him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember how you told us to have our patients bring in all
their pills in a box?'' Wheaton asked during a recent visit. ``I
never forgot that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I got through to one person, didn't I?'' Chaney smiled.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that Chaney is against modern medicine _ far from it.
It's simply that he believes that technology, however miraculous,
can never replace the power of touch, the power of listening.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get too busy to listen and shut off your patients,'' he
writes. ``Please note that the news will soon spread that 'My
doctor listened to me.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Contact Mary McCarty by e-mail at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
