<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Protection of minority views is essential to our democracy
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The outburst of Christian fundamentalism and activism is a red
light for America, we are the warning light for our culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I could watch TV without being offended at the casual sex
portrayed, the defiant attitude of children in sitcoms toward their
parents, the increasing news reports of kids shooting up their
schools, mothers killing their own children through abortion, I
would not have reason to pray out loud,'' wrote one of the many
readers who objected to a recent column about ``spontaneous
prayer'' at high school football games.
</P>
<P>
   The column was written in response to a ``No Pray, No Play''
movement at the Santa Fe, Texas, high school where student-led
prayers over loudspeakers were ruled unconstitutional by a 6-3 vote
on the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   The court's majority has consistently struck down efforts to use
government to dispense religion. The constitutional principle
always is the First Amendment's establishment clause that the
justices consistently interpret as calling for a separation of
church and state.
</P>
<P>
   While I agree with that interpretation, it is clear that many
Americans strongly disagree.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus told us to make disciples of all men, we are just
obeying our God when we tell others about Jesus and God'' was a
typical response to my column.
</P>
<P>
   I tried to make the point that the United States was not founded
to be a Christian nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States was once a Christian nation,'' wrote another
reader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope we return to honoring God and having prayer,'' she
wrote. She finished with a nice prayer for me.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court has never ruled against prayer. Actually, the
right to pray is constitutionally protected free speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do schools have Halloween and Valentine Day programs when
these are celebrations of pagan gods that dwell on the supernatural
and erotic practices?'' asked another reader.
</P>
<P>
   Other readers went to great lengths to provide historical
evidence that many of the Founding Fathers believed in God and were
deeply religious. No doubt that is true. But being religious and
keeping the government out of religion are not mutually exclusive
concepts.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goodness, have you been living under a brick?'' asked
another unhappy reader. ``Since the '60s and all the junk that has
filtered out since, our country is being seen as the most backward
country on the face of the earth.''
</P>
<P>
   The reader urged support for more prayer at school and football
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were founded on the American ideal of being a Christian
nation,'' wrote another reader who challenged me to read the
history books.
</P>
<P>
   Several readers wanted to know why I wrote that Santa Fe's
minority of Jewish, Mormon and Catholic residents report they feel
surrounded by hostile forces in a religious war.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, they wanted to know why Catholics would object to
the recitation of the Lord's Prayer at Santa Fe high school
football games.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Fe officials were sued by two anonymous families, one
Mormon and the other Catholic. These two religions are distinct
minorities in the small town 30 miles southeast of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, the supporters of public prayer over high
school loudspeakers have made life difficult for Catholic, Mormon
and Jewish families in Santa Fe.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the responses to the column opposed my opinion.
Perhaps even the majority of Americans would like to see the
government advocate religion. It makes me appreciate even more the
Constitution's protection of the minority from being squashed by
the majority.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
