<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Texas loses ground in emissions testing
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The '80s model car takes off from a standing start and leaves a
milky trail. One hundred yards and a cloud of smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The car disappears down the road. The exhaust sits abandoned,
then drifts. It is a scene witnessed without note at intersections
across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   If you could bottle that pollution, how much would you have?
</P>
<P>
   Modern-day automobiles with the latest pollution controls and
fuel efficiency are 97 percent to 99 percent cleaner than those 20
years ago, said Dr. Neal Carman, clean air director of the Lone
Star Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   The average car emits about 22 grams of carbon monoxide a mile.
The smoking car at the intersection may be kicking out 100 times
more, said Carman. That would mean roughly six times the pollution
over those 100 yards than the average car emits over a mile. There.
For you to breathe.
</P>
<P>
   In three metropolitan areas _ Houston, Dallas-Forth Worth and El
Paso _ cars are checked for tailpipe emissions exceeding federal
standards. But getting to that point has not been as straight a
line as from one intersection to the next.
</P>
<P>
   With the Environmental Protection Agency threatening to withhold
millions of highway dollars under the Clean Air Act of 1990, the
Texas Legislature in 1994 set up tailpipe emissions testing in the
three metro areas.
</P>
<P>
   For a variety of reasons, the system lasted only one month
before the state pulled the plug. The firm contracted, Tejas
Testing Technologies, sued the state and won $135 million for its
troubles.
</P>
<P>
   For another year and a half Texas went without any emissions
testing. Then, the EPA growing irritated, the legislature
authorized a new on-site inspection program paired with safety
inspections. It began in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In the interim, pollution had gotten so much more acute in the
Dallas area, for instance, that it got bumped up a notch from
``moderate'' to ``serious'' non-attainment of the Clean Air Act.
</P>
<P>
   The absence of emissions testing alone could hardly be blamed
for the increase, but EPA spokesman Dave Bary observed the irony
that with modest and inevitable measures having been postponed,
Texas found itself this year staring down the barrel with even
tougher measures including reduced speed limits in D-FW and Houston
and morning restrictions on the use of heavy equipment and
gas-powered lawn mowers in the the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Austin, San Antonio, Tyler, Marshall and Longview are
on the verge of lifestyle changes themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission in May said
those metro areas were in non-attainment and would have to curb
ozone levels in undetermined ways. They are spared the EPA hammer
for now only because of a lack of sufficient information about
exactly how poor their air is. Until then, their Clean Air Act
status is recommended as ``unclassifiable'' by the TNRCC. The
commission says it means the state can get to work on cleaning up
those cities' air in advance of an EPA mandate.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's Bary said it is not beyond possibility that in the
near future a greater swath of Texas _ for instance, other cities
along the I-35 corridor _ would be required to have tailpipes
checked.
</P>
<P>
   If current regional plans don't produce the desired effect, the
EPA could order Texas to adopt ``more stringent control
strategies.''
</P>
<P>
   That sounds like an insistence on more action, less smoke.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is the Opinion page editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune-Herald. E-mail: jyoung(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
