<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3774 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-FILE     09-06 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-FILE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A report on the radio said there's a new treatment for
migraines. Do you have any information?
</P>
<P>
   A: You probably heard about injections of Botox, a
muscle-relaxing agent used to remove lines and wrinkles in
patients' foreheads.
</P>
<P>
   Results of a study showing the serendipitous side effects on
migraines were presented in September by Dr. William Binder of UCLA
and Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in California. The study was done
on 106 patients. Of those who had injections for wrinkles and who
also suffered from migraines, 60 percent experienced total relief
from their headaches for three to five months, the same amount of
time they experienced wrinkle relief.
</P>
<P>
   Studies are under way to determine if Botox should have FDA
approval for marketing as a migraine treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that so-called ``nonalcohol'' beer is brewed by
the same process as regular beer, and in fact does contain some
alcohol. Is it inadvisable for me to serve it to a friend who is a
recovering alcoholic?
</P>
<P>
   A: Recovering alcoholics should avoid such products ``to be on
the safe side,'' said Dr. Richard Fuller of the National Institute
on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   While admitting that he had no statistical evidence to support
his conclusion, Fuller said he based it on statements by alcoholics
that the ``nonalcohol'' beer tastes just like the more potent
beverage, and therefore ``elicited cravings for it.'' He added that
it's those cravings, perhaps as much as or more than the presence
of low amounts of alcohol, that pose potential problems.
</P>
<P>
   Although many people use the ``nonalcohol'' label for a beverage
such as O'Doul's, it does have a slight alcohol content: less than
0.5 percent by volume, according to its manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I remember reading that someone or some group was digging for
buried treasure around the Alamo. Was anything found?
</P>
<P>
   A: Nothing of significance. In the 50-day dig, in 1995,
archaeologists unearthed a cow horn, a knife-shaped piece of rusty
metal, animal bones, pottery shards and a coin-size copper object.
</P>
<P>
   Amateur historian Frank Buschbacher hoped the dig would locate
the legendary treasure of the San Saba mines. Buschbacher
apparently had been told by a Mexican mystic a decade earlier that
buried treasure could be found under the Alamo grounds. Buschbacher
theorized that Jim Bowie found silver along the hills of the San
Saba River and carried it to the Alamo. When Texans there were
attacked by Mexican forces, Bowie's men tossed the treasure into a
well.
</P>
<P>
   Buschbacher claimed not to be disappointed. ``We haven't lost
anything,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The archaeologists, meanwhile, found three sites they identified
as metal-bearing anomalies. The metal turned out to be high iron
content in rocks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that Marilyn Monroe had six toes on one of her
feet?
</P>
<P>
   A: That claim is made by former ``photographer to the stars''
Joseph Jasgur, 81, of Orlando. He spent most of six decades in
Hollywood photographing celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   Jasgur was the first to do glossy shots of young Norma Jeane
Dougherty, who became Marilyn Monroe. He says he has the pictures
to prove that Norma Jeane _ the spelling she used on model release
forms she signed when he photographed her, and the spelling on her
birth certificate _ had six toes on her left foot. A report in the
Detroit News in 1992 said the abnormality was corrected later by
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article I read on the Internet said Hillary Rodham Clinton
(or her mother) is Jewish. Is this so?
</P>
<P>
   A: You could say there's a Jewish branch on her family tree, but
that's the extent of it.
</P>
<P>
   Max Rosenberg, the second husband of Clinton's maternal
grandmother, Della Howell, was a Russian-born Jew. Howell married
Rosenberg in 1933, seven years after she and Edwin Howell,
divorced. Clinton's mother, Dorothy, was born during the first
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Della and Max Rosenberg filed a petition for Max to adopt
Dorothy and Della's other children, but the attempt failed. Max
Rosenberg died in Los Angeles in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton, a Methodist, ``has very fond childhood
memories'' of Max Rosenberg, said Howard Wolfson, a spokesman for
Clinton's Senate campaign. Wolfson said he doesn't expect any
electoral impact to be derived because of Rosenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Whom did Butch Harmon caddy for before he caddied for Tiger
Woods?
</P>
<P>
   A: Harmon is Woods' coach, not his caddy. You may be thinking of
the caddy change Woods made last year, when he jettisoned Mike
``Fluff'' Cowan in exchange for New Zealander Steve Williams.
Before Woods, Williams worked for Greg Norman (eight years), Ray
Floyd, Ian Baker-Finch and Waybe Grady.
</P>
<P>
   Q: My mother will be 94 soon. Can you repeat the information
about requesting greetings from the White House?
</P>
<P>
   A: Put the request in writing and mail to: The President,
Attention Greetings Office, Room 39, The White House, Washington,
DC 20500. Or fax it to 202-395-1232. To listen to recorded
information, call 202-456-2724 (press 2). A response will be sent
to the recipient 10 days prior to the event, according to the
recording.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I see where Delta Air Lines will be flying its new
twin-engine B-767-400 to Hawaii. I thought flights from the
mainland United States to Hawaii had to be operated by aircraft
with at least three engines. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Federal Aviation Administration permits airlines to
operate twin-engine aircraft on such over-water routes if they have
applied to the FAA and the application has been approved. The
applications are ``airline-specific, aircraft-specific and
route-specific,'' said agency spokeswoman Kathleen Bergen, so
there's no blanket authorization for any airline to operate any
twin-engine aircraft on any over-water route.
</P>
<P>
   In Delta's case with 767s to Hawaii, the authority has been
granted by the FAA. Airlines also have been operating 767s to
Europe, so there's precedent.
</P>
<P>
   Bergen said the FAA carefully monitors engine performance and
other factors after the airlines begin flying the twin-engine
planes on these routes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Have the fires in Montana affected any of Ted Turner's
property?
</P>
<P>
   A: There was some damage to Turner's ``Bar None,'' a 23,000-acre
ranch near Toston. Turner publicist Maura Donlan said the fire was
contained within a perimeter covering about 7,000 acres, but not
everything within the area was damaged. Volunteer and paid
firefighters put it out.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is Socks, the White House cat, still around? How about Buddy,
the White House dog?
</P>
<P>
   A: They're both still residents of 1600 Pennsylvania Avenue in
Washington. The latest news is that they're answering mail. Well,
not them, but dozens of retired veterans who volunteer to respond
to the thousands of letters sent to the White House each day,
including many letters sent to Socks and Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Since March 1993, when the White House asked for volunteers to
help respond to the mail, veterans from Washington's Soldiers' and
Airmens' Home have answered about 1.9 million letters _ 320,000 of
them for the Clinton family's pets.
</P>
<P>
   Recipients receive a portrait postcard from one or the other
signed with a pawprint at the bottom. The typical message: ``Thank
you for writing me. Living at the White House is exciting. I am
honored to be your `First Cat.' ''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
