<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 11:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-FILE     09-06 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWS-QUESTIONS07-FILE2-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS: THIS IS FILE 2 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: At Atlanta's Hartsfield International Airport security
checkpoint recently, my friend was asked for her purse. The guard
used a wand with a cloth attached to wipe the purse. Then she
placed the cloth in a machine. What is this procedure all about?
</P>
<P>
   A: Although Hartsfield officials refused to comment on specific
security procedures, others familiar with what your friend
encountered say the wand and machine are used to detect any
bomb-making materials that might have been present in her bag. The
wand is moved over the zipper and around the bag. If present,
traces of bomb-making materials would leave residue on the bag, so
the machine is used to detect any such materials.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recall some discussion about leasing Navy facilities in
Long Beach, Calif., to Chinese interests. What's the status of
that?
</P>
<P>
   A: It never happened. The Long Beach Naval Station had closed in
1994, and the Naval Shipyard shut down in 1997. The defunct complex
became part of the Port of Long Beach, and the city had planned to
lease the terminal to China Ocean Shipping Co., a major shipping
concern owned by the Chinese government.
</P>
<P>
   But the proposed lease of the facilities was blocked in 1998 by
members of Congress who feared it would pose a threat to national
security. Two Republicans from Southern California, Reps. Duncan
Hunter and Randy Cunningham, first raised the security issue.
</P>
<P>
   The latest development came Aug. 10 when regulators from the
California Environmental Protection Agency and the Navy agreed on a
cleanup plan for the site.
</P>
<P>
   Q: An article reported on rankings of the 50 states and District
of Columbia on SAT scores. Where on the Internet can I find
information about all states and their SAT scores?
</P>
<P>
   A: The College Board's results for all states can be found
online at www.collegeboard.org/sat/cbsenior/yr2000/states00.html.
But the College Board doesn't rank states ``nor does it have that
information available,'' said spokesman Henry Faulkner. ``There's a
lot of conjecture when anyone says how any states rank.''
</P>
<P>
   You can get an idea, however, if you check
www.collegeboard.org/press/senior00/html/000829.html and, in the
box at the right of your screen, click on Tables and Related Items.
Note the proviso at the top: ``Comparing or ranking states on the
basis of SAT scores along is invalid and strongly discouraged by
the College Board.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: A KLM jet dumped 83 tons of fuel over the Pacific when it had
to return to the Los Angeles airport Sunday after an engine part
fell off. What happens to that fuel?
</P>
<P>
   A: It normally vaporizes. Dumping is done to reduce the weight
of the airplane and to slow the landing speed, as well as to reduce
the risk of fire in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Q: There was a 4-C draft classification in World War II. What
was it for?
</P>
<P>
   A: 4-C was for aliens or dual nationals. These are some of the
other classifications used between 1948 and 1976, when they ended:
1-A, available immediately for military service; 1-0 and 1-A-0,
conscientious objector; 2-A, job considered essential to the
national interest; 3-A, hardship deferment; 4-D, minister of
religion; 4-F, physically or mentally unable to serve; 5-A, over
age of liability for service.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.sss.gov.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What is the background of Jacques Nasser of Ford Motor Co.?
In the TV ads regarding the tire recall, his pronunciation seems
like a blend of Tidewater Virginia-Outer Banks North Carolina, Low
Country South Carolina, and Cajun, with a few words pronounced as
though he's direct from the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   A: His accent is considerably more global. Nasser, 52, Ford's
CEO and president, was born in Lebanon and raised in Melbourne,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   When he was barely 20, he accepted a job as a financial analyst
at Ford of Australia. He worked for the company in Thailand, the
Philippines, Venezuela and Argentina before returning in 1990 to
head Ford of Australia. Over the next three years he sliced the
15,000-person work force in half, earning him the nickname ``Jac
the Knife.''
</P>
<P>
   He became Ford's head of auto operations in the United States in
1996, and was elevated to CEO on Jan. 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   His 90-second TV ad guaranteeing that ``no one at Ford will rest
until every recalled tire is replaced'' premiered Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A report mentioned that Asheville, N.C., ranks among Money
magazine's top 10 places to retire. What are the others?
</P>
<P>
   A: Bradenton, Fla.; Fort Collins, Colo.; Brunswick, Maine; and
Bend, Ore. Money's runners-up: Santa Fe, N.M.; Hot Springs, Ark.;
San Luis Obispo, Calif.; Madison, Wis.; and Amherst, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.money.com/money/depts/retirement/. The
Web site, by the way, has information about housing costs, tax
rates, crime statistics and other retirement-pertinent factors in
nearly 500 U.S. cities and towns. Enter the name of the place
you're interested in, and the information is displayed.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Everyone says Audie Murphy was the most decorated U.S.
soldier in World War II, but I think it was Neville Brand, who also
became an actor. Can you confirm?
</P>
<P>
   A: Brand was one of the most decorated GIs in World War II, with
the Silver Star and seven Purple Hearts, among other medals. But he
didn't receive more than Murphy, according to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   It's generally considered that Murphy and Matt Urban were
America's most decorated soldiers, although a spokesman said the
Pentagon no longer lists anyone as having received ``the most''
medals, because it depends on which ones are counted.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Brand, who grew up in Kewanee, Ill., moved to Los
Angeles and attended the Geller Drama School on the GI Bill. His
first big break in movies came as a hoodlum in the 1950 thriller
``D.O.A.'' Among his other films: ``Stalag 17,'' ``Return From the
Sea,'' ``Riot in Cell Block 11'' and ``Birdman of Alcatraz.''
</P>
<P>
   Brand died at age 71 in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Q&AMP;A mentioned that Matt Urban was one of America's
most-decorated soldiers. Can you tell us more about him?
</P>
<P>
   A: Urban was awarded 29 medals for bravery during World War II,
including seven Purple Hearts _ one for each time he was wounded in
battle. At one time he was listed in the Guinness Book of World
Records as the most-decorated soldier in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   In wartime, Urban, an Army lieutenant colonel, was nicknamed
``The Ghost'' because of his sophisticated combat exploits. He led
his troops through campaigns in North Africa, Sicily, Belgium,
France and Germany. He later wrote ``The Matt Urban Story: Life and
World War II Experiences,'' and was awarded the Medal of Honor in
1980, 35 years after the original nomination was lost.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Urban lived in Michigan, where he died in March
1995 at age 75. A monument to his courage was unveiled in Holland,
Mich., in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
