<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 12:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3856 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r d BC-CARROTS-HNS &LR;      09-06 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARROTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CARROTS DON'T HAVE TO BE BOILED INTO OBLIVION 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometime before people become grown-ups, carrots go from being a
wonderfully sweet and crunchy snack to a vegetable.
</P>
<P>
   Cut into circles and boiled until soft, carrots are about as
appealing as a root canal. Shaped into little cubes and combined
with some mealy peas to be canned or frozen, they're even worse.
And that's a shame because carrots are healthful, versatile and, if
not boiled into mush, a sweet counterpart to green vegetables that
are even less popular, such as peas and broccoli.
</P>
<P>
   At one time, carrots were just about every color in the food
realm except orange, write cookbook authors Jeannette Ferrary and
Louise Fiszer, on Sally's Place, a culinary Web site
(http://www.sallys-place.com). They were red, black, yellow, white
and purple.
</P>
<P>
   ``Originally cultivated in Afghanistan in the 7th century,
carrots originally had purple exteriors and yellow flesh. In the
Middle Ages, the Dutch developed the bright orange carrot we now
know as the bearer of carotene,'' they write.
</P>
<P>
   Around 1900, people finally settled on orange carrots, says Paul
Arnold, who grows carrots of many colors at Pleasant Valley Farm in
Argyle, N.Y. ``I think the other colors may have gotten pushed
aside because some of them aren't machine-harvestable and
therefore, they didn't have as much value.''
</P>
<P>
   With the resurgence of farmers markets and small farms, colorful
carrots are making a comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Arnold sells the orange, purple and white carrots he grows at
the farmers markets in the upstate New York communities of Saratoga
Springs, Glens Falls and Queensbury. He says he has seen interest
in the off-hued vegetables increase in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only do our customers really enjoy seeing the different
kinds, they come back and want them because of the flavor,'' Arnold
says. ``They have a stronger flavor than commercially grown
carrots.''
</P>
<P>
   Carrots contain a substantial amount of beta carotene, which is
one of the antioxidant nutrients associated with the prevention of
some cancers. During digestion, beta carotene is converted to
vitamin A, a nutrient necessary for proper bone growth, healthy
skin and hair, tooth development and eyesight. In addition, carrots
have only 35 calories per 1-cup serving.
</P>
<P>
   While carrots seem to be relegated to a supporting role in
vegetables mixtures, salads and crudite plates these days, the root
vegetable was quite popular in other times. Early New Englanders
gave carrot cookies as Christmas gifts and ``tzimmes'' a sweet
carrot stew, is traditional for the Jewish New Year, write Ferrary
and Louise Fiszer.
</P>
<P>
   When cooking carrots, use as little liquid as possible, writes
James Peterson in ``Vegetables'' (Morrow, 1998) because the liquid
draws out the root's natural flavors and sweetness. If you must
boil carrots, try to use the liquid in the recipe.
</P>
<P>
   Since carrots are fatter at one end, sliced carrots tend to cook
unevenly. To prevent this, cut the larger circles into wedges
before using.
</P>
<P>
   When buying carrots, look for well-shaped roots and brightly
colored vegetables. If sold with the tops still attached, look for
fresh greens. Cut the tops off before storing in a tightly sealed
plastic bag in the refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Carrots will keep for up to a month in a plastic bag and in the
refrigerator. To store up to two months, add a damp paper towel to
the bag.
</P>
<P>
   If you have a root cellar, you can keep fresh carrots through
the winter, says Arnold. ``Keep them between 33 and 35 degrees and
at 100 percent humidity. That's what they like.''
</P>
<P>
   The following recipes are from ``Generation to Generation: A
Celebration of the Senses'' compiled by Congregation Agudat Achim
in Schenectady, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   CARROT SOUP
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds carrots
</P>
<P>
   2 medium to large potatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion
</P>
<P>
   2 bay leaves
</P>
<P>
   6 cups chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   Slice carrots, cube potatoes and dice onions. Place in a large
stock pot, add bay leaves and chicken broth. Bring to a boil,
reduce heat and simmer for 1 hour. Remove bay leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Use an immersion blender to puree soup before serving.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SAUTEED CARROTS, GREEN BEANS AND ROASTED GARLIC
</P>
<P>
   16 large garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound green beans
</P>
<P>
   1 quart water
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound carrots, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons margarine or butter
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 275. Place garlic cloves in a packet of aluminum
foil. Drizzle with olive oil. Bake for 30 minutes. Open foil and
roast garlic until golden brown and soft enough to be pierced with
a knife, 15 minutes. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Cook beans in a large pot of boiling salted water until just
tender, 4 minutes. Drain; refresh under cold water, drain. Set
aside.
</P>
<P>
   Bring 1 quart water to a boil in a medium saucepan with sugar
and 1/2 teaspoon salt. Add carrots and cook until just tender, 10
minutes. Drain and cool. (Vegetables can be prepared a day ahead.
Combine, cover and refrigerate).
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter or margarine in a heavy skillet over medium-high
heat. Add garlic, beans, carrots and saute until heated through.
Season with salt and pepper. Serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   SOUR CREAM VEGETABLE PANCAKES
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups shredded carrots and yellow squash
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Melt 2 tablespoons butter in a large skillet over medium heat.
Add vegetables and saute 1 to 2 minutes, stirring constantly. Cool
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Beat egg yolks in a medium bowl. Add sour cream, cornstarch salt
and pepper. Mix well. Stir in sauteed vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Melt 1 tablespoon butter in a large pan over medium-high heat.
Spoon pancake batter into 1 3/4 -inch rounds in pan. Brown on both
sides.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
