<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 12:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3885 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-FASHION-MAKEUP-HNS &LR;      09-06 0718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-MAKEUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     PUTTING A NEW, MORE COLORFUL FACE ON MAKEUP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CYNTHIA ROBINS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Never has retro makeup been such a complement to
the return of elegance in fashion as it has this fall. The '50s
live on faces that have long been void of color and form.
</P>
<P>
   While the neutral/natural/beige look is a style that Calvin
Klein clings to, it is not strong enough for fall's jewel-toned
gowns, black and white suitings, or the sharp, womanly tailoring
that glorifies a female's best assets.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not a fan of well-defined red lips and strong,
shapely eyebrows, then maybe you'd better sit this one out. Better
yet ... find a red lipstick that works for you. Everyone can wear
red lips ... if they find the right shade. It has to do with the
undertones of your skin. (Everyone has a little yellow in their
skin; some women are tawnier, some are pinker.)
</P>
<P>
   How do you determine what color is the real you? Rule of thumb:
If you look great in paper white shirts next to your face, chances
are you have some pink in your skin. You'd be considered a ``cool''
color person. The lipstick for you: Reds with a little blue in
them, like Chanel's new ``Calypso'' _ maybe slicked up with a
highlight of ``Pulsar Glossimer'' or YSL's new ``No. 82 Rouge
Pur,'' a lipstick so vividly blue-red, it is designed to wear with
black velvet and diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   If creamy colored off-white shirts make your skin glow, you
probably have a lot of gold or yellow in your skin. Then, a true,
clear red or a brown-red works _ or even a red with a little bit of
yellow, like M.A.C's new ``Lady Danger,'' Lauder's ``Fiery
Russett'' or YSL's ``Copyright Red'' (``No. 83 Rouge Pur'').
</P>
<P>
   Bright red lips put you off? Try a milder form, like a gloss or
a lipstain from Bobbie Brown, Frederic Fekkai or Laura Mercier.
</P>
<P>
   As for the eyes: They start with a great brow. Not pared down as
much as groomed within an inch of its life. The best way to
accomplish a great brow is to have it done professionally. Alexis
Simonsen at Saks Fifth Avenue's YSL counter, Angelina Umansky of
Spa Radiance, Robert Williams at Saks' Franois Nars counter _ all
do very strong, flattering brows.
</P>
<P>
   A great way to groom a brow: Select a small, slant-edged brush
and brow powder (YSL, Chanel and Lancome have brow compacts with
several colors in them so you can mix up just the right shade.) Run
the brush lightly over the surface of the brow powder, tapping off
the excess. Sketch in your brows, brushing the color in the
direction your brow grows, using tiny, short strokes. Anchor into
place with either a clear brow fixative or with transparent mascara
(Calvin Klein makes one; so does Max Factor). When you get your
brows where you want them, and while the brow fix is still damp,
take a piece of tissue and blot your brows as you would your
lipstick to remove the excess.
</P>
<P>
   If you prefer using a brow pencil, T. LeClerc's ``Crayon de
Sourcils'' in brownish taupe (one end is pencil, the other is a
brow brush) is a good universal color that will work for blondes as
well as brunettes and redheads. A third option is Shiseido's
lightly tinted brow fixative (Macy's).
</P>
<P>
   Under a strong brow, there needs to be an elegant eye but
nothing that will compete with the mouth. The '50s ballerina eye
with its strong, winged black eyeliner, is enough with possibly a
color wash of the lightest dove gray, taupe or even ice blue _ so
delicately applied, you can hardly see it. False eyelashes have
made a strong return, but not for the entire eye. Try Lancome's
individual eyelashes, applied to the outside corner of the top row
of lashes. Mascara: Good, dark, deep black, even on blondes.
</P>
<P>
   As for the cheeks _ shine is out. No glitter, no glitz, no
little mica sparkles. Just a blush accomplished with any number of
the face tints available, including the original: ``BeneTint'' by
BeneFit and the recent copies by Francois Nars and Lancome. (One
word of warning: This stuff requires some rehearsal before you
start to dress for the evening. Get it, play with hit until you're
applying it like a pro.)
</P>
<P>
   Better yet: Have a makeup lesson. The festive fall face is
fairly simple to accomplish. Once you know how.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
