<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 12:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3905 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r e BC-BOOK-REVIEW-THRILLERS     09-06 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-REVIEW-THRILLERS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLANCY'S FANS DESERVE BETTER THAN THIS BEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (Eds: Also, reviews of ``Pagan Babies,'' by Elmore Leonard;
``Stalker,'' by Faye Kellerman; and ``Even Steven,'' by John
Gilstrap)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOBBIE HESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tom Clancy's latest thriller, ``The Bear and the Dragon,'' is a
work in progress _ for the reader, who has to plow through 1,028
pages and subplot upon subplot. However, G.P. Putnam's Sons has
made it a real bargain by pricing it at only $28.95.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Ryan is now the duly elected president and faces big
problems on the world stage. In Russia, assassins use a
rocket-launched grenade to take out a white Mercedes carrying a key
Moscow mafioso.
</P>
<P>
   However, many think the assassins got the wrong Mercedes and
really meant to take out Sergey Nikolaych Golovko, the head of the
state security service, formerly the KGB. FBI agent Mike Reilly,
assigned to the U.S. Embassy in Moscow and an expert on organized
crime, helps the local officers in their investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ryan has angered the mainland Chinese by granting
independent-nation status to Taiwan. Trade talks are going badly
because Beijing will not open its markets to American business, is
ripping off foreign technology and refuses to discuss what the
United States considers human-rights violations.
</P>
<P>
   Having spent billions to build up their army and navy, the
Chinese are facing bankruptcy and are drawing up plans for an
invasion of Siberia, where huge oil and gold fields have been
discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, when a Chinese woman trying to get around the
one-child rule goes into labor, a doctor tries to abort the child.
Her husband calls their Baptist minister begging for help.
</P>
<P>
   The minister and the newly named papal nuncio to China rush to
the hospital and try to stop the abortion, but both are killed,
setting off a huge wave of anti-Chinese sentiment around the world
because the Chinese refuse to issue a public apology.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans get their first break when a young CIA agent woos
the secretary of one of the Chinese politburo members and installs
a secret device in her computer that automatically sends notes on
her boss's meetings to the CIA. Thus, the CIA gets early warning
about the Chinese plans.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the best Clancy thriller. It is overwritten and very
racist, and no writer should make his reader work so hard _ I
almost made a flow chart to keep the story straight.
</P>
<P>
   This is a real shame because there is a very good story buried
in ``The Bear and the Dragon.'' However, since the book is already
at the top of the bestseller lists, Clancy will have no worries.
His hard-core fans will buy it even though they deserve better.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Pagan Babies.'' By Elmore Leonard. Delacorte Press. $24.95.
263 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard's latest crime thriller should be accompanied by a CD
with Andy Williams singing ``Two grifters, out to con the world,
there's such a lot of world to con '' With apologies to Henry
Mancini, Leonard, as usual, has hit a winner with ``Pagan Babies.''
</P>
<P>
   He begins his tale in Rwanda. Five years ago, the Rev. Terry
Dunne left Detroit and went to Rwanda to help his ailing uncle, a
priest in a small village. As Terry says Mass one Sunday, Hutus
enter his church and massacre 70 of his congregation.
</P>
<P>
   Terry never gets over the horror of that morning. He says Mass
on Christmas and Easter and hears confessions once a week, but
mostly, he sits on his porch and drinks Johnny Walker Red with his
housekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Then his brother Fran, a lawyer, calls to say that their mother
has died. As he prepares to leave for home, one of the Hutus who
participated in the church massacre brags that the killings will
begin again. So Terry takes his housekeeper's gun, goes to the
local banana beer bar and fatally shoots the Hutu and three of his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   Terry gets back to Detroit too late for the funeral, but in time
to meet up with a local prosecutor to discuss his possible
indictment for smuggling illegal cigarettes across state lines
before he left Rwanda.
</P>
<P>
   Fran introduces Terry to Debbie Dewey, a former personal injury
investigator and would-be stand-up comic who has just finished
serving three years for aggravated assault after she ran down her
former lover, who conned her out of her savings.
</P>
<P>
   Street-smart Debbie knows instantly that Terry is no priest and
is probably a fellow con-artist. She convinces him to help her get
her ex-lover, Randy, to repay the money he swindled from her.
</P>
<P>
   Her plan will get her money back and raise money for the orphans
of Rwanda. The two set up a con that uses the local mob bosses to
outfox Randy.
</P>
<P>
   Leonard peoples ``Pagan Babies'' with his usual assortment of
low-lifes, off-the wall dialogue and a plot that will keep you
guessing.
</P>
<P>
   And the title is a hoot. For years, Catholic grade school kids
were given Pagan Baby boxes. When they saved up $5, they took the
box back to school and got to give a Christian name to a pagan baby
for his baptism.
</P>
<P>
   Only Leonard would be crazy enough to use this barbaric premise
for the basis of a truly unique novel.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE MORE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; UNDATED: x x x unique novel. &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Stalker.'' By Faye Kellerman. William Morrow. $25. 406 pages.
</P>
<P>
   Kellerman's latest in the Peter Decker/Rina Lazarus mystery
series focuses on his daughter, Los Angeles police Officer Cynthia
Decker, a redhead with an attitude that does not go down well with
her fellow officers.
</P>
<P>
   She can't help giving the impression that she is better than
everyone else because she has an Ivy League education and her
father is a lieutenant in the department.
</P>
<P>
   After antagonizing her immediate superior by disobeying orders
while trying to halt a domestic dispute, Cindy gets the feeling
that someone is following her. She finds things out of place in her
apartment; then her apartment is vandalized. She gets support from
Detective Scott Oliver, who works for her father.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver and his boss are investigating a string of carjackings
that may be tied to the murder of a tycoon Cindy knew. She starts
investigating the murder, placing herself in great peril.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy is a cocky, smug, arrogant, very intriguing character. It
will be interesting to see where Kellerman takes her in future
mysteries. ``Stalker'' is a pleasant read with good characters,
well-developed plot and realistic dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   ``Even Steven.'' By John Gilstrap. Pocket Books. $24.95. 357
pages.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Gilstrap has produced an incredibly original
thriller centered around a child in peril.
</P>
<P>
   When Susan and Bobby Martin's baby is born dead, they are
devastated. They go camping in West Virginia hoping to heal the
emotional wounds that haunt them both. Suddenly, they hear rustling
in the bushes and think it's a bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Squealing like a frightened pig, the beast bolted out of the
trees, coming straight at Bobby, then breaking off to the right,
across the rocks toward the river. Only it wasn't a bear. `Oh, my
God!' Susan yelled. `It's a little boy!' And he was scared to
death. Screaming, he ran in a blind panic toward the edge of the
rocks, and the rolling waters below.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby takes off after him and grabs the child before he plunges
into the river. About 3 years old, the boy is wearing only a pair
of footy pajamas, and he is caked with dirt. Susan eventually
quiets the crying child as they decide to take him to the nearest
ranger station in hopes of finding his parents.
</P>
<P>
   Before they can act, they hear more rustling in the trees. A man
appears and says he is looking for his son. When Bobby doesn't
appear to believe his story, the man pulls a gun on him, a fight
ensues and Bobby eventually kills the man. Checking for
identification, they discover the dead man is a cop. In a panic,
they flee the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, April Simpson returns home from work and learns her
son has been taken because her husband owes a drug dealer a lot of
money. Simpson enlists the help of another drug dealer to get her
son back. She also tries a hold-up that lands her in jail.
</P>
<P>
   Page by page, the tension mounts. Will the Martins' marriage
survive Susan's refusal to give up the child? Will Simpson be able
to get the police involved in finding her son?
</P>
<P>
   Gilstrap is a unique storyteller, with a crisp writing style, a
fine eye for detail and an obvious love of children. Once again,
Gilstrap delivers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
