<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3939 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-POPCORN-PREVIEW-LADN &LR;      09-06 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POPCORN-PREVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATURAL BORN THRILLER
</HEADLINE>
  Artistic director dares to deal with controversial subject on the
stage 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
 
 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's with all the talking? wonders Wayne Hudson. If two people
are pointing guns at each other in one of those cinematic
stand-offs, why doesn't somebody just start shooting?
</P>
<P>
   Wayne knows a little bit about these situations. Not only has he
killed a bunch of people, but he's seen too many movies in the
``Pulp Fiction'' and ``Desperado'' genre. Just to make things
interesting, he has also kidnapped _ at gunpoint _ Bruce Delmetri,
the Tarantino-esque maker of bang bang splatter pictures on the
very night Bruce has won an Oscar.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to ``Popcorn'' a kind of Natural Born Morality Play that
has playwright Ben Elton taking the ``Scream'' treatment to the
serial killer genre. Hudson is dangerous not simply because he's
holding the weapon, but because he knows how the game is played,
and he blames Delmetri for making him the way he is.
</P>
<P>
   A best-selling novel before it became a critical favorite on the
London stage, ``Popcorn'' has had only one non-professional
production in the United States before artistic director Jeremiah
Morris secured the rights for the El Portal Center for the Arts in
North Hollywood. The production, which opens tonight may insure
that the theater's inaugural season ends in a blaze of gunfire and
four letter words, the likes of which El Portal audiences may not
be expecting.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes, says Morris, the El Portal's artistic director and
the director of ``Popcorn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of people thought I was crazy (for staging it),''
admits Morris, who fell in love with the play after stumbling into
the London production a few years ago. ``The language is rough at
times and there's violence in it. But it's a very funny black
comedy and it's about responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This one is just going to rock the rafters,'' says Maxwell
Caulfield, who plays the kidnapped director Bruce Delmetri. ``It's
very courageous of Jeremiah to mount this piece at his theater
because we're doing it literally in Hollywood's back yard. I'm
expecting to hear a few seat backs slapping (from people leaving
the theater), but if the audience can handle the dialogue for the
first two minutes, hopefully we've got 'em for the rest of the
night.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who haven't been paying attention to the rantings of
Democratic vice presidential hopeful Joseph Lieberman the past few
years, ``Popcorn'' is a kind of answer to the glorification of
celebrity serial killers and all those charges of reckless and
over-violent content on TV in videogames or at a multiplex near
you.
</P>
<P>
   We've heard the ``responsible art'' debate throughout the 1990s,
with ``The Silence of the Lambs,'' ``Natural Born Killers'' and
even in connection with the recently opened Jennifer Lopez hit
``The Cell.'' It's a question that won't seem to die no matter how
many bullets you pump into it, how many slashes it absorbs or how
many times you set it on fire. Are the Oliver Stones, Quentin
Tarantinos and Tarsems (director of ``The Cell'') of the world in
some way culpable when a kid takes an uzi to school? Whose fault is
Columbine? Do we have to watch? Can we tear ourselves away?
</P>
<P>
   Caulfield and David Faustino, who play ``Popcorn's'' two
adversaries, have examined questions. Faustino, a Burbank native,
grew up in a household where crude language and nudity on
television were considered taboo, but the depiction of violence was
acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   He then went on to play the perpetually horny Bud Bundy for 11
years on Fox's ``Married ... with Children,'' a program that drew
more than its share of criticism for raunch. Ironically, it was the
initial controversy and threat of advertisers to pull their ads,
that helped the TV program take off. Told they shouldn't watch,
audiences couldn't turn away.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were offended about it because we dissed each other
back and forth and there was some sexual innuendo,'' says Faustino,
playing against type as ``Popcorn's'' serial killer Wayne Hudson.
``Our whole thing was like, 'You know, if you don't like it just
turn the channel. You don't have to watch it.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really started thinking about it until the Columbine
situation. Then I started thinking, 'Wow, could it really affect
people that greatly and are we responsible?' 'Popcorn's' coming at
a perfect time because everybody is starting to ask the question
and it's really an interesting question.''
</P>
<P>
   Caulfield, a British actor who has appeared in more than a few
low budget shoot-'em-ups, says that he raised an eyebrow when the
Motion Picture Academy bestowed its 1991 Best Picture Oscar on
``The Silence of the Lambs'' _ a movie Bruce Delmetri probably
would have considered tame.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought ('Silence') was a hugely entertaining movie, but I
didn't feel that a play celebrating a super-villain, this Hannibal
Lecter character, should play and resonate around the world. I
frankly didn't see the value of it,'' says Caulfield. ``Now I know
that runs counter to the character I'm playing (in 'Popcorn'), but
one of the reasons I was drawn to the play is the subject matter.''
</P>
<P>
   And even though he isn't necessarily a fan of Delmetri-esque
flicks, Caulfield acknowledges that the play's argument over
responsibility is by no means a black and white discussion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bruce is a complex contradictory character who refuses to have
the blame shifted on to him,'' Caulfield says.
</P>
<P>
   Elton's work isn't widely known across the Atlantic. The
41-year-old playwright/stand-up comedian co-wrote the successful
BBC sitcom ``The Young Ones,'' and later wrote the ``Blackadder''
series with his partner, Richard Curtis. ``Popcorn,'' Elton's
fourth novel, was a best-seller and was nominated as Book of the
Year by the Booksellers Association.
</P>
<P>
   The play, written to address the fervor over celebrity serial
killers in Oliver Stone's ``Natural Born Killers,'' won the
Laurence Olivier Award for best comedy. Its film rights are
currently in the hands of director Joel Schumacher.
</P>
<P>
   El Portal administrators say they hope to being Elton to NoHo
for ``Popcorn's'' premiere, but to do that, they'll have to pry him
away from Andrew Lloyd Webber with whom Elton is collaborating on
the new soccer-themed musical, ``The Beautiful Game.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our appreciation for the piece grows every day,'' says
Caulfield. ``It's one of these plays where as people are laughing,
you ram the truth down their throats.'' &QL; 
____ &QL; 
What: ``Popcorn.'' &QL; 
Where: El Portal Center for the Arts, 5269 Lankershim Blvd., North
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   When: 7 p.m. Tuesday through Wednesday, 7 p.m. Sunday, 8 p.m.
Thursday through Saturday, 2 p.m. Saturday and Sunday, 7:30 p.m.
Sunday; through Oct. 1. &QL; 
Tickets: $25-$42. Call (818) 508-4200. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1322EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
