u k BC-INTERNET-SAFE-NNS &LR;      09-06 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SAFE-NNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW WEB-BASED GAMES SPEAK DIRECTLY TO CHILDREN IN TEACHING INTERNET
SAFETY 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
TUESDAY, Sept. 5, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.)  
 ART ADVISORY: With illustration of child using Internet sent as
photo (NNS1), and a graphic with Web site addresses and
descriptions. For information about purchasing these photos, call
202-383-7824.  
 (Editors: `Parry' in 19th graf is cq)  
 By MICHELE M. MELENDEZ  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Parents teaching their children how to use the Internet safely
now may call upon a growing group of spunky cartoon characters
armed with advice.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Duck slays computer viruses with a pea shooter. The Three
CyberPigs uncover racism on the Web. And the Idea Seekers gang,
which includes a superhero who fights the ``Darkness of Dumbness,''
urges children not to respond to ``strange, mean or upsetting''
e-mail messages.
</P>
<P>
   Web sites run by law enforcement agencies and children's
organizations have offered tips to parents on shielding their
children from Internet harm. But until recently, few sites spoke
directly to children about Internet dangers. And those that did
were normally flat _ minimal color, movement and opportunity to
interact.
</P>
<P>
   That's changing. This year, with an estimated 25 million
children online in the United States, site developers are melding
rainbow vibrance with sound and motion to foster safe and
responsible Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to deliver the content in a very engaging way,''
said Lane Beauchamp, a development director for Circle 1 Network,
which produces Web sites for children. ``White text on a black
background, or vice versa, is not terribly engaging to
8-year-olds.''
</P>
<P>
   Beauchamp called Internet safety games ``the Mary Poppins
approach _ a spoonful of sugar helps the medicine go down.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Web sites are reflecting that method with free games
aimed at pre-teens. In April, the Canadian Media Awareness Network
(www.media-awareness.ca) released ``Cybersense and Nonsense,'' in
which children help three skateboarding pigs learn that not all
wolves blow houses down. In June, Circle 1's KidsCom Web site
(www.kidscom.com) charged up its Internet safety word puzzles with
cartoon characters that swirl around the mouse-controlled arrow
pointer.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Disney Online established ``Surf Swell Island''
(www.surfswellisland.com), where children guide Disney characters
through spooky Internet scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been devoted to Internet safety,'' said Carol
Rozio, Disney Online spokeswoman. ``We just think (children) should
be armed with these tools.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Surf Swell Island includes links to Disney's vacation
packages and merchandise _ links that Rozio said appear for
consistency on all Disney Online pages _ Rozio said Disney makes no
money from the Internet safety site. It does not, she noted,
include advertising.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, children will be able to choose among even more games.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the year, the Cybercitizen Partnership, a project
of the U.S. Department of Justice and the Information Technology
Association of America Foundation, plans to launch a site with
safety games. The Boys &AMP; Girls Clubs of America has enlisted the
National Center for Missing &AMP; Exploited Children to develop an
Internet safety curriculum with games to be available to members by
early next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope it will have a different effect than sitting them down
with a bunch of rules in front of them,'' said Tina Schwartz, a
national center spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM BEGINS)
</P>
<P>
   Playing an Internet safety game feels like any other computer
game for children. Happy music accompanies cute animation that
glides across the screen. In the Disney site's ``No Privacy Beach''
game for example, children save Minnie from peeping Toms, who find
out her vacation destination on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   As Minnie lounges in a chair, children use the computer mouse to
click on the creeps that sneak peaks. With every few successful
clicks, messages pop up, like ``Never, ever give out your
password.''
</P>
<P>
   The games quiz children about Internet safety in some way. At
the end of ``No Privacy Beach,'' Minnie asks the children to
respond to true-or-false statements, including, ``It is bad to tell
your password to your online pals'' and ``It is OK to tell someone
in a chat room your name and address as long as the person is a
grown-up.''
</P>
<P>
   (OPTIONAL TRIM ENDS)
</P>
<P>
   Instructional games are the way to go, said Jane Tallim,
Internet and media education specialist for the Media Advocacy
Network.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think kids enjoy games because of the same interactivity
that makes the Internet so appealing to them,'' she said. ``Putting
(safety tips) in a game form can make some of the more serious
issues not as threatening.''
</P>
<P>
   Parry Aftab, executive director of the child advocacy
organization Cyberangels, said the biggest Internet hazard for
children isn't pornography.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to see porn. They're going to see really crummy
stuff. They're going to see sites that say the Holocaust never
happened, hate sites, not scholarly ones,'' she said. ``If parents
understand that the Internet is not (like) the television but
(like) the telephone, they'll see that the greatest danger is
meeting strangers.''
</P>
<P>
   In a report this year, the National Center for Missing &AMP;
Exploited Children noted 785 sex crime cases during 1999 in which a
child or adult went to see someone they had met over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Aftab said children willingly meet the strangers face-to-face
because they don't know any better. She said children need to grasp
the safety rules of the Internet, just like they should know to
look both ways before crossing the street.
</P>
<P>
   Internet safety games, along with parental guidance, can teach
children the basics: don't give personal information; don't open
e-mail files you weren't expecting; don't arrange to meet with
strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't yet found a kid killed online,'' said Aftab, author
of ``The Parent's Guide to Protecting Your Children in
Cyberspace.'' ``The kids are still safe when they're on the other
side of the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet safety experts say parents shouldn't rely on computer
programs that filter undesirable content such as profane language
and nudity from appearing on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, 61 percent of the 30,000 children who took part in
a survey conducted by children's publishing giant Scholastic Inc.
said that parents and teachers should be able to block their access
to certain Web sites. Not surprisingly, 88 percent of the 1,200
parents who participated and 94 percent of the 3,200 teachers
agreed.
</P>
<P>
   But Tallim said that keeping explicit content from children
can't protect them from predators in Internet chat rooms or help
them pinpoint shady commercial Web sites. The best way to help
children navigate the Internet safely, she said, is to give them
the critical knowledge necessary to distinguish truth from lies on
their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it comes to the Internet, the kids are ahead of the
adults as far as exploration,'' she said. ``The important point is,
they might be ahead in their activity, but they are not that far
ahead in terms of life understanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Aftab said the games emerging now can help parents who are
squeamish about talking to their children about tough issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``With these games, kids don't know they're learning,'' she
said. ``They think they're playing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
