<HEADER>
A3954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-ART-BOS     09-06 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONJOBS-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRUANT EMPLOYEES THINK THEY'RE ENTITLED, EXPERT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Call it the ``no show'' factor.
</P>
<P>
   That's the term workplace analyst Nancy Kaylor uses to explain a
growing concern that an increased percentage of employees are not
only playing hooky, they're feeling entitled to the time off.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at CCH, a consultancy that tracks human resource
issues, call the trend part of an ``entitlement mentality'' or
backlash triggered by the downsizings, mergers, and reorganizations
that left millions of workers unemployed and shell shocked in the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that people called in sick because they were
sick,'' noted Kaylor, a member of the CCH staff. ``Now, because
they are frazzled or stressed and, in some cases, working longer
hours, people are calling in sick when they aren't sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the unexpected 8 a.m. calls that come into the
bosses' desk on Friday and are usually attributed to the sniffling
that actually started at 3 p.m. Thursday. We refer to it as an
entitlement mentality because people now feel, `I deserve it. You
owe me.' ''
</P>
<P>
   After surveying 350 human resource executives from mid-sized and
large companies in the United States, CCH found while absenteeism
has declined seven percent since 1995, the percentage of
unscheduled absences due to stress and the entitlement mentality
has soared, rising to 19 percent from six percent five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The cost to large companies? About $3.14 million per year.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, family issues and personal illnesses are still the
two leading reasons for unexpected or unscheduled absences, each
accounting for 21 percent of all such absences, CCH reports.
</P>
<P>
   Still, says Kaylor, the jump in stress-related absenteeism bears
watching.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this very, very tight labor market, it falls to fewer
workers in a lot of cases to get the job done,'' she said. ``At a
certain point, having given 120 percent over days, weeks, or even
months, people begin to feel that they now deserve a break, but
they don't want to take a vacation day.''
</P>
<P>
   When CCH researchers looked at the numbers, they found
university, government, and health care workers are more likely to
take time off than any other sector. Indeed, the rate of
absenteeism among university employees increased 17 percent between
1998 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The health care industry, which experienced a 12 percent
increase during the same period, now has the highest number of
absences among all industrial sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are finding ways to ease high stress levels and
unscheduled days off.
</P>
<P>
   When First Union Corp. of Charlotte, N.C., found that some of
its 80,000 employees were routinely taking time off while others,
also hard workers, never called in sick, it instituted a PTO, or
paid time off policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved from traditional sick pay and vacation day policy to
paid time off for several reasons,'' said Angela Mull, assistance
vice president of human resources. ``The biggest one was that a lot
of people felt they were entitled to sick days. We noticed that
certain employees would sit at the office and pick up the slack all
the time. They rarely or never used their sick days.''
</P>
<P>
   The company responded by putting all paid sick and vacation days
into a bank. ``If you don't get sick, you get six additional
vacation days. . . Now, all of a sudden we don't have as many sick
people anymore. Instead of unscheduled absences, we require that
workers call in advance and schedule the day off. People don't have
to steal a day off anymore. They are entitled to them.''
</P>
<P>
   First Union also offers 10 paid days per year for people who
need time for family matters to take that time without dipping into
their paid time off. The company calls this benefit family care
time.
</P>
<P>
   Noted Kaylor, ``Paid leave banks are good for the worker and the
boss. There is no longer a situation where an employee is calling
in at the last minute. It's the last-minute no show that throws a
wrench into things for the employer and for co-workers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane E. Lewis can be reached at 617-929-2069, by e-mail at
dlewis(at)globe.com, or at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378, Boston,
MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
