<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HONDA PLANS NEW FEATURES TO BOOST ACCORD SALES 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Freshened styling,'' a longer list of standard features and
enhanced safety are among the changes for the 2001 Honda Accord
sedan and coupe, Honda says.
</P>
<P>
   The changes are designed to further broaden the appeal of the
second-best-selling car in America and perhaps help Honda regain
the lead in the all-important midsize sedan market.
</P>
<P>
   As for safety, the 2001 Accord includes dual-threshold front air
bags that monitor seatbelt use and crash severity, and then adjust
air-bag deployment accordingly. In addition, side air bags are
standard on all V-6 and four-cylinder EX models. For DX and LX
models, the side air bags will be optional.
</P>
<P>
   This advanced system prevents the passenger side air bag from
deploying if a child or small adult is leaning into the path of the
air bag.
</P>
<P>
   Styling has been refreshed, with more sharply chiseled front
fascia and hood on the sedans, along with new taillights and
revised rear deck lid.
</P>
<P>
   The ``sporting character'' of the Accord coupe is enhanced by
more aggressive front and rear bumpers, a body-color grille and new
alloy wheel designs, Honda says.
</P>
<P>
   More than 20 engineering refinements are designed to reduce road
and wind noise for a more comfortable driving experience.
</P>
<P>
   New features for 2001 include body-color side moldings and
illuminated power window switches on all Accord models except the
DX sedan.
</P>
<P>
   Standard on all EX models will be floormats and an AM/FM stereo
with in-dash six-disc CD player.
</P>
<P>
   All V-6 powered Accords will get Honda's traction-control system
as standard equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ___
</P>
<P>
   PROTECT THOSE CLASSIC CARS
</P>
<P>
   For those of you with classic cars or other vehicles that are
stored most of the time, and which need long-term protection from
the elements even while inside your garage, PDK Automotive of
Indiana now offers the CarCapsule, a patented system to seal the
vehicle inside a plastic ``bubble.''
</P>
<P>
   The clear vinyl bubble keeps dust, dirt and insects away from
the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-volt high-pressure fan, with a five-year rating, provides
continuous airflow inside the bubble to keep the vehicle dry. The
air changes inside the bubble three or four times every hour to
keep moisture from condensing on the vehicle's exposed surfaces.
</P>
<P>
   Cost of operation of the fan is less than $1.50 a month, the
company says.
</P>
<P>
   You drive the vehicle onto the laminated fabric base mat, put
the cover over the vehicle, zip it closed, and then turn on the
fan.
</P>
<P>
   The vinyl covering is 8mm double-sewn polyvinyl-chloride, the
zipper is all nylon so it won't scratch, and the base is impervious
to gasoline and oil drippings.
</P>
<P>
   Suggested retail prices range from $229 to $449, depending on
size; you can cover everything from a motorcycle to a truck. For
information, call 800-735-2822 or visit the company's Web site at
www.carcapsule.com.
</P>
