<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3957 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-ESPRESSO-2TAKES-     09-06 1218
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ESPRESSO-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 DARK AND DELICIOUS, ESPRESSO PRIMES THE PUMP ALL DAY 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DEBORAH P. JACOBS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Only Americans would think of pouring acid on the stomach
first thing in the morning,'' Marlene Dietrich reportedly said
about the national fondness for orange juice, and who knows what
wonders the work force could produce were it to abandon juice for
espresso.
</P>
<P>
   The magical properties of this beverage were first revealed to
me by my landlady in Florence, a feisty, maniacally energetic
grandmother. Fifty weeks out of the year, she and her husband
provided room and board for as many as four foreigners studying
Italian at a school in the city center. While signore had a few
responsibilities _ fetching fresh rolls every morning for
breakfast, helping load the dishwasher, and operating the cunning
cheese grater with a proprietary flourish at dinner _ signora was
the motor that drove the household, and we all knew it. A dynamo in
an apron and bravely dyed hair, she was constantly in motion,
cooking, washing up, laundering, and, at the end of the day,
ironing in the kitchen while the Italian version of ``People's
Court'' played on the TV.
</P>
<P>
   Signore spoke at a normal conversational speed and was thus
incomprehensible to me and the other students. But signora was
always careful to enunciate clearly for the foreign contingent, to
compliment us extravagantly on our vocabulary and accents (``Why,
you could be Italian!''), to exclaim over the accomplishments of
our families (``Ma pensa,'' she would breathe in admiration, ``Just
think''), and to pass politely over our mistakes (as when Ana from
Slovenia attempted to convey with the phrase ``Sendo il
telegrammo'' that she had sent a telegram home). She took us into
her confidence too, sharing her ferocious political opinions,
culinary preferences, and tales of shiftless relations.
</P>
<P>
   Signora and signore always rose before dawn, to get breakfast
ready for the students, so it was not until the day that I left
Florence, on an early train, that I had a glimpse of their private
morning routine. Wearing a stylish dressing gown, her hair in
curlers, signora was sipping an espresso from a demitasse cup, and
graciously offered me my own.
</P>
<P>
   That morning I was too distracted by the prospect of my journey
to accept, but years later I learned that this canny soul who knew
so much also knew the best way to begin the day. Nothing can
surpass the perfection of espresso first thing in the morning;
potent beyond its size, deliciously dark and licorice-y, it clears
the brain with an astonishing rapidity and then departs, leaving
only a pleasant afterglow. In both stovetop and pump-driven
espresso machines the water is forced through the finely ground
beans at high pressure, with the result that it acquires less
caffeine than drip or brewed coffee (100 milligrams per 2 ounces of
espresso as compared with 115 to 175 milligrams for a 7-ounce cup
of drip, and 80 to 135 milligrams for 7 ounces brewed). It thus is
less likely to upset the digestive system or cause insomnia, common
effects of the usual American coffee-making methods.
</P>
<P>
   One of espresso's many other virtues is how easy, quick, and
economical it is to prepare at home. The maker found in almost
every Italian household, including signora's, is the caffettiera, a
three-piece aluminum model that in the five-inch-high, three-cup
version (6 ounces of espresso) runs around $15. Even with
high-quality coffee closing in on $11 a pound, an espresso habit
won't break the budget, since you need only 2 tablespoons of ground
beans to make 6 ounces. Once you've filled the caffettiera with
water and coffee, and set it on a hot burner, it takes less than 3
minutes to bring the espresso spluttering into the top chamber of
the machine.
</P>
<P>
   The recipes that follow either use espresso as an ingredient or
pair harmoniously with it. And that brings us to the other, equally
enjoyable roles that espresso can play: a midmorning pick-me-up; a
delaying tactic after lunch, to postpone the return to work; with a
midafternoon sweet, to keep one going till supper; as the perfect
finish to a fine dinner . . . Ma pensa!
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
STOVETOP ESPRESSO &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Italians believe that you must grant the caffettiera a seasoning
period; with faithful daily use, the theory goes, it will produce
excellent espresso in a couple of months.
</P>
<P>
   French roast beans are the darkest and therefore the traditional
choice for espresso, although Italian roast and such types as
espresso blend also work well. If you don't have a good grinder at
home, ask the clerk at your local beanery to grind them
medium-fine; the result should be nearly a dust-like powder.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Water
</P>
<P>
   Finely ground French roast or other dark coffee
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the maximum amount of espresso the caffettiera will make,
fill the bottom half with cold water till just below the safety
valve mark. Set the perforated coffee basket in place and add 2
tablespoons of ground coffee for the 3-cup model, 4 for the 6-cup.
Tamp down the coffee lightly with the back of a spoon.
</P>
<P>
   Place the caffettiera on a hot burner. If you have an electric
stove, you can move the caffettiera around so that it's always
resting on a warm part of the burner. After about 2 1/2 minutes,
depending on the heat of your burner, the water will begin bubbling
as it is forced up through the ground coffee. As soon as all the
water has made it into the top chamber (you can check by carefully
tipping the pot forward; you'll be able to see the espresso in the
spout if it's done), remove the caffettiera from the heat; if you
leave it too long, the espresso will have a burned flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Any leftover espresso can be refrigerated and later reheated in
a microwave (forgive me, signora). Another use for cold espresso,
especially appealing in the summer, is to sweeten it and pour over
ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE-PISTACHIO BISCOTTI &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Karen Witt, co-owner of Nashoba Brook Bakery in West Concord,
Mass., has created an extraordinary result with this recipe:
biscotti that are not dry, like the traditional twice-baked cookie,
but moist and cookie-like. The combination of the deep-brown
biscotti and pale-green pistachios appeals to the eye as well as
the palate. Witt calls for Valrhona cocoa powder, but other brands
will work if you can't find it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 pound butter
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sugar
</P>
<P>
   4 eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 cups flour
</P>
<P>
   1 cup cocoa powder, sifted
</P>
<P>
   2 cups pistachios, toasted and roughly chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 cups semisweet chocolate chips or chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup pistachios, finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 350 degrees. Line a cookie sheet with waxed
paper or parchment.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, cream the butter and sugar together.
</P>
<P>
   Add the eggs one at a time, scraping the bowl and blending well.
</P>
<P>
   Add the flour and sifted cocoa powder. Mix until the ingredients
are just incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   Add the chopped pistachios and chocolate chunks. Mix well.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the dough in half and shape each half roughly into a log.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
