<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3959 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     09-06 1086
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN FEEDING FRENZY FOR ALL THINGS NET, SOME FIRMS BECOME LUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Viant Corp. stock fell by about 20 cents a share Tuesday in
perhaps one of the most deceptively negative bits of news floating
around the market all day.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a little pocket change per share mattered because the
Boston-based Internet consulting company had been hammered so
mercilessly Friday, when Viant announced it would fall well below
quarterly financial projections. That was on top of selling that
had gutted more than half the company's stock value the previous
two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Many other companies working in similar corners of the Internet
took a hit with Viant on its news Friday. But most of them, like
Sapient Inc. of Cambridge, Mass., regained at least a chunk of
their lost ground Tuesday in seeming recognition of a hasty
overreaction last week. Not so for Viant stock.
</P>
<P>
   Internet consulting firms of this sort, often known as
``implementors'' because they help corporate clients build their
Internet operation, have been under pressure recently because of a
growing sense that the pace of their business growth is about to
slow.
</P>
<P>
   Established companies building out Internet sites are spending
more cautiously now and dot-com companies are under so much
stock-market pressure of their own that they must cut expenses
wherever possible, the argument goes. Consultants' bills are among
the expenses thrown overboard first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there does seem to be some indication many larger
companies that were in a race to become Web-ified have taken a step
back,'' said Marc Klee, comanager of the John Hancock Technology
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors disagree that any such slowdown is really taking
place and say that revenues among the Web consulting companies will
continue to impress for at least the balance of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, the Internet is going to show good to very good
results in the fourth quarter,'' said David Smith, a technology
analyst at Loomis Sayles &AMP; Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But bits of evidence pile up. Another consulting company,
Xperior Inc. of Chicago, came out with bad forecasting news Tuesday
and lost more than 20 percent of its stock market value. Those
shares are down 42 percent since Xperior went public in December.
</P>
<P>
   The current stock market experience among Internet consultants
illustrates an important pattern that holds true across a much
broader span of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Those stocks, even most of the ones that have taken hits this
year, are still very expensive based on conventional standards.
People are willing to pay up for a group of companies that
specialize in something on the Web because revenues are growing
very fast, often 100 percent or more per year, and the firms have
some plausible explanation of how they are going to make money. In
short, they have a good story.
</P>
<P>
   But that involves more than a bit of the ``comp'' valuation
model used in real estate, in which a house is priced based on what
a comparable home in the same neighborhood sold for recently.
Announce a reason why any one company doesn't really belong in the
group _ slower sales growth, for example _ and it's a long fall
down.
</P>
<P>
   This is very bad news for the companies that miss early, because
Wall Street creates more stocks than any industry can really
support. Investment bankers will sell issues of anything popular
until people refuse to buy them any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Once a young Web company falls out of favor in comparison to its
industry competitors, bad things tend to happen and make it hard
for the stock to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Those weak shares make it harder to attract new employees or
retain those already on the job. It makes the process of raising
money needed to expand much more expensive. Customers begin to
gravitate toward the few companies perceived as leaders in their
field.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, talk about problems among the Internet consultants
gained profile last week when CS First Boston analyst Mark
Wolfenberger hammered away at Cambridge Technology Partners Inc.
and a few other stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the cast-out phenomenon played out in Cambridge long ago.
Look it over and expect more of the same elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge Technology was once the leader of the pack among
consultants, back when client-server systems were the focus and the
Internet was barely in the picture.
</P>
<P>
   The company missed the turn to the Web and has been drained of
both capital and talent ever since. Cambridge stock is now down
about 86 percent from its peak, and employee turnover has been
clocked as high as 48 percent a year.
</P>
<P>
   Cleaving between top-notch leaders and all the others in their
Internet field is likely to accelerate if the pace of customer
spending and stock market investing begins to slow.
</P>
<P>
   The question: Is that what we're seeing right now?
</P>
<P>
   No one doubts huge sums of money will find their way to the
Internet over time, but there could be fits and starts that dim
spending growth temporarily. That will ripple through practically
every segment of the Internet stock market.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Ouch! Shareholders of the Standish Small Cap Tax-Sensitive
Equity fund must still be hurting from last month's special
short-term capital gains distribution amounting to about 14.3
percent of the fund's assets. That's exactly the kind of event
tax-sensitive funds like this one managed by Boston's Standish Ayer
&AMP; Woods are designed to avoid. Chris Kelsch of Morningstar.com says
it's the biggest-ever for a tax-sensitive fund. He said the fund,
which was up more than 100 percent last year, had to sell assets to
match redemptions by many shareholders who cashed out to move with
manager Nicholas Battelle when he quit recently.
</P>
<P>
   --Back from the dead? Centennial Technologies Inc. of
Wilmington, Mass., the company former chief Emanuel Pinez rode
first to fame and finally to jail, has been soaring lately.
Centennial shares had been in the dumps ever since Pinez (now
serving five years in prison) and others were arrested in one of
the state's largest stock frauds. But they have been rejuvenated
ever since the company issued a very good quarterly report in
mid-July, soaring 140 percent to $19.75 as of Tuesday. Don't get
too excited about the comeback: Centennial's stock market value is
still just $63 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0101 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-06 0736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE UN-SECRET SOCIETY: A TELLING STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's invasion of privacy time again. Comes now Peggy Salinger,
the only daughter of reclusive author J. D. Salinger, with a
heavily promoted tell-all memoir of her famous father. Peggy, an
aspiring writer, invokes ``the examined life'' as the reason for
her expose. ``I totally respect and uphold privacy,'' she told one
interviewer. ``But not an unhealthy secrecy.'' Translation: Call my
agent for movie rights.
</P>
<P>
   I have been keeping a list of people who, for the sake of a
measly five-figure book contract or some similar pittance, have
sold out private or privileged relationships. Richard Nixon's
psychiatrist, we learn, was dying to write a book. Instead, he has
offloaded some curious half-truths about his famous patient onto
patho-biographer Anthony Summers.
</P>
<P>
   During the Monica Lewinsky imbroglio, the Rev. J. Philip Wogaman
released a book called ``From the Eye of the Storm _ A Pastor to
the President Speaks Out.'' On the one hand, Wogaman wanted
everyone to know that Clinton often worshiped at his Foundry United
Methodist Church in Washington. From the other side of his mouth,
Wogaman insisted that ``I would never exploit personal
relationships.'' London's fashionable pop therapist Susie Orbach
has given so many interviews praising herself for not discussing
her most famous patient, Lady Diana, princess of Wales, that _
well, draw your own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   I have also been keeping another, more interesting list, of men
and women who did not succumb to the Salinger Impulse. Joe DiMaggio
reportedly turned down a $2 million memoir offer because he didn't
want to write about his ex-wife Marilyn Monroe. And at the margin
of recent memory stands the oft-reviled CIA director Richard Helms,
who was charged with perjury because he declined to tell a Senate
committee about the CIA's involvement in the overthrow of Chile's
Salvador Allende. After Helms plea-bargained, a federal judge fined
him $2,000, issued a suspended sentence, and said that he had
covered himself in ``disgrace and shame.''
</P>
<P>
   Helms's gritty silence seems quaint in an era when out-of-work
CIA station chiefs rush into print with thinly veiled roman a clefs
about their derring-do in faraway lands. But it won him many fans,
not only inside the intelligence apparat, but even one inside the
journalistic establishment. Author Thomas Powers' 1979 biography of
Helms proved surprisingly sympathetic. The title: ``The Man Who
Kept the Secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Thomas Merton, the successful New York
author/boulevardier who left Manhattan for a life of silent
contemplation at the abbey of Gethsemani in central Kentucky, is
quite well known, through profiles, biographies, and his
best-selling spiritual autobiography ``The Seven Storey Mountain.''
Less known is that during his years as the Trappist monk Brother
Louis, Merton had a sexual affair with a young woman in Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   Merton's furtive phone calls to Louisville were monitored, and
he was forced to confess his transgression to his abbot. He
remained at Gethsemani, and the affair ended. Washington Post
writer Paul Hendrickson picks up the sequel: ``Margie Smith went
back to Ohio and married a doctor and raised sons. In all these
years, she has never once spoken publicly of Merton. Even Michael
Mott, the authorized biographer . . . never met her (They spoke on
the phone.) . . . She has declined to become part of a culture in
America that would reward somebody with millions for writing a book
titled ``I Was Thomas Merton's Secret Love.''
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, I tried to interview a woman once named Ann
Adden, with whom the poet Robert Lowell had a brief affair in the
1950s. He dedicated _ and later un-dedicated _ several beautiful
poems to her, and her name still survives in one poem from the
``Notebook 1967-1968'' collection. It's not hard to find her, but
there's no evidence that she wants to discuss Lowell. Neither of
his biographers records a conversation with her, and my own letter
vanished into the wilds.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, I felt thwarted, maybe even a little hurt; how could
someone doubt my motives? But I also admired her for keeping her
peace. Silence has an eloquence that sometimes speaks louder than
words.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
