<HEADLINE>
EATING CROW BEATS EATING RAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   News item: George W. Bush, the Republican nominee, rejects the
debate format proposed by the Commission on Presidential Debates.
Instead, he offers to meet the Democratic nominee, Al Gore, on
special prime-time versions of ``Larry King Live'' and ``Meet the
Press,'' and at one of the debates proposed by the commission.
</P>
<P>
   Who knows if the following e-mail hasn't already appeared on an
Air Force Two computer screen?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MEMO TO: Al Gore
</P>
<P>
   FROM: Democratic media team
</P>
<P>
   SUBJECT: A taste of his own (non-Medicare-funded) medicine
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So Dubya would rather fold this year's presidential debates into
regularly scheduled television programs. All right, then, we'll see
him and raise him.
</P>
<P>
   Let him pick any three from the following six, and you'll be
there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Antiques Roadshow''
</P>
<P>
   FORMAT: Each candidate describes his programs to a panel of
nonpartisan experts; the panel then tells him the likely cost.
</P>
<P>
   PRO: You're the policy wonk, not him.
</P>
<P>
   CON: When has a Republican domestic program ever cost more than
a Democratic one?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Ebert &AMP; Roeper and the Movies''
</P>
<P>
   FORMAT: You and Bush offer views on five leading issues of the
day, then each gives a thumbs up or down.
</P>
<P>
   PRO: It's almost like a debate, and everyone knows what a good
debater you are.
</P>
<P>
   CON: What if you give thumbs up to an issue Lieberman has
criticized for immorality?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday Night Football''
</P>
<P>
   FORMAT: Al Michaels handles the play-by-play, while you and Bush
fill in for the new guys, Dennis Miller and Dan Fouts.
</P>
<P>
   PRO: You can't be any worse at providing comic relief than
Miller has.
</P>
<P>
   CON: What if the most presidential guy in the booth turns out to
be Michaels?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor II''
</P>
<P>
   FORMAT: All this year's presidential candidates, including
third-party nominees as well as you and Bush, have to spend a night
in a function room at the Sheraton Wayfarer, in Bedford, N.H. As
presidential contenders give speeches, shake hands, and discuss the
issues, they are eliminated one by one until only a single
candidate remains.
</P>
<P>
   PRO: Eating crow beats eating rat.
</P>
<P>
   CON: Ralph Nader, the Richard Hatch of US politics?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire''
</P>
<P>
   FORMAT: Regis Philbin asks you and Bush to answer a series of
increasingly difficult questions. Each correct answer earns
ever-greater amounts of electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   PRO: Who needs lifelines? You invented the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   CON: Dubya's grades at Yale weren't that much worse than yours
at Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``WWF Smackdown!''
</P>
<P>
   FORMAT: Self-explanatory.
</P>
<P>
   PRO: You're bigger than he is.
</P>
<P>
   CON: For once, the wrestling isn't scripted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
