<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3969 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-AUTO-ACURA-SUV-HNS &LR;      09-06 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-ACURA-SUV-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ACURA'S OWN SUV TO DEBUT NEXT MONTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Acura finally is doing its own SUV thing.
</P>
<P>
   After several years of selling a rebadged version of the Isuzu
Trooper as the Acura SLX sport-utility vehicle, Honda's luxury-car
division has decided to produce its own premium sport-utility
vehicle, designed from the ground up as an Acura.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there really wasn't anything wrong with the SLX,
seeing as though it was based on the outstanding Trooper, one of my
all-time favorites.
</P>
<P>
   But it really wasn't an Acura or a Honda, and you can
understand, I'm sure, that this high-quality Japanese automaker
wants to design and build its own cars rather than using someone
else's.
</P>
<P>
   Honda and Isuzu have been trading products for several years,
and at least one of those trades will continue: Honda sells a
version of the compact Isuzu Rodeo SUV as the Honda Passport.
</P>
<P>
   Isuzu _ which no longer builds cars, just trucks _ did sell a
version of the Honda Odyssey minivan, called the Oasis, but when
Honda redesigned the Odyssey in 1999, it decided not to share the
new vehicle with Isuzu.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's why Isuzu won't be sharing its new Trooper with
Acura when the redesigned Trooper comes out in a year or so.
Perhaps that's one reason Acura chose to develop its own SUV now.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the MDX is on the way to Acura dealers and
will make its nationwide debut Oct. 5 as a 2001 model, with a price
beginning in the mid-$30,000s (about the same as the SLX).
</P>
<P>
   This is Acura's first attempt at designing a truck product from
scratch, and from all appearances, it's a great effort.
</P>
<P>
   Acura promises ``a full-featured luxury SUV that delivers
exhilarating performance.'' It was designed by Honda's Los Angeles
and Ohio research-and-development centers and will be built in
Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the new full-size SUVs that have come out recently
or are arriving this fall, the MDX adds a third row of seats that
wasn't offered in the SLX.
</P>
<P>
   As sport-utilities have increasingly taken the place of minivans
for a lot of consumers, that third seat has been in great demand.
SUVs that offer the third seat have had quite an edge on their
competitors. Many buyers had been choosing the Ford Expedition and
Lincoln Navigator over the Chevrolet Tahoe and GMC Yukon, for
instance, but for 2000 a third seat option was added to the
Tahoe/Yukon.
</P>
<P>
   The MDX will seat up to seven people, and also will offer
``outstanding all-weather handling, class-leading fuel-economy,
ultra-low emissions and an expected five-star safety rating,''
Acura says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The MDX is a no-compromise SUV,'' Acura Executive Vice
President Dick Colliver said. ``It is the first luxury
sport-utility vehicle to deliver both the sport and the utility
customers desire in one thoroughly refined package.''
</P>
<P>
   It is powered by an all-aluminum 3.5-liter, 24-valve V-6 engine
featuring Honda's patented VTEC variable valve-timing system,
connected to a five-speed automatic transmission. The engine is
rated at 240 horsepower and 245 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   Also standard will be Acura's new ``variable torque management''
four-wheel-drive system, which uses advanced electronic sensing and
control mechanisms to monitor the drive wheels and to apply power
to wheels as necessary to prevent spin. A unique locking feature,
activated by a button on the dash, sends maximum power to the rear
wheels for use in low-speed, low-traction situations.
</P>
<P>
   All MDX models meet California's new ultra-low-emissions-vehicle
standards, and have EPA estimated fuel economy of 17 miles per
gallon in the city and 23 mpg on the highway _ the best in the
class.
</P>
<P>
   The second and third rows of seats split and fold flat into the
floor to accommodate a wide variety of passenger and cargo
configurations, and all seating positions have headrests as well as
three-point seatbelts.
</P>
<P>
   Other safety features include dual-threshold front air bags,
seatbelt pre-tensioners and a passenger-side air bag system that
can sense whether someone is sitting in the passenger seat.
</P>
<P>
   Standard luxury features include leather seats (first and second
row only), leather door inserts, power windows/mirrors/door locks,
power tilt and sliding sunroof, cruise control, seven-speaker
AM/FM/cassette stereo with in-dash CD player, power adjustable
heated front seats, alloy wheels and a digital trip computer.
</P>
<P>
   Options include a touring package that adds a two-position
driver's seat and mirror memory system, eight-way power adjustable
passenger seat, roof rack, reverse-mode tilting passenger-side
mirror, exclusive alloy wheel design, and an upgraded 200-watt,
eight-speaker Bose audio system with six-disc in-dash CD changer.
</P>
<P>
   The Acura GPS navigation system will be offered as a stand-alone
option.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
