<HEADER>
A3973 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-TECH-BOSTON-LIFE-BOS &LR;      09-06 1581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TECH-BOSTON-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIOTECH R&AMP;D, BUT WITHOUT A LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NAOMI AOKI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Newbury Street is better known for its salons than its
science. But nestled among the cafes and art galleries Dr. Marc E.
Lanser spends his days pursuing breakthroughs in the diagnosis of
conditions such as Parkinson's disease and attention-deficit
disorder.
</P>
<P>
   Like many of his neighbors, however, Lanser and his company,
Boston Life Sciences, are a bit unconventional. In Lanser's case,
that means having founded a 15-employee biotechnology firm that has
only one floor of rented space, no laboratory, and no research
scientists on staff.
</P>
<P>
   Call it virtual biotechnology.
</P>
<P>
   Investors and colleagues were skeptical when Boston Life
Sciences Inc. started in 1992. The company struggled to raise just
$3 million in seed money. Eight years later, its prospects have
brightened:
</P>
<P>
   It recently raised $10 million in capital, almost doubling its
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   It is working to get Food and Drug Administration approval for
its first product, and if approved, the product, a diagnostic agent
for Parkinson's disease, would lead the company quickly into
profitability.
</P>
<P>
   And it has six more products in its pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel vindicated,'' said Lanser, the company's chief
scientific officer.
</P>
<P>
   When Boston Life Sciences started, it had a staff of four:
Lanser, a chief operating officer, a vice president, and a
bookkeeper. The company added two more in the first year. Over
time, the staff has grown to 15, including four people to manage
ongoing clinical trials and two to handle regulatory issues.
</P>
<P>
   The staff picks the technology and shepherds it from lab to
marketplace. But they turn to others to do the work: There are
contracts with Harvard University researchers to develop the
product in its rawest form. Contracts with outside labs for animal
testing and human clinical trials, with manufacturers to make the
drugs. And eventually, there will be contracts to market the
products.
</P>
<P>
   From the beginning, Lanser has argued that the business model
makes perfect sense, especially for a biotech start-up. A decade
ago, most biotech companies were built around one piece of
promising science. They'd spend upward of $2 million to build a
lab, buy equipment, and hire researchers. They'd spend millions
more testing a drug. And if the drug failed, the company crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a graveyard littered with biotech companies that had
that one great product,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With several products in the pipeline, Lanser reasoned, he could
spread the risk. If one failed, he had others to fall back on. But
it would be virtually impossible for a start-up to raise enough
capital to build lab space and hire researchers for five or six
projects. So Lanser came up with another business model _ one that
didn't require so much overhead and that allowed him to run
multiple projects.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of spending the company's capital on facilities and
payroll, Lanser spent it on research, by paying organizations that
already had the facilities and people to do the work. If a project
didn't pass a certain phase of testing, he could cancel it without
having to fire people or sell equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The company survived its first two years on less than $5
million. Over the years, it has raised about $55 million and now
has a cash reserve of $22 million. The company spends about $9
million a year, more than $5 million of which goes to research and
development.
</P>
<P>
   If Altropane is approved by the FDA late next year, as Lanser
predicts, it would be the only drug on the market designed
specifically to screen for Parkinson's. It would help doctors
detect the disease earlier and more accurately. And it would tap
into a $100 million to $125 million market.
</P>
<P>
   Lanser expects to make $30 million in the first full year of
sales, a small amount when compared to the billion-dollar proceeds
of blockbuster drugs from big pharmaceutical companies _ but more
than enough to make Boston Life Sciences profitable. It also would
put the company in a select group of biotech companies that
actually make money.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out to be a very efficient way to run things,''
Lanser said. ``I think we've proven the model can work.''
</P>
<P>
   While few companies depend on contracts to the extent that
Boston Life Sciences does (most have their own labs and
researchers), contracts, partnerships, and licensing deals are
common in the biotechnology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Companies contract with outside labs to augment their own
research. They enter into licensing deals with companies whose
science complements their own. They partner with big pharmaceutical
companies to benefit from their experience.
</P>
<P>
   But eight years ago, those deals weren't as common. The industry
was in its infancy. Investors and colleagues were understandably
leery about a biotech company that didn't even have its own lab.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds to me like they are playing on the fringes,'' one
observer said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Others questioned whether Boston Life Sciences would be able to
assure the quality of its research and keep a project on a
competitive timeline.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the concerns are valid, Lanser said. Boston Life
Sciences is just one client of many for an outside lab or
manufacturer. Sometimes, the outside organizations have conflicting
priorities. At times, they have been slower than Lanser would like.
He wanted to get Altropane to market in three or four years. So
far, it has taken seven. The industry average is 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a certain loss of control that we've become
comfortable with, but a lot of executives would not be comfortable
with it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A certain loss of control does not translate into a lack of
scrutiny, said S. David Hillson, the company's chief executive. The
staff designs the preclinical and clinical trials for all projects.
They contract with labs that have expertise in the project area _
whether it be nerve growth factors for treating stroke and spinal
cord injury, or antiangiogenic proteins for the treatment of solid
cancer. Staff members routinely call and visit the labs.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Goldberg, chief executive of New Drug Associates Inc., a
Framingham biotech company with a business model similar to Boston
Life Sciences', likes the model. He said it's leaner, more
flexible, and if managed correctly, faster.
</P>
<P>
   When starting a project, the company doesn't wait to build the
lab, hire the people, or gain in-house expertise, Goldberg said. It
can simply contract with the best people. And if contracts are
well-coordinated _ so a drug that is ready on Tuesday, for example,
is shipped directly to a lab for testing Thursday _ there is no
downtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It creates a much more nimble company,'' he said. ``And it's
something that is beginning to look interesting to people. We're at
the front edge of the wave.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Opel, an analyst at the Boston investment bank H.C.
Wainwright &AMP; Co., said more biotech companies are outsourcing
portions of their business. So last spring, when he started
following Boston Life Sciences, Opel didn't give its business model
much thought, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a major issue in my thinking,'' said Opel, who rates
the company as a buy. ``At this point, and up until now, it's been
working real well.''
</P>
<P>
   The company contracts with top scientists and does a good job of
bringing products along, he said. Testing showed that Altropane
correctly diagnosed Parkinson's in about 80 percent of patients,
exceeding the accuracy of some FDA-approved diagnostic agents for
other illnesses. The company already has an agreement with a
Canadian manufacturer to produce Altropane. Opel expects a deal
early next year with a large pharmaceutical company to market the
product.
</P>
<P>
   And if testing shows Altropane can also diagnose attention
deficit hyperactivity disorder, he said, the product could generate
$500 million in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   The company has other promising products, he said, noting its
nerve growth factor, Inosine. Although it is still in animal
testing, Inosine could be used to treat victims of strokes and
spinal cord injuries.
</P>
<P>
   If all that happens, however, Boston Life Sciences might have to
change its business strategy, Opel said. With products on the
market, a company must be able to solve problems quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Research and development needs to work closely with
manufacturing; manufacturing needs to work closely with
marketing,'' he said. ``When it's all under one company, I think
there's a greater chance of the turnaround being as brief as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lanser and Hillson don't envision bringing all those functions
under Boston Life Sciences' roof. But they know some change is
inevitable. The company will need additional staff in coming years
to manage its increasing number of clinical trials and related
regulatory issues. As it becomes profitable, it will put more
products into the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   More remarkable, however, are the company's plans to add a
laboratory, albeit a small one, and three researchers to study
protein purification. Lanser said he is spending about $200,000 on
the lab because he hasn't been satisfied with the quality of
resarch available in that area.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning, the business model as been dictated by the
recognition that science makes the company,'' Hillson said. ``And
in the end, science will continue to dictate how we run the
company.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
