<HEADER>
A3974 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-BOOK-GUCCI-BOS &LR;      09-06 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-GUCCI-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE GUCCI SAGA: SHOES, AND SOME SPIKES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
THE HOUSE OF GUCCI 
A Sensational Story of Murder, Madness, Glamour, and Greed 
By Sara Gay Forden. Morrow. 351pp. $26. 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The average consumer knows perhaps only a few key things about
Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   The consumer either owned one of the designer's purses with an
all-over double G pattern in the 1980s or had the next best thing:
a fake. Then the company seemingly disappeared, until a few years
ago, and now, you either wear the luxury retailer's horse-bit
loafers, thought to have first been created in the 1950s, or think
they're showy and overpriced.
</P>
<P>
   But there's much more to know.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Gucci, from its Florentine roots to the relaunch of
its Madison Avenue flagship store that opened this week, is
complicated and often dramatic, as Italian stories often are.
</P>
<P>
   The sordid tale spans false legend about the company's
beginnings (they were not saddlemakers for aristocrats), bitter
family fueds (which sent pocketbooks flying out of boardroom
windows, and much worse), near-financial collapse (thanks to the
Asian economic crisis), hostile-takeover attempts (by Prada and
others), a murder (of a Gucci), a conviction (of his wife), and the
meteoric rise of one of the world's hottest designers (Tom Ford).
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Gay Forden, the former Milan bureau chief for Women's Wear
Daily, had covered the many twists and turns of the company,
including the 1995 homicide of Maurizio Gucci.
</P>
<P>
   Several years earlier, he had secretly wrested control of the
company away from other family members in an attempt to restore
some of its lustre. But ultimately, he sold out under pressure to
investment bankers Investcorp in 1993 when financial prospects
looked grim. Just as he tried settling into a new life away from
the company, he was slain.
</P>
<P>
   In tragic operatic fashion, his life ended shortly before Ford
rolled out the Spring 1996 line that had fashion writers all but
using exclamation points in their reports. After a year of mounting
praise, it was the show that gave Gucci a much needed kick start,
lending gravitas to the style-setter the world knows today.
</P>
<P>
   However, Forden's book, ``The House of Gucci: A Sensational
Story of Murder, Madness, Glamour and Greed,'' is more about the
rebirth of a brand than the death of a Gucci, which is unfortunate
_ but not because the company's history is dull. Far from it.
</P>
<P>
   It's just that the chapters describing how Patrizia Reggiani
Gucci plotted to kill her ex-husband are so grippingly bizarre that
one wishes there were even more details about her consultations
with fortune tellers, her employ of potions and spells, her network
of spies, the bumbling group she lined up to do the hit, her
over-the-top fashion sense and her quick takeover _ after she had
him killed _ of the sumptuous Milan quarters which Maurizio Gucci
had just furnished for himself and his girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently suffering from a ``narcissistic personality
disorder,'' according to the judge presiding over her trial,
Patrizia plotted to kill the father of their two daughters after
years of separation, just as she suspected he was going to marry
his live-in girlfriend. ``In his wife's eyes, he committed a
unpardonable wrong: Maurizio Gucci had stripped her, through their
divorce, of formidable patrimony and an internationally recognized
name _ and the accompanying status, benefits, luxuries, and
prerogatives,'' the judge wrote in his decision. ``Patrizia
Reggiani did not intend to give these up.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even after she was arrested. Forden writes that Reggiani
Gucci adorned herself in fur and gold as she braced for the police
interrogation, despite being told such possessions would be
confiscated behind bars. The day a hired gun pumped a bullet into
his Gucci's head, she drew a one-word entry in her diary:
``PARADEISOS.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the daily life of Gucci, the company, had been anything but
paradise.
</P>
<P>
   Guccio Gucci fled his parents Florence home and their failing
straw hat company around the turn of the 20th century, landing a
job at London's Savoy Hotel, where famous guests had luxurious
leather luggage. Or so another family legend goes. His first job
back in Florence was at a leather goods company, where he learned
the trade, that glamorous baggage on his mind, before opening his
own such firm in 1921.
</P>
<P>
   Guccio Gucci's children, and their children, would one day rule
the Gucci dynasty, splintering the company into factions, and
struggling for control, or for a larger share of the pie or for
respect, as happens with so many family businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The telling of those struggles is more of straight news
accounting than a psychological soap opera, a flaw that slows the
book down. Also, the book dwells more on the earlier days of the
company than its post-1995 explosion of prosperity, a period that
could have been explored more.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this being a story that could seemingly write itself,
Forden's account seems as if she, too, is trudging through some of
the material, especially when dealing with financial details in the
thick midsection of the book. Elsewhere, even with the rich subject
matter at hand, Forden sometimes overreaches and misses the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bright red blood spatters formed Jackson Pollack-like patterns
on the doors and the white walls on either side of the entryway
where Maurizio lay,'' goes the opening paragraph in the chapter
about Gucci's murder. Maybe that's the way it looked. But the story
of the Guccis is overwrought enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
