<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3975 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      09-06 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAGAZINE-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OF ARMS AND LIBERAL SETBACKS, FATHERS AND FOUL FRONTIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is Dick Cheney, George W. Bush's vice presidential choice, on to
something? In this post-Cold War era, when individual terrorists
seem to pose more of a security threat than hostile armies, a
campaign debate over old-fashioned military preparedness feels like
a nonstarter for the swing voters supposedly ready to decide the
election on the price of drugs and the quality of schools.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the ominous ``Peace for Our Time?'' essay in the September
issue of Commentary magazine by historians Donald and Frederick W.
Kagan suggests we ought to worry a lot more about the next war.
Desperate to shatter America's global nonchalance, the writers
compare the current US situation to that of the powerful but unwary
Britain after World War I. Lulled into a false sense of security,
the English stumbled into crises involving Iraq (ironically
enough), Turkey, and Italy, eventually emboldening a rearming
Germany into concluding that ``the English were not willing to risk
a fight even for their self-proclaimed vital interests.''
</P>
<P>
   The litany of fears _ Saddam Hussein still in Iraq, flashpoints
in the Balkans and in Korea, too much reliance on the UN, and a
weakening of US will and firepower _ seems a little too ordinary to
instill much fear. So the authors settle on a more effective
method: Behind every silver lining lies a dark cloud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sky seems blue, as blue as it did for England'' they warn,
so beware the turn of the geopolitical wheel. Now here's a foreign
policy paradigm that the nation can buy: We're due for some bad
luck.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With Election Day looming, the Clinton legacy is sure to be
batted around with growing intensity. The September/October issue
of Mother Jones magazine lets two lefties dissect the man who moved
both Democrats and Republicans to the middle. Speaking for the
affirmative (and a tepid endorsement it is) is a Georgetown history
professor, Michael Kazin. He sifts through some successes, like the
Family and Medical Leave Act, some wedge issues, like the gay- and
abortion-rights stance, and some intangibles, like Clinton's
``galvanic empathy,'' to suggest that what the hell, he was better
for the left than Ronald Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   A darker view is taken by Christopher Hitchens, the journalist
and inveterate Clinton-basher, who flatly equates the current
president with Reagan. ``The Clinton years, in other words, have
completed and locked in the Reagan revolution,'' he writes,
assailing the president's cozying up to Wall Street, his
Kissinger-esque diplomacy, and his Dan Quayle-like preaching on
morality, movies, and school uniforms. ``In all essentials,''
Hitchens declares, ``the Clinton-Gore admininstration has been
Republican, and not all that moderate.''
</P>
<P>
   With friends like these, who needs Ken Starr?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only two issues old, dads magazine _ dubbed ``The Lifestyle
Magazine For Today's father _ has garnered favorable reviews in
Time magazine and The New York Times. Its September/October issue
has an eye-catching cover story featuring the top ESPN anchors
Chris Berman and Dan Patrick talking about life as a modern dad.
It's apparent that both guys try hard, but the story itself is more
than a little wistful.
</P>
<P>
   Berman recalls how his father, a mechanical engineer, regularly
took his sons to New York Jets football games, not because he liked
the sport, but because he liked watching his boys watch the game.
Patrick describes his dad as an ``everyman, a normal guy'' who was
always the loudest spectator in the gym, screaming his lungs out
for his basketball-playing son. Now, fast-forward a generation.
</P>
<P>
   On fall weekends, ``when other parents are kicking back with
their children and relaxing, Berman routinely spends 14-hour days
at the studio going through highlight tapes,'' the story reports.
And given the demands of Patrick's job, he could go two or three
weeks ``without any meaningful father-child contact.'' Not
surprisingly, both dads were on the road on Father's Day 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Dan and Chris may be good guys in cool jobs. But this story
makes you long for Ward Cleaver and the 40-hour work week.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For those looking to escape the rat race _ and fantasizing about
a home where the buffalo roam and the skies are not cloudy all day
_ the September/October issue of Country Journal has a few
discouraging words.
</P>
<P>
   A series of short essays on the future of rural America paints a
less than idyllic picture. Environmental writer Bill McKibben warns
about the deterioration of rural education. Atlantic Monthly
correspondent Eric Schlosser talks about the explosion in rural
prison construction. Author and livestock farmer Gene Logsdon flags
``agricultural pollution,'' a nice euphemism for what happens to
untended animal waste. Here's a hint: One night he awoke to find
his house infested by flies emanating from hens _ five miles away _
toiling for a major egg producer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1343EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
