<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-TRUBEK-ART-BOS &LR;      09-06 1901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-TRUBEK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 THE DELICIOUS STUDY OF FRENCH COOKING TRADITIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amy Trubek likes to use the potato as an example of the
difference between everyday French cooking and haute cuisine,
which, as the name implies, is the most elaborate cooking on the
French table. At a talk she gave recently to the students and
faculty of the New England Culinary Institute in Montpelier, Vt.,
where she teaches, she used the potato to illustrate her point. ``I
wanted to convey how much the French were committed to this idea of
mastery,'' she tells me over lunch at Boston's Maison Robert. ``A
French chef wants to show what he can do with a potato.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, almost on cue, as if the waiter had overheard Trubek
and then raced to tell Jacky Robert it was time to take a potato
and make some magic, a plate of amazingly crisp, hollow, golden
brown pommes souffles appeared. Trubek could only muster, ``That's
amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The author of ``Haute Cuisine: How the French Invented the
Culinary Profession'' (University of Pennsylvania Press), Trubek is
usually more articulate, especially on her favorite subject. The
book begins with the origins of French cooking and examines it
through the appearance of restaurants and the training of chefs,
then and now. ``Haute cuisine'' was the subject of Trubek's
doctoral dissertation in anthropology. (A dissertation on French
cooking? Raised eyebrows went with that pronouncement.) Trubek, 37,
says, ``I was not a mainstream student.'' But she understood French
cuisine from both sides of the plate _ as a professionally trained
cook and as an interested diner.
</P>
<P>
   To take a less academic but nevertheless scholarly look at the
subject, we decided to meet at Maison Robert and, course by course,
examine a traditional French meal. On a sweltering day last month,
Jacky Robert agreed to make a series of courses right out of
Escoffier. Like all cooks with classic French training, Robert (who
did an apprenticeship at Prunier in Paris, then worked at Maxim's)
still feels the influence of the late-19th-century chef and his
writings.
</P>
<P>
   Auguste Escoffier's meals consisted of many courses, including
both fish and meat. Robert followed Escoffier tradition but pared
down the number of courses. He made a tiny nibble of crabmeat in
pastry to begin the meal, then a dish of feathery quenelles (airy
fishcakes), then a classic molded squab with sauteed cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   It was after the squab _ and before a nectarine charlotte
dessert _ that Robert sent the pommes soufflees to the table. Most
cooks, says Trubek, think that ``a potato is a potato is a
potato.'' But the technique for making pommes soufflees, she says,
is one of the trickiest in the French repertoire, requiring two
deep-fat baths. Even the initial handling of the potato requires
tremendous skill. ``It has to be cut to a certain thinness and a
certain bias,'' she explains. ``Then you fry it once at a low
temperature, once at a higher temperature.''
</P>
<P>
   And voila! The potatoes form a crust the first time, without
cooking through. The second, hotter frying steams the center of the
potato, which opens to form hollows. ``You have to be ready to
waste alot of potatoes,'' Robert explainslater, when he joins us at
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Pommes soufflees belong to haute cuisine not only because of the
risk in making them, but also because they have an extravagant
feeling. Only a kitchen with extra manpower can afford to allow a
cook to hover over one serving of potatoes at the last minute.
Skill and attention show in every single little oval puff.
</P>
<P>
   All you have to do is look at a plate of food, says Trubek, to
tell the social and economic standing of the person who is going to
consume it. Traditionally in France, the upper classes ate fine
cooking, while the poorest people drank watery soup. ``In France
during the medieval period,'' she writes, ``the peasantry subsisted
chiefly on bread. Though of France, their food had no real
resemblance to French haute cuisine.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen workers formed the bridge between the working class and
the wealthy patrons. The apprenticeship system, in which young men
hardly into their teenage years went to work for little more than
room and board, gave poor boys a peek into life outside their
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``The role of the worker cannot be underestimated,'' Trubek
writes. ``Beginning in the mid-nineteenth century, chefs made
French haute cuisine more than a convenient sign of social status
for European elites. Adopting the cuisine for their own social
purposes, chefs made it a marker of their own status as elite
culinary professionals.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the first hint that chefs were about to become
celebrities. When they did, at the end of the last century, they
began mixing ethnic ingredients into classic French food.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's interesting what disappears and what stays,'' says
Trubek, as Jacky Robert's tiny bouchees a la reine with crabmeat
arrive to start the meal. These puff pastry rounds, no bigger than
silver dollars, are mini versions of the vol-au-vent, a large airy
pastry round filled with seafood or poultry _ a presentation rarely
seen today. ``Certain classic dishes are impossible to find
anymore,'' Trubek says.
</P>
<P>
   Quenelles are another of these lost dishes. Tasting Robert's two
kinds of fish mousse shaped into ovals and poached gently, Trubek
compares the two. One is made the old way, with pureed fish
combined with beef suet, bound with a panade _ in this case, cream
puff dough made quite firm. The newer quenelle contains only salmon
and cream in equal proportions. Trubek is surprised. ``I'm amazed
at how different they taste,'' she says. Rather than being heavy
and unpalatable from the suet and binding, the old technique's
result is a light, airy quenelle, one that suggests egg whites. And
the flavor is beautiful. ``You can taste the fish more,'' says
Trubek. In contrast, the modern quenelle is chewy. ``Almost
spongy,'' says Trubek. ``And the fish flavor isn't as strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert's glacage, a faintly pink, thin sauce made from lobster
bodies, cream, and yolks _ with a hint of heat from cayenne pepper
_ is another lost technique. The classic method dictates that the
chef slide the dish of quenelles and glacage under a salamander
right before sending it to the table, Robert tells us, so the edges
brown slightly and the dish stays hot.
</P>
<P>
   Many modern chefs remember making quenelles during their
training. Trubek wonders how many know the molded dish chartreuse,
the 17th-century specialty first made for the vegetarian Carthusian
monks. ``Careme brought it to the classic French repertoire,'' says
Robert.
</P>
<P>
   He has made individual chartreuses in souffle dishes, combining
braised cabbage and bacon with sauteed squab. Standing around the
edge are tiny rectangles, like a miniature deck of cards cut from
turnip, carrot, and leek. In the vegetarian tradition, he likes to
use what's available and sometimes sprinkles the edges with peas
and corn. His squab are rare, in keeping with today's style
(Escoffier would probably shudder). Trubek loves this dish, its
mildly smoky cabbage, the tender succulent squab tucked inside. She
also likes the fact that it is so flavorful.
</P>
<P>
   Student cooks at New England Culinary Institute are no longer
taught to follow Escoffier blindly, she says. Today, chefs ``don't
think they have an obligation to the whole system.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at Alice Waters saying, `I'm going to take some
aspects of this system, but I'm not going to do a lot of it.' ''
Waters's interpretations made Chez Panisse in Berkeley, Calif., one
of the most innovative restaurants in the country.
</P>
<P>
   But tradition is still an important part of a culinary
education. So is taste. Students at New England Culinary Institute
are introduced to a whole range of foods and flavors, Trubek says,
because when they begin, ``some have no sense of what goes
together.''
</P>
<P>
   People are often drawn to cooking not because of a long-held
passion, she says, but because the kitchen is perceived as a good
place to work and a steady income. They often learn taste at
school, says Trubek, and they get their passion as students.
</P>
<P>
   She learned good taste at home in Madison, Wis., because her
parents were passionate about food. She tells a story in ``Haute
Cuisine'' about going to the celebrated Le Francais restaurant
outside Chicago when she was 20 and being bowled over by the
copper, plush seating, and attentive waiters. ``I knew this was a
world I must explore,'' she writes.
</P>
<P>
   After Haverford College, Trubek came to Cambridge to work at Sue
Small's The Peacock restaurant. Small, who trained at London's
Cordon Bleu School of Cookery, encouraged Trubek to follow suit.
After London, Trubek began a master's program in anthropology at
the University of Pennsylvania. ``I wanted to become a food
writer,'' she says. ``But I stayed to get a PhD. I wanted to look
at food from a cultural perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   Haute cuisine ``was a little controversial,'' she says. ``It was
not the fashion of the times in anthropology.'' There was no
precedent in studying culinary professionals, she says.
Anthropologists tended to look at food in exotic cultures. For help
and direction, she turned to Concord food historian Barbara
Wheaton, an authority on French cooking, who is honorary curator of
the culinary collection at Radcliffe's Schlesinger Library. Trubek
spent hours at the library delving through the collection.
</P>
<P>
   She learned about trends in haute cuisine, how plates began to
have a certain look, how chefs changed their styles. Everything had
a place, foods had natural partners, and there was a certain way to
do everything in the kitchen. Cooking was codified. Filet of beef
steaks automatically meant the creamy potato dish, pommes
dauphinois. If you wanted to make a julienne strip, she writes (as
she learned at the London Cordon Bleu), you cut the vegetable into
1 1/2-inch-long pieces, then cut those into thin slices, then cut
the slices into strips.
</P>
<P>
   Chefs began veering away from classic combinations at the end of
the last century, Trubek says. But where does that leave classic
French cooking?
</P>
<P>
   If it disappears entirely, it would be a world without
charlottes. We are eating individual charlottes, which are small
rounds of pureed essence of nectarine mixed with gelatin and
whipped cream, circled with crisp ``spoon cookies,'' a cousin of
ladyfingers, but airier. Each plate is garnished with a miniature
marzipan nectarine that looks so real, at first glance two informed
diners can't figure out how Robert found such tiny fruit.
</P>
<P>
   This is Trubek's era _ classic food slightly updated to account
for new ingredients. ``What people underestimate is the mastery,''
she says. ``I'm not a conservative person. But today there's no
sense of what goes together. Great cooks and chefs keep some form
of mastery as their goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you think?'' she asks. ``If someone opened a
restaurant and served this food, would anyone come?''
</P>
<P>
   Jacky Robert thinks ``there are some great ideas to take from
the classic.''
</P>
<P>
   Trubek agrees. ``When was the last time you got pommes soufflees
at a restaurant?'' she asks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
