A3978 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u d BC-FOOD-ESPRESSO-2ND &LR;  &UR; TA     09-06 1097
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-ESPRESSO-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-ART-BOS  
 UNDATED: ... a log.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Toss together the sugar and finely chopped pistachios, mixing
well, and spread the mixture on a work surface.
</P>
<P>
   Roll each piece of dough in the mixture to form a log. The logs
should be a couple of inches shorter than the sheet pan and about 2
inches wide.
</P>
<P>
   Bake the logs on the prepared pan at 350 degrees until firm to
the touch, about 30 minutes. Remove from the oven and let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Set the oven at 300 degrees. Cut each log on the diagonal into
1/2-inch-wide pieces. Lay each piece on its flat side on the baking
sheet. Bake at 300 degrees until the biscotti are firm in the
center and lightly toasted on top, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 20 pieces.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
GINGERBREAD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The unusually dark and somewhat sticky cake produced by this
recipe goes beautifully with espresso. From ``Beard on Bread''
(Knopf, 1973).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1 cup light or dark molasses
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 to 2 teaspoons ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 or 3 tablespoons chopped candied ginger (optional)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Preheat the oven to 375 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Put the molasses in a mixing bowl, add the boiling water and
butter, and stir until well mixed. Add the salt, ground ginger, and
soda and stir lightly. Then stir in just enough of the 2 cups flour
to moisten and mix the ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   Turn the batter into a 9-by-9-by-2-inch baking pan. If desired,
sprinkle the candied ginger on top. Bake at 375 degrees for 25 to
35 minutes (or a few minutes longer if you've used the candied
ginger), or until the top springs back when pressed lightly and the
bread pulls away from the sides of the pan. Cut into 9 to 12
squares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
TIRAMISU &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although this Italian concoction has recently been eclipsed in
popularity by creme brulee, few desserts can match its wonderful
blend of flavors. Instead of the Pan di Spagna called for below,
you can use poundcake or ladyfingers. From Nick Malgieri's ``Great
Italian Desserts'' (Little, Brown, 1990).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the Pan di Spagna:
</P>
<P>
   4 large eggs, separated
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the espresso syrup:
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup very strong brewed espresso
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup Italian or other brandy
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the zabaione filling:
</P>
<P>
   3 large egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sweet Marsala
</P>
<P>
   1/2 pound mascarpone, at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the garnish:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup heavy whipping cream
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   Ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   Ground coffee or unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To prepare the Pan di Spagna: Butter and line with wax paper or
parchment a 9- or 10-inch round cake pan that is 2 inches deep.
Preheat the oven to 350 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium mixing bowl, whisk the egg yolks with the vanilla.
Whisk in half the sugar and continue to beat until very light and
frothy, about 5 minutes, either by hand, with a hand mixer set at
medium, or in a heavy-duty mixer fitted with the whip.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the flour and cornstarch and sift once to aerate the
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   In a clean, dry bowl, beat the egg whites with the salt until
they hold a very soft peak, either by hand, with a hand mixer set
at medium, or in a heavy-duty mixer fitted with the whip. Beating
faster, add the remaining sugar in a very slow stream, beating
until the egg whites hold a firm peak.
</P>
<P>
   Fold the yolk mixture into the whites with a rubber spatula.
Sift the flour and cornstarch over the eggs in three additions,
folding them in gradually. Do not overmix.
</P>
<P>
   Pour the batter into the prepared pan and smooth the top. Bake
at 350 degrees for 30 to 40 minutes, until it is well risen and
feels firm when pressed gently with your palm.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately loosen the layer from the sides of the pan with a
small knife or spatula. Invert the layer onto a rack, leaving the
paper stuck to it. Turn the layer right side up and cool it on a
rack.
</P>
<P>
   For the espresso syrup: Combine the sugar and water in a
saucepan and bring to a boil. Cool and stir in the espresso and
brandy.
</P>
<P>
   For the zabaione filling: Beat the egg yolks in the bowl of an
electric mixer or another heat-proof bowl and beat in the sugar and
Marsala. Whisk over over a pan of simmering water until thickened.
Remove and beat, either with a hand mixer set at medium, or in a
heavy-duty mixer fitted with the whip, until cold. Smash the
mascarpone in a bowl with a rubber spatula until it is smooth. Fold
in the zabaione. Whip the cream and fold it in.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Cut the Pan di Spagna into vertical slices about
1/4 inch thick. Place a layer of the slices in the bottom of a
shallow 2-quart dish, such as a gratin dish, and soak with
one-third of the espresso syrup, using a brush. Spread with half
the zabaione filling. Repeat with Pan di Spagna, another third of
the syrup, and the remaining filling. Place a last layer of Pan di
Spagna on the top and soak with the remaining syrup.
</P>
<P>
   To decorate: Whip the heavy whipping cream with the sugar until
it holds its shape and spread it on the surface of the dessert.
Sprinkle with ground cinnamon and ground coffee or unsweetened
cocoa powder. Refrigerate for several hours before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL; 
CHOCOLATE AND COFFEE POTS DE CREME &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warning: This spectacularly rich dessert, a snap to make, is
only for those equal to extreme sweets. From Nick Malgieri's
``Chocolate'' (HarperCollins, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   2 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 vanilla bean, split
</P>
<P>
   6 egg yolks
</P>
<P>
   12 ounces bittersweet chocolate, cut into 1/4-inch pieces
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup very strong espresso
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bring the cream and sugar to a boil with the vanilla bean in a
saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk the yolks in a bowl. Whisk about a third of the boiling
cream into the yolks. Return the remaining cream to a boil and
whisk in the yolk mixture. Continue to cook, whisking constantly,
another 15 or 20 seconds, until slightly thickened.
</P>
<P>
   Strain the cream into a bowl and add the chocolate. Whisk
smooth, whisk in the espresso, and pour into 8 4- to 5-ounce
custard cups or ramekins. Refrigerate until cooled.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with whipped cream or crisp cookies. For advance
preparation, cover the pots de creme with plastic wrap and
refrigerate. Uncover and leave at room temperature for an hour
before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8.
</P>
</TEXT>
