<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3979 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BO     09-06 1321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-COLUMN-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 UPTIGHT ABOUT CASUAL? HERE'S THE STYLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Evan Fox is like a lot of guys: He doesn't know what to wear.
</P>
<P>
   As office dress codes switched from corporate attire to business
casual, Fox traded one uniform, the business suit, for another:
khakis and polo shirts. The trouble is, khakis and polos are all he
finds himself wearing these days, unsure of what other types of
pants or shirts meet the ``casual'' qualification.
</P>
<P>
   So while his dry-cleaning bills are lower, his anxiety is
higher, and the 36-year-old computer engineer feels stuck in a
boring sartorial rut.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can you wear other than a polo and khakis?'' Fox wants to
know.
</P>
<P>
   It's a question causing increasing consternation as more men
open their inter-office mail and _ with equals parts dread and
delight _ find one of those ``we're-turning-business-casual''
memos.
</P>
<P>
   The solution to Fox's boring wardrobe problem, retailers say, is
that casual dressing for work means thinking more broadly, not
pulling on clothes otherwise reserved for weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should still be wearing tailored clothing,'' says Andy
Lew, Nordstrom's East Coast men's merchandise manager. ``Not
something you'd throw in the laundry . . . The big challenge is
that the word `casual' has thrown everyone off.''
</P>
<P>
   For fall, men trading in their pinstripe suits, starched white
shirts, ties, and wingtips should opt for tailored trousers, a
shirt with more texture, maybe even a wool turtleneck, a blazer
that can be added or removed, and shoes with chunkier soles in, for
example, a matte leather or suede rather than a high polish.
</P>
<P>
   Fox, meanwhile, owns nothing of the kind.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he's got four suits hanging in the closet and each can
be traced back to his days at IBM, where he was part of the
company's field organization from 1986 to just two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But those suits rarely see the light of day anymore because Fox
is now a sales engineer working for a start-up out of his Natick
house. It's a position that seldom calls for dressing up, or
dressing at all, he slyly notes.
</P>
<P>
   He's also got four or five pairs of khakis, mostly Dockers, with
a couple pairs from Structure thrown in. For shirts, he's got polos
and oxfords. There are some corduroys in the mix, but he never
wears them, afraid they're out of style. (They're not.)
</P>
<P>
   The khaki route is also a little too casual for those first
encounters with new clients, many of whom are in retail but aren't
wearing suits themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I'm not real good at,'' Fox says of that vast
middle ground of wardrobing.
</P>
<P>
   Dan McCampbell, vice president of the men's fashion division at
Saks Fifth Avenue, tried to give Fox some direction on a recent
visit to the Boston store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our suggestion is, it all begins with the jacket,'' McCampbell
said. ``You're still at work, and we feel that's appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, because blazers are often the most expensive component of
business attire, workers will have fewer of them, so choosing the
right ones can provide the proper foundation for the rest of the
wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Fox already has a navy blazer, which is a staple McCampbell said
everyone should have for dressier occasions. Beyond that, reach for
a blazer in a shade of black or in earth tones that can be worn
separately. Often, if a blazer has a textured fabric, such as a
nappy or flecked wool, or a a light plaid pattern, it can easily be
mixed and matched with different trousers. Versatility is the key.
</P>
<P>
   According to McCampbell, two or three-button jackets are the
most popular now. In other words, don't try wearing that outdated
double-breasted jacket from an old suit in this sort of casualized
ensemble. It won't work.
</P>
<P>
   After choosing a jacket _ Fox really liked a brownish wool
Canali model with a thin orange windowpane plaid _ McCampbell
recommended finding three pairs of coordinated pants.
</P>
<P>
   They included an olive wool, eventually paired with a pumpkin
flannel sports shirt and brown suede loafers; and grey flannels,
which he wore with a burgundy cotton sports shirt, an orange V-neck
sweater, and black half-boots. All the pieces were interchangeable.
Tan corduroys could also be added to the mix, making the outfits
much more laid-back.
</P>
<P>
   As for the perplexing issue of whether a shirt looks okay
without a tie, McCampbell said fabric is a key indicator. A matte
cotton, a textured fabric, or a pattern, such as plaid or check,
can easily be worn open-neck. Also, look for a less constructred
collar, avoiding shirts with collar stays, for example. And
knitwear, including turtlenecks or crewnecks in light wool,
cashmere, or silk, are also easy alternatives for fall.
</P>
<P>
   After changing out of the outfits McCampbell and his staff
chose, Fox emerged from the dressing room, back in his khakis and
black polo shirt, releasing a big sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt better in the dressier clothes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It's not an unusual phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Maysonave, author of ``Casual Power: How to Power Up Your
Nonverbal Communications and Dress Down for Success,'' says
dressing too far down, as far down as khakis and polos, can send
the wrong message to clients and have an impact on the wearer's own
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they get dressed up they go more into business mode,''
Maysonave said. ``You'll actually see their posture change,'' as
Fox's did when he tried on the outfits Saks had handpicked. ``I see
it with my clients in workshops. Shoulders come down when people
put on khakis and a golf shirt.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
CORPORATE CASUAL THIS FALL:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --TEXTURE _ Adding texture to a wardrobe is an easy way to take
the edge off business attire while still looking polished. Look for
shirts in heavy fabrics or cotton checks, as well as knit mocknecks
or turtlenecks in silk, wool, or cashmere. If a tie is still
necessary, reach for one that's woven instead of silk. Texture also
applies to blazers and socks.
</P>
<P>
   --PANTS _ Go for basic wool pants or corduroys in colors that
are easily coordinated throughout the wardrobe. Cuffs are a matter
of choice. Flat front pants are the most slenderizing.
</P>
<P>
   --JACKETS _ Choose a blazer that does not look like it's part of
a suit. Tweedy blazers or those with elbow patches work better. You
can also wear a V-neck sweater over an oxford for occasions when
blazers are not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   --FOOTWEAR _ Half-boots or shoes with a chunkier, heavy sole can
change the tone of an outfit to something more rugged or casual. So
can a woven, buckskin, suede, or matte leather shoe. The rule of
thumb is, if you can't polish it, it's casual. The same criteria
apply to belts, which, of course, should match the shoes. Even
socks _ which should always be worn _ have a way of being
casualized. Those that are thicker or subtly patterned are
considered less dressy than those solid and thin black or blue
varieties.
</P>
<P>
   --COLORS _ This fall, colors tend to be ``dusty'' blues, greens,
or roses, as well as earth tones.
</P>
<P>
   --ACCESSORIES _ Structured briefcases don't look right when the
rest of the outfit is more casual. Instead, try a carrying case in
unstructured leather or nylon. Also, techno watches made of rubber
or plastic _ which have been popular on Wall Street for the last
couple years even with the Rolex crowd _ have hit the mainstream
and may help convince younger clients that you're hip.
</P>
<P>
   --IF YOU MUST WEAR A SUIT _ For fall, the general silhouette is
a three-button jacket (which happens to be slenderizing) with a
higher lapel and flat-front pants. The leg is thinner and more
tailored. To update the suit, incorporate plaid, check, or textured
shirts and leave the double-breasted suit in the back of the
closet.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
