<SLUG> BC-HOSPITAL-SURVEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOSPITAL GROUP TO KEEP PATIENT SURVEY SECRET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The results of a major survey on what patients think is
right or wrong with Massachusetts hospitals will not be made public
because of worries about how it was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to keep the findings secret was disclosed in a
letter mailed to hospitals late last week by the Massachusetts
Hospital Association in which it warned that any public release of
the institutions' scores in the survey ``would be misleading and
improper.'' The survey, only the third of its kind, was intended to
help consumers choose a hospital and measure what, if any,
improvements hospitals have made since 1998, when a similar
patient-satisfaction survey was made public.
</P>
<P>
   The MHA said it feared the findings are tainted because of
troubles in preparing the survey, which is due to be released to
hospitals this fall. Bay State hospitals remain committed to their
first-in-the-nation bid to publicly respond to patient complaints,
the letter says, but it contends that effort has been dealt a blow
by ``widespread confusion, disappointment and frustration'' over
the survey, which was conducted by Boston's Picker Institute and
paid for by the hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The survey mixups could reflect deep-seated problems at Picker,
a highly regarded nonprofit organization that has conducted similar
surveys for groups ranging from General Motors Corp. to the US
Department of Defense. They also could prove extensive and
embarrassing to the Boston-based CareGroup hospital network that is
one of Picker's biggest financial backers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public reporting only works when the information is valid and
fair, and there were enough questions about the validity and
fairness of this data that no one felt comfortable about releasing
it publicly,'' says Andrew Dreyfus, executive vice president of the
hospital association. ``We're disappointed because we're so proud
of this project and we think hospitals have worked hard to improve
care.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Tom Delbanco, who chaired the Picker Institute when it was
founded in 1987 and still oversees its European operations, adds
that ``it would be a tragedy if a problem with our delivering
(survey) services dilutes the really important message that the
Picker adventure has brought to the nation _ of the importance of
listening to patients, learning from them, and working with them to
improve care.''
</P>
<P>
   Picker's origins go back nearly 25 years to when Harvey and Jean
Picker decided to make patient-centered care the new focus of their
family foundation, created with revenues from the sale of America's
first X-ray machines. In 1987 they launched a modest research
organization devoted to finding out what mattered to patients and
how to measure whether hospitals were delivering. The measures
worked so well that the Picker Institute was launched in 1994 to
conduct surveys and, over the last six years, it has administered
questionnaires to more than 500,000 patients.
</P>
<P>
   Picker's problems began two years ago, when it decided it needed
tighter control over data collection than it got from outside
contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Picker helped form a new company, Atlanta-based
CarePointe Research, to survey patients and write reports. In
February, however, Picker says it became clear that CarePointe
President Daryl Savell was not delivering the reports he had
promised.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's continued to fail to meet all his deadlines. And even
though he has continued to assure us that if we just give him a
little more money he'll be there, right now we have no faith,''
says Susan Edgman-Levitan, Picker's president. ``We decided in
April that we just can't keep doing this and that we had to do
those reports in-house at Picker.''
</P>
<P>
   Savell tells a different story, saying he and his firm have done
the work ``promptly and without delay.''
</P>
<P>
   The two sides are working on a settlement that would sever ties
even as Picker is trying to fix things with its current clients,
including the Massachusetts hospitals. Early on it took away
responsibility for the Massachusetts survey from Savell and gave it
to another firm. But there ended up being discrepancies in how
patients at different hospitals were handled. Some were asked about
their care two months after discharge while others were asked
several months later, opening the possibility that results might
vary because of failed memory rather than differences in care. The
length and season of the surveys also differed, which could further
skew results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we were planning to publicly release this data, all
the sampling had to be pristine so we could assure everyone we were
comparing apples to apples,'' explains Edgman-Levitan, adding that
troubles with the surveys meant that assurance could not be given.
</P>
<P>
   The setback to the Massachusetts survey is of concern across the
country, since the program was a model for California, Maryland,
and other states. Picker has worked with Bay State hospitals since
1996, and there now are 54 facilities participating that serve 90
percent of all adult patients. Each hospital pays about $5,500 for
its survey, with other costs picked up by the Massachusetts Health
Quality Partnership, a coalition of insurers, business and
professional groups.
</P>
<P>
   The first survey results, in 1997, were not made public but the
second set was released in 1998, and showed Massachusetts hospitals
outperforming their counterparts nationwide on everything from
providing emotional support for new mothers to ensuring physical
comfort after surgery. Responses to this third round of questions,
which were mailed to 39,379 patients, were eagerly anticipated as a
way to measure the effectiveness of expensive programs that
hospitals across the Commonwealth launched in 1998 to improve their
sensitivity to patients.
</P>
<P>
   The hospitals have not seen their round-three scores yet, but
they will get them sometime this fall. In their Friday letter the
Massachusetts Hospital Association and the Health Quality
Partnership made clear the findings will not be made public and
will not be not be presented in the form they were in 1998, which
made it easy to compare hospitals. ``Any public communications
about your hospital's performance'' with regard to the new survey
results, the groups added, ``would be misleading and improper.''
</P>
<P>
   Craig Melin, chairman of the hospital association and president
of Cooley Dickinson Hospital in Northampton, said he trusts that
all hospitals will honor the request to keep the scores secret. But
he added that he would feel comfortable generally telling the
public where his hospital still needs to improve and how it is
going to do that.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Picker Institute, it is trying to work out how to
honor the millions of dollars in contracts it has with clients, and
how deeply it should stay involved in the survey business. Its
surveys are used across the United States, as well as in Sweden,
Great Britain, Germany, France, and Switzerland, so it is reluctant
to shed the business. But institute officials learned from the last
year's headaches how difficult coordinating all aspects of
questionnaires can be _ and their sponsors, including CareGroup,
which has its own financial worries at Beth Israel Deaconess and
other hospitals, have learned how costly survey troubles can be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said to CareGroup and the Commonwealth Fund, `You've made
a tremendous contribution to the institute and it's unfair to keep
making you pour money in,''' says Harvey Picker, chairman of the
institute's board. ``We've got to go back to trying to make sure
that survey instruments are good and that they are done properly,
but let others do the surveying. . . . We ought to go ahead as the
organization advancing knowledge in the field and move out of the
survey business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
