<HEADER>
A3986 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-06 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     UNIONS COULD LEARN SOME LESSONS FROM THE NRA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I realize how warped this might sound, but bear
with me: Labor unions can learn a lot from watching the National
Rifle Association.
</P>
<P>
   This is about political strategy, not ideology. The NRA and
organized labor might well be at opposite ends of the ideological
spectrum, but that doesn't mean they can't learn from each other _
just as good workers can learn a lot from watching their rivals.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, both groups have a lot in common. Their basic message
is one of safety and security. The NRA wants people to feel secure
in their homes; labor wants workers to feel secure in their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the groups can go to extremes, whether it's the NRA
protecting assault weapons or a union protecting an incompetent
worker. Sometimes that makes them convenient scapegoats.
</P>
<P>
   People blame the NRA when there is a gun-related tragedy, saying
that gun control would have prevented it. Maybe, maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   People blame unions when a company crumbles, saying that the
unions tied the company's hands. Maybe, maybe not. Poorly managed
companies tend to go out of business, even if they are nonunion.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of both groups also might describe their members in
stereotypes, like heavily armed rednecks or slow-moving, apathetic
workers. But the groups wouldn't be nearly as successful as they
are if they couldn't attract large numbers of moderate, rational
people.
</P>
<P>
   What the NRA has done more effectively than unions have, though,
is to take a compelling, emotional issue and mobilize voters behind
it. That has gotten the attention of politicians and made many of
them less likely to stand up to the association.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people feel safer knowing they have a handgun at home.
A lot of other people feel safer knowing they don't. But some of
them would be perfectly willing to run out and buy a gun if they
felt threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Fear is one of the strongest emotions, even if sometimes it
borders on paranoia. The NRA capitalizes on people's fears _ not
only the fear of being attacked in their homes, but the fear of
losing what many consider is the right to protect themselves.
</P>
<P>
   If the NRA goes after a particular politician, that fear can be
a strong motivation for its members to vote the way the association
says. It can carry more weight than the politician's stands on all
the other issues put together.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, those who favor gun control can't draw on the
same strong emotions, other than from the relatively few people who
had a personal tragedy and blame the lack of gun control for it.
Most other supporters see it as a campaign issue, not the campaign
issue.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a democracy, sometimes the minority rules.
</P>
<P>
   Unions have passionate supporters, too, but most of them are
already union members, and membership has been declining for
decades. Union members make up less than one-seventh of the U.S.
work force today, compared with about one-third during organized
labor's peak in the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with many unions is their main focus is protecting
jobs _ even in dying industries. That means membership eventually
dwindles because little recruiting can be done, and the union is
often seen as an obstacle to the company's success because it is
busy clinging to the status quo rather than focusing on the future.
</P>
<P>
   As the economy changes and the country progresses, unions have
lost much of what used to give them emotional appeal. Most of the
sweatshops these days are in the high-tech industry, and workers
there make so much money they can afford to hire someone to sweat
for them.
</P>
<P>
   Because society has changed, unions aren't making the kind of
negotiating breakthroughs that they used to, such as getting a
shorter workweek or markedly better benefits. When unions were more
widespread and made negotiating breakthroughs, often their benefits
trickled down to nonunion workers, helping to make labor at least
somewhat popular even with those who weren't in a union.
</P>
<P>
   Because society has changed, unions don't have the emotional and
political rallying cry that they used to. The main issue labor
seems to push for is raising the minimum wage, which is a nice
little issue, but hardly the kind that stirs middle-class emotions.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry to say it, but the future looks bleak for labor unless it
can make that emotional connection. It's never going to find an
issue with the emotional baggage of gun control, but it needs to
search for something of substance.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know that there is an answer, but the biggest emotional
hot spot for workers these days seems to be the continuing layoffs
and the cavalier attitude some companies have about throwing people
out on the street. On top of that are unemployment benefits that
are so small as to be relatively useless to middle-class workers.
</P>
<P>
   If labor could position itself as the hero in this struggle,
using political pressure to get better treatment for all laid-off
workers, it might be able to turn things around. Even if you have
never been laid off, the fear of losing your job can be a powerful
emotion.
</P>
<P>
   As the NRA knows, people's fears can make up a powerful
political weapon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
