<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3987 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-06 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOLAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MIGHTY FOOTBALL HAS STRUCK OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARTIN F. NOLAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SAN JOSE, Calif. _ The National Football League has begun its
season on corporate logo turf with bizarrely dorky names. But from
Milquetoast Stadium to Fughedaboutit Field, dot.com sponsorship
can't conceal the bad news for the NFL: boring teams and bored
fans.
</P>
<P>
   If Ernest Lawrence Thayer wrote a football version of ``Casey at
the Bat,'' he might begin: ``It looked extremely geeky for the
Nerdville nine that day.'' Baseball, for all its ills, is much as
it was when Thayer wrote ``Casey'' in 1888. Football changes often,
not for the better.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A pallor wreathed the features of the patrons of the game.
</P>
<P>
   A straggling few got up to go, leaving there the rest,
</P>
<P>
   With that hope which springs eternal within the human breast.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One NFL hope may be that fans forget January's Super Bowl. No
problem. Only diehards remember the teams. Only those who bet
heavily recall the score. The NFL faces a rival next year, the XFL,
with smaller-market teams sporting fiercer names and gorier
graphics. The Orlando Rage franchise proclaims: ``Sensory overload
is the theme.'' The Birmingham Thunderbolts, the Las Vegas Outlaws,
and the Memphis Maniax seek fans with sensory underload. As fewer
Americans engage in physical work, the need for vicarious excitment
escalates.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then from the gladdened multitude went up a joyous yell-
</P>
<P>
   It rumbled in the mountaintops, it rattled in the dell;
</P>
<P>
   It struck upon the hillside and rebounded on the flat.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here in Silicon Valley, computer programmers and cyberwranglers
will see the San Jose Demons. As XFL marketers ask, ``What name or
symbol could be more menacing?'' The Demon major domo is named
Michael Preacher, no hellish handle. Introduced as the team's
general manager, Preacher said: ``This isn't a sissy man's game.''
Fans must take his word for it. He was a punter, a nonferocious
position, for the University of Oregon. Preacher's progress follows
the XFL's preferred formula: from a Duck to a Demon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ten thousand eyes were on him as he rubbed his hands with dirt,
</P>
<P>
   Five thousand tongues applauded when he wiped them on his shirt;
</P>
<P>
   Then when the writhing pitcher ground the ball into his hip,
</P>
<P>
   Defiance glanced in Casey's eye, a sneer curled Casey's lip.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(end poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York spoke at a
Conference of Sociological Visions at Yale University. His theme
was ``Defining Deviancy Down.'' Moynihan was prescient, as XFL
marketing proves in statements ranging from oxymoronic to moronic.
``The XFL is going to be serious football,'' says one. Another
declares: ``The XFL will be a league that allows men and women to
live out their dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   XFL propaganda evokes professional wrestling because the XFL is
wrestling's corporate spinoff. But it is also a logical destination
on the NFL's downward path from a team sport to a circus of
individual showoffs. Here, I feel sadly prophetic; in 1999, noting
the NFL's decline from a time when athletic skill and dignity were
teammates, I wrote what could be the XFL's prospectus: ``Pro
football increasingly resembles pro wrestling: trash talk
punctuated by silly dances.''
</P>
<P>
   Someone at XFL marketing agreed. Another statement guarantees
fake misbehavior: ``The XFL is never going to bottle up the natural
personalities of its players, coaches, or other personnel. Instead,
the XFL is going to showcase each person's enthusiasm and
charisma.''
</P>
<P>
   Herewith a prediction on women's pro basketball. Some
entrepreneur of lewd deviance will start the Bikini Basketball
League. Will it succeed? I hope not, but I'm a sentimentalist. I'm
from Mudville. I root for Casey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(poetry style) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Oh, somewhere in this favored land the sun is shining bright,
</P>
<P>
   The band is playing somewhere, and somewhere hearts are light;
</P>
<P>
   And somewhere men are laughing, and somewhere children shout,
</P>
<P>
   But there is no joy in Mudville_mighty Casey has struck out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Martin F. Nolan's column appears regularly in the Globe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
