<P>
   For Thursday:
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP (Undated) _ Al Gore lays out a 191-page
blueprint for ``a new prosperity'' in America, with 10 million new
high-tech jobs, expanded home ownership and a one-third boost in
family income over 10 years. George W. Bush charges that Gore has
promised ``more than he can possibly deliver'' and is setting the
stage for a resumption of federal ``red ink'' spending. By STEWART
M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-FBI (Washington) _ Senate leaders and privacy advocates
warn that a new FBI program to police the Internet threatens to
slow the growth of e-commerce and the high-tech industry. The
e-mail-sniffing system, known as Carnivore, allows agents to sift
messages to and from a targeted suspect out of the full stream of
data passing through an Internet service provider, like America
Online. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HELEN-THOMAS (Washington) _ When presidential candidates find
their issues aren't selling with the electorate, they usually warn
that the other party's policies would weaken national security.
That's what Republicans George W. Bush and Dick Cheney are doing
now _ raising a red flag that both Republicans and Democrats have
used successfully in the past. By HELEN THOMAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ While Al Gore and George W. Bush
zoom from state to state searching for votes, Bill Clinton blithely
circumnavigates the globe doing his own thing in his own way. With
less than five months left in his presidency, Clinton has
intensified his efforts to leave his mark on world and national
affairs. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON.
</P>
