<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-ADV09-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV09 
 TV TONIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (For Release: Saturday, Sept. 9, 2000) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: Please check local listings for time and channel. All
times listed are EDT unless otherwise specified.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Will ``The Sopranos'' get its due? Or will ``West Wing''
exercise a presidential veto?
</P>
<P>
   That's the big question hanging over the 52nd annual Emmy
Awards, hosted by Garry Shandling and airing on ABC Sunday at 8.
</P>
<P>
   The two acclaimed dramas tied with the most nominations _ 18
each _ must be considered the favorites in most of their respective
categories. Emmy voters' longtime preference for the tried and true
_ along with the fact that it's an election year _ suggests NBC's
traditional ``West Wing'' has the edge. But a new system that
allows Academy members to vote at home, rather than attend marathon
screenings, may bring in a wider field of voters and give HBO's
raw, brilliant Mafia drama ``Sopranos'' the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   The one thing it seems safe to count on is that the Oval Office
and the mob will be featured in Shandling's comedy bits.
</P>
<P>
   The other best-drama competitors are ``Law &AMP; Order,'' ``The
Practice'' and ``ER,'' all of which have won before and can't
compare to the two front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   For best comedy, the nominees are ``Everybody Loves Raymond,''
``Frasier,'' ``Friends,'' ``Sex and the City'' and ``Will &AMP;
Grace.'' ``Will'' is NBC's newly anointed 8 p.m. Thursday comedy
and could be a surprise winner here, but buzz for the hilarious if
traditional ``Raymond'' has been building. Smart money is not
betting this category.
</P>
<P>
   Emmy viewers will want to tune in to ABC at 7 for an hourlong
pre-show featuring red-carpet arrivals. The truly dedicated (or
demented) will start at noon with a six-hour Emmy preview on
cable's E!, followed by Joan and Melissa Rivers' catty two-hour
red-carpet show at 6.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS Saturday at 8: We're rooting for a comet,
or at least a big earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   College football, ABC Saturday at 8: Florida State at Georgia
Tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sleepless in Seattle,'' CBS Saturday at 9: The terminally
adorable Meg Ryan and Tom Hanks star in this 1993 story of
long-distance romance. To guys, though, it sorta feels like one
long International Coffee moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hispanic Heritage Awards,'' NBC Saturday at 10: Raquel Welch
and Bobby Cannavale co-host the 14th annual salute to
Hispanic-Americans with high achievement in the arts, sports and
society. Sammy Sosa and Martin Sheen are among those scheduled to
appear.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Live,'' NBC Saturday at 11:30: The series is
often criticized for being too white, but tonight's show focuses on
cast member Tim Meadows. (Hint: He's the black one.)
</P>
<P>
   ''60 Minutes,'' CBS Sunday at 7: Tick, tick, tick. TBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Speed,'' Fox Sunday at 7:30: For better or worse, Keanu Reeves
became an action star in this 1994 thriller about a SWAT team cop
who must keep a bus going more than 50 miles per hour or a madman's
bomb will explode. Sandra Bullock became a star as the bus driver.
And Dennis Hopper plays ... well, you can guess, right?
</P>
<P>
   ``On Our Own Terms: Moyers on Dying,'' PBS Sunday at 9: A
four-part series, airing through Wednesday, in which Bill Moyers
turns his thoughtful lens on the process by which we leave this
world.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OK, there's not much for the little ones this weekend, but you
have a great chance to get your bright 'tweeners and early teens
hooked on cinema (as opposed to the junk they get too often at the
multiplex today). Two cable networks are airing behind-the-scenes
shows about great movies, followed by the movies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstory,'' on American Movie Classics Saturday at 5:30,
takes on the Bette Davis classic ``All About Eve.'' The bumpy night
continues at 6 with the movie itself. ``Destination Hitchcock: The
Making of North By Northwest'' airs on Turner Classic Movies Sunday
at 8:30. The documentary is followed at 9:30 by the classic 1959
film itself, with Cary Grant and Eva Marie Saint, plus those great
scenes in the cornfield and on Mount Rushmore.
</P>
<P>
   There may be a few minor content issues to discuss with the
kids, but pretty mild stuff compared to say, the latest Adam
Sandler movie. And maybe these shows will help them understand the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Blade Runner,'' Sci Fi Saturday at 9:30: The uncut,
letterboxed director's cut of Ridley Scott's 1982 science fiction
classic. Harrison Ford stars as the private eye tracking down
rebellious androids in a dystopian future.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Football, ESPN Sunday at 8:30: Cowboys at Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confessions,'' Court TV Sunday at 10: It's becoming hard to
stir the public's outrage about reality TV, but this show has done
it. The cable network will be broadcasting real killers' taped
confessions, allegedly with the really gory stuff edited out.
Still, the show looks chilling. And all of Court TV's high-minded
rationales can't wipe away the creepy, exploitative nature of going
for ratings in this fashion. Let's all do ourselves a favor and
tune out. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ----------- &QC;
</P>
