<P>
   UNDATED _ In August and September, it's easy to miss the glory
of cactus fruit. Certainly, it's more comfortable to keep to the
air-conditioning in the dire heat. But a field trip, particularly
to the homes of wise neighbors who have xeriscaped their property,
would reveal Texas' state plant festooned with ``tunas,'' the red
fruit or ``pears'' that are the yin to the yang of the paddles of
the prickly pear cactus. This survivor may well be one of the
wonders of the flora universe. By BEVERLY BUNDY. Story will move in
``d'' food and dining category &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ROAD FOOD-LA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even without my trusty Rand McNally, it's not hard
to recognize that I'm in California. Road signs on Highway 1 direct
me to vineyards. The passenger window is open so I can hear the
ocean hitting the rocks. And when I reach Santa Barbara, the
gas-station cashier is stationed in front of a towering carved
coffee bar. She can't locate the restroom key for me, but she can
put a mean head on a cappuccino. The Pacific hem of California is
far different from the fabric that makes up the rest of the state.
Here, things seem ethereal, almost otherworldly _ until, whack, you
hit the freeways of Los Angeles. By BEVERLY BUNDY. Story will move
in ``d'' food and dining category &QL; 
