<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4007 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-OREGON-REALTY-HNS &LR;      09-06 0463
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OREGON-REALTY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COASTAL TOWN IN OREGON BECOMES PLAYGROUND FOR CALIFORNIANS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RICHARD PAOLI  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FLORENCE, Ore. _ While summer weather along the Oregon coast can
offer bright blue skies and fogless mornings, the coastal winter
can be gray, wet and windy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best weather is about five months during the summer,''
said Andy Johnson, a real estate broker in the seaside town of
Florence. ``It's just that people planning to move here, or retire
here, should know about the colder, wetter and windier days.''
</P>
<P>
   Why move to a place where the weather gets raw in winter?
</P>
<P>
   Housing prices would be one reason. Johnson's firm, Coastal Real
Estate Inc., affiliated with Coldwell Banker, does about 40 percent
of its business with Californians moving up the coast to Oregon.
``An entry-level new home here costs $150,000. Figure the costs at
about $100 a square foot,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   For $200,000 ``you'll get a lot more house,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a ``laid-back market,'' Johnson said. ``We have houses
that stay on the market for six to seven months.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a sharp contrast to many markets in the San Francisco
Bay Area and the Silicon Valley in Northern California, where
housing costs are among the highest in the nation and properties
move at a frenetic pace.
</P>
<P>
   For Florence Mayor Alan Burns, while welcoming new home buyers
to this town of 7,000, says the future population make-up is a
concern. ``We want to try and a maintain a balance of retired and
working families,'' he said. ``We need the younger folks to provide
the services that make this an attractive place to retire to.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But this is a small, rural town,'' the mayor added, ``not a
big city. And we have to preserve that character.''
</P>
<P>
   North of Florence, just past the city limits, are a number of
communities developers have designed for the California buyer.
</P>
<P>
   The homes are built in clearings among the wax myrtle, shore
pines and native rhododendrons behind the dune-edged beaches. The
developments, with names like Mariner's Village and Shelter Cove,
are often gated. ``I think that's something the builders picked up
on from the California buyers,'' Johnson said. ``It was a matter of
security because some of the homes aren't occupied all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Florence was once an active timber port and harbor for a fishing
fleet. The lumber industry casts a mere shadow now and most of the
fishing fleet has sailed away.
</P>
<P>
   But visitors to the beaches and summer vacationers have pumped
new life into many Oregon coastal towns such as Florence. And,
while that takes care of the summer, the growing number of retired
residents has given the towns a winter boost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1427EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
