<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 14:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4010 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-BACKSTAGE-TEX     09-06 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BACKSTAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSIDE RAP: DOCUMENTARY RIFE WITH RHYME, BUT NO REASON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROBERT PHILPOT 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1999, mega-hot rapper Jay-Z rounded up a bunch of friends,
rivals and label-mates and put together a hugely popular 54-city
extravaganza called the Hard Knock Life tour. Rock fans didn't have
to be intimate with rap to know many of the names _ Method Man,
Redman and gazillion-selling DMX among them _ on the
Lollapalooza-esque bill. The rappers had enough cultural impact to
make the tour an arena-filling success.
</P>
<P>
   ``Backstage,'' Chris Fiore's documentary about the tour, comes
advertised with the tag line: ``Behind the applause. Behind the
lyrics. There is the truth.'' Not so fast, bucko. Questionable
punctuation aside, the tag line advertises more than it delivers.
``Backstage'' is relentless, and the performances often ferocious,
but despite all the access the rappers granted Fiore, the movie is
too much surface, not enough depth.
</P>
<P>
   Fiore, who has done several shorter documentaries, is an
acclaimed editor. He knows how to drive the movie along, with help
from a pulsating score that's interrupted only by concert scenes.
At times, you might wish he'd slow down a little; he rarely lets a
performance linger all the way through. But then, the movie is
called ``Backstage,'' and Fiore and his crew hang out with the
rappers as they bicker, scam on groupies, throw dice, smoke blunts,
and, well, generally indulge in the sort of offstage bacchanalias
that pop stars are known for.
</P>
<P>
   The best moments in ``Backstage'' come when the rappers start
getting in the filmmakers' faces, but even the most threatening of
those moments seems more like bluster than brutality. Fiore's
juxtapositions reveal an ironic sense of humor; he cuts from a
rapper's tantrum to a goofy guided tour of the posse's bus, and
from talk about how the rappers formed a ``family'' to scenes of
bloodied noses.
</P>
<P>
   The most pointed comment comes from turntable-master Raymond
``DJ Twinz Z'' Grant, who notes that mosh-pit violence at rock
concerts never attracts the attention that violence at rap concerts
does, and the movie emphasizes the lack of violence during the tour
and includes a concert scene in which a troubled Jay-Z decides to
donate half the tour proceeds to victims of the Columbine High
School shootings. After the violence at the recent ``Source''
Hip-Hop Awards, it's refreshing to see a rapper show that much
heart.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie doesn't dig deeply enough into the frequent
dichotomy of rap _ Jay-Z might talk peace, but the music too often
celebrates violence _ and doesn't provide any revealing glimpses
into anyone's personas. For that, maybe you're better of
subscribing to ``Source.'' Maybe there you'll learn the rationales
for the frequent misogyny and tiresome boasting that detracts from
the vibrant beats and imaginative, sometimes stunning, rhymes.
``Backstage'' stops just short of being a shill, but it's still a
case of rapping to the choir.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Backstage''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Director: Chris Fiore
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Jay-Z, DMX, Method Man, Redman
</P>
<P>
   Length: 89 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ strong language, nudity, sexual situations and drug
use
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
