<HEADER>
A4011 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d B-FOOD-CONVERSATION07-C     09-06 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CONVERSATION07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Get out of the red-sauce rut and let pasta's good taste shine
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was growing up, pasta was spaghetti, and it came from
Chef Boyardee. Not the kind in the can, mind you, but the kit in
the box.
</P>
<P>
   My grandmother prepared most of my meals, and she was quite
smitten with convenience foods from a box. So I believed that pasta
was squishy noodles under a thick blanket of pasty tomato sauce
with a dusting of processed Parmesan cheese.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, I know better now. I've learned my fusilli from my
orecchiette, and, with an endless harvest of basil from my back
yard this summer, pesto has knocked tomato sauce off its throne.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, I've been working through some marvelously simple
recipes in Susan Herrmann Loomis' new ``Italian Farmhouse
Cookbook'' (Workman, $16.95) that have elevated my view of pasta
even more.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Italy, pasta is not about a bunch of sauce over something
starchy,'' Loomis explained at a recent demonstration at Cook's
Warehouse in Midtown. ``Italians really love the pasta, so they
don't hide it.''
</P>
<P>
   For ``sauce,'' Italian farmhouse cooks are more likely to step
outside the door and gather some fresh parsley, chop it and toss it
with olive oil, pine nuts and lemon zest. Nuts, herbs, cheeses,
tomatoes, sardines _ the combinations are endless and usually are
driven by what's on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta may be fresh, but just as often dried. Either way, it
won't be crammed into a pot that's too small, and then boiled to
death. Loomis walked the class through the basic techniques of
careful pasta preparation. Some of the tips I'd already practiced,
but for the last month I've followed these to the letter, with
great results.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Use a very large pot, either a big pasta cooker with fitted
colander or a large soup pot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cook pasta in an abundant quantity of water, which means more
than you ever imagined. Six quarts of water for 1 pound of pasta.
(Cook's Illustrated says, contrary to common belief, that you can
start with hot water.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Add a good quantity of salt to the water to avoid bland pasta.
If using regular table salt, use one full tablespoon of salt for 6
quarts (twice that much if using kosher or sea salt).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Make sure the water is boiling vigorously before adding pasta,
which you should do slowly, and then stir once so it cooks evenly.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Time carefully. Fresh pasta is usually cooked in 1 1/2
minutes. Dried pasta, depending on the shape and brand, takes 7 to
8 minutes for al dente, which is tender but still firm to the bite.
If adding to a hot sauce, reduce time by about 1 minute.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Drain the pasta in a colander set in the sink, or remove the
pasta quickly with a hand-held strainer or tongs. The advantage to
the latter is that you can use a bit of the pasta water with the
sauce _ a secret of many a good Italian farmhouse cook.
</P>
<P>
   If you've been in a spaghetti-and-tomato-sauce rut or are
skeptical that these steps are necessary, why not try out this dish
that's been making a weekly appearance on my table. It's one of the
easiest things in the world to make. And one of the best.
</P>
<P>
   Giusto's Pasta with Mint Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Bring a large pot of salted water to a boil over high heat.
Mince 1 cup of gently packed fresh mint and transfer to a large
bowl. Drizzle with about 1/3 cup extra-virgin olive oil. Stir in 2
minced cloves of garlic and 1/3 cup raisins, then season with salt
(and hot paprika if desired).
</P>
<P>
   Cube 1 pound of eggplant. Add the eggplant and 1 pound of a
short dried pasta, such fusilli or penne, to the boiling water at
the same time, stir once and cook about 8 minutes. Drain, saving
1/2 cup of the pasta water.
</P>
<P>
   Add the pasta, eggplant and 1/2 cup water to the mint sauce and
toss thoroughly to coat. Serve with grated cheese. Makes about 4
servings.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4012 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-CUPCAKE-RECIPE07     09-06 2943
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CUPCAKE-RECIPE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cupcakes attract all kinds of folks
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   What more proof does one need that good things come in small
packages than a cupcake?
</P>
<P>
   Kids love them. Adults love them. And cooks love them because
they are easy and versatile. A muffin/cupcake pan is ideal, but if
you don't have one, foil baking cups hold up on their own. Simply
place on a cookie sheet and fill.
</P>
<P>
   Paper liners come in so many patterns and themes, the decorating
can begin with them. And liners mean pans don't have to be greased
and floured or scrubbed. Fill the liners about 2/3 full _ generally
about 1/2 cup batter. I like enough for a nice dome to rise above
the liner.
</P>
<P>
   Recipe tester Margaret Ann Surber offers this tip for quick
filling of the cups: Pour the batter, a bit at a time, into a
pastry bag or a plastic bag with a small tip cut off one corner and
squeeze the batter into the cups.
</P>
<P>
   Cake mixes work fine, and most have cooking times for cupcakes
with the baking instructions. We give you a gussied-up chocolate
cake mix to work with below, along with a vanilla cake from
scratch. Both are excellent, all-around recipes (that work fine for
layer cakes, too). We give you some classic frostings to work with
as well. Our preparation times include about 10 minutes to frost
the cupcakes. Decorating time depends on your own ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   A treat for any occasion
</P>
<P>
   Here are just a few ideas for decorating cupcakes to fit
different occasions. We found many more super suggestions on two
Web sites. The Reynolds folks (who sell foil bake cups) have a nice
selection. Go to www.reynoldskitchens.com and do a search for
``cupcakes.'' Be sure and check out the smiling sunshine cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   Folks at www.family.com recently held a contest to come up with
a cupcake for every letter in the alphabet. Do a search for
``cupcake'' in the search field for the overall site (not in the
recipe finder).
</P>
<P>
   Check out the cake decorating supplies at your favorite grocery,
but if you want to get a little more creative, stop by a party
store, craft store or cake decorating supply store. We had good
luck at Michaels Arts and Crafts (several metro locations), Cook's
Warehouse in Midtown and Cake Art in Stone Mountain and Duluth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Ice cream cone method (below): Small, flat-bottomed ice cream
cones can substitute for paper liners so both cupcake and holder
can be eaten. Wrap the bottom half of the cones in foil and stand
them up on a cookie sheet. Spoon about 1/2 cup batter into each
cone _ leaving about a 1/4-inch rim. Carefully put the cookie sheet
in the oven and bake at 350 degrees for about 25 minutes. Then
frost and decorate.
</P>
<P>
   You may need to experiment with how far you fill the cup to get
the shape you want. For a real tall dome shape on top (to look like
scoops), bake some additional batter in paper liners, filling the
cups about halfway. Once cooled, invert those on top of the cones,
frost and decorate. These are best eaten the day they are prepared,
as the cones get soggy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Boo-tiful Cupcakes (above): Bake and frost cupcakes. (A little
orange food coloring blended into a cream cheese frosting is nice.)
Then, in a medium-size, heavy saucepan, combine 1 cup white
chocolate morsels with 2 teaspoons vegetable shortening (not butter
or margarine). Stir gently until melted.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon or brush the mixture into ghost shapes on a cookie sheet
lined with wax paper. Use chocolate sprinkles for eyes. Refrigerate
until firm, about 30 minutes, and then stand 1 ghost in the center
of each cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tailgating: Frost cupcakes with fall colors such as yellow,
orange and brown (chocolate) and sprinkle with similar-colored
sugars or sprinkles. Then insert decorator picks like footballs
into the centers. Or frost and sprinkle with school colors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Elections: You guessed it _ red, white and blue works here. We
looked for donkeys and elephants, but no luck. But it wasn't too
hard to find sprinkles, flags, cupcake liners and other decorations
in patriotic colors.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Olympics: If you're thinking of hosting some Olympics viewing
parties, pick up a package of international flag picks to stick in
cupcakes. Or create your own little Olympic competition and give
folks some decorating gels and see who can create recognizable
flags.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Coffee break: Check out the chocolate cappuccino cupcake and
mocha cream cheese frosting recipes at left. Then top with
chocolate-covered espresso beans. Brew up a pot and invite your
best friends over for a chat and a buzz.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Weddings/showers: I have a friend who had a very small
centerpiece cake made for her wedding, and then loaded up the table
with cupcakes. For a shower, why not put a mini bride and groom on
a cupcake and place it in the center of the serving tray, then
surround it with cupcakes decorated with flowers?
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Cupcake Cafe
</P>
<P>
   Vanilla Cake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 cupcakes (or two 9-inch cake layers)
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cupcake Cafe is an adorable bakery in New York that tempts
passers-by with window displays of scrumptious cakes and treats.
This cake has a delicate crumb, and it melts in your mouth _ a
great all-purpose cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   24 baking cup liners
</P>
<P>
   9 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3/4 pound (3 sticks) butter
</P>
<P>
   3 cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 cups cake flour
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons baking powder
</P>
<P>
   3/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line muffin pans with paper or foil
liners.
</P>
<P>
   Carefully separate the eggs, making sure not to get any yolk in
the whites. Put the whites aside at room temperature to be beaten
later.
</P>
<P>
   In a larger mixing bowl, cream the butter and sugar together
with an electric mixer. Beat in the egg yolks and add the vanilla,
then set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Sift together the cake flour, baking powder, baking soda and
salt and set aside. In a large mixing bowl, beat the egg whites
until they are fluffy (they should just hold their shape) but not
dry.
</P>
<P>
   Mix the dry ingredients alternately with the buttermilk into the
creamed egg-and-butter mixture. Once those ingredients are blended
(do not overbeat) gently fold in the beaten egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon batter into the cupcake liners, filling about 2/3 of each
cup. Bake for 25 to 30 minutes, until a straw or cake tester
inserted into the center of a cupcake comes out clean. Allow to
cool completely, then frost. _ From ``The Cupcake Cafe Cookbook''
by Ann Warren and Joan Lilly (Doubleday, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 283 calories, 4 grams protein, 14 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 38 grams carbohydrates, 111
milligrams cholesterol, 275 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Sour Cream Cupcake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 cupcakes (or two 9-inch cake layers)
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Start with a mix, spike it with extra cocoa and tangy sour cream
for depth, and you get a chocolate cupcake that's all-purpose and
oh-so-delicious.
</P>
<P>
   24 baking cup liners
</P>
<P>
   1 (18 1/4-ounce) package plain devil's food cake mix
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsweetened cocoa powder
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees and place a rack in center position.
Line cupcake/muffin pan with liners; set aside. Place cake mix,
cocoa powder, sour cream, oil, water, eggs and vanilla in large
mixing bowl. Blend with electric mixer on low speed for 1 minute.
Stop and scrape down sides of bowl with a spatula. Increase mixer
speed to medium and beat 2 minutes more. Pour batter into lined
cupcake pans, filling each 2/3 full. Place pans in oven. Bake until
cupcakes spring back when lightly pressed with finger and a
toothpick inserted in center of a cupcake comes out clean, about 25
to 30 minutes. Remove pans from oven and place on wire racks to
cool for 5 minutes. Run a knife around the edges of cupcake liners,
pick cupcakes up carefully with your fingertips and place on a wire
rack to cool completely, then frost. _ From ``The Cake Mix Doctor''
by Anne Byrn (Workman, $14.95)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 163 calories, 3 protein, 10 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 55), 16 grams carbohydrates, 44 milligrams
cholesterol, 197 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Variations
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Cappuccino: Dissolve 2 tablespoons instant coffee in 1
teaspoon hot water and add to the cake mix before blending with
other ingredients. This works well with the Chocolate Sour Cream
Cupcakes as well as any chocolate cake mix. Serve with mocha
variation of Cream Cheese Frosting.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with Mocha Cream Cheese Frosting): 263 calories, 3
grams protein, 15 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 52), 29
grams carbohydrates, 60 milligrams cholesterol, 245 milligrams
sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Filled: For a nice after-dinner cupcake, mix 6 ounces cream
cheese, 2 tablespoons raspberry preserves and 1 tablespoon
confectioners' sugar. Fill cupcake liners halfway with batter, then
drop a teaspoon-size dollop of filling into the center. Top with
more cupcake batter and bake as directed.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without Mocha Cream Cheese Frosting): 194 calories,
3 grams protein, 12 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 58), 18
grams carbohydrates, 52 milligrams cholesterol, 219 milligrams
sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Hostess: For that nostalgic Hostess cupcake effect, mix together
6 ounces cream cheese and 2 tablespoons confectioners' sugar. Fill
cupcake liners halfway with chocolate cake batter, drop
teaspoon-size dollops into the centers, then top with more batter.
Bake as directed. Top with chocolate glaze and chill until set.
Then melt 1 ounce white chocolate, cool slightly and transfer to a
pastry bag or small plastic bag with the corner tip snipped off.
Pipe the chocolate in curls on top of the cupcake.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (with Chocolate Glaze): 231 calories, 3 grams
protein, 16 grams fat (percent calories from fat, 62), 20 grams
carbohydrates, 57 milligrams cholesterol, 238 milligrams sodium, 1
gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Gingerbread Cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   With Lemon Cream Cheese Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes 24 cupcakes Preparation time: 35 minutes Cooking time: 20
minutes
</P>
<P>
   A little gingerbread can add a lot of spice to fall harvest
parties, tailgating spreads and Thanksgiving buffets. Top this with
the lemon variation of Cream Cheese Frosting.
</P>
<P>
   24 baking cup liners
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground ginger
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsulfered molasses
</P>
<P>
   2 large eggs, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup boiling water
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Cream Cheese Frosting (see recipe below)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons thinly sliced crystallized ginger
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place baking cup liners in muffin
tins and set aside. In a large mixing bowl, sift together flour,
ground ginger, cinnamon, cloves, allspice and salt and set aside.
In the large bowl of an electric mixer, beat butter until fluffy.
Add granulated sugar and beat again until fluffy. Add molasses and
eggs and beat until smooth. In a measuring cup, combine the baking
soda and boiling water. Stir this mixture into the molasses-egg
mixture (the mixture will appear curdled). Pour the molasses
mixture into the flour mixture, stirring to combine well. Spoon or
pipe the batter into the baking cups. Place in the middle of the
oven and bake about 20 minutes, or until a tester inserted in the
middle of a cupcake comes out clean. Remove from oven and set aside
to cool.
</P>
<P>
   When cool, frost with Lemon Cream Cheese Frosting. _ From
epicurious.com
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 259 calories, 3 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 34), 42 grams carbohydrates, 44 grams
cholesterol, 251 milligrams sodium, 1 gram fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Cream Cheese Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for 24 cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   We adapted this recipe from several similar ones and also offer
two variations: mocha and lemon.
</P>
<P>
   1 (8-ounce) package cream cheese, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup ( 1/2 stick) butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   3 cups sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl on medium speed of an electric mixer, beat
cream cheese and butter until smooth, about 3 minutes. Add vanilla
extract. Gradually add confectioners' sugar and beat until
well-incorporated.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 99 calories, 1 gram protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 48), 13 grams carbohydrates, 16 milligrams
cholesterol, 48 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Variations:
</P>
<P>
   Lemon: After adding vanilla extract and before adding
confectioners' sugar, blend in 1 teaspoon lemon juice and the
grated zest of 1 lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Mocha: Dissolve 2 tablespoons instant coffee in 1 teaspoon hot
water. Blend into cream cheese mixture after adding the vanilla
extract but before adding confectioners' sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Traditional Vanilla
</P>
<P>
   Buttercream
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for 24 cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5-7 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Familiar and yummy, this buttercream is a standard. Mix in a few
drops of food color when you want hues to match cupcake themes.
This recipe comes from ``The Magnolia Bakery Cookbook'' by Jennifer
Appel and Allysa Torey (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25) _ a wonderful place
for a cupcake pick-me-up in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) unsalted butter, very soft
</P>
<P>
   4 cups confectioners' sugar, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Place butter in a large mixing bowl. Add 2 cups confectioners'
sugar, the milk and vanilla extract. Beat with an electric mixer
until smooth and creamy. Gradually add remaining sugar, 1 cup at a
time, until thick enough to be of good spreading consistency (you
may not use all the sugar or you may want to use slightly more). If
desired, add a few drops food coloring and mix thoroughly. Use and
store icing at room temperature, keeping in an airtight container
up to 3 days.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 101 calories, trace protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 47), 13 grams carbohydrates, 16 milligrams
cholesterol, 48 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Buttercream Frosting
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for 24 cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   The chocolate version of traditional buttercream is as essential
as vanilla.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup (1 stick) butter, softened
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons milk
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces semisweet chocolate, melted and cooled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   2 cups sifted confectioners' sugar
</P>
<P>
   In the large bowl of an electric mixer, beat butter until
creamy, 2 to 3 minutes. Add milk and beat until smooth. Add melted
chocolate and beat well. Add vanilla and beat again. Gradually add
confectioners' sugar and beat until creamy and of desired
consistency._ From: ``The Magnolia Bakery Cookbook'' by Jennifer
Appel and Allysa Torey (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $25)
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 84 calories, trace protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 53), 11 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 40 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate Glaze
</P>
<P>
   Makes enough for 24 cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Standing time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This glaze is excellent on dark chocolate cupcakes or drizzled
over a 10-inch bundt cake. Try Chambord with the filled
after-dinner cupcakes we noted above; kahlua is delicious for
cupcakes served with coffee.
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces semisweet chocolate
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons ( 1/2 stick) butter or
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup cream
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons liquor or liqueur of your choice
</P>
<P>
   In medium-size saucepan over low heat, melt chocolate and butter
(or cream), stirring occasionally until completely melted. Remove
from heat and stir in liquor or liqueur. Use immediately to glaze
completely cooled dessert. Allow glaze to set for 15 minutes. _From
``The Magnolia Bakery Cookbook''
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 42 calories, trace protein, 3 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 72), 3 grams carbohydrates, 5 milligrams
cholesterol, 20 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Raspberry Pound Cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 36 cupcakes
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15-20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Jane Thompson of Mondo loves to add cupcakes to her daily
offerings of sweet things. This one has been a big hit. It's a
portable poundcake ideal for tailgating, picnics and lunch boxes.
</P>
<P>
   1 cup (2 sticks) unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 2/3 cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   6 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   Zest of 3 lemons
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Place 2 1/2-inch cupcake liners
into pan. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In the large mixing bowl of an electric mixer, cream together
butter and sugar. Add eggs one at a time, mixing well after each
addition. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, sift together flour, salt and soda. Add to
batter alternately with sour cream in three additions. Stir in
vanilla and lemon zest. Scoop into prepared cups, filling each
halfway. Drop 3 or 4 raspberries into each cup. Bake in batches for
15 to 20 minutes, or until toothpick inserted in center comes out
clean. Remove from pan and cool.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 161 calories, 2 grams protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 40), 22 grams carbohydrates, 52 milligrams
cholesterol, 55 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
