<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Those diminutive sweet treats `bring out the kid in all of us' _
and they're a snap to make
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember those long, dull afternoons at school? After the
initial two weeks, the new routine has become familiar and reality
begins to sink in _ nine more months of reading, writing and
'rithmetic.
</P>
<P>
   The playground looks sunny; the school gates invite escape. But
there's no way out. Wait a minute. Is that Joey's mom? Hey, didn't
he say today was his birthday? What's she carrying in that box?
</P>
<P>
   It's a cupcake break!
</P>
<P>
   There's no more complete, petite package of pleasure. No knives,
no plates, no forks required. Just peel back the paper and sink
your teeth into sweetness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everyone likes cupcakes. They bring out the kid in all
of us,'' said Pat Schweitzer, senior home economist in the Reynolds
Kitchens. ``And this time of year, there will be lots of occasions
to send treats to school, and birthday parties really start up
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cupcakes are ideal for grown-up gatherings, too. ``They've
become more popular for coffee breaks and office parties and
holiday parties, '' Schweitzer said.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers, after all, were the first to enjoy home-baked
cupcakes on a broad scale. The term ``cupcake'' is believed to be
of British-American origin but originally referred to the
ingredients _ a cup of flour, a cup of sugar _ much as
``poundcake'' first referred to a pound of butter, a pound of eggs,
a pound of flour.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial bakers began using paper baking cups just after World
War I, but they weren't widely marketed to the home consumer until
the 1950s. (The aluminum foil cups were called ``Shape Guards.'')
Since then, cupcakes have been a home-baking standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started serving cupcakes because it's so nostalgic,'' said
Jane Thompson, chef-owner of Mondo Bakery at Howell Mill and Huff
roads. ``I did my version of the classic Hostess cupcake just to
see what people would do. They love them.''
</P>
<P>
   Cupcakes are easy. There's no greasing, flouring or cleanup of
pans. In fact, with foil baking cups, you don't even need a special
cupcake or muffin pan. Simply place them on a cookie sheet and
fill. Most take 20 to 30 minutes to bake and less than 10 minutes
to frost.
</P>
<P>
   Cupcakes invite creativity. A basic vanilla buttercream can be
transformed with food coloring. Or simply sprinkle the tops with
colored sugars, candy bits or sprinkles, readily available in many
seasonal varieties in grocery stores. We spotted red, white and
blue sprinkles around the Fourth of July; now orange, red and brown
leaves are available for fall.
</P>
<P>
   At Cook's Warehouse, we found a multishaker of colored sugars in
orange, purple and green hues. At Cake Art in Stone Mountain, Ga.,
we uncovered oodles of cupcake-sized decorations: footballs for
tailgating, flags for Olympic or election parties, and even a
miniature bride and groom for showers or weddings. And Cake Art and
Michaels craft stores offer cupcake papers with Halloween, fall,
sports and patriotic themes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't be afraid to enlist the kids for help,'' advised
Schweitzer. Set up an assembly line or simply frost the cupcakes,
set out a number of decorations and let kids (young and old)
decorate their own.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, we offer recipes for classic vanilla, sour cream
chocolate, spicy gingerbread and tart lemon cupcakes. For
frostings, we walk you through vanilla and chocolate buttercream
and a versatile cream cheese variety. And we offer decorating tips
for cupcakes for every occasion.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, for the kid in us, cupcakes can be the occasion any
day.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan Walker writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
