r d BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE07-COX     09-06 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-CYBERSPICE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smart, nutritious snacking for kids? Yes, it's possible
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Technology, fast food, suburbia and busy working families have
taken a toll on America's kids. It's been in the news of late, but
to many parents it's no news flash that too many kids are
overweight, don't get enough exercise and have notoriously bad
eating habits.
</P>
<P>
   With both parents working, keeping up with what kids eat all day
is almost impossible. But even if they've spent more time at
McDonald's than at the kitchen table, it's never too late to
upgrade your child's nutritional profile. So quit the nagging and
visit some of these excellent sites for ideas and tips.
</P>
<P>
   SNACKING
</P>
<P>
   Since studies have shown that snacking is a big culprit in the
area of poor nutrition and that most kids snack when parents are
not around, this is a good place to start advancing toward good
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  A couple of minutes at this site will arm you with confidence
that indeed something can be done. Here are tips from the American
Dietetic Association, Center for Science in the Public Interest and
the U.S. Department of Agriculture, Center for Nutrition Policy and
Promotion. See www.healthatoz.com/atoz/fitness
</P>
<P>
   /nutritioncenter/Kidsnack.asp.
</P>
<P>
   Snacks should be kid friendly. Cut fruits and vegetables into
easily manageable, bite-size portions.
</P>
<P>
   Kids enjoy and eat more fruits and vegetables when they're
accompanied by yogurt dips and low-fat salad dressings.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid soft drinks and caffeine, and serve only juices that are
100 percent juice.
</P>
<P>
   Substitute bagels, rice cakes or tortillas for cookies,
doughnuts and other sweet baked goods. Let children add a bit of
peanut butter, jam or low-fat cream cheese to their selections.
</P>
<P>
   Limit salty, high-fat snacks. Instead, offer baked pretzels,
air-popped popcorn, dry cereal, granola or low-fat cheese and
whole-grain crackers.
</P>
<P>
   Plan ahead when going on family outings. Instead of buying
snacks at fast-food restaurants or concession stands, pack
individual snack bags.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid classifying foods as ``good'' or ``bad.'' There are only
bad diets _ when foods high in sugar, salt and fat are eaten in
excess. All snack foods can be enjoyed in moderation.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be swayed by advertising. Many prepared foods that are
packaged to catch young eyes are poor in nutrition. The Oscar Mayer
Lunchables that come with a treat and drink get two-thirds of their
calories from fat and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Mayo Clinic recognizes the importance of snacking at
www.mayohealth.org/mayo/pted
</P>
<P>
   /htm/snacks.htm. Snacking can be a good way to meet nutritional
needs, and healthy snacking should become a regular part of a kid's
daily diet. Some guidelines:
</P>
<P>
   Have healthy snacks available in a special area in your
cupboards and refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   Serve snacks at set times rather than throughout the day _ and
not too close to meals.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful with foods that may cause choking. Foods such as
popcorn, peanuts, raw vegetables and dried fruits (including
raisins) are not recommended for children younger than 3.
</P>
<P>
   If a child's diet is generally well-balanced, foods high in
sugar or fat may be used as snacks, because they can provide
calories needed for growth.
</P>
<P>
   Also listed are many snack items to keep on hand.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  At ``Healthy Snacks for Grandkids,'' at
www.grandtimes.comsnack.html, grandparents are shown how they can
positively influence their grandchildren's diets. One
tried-and-true tip tells how to smuggle healthy food into old
favorites.
</P>
<P>
   STREAMLINING HEALTHY RECIPES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Take a look at Recipe Makeover at www
</P>
<P>
   .thriveonline.com/nutrition/recipemakeover
</P>
<P>
   /index.html and you will find that you do not have to give up
familiar calorie- and fat-loaded family favorites. This free
service helps you slim down some beloved dishes. Just submit a
recipe online to Joan Salge Blake, a professor and dietitian, who
will give it the once-over, substituting ingredients, and e-mail
you a guilt-free, slimmed-down version minus a lot of calories, fat
and sodium. The archive of trimmed-down recipes includes snacks as
well as main dishes. For comparison, the original recipe is shown
next to the makeover. Her guacamole, for example, trims calories
and fat almost in half.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Eaters Digest at www.cyberdiet.com
</P>
<P>
   /modules/gi/healthysnacks/ takes the work out of finding healthy
snacks. First, they ask you to decide what you are hungry for,
selecting a category of snack: crunchy, salty, hot, sweet, smooth
or cold. Then you select a calorie range you want to abide by: 50
or fewer, 50-100, 100-150, 150-200. To further streamline your
choice, they ask you to click on options of low fat, low
cholesterol, kid friendly, low sodium, high fiber. We clicked on
crunchy, 100-150 calories and kid friendly and were treated to more
than 100 recipes with complete nutritional analyses.
</P>
<P>
   JUST FOR KIDS
</P>
<P>
   If you can get kids interested in nutrition, you have half the
battle won. There are some excellent sites that are light-years
better than sitting through a middle school health class.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  For kids old enough to surf the Internet, bookmark the links
at Smart Kids Health Zone at
cyberdiet.com/modules/sk/smartkids.html, designed to interest them
in healthy eating and nutrition. Using quizzes and games, kids can
determine their own nutritional profile. They will learn about
labeling, become familiar with the Food Guide Pyramid and get the
eye-opening nutritional lowdown on fast-food burgers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chow Club at www.cspinet.org/kids/kffk.htm offers nutritional
information and healthy recipes for cooks ages 7 to 12. Recipes
include one for blueberry pancakes with 68 calories and 2.1 grams
of fat.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  One of the best child-oriented nutrition sites we ran across
is sponsored by Dole (the pineapple people), who partnered with the
American Cancer Institute and the Produce for Health Foundation to
produce ``5 a Day'' at www.dole5aday.com. Based on the idea that
good nutrition includes five to nine servings of fruit and
vegetables daily, the site does a splendid job of presenting what
could be boring nutritional information in palatable, visually
delightful portions.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Quaker weighs in with a kids' site at www.quakerchewy.com,
which offers snacking tips, answers to questions about snacking and
ways to use ever-popular granola.
</P>
<P>
   SNACK
</P>
<P>
   New Granola
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: about 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooling time: about 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups old-fashioned oats
</P>
<P>
   1 cup slivered almonds
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup frozen apple juice concentrate, thawed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons packed brown sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup unsweetened shredded coconut
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried sour cherries or raisins
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup golden raisins
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Combine oats and almonds in a
medium bowl. Mix in juice concentrate. Add sugar and cinnamon and
toss. Spread on cookie sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Bake 25 minutes, stirring occasionally. Stir in coconut and bake
until golden, about 15 minutes. Remove from oven and cool, about 30
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Add cherries and golden raisins to granola. Stir well. Store in
airtight container at room temperature up to 1 week.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 415 calories, 11 grams protein, 19 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 38), 58 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 91 milligrams sodium, 9 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Parham writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
