<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4016 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE07-COX     09-06 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Readers point out case of fly's mistaken identity
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a recent column about the garden's occupation by beetles and
wasps and moths, oh my, I confessed to knowing nothing about a
huge, intriguing winged insect that flew in on gossamer wings and
parked on my porch in McCaysville, Ga., lending a primeval look to
the view down to Fightingtown Creek. A Fannin County friend saw my
photograph of the creature and immediately identified it as a
stonefly.
</P>
<P>
   Some insect-savvy readers wrote to differ, others sent accounts
of nonfly experiences in the garden during summer's Bug Days:
</P>
<P>
   I very much enjoyed today's article about the insects being in
charge of our world. The bugs around my house are a close second in
command to my beautiful orange and black tabby, Halle. However, the
insect you saw on that front porch was a dobsonfly, not a stonefly.
</P>
<P>
   Dobsonflies are also creek area breeders, just as the stoneflies
are. The adults lay their eggs on objects that overhang water. When
the eggs hatch, the larvae fall into the water where they prey on
anything they can overpower. And, at up to four inches long, that
is a lot!
</P>
<P>
   In the Adopt-a-Stream program, we use these aquatic larval
stages of insects to gauge the health of a stream's habitat and
water quality. Both dobsonfly and stonefly larvae are very
sensitive to pollution, and can only be found in very good quality
water.
</P>
<P>
   SHARON COWDEN
</P>
<P>
   Fulton County Adopt-a-Stream coordinator
</P>
<P>
   I enjoy reading your articles in the paper. The picture in the
Thursday, Aug. 17, column is not a stonefly but a dobsonfly. If you
look in an Audubon book on insects and spiders you can see a
picture of the larva and winged stages of the stonefly and the
dobsonfly. I fish with what I call a ``rock worm'' in the Flint
River, which is the larva stage of the dobsonfly.
</P>
<P>
   TOMMY HUCKABY
</P>
<P>
   Thomaston, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   I was reading your column this morning and noted that you had a
nice picture of a dobsonfly mislabeled as a stonefly. I'm afraid I
can't tell you a lot about dobsonflies other than the larvae of
both make good bait. According to my insect book, larvae of
dobsonflies are beneficial because they eat black fly larvae, and
stonefly larvae, when absent, are a good indicator of pollution.
</P>
<P>
   TOM TOROK
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   This afternoon I was watching the butterflies on our verbena. I
saw this little creature and called my husband out. Quick.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like a baby hummer. We were so excited. About two
inches long. Wings and two little antennae. Somewhere in the back
of my mind I remembered reading about a look-alike hummer. I dug
through my Home &AMP; Garden section and found the article you wrote
describing the hummingbird moth (winged, pointy-beaked).
</P>
<P>
   I sure was glad I had the Aug. 17 issue on hand. What fun. I
know nothing else about the hummingbird moth. It is such a tiny
little creature. Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   BARBARA PORTER
</P>
<P>
   Hoschton, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And thanks to my correspondents who espy bugs in newspapers and
read books on insects. Inspired, I went out and bought the National
Audubon Society Field Guide to North American Insects &AMP; Spiders
that Tommy Huckaby mentioned. What a bug feast. This book contains
words and pictures about critters I never dreamed of. And wouldn't
want to.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, both the stonefly and the dobsonfly are pictured and
depicted. The book, quite a learning experience, certainly makes it
look as if my porch fly was a dobsonfly.
</P>
<P>
   Could it be that a dobsonfly to many is a stonefly to some? A
fly by any name has never been so intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   LEE MAY / Staff
</P>
<P>
   Hey, that's a dobsonfly! That's what readers said about this
insect, which was identified as a stonefly in a previous column.
</P>
