<HEADER>
A4017 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-PLASTICS07-COX     09-06 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLASTICS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Plastic makes perfect: Consumers snap up product designs, both
vintage and new
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember when mere mention of the word plastic evoked images of
cheap stuff? A formal dinner served with _ gasp! _ plastic knives
and forks. An English garden strewn with plastic lawn chairs. A
weathered tombstone adorned with plastic roses.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   These days, plastics are commanding a high level of respect _
and often high prices _ that's earning them a spot in homes on the
right side of the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Better plastics are available today, and people are finally
realizing you can mix them with pieces from the entire 20th
century,'' said Scott Reilly of retromodern.com, an Atlanta
retailer that specializes in plastic furnishings and accessories.
</P>
<P>
   As consumers look back on the highlights of the past century,
many are drawn to the clean, simple lines of modern design. That
appeal, in turn, opens their minds to products created in the 1940s
through the 1960s by some of the world's most respected designers,
who recognized the potential of plastic.
</P>
<P>
   Today, many classic plastic furnishings net top dollar from
collectors of vintage design. But at the same time, advances in
manufacturing technology have made new products _ even knockoffs of
vintage pieces _ affordable by the masses. Mainstream retailers are
selling everything from plastic housewares to plastic CD storage
cabinets faster than you can burp your Tupperware.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are getting more conscious of plastic through places
like Target,'' Reilly said. ``When the economy is good, it says to
me they're interested in the way objects look. They'll pay more for
aesthetics, way beyond just function.''
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing innovations _ high-tech resins, polymers and
polypropylenes _ are allowing designers to create products that are
strong but lightweight, flexible and versatile enough for indoors
or out.
</P>
<P>
   The same material used to make crash helmets can be found in
many furnishings. ``You can throw these pieces on a cement floor,
and they won't crack,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty years ago, consumers were mesmerized by not only the funky
shapes and forms such an inexpensive material could produce but
also its radiant, translucent rainbow of colors.
</P>
<P>
   Today's plastics offer that same hook, but there's a greater
emphasis on pastels _ baby blue, citrus green, sage and tangerine _
and matte rather than shiny finishes.
</P>
<P>
   Furniture and product designers are also mixing plastic with
materials such as glass, metal and even wood. That helps consumers
who might feel skittish about plastic to blend these pieces with
more traditional ones.
</P>
<P>
   One attraction when plastic first came on the scene was its
functionality. Nowadays, who could imagine the vast array of
storage products sold by retailers such as the Container Store if
it weren't for plastic?
</P>
<P>
   Still, a half-century ago, part of the material's lure was the
obscure products that were made from it. At retromodern.com, you
can gaze at one of European houseware giant Alessi's kitschy
objects for a long time before realizing it's a butter dish, a soap
dispenser or a cigarette lighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people who buy plastics just as objects to make you
laugh,'' said Bryan Albrecht of Domus, an Atlanta contemporary
furnishings store.
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkled among the sleek chrome, wood and glass modern pieces
in his showroom are Philippe Starck's classic bright red, orange
and green stackable Bu Bu stools. On a back shelf is a candy shop
of plastic chairs, many of them reproductions of vintage furniture.
</P>
<P>
   One, Danish designer Verner Panton's famed Panton chair, which
stunned the world in 1960 as a one-piece curvaceous design made
totally of plastic, is now out of production. Vintage pieces go for
thousands of dollars. But Vitra recently reissued the design in a
less expensive plastic _ in vibrant red, blue, yellow, black and
white _ for about $200.
</P>
<P>
   The chair is a top seller for Reilly, who just three years ago
started his Internet business after surfing the Web to find
plastics for his extensive home collection. Today, the company
sells more than 5,000 products to consumers worldwide. This fall it
plans to move its tiny showroom off Monroe Drive to Midtown's 805
Peachtree Lofts building.
</P>
<P>
   At first, most of his business was vintage furnishings. Now,
that's rivaled by new designs, a sign, he said, of plastic's move
into the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   And that acceptance should only grow as interiors become
increasingly eclectic _ with traditional antiques mixing it up with
contemporary art, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly points to the Italians, harbingers of innovation in both
fashion and furniture. On a recent buying trip to Milan, he was
struck by how the city's restaurants were decorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had all this classic, old architecture,'' he said, ``and
juxtaposed with it were all these wonderful plastic chairs!''
</P>
<P>
   Sources
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond: Eight metro locations. 404-869-0457
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Domus: 1919 Piedmont Road N.E. 404-872-1050
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Retromodern
</P>
<P>
   .com: 1037 Monroe Drive N.E. 404-724-0093
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Target: many metro locations. 404-237-9494
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Alessi:
</P>
<P>
   www.alessi.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  American Plastics Council: www.plastics.org
</P>
<P>
   On the cover
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Vitra has reissued the famed Panton chair, an all-plastic
``S''-shape chair. Photo location courtesy of Nancy Solomon
Gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
