<HEADER>
A4018 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE07-COX     09-06 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-GUIDE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Locate hard to find items
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Having trouble finding a particular item? We'll try to help you
locate it. But because of the volume of mail, we cannot track down
every request. Readers whose queries are answered in the column
will receive a blue-and-cream canvas Buyer's Edge tote bag. Write
us at Buyer's Edge Find It,The Atlanta Journal-Constitution, P.O.
Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302; e-mail us at buyersedge(at)ajc.com
(please include your name, the city you live in and daytime phone
number); or call 404-582-7642
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a jellylike Greek candy, coated in
confectioners' sugar and filled with a delicate raspberry, lemon
and cherry filling. A photographer friend bought me a box from
Greece. However, since the package label is in Greek, I can't even
tell you the manufacturer. Can you help me find the candy? I've
enclosed a sample of the sweet for you to try.
</P>
<P>
   _ Harvey Bourland, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: It's a tough job, sampling candy from readers! But Bourland
is right _ it's a treat for those with a sweet tooth. We found a
similar candy at the International Bakery, 2165 Cheshire Bridge
Road N.E. (404-636-7580). A 1-pound box is $3.15. This candy is
manufactured by Krinos Foods Canada and is labeled a ``delicious,
authentic Greek delight.'' Our candy has the same consistency as
the sample but contains peanuts.
</P>
<P>
   Q: About 20 or 30 years ago, there was a superior salad
dressing, Milani's 1890 Dressing. All stores carried it, but now
the product seems to be extinct. Is it still being made and is it
available in the Atlanta area?
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert F. Elliott, McDonough, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Dress up those salad greens with your favorite Milani 1890
Dressing. It's still being produced in three flavors: French,
Italian and Red Wine Vinaigrette. However, the dressing can prove
difficult to find. You can order it from Precision Foods by calling
1-800-647-8170. A case (12 8-ounce bottles) is $20.80, which
includes shipping.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like to find the perfume Privilege. I understand that
it may not be manufactured anymore. Every time I wear it, someone
asks me what fragrance I am wearing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Marian Gravley, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   Yet another perfume request: For two years, I have been
searching for Listen, a cologne by musician Herb Alpert.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maxine McDonald, Dunwoody, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   And a final perfume plea: I am looking for the perfume Moment
Supreme.
</P>
<P>
   _ Maria Harm, Lawrenceville, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: It's back to the classics for many of you perfume lovers. All
these fragrances are at Scentimentals, 9700 Medlock Bridge Road,
Duluth (678-417-0422). Tara Ciul and her mother Anne Pelz own this
shop, which boasts more than 700 fragrances. But the duo can also
track down other scents, if they don't have them on hand.
</P>
<P>
   Privilege, which dates from 1986, is a blend of narcissus,
mosses and wood notes. A 6-ounce body powder is $20, the eau de
toilette is $25. Listen by Herb Alpert, the musician, is a melange
of florals, spices and wood notes. A 1.2-ounce bottle is $30. This
scent is also found at Perfume Outlet in Riverdale (770-997-6258).
Prices vary. Finally, Moment Supreme from Jean Patou debuted in
1929 and has a warm, subtle, spicy aroma with a floral base. A
2.5-ounce splash is $50.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I heard there's a company that makes ``green ketchup.'' Where
can I buy it?
</P>
<P>
   _ Max Nystrom, Atlanta
</P>
<P>
   A: Kids of all ages will enjoy the lastest offering from the
H.J. Heinz Co. _ Blastini green ketchup. Called EZ Squirt, the
ketchup, which gets its unusual shade via food coloring, will be on
shelves of major grocery store chains in mid-October. A 24-ounce
bottle is $1.79.
</P>
<P>
   Both the green and traditional red ketchups will be available in
a kid-friendly, easy-to-handle bottle. A new nozzle provides kids
with better control and an ultra-thin stream that directs ketchup
exactly where they want it. Heinz developed the green condiment
with input from children across the country, since they consume
more than 5 billion ounces of ketchup each year, according to
Heinz. Why green? In tests, kids said it was their favorite color.
And how does it taste? Just like the red stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I am looking for a men's skin care lotion, ``Lab Series Skin
Rebuilder,'' by Aramis. My husband always bought it at Rich's, but
the item hasn't been there recently. Is there any other place I
could find it, or could I order it on the Internet?
</P>
<P>
   _ Jutta Peine-Wolski, Peachtree City, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   A: Like many items we love, this one has been discontinued.
However, Aramis, which is part of the Estee Lauder company,
introduced U-Turn Age Defying Formula Gel as its replacement. This
product, according to a spokeswoman, ``works to firm and strengthen
the skin's appearance while protecting it from environmental
elements.'' The gel includes vitamins C and E and green tea
extract, whey protein and lactose. A 1.7-ounce bottle is $28,
available at stores with Aramis counters, including Macy's and
Rich's.
</P>
<P>
   _Contributing: Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
