</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   WTIMOR-VIOLENCE (Undated) - On the growing violence in West
Timor, where refugees from East Timor have been living for a year.
By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA-POLITICS (Buenos Aires) - In a scandal with more
twists than a soap opera, the Argentine Senate is paralyzed by
charges that 11 of its members took bribes to vote for a vital
piece of President Fernando de la Rua's economic package. By
Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   HONG-KONG-POLITICS (Hong Kong) - Two top officials at Hong Kong
University resigned Wednesday in the aftermath of an investigation
that found that they and an adviser to the territory's chief
executive, Tung Chee-hwa, had pressured a prominent pollster not to
publish surveys critical of Tung. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BRIEFS (Undated) - World news in brief.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED STATES - General
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `a' category or as noted)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ECON (Cleveland) - Vice President Al Gore presented a
voluminous and detailed spending plan for the nation on Wednesday,
promising to create 10 million high-tech jobs, send poverty to
historical lows and boost family income by a third if his policies
are put in place. By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `p' category)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ECON (Dateline to come) - Gov. George W. Bush and Dick
Cheney on Wednesday promoted their economic plan and criticized
Vice President Al Gore's. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `p' category)
</P>
<P>
   COLO-BEARS-HUMANS (Basalt, Colo.) - Because of a long hot dry
spell that withered their food supplies, and the ever increasing
number of people living closer to forests and wilderness areas,
bears have been crossing paths with humans at an alarming pace
throughout Colorado. So far, things have been worse for the bears,
about 60 of which have been euthanized, compared with only a
smattering of reported human injuries. But if conditions do not
change and home construction continues, biologists and state
officials say more dangerous confrontations are inevitable. By
Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INDIANS-CANNIBALS (Undated) - Researchers have found the
first direct evidence of cannibalism among prehistoric Indians in
the Southwest, belying the image of these people as peaceful
farmers. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPACE-SHUTTLE (Washington) - The space shuttle Atlantis is
ready to lift off Friday for the International Space Station, which
is now the size of a 14-story building. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MAFIA-ARRESTS (New York) - In what officials say is the
largest number of Mafia arrests since the 1980s, the police have
detained Mafia leaders and their underlings on charges of trying to
regain control of the construction industry through intimidation
and violence. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BELGIUM-ROYALS (New York) - On the planned visit to New York
later this week of Crown Prince Philippe of Belgium and his new
bride Princess Mathilde. By Glenn Collins.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-CONVICTION (Richmond, Va.) - The story of Earl Washington
Jr., one of the prime causes at the Innocence Project, the pro bono
DNA defense program. Six years after DNA testing raised strong
doubts about his guilt in a rape and homicide conviction,
Washington - a model prisoner with the IQ of a 10-year-old - awaits
the results of a more definitive test as his lawyers petition the
governor of Virginia Wednesday for a full pardon after 17 years in
prison. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOLS-GAY-CLUBS (Los Angeles) - A southern California school
district has reversed an earlier decision to ban a gay-tolerance
club from meeting at an area high school, settling a federal
lawsuit. Officials in Salt Lake City, Utah, have lifted a similar
ban. By Barbara Whitaker.
</P>
<P>
   (This article is tentative and may be eliminated later.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news category)
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Washington) - Congressional committees conducted
hearings Wednesday on what Firestone, Ford Motor Co. and federal
regulators knew about the problems that prompted the tire recalls.
By Keith Bradsher and Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-ASSOCIATES (Undated) - Citigroup is acquiring
Associates First Capital, the former Ford Motor financing unit, for
$31.1 billion in stock. The acquisition would cement Citigroup's
dominance in consumer finance and give it a greater presence in
Asia. By Patrick McGeehan.
</P>
<P>
   SEAGRAMS-MP3-MUSIC (Undated) - A federal judge in New York is
expected to make a ruling in the case brought by Seagram's
Universal Music unit against MP3.com. The judge ruled in April that
MP3.com, an online database of 80,000 CDs', had violated the
copyrights of the major record companies. On Wednesday, he may rule
on whether MP3.com willfully broke the law or started the service
in good faith. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-U.S.-TAX (Geneva) - On the standoff between the European
Union and the United States over a tax system that saves large U.S.
corporations millions of dollars a year. By Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   SEASIA-ECON (Singapore) - The Association of Southeast Asian
Nations has made public a report that warns that despite economic
recovery, globalization threatens the region's competitiveness as
an exporter and investment. By Wayne Arnold.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-OIL (St. John's, New Foundland) - Atlantic Canada, from
Nova Scotia to Labrador, is poised to become the next North Sea or
Prudhoe Bay, as oil and natural-gas production begins to gear up.
Newfoundland, long Canada's poorest province, stands to reap the
biggest benefit. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   (This article was scheduled earlier but later eliminated.)
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-BIZ-BRIEFS (Undated) - Short items on business news from
around the world.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``e'' news category or as indicated)
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO-FILM-FEST (Hollywood) - This year marks the 25th annual
gathering in Toronto of filmmakers, actors, agents, producers,
publicists and the ladies and gentlemen of the entertainment press,
an event that has not only grown over the decades into one of the
world's most important film markets, but become the prime launching
pad for the fall and holiday season's films. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   QUINN-HISPANIC-YOUTH (New York) - On the actor Anthony Quinn,
who will receive the Hispanic Heritage Award this week, an honor
sponsored by a coalition of 34 national Hispanic organizations that
identify role models for Hispanic youth. By Dave Kehr.
</P>
<P>
   LASCALA-OPERA-STANDEES (Rome) - When the season starts next week
at Milan's La Scala opera house, the 200 standing-room places of
the first and second galleries will no longer be on sale. This is
tragic news for its habitual dwellers, the feared and respected
``loggionisti,'' the ardent opera buffs who sit or stand in the
galleries and are said to dictate the failure or success of a
performer, a conductor or even an opera at the theater. By
Elisabetta Povoledo.
</P>
<P>
   PAGAN-BOOK-REVIEW (Undated) - Elmore Leonard's ``Pagan Babies.''
Reviewed by Janet Maslin.
</P>
<P>
   PET-HEALTH-SPAS (New York) - The latest pet spas are beginning
to offer the same therapies available to humans - from
electro-stimulation to underwater treadmills. Ten years ago,
physical therapy was mainly for people. But today, as pets become
more prized, and a booming economy creates more discretionary
income, pet care extends to surgery and $400 customized weight-loss
programs at health spas. By Julie V. Iovine.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in `l' category)
</P>
<P>
   ANGLO-AMERICAN-ROMANCE (Undated) - The British male represents
something that has gone missing from his American counterpart:
chivalry. Hence, many American women find the British male to be
the ultimate challenge. Where I live in Notting Hill,
Anglo-American alliances are practically as numerous as the
Mercedes estate cars parked outside. By Helen Kirwan-Taylor.
</P>
