<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTO-GM-SUVS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 &HT;     GM ROLLS OUT TRIO OF SUVs  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By G. CHAMBERS WILLIAMS III  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ General Motors is rolling out three new
sport-utility vehicles that are just what truck-loving Texas
consumers ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The three models are the all-new 2002 Cadillac Escalade, 2001
GMC Yukon Denali and 2001 GMC Yukon Denali XL (better known as the
Suburban).
</P>
<P>
   The Escalade, a full-size sport-utility based on the Yukon and
the Chevrolet Tahoe, will be built in General Motors' Arlington
plant, and will go on sale in January as an early 2002 model.
</P>
<P>
   And the Denali and Denali XL, the most expensive, most upscale
versions of the Yukon brand from GM's Janesville, Wis., factory,
will go on sale in mid-October as 2001 models. The Yukon and
Escalade are the same size as the Chevy Tahoe, while the Yukon XL
is GMC's new name for its version of the Suburban, a slightly
longer Yukon/Tahoe.
</P>
<P>
   This past model year, GM introduced the completely revised
Tahoe, Yukon, Suburban and Yukon XL, based on the all-new
full-sized GM pickups that debuted in 1999. Now, these upscale
versions of the Yukon Denali (Denali is the American Indian name
for Mount McKinley, meaning ``the high one'') as well as the new
Escalade are coming to market.
</P>
<P>
   All three of these high-end vehicles are expected to do well in
Texas, where General Motors' Suburban has been a best-seller for
decades.
</P>
<P>
   For Cadillac dealers, the Escalade promises to bring even more
younger, affluent and educated buyers into their showrooms than
ever, a shift that is essential to the survival of the Cadillac
brand.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors hastily introduced the first Escalade two years
ago as a gussied-up version of the Tahoe and Yukon to meet the
competition from the Lincoln Navigator, Ford's upscale version of
the full-size Expedition.
</P>
<P>
   Almost since the day the Escalade was introduced, GM has been
working on its replacement, and even though the first version sold
well, this new one is much more of a Cadillac and should give the
Navigator some serious competition, dealers say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had customer interest in it for six months, and we
already have a list of customers waiting for it,'' said Steve
Sinclair, sales manager for Cavender Cadillac in San Antonio. ``All
we have to show them so far is some pictures of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Many would-be Escalade buyers over the past two years chose the
Navigator instead, because it had a third row of seats and the
Escalade didn't, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The new Escalade fixes that. The third seat is standard, and
with a bench seat in the middle row and two bucket seats up front,
it will hold up to seven people. And to add cargo capacity, the
third seat is split into two easily removable sections that weigh
just 35 pounds each.
</P>
<P>
   ``That third seat is a huge plus factor for us,'' Sinclair said.
``There were people coming in before who had small children or
carpools and needed that extra seating capacity, and we just didn't
have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other amenities that make it more of a Cadillac than before
include the StabiliTrak vehicle-stability system that is exclusive
to the Cadillac brand, as well as dual-zone automatic climate
control, a premium Bose audio system and Cadillac's new ultrasonic
rear parking-assist system, he said.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, GM will offer a two-wheel-drive version of
the Escalade, aimed specifically at Sun Belt markets where
customers don't particularly need four-wheel drive, said Cadillac
spokesman Mike Albano.
</P>
<P>
   The two-wheel-drive model will come with a new Vortec 5.3-liter
V-8 engine rated at 285 horsepower and 325 foot-pounds of torque,
up from 255 hp in the 5.7-liter V-8 that came with the original
Escalade.
</P>
<P>
   Four-wheel-drive models come with a special version of GM's
Vortec 6.0-liter V-8, exclusive to the Escalade with its 345
horsepower and 380 foot-pounds of torque. That's more power than
any other GM sport-utility and far more than any other SUV in this
class.
</P>
<P>
   The Denali and Denali XL will have a version of the 6.0-liter
V-8 that turns out 320 horsepower and 365 foot-pounds of torque.
</P>
<P>
   The extra power is just one way that GM will differentiate the
Escalade from the Denali. Price is another. Although no prices have
been announced yet for the Escalade, expect it to be a bit higher
priced than the Yukon Denali, which lists for $46,650 including
destination charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will cost more than the Denali because of the extra power
and some of the other Cadillac amenities,'' Albano said. The
current generation of the Escalade starts at about $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   The Denali and XL Denali ``have a confident, powerful new look
that underscores their enhanced capabilities and a higher degree of
refinement,'' GM says. They are slightly taller and wider than the
previous generation Yukon and Suburban, which helps provide
significantly more interior passenger room and added storage
capacity. Still, both fit into a standard residential garage, and
the Denali is sized for regular parking spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Length of the Denali is 198.9 inches, the same as the Escalade.
The larger Denali XL, with even more interior room, is 219.3 inches
long, like the Suburban and Yukon XL.
</P>
<P>
   The Denali XL, the fanciest Suburban to come straight from any
GM factory, will list for $48,185, including destination, and will
be exclusive to the GMC truck brand, said Lisa Grutta, assistant
brand manager for Denali.
</P>
<P>
   ``There won't be such an upscale version of the Chevrolet
Suburban, and there won't be an Escalade in the Suburban body
length,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Now, many Suburban and Yukon XL buyers in Texas have their
vehicles customized and upgraded by aftermarket companies that
specialize in those brands. Grutta said she doesn't believe that
the new Denali XL will put any of those companies out of business,
but that the Denali XL will appeal to consumers who don't want the
uncertainties over factory warranty coverage that come with such
aftermarket customization.
</P>
<P>
   GMC dealers already are taking orders for the Denali and Denali
XL, which go into production Oct. 1. But Cadillac dealers don't yet
have the authority to take orders for the Escalade, Sinclair said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're taking names and will contact our customers when we can
begin taking orders,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Demographics for the Escalade are a bit different from those for
the Denali and Denali XL, in that Escalade buyers are expected to
have an average household income of about $155,000, compared with
$110,000 or more for Denali buyers, GM said.
</P>
<P>
   Escalade's current sales proportion of 35 percent to female
buyers is expected to climb to 45 percent because of the third row
of seats, Albano said. Consumers are expected to be primarily
well-educated people, with an average age of 45 (down from
Escalade's current average buyer age of 50).
</P>
<P>
   For Denali, the managerial and entrepreneurial ranks are
expected to be well-represented among buyers, and the average age
of 45 also is expected for this brand, Grutta said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact G. Chambers Williams III by telephone at 210-250-3236
or by e-mail chambers(at)express-news.net)
</P>
