<HEADER>
A4033 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     09-06 1043
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PASTA, GNOCCHI: DELICIOUS IN ANY LANGUAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We're all Italian today.
</P>
<P>
   Shari Pitts lost one of her favorite recipes, the bow-tie pasta
with cream and ham that was served at the Worthington hotel (now
the Renaissance Worthington in downtown Fort Worth). We ran that
recipe in 1993, and here it is from our files.
</P>
<P>
   Then I received a request from John Long of Arlington, Texas,
for gnocchi, the potato pasta from Italy. Gnocchi means ``lumps''
in Italian, and that's pretty much what they resemble. Usually, the
gnocchi are ball-shaped and served with the same sauces you'd see
with spaghetti. You don't want a heavy sauce with these little guys
_ something that bathes them in flavor is best; a butter sauce, a
cream sauce or a tomato sauce all work well. We're running chef
Mario Batali's recipe.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   THE WORTHINGTON HOTEL BOW-TIE PASTA WITH PESTO CREAM AND HAM
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10
</P>
<P>
   Pesto alla Genovese:
</P>
<P>
   3 cups tightly packed fresh basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup pine nuts
</P>
<P>
   3 or 4 garlic cloves, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   3 ounces Parmesan cheese, finely grated and at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   1 ounce Romano cheese, finely grated and at room temperature
</P>
<P>
   Combine basil, pine nuts, garlic, salt and pepper in food
processor and process to a fine paste. With machine running, pour
half-and-half through feed tube in steady stream. Add cheeses and
process until well-combined.
</P>
<P>
   Bechamel sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 cups heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   Bring cream and milk to simmer in small saucepan.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in heavy saucepan, over low heat, melt butter.
Gradually whisk in flour and let cook 1 to 2 minutes, stirring
constantly; do not brown.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually whisk in heated cream mixture. Raise heat to medium
and cook, stirring occasionally with a wooden spoon, until sauce
thickens. (Sauce should coat the spoon heavily when thickened.)
</P>
<P>
   Remove from heat and season with salt, pepper and nutmeg to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Pasta:
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dry bow-tie pasta
</P>
<P>
   1 pound sliced ham, julienned
</P>
<P>
   1 cup julienned carrots
</P>
<P>
   1 cup julienned zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 cup julienned red bell pepper
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Grated Parmesan, chopped fresh basil and toasted pine nuts, for
garnish
</P>
<P>
   Cook pasta according to package directions and drain.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly saute ham and vegetables in olive oil. Combine with
pasta.
</P>
<P>
   Add pesto to bechamel sauce over heat. Fold sauce into
pasta/vegetable mixture. Garnish with grated Parmesan, chopped
fresh basil and toasted pine nuts.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 504 calories, 27 grams fat, 42
grams carbohydrates, 25 grams protein, 82 milligrams cholesterol,
1,029 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MARIO BATALI'S BASIC GNOCCHI
</P>
<P>
   Serves 12
</P>
<P>
   3 pounds russet potatoes
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 extra-large egg
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup canola oil
</P>
<P>
   Place the whole potatoes in a saucepan with water to cover.
Bring to a boil and cook at a low boil until they are soft, about
45 minutes. While potatoes are still warm, peel them and pass them
through a vegetable mill onto a clean pasta board.
</P>
<P>
   Bring about 6 quarts of water to a boil. Set up an ice bath with
6 cups ice water nearby. Make a well in the center of the potatoes
and sprinkle all over with the flour. Break the egg into the center
of the well, add the salt, and, using a fork, stir into the flour
and potatoes as if you were making pasta. Once the egg is mixed in,
bring the dough together, kneading gently until a ball is formed.
Knead gently for 4 more minutes, until ball is dry to the touch.
</P>
<P>
   Divide the dough into 6 large balls. Roll each ball into ropes
that are 3/4 inch in diameter and cut the ropes into 1-inch-long
pieces. Flick the pieces off a fork or along the concave side of a
cheese grater to score the sides. Drop the dough pieces into the
boiling water and cook until they float to the surface, about 1
minute. Use a slotted spoon to transfer the gnocchi to the ice
bath. Meanwhile, continue with the remaining dough, forming ropes,
cutting 1-inch pieces, and flicking them off a fork. Continue until
all the gnocchi have been cooked, and allow them to sit several
minutes in the ice bath.
</P>
<P>
   Drain the gnocchi and transfer to a mixing bowl. Toss with the
canola oil and store covered in the refrigerator for up to 48 hours
or until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 226 calories, 8 grams fat, 34
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 35 milligrams cholesterol,
213 milligrams sodium, 32 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Pritchard would like a recipe for pecan diamonds. They
are made with small pastry cups, about the size of a Reese's cup,
filled with pecans and honey or maybe caramel.
</P>
<P>
   She is also looking for a Black Forest cake that doesn't include
cherries. It has some sort of baked meringue crust, plus frozen
whipped cream and chocolate flakes.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Hayes of Fort Worth would like a recipe for corn-cob
jelly.
</P>
<P>
   Freida Sue Enlow-Rhodes would like the guacamole recipe that
used to run on the label of the 4-ounce can of Old El Paso Taco
Sauce. She would also like the shrimp salad recipe from the old
Zuider Zee restaurant in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   A reader would like a recipe for the mud pie served at Billy
Miner's restaurant in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Presley would like a recipe for the chocolate decadence
that was served at Bennigan's restaurants in the 1970s and '80s.
She would also like the recipe for the refrigerator cookies that
were served at the Hurst Hills Elementary School cafeteria during
the early to mid-'70s.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1449EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 15:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4036 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-BRENDARUSSELL-CD-TEX     09-06 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRENDARUSSELL-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRENDA RUSSELL POURS SEVEN YEARS OF SELF-REFLECTION INTO `PARIS
RAIN'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MIKI TURNER 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a handful of singer-songwriters can consistently write
tunes that inspire, encourage and challenge us at the same time.
One of them is Brenda Russell, who's back on the scene after a
self-imposed seven-year hiatus with a new CD called ``Paris Rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Russell hasn't been as commercially successful as Barry
Manilow, Carole King, John Lennon and Paul McCartney, Marvin Gaye,
Lionel Richie, Stevie Wonder, Joni Mitchell or any of the other
great lyricists of our time, she has written some pretty terrific
songs that routinely take us back to the days when we had time to
listen to a ``Piano in the Dark.''
</P>
<P>
   That Grammy-nominated Top Five composition along with the richly
crafted ``Get Here'' and her breakthrough hit ``So Good, So Right''
are just a few of the tunes that helped Russell take her rightful
place among the higher echelon of singer-songwriters. Her ascent,
however, has also been aided by her conviction. Her music can't be
typed, and ``Paris Rain'' with its intoxicating blend of ballads,
funk, Latin and Brazilian beats and jazz is no exception. It's her
first recording on the Hidden Beach//Epic label.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe in this album so much,'' Russell says while
flipping a few stray dreadlocks away from her face during lunch in
the San Fernando Valley. ``It's divinely inspired. I cried when I
first heard the music. It blew me away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Catch On,'' a delightful uptempo anthem celebrating the glory
of life, is the first release from Russell's new CD. But one of the
songs she's most excited about is ``Move the Moon,'' a track she
co-wrote with her idol, Carole King.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a little kid I used to have a lot of records that
had (Gerry) Goffin and King on them,'' Russell says. ``I didn't
know they were songwriters. Later, when `Tapestry' came out, I
remember sitting in a restaurant and I heard `I Feel the Earth
Move.' I thought, `This is what I want to do!' So you can imagine
how thrilled I was to be working with her. When we'd be at the
piano I'd be all business, but the moment I was out of her eyesight
I'd be dancing around like Snoopy!''
</P>
<P>
   Russell, who was born in Brooklyn and grew up in Canada,
experiences that same type of euphoria every time another artist
records her songs. Although the sultry-voiced alto recorded ``If
Only for One Night'' on her self-titled debut album in 1979, it
became a monster hit for crooner Luther Vandross several years
later. Also, ``Get Here,'' from her most commercially successful
project, ``Piano in the Dark,'' was moderately successful for
Russell but was a breakthrough hit for Oleta Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``Songs are like babies to me. If you can't raise it, then
someone else has got to,'' Russell says. ``That's how I feel about
it. I knew `Get Here' was a hit song, but the record company I was
signed to at the time did not really believe in it enough to
promote it. When Oleta recorded it, I was like, `Thank
you God,' because I knew the first time I'd ever sang `Get Here' in
the United States, people were screaming at me from the audience. I
knew it was something special.''
</P>
<P>
   Motown hitmakers Holland-Dozier-Holland, Lennon and McCartney
and Sting are among the songwriters Russell says influenced her
early in her career. She concedes that most of the songs on the
seven albums she has recorded are autobiographical. ``Get Here,''
for example, was written when Russell was living in Sweden and
waiting for that special someone to get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always heard that a good writer writes about what they
know about,'' says Russell, who says ``So Good, So Right'' came to
her while she was washing dishes. ``I know about my experiences in
life. Also, it's like therapy for me. If it's therapy for me, then
I figure it will help somebody else, too. It's especially good for
heartbreak. Heartbreak makes great songs! It's therapeutic to get
it out in music.''
</P>
<P>
   EMI, Russell's former label, apparently didn't understand her
need for therapy, which is one of the reasons why she bolted after
1993's ``Soul Talkin'.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You put so much effort into a project _ and in my case, I'm
writing, singing, arranging and producing _ to have someone just
throw it out there and
see what happens was not good enough for me,'' Russell says. ``I
wanted to see what life was like without a record company, and it
was great. I got to really experience a much fuller life with less
stress. I had been working all the time with other artists on their
projects, traveling and working with writers around the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   During her hiatus Russell traveled all over the world, penned
tunes for Tina Turner, Diana Ross, Dionne Warwick and Patti
LaBelle, and contributed to the soundtracks for ``How Stella Got
Her Groove Back'' and ``Liberty Heights,'' a film she had a small
role in.
</P>
<P>
   She also took time to reflect.
</P>
<P>
   ``My spiritual evolution has been huge,'' Russell says. ``The
reason why I'm back out here actually is because God's kicking my
butt. Personally, I was listening to the music that was out there
and going, `I don't know where I fit
in here.' It wasn't very musical to me what was going on. I'm a
person who loves poetry. I was like, surprise me. Go somewhere
where I don't expect you to go. It just made sense to come back and
do what I do, and I'm grateful to be with a company now that wants
me to do just that.''
</P>
<P>
   (Miki Turner is pop culture critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
