A4040 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS &LR;      09-06 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NINERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     49ER'S GARCIA CAN'T WIN FOR LOSING 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEVIN LYNCH  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ San Francisco 49ers quarterback Jeff Garcia is
shivering in the long, dark shadow cast by Steve Young and Joe
Montana. No matter what he does, if he doesn't win, the comparisons
to these two will cast him in an ugly light.
</P>
<P>
   Take Sunday's loss in Atlanta. Garcia completed 23 passes, threw
for three touchdowns, and guided the team on four scoring drives.
He compiled a quarterback rating of 100.8, fourth-highest of any
quarterback on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was grousing about Garcia's performance. He didn't
spot open receivers, he missed passes, and he threw a devastating
and bone-headed interception that was returned for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the 49ers should be thrilled if Garcia replicates
Sunday's performance in each of the remaining 15 games. If Garcia
throws one interception for every three touchdown passes, no one
would complain. If his quarterback rating is more than 100 for the
season, that would be outstanding.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing one interception every 36 passes is no sin. Coach Steve
Mariucci said it's unusual to have an interception returned for a
touchdown, and he's right.
</P>
<P>
   On any given play, a quarterback has dozens of decisions to
make. Should he audible? Where should he throw? Should he move to
avoid the pass rush and when? Should he try to throw the ball away
if in trouble? When should he flee the pocket and make yards on his
own?
</P>
<P>
   One player guessed after watching the Atlanta tape that Garcia
made the right choices 90 percent of the time. Joe Montana and John
Elway were never right on 100 percent on their decisions in any
game. No quarterback has been that perfect. No one should quarrel
with 90 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia was the losing quarterback, and with that, comes a
huge magnifying glass under which all his poor decisions are
unmercifully examined. Even under intense scrutiny, Garcia's
mistakes don't seem all the bad.
</P>
<P>
   Take Ashley Ambrose's third-quarter interception for a
touchdown. Linebacker Keith Brooking's blitz up the middle forced
Garcia to throw the ball falling away to Jerry Rice on the
sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   It looked as if Garcia was tossing up a fall-away jump shot, and
thus, he didn't get any zip on the pass. The lollipop throw made
for an easy interception.
</P>
<P>
   Brooking came straight up the middle and was picked up late by
guard Ray Brown, who actually held him on the play. If Brown or
center Jeremy Newberry pick up Brooking earlier, Garcia has a safe
little pocket in which to throw.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Garcia could have made a better decision by either
running away from Brooking or throwing the ball away. And his
mistake was made all the more glaring because the game turned on
that play. The Ambrose score put the Falcons up by 15 points.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia also has to face the Quarterback Bias, a condition in
which the quarterback gets far too much credit for a win, and too
much blame for a loss.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of Jim Druckenmiller's 1997 win against the Rams.
Druckenmiller, then a rookie, was forced to play because of a
concussion to starter Steve Young and backup Jeff Brohm's broken
finger.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller completed 10 of 28 passes for 102 yards, a
touchdown and three interceptions, but the 49ers won 15-12, and
Druckenmiller drew praise. Some even thought Druckenmiller should
have started the next week over Brohm if Young wasn't ready.
</P>
<P>
   Druckenmiller was horrible. The 49ers only won the game because
of defense and special teams play.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, following Young and Montana doesn't help Garcia
either. They knew the offense so well and were so abundantly
talented. Against the backdrop of 20 years of Hall of Fame
quarterbacking, Garcia's in for a season of unfair comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Montana and Young were better than Garcia is now, but they
both played on teams with strong defenses and decent special teams.
</P>
<P>
   So Garcia is left to function in the dark. To toil in the shadow
of men who defined quarterbacking in the modern era. Maybe Garcia
isn't the long-term answer at quarterback, but he should at least
be given a chance to prove that he is.
</P>
</TEXT>
