<HEADER>
A4071 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-SUSANDELL-FASHION-100     09-06 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUSANDELL-FASHION-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLIONAIRE'S WIFE LAUNCHES HER OWN LINE OF HIGH-FASHION CLOTHING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ALYSON WARD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You've probably heard Susan Dell's name. Of
course, her name is almost always the second half of a phrase that
begins with ``Michael and'' _ her husband is computer magnate
Michael Dell, the Austin billionaire who made his fortune selling
pre-ordered PCs.
</P>
<P>
   If things go as Susan Dell plans, though _ and they usually do _
you'll soon be throwing her name around on its own. And if you have
the money, you'll quite possibly be wearing her name inside your
designer dresses, your business suits and your cashmere sweaters.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, Dell has developed a line of high-fashion
designer clothing and has opened an Austin boutique to sell her
wares. But the Austin shop is just the friendly face on her
developing empire. Her company _ Susan Dell Inc. _ has a staff of
50 and occupies three floors on Seventh Avenue in New York. Dell
plans to keep expanding _ she'll open more shops in other cities
(she has her eye on Fort Worth-Dallas) and launch a Web site to
sell her clothing online.
</P>
<P>
   So the wife of the richest man in Texas (according to Forbes
magazine's 2000 ranking of billionaires) wants to become a heavy
hitter in the fashion world.
</P>
<P>
   Why? I called to request an hourlong interview _ and eight
months and perhaps 1,000 phone calls later, I got it.
</P>
<P>
   In that hour (which she generously allowed to turn into two), I
learned that Susan Dell isn't just a billionaire's wife; she's the
mother of four, a savvy businesswoman and quite a serious fashion
designer, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   In the time I spent seeking Susan Dell, though, I learned
something just as interesting: Whatever the public learns about
Dell, it will be precisely what she wants us to know _ and nothing
more.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I started this story eight months ago. It was late January _ Y2K
panic was just dying down, and the presidential primaries were only
beginning _ when I learned about Dell's clothing line. My initial
call to Austin was promptly rerouted to New York, and I spent
months dealing with a string of Dell's PR representatives and
company employees. Reversing the usual procedure, they interviewed
me. ``What is the nature of the story you want to write?'' ``What's
your background in fashion reporting?'' ``Can you tell us anything
about yourself that might interest Susan?''
</P>
<P>
   What?
</P>
<P>
   Arranging this interview got more and more complicated.
Photography was banned, then welcomed. Conditions were set, then
withdrawn. In May, my interview request was turned down entirely; I
was told that Dell ``prefers not to do any more Texas press at this
time.'' By June, the story was renewed. I could have some time with
Dell in late August.
</P>
<P>
   I thought I was in. And I was. Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Dell's store stands tall in an upscale shopping center in the
well-heeled Westlake area of Austin. The store is surrounded by
cafes, specialty shops and a parking lot full of Lexuses and
Mercedeses. Inside, the look is limestone and maple and glass _ a
tasteful, uncluttered design that complements Dell's tasteful,
uncluttered clothing line. Calla lilies rest in heavy glass vases,
and the summer sun pours in through full-length windows.
</P>
<P>
   The store was designed by Charles Gwathmey, the architect who
designed the addition to New York's Guggenheim Museum (and the
Dells' hilltop mansion). Fashion photography legend Lillian Bassman
did the photography for an ``image wall'' facing the front door.
</P>
<P>
   The shop is much like Dell herself: appealing and elegant, sleek
and sophisticated; nothing is out of place.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's company president, Linda Beauchamp, who founded Donna
Karan's menswear line, greets me at the door. Behind her, moments
later, Susan Dell appears.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, 36, is wearing a white sleeveless sweater and dark, fitted
tech-cotton twill pants, both part of the Susan Dell line. The look
is completed by a pair of black cowboy boots. (''I feel like `Texas
girl' today,'' she later says, explaining the way our clothes show
different sides of our personalities.)
</P>
<P>
   She is tall. She is professional. She is polite. And she is
efficient. She disappears after about a minute, deciding it would
be better to get some work done while Beauchamp gives us the grand
tour of the building.
</P>
<P>
   First, Beauchamp introduces the clothing, pointing out details,
colors and fabrics. The clothing displayed is sleek. Classic.
Timeless. Everything is made in Italy: day wear, evening wear,
couture clothing. A selection of jersey knits has just arrived; the
skirt and single-shoulder top can be worn alone or paired with a
stylish wraparound cardigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our clothes are things you keep,'' Beauchamp explains. ``This
isn't about clothes that are disposable.''
</P>
<P>
   She takes me through the palatial dressing rooms, complete with
thick carpet, comfortable furniture and flattering lighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could stay in here all day,'' Beauchamp says, encouraging
me to lounge on the furniture. Leaning back, she admits, ``I had a
meeting in here with the store manager.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   I get glimpses of who the woman behind the name truly is. When I
am left in Dell's company, I discover that what I've read about her
is true: She doesn't sit. Dell is constantly moving here and there
_ adjusting material on a mannequin, showing pieces of her fall
collection. Her office was designed with a high countertop so she
can stand up to type, and the only chairs in the room are the four
child-size ones that surround a miniature table where her children
often play.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder she can't sit down, I think as Dell begins a monologue
about her business. Susan Dell is excited about fashion.
</P>
<P>
   She explains how she'll find color inspiration in a lipstick,
clothing on her children's dolls or the petal of a flower on the
table in a restaurant. She incorporates these colors into her
collection, weaving them together with elegant design.
</P>
<P>
   Dell studied fashion merchandising and design at Arizona State
University. She began designing her clothes and having them made;
when she got compliments, she began designing for friends.
Eventually, she decided to turn her passion into a business.
</P>
<P>
   Dell explains how her business is expanding perfectly on
schedule, just as her youngest children are starting to grow up
(her twins just turned 4).
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't something I suddenly decided to do,'' she says _
although fashion design hasn't always been her career, it's always
been in her blood.
</P>
<P>
   Dell talks a great deal about passion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it's clearly fashion,'' she says. ``I love fashion. I
love fabric, I love color, I love women's bodies _ all shapes and
all sizes. I think every woman should feel beautiful, confident,
empowered.''
</P>
<P>
   Her speech picks up speed as she talks about her work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Susan Dell is a woman who's involved in many things,'' she
points out _ from philanthropy to business to family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wear a lot of hats.... This particular role is the one I'm
most passionate about, besides wife and mommy,'' she says. ``This
is what makes me tick. This is what lights my fire.... This is why
I can't sit down at work _ I'm so excited about work.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all her talk about passion at the office, it is the
stories Dell tells about her children that are the most revealing
and genuine; it's hard not to love how she encouraged her oldest
daughter or the way she understands her 4-year-old son. But family
stories are strictly off the record.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Am I in the room? I wonder. Dell and her staff are
excruciatingly careful about what they tell me. In front of me,
they openly discuss what should and shouldn't be done for press
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   While the photographer takes Dell's picture, I find myself
standing next to the store manager. On the record, of course, but
mainly just to make conversation, I ask her to tell me how she
ended up working for Susan Dell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably shouldn't,'' she says. ``I really can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Awkwardness follows. But I get used to it. By the end of the
interview, I forget I'm writing about a woman and her boutique; I
feel as if I've attempted to pry into classified government
information.
</P>
<P>
   Regal and charming, Beauchamp is the most open member of the
Susan Dell team. But even she won't allow us to take photos of her
_ ``I would rather it be about Susan,'' she says with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the obvious guardedness, it is easy to like Dell.
</P>
<P>
   She debates the merits of lying on her stomach for a photo, head
propped on her hands and boots in the air. Is the pose dignified
enough? ``I don't want to look like _ `Cute chick does designs,' ''
she says, making everyone in the room laugh.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   I finally ask: So why did it take eight months to get an
interview?
</P>
<P>
   ``My schedule is pretty tight,'' Dell says.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed; she's often out of town, working in New York or
overseas. And when she's in Austin, she explains, time-consuming
interviews keep her from doing the work she loves.
</P>
<P>
   That's why there's a multilevel buffer zone between Dell and
annoying reporters like me. Those buffers ask questions, get
specifics, and decide if the request seems reasonable _ or, as Dell
puts it, ``makes sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, this seemed strange and suspicious to me. Since
January, I've been wondering why a business _ and a new designer _
would turn down the free publicity my story would offer. Now I
think I understand.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a fashion story, really, examining the work of a new
designer. It's not a business story, either. It's a personality
profile of a woman who doesn't really want her personality
profiled. And it's an opportunity for us all to gaze at the
activities of one of the world's wealthiest people.
</P>
<P>
   Dell recognizes this. I think she even forgives me for being
curious.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what I do or don't do, people will be inquisitive,''
she says. ``We are in the public eye.''
</P>
<P>
   She's in the public eye, yes, but Susan Dell is clearly,
beautifully, in control.
</P>
<P>
