<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAT-DNA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     FEDS BUILDING DATABASE ON CAT DNA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KEAY DAVIDSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Impressed by cases in which cat hair has helped
solve crimes, the federal government is bankrolling a two-year,
$265,000 project to develop a national database of genetic
information from cats.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists and the U.S. Department of Justice are asking
volunteers to send samples of their cats' DNA to a federal
laboratory near Washington. The genetic material could be used to
identify cat blood, hairs or tissue found at crime scenes,
officials say.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being able to identify an individual domestic animal can be a
powerful aid to solving a crime,'' said Lisa Forman, the acting
director of the investigative and forensic sciences division at the
Office of Science and Technology, part of the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   In several cases, animal blood or hair found on bodies or
clothing at crime scenes has helped the police in tracking down
suspects. By using genetic techniques to identify the animal breed
_ sometimes even a specific animal _ investigators have charged
criminals on whose bodies those cats or dogs had rubbed, snuffled
or snoozed.
</P>
<P>
   A celebrated case occurred recently in Canada: The Royal
Canadian Mounted Police charged a man of killing his estranged wife
using on genetic identification of hair from his cat, Snowball. The
man was convicted.
</P>
<P>
   In developing the feline DNA database, ``we're trying to get
about 50 (cat DNA) samples from each breed. There are about 35
breeds, so we need upwards of 1,600 samples,'' said geneticist
Marilyn Menotti-Raymond of the Laboratory of Genomic Diversity,
part of the National Cancer Institute.
</P>
<P>
   DNA, or deoxyribonucleic acid, is shaped like two intertwined
spiral staircases and carries the genes or chemical codes that tell
cells how to grow in all living organisms.
</P>
<P>
   The feline DNA database, once completed, would let investigators
identify hair, blood or tissue samples from specific breeds of
cats. In the past, investigators could examine hair from a crime
scene and say whether it came from a cat or dog, but that's about
it.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in the program should first write for
information to: Dr. Marilyn Menotti-Raymond, Laboratory of Genomic
Diversity, National Cancer Institute, Building 560/Room 11-38, Fort
Detrick, Frederick, MD 21702.
</P>
<P>
   Forman said the Justice Department has no immediate plans to
develop a database of dog DNA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
