<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 15:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4098 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-ROADFOOD-LA-TEX     09-06 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROADFOOD-LA-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN IN LA'S CAR CULTURE, YOU CAN WALK TO GREAT FOOD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even without my trusty Rand McNally, it's not hard
to recognize that I'm in California.
</P>
<P>
   Road signs on Highway 1 direct me to vineyards. The passenger
window is open so I can hear the ocean hitting the rocks. And when
I reach Santa Barbara, the gas-station cashier is stationed in
front of a towering carved coffee bar. She can't locate the
restroom key for me, but she can put a mean head on a cappuccino.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific hem of California is far different from the fabric
that makes up the rest of the state. Here, things seem ethereal,
almost otherworldly _ until, whack, you hit the freeways of Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   I was determined not to do as my father had done 35 years
earlier. We had just spent a week driving across the country to his
next assignment, at Vandenberg Air Force Base outside Lompoc. We
hit LA at dark, with the tangled ribbons of headlights coming at us
from all directions. My father, after three years of driving in
sane and stoic Norway, was, well, he was freaked.
</P>
<P>
   I was not going to do the same. I called ahead to my sister,
asking for directions to her house. Which interstate to take, which
exit to take, which interstate to take next. I was ready.
</P>
<P>
   One hour later, I called her again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Forget it, I'm lost; I'm checking into a hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not you're not _ the Democratic Convention is in town.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So maybe I'll run into Rob Lowe.''
</P>
<P>
   But no, much younger sister had another idea and, via cellphone,
she reeled me in. But I agree with my father; for the rest of my
time in Los Angeles, I decided to walk.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, you can walk in Los Angeles, even in August. There are
neighborhoods, with restaurants, in which you can walk. So although
my meals for the next few days were geographically limited, they
were hardly restricted.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles Farmers Market, Fairfax and Third Street, south of
Hollywood &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Locals bemoan that the Farmers Market, a Los Angeles institution
since 1934, is no longer home to real farmers. Instead, each peach
has a paper sticker identical to the ones on the peaches in the
Albertsons across the street.
</P>
<P>
   The locals should gripe about something else _ like the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But imagine; here's a place that doesn't charge for parking, has
outdoor seating you can use year-round and newspapers from around
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Although most California supermarkets didn't show me much (I am
eating my complaints about Texas grocery stores), the farmers
market almost made up for it. Here you'll find the Mr. Marcel
Cheese Shop with offerings that go beyond the havarti that seems to
be the apex at the popular Trader Joe's. Mr. Marcel also stocks
olives by the pound and a terrific selection of caviar. Or try
Thee's Continental Pastries, where a sign announced ``First of the
season _ Pflaumenkuchen.''
</P>
<P>
   And the restaurant offerings are fabulous. Try Moishe's for
shish kebab or falafel or more mundane rotisserie chicken. Or order
from one of the Filipino staff at the French Crepe Co. The opera
crepe (No. 7 if you're counting) is $5.85 and includes Swiss
cheese, avocado, onions and tomato and is paired with the wonderful
field greens salad dressed with a mustard vinaigrette. They'll call
your name at the counter, but you can eat outdoors, on a real
plate, and servers clean up.
</P>
<P>
   Swingers Hollywood Diner, 8020 Beverly Blvd., (323) 653-5858 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, I am in Los Angeles. So many pretty people, you hope to
spy someone overweight in a Bedazzled T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   My 5-foot-10-inch tall, 120-pound sister leaned across the table
as we were making our way through the menu.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I never believed that there were people who actually
had ribs removed to look thinner until I moved here. Some of these
people, I wonder how they have room for their intestines.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, they're obviously not really eating at Swingers _ hanging
out, maybe, drinking water maybe, but obviously not eating. (Well,
they might be checking out the staff. On our visit, a trio of
Amazon women who looked as if they once danced behind Robert Palmer
were waiting tables. They'd changed out of the black dresses,
though, and wore micromini schoolgirl pleated skirts and knee-high
black boots.
</P>
<P>
   It made eating my ahi tuna sandwich a little difficult. I
wondered where they were keeping their intestines.
</P>
<P>
   In-N-Out Burger, 140 locations in California, Nevada and
Arizona &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In-N-Out Burger is to Southern California what Whataburger is to
Texas _ the hometown burger. The places are packed, day and night.
And I wasn't in town during the car giveaway, the annual autumn
promotional event that packs in car-crazy Angelenos.
</P>
<P>
   In-N-Out Burger was started by Harry and Esther Snyder in 1948;
it was the first California burger spot with a drive-through
window. Esther still shows up at the office, and the chain has
grown to 140 stores.
</P>
<P>
   The best stuff at In-N-Out Burger is not on the menu. A burger
ordered ``animal style'' is a hamburger topped with fried onions,
both grilled in mustard. A ``protein burger'' is the hamburger with
the works _ minus the bun. Instead, the meat and topping are
wrapped in lettuce leaves. Or, if you're on the opposite end of the
food chain, order the ``wish burger,'' or the ``I wish I had a
burger.'' That's the bun and all the toppings, minus the meat.
</P>
<P>
   You just gotta love LA.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
