<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4108 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-FURNACES0906-COX     09-06 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FURNACES0906-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fireplace `backsmoking' might be culprit behind wall stain
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - J.M. of Springboro had a room addition with a
wood-burning fireplace added to her house about four years ago, and
ever since she's had a problem with smoke stains high on the walls
of the great room adjoining the addition. She uses the fireplace
four or five nights a week during cold weather and fears the walls
she just had repainted will become smudged again if she can't solve
her problem before the heating season starts. Her house doesn't
have natural gas, so a natural gas fireplace is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: Caryl Hoelscher of Abbey Road Chimney Sweeps says
soot stains high on the wall usually are caused by soot that can
come from frequent candle burning or from a fireplace that is
``backsmoking,'' which means releasing some smoke from the firebox
instead of sending it all up the chimney. To see if a fireplace is
releasing smoke indoors, Hoelscher suggests shining a strong
flashlight across the face of the fireplace. The beam will
illuminate smoke particles that might otherwise be invisible.
</P>
<P>
   Hoelscher and a technical adviser for Temco Fireplaces, the
manufacturer of J.M.'s fireplace, said smoke escaping from a
fireplace is often related to negative air pressure in the room.
Modern houses are so tightly constructed that outside air has a
hard time getting into the house. Anything that draws air out of
the room _ for example, the air-intake duct of the furnace or an
exhaust fan _ can reduce the air pressure in the room to the point
that smoky air inside the fireplace is sucked out. It's sometimes
necessary to crack a window near a fireplace to provide a fresh-air
source.
</P>
<P>
   Other possible problems with the fireplace include an
incorrectly positioned vent opening on the roof above the room
addition or an improperly installed fireplace. J.M. got a toll-free
number to contact Temco's customer service department and can
explore the problem further with them.
</P>
<P>
   BRICK EXTERIOR CRACKS
</P>
<P>
   OK IF THEY'RE SMALL
</P>
<P>
   Cracks are forming in the brick exterior of L.H.'s house in
Huber Heights, and she's concerned that she has a serious problem
and that the neighbors will think she's letting her house go to
pot. The cracks started appearing in the past couple of years along
the mortar between rows of bricks and at windows. A few bricks are
also cracked. Most of the cracks are 1/8-inch or less. She wants to
know what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: Cracks as small as the ones L.H. is seeing aren't
especially unusual or serious. Cracks form when the soil under the
house shifts, putting stress at points such as window seals and
corners. Foundation experts say the dry weather the Dayton area has
had for the past few years has created unusual cracking because the
clay soils common in the Miami Valley tend to contract a bit when
they get dry. As long as the cracks aren't large enough to stick a
finger through, and the basement walls don't bow inward or lean,
it's not time to panic. L.H. should keep an eye on the cracks to be
sure they are expanding or moving. She should put a piece of tape
across the worst cracks, then check back in a few days. If the tape
is twisted, that means the wall is continuing to shift rapidly, and
it's time to call in a professional to take a look. Extensive
shifting may require excavation and foundation reinforcement to
correct, and that's expensive.
</P>
<P>
   When the weather cools a bit, she should apply a little silicone
and latex caulk to visible cracks in the mortar. Caulk waterproofs
the cracks so rain doesn't reach the sheathing underneath. Caulk
applied during moderate fall weather should be able to stretch to
keep covering the cracks when they are at their widest during the
coldest days of winter. Hardware and home-improvement stores carry
caulk colored to match concrete approximately, but don't expect an
invisible repair.
</P>
<P>
   If the cracks between bricks have stabilized and aren't growing,
the problem can be fixed more or less permanently by tuckpointing.
Tuckpointing involves removing some of the deteriorating mortar
between the bricks and replacing it with fresh mortar. You can get
tips on tuckpointing from places where bricks and mortar are sold.
It will keep you hunched in front of a brick wall for hours at a
time, but it's a job the average do-it-yourselfer can handle with a
little instruction.
</P>
<P>
   CAULK, RIGHT DIMENSIONS
</P>
<P>
   SHOULD FIX LEAKY SHED
</P>
<P>
   M.H. of Fairborn built a storage shed in his yard using a kit
from Arrow Sheds. He built the shed on a platform of treated
plywood. When it rains, water seeps into the shed along the bottom
of the walls. He wants to know how to keep the inside portion of
the plywood platform dry.
</P>
<P>
   Suggestion: A spokeswoman for Arrow Sheds said M.H. should work
inside the shed and apply caulk at the lines where the walls of the
shed meet the plywood. The caulk will create a watertight barrier
that will keep rain out.
</P>
<P>
   Arrow's Web site says the best base for one of their sheds is a
level concrete pad, but plywood also works. The spokeswoman said
the trick is not to make the platform too large. The plywood should
be cut so the lip around the shed is no more than 9/16 of an inch
wide. Arrow sheds have overhangs at their roof lines that keep rain
from running down the outside walls. If the plywood only extends a
short distance outside the walls of the shed, the overhangs carry
the water out far enough that the wood stays dry and doesn't
provide a path to the interior.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Email: jamescummings(at)coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
