<HEADLINE>
BENEATH THE PRICKLY EXTERIOR OF THE CACTUS, LIES A SWEET FRUIT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beauty, abuela says, is more than skin deep.
</P>
<P>
   Grandmother must be from the Southwest. She probably grew up
with a stand of prickly pear cactus fronting the adobe and could
see the beauty beneath the sun-weathered pads of this needle-ridden
fellow. And she, because she was accumulating her motherly wisdom,
must have recognized the bounty these plants produce in the worst
of the desert summer.
</P>
<P>
   In August and September, it's easy to miss the glory of cactus
fruit. Certainly, it's more comfortable to keep to the
air-conditioning in the dire heat. But a field trip, particularly
to the homes of wise neighbors who have xeriscaped their property,
would reveal Texas' state plant festooned with ``tunas,'' the red
fruit or ``pears'' that are the yin to the yang of the paddles of
the prickly pear cactus.
</P>
<P>
   This survivor may well be one of the wonders of the flora
universe.
</P>
<P>
   When the paddles are young and relatively spine-free, they're
appealing to cattle as feed. Some pioneers in straw bale
construction have experimented with using juice from the cactus as
an ingredient in the plaster that seals the walls.
</P>
<P>
   The mature paddles can be shorn of prickles and slivered into
julienne used in everything from omelets to vegetarian tacos to
salads. The strips can also be battered and deep-fried, a la okra,
which has a similar viscous quality.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowns on these thorns are the fruits that ripen in the
hottest months. Twisted warm from the plant, a broken tuna reveals
lush garnet flesh flecked with tiny black seeds. The flavor is
sweetish, but not cloying. And the color makes for dishes that are
meal stoppers.
</P>
<P>
   If lucky, you have a source for local tunas. If not, then
specialty produce purveyors are here to assist you. Look for tunas
in the ``gourmet'' department of the fruit section of your
supermarket. If your supermarket doesn't tend toward the outre,
find the fruit at Hispanic markets.
</P>
<P>
   It's important to peel the fruit well; the hide contains
glochidia, tiny 1/32-inch long spines that are as thin as hairs yet
sharp, nonetheless. Straining the seeds from the flesh is usual,
but not absolutely necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CACTUS PEAR BREAKFAST SHAKE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   2 cactus pears, peeled and cut into large chunks
</P>
<P>
   1 large banana, peeled and cut into large chunks
</P>
<P>
   4 ice cubes
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons honey
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk
</P>
<P>
   Press cactus pear through medium disk of food mill. Combine
puree in blender or processor with banana, ice cubes, honey and
milk; whirl until no chunks of ice remain. Serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 207 calories, 5 grams fat, 40
grams carbohydrates, 5 grams protein, 17 milligrams cholesterol, 64
milligrams sodium, 20 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Uncommon Fruits &AMP; Vegetables: A Commonsense Guide'' by
Elizabeth Schneider (William Morrow, $28)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CACTUS RITA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 5-6
</P>
<P>
   6 prickly pears, peeled
</P>
<P>
   4 cups inexpensive tequila
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly squeezed lime juice or undiluted Minute Maid
frozen limeade
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup Triple Sec, Grand Marnier or Cointreau
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup crushed ice
</P>
<P>
   Honey or sugar syrup, optional
</P>
<P>
   Place prickly pear fruit in large glass container or jar. Top
with tequila, cover and refrigerate at least overnight or as long
as three days. Transfer prickly pear and tequila to a blender or
food processor and puree. Strain through a sieve with holes large
enough to hold back seeds but let most of the pulp through. Measure
out 1 cup of puree. Freeze remainder for another use.
</P>
<P>
   Place 1 cup puree, lime juice, liqueur and ice in blender; mix
well. If it is too tart, add a little honey or sugar syrup. Pour
into margarita glasses and served immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 109 calories, trace fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 3 milligrams
sodium, 2 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Savor the Southwest'' by Barbara Pool Fenzl (Bay Books,
$19.95)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PRICKLY PEAR SALAD DRESSING
</P>
<P>
   Yields about 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup prickly pear puree, see Note
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup light-flavor vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 tablespoons tarragon white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Note: In food processor, puree 1/2 pound peeled cactus fruit.
Force puree through strainer set over a bowl; discard seeds. There
should be about 2 cups of seedless puree.
</P>
<P>
   Shake all ingredients together in covered jar. This pretty, pink
dressing is thin like an oil and vinegar dressing but much lower in
calories. Use on fruit or tossed green salad.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per tablespoon: 49 calories, 4 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 0 protein, 0 cholesterol, 147 milligrams
sodium, 79 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ www.kitchenlink.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   CACTUS CHICKEN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6-8
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds peeled prickly pear fruit, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup fresh lime juice
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup honey
</P>
<P>
   2 (3 1/2 pounds each) chickens, quartered and skinned
</P>
<P>
   2 cups wood smoking chips, preferably fruit wood
</P>
<P>
   Salt, to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper, to taste
</P>
<P>
   In food processor, puree cactus fruit. Force puree through
strainer set over a bowl; discard seeds. There should be about 2
cups of seedless puree.
</P>
<P>
   In medium, nonreactive pan over medium heat, combine cactus
puree, lime juice and honey. Bring to simmer, skimming any scum
that foams to top and cook, uncovered, stirring once or twice,
until reduced by one fourth, about 15 minutes. Remove from heat and
cool to room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   In shallow nonreactive dish just large enough to hold them, coat
chicken quarters with cooled cactus mixture. Cover and marinate in
refrigerator, turning once or twice, for 1 hour.
</P>
<P>
   Light charcoal fire and let burn until coals are evenly white,
or preheat gas grill to medium. Wrap wood chips partially in foil,
forming small packet that is open at top. To create a ``cool zone''
take charcoal to one side of grill; if you're using propane, shut
off one or two burners. Set packet of wood chips on hot coals or
hot lava stones; position grill rack about 6 inches above heat
source.
</P>
<P>
   When wood chips are smoking, arrange leg quarters on rack, meaty
side down, on cool zone of grill. Cover and cook 15 minutes. Baste
leg quarters with some of the cactus mixture, then turn them and
move them to edges of cool zone. Arrange chicken breasts, meaty
side down, in center of cool zone, cover, and grill for 15 minutes,
basting all the chicken quarters once or twice with cactus mixture.
</P>
<P>
   Turn breasts meaty side up. Continue to grill, covered, basting
until cactus mixture is used up and rearranging chicken quarters as
necessary to brown them evenly but continuing to avoid direct heat,
until just cooked through but still juicy, about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Remove chicken from grill immediately, season with salt and
pepper to taste and serve hot or warm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 377 calories, 7 grams fat, 18
grams carbohydrates, 58 grams protein, 158 milligrams cholesterol,
142 milligrams sodium, 17 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The El Paso Chile Company's Burning Desires: Salsa, Smoke,
and Sizzle from Down by the Rio Grande'' by W. Park Kerr (William
Morrow, $16)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   CACTUS PEARS AND ICE CREAM
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 canned peach halves, in light syrup
</P>
<P>
   1 cinnamon stick
</P>
<P>
   2 cactus pears, peeled and cubed
</P>
<P>
   1 cup frozen raspberries, thawed, drained
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup orange liqueur, optional
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vanilla ice cream
</P>
<P>
   Drain peaches and reserve juice.
</P>
<P>
   In saucepan, bring peach juice and cinnamon to a boil, then
simmer for 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Pour liquid over peach halves and cool.
</P>
<P>
   In blender, puree cactus pears, raspberries and liqueur, if
using.
</P>
<P>
   Place peach halves in dessert cups, garnish with scoop of ice
cream and top with cactus pear-raspberry sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving with liqueur: 152 calories, 4
grams fat, 30 grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, 15 milligrams
cholesterol, 33 milligrams sodium, 24 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ Melissa's specialty produce
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   PRICKLY PEAR SORBET
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup water
</P>
<P>
   2 cups prickly pears, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon raspberry liqueur (Chambord or framboise)
</P>
<P>
   Raspberries and lime slices, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar and water in small saucepan over medium-high heat.
Bring to boil, reduce heat and simmer until sugar is dissolved,
about 2 minutes. Let cool completely.
</P>
<P>
   Puree prickly pears in blender or food processor; strain into a
bowl. Add cooled sugar syrup and raspberry liqueur. Refrigerate
until well-chilled.
</P>
<P>
   Pour mixture into an ice cream machine. Process according to
manufacturer's directions. Serve in margarita glasses with fresh
raspberries and a slice of lime.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 153 calories, 0 fat, 39 grams
carbohydrates, trace protein, 0 cholesterol, 3 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Savor the Southwest''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
