<P>
   BRIT-U.S.-COUPLES (London) - Like the main character in ``Single
Process,'' a novella in her new book, ``Four Blondes'' (Atlantic Monthly
Press), Candace  Bushnell appears to have found love at last with a suave
Brit after years of exasperation  with the New York dating game. By
Christopher Mason.
</P>
<P>
   ANGLO-AMERICAN-ROMANCE (Undated) - The British male represents
something that has gone missing from his American counterpart: chivalry.
Hence, many American women find the British male to be the ultimate
challenge. Where I live in Notting Hill, Anglo-American alliances are
practically as numerous as the Mercedes estate cars parked outside. By
Helen Kirwan-Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   PET-HEALTH-SPAS (New York) - The latest pet spas  are beginning to
offer the same therapies available to humans - from electro-stimulation to
underwater treadmills. Ten years ago, physical therapy was mainly for
people.   But today, as pets become more prized, and  a booming economy
creates more discretionary income,  pet care extends to  surgery  and $400
customized weight-loss programs at health spas. By Julie V. Iovine.
    With photo, NYT10
</P>
<P>
   LIST-MAGAZINE (New York) - Reading the telephone book used to be a joke
until List magazine, also exclusively a collection of lists, appeared in
June. Four thousand copies later (at $15 a pop), the new magazine's last
laugh is the next item on the editors' list: Issue 2 arrives in October.
The White Pages, at least, are free. Detractors and admirers - along with
List's creative directors, Lisa Ano, 28, and Serge Becker, 39, who are
designers by background - like to think of List as a kind of literary
Armageddon: the arguments of the traditional magazine piece stripped to a
corrosive litany of disinterested facts. By William L. Hamilton.
    With photo.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) - Garden questions answered. By Leslie Land.
</P>
<P>
   LAPIDUS-ARCHITECTURDE (New York) - When  Morris Lapidus, who is 97 and
architect of the iconic, mid-'50s Fontainebleu Hilton and Eden Roc hotels
in Miami Beach and more than 1,000 other projects, was in town recently, he
had lunch with his  colleague Philip Johnson as well as his former clients,
the brothers Tisch. Between lunches with friends and meetings with
manufacturers to discuss licensing his product designs, Mr. Lapidus sat
briefly in Central Park, recounting for the New York Times some of his most
memorable New York projects and looking back on his life as a contrarian.
By Bonnie Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
