<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4117 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-WAYOFTHEGUN-HNS &LR;      09-06 1301
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WAYOFTHEGUN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD YOUNG BLOOD GIVES A DIFFERENT LOOK TO THE ACTION THRILLER
IN ``THE WAY OF THE GUN''
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Director Christopher McQuarrie was dead-set against Ryan Phillippe
for the starring role in ``The Way of the Gun''.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``He was not at all what I imagined (his character) Parker to
be,'' McQuarrie said. ``Artisan (the studio) was very excited about
Ryan and was convinced he could do it. I just couldn't imagine
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that's rare _ and refreshing. Once a movie is made, the
director usually insists that the star he got was always his first
choice, no matter how hard he really fought to get someone else.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that such filmmakers are lying, exactly; it's just
that, well, the director has convinced himself that Phillippe was
who he really wanted all along. Call it artistic self-delusion.
</P>
<P>
   First-time director McQuarrie, who scripted ``The Usual
Suspects,'' felt that using Phillippe, currently hot with teen
audiences, would work against the dark, edgy tone he wanted for
``The Way of the Gun'', which opens Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is an action film that both honors and wryly mocks the
thriller genre by twisting its conventions. The large ensemble cast
features young performers, including Benicio Del Toro, Juliette
Lewis, Taye Diggs, Nicky Katt and Phillippe, plus old pros James
Caan and Scott Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro, a buddy of McQuarrie's who helped develop the film's
story and tone, was set to play Longbaugh, one of two buddy
criminals who kidnap a pregnant surrogate mother (Lewis) to hold
her undelivered baby for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie had his own ideas about how to cast the role of Del
Toro's partner, and said no to Phillippe, 25, even though the young
actor was sizzling from roles in the teen hits ``I Know What You
Did Last Summer'' and ``Cruel Intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillippe, calling from Chicago, said McQuarrie was reluctant
because of the actor's ``lightweight'' films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two that I've done have been fairly successful, so I'm
identified with that in the (film) community,'' Phillippe said.
</P>
<P>
   But the actor refused to accept a rejection until he had a
meeting with the director.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Phillippe) said, `Look, I'm an actor, and people are
trying to make me a movie star. I'm just not going to do that,'''
McQuarrie recalled. ``I very much respected that approach.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillippe told the director he would put on muscle and change
his appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of hounded him,'' Phillippe said.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie finally relented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `You know, Ryan, let's not change who you are. Let's
re-think the role so it's one that suits you.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Phillippe showed up for rehearsals six weeks later, he
didn't look like the teen-scream cover boy anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``I put on 25 pounds of muscle,'' Phillippe said. ``I worked out
five days a week and drank protein shakes _ did a lot to change
myself physically and the way I talk, and kind of came up with a
whole different guy. Or at least I tried to.''
</P>
<P>
   He also had a scruffy beard and cropped hair.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked exactly like Parker needed to be,'' McQuarrie said.
``I went back to the way Parker had been.''
</P>
<P>
   The character names Parker and Longbaugh were the real names of
turn-of-the-century outlaws Butch Cassidy (Robert LeRoy Parker) and
the Sundance Kid (Harry Longbaugh). McQuarrie, a movie buff,
included a lot of references _ verbal and visual _ to such film
favorites as ``The Magnificent Seven'' and ``The Wild Bunch.''
</P>
<P>
   But his Parker and Longbaugh are not the sweet charmers that
Paul Newman and Robert Redford made Butch and the Kid. They don't
hesitate to kill people who get in their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going to make a movie about criminals,'' McQuarrie
said, ``what I don't want to do is go down the road of making
criminals sympathetic _ giving them reasons and justifications and
qualifications for their deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that really repellent and, frankly, too easy. I was
more interested in following two characters who were bad people. We
were not allowed to see their past lives or dysfunctional
childhoods. You were forced to make a judgment. No effort was made
to make the audience happy.''
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie may be misjudging the ability of viewers to find
positive attributes in his heroes. His Parker and Longbaugh seem
cool and hip in their enigmatic detachment _ especially as played
by Del Toro and Phillippe.
</P>
<P>
   But there's no doubt that ``The Way of the Gun'' turns
action-movie conventions on end. Like an early gunfight in which we
hear, but don't see, most of the shooting. Or a cat-and-mouse car
chase in which the pursued and pursuing go so slowly they actually
push the cars with their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to make something different,'' McQuarrie said.
``I don't know how far away from the conventions I got, but I was
definitely trying to make a film that said, `OK, you've shown up to
see a crime story: Here's what guns really sound like; here's what
criminals really are; here's what consequences really are.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the action is so explosive, the situations so bizarre,
that moviegoers may come out of the theater feeling like they've
been hit by a truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now to me, that would be a good thing,'' Phillippe said. ``Far
too many movies, we don't feel anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite his fight to get the role, Phillippe said diving into
the mind-set of his desperate character was a real switch,
especially learning to look handy with the many weapons in the
film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is strange, 'cause I didn't grow up in the South, where
(guns are) a little more common. I grew up on the East Coast
(Delaware). We never went out hunting. I never really held a gun.
My mother wouldn't let me have toy guns. Which I think was pretty
forward-thinking.
</P>
<P>
   ``On some level, as a guy, you can't help feeling like you're
playing cops and robbers. I trained with a SWAT team member and a
Navy SEAL. It's fascinating. It is a power thing. There's something
about the gun and what it represents.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillippe, who gained early popularity playing Billy Douglas,
daytime TV's first gay teen, on ``One Life to Live,'' 1992-93, is
married to actress Reese Witherspoon. They had their first child,
daughter Ava Elizabeth Phillippe, when he was shooting ``The Way of
the Gun'' last fall. That gave Phillippe an instant connection to
the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, I was connected to the movie because we had
similar themes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pregnancy angle was also a primary interest for McQuarrie.
After his big success with ``The Usual Suspects'' script _ for
which he won a 1995 Oscar _ no studio was interested in any film
idea from him unless it was a crime movie. He wanted to direct a
film about Alexander the Great and has tried to get it off the
ground for years.
</P>
<P>
   But like actors and directors, writers get typecast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benicio Del Toro said, `Look, if you want to make a movie your
way, you're going to have to make the kind of movie they want.' But
my heart wasn't in it,'' McQuarrie said.
</P>
<P>
   That changed with his ``The Way of the Gun'' story gimmick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was my wife who gave me the idea about the surrogate
mother. I was hooked; I was back into it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to coming up with the kernel of the idea, Heather
Neely McQuarrie was also the film's costume designer.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie immediately envisioned one of the film's most bizarre
tongue-in-cheek scenes, in which three gunmen and a doctor are
trapped in a weapons-cocked stand-off over a woman having a
Caesarean section.
</P>
<P>
   ``That literally was the image. I thought, `What are all the
things that could go wrong?' It was almost an instant connection
from `surrogate mother' to `guys in a birthing room shooting it
out.'''
</P>
<P>
   XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
