<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 16:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4146 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CONGRESS06-COX     09-06 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SOME IN CONGRESS SNUB HASTERT'S OFFER TO CLINTON
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sign that the upcoming negotiations between
Congress and President Clinton may be rocky, leading Republicans
and Democrats declined Wednesday to endorse an end-of-session
compromise offered by Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Hastert suggested last week to Clinton that a minimum wage
increase sought by the Democrats be paired with a Republican
package of $76 billion in tax relief for businesses and the
self-employed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally commend the speaker for trying to extend an olive
branch to the president and saying, 'Let's work on these things
that we can work on to get them done for the American people,' ``
said Rep. J.C. Watts of Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   But Watts, who chairs the group that includes all Republican
House members, declined to be pinned down on whether he or a
majority of rank-and-file Republicans would vote for Hastert's
plan. So did the other Republicans who flanked him at a news
conference held after a strategy session for two dozen GOP House
members.
</P>
<P>
   Meeting separately with reporters, Senate Democratic Leader Tom
Daschle of South Dakota was also skeptical. He complained that by
restoring the full deduction for business-related meals, the
compromise would ``put the three-martini lunch break back in, and
that's a $30 billion cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Dropping that $30 billion tax break would bring the $76 billion
package closer to ``a cost parameter that I could be more
enthusiastic about,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Deals on spending levels are more likely than agreement on
taxes, indicated the House GOP strategists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're prepared to meet the president more than halfway in
getting these bills done,'' said Rep. Jim Kolbe, R-Ariz., who
chairs an appropriations subcommittee. ``But we need to have the
president of the United States tell us how much money he needs to
have in these appropriation bills to satisfy him.''
</P>
<P>
   A meeting to kick off negotiations between the parties is being
planned for next week. Clinton, Daschle and House Minority Leader
Dick Gephardt, D-Mo., will represent the Democrats. Hastert and
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., will lead the GOP team.
</P>
<P>
   Each leader will need rank-and-file support from his own
followers in the negotiations that are expected to follow.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans will be skeptical of any deals struck with
Clinton, said Rep. Jim Greenwood, R-Pa.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadly, it was the consensus of most of us in that room that
... what Bill Clinton wants as a legacy is to wrest control of
Congress from Republicans to the Democrats,'' Greenwood told
reporters, ``and therefore we can't expect him to play straight and
fair with the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   Congress: thomas.loc.gov
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Mollison's e-mail address is AndyM(at)Coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
