<SLUG> BC-DENTIST-ADS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     COURT BACKS AD STANDARDS FOR DENTISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BOB EGELKO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If you are a dentist who advertises that your
rates are low, your quality is high and your sterilization methods
are state-of-the-art, the California Dental Association says you
may not be ethical enough to be a member.
</P>
<P>
   The CDA's code, which details advertising practices that the
organization considers false or misleading, prompted an antitrust
challenge by the Federal Trade Commission, which said customers
were being deprived of full competition for price and services. But
the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the restrictions
actually helped customers make better-informed choices.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC failed to show that the limits on advertising claims led
to higher prices or reduced competition, or that dentists who
wanted to advertise unspecified low rates or high quality actually
were cheaper or better, said Judge Cynthia Holcomb Hall in the 3-0
ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing in the record contradicts our intuition that when a
dentist advertises using an empty slogan like `The Best Dentist in
the State,' a reader learns more about that dentist's lack of
modesty than anything else,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   All state dental associations and the American Dental
Association have largely similar advertising rules, and many state
medical societies make comparable attempts to prevent deceptive ads
for doctors, said Peter Sfikas, the CDA's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   CDA membership is not required to practice dentistry, but about
19,000 of California's 26,000 licensed dentists belong. The
organization can expel members who violate its code.
</P>
<P>
   The appeals court had agreed with the FTC in 1997 that the CDA's
standards were illegal, but was ordered by the Supreme Court last
year to reconsider the case under a standard that required weighing
the benefits and harms to consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The case, the first in the nation to address such rules, is part
of a long-running dispute over professional advertising _ regarded
by its advocates as an infusion of competition into fortress-like
occupational guilds, and by opponents as an attempt to let
modern-day patent-medicine salesmen prey on an unsuspecting public.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1977 that a state could not ban
advertising by lawyers, but left the door open for regulation of
advertising practices.
</P>
<P>
   The CDA's advertising code says a dentist who claims that fees
are low must be able to prove that they are lower than other
dentists' fees. An ad proclaiming price discounts must also state
the amount of a non-discounted fee for each service and other
specifics, the CDA says, a restriction that the FTC said would
virtually rule out across-the-board discounts.
</P>
<P>
   The code also says claims of high quality should usually be
considered misleading because they cannot be proved. The CDA has
dropped its former ban on ads touting ``gentle'' dentistry, but
still frowns on claims that imply a dentist is superior to others,
Sfikas said.
</P>
<P>
   The ruling provides assurance that ``patients and consumers can
rely upon ads by CDA members,'' Sfikas said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
