<SLUG> BC-LAWNMOWER-RACER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOWERS BECOME LEAN, MEAN RACING MACHINES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GAILE ROBINSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEATHERFORD, Texas _ ``Rocket'' Reece Reeves is the man to see
for racing machines. He is the Enzo Ferrari of stroked crankshafts,
milled heads and custom-forged pistons. He customizes engines. He
turns suburban machines into lean, mean, lawn mower racing
machines.
</P>
<P>
   That's right, lawn mower racing. It may be the fastest growing
sport in ... well, who knows. The spokespeople are flaky and the
racers are downright crazed. ``It's the sport of the new
mow-lennium,'' says Bruce Kaufman, a racer and president of the
United States Lawn Mower Racing Association.
</P>
<P>
   The group is sponsored by Chicago's Gold Eagle Co., manufacturer
of Sta-bil, a fuel additive. Their slogan: ``We turn a chore into a
competitive sport.''
</P>
<P>
   There's the come-on. For every sod warrior who fancies himself
(or herself; there are a few) an Andretti as he corners the mailbox
and zooms down the straightaway past the air conditioner and into
the back yard, there is a reality.
</P>
<P>
   Flash to a lawn-mower racetrack; OK, it's only a hay-bale lined
soccer field, but it has all the sounds of a racetrack. Drivers
line up shoulder to shoulder for the start, they lean into the
tight turns, machines rolling up on two wheels, engines screaming
like monster motorcycles. Mowers spin out of control and crash into
the infield. There, at the finish line, with the checkered flag
madly waving in figure-8s, lengths in front of everyone else, is
the sod warrior pushing his one cylinder engine to the max, 45, 50,
sometimes in excess of 60 miles an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine was clocked at 67 miles per hour at the Texas Motor
Speedway. Now, it'll go 80, but that's not official,'' says the
30-year-old Reeves, who tinkers with Murrays, John Deeres and
Snappers at his shop, Reeves' Mow Better. It's a three-bay space in
an industrial strip mall that has tripled in size since Reeves
opened at the beginning of the year. There are racing machines
filling up one entire garage _ three of them belong to Reeves. One
is a Little Mustang by Huffman, the most coveted lawn-mower racer.
Reeves found it abandoned and rusting in a field outside
Weatherford. He paid $15 for the privilege of digging it out of the
soil that had solidified around it. Reeves is itching to get his
hands on the racers, but on this day, customers keep intervening.
</P>
<P>
   They arrive with lawn mowers that actually cut grass, or don't,
and that's the problem. Instead of aluminum heads, they need a
starter fixed. The woman in the Ford Explorer does not want a
$1,200 titanium rod. She wants her engine to quit smoking.
</P>
<P>
   Lawn Mower Racing is still in its infancy, which is why Reeves
still works with civilians as well as customizing engines for
racers from Australia, Holland and England. The international
circuit is huge. In the United States, the sport is a mere 7 years
old, with 500 registered racers on the Sta-bil circuit. The mow the
merrier, enthuses Kaufman. The 2000 Sta-bil nationals were held
Labor Day weekend outside Indianapolis, on a county fairgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   The sport is still in its infancy. There are no big purses, only
trophies and the honor. All the proceeds go to charity. A regular
Joe can participate on a $200 to $300 investment, Reeves says.
``It's a lot less expensive than NASCAR and a hundred times better.
With a car, you can control it. With a lawn mower, you don't know
what it's going to do, go sideways, or what. There is so much more
adrenalin.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves dons his racing gear: a full helmet, flame-retardant
motorcycle pants, a neck brace, a chest protector and heavy boots.
He proudly shows off his three trophies; the 2-foot-tall awards are
about the size you get when you win the company softball
tournament. ``Next year, we'll have to get a big trophy cabinet.''
The vehicle that will help fill that cabinet is Reeves' 1992 Murray
that he bought for $25 at a garage sale.
</P>
<P>
   The mower's blade has been removed, and Reeves has fiddled with
the engine and treated the body to a professional paint job. Every
flat surface bears a decal _ Weatherford Sign Co., Turpin Tire,
Sta-bil. The local sponsorships are not enough to allow Reeves to
travel the circuit with his pit crew: his wife, Shawntel, and two
young sons. ``Although Briggs &AMP; Stratton have been very kind,''
Reeves says.
</P>
<P>
   He hopes that the custom work will someday consume all of his
time; now it is only 30 percent. Racers who have used Reeves'
services think the day may come. ``The people who will succeed in
this business will be able to work frames and metal. They will have
to do chassis as well as engines,'' says Bob Frennesson of Katy,
Texas, one of the Team Texas racers.
</P>
<P>
   It would help if the sport became big, as in, known. For that to
happen, there will need to be bags of cash at the finish line and
hobbyists with more money than sense, willing to shell out
thousands of dollars for titanium rods that will help them crash
through hay bales at ever greater speeds. Until that day, Reeves is
relegated to fixing starters, and not attending the nationals.
</P>
<P>
   The extreme heat in Texas has kept the grass from growing, which
has kept mowers in the garage and Reeves shy of work. As the sun
blazes across the empty parking lot next door, Reeves is doing
figure 8's at what seems an incredibly dangerous speed. His wife,
left to manage the repair shop, watches, only sightly bemused. When
Reeves became a racer, she became the family lawn mower.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
