<SLUG> BC-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    PUTTING WALLBOARD IN ITS PLACE QL
</HEADLINE>
 QL  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is being sent
to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) QL 
By EDWARD R. LIPINSKI QC 
  QL 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service QC 
<TEXT>
  &QL; QL &QR; 
     Before the introduction of gypsum wallboard, interior walls were
finished with plaster. Wallboard is essentially a flat sheet of plaster
sandwiched between sheets of special paper. Unlike plaster, wallboard is
fastened to the studs in a dry state and for this reason it is frequently
called drywall. (It is also sometimes called Sheetrock, but this is a trade
name of the USG Corp. and should only be used in reference to its product.)
   The thickness of wallboard varies from one-fourth to 5/8 of an inch in
1/8-inch increments. The half-inch thickness is best for most uses. Use
the thicker 5/8-inch board in areas where a firewall is required or on
walls to muffle sound transmission. The thinner grades, 3/8 and 1/4-inch,
should only be used for curved wall surfaces or on walls where the new
material will have to match the thickness of a thin adjacent  wall.
   Wallboard is also available with a water-resistant core. This product
should be installed in areas where humidity may be a problem, such as damp
basements. Water-resistant wallboard is not waterproof, however, and should
not be used in  wet areas like showers (where it is best to install cement
backer board with a waterproof membrane).
   The standard width of wallboard panels is 4 feet. Panels vary in length
from 6 feet to 16 feet. The most popular lengths are 8 and 12 feet. The
larger panels cover more area, creating fewer joints to tape, but they are
heavy -   12-foot panels weigh 82 pounds; the 8-foot panels weigh 55 pounds
- and are difficult to maneuver in small rooms.
   You can use drywall nails or screws to secure the panels to the studs,
but  screws are superior fasteners because they do not pop loose like nails
can. Use 1 1/4-inch screws for mounting 1/2-inch-thick wallboard, and 1
5/8-inch  screws for 5/8-inch-thick panels. The ideal tool to use for
driving drywall screws is a drywall screwgun (this can be rented at rental
centers). It is better than a variable speed drill because it has an
adjustable nose that allows you to set the screws at a precise depth and it
operates at low torque  so the screws will not rip into the plaster core.
   To estimate the quantity of material needed, add the total surface area
that you intend to panel. Do not deduct the area of the doors and windows
unless  they are very large. Then divide that number by the total square
feet per sheet. A 4-by-8 panel covers 32 square feet and a 4-by-12 covers
48 square  feet.
   Drywall does not store well, so try to order the exact number of panels
needed. At your work site, stack the panels on edge, making sure they are
evenly supported so they do not bend or warp.
   Before mounting the wallboard, check the condition of the plumbing and
electrical lines in the walls and make any repairs or additions while
everything is still exposed. Next, check the corners where adjacent walls
meet and where the walls and ceiling join. Usually the corner posts and the
top  plates do not extend far enough to provide support for the drywall. It
is best to nail backers made of 2-by-4's to provide mounting surfaces in
these  places.
   If you are finishing an entire room, start by installing the ceiling
panels (called the lids) first, and then work on the walls from the top
down. When the  wall panels are in place they will support the ceiling.
   Lifting drywall panels overhead is hard work. You will need a helper for
this. You can also rent a drywall jack (also called a lift) at rental
outlets  to raise the panels and hold them in place while you secure them
to the joists.
   Whenever possible, try to install complete panels so you will have fewer
joints to tape over. There will be areas where you will have to cut a panel
to  fit. First, mark the length needed on the finish side of the board,
then score across the line with a utility knife. Use a metal straightedge
as a guide.  Stand the wallboard on edge and bend it toward the backside;
this will snap the board at the score line. Once the board breaks, fold it
back to form a right  angle. Cut the backing paper at the fold with the
utility knife.
   Press the panel against the studs and drive the screws, spaced evenly
every 12 inches, through the board into the studs. It is important to drive
the  screws so the heads are slightly depressed below the surface of the
panel yet not so deep the screw breaks through the paper. If you do drive a
screw too  deep, install another about an inch away, then remove the
improperly set screw.
</TEXT>
</BODY>
