<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOADIES-CD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOADIES FANS WON'T BE HOPPING ON NEW CD THIS YEAR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There it was, just a few weeks ago, on record label Interscope's
schedule of CDs for fall release: a new disc from Fort Worth's
Toadies.
</P>
<P>
   A title was not given; nor was a concrete release date.
Nonetheless, that piece of paper had the Toadies' name etched on
it, promising a new disc.
</P>
<P>
   After five years of scrapping songs, producers, band members and
ideas, the North Texas punk-pop group was finally releasing a
follow-up to its 1994 major-label debut, ``Rubberneck.'' That
surprise first CD spawned a handful of hit singles _ including the
``do-you-wanna-die?'' anthem ``Possum Kingdom'' _ and sold more
than a million copies, making the Toadies the first
alternative-rock success story for Fort Worth. Ever since, fans
have been waiting for a sophomore effort.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks after the follow-up album was announced, an
updated list was put out _ and it was gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know; it's just not on here anymore,'' says Interscope
publicist Terry Wang, scanning the list while on the phone.
</P>
<P>
   To Toadies fans, news of the disc showing up on a release
schedule, and then disappearing, is not the least bit surprising.
At this point, they're used to it.
</P>
<P>
   For the past few years, the record _ initially called
``Feeler,'' now called ``Hell Below, Stars Above'' _ has been
penciled in and erased, recorded, then rerecorded.
</P>
<P>
   As of today, it is tentatively set to come out early in 2001,
well after Interscope's fall shower of high-profile releases, such
as Marilyn Manson's ``Holy Wood'' (''In the Shadow of the Valley of
Death''), U2's ``All That You Can't Leave Behind'' and the
Wallflowers' ``Breach.''
</P>
<P>
   Toadies drummer Mark Reznicek says Interscope's strong fall
lineup is the reason for the latest delay: The label and the band
don't want the record to get lost in a shuffle of priority-one
discs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to be competing with records on our own label,''
Reznicek says. ``Everyone thinks the best time for it to come out
will be early next year, when there's not so much other stuff
coming out. It's not like Interscope is delaying it. They wanna put
it out as much as we do. Sure, I wanna put it out as soon as
possible, but I also want it to do as well as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they long ago fell off the national scene, the Toadies
never really dropped out of sight locally. The band plays
occasional shows here and records at Last Beat studios in Dallas.
Tracks from Rubberneck still get airplay on area rock radio
stations such as KEGL/97.1 ``The Eagle'' and 94.5/KDGE ``The
Edge.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, they still have a local presence.
</P>
<P>
   It's their presence nationally _ or lack thereof _ that has some
industry watchers worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will always care locally. They're huge here,'' says
Duane Doherty, program director for The Edge. ``But it's been so
long since `Possum Kingdom' came out, I don't know if people will
remember them nationally. So many bands come and go, it's hard to
say if they'll remember this one.''
</P>
<P>
   Eric Grubbs, an evening DJ at 88.7/KTCU ``The Choice'' _ the
Texas Christian University station credited with ``discovering''
the Toadies locally during the early '90s _ thinks they will.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that band is more than just a local cult act now,''
Grubbs says. ``They've got a major national following. I'd say
their new record is as big a deal as Weezer's new one, in terms of
anticipation.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubbs adds that ``the Internet buzz is very big'' on a new
Toadies song that's floating around in cyberspace and also
available on a sampler CD that was passed out to fans at the recent
Vans Warped Tour in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The track, ``Heel,'' has wound up on a handful of Texas radio
stations, The Edge included.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's proof that people still care,'' Grubbs says of the
airplay the song has received. ``That record has been so
long-awaited, when it finally comes out, there will be people
lining up to get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, the only thing fans are lining up to do is ask the
Toadies what has taken the band so long to release a new disc.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons are numerous.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Rubberneck'' took off in 1995, the band went through a
membership shuffle: Guitarist Darrel Herbert, who co-wrote three
``Rubberneck'' tracks, left; Clark Vogeler, a former member of
another North Texas rock group, Funland, took his spot and had to
be broken in. Herbert's departure was the first in a series of
setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   After tours with Bush and the B_hole Surfers, among others, the
band _ Reznicek, Vogeler, singer Todd Lewis and bassist Lisa
Umbarger _ recorded a batch of songs with B_hole Surfers member
Paul Leary producing. At the end of the sessions, neither the band
nor the label, Reznicek says, was too thrilled with the songs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The label and us just didn't like the way they turned out,''
Reznicek says. ``They sounded computerized and processed. They
didn't have that live sound that we like. But chances are, we'll
release some of that stuff in one form or another, someday.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of that material, Umbarger said, was shelved. New songs
were written, and to tweak them, the group turned to the team
responsible for producing and engineering ``Rubberneck:'' Tom
Rothrock and Rob Schnapf. Andy Wallace was brought back in to
reprise his ``Rubberneck'' role as mixer.
</P>
<P>
   Writing new songs and scrambling to rehire and get comfortable
working again with the three studio whizzes came on the heels of a
long down period for the band, brought on by a record-company
merger that resulted in layoffs and band axings.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Toadies sold more than a million copies of
``Rubberneck'' _ ensuring them a home at Interscope during the
merger _ funds were temporarily frozen, keeping them from making
progress on the new disc.
</P>
<P>
   After the merger blew over, the band resumed recording,
eventually coming home with ``Hell Below, Stars Above.''
</P>
<P>
   But again, they must wait, this time until Interscope has
released efforts from Limp Bizkit, U2 and the Wallflowers _ sure
things that will sell well during the music-industry's cutthroat
Christmas season.
</P>
<P>
   All this waiting has left the band members strapped for cash,
hence a string of Texas shows over the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had to take day jobs, but we've come pretty
close,'' Reznicek says. ``People ask that all the time. That, and
they ask, `Where's the record?' That's been the question for years.
I just say, `It's a long story.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
