<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF NEW VIDEO GAMES
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You can smell it in the air: sweat, hot dogs and more sweat.
</P>
<P>
   It's outdoor professional sports season. Has been for a while.
And it'll rage on for a few months, causing traffic jams around The
Ballpark in Arlington, fistfights in the parking lot of Texas
Stadium and a rash of yawning wherever our soccer team does its
thing.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative: Stay at home and simulate the lovely nuances of
outdoor sporting events with these three games:
</P>
<P>
   Sydney 2000 (Eidos for Sony PlayStation): Man, is there a
sporting event that vidgame companies haven't gotten their hands on
yet? How 'bout that chuck-wagon championship in Iowa?
</P>
<P>
   This new arrival is, obviously, self-explanatory: It's based on
the upcoming Olympic tournaments in Sydney, Australia, and features
a dozen events. Players compete with the computer or against one
another in events such as high jump, javelin throw, skeet shooting,
cycling, kayaking and swimming.
</P>
<P>
   Before the events begin, players can train their characters in
the virtual gym, which is about the only working out that I've ever
done.
</P>
<P>
   The graphics are OK, but you can tell Sony and its third-party
game makers are cutting corners and costs, probably to gear up and
save up for this fall's PlayStation 2 arrival. The graphics are a
little boxy and the response time is slightly slow, so proceed with
caution.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Tennis (Nintendo for Nintendo 64): This is more about
having a good, goofy time than playing a good game of tennis. If
you want the latter, Sega Dreamcast's Virtua Tennis is where it's
at. Mario Tennis will only frustrate you.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of the army of Mario games will undoubtedly love this,
though. You can choose your fave Mario characters for rounds of
singles and doubles. There are also some cool minigames and special
effects, such as a tilting court. Fun stuff, but don't expect any
more than that.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry McGrath Supercross 2000 (Acclaim for Sega Dreamcast): This
was lame for PlayStation, and it hasn't improved a bit for
Dreamcast. Yet another motorcross racing game with absolutely no
personality or distinguishing characteristics, Supercross 2K is
simply a retread of Excitebike and all the others that have come
before: Choose your ride, choose your track, race, spill, cross the
finish line. Repeat until boredom sets in. Which is gonna be pretty
fast. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
