</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SCREEN-NAMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD SCREEN NAMES ARE HARD TI FIND, AND GETTING HARDER QL
</HEADLINE>
 nnn$tie-z QL  
 &HT;    u axxnt26 nt22 nt11 nt33 QL 
uaxx QL QL (Circuits) QL 
By JOYCE COHEN QC 
  QL 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service QC 
<TEXT>
  &QL; QL &QR; 
     Who knew that so many grandfathers went by the name Poppop?

      Robert Sullivan found out. A grandfather of eight who lives in
Summerville, S.C.,  Sullivan uses the name Poppop(at)aol.com as his e-mail
address. He gets about five e-mail messages a day for the wrong Poppop.

     Sullivan suspects that many of the missives are meant for variations
of Poppop - Poppops burdened with additional numbers or initials - owned by
people who were too late to claim the pure, unadulterated version that he
registered  in 1992.

    A good screen name is hard to find, and getting harder. AOL has 23
million members and allows seven names for each account. So theoretically,
154 million names have already been taken, although AOL said the average
was 2.1 screen names per account.

    People looking for new names are frustrated. Some switch e-mail
services, try other spellings, add numbers or finally just settle on a less
appealing name.

   ``I must have tried a million combinations of my name,'' said John Noh,
who works in public relations in Silicon Valley. ``You wouldn't believe how
many JNohs or JohnNs or JohnNohs there are in the AOL database.

    ``Each abbreviation I tried had to be accompanied by some number,''
said   Noh, who used to think that his Korean last name was not very
common. ``I got so fed up I said, `I'll put my own number in there.'''

     Noh claimed noh666(at)aol.com.

   ``I had such a devilish time trying to get a screen name,'' he said,
``maybe I chose it subconsciously.''

    But the screen name became a problem when he began looking for a job.

   ``I felt stupid sending it out,''  Noh said. ``It was a conversation
piece among my friends, but in a professional setting I realized how
inappropriate it was.''  He was relieved to get jnoh(at)excite.com.

    Screen names are now an important part of people's identities, said
Steve Jones, a communication professor at the University of Illinois in
Chicago who studies online social relations.  People's screen names are
often meaningful to them, even if they are inscrutable to others.

    When someone asks for a screen name that is already taken, e-mail
services often suggest adding a number. That can be a problem. Even numbers
that mean something to the user - a  street address, a ZIP code, a birth
date, a lucky number - seem random and hard for others to remember. That is
why people prefer sequences, like 1234, or patterns, like 8888, Jones said.

      The earliest AOL users were able to get ordinary screen names.
``Having anything normal-sounding on AOL is a gold star of the early
adoptive personality,'' said Rachel Pine, a former AOL user in New York.

      Last fall,  Pine planned a party that was supposed to have Curious
George as the host. She wanted to register ``curiousgeorge'' as a screen
name where people  could send RSVPs. She tried  CuriousGeorge(at)yahoo,
then CGeorge,  CuriousG, CuryosGeorge and even YellowHat -  a ``desperation
move,'' she said.  All were taken.

     So she went elsewhere. RachelPine(at)yahoo.com was also taken, but she
got Rachel(underscore)Pine(at)yahoo and decided that she liked the
underscore. ``My name is not RachelPine all one word,'' she said. She also
claimed  her name - underscore included - on several free e-mail services,
fearing that the chance would never come again.

   Many people have different screen names for business and personal  use.
For e-mail messages at work, people often have their names or variations of
them, sometimes in  standard formats required by their offices. Personal
e-mail messages tend to operate according to what Jones calls the concert
T-shirt effect: People choose the name of something they like, whether it
is a band, song, sports team, celebrity or fairy tale character. People
also choose names that help them adopt different personalities or sexes  in
chat rooms, for dating services and on message boards, ``just as
adolescents might choose to have a nickname or choose how to dress,'' Jones
said. ``Because we have a high degree of anonymity on e-mail,'' he added,
``the screen name is the only thing  that distinguishes us.''

       Unlike domain names,  screen names can be used by more than one
person as long as the suffix is different. That was one of the ideas behind
Mail.com,  which lets each user pick the first two parts of each e-mail
address, not just the first part. Mail.com has about 17 million addresses
in use.

       ``We recognized that if you went to AOL or Hotmail or Yahoo,
millions of people had already picked the main address,'' said Gerald
Gorman, Mail.com's chairman and chief executive.

       Mail.com circumvents the problem by offering about 100 choices for
the second part of the e-mail address. It also permits the use of various
keyboard characters like ampersands, asterisks and dollar signs. They might
be cumbersome to say aloud, but at least that allows many versions of the
same name, from common&AMP;name(at)writeme.com to
common(star)name(at)cheerful.com to common$name(at)london.com.

       People especially like professional suffixes -  (at)deliveryman.com,
(at)doctor.com, (at)priest.com -  as part of their e-mail addresses on
their business cards,  Gorman said.

       AOL, which allows only letters, numbers and spaces, responded to the
demand for more names by expanding the number of characters allowed per
name to to 16 from 10, said a spokeswoman, Tricia Primrose. One advantage
is that more people can fit in their full names. People sometimes fill
their seven AOL slots by registering names for their children, or even for
their unborn babies. ``It's never too early,''  Primrose said.

        But it is often too late. When people drop AOL, their screen names
remain out of circulation for a minimum of six months, and often for far
longer. ``We don't want to recycle too quickly,''  Primrose said, ``the
danger being that too much wrong mail will get to the former user.''

   t can also be difficult to get a first choice for a name  on sites
requiring registration.

   Brenda Nashawaty, a frequent online shopper from Boston, was surprised
to find that even her unusual last name, which is Middle Eastern, did not
help.

   ``The Nashawatys must be an online bunch,'' Nashawaty said. On shopping
sites, her name is inevitably taken as either a log-in name or a password.

       ``I've used my cat's name, MishMosh, my perfume, Vanille, and my
car,  GrayCamry,'' she said. ``I'm reduced to looking around my office for
names I'd  remember.''

      Of course, names that are too catchy end up with the Poppop problem.
Names that are too common can be undesirable because they get so much junk
mail,  said John Levine, one of the authors of ``E-Mail for Dummies'' (IDG
Books Worldwide, 1997).

       Many AOL members will not accept e-mail messages from just any
sender, and their AOL profiles explain why. Mike(at)aol.com wrote in his
profile: ``You probably have me confused with some other person named Mike.
His screen name is not Mike. If he has sent you e-mail, check the  From
line to obtain the correct screen name.''

       In his profile, Tony(at)aol.com was more irritated. ``No I am not
the Tony you are looking for,'' he wrote, ``so before you IM me out of pure
ignorance with something like, `How was your day at work,' or, `Hey, Tony,
how's your wife?' think for a minute about how many people use AOL and how
many are potentially named Tony.''

        Sullivan confirmed that such errant correspondence was both boring
and  bothersome. ``The messages say things like: `Thank you for the book,'
`See you at Easter,' `We had fun on vacation,''' said  Sullivan, who used
to reply with a polite note and a suggestion for finding the right Poppop.
He now  answers with a terse, ``Wrong Poppop!''

       One instant message encounter turned into an almost hourlong
computer confrontation that became ``kind of heated,''  Sullivan said.

       ``This was an older gentleman like myself,  and he didn't know much
about computers,''  Sullivan said. ``He said I had put my name on his IM
list and it was costing him money and he was going to report me to AOL.
Evidently he had a friend he called Poppop. I said, `This is my e-mail
address,  no matter what your friend's name is.' He didn't understand that.''
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1711EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
