<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0170 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4171 &Cx1f; tad-z
r p BC-POL-TICKER0907-COX     09-06 1758
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE OFFERS MASSIVE ECONOMIC PLAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore offered up a voluminous and detailed spending plan for
the nation Wednesday in Cleveland, promising to create 10 million
high-tech jobs, send poverty to historic lows and boost family
income by one-third. Gore also said he would erase the national
debt and strengthen the finances of Social Security and Medicare.
Senior aides said by focusing on reducing the national debt, Gore's
191-page plan, ``Prosperity for America's Families,'' casts him as
the fiscal conservative in his fight with George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH TELLS VETS MILITARY DETERIORATING
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush appeared at the American Legion convention in
Milwaukee Wednesday and accused Al Gore of letting military
readiness slide. Bush got a boost from the national commander of
the veterans organization, Alan Lance Sr., who blasted Gore for
skipping the group's convention and offering to send his running
mate, Joe Lieberman, in his place. The Legion ``deserves to hear
directly from the man himself, a man who would be our commander in
chief,'' Lance said. The Gore campaign said the event conflicted
with the vice president's speech on economics, and said Bush's
criticism of military readiness carried no credibility.
</P>
<P>
   DIGGING IN DEEPER ON DEBATES
</P>
<P>
   The argument between Al Gore and George W. Bush over debates has
become part of a new Bush campaign ad. The spot says Gore promised
to debate anytime, anywhere _ but now insists that debates be
sponsored by a non-partisan commission. Bush told reporters he'll
stick to his plan to show up for a first debate with Gore in
Washington next Tuesday, even though NBC, the host network, said it
won't air the event without Gore. Said Gore: ``I'm not going to
play games to try to substitute a talk show for the national
bipartisan commission debates.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE OVERTAKES BUSH IN MISSOURI
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has caught George W. Bush in Missouri after trailing
much of the year, according to a new poll published in the Kansas
City Star. Gore led 45-41 percent, jumping from an 11-point deficit
in early July. The Mason-Dixon poll had a 4 percentage point margin
of error, making it a statistical tie. Green Party nominee Ralph
Nader had 2 percent, while Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan was
at 1 percent. Gore made the most progress in Missouri among women,
who now back him by 53-35 percent. In July, Bush led among women
44-41 percent. Bush led by 10 points among men, although the spread
has decreased from 19 points.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE BATTLE SET IN FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   Two candidates hoping to become Florida's next senator glided
through primaries. Democrat Bill Nelson, the state insurance
commissioner, and Republican Rep. Bill McCollum easily won their
parties' nominations to fill retiring Republican Sen. Connie Mack's
seat, setting up a competitive race in the fall with national
importance. McCollum, who served as a floor manager in President
Clinton's impeachment hearing, took 82 percent of the 800,000
Republican votes, while Nelson won 77 percent of the 850,000
Democratic votes.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-DADE MAYOR WINS RE-ELECTION
</P>
<P>
   In another Florida race, Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas won a
second term after months of tumult over the Elian Gonzalez case.
Penelas outpaced nine other candidates after being widely accused
of pandering to Cuban-Americans for vowing to deny police
assistance for Elian's removal. Needing more than 50 percent of the
vote to avoid a runoff, Penelas got 51.6 percent to county
Commissioner Miguel Diaz de la Portilla's 20.9 percent. Businessman
Jay Love was third with 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   SENATE FACE-OFF SET IN NEVADA
</P>
<P>
   John Ensign, a veterinarian and former congressman, swiftly won
the Republican primary for an open Senate seat in Nevada. Final
results showed Ensign trouncing his closest opponent by a nearly
20-to-1 margin. In November, Ensign faces millionaire Democratic
lawyer Ed Bernstein, who ran unopposed. Republican leaders consider
Nevada one of their best chances nationally to turn a formerly
Democratic seat their way. Democratic Sen. Richard Bryan decided to
retire after two terms.
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY CLINTON GETS ENVIRONMENTALISTS' BACKING
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton won the endorsement of the Sierra Club, one of
the nation's oldest environmental groups, whose backing set off a
duel between the Senate candidates over who has done more to
protect natural resources. Sierra officials said Rep. Rick Lazio,
the Republican candidate, offered inconsistent support for
environmental matters in his eight-year tenure in Congress. And
members of the group said in an interview with the New York Times
that Lazio did not demonstrate a firm grasp of the environmental
issues the group studies. By contrast, said Rhea Jezer, head of the
club's New York chapter, Clinton ``showed an unequaled depth of
knowledge on a plethora of state and national issues.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS FUND-RAISER BACK ON NEW YORK SCENE
</P>
<P>
   When John McCain lost the New York Republican primary last
spring, he put a large part of the blame on what he asserted was an
illegal $2.5 million ad campaign that attacked his environmental
record financed by two wealthy Texas brothers with close ties to
George W. Bush. One of those two brothers, Charles Wyly, has
resurfaced on the New York political scene. This time, he's allied
with Rick Lazio, whom McCain is supporting energetically against
Hillary Clinton. Wyly is a sponsor of one of three out-of-state
fund-raisers Lazio attended Wednesday. Wyly is one of nine
signatories to a letter asking Texans to attend a fund-raiser in
Dallas. ``Many people believe that Mrs. Clinton is the driving
force behind some of the most radical ideas put forth by the
Clinton administration,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   LONG-AGO ADVICE ON DEBATING
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney, as chief of staff to President Ford, helped craft a
battle plan to defeat Jimmy Carter that questioned whether he was
ready for the White House. Challenge him to debates, then try to
get him to come across as ``fuzzy and indecisive'' on issues such
as domestic affairs, the economy, national defense and foreign
policy, Cheney advised. The strategies were captured in a post-1976
election essay Cheney wrote that is on file at Ford's presidential
library in Ann Arbor, Mich. ``We did not believe his `trust me'
approach would be very effective in a debate setting when he was
asked for specific views on major national issues,'' Cheney wrote
of Carter. Carter won that election.
</P>
<P>
   AD HITS BUSH ON CHILD HEALTH CARE
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic National Committee will begin running a new TV
spot today that takes a critical look at Texas Gov. George W.
Bush's record of providing health care for children in Texas. The
30-second ad is to run in nine states: Arkansas, Delaware,
Louisiana, Michigan, Missouri, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Washington and
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY DEFENDS HIS CHARITABLE GIVING
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney defended his charitable contributions as
``appropriate'' and insisted he should be given credit not only for
direct contributions, but for speaking fees he directed to charity
and for corporate gifts that matched his own donations. Cheney
challenged the suggestion that his generosity should be measured by
comparing his direct contributions of $209,832 over the past 10
years to his income of $20,677,742, a standard by which he gave
1.01 percent of his income. He also counted $89,500 in speaking
fees and $142,820 in matching grants from corporations on whose
boards he and his wife, Lynne, sit. Bush and Cheney have been
urging support of faith-based organizations and charities that
provide services to cure social problems and help poor people.
</P>
<P>
   COMPLAINT HITS LIEBERMAN'S SENATE CANDIDACY
</P>
<P>
   A politics professor asked the Connecticut Elections Enforcement
Commission to declare Joe Lieberman's Senate campaign ``frivolous''
and order him off the state ballot. Lieberman, the Democratic
nominee for vice president, already had announced his intention to
run for re-election when Al Gore selected him as a running mate.
Lieberman has since said he will continue both campaigns _ a
decision criticized by both Republicans and Democrats. State law
permits him to conduct the dual campaigns. But John Orman of
Fairfield University contends in his complaint that Lieberman's
candidacy is illegal, because he would not serve in the Senate if
elected to both offices and because the dual candidacies give
Lieberman an unfair fund-raising advantage.
</P>
<P>
   SUIT SEEKS BUCHANAN RECOGNITION AS NOMINEE
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for a faction of the Reform Party loyal to Pat Buchanan
asked a California state court to declare him the party's true
presidential nominee. Their rivals in the fractured party are
planning their own lawsuit seeking a legal judgment backing up
their contention that John Hagelin is the nominee. At stake is
$12.6 million in federal subsidies for the winning side. The action
came a week after a federal judge in Lynchburg, Va., refused to
referee the party's bitter split, saying he lacked the jurisdiction
to do so. Dale Cooter, an attorney for the Buchanan contingent,
filed the claim in Superior Court in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   SHE CAN SEE IT CLEARLY NOW
</P>
<P>
   If psychic Dee Dee Smith is to be believed, Democratic vice
presidential candidate Joe Lieberman can stop campaigning. He and
Al Gore have already won. ``I predict Gore will do very well. He'll
win Illinois and I do see him in the White House,'' said Smith, a
63 year-old prognosticator, of the Democratic ticket's chances.
Smith was at the coffeehouse where Lieberman held a round-table
discussion on middle-class tax cuts with local families. She went
in for breakfast and stayed for the talk. Smith said her
predictions are usually about 85 percent accurate.
</P>
<P>
   MAKING FEELINGS KNOWN IN FRANCE
</P>
<P>
   American film director Robert Altman, in France to promote a
movie, said that should George W. Bush win in November, he's
fleeing the U.S.A. Altman, quoted by Reuters at a film festival:
``If George Bush is elected president, I'm leaving for France.''
More Altman: ``I don't think show business personalities should get
involved publicly and show their feelings, because that ends up
working against them. That's why I stay discreet about these
questions in America but, no matter what, it would be a catastrophe
for the whole world if George Bush is elected.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
