<SLUG> BC-AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INTERNATIONAL
</HEADLINE>
 


   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for the Page
1 of Thursday, Sept. 7. The N.Y. Times News Service night supervisor is Pat
Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail: patryan(at)nytimes.com.   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)



   U.N.-CLINTON (United Nations) - President Clinton on Wednesday told the
largest gathering of world leaders in history that the United Nations must
reconfigure itself to deal with a world in which there are ``fewer wars
between nations, but more wars within them.'' With the energy of a man who
sees his moment on the world stage quickly slipping away, he immediately
used the Millennium Summit meeting here to take a last stab at many of the
issues that have defied resolution during his presidency. He tried to fend
off a proposal from Russian president Vladimir Putin that would lead to a
demilitarization of outer space - an effort by Putin to put an end to
American talk of a national missile defense - and met with the Palestinian
leader, Yasser Arafat, and Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak in one last
effort to rescue the Middle East peace process. By David E. Sanger.



   U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT (United Nations) - The question hangs out there.
Why would 152 leaders leave their not-always-stable governments unattended
to come to New York and make five-minute speeches, mostly to each other and
the television cameras from back home? Secretary General Kofi Annan had an
answer today as he lifted his glass to the biggest power lunch in history.
``You,'' he said, looking out over the world's political elite, ``have the
ability to transform the lives of 6 billion people.'' By Barbara Crossette.



   WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS (United Nations) - An armed mob ran amok through a
U.N. refugee office in West Timor on Wednesday, beating to death three
unarmed U.N. workers, including an American, and touching off repercussions
of outrage halfway around the world at the Millenium Summit meeting of
world leaders here. By Christoher S. Wren.



   NATIONAL GENERAL

   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)



   NY-MAFIA-ARRESTS (New York) - The Manhattan district attorney Wednesday
charged 38 union officials, contractors and reputed mobsters with bribery,
bid-rigging or other racketeering schemes that siphoned millions of dollars
from public and private building projects throughout the city over the last
two years. By William K. Rashbaum.



   NY-BELGIUM-ROYALS (New York) - The royals are coming. No, no, not the
poor old British Crown Prince, still overshadowed by the tragic legacy of
Diana, Princess of Wales. Nor any of his relatives, like that fellow who
flies the helicopter and his former lady who does the weight-loss thing.
No, New York is getting the other ones, the fabulously cool new royals:
handsome Crown Prince Philippe of Belgium and his ravishing Princess
Mathilde, the fairy-tale couple that has monopolized magazine covers and
glossy photo spreads throughout Europe. Their mission is nothing less than
to take New York City by storm, winning hearts, minds, media and, more
importantly, market share. By Glenn Collins.



   DNA-CONVICTION (Richmond, Va.) - Six years after DNA testing raised
strong doubts about his guilt in a rape and homicide conviction, Earl
Washington Jr., a model prisoner with the IQ of a 10-year-old, awaited the
results of a more definitive test today as his lawyers filed a petition for
a full executive pardon after 17 years in prison. His lawyers, pioneers in
the increasingly successful DNA challenges of criminal convictions,
describe Washington as their long suffering poster child, an amiable,
passive farm hand with an IQ of 69 whose habit is to cooperatively agree
with people. They maintain his case is a summary of the main problems
prompting the rising national concern about capital convictions: race,
mental incapacity, convictions based solely on confession, appeal
limitations, and the inevitable pressures of politics. By Francis X. Clines.



   POLITICS

   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)



   GORE-ECON (Dateline to kum) - In a cadence mimicking former President
Bush's ``read my lips,'' Al Gore reached Wednesday for the mantle of fiscal
conservative, asking voters to ``read my plan'' in a hefty budget book
coupling balanced budgets and ambitious economic goals. (Summary from
wires) By Katharine Q. Seelye.



   GORE-ECON-ASSESS (Washington) - The economic policy blueprint released
Wednesday by Vice President Al Gore is an attempt to spell out for voters,
with considerable specificity, how Gore would seek to harness continued
prosperity on their behalf. A news analysis by Richard W. Stevenson.



   FINANCIAL

   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)



   TIRE-RECALL (Washington) - Faced with growing evidence that
Bridgestone/Firestone and possibly the Ford Motor Co. knew about tire
problems for years and did nothing, Republican and Democratic members of
Congress began hearings on the issue Wednesday by calling for more money
for safety regulators and stiffer penalties for violators. By Keith
Bradsher and Matthew L. Wald.



   CITIGROUP-ASSOCIATES (New York) - Continuing its campaign to become the
dominant financial services provider around the globe, Citigroup said
Wednesday that it would buy the Associates First Capital Corp., the biggest
American consumer-finance company, for about $31.1 billion in stock. The
acquisition, Citigroup's largest since its controversial formation in 1998,
would give Citigroup a significant position in consumer lending in Japan
and a few other countries. It also would improve Citigroup's standing in
the credit card and commercial leasing businesses. By Patrick McGeehan.



   SEAGRAMS-MP3-MUSIC (New York) - In a victory for old line music
companies over an online music start-up, a federal judge ruled on Wednesday
that MP3.com willfully violated copyrights  and awarded Universal Music
Group $25,000 per CD, a penalty that could reach as much as $250 million.
Judge Jed S. Rakoff of U.S. District Court in Manhattan said some Internet
companies ``may have a misconception that, because their technology is
somewhat novel, they are somehow immune from the ordinary applications of
laws of the United States, including copyright law.'' By Amy Harmon.



   SCIENCE

   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)



   SCI-INDIANS-CANNIBALS (Undated) - Scientists have found what they say is
the first direct evidence of cannibalism among prehistoric Indians in the
American Southwest, belying the image of these people as steadfastly
peaceful farmers and perhaps reigniting controversy over whether ancestral
Indians ever made a practice of eating human flesh. By John Noble Wilford.





