<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4179 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     09-06 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    TEMPTATION, IN SPIKE HEELS AND A DEVILISH PRICE TAG QL
</HEADLINE>
 QL  (Circuits) QL 
By MICHELLE SLATALLA QC 
 QL 
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service QC 
<TEXT>
    &QL; QL &QR; 
  Here is how I am used to shopping on the Internet. I arrive at an online
store that reminds me of a file cabinet, with all the merchandise tucked
away in tabbed folders. I click on the appropriate folder. Inside I find a
brochure for each item, with a short  description, a price and sometimes a
simple image to confirm that yes, this is the specific thing I have been
trying to track down.
   Here is how I shopped online last week. I walked down a narrow, hidden
alleyway, following a yellow butterfly as it flew past shuttered
townhouses. Then, as if I were wandering around in a version of Myst
optimized for shoe addicts, I peered through the window of a discreet door
set in the middle of a mysterious brick wall and caught a glimpse of
beautiful, spiky-heeled footwear displayed on simple metal perches.
   Beyond the door lay the Manolo Blahnik boutique that neimanmarcus.com
started last month to sell really (really) expensive shoes, using
technology that compresses and streams computer-generated video content at
a rate that enables even shoppers who connect over pokey dial-up modems to
feel as if they are browsing in the ladies' department of the Matrix.
   The technology comes from RichFX, a company headquartered in New York
that also licenses its technology to the jewelry Web site Kirabo.com and
will announce more partnerships in the next few months, company officials
said. The software creates an immersive setting that appears  in a single
window - no annoying pop-up boxes to clutter the screen - and is as
compelling as a video game.
   ``The idea is to turn the Internet into a place that you can move around
in, a place that feels real,'' said Tal Kerret, RichFX's chief executive.
``If you come in at different times of day or night, you get a different
experience, for example. The lighting in the store will be completely
different.''
    Plenty of other technologies have offered similar promises, of course.
``Other three-dimensional environments exist, but they don't download and
stream on demand to deliver what you want when you want, and others didn't
create a formula for such an elegant user interface, either,'' said Peter
Ausnit, an equity analyst at Deutsche Banc Alex Brown in San Francisco.
       All I had to do to visit the shoe boutique, for instance, was to
click on Introducing Blahnik on the neimanmarcus.com home page
(www.neimanmarcus.com) and then download (it took a few seconds) an update
to the Real Networks Real Player already installed on my computer. (The
update includes the RichFX Player). To navigate, all I had to do was click
on Right, Left or Pause. The site also has a zoom feature, which loads
speedily.
    Still, when the yellow butterfly paused at the boutique's doorway, so
did I. Don't go in, I told myself: It's a trick. This is not just some
harmless computer game where I can pump my enemies full of bullets and
splatter their kidneys against the wall. No, this  technology  may have a
harmful impact on my behavior. No one needs $500 shoes, especially not me,
a person who works at home in shorts. Where would I wear them, to the next
meeting of the nursery school board?
   The door opened, the butterfly flew inside and I saw a pair of pointy
black suede mules with a discreet two-inch heel. They looked as sleek and
fast as a cigarette boat. I suddenly remembered that I am the nursery
school board's recording secretary. A person entrusted with the
responsibility of taking the minutes every month should look put together,
no?
   I went in. I browsed. I found it so easy to sit back and let the action
unfold.  ``It's a quicker way to convey more information and at the same
time you ask the shopper to do less work,''  Ausnit said. Then he added, as
if this were a good thing, ``This technology will be explosive because it's
 fun.''
    Ausnit, who does not have to pay the credit card bills in my household,
probably also would be charmed by the fact that as  the suede mule, the
shoe stayed in perspective, getting bigger. He might even be thrilled to
know that after I clicked on it, the shoe floated off its perch to preen in
midair like some enchanted object in a Harry Potter novel, spinning so
close to my face that I was afraid the pointy toe would nick my nose and
draw blood. I was in the Seventh Circle of Shopping and these were the
Suede Mules from Hell. From Hell, I tell you.
       I phoned Gayle Tremblay, vice president of Neiman Marcus Online, to
ask her how in good conscience she could tempt shoppers so cruelly.
   She did not seem wracked by guilt. ``I can tell you, those shoes would
look fabulous on you,''  Tremblay said. ``You can wear them with anything.
With jeans.''
    I looked once more at the very, very, very beautiful shoes. I pictured
myself wearing them. Even in jeans, I would look very, very, very
beautiful. I would float in midair.
   Then I noticed the price, displayed unobtrusively on screen to the right
of the RichFX window: $445.
   That brought me back to reality.  I went upstairs to my closet and
unearthed a pair of black and witchy Manolo Blahnik pumps I bought at a
triple-reduced-price-end-of-season sale a few years back (they still cost
too much). Wearing them, I sat down in front of my husband's computer to
play Doom, which suddenly seemed a lot safer.
</TEXT>
</BODY>
