<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4182 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-MINIMALIST-LIVING-TEX     09-06 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMALIST-LIVING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS COUPLE MAKES AN ART OF LIVING SMALL
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GAILE ROBINSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURLESON, Texas _ It's a landmark house. Not the historically
recognized kind, but one the neighbors will use to give directions.
``We're two houses past the metal box.''
</P>
<P>
   The 2-story galvanized metal and stucco house is remarkable for
many reasons, not just for its role as a directional beacon.
</P>
<P>
   It's the size of a three-Suburban garage: large by garage
standards, teensy-weensy by house standards.
</P>
<P>
   It was designed by an architect, Aledo-based Richard Wintersole.
</P>
<P>
   It's in Burleson, Texas, a Fort Worth suburb.
</P>
<P>
   The home of Michael Young, 31, and Gayla LaBry 32, is not tiny
because the owners wanted minuscule. They wanted a well-designed,
high-functioning house, built of quality materials, that they could
pay for in cash.
</P>
<P>
   This ruled out most of what was on the market. ``I couldn't
imagine buying an existing house,'' says Young. ``They're ugly. Big
and ugly.'' He also says he couldn't imagine not hiring an
architect, a sophisticated decision, rarely on the first-time
home-buyer's agenda.
</P>
<P>
   After collaborating with Wintersole and hiring Aledo contractor
Mike Barnett, Young and LaBry have what many people aspire to _ a
unique, spare, streamlined house, free of clutter.
</P>
<P>
   The entire house, one large room actually, is a clutter-free
zone, an aspect of living in a small space that takes some
discipline. ``In our apartment we had clothes all over the place,''
Young says. In his new house, the clothes washer and dryer are next
to the bedroom closet, and clothes do not tend to migrate.
</P>
<P>
   Living in one room ``forces us to be neater,'' says LaBry. There
is a place for everything and if there isn't, it can't stay. ``When
we shop we look for things we need and have a place for,'' she
says. Already she has received some problematic housewarming
presents. Gifts for small-space users, says LaBry, should ``be
consumable.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to move-in day in May, LaBry and Young got rid of all
their knickknacks. After 11 years of marriage, LaBry admits they
had a number of former treasures that had lost all meaning. Even
though they came from apartment life, Young knew the pitfalls of
multiple bedrooms and walk-in closets. ``The bigger the house, the
more stuff you put in it. The more stuff, the messier it gets. We
threw away a lot of junk, and we don't miss it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no hidden walls of storage, a garage for stacking
boxes and stowing the lawn mower, or an outbuilding.
</P>
<P>
   There are cabinets in the kitchen, a closet in the bedroom, and
some linen storage in the bathroom. Period.
</P>
<P>
   They willingly chose this. The economy of space and of storage
were just two of the many things on Young and LaBry's list. They
wanted metal; they liked the low-maintenance aspect and the look.
They wanted open space, lots of windows and a porch. Before they
even met Wintersole, Young had noodled out some plans on his
laptop. He and LaBry had scoured magazines and books, tearing out
photos of houses and details they liked from ``Metropolitan Home''
and ``Fine Homebuilding'' magazines.
</P>
<P>
   Once the final plans were drafted, Young, who is a
manufacturer's engineer in the glass business, acted as his own
purchasing agent. He found the windows, appliances and lighting
systems. He bought every switch, every outlet. ``I got what I
wanted for a decent price. Light fixtures can run thousands of
dollars. All my light fixtures cost less than $300.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the space is small and storage at a premium, the living
area seems expansive. The space is manipulated by furniture
specifically chosen by Young and LaBry. The living room chairs are
transparent, so they do not consume any visual space. The long,
dark purple planes of the armless B&AMP;B Italia sofa seem to levitate
off the slender chrome legs.
</P>
<P>
   The counter top in the kitchen extends to form the window ledge,
making an uninterrupted horizontal line. The vertical-space wall of
floor-to-ceiling cabinets, double ovens and refrigerator is equally
smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bit of space is wasted. Nothing is out of place.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
