<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4183 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-PRESSING-LEAVES-TEX     09-06 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRESSING-LEAVES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE WHO LOVE AUTUMN'S BOUNTY WILL FALL FOR THIS BOOK
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By GAILE ROBINSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are people who are captivated by fallen leaves, and there
is everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Author Louise Kollenbaum is captivated. ``One fall I pressed so
many leaves that they spilled over from my studio into the living
room. Rather than apologize to visitors. I simply gave the look a
designer name, `Herbarium chic.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Kollenbaum has written a book for those who spend the month of
October hunkered over, searching the ground for yet another
wonderful example of nature's palette. (Hint: If you know one of
the leaf people, this book is great present material.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Fallen Leaves'' (Chronicle Books, $22.95) is about the art of
pressing leaves. Even better, the book is a piece of art. The
binding is a clever configuration with elastic bands that allow for
expansion as the book fills with leaves, glassine pages for
displaying leaves, and journal pages for record keeping and deep
thoughts. Poetry about trees is included on the journal pages for
inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves that illustrate the book are quite lovely, instilling
a desire to collect fall's beauty even if one has never done so
before. There is an artistry in selecting leaves, but the list of
materials needed for pressing is quite basic.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The basic ingredients for pressing include:
</P>
<P>
   a leaf
</P>
<P>
   blotter paper
</P>
<P>
   newspaper
</P>
<P>
   a press or heavy books
</P>
<P>
   six to eight weeks' drying time
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1731EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0176 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-DEBATES07-COX     09-06 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBATES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSH URGES GORE TO 'GET IT ON' WITH LIMITED DEBATES
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush challenged Al Gore on Wednesday to
``get it on'' with presidential debates, even as he insisted on a
plan that would significantly limit the number of voters viewing
the face-to-face encounters.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge coincided with a new Bush TV ad campaign
suggesting that Gore's refusal to accept the Texas governor's
debate terms illustrates the vice president's lack of credibility.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's challenge also coincided with a coast-to-coast flood
of newspaper editorials criticizing the Republican nominee for
rejecting a three-debate proposal by the bipartisan Commission on
Presidential Debates, which was organized in 1988 to end the
bickering that typically surrounds them.
</P>
<P>
   And it led to suggestions from political analysts that Bush's
display of bravado, while highlighting Gore's credibility problems,
also reinforces the view that the governor is not ready for
prime-time encounters with the Democratic nominee, whose debating
skills are highly regarded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has given people the feeling that he's afraid to meet
Gore,'' said Larry Sabato, an expert on the media and politics at
the University of Virginia. ``Bush doesn't want to be followed by a
guy in a chicken costume, which will happen soon if this isn't
resolved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get it on, Mr. Gore,'' Bush declared Wednesday morning
at the end of an NBC ``Today'' program interview in which the
governor continued to insist on one debate and two joint talk-show
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Rival TV networks have said they would not carry the talk shows,
meaning the sessions would reach only a fraction of the viewers
that the commission-sponsored debates ordinarily draw.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the joint interviews would be in Washington next
Tuesday, hosted by NBC's Tim Russert. Bush vowed Wednesday that he
would show up for the event, even though an NBC spokeswoman said it
would not air without Gore. ``We offered a debate, not an
appearance,'' said NBC's Barbara Levin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to play games to try to substitute a talk show
for the national bipartisan commission debates that everybody can
see,'' Gore said on ABC's ``Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would allow Bush to appear on NBC alone, Gore
replied, ``Oh, sure. Absolutely. ... It's seen by far fewer people
and, again, I'm happy to do it, but not as a substitute for the
main debates that the bipartisan commission has set up.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has proposed three 90-minute debates between Bush
and Gore next month. All three would be televised simultaneously by
the major TV networks in order to minimize the number of viewers
fleeing to other programming.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also has proposed one debate between the two vice
presidential nominees, Republican Dick Cheney and Democrat Joe
Lieberman.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has rejected that plan. In addition to the one-hour joint
interview with Russert, the governor has proposed another one-hour
joint appearance on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' program and one
commission-sponsored debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the three debates I'll do,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Russert's ``Meet The Press'' program averages 3.6 million
viewers on Sunday mornings, and ``Larry King Live'' which airs
daily during the week, normally draws 936,000.
</P>
<P>
   The commission-sponsored debates in 1996 between President
Clinton and former Senate Majority Leader Bob Dole averaged 41.2
million viewers. And the 1992 debates involving President George
Bush, Clinton and independent Ross Perot drew a record 90.3 million
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush's handlers seem resigned to their man taking a drubbing
at the hands of Gore and want the audience as small as possible,''
observed the Denver Post, one of the many newspapers whose
editorial pages weighed in Wednesday with harsh criticism of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   But the new Bush TV ad titled ``Credibility'' notes that Gore
had previously agreed to debate Bush ``any time, any place,
anywhere'' but now refuses to meet the governor on the NBC and CNN
programs. ``If we can't trust Al Gore on debates, why should we
trust him on anything?'' the ad says.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign, in response, questioned Bush's own
credibility by pointing to an August interview with CNN in which
the governor insisted he hoped ``more people watch'' the debates
than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than spending millions of dollars on negative ads,
George W. Bush should do what his father and Bob Dole did and agree
to the bipartisan proposal for debates,'' said Ron Klain, a senior
Gore campaign official. ``Governor Bush should end the excuses and
the name-calling and live up to his commitment to ensuring that
more people watch the debates than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell West, a political science professor at Brown University,
said the Bush and Gore camps both look bad in the squabble over the
debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters see this as politicians arguing over trivial details,''
West said. ``Neither side looks good. Bush appears as if he is
ducking sustained questioning, while Gore has broken his word to
debate anywhere, anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   www.debates.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1733EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
