<P>
   ``Rather than spending millions of dollars on negative ads,
George W. Bush should do what his father and Bob Dole did and agree
to the bipartisan proposal for debates,'' said Ron Klain, a senior
Gore campaign official. ``Governor Bush should end the excuses and
the name-calling and live up to his commitment to ensuring that
more people watch the debates than ever before.''
</P>
<P>
   Darrell West, a political science professor at Brown University,
said the Bush and Gore camps both look bad in the squabble over the
debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters see this as politicians arguing over trivial details,''
West said. ``Neither side looks good. Bush appears as if he is
ducking sustained questioning, while Gore has broken his word to
debate anywhere, anytime.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   www.debates.org
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
