<HEADER>
A4190 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROV     09-06 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV24-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., SEP. 24, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The bathroom sink in my old apartment has developed an
annoying sewer-like odor that seems to be coming up through the
drain opening.
 &HT;    The sink drains out OK, but I tried cleaning out the drain line
anyway, using a chemical cleaner. There was no apparent clog.
 &HT;    I then disconnected the drain line where it goes down through
the floor below the trap. I used a ``snake'' to probe the drain for
clogs, but found none.
 &HT;    What do you think could be causing the odor?
 &HT;    A: From your description of the trap and drain line it sounds as
though you have an ``S'' type trap under your sink. Although most
codes no longer permit installation of this type, some older houses
still do have them.
 &HT;    The purpose of any plumbing trap is to keep the U-shaped section
full of water, thus forming a seal against any sewer gases coming
up through the drain opening.
 &HT;    However, with an ``S'' type trap this seal can be lost when a
heavy flow of waste water goes down the drain and actually siphons
water out of the trap. This is very unlikely with a ``P'' trap
which goes horizontally through the wall behind the sink.
 &HT;    Your problem can be solved by simply adding more water to the
trap. Open a faucet and allow water to run into the drain opening
for about 10 seconds.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Even when I don't flush my toilet, the water seems to come on
and the toilet seems to run by itself. It does this periodically
several times, then stops for awhile, sometimes not happening again
for several days.
 &HT;    Can a neighborhood handyman fix this, or is it something only an
experienced plumber can repair safely?
 &HT;    A: I believe your problem is caused by a worn flapper valve that
is no longer forming a tight seal against its seat or opening in
the bottom of the flush tank.
 &HT;    The poor seal allows water to leak through into the toilet, even
when it is not flushed. As the water level inside the tank drops,
the ballcock (the inlet valve) opens and more water comes into the
tank to fill it. This cycle is repeated until finally the flapper
does form a tight seal.
 &HT;    Replacing the rubber flapper valve with a new one should solve
your problem, and is a very simple task you can do yourself.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The self-adhesive, non-skid plastic appliques that I applied
to the bottom of my bathtub some years ago have worn off, but the
outline of each applique is still noticeable.
 &HT;    I have tried various cleaners, but the shapes remain. Can you
suggest anything?
 &HT;    A: The residue that you see is probably slight remnants of the
adhesive that are still left on the tub's finish.
 &HT;    This can be cleaned off by using one of the special adhesive
removers on the market, such as the one made by 3M.
 &HT;    A solvent such as lacquer thinner or nail polish remover also
works well in most cases.
 &HT;    If all of these fail, and if the design has actually soaked into
the finish, then the only other possibility I can think of would be
to try a bleach _ assuming the tub is white. I cannot say how
bleach would affect a colored tub.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: Some years ago a telescoping jack post was installed under
one of the beams in my basement to provide support for a stone
fireplace on the main floor above it.
 &HT;    In recent years I notice that there is considerable cracking in
the concrete floor and the crack extends about 12 feet across the
floor.
 &HT;    What is the simplest and least expensive remedy for this?
 &HT;    A: The crack is probably due to the fact that a proper footing
or foundation was never put down under it to properly support the
post, so now all the weight is on the concrete floor slab, causing
it to crack.
 &HT;    The only cure now is to replace this post with a new one that
sits on a proper footing. This usually means digging through the
floor and going down about 12 inches. Then pour a 12-cubic-inch
block of concrete and set the new post on top of this.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``PLUMBING TRAPS'' goes with this
column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Outmoded ``S'' trap (top) can allow water to be
siphoned out of trap, thus allowing sewer gases to enter. Approved
type ``P'' trap (below) prevents this.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
