A4193 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX     09-06 0557
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Bush has muddled debate issue
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   George W. Bush is back in full-smirk mode now that he's muddled
the issue over presidential campaign debates. He appears to think
he has muddled it successfully, and perhaps he has.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't Al Gore say he would debate Bush any time anywhere and
isn't he now, just as Bush charges, refusing to do just that?
Indeed. But Gore's rhetorical sally assumed Bush would first buy
into the debates that the presidential debate commission would set
up. After all, every candidate since 1988 had, including daddy
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is trying to suggest, without quite saying so and thus
laying himself own to challenge on the point, that there's some sly
partisan dirty work afoot in the commission's proposal for three
stand-up debates to be telecast on all networks simultaneously.
</P>
<P>
   The commission, however, is rigorously bipartisan and has as its
sole client the American electorate. If Bush thinks holding one of
the debates near _ near, not in _ the Kennedy Library is, in
effect, a thumb on the scale, then surely an alternative site could
be picked. This is a triviality, easily fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he would go for one commission debate, but for the
rest wants to sit down for schmooze-fests with Gore on NBC's ``Meet
the Press'' with Tim Russert and on CNN's ``Larry King Live.''
Russert at least knows politics but King, a celebrity debriefer, is
to politics what, oh, rocks are to an omelette.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor figures the relative informality of those
shows -- and ``shows'' is the right word -- would favor his genial,
good old boy manner while showing that Gore sits up straight. They
would also limit any damage Bush might do to himself. The
audiences, by most estimates, would be a third or a fourth the size
of audiences for full-out debates.
</P>
<P>
   The confusion Bush has sown has had the, to him, happy side
effect of suckering NBC and CNN into de facto cahoots with his
proposal. Each would love to have the coup he has offered it and
NBC has fallen to all but promoting the idea outright. Its
newscasts were pushing NBC's offer to share ``Meet the Press'' with
other networks on the morning when newspapers were reporting, and
NBC was not, that CBS and ABC already had announced they would
reject programs originating on other networks.
</P>
<P>
   If Bush has managed to confuse this matter enough to neutralize
the advantage Gore had enjoyed in it previously, well, that's
politics. But if the winner isn't clear, the loser is. That's the
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The evolved tradition of formal presidential debates offered
voters a chance to assess the candidates outside the narrow lists
of their thrust-and-parry TV ads and free of their megabuck self
aggrandizements. The custom, too, had closed off the candidates
from the past practice of bickering their way out of debates
altogether -- or had seem to until this Bush ploy.
</P>
<P>
   All needn't be lost. If Bush accepts the commission debates, he
would be free to taunt Gore into other formats and venues, turning
a disservice to voters into a service.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
