<P>
   U.N.-CLINTON (United Nations) - President Clinton on Wednesday
told the largest gathering of world leaders in history that the
United Nations must reconfigure itself to deal with a world in
which there are ``fewer wars between nations, but more wars within
them.'' With the energy of a man who sees his moment on the world
stage quickly slipping away, he immediately used the Millennium
Summit meeting here to take a last stab at many of the issues that
have defied resolution during his presidency. He tried to fend off
a proposal from Russian president Vladimir Putin that would lead to
a demilitarization of outer space - an effort by Putin to put an
end to American talk of a national missile defense - and met with
the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, and Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak in one last effort to rescue the Middle East peace
process. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-MILLENNIUM-SUMMIT (United Nations) - The question hangs out
there. Why would 152 leaders leave their not-always-stable
governments unattended to come to New York and make five-minute
speeches, mostly to each other and the television cameras from back
home? Secretary General Kofi Annan had an answer today as he lifted
his glass to the biggest power lunch in history. ``You,'' he said,
looking out over the world's political elite, ``have the ability to
transform the lives of 6 billion people.'' By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS (United Nations) - An armed mob ran amok
through a U.N. refugee office in West Timor on Wednesday, beating
to death three unarmed U.N. workers, including an American, and
touching off repercussions of outrage halfway around the world at
the Millenium Summit meeting of world leaders here. By Christoher
S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-MAFIA-ARRESTS (New York) - The Manhattan district attorney
Wednesday charged 38 union officials, contractors and reputed
mobsters with bribery, bid-rigging or other racketeering schemes
that siphoned millions of dollars from public and private building
projects throughout the city over the last two years. By William K.
Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BELGIUM-ROYALS (New York) - The royals are coming. No, no,
not the poor old British Crown Prince, still overshadowed by the
tragic legacy of Diana, Princess of Wales. Nor any of his
relatives, like that fellow who flies the helicopter and his former
lady who does the weight-loss thing. No, New York is getting the
other ones, the fabulously cool new royals: handsome Crown Prince
Philippe of Belgium and his ravishing Princess Mathilde, the
fairy-tale couple that has monopolized magazine covers and glossy
photo spreads throughout Europe. Their mission is nothing less than
to take New York City by storm, winning hearts, minds, media and,
more importantly, market share. By Glenn Collins.
</P>
<P>
   DNA-CONVICTION (Richmond, Va.) - Six years after DNA testing
raised strong doubts about his guilt in a rape and homicide
conviction, Earl Washington Jr., a model prisoner with the IQ of a
10-year-old, awaited the results of a more definitive test today as
his lawyers filed a petition for a full executive pardon after 17
years in prison. His lawyers, pioneers in the increasingly
successful DNA challenges of criminal convictions, describe
Washington as their long suffering poster child, an amiable,
passive farm hand with an IQ of 69 whose habit is to cooperatively
agree with people. They maintain his case is a summary of the main
problems prompting the rising national concern about capital
convictions: race, mental incapacity, convictions based solely on
confession, appeal limitations, and the inevitable pressures of
politics. By Francis X. Clines.
</P>
