<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4195 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-CIR-AUSSIE-I-CAFES-NY     09-06 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-AUSSIE-I-CAFES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    AUSTRALIAN E-CAFES OFFER COMMUNICATION AND MORE QL
</HEADLINE>
 QL  (EDS: in reference to Micheal O'Grady, spelling is CQ) QL 
By JEAN E. HERSKOWITZ QC 
 &HT;    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service QC 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Three years ago, while touring Britain,  Philip Dean had to use Internet
connections  at local universities to e-mail home.
</P>
<P>
   ``In those days there really weren't any Internet cafes there,'' said
Dean, a 29-year-old British native transplanted to Australia. His  desire
to communicate easily and cheaply with faraway friends resulted in his
opening Global Gossip  - ``a store with phone booths and a couple of
terminals'' -  along with  Peter Ovenden, 31, after  Dean returned from
Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The store grew into a chain of 12 Internet  and telephone
``lounges,'' spread across nine Australian cities.  Visitors to any of the
communication centers can fax, phone, scan, rent a mailbox, photocopy and
send e-mail. Global Gossip's young owners are seeking U.S.-based partners
for  global expansion.
</P>
<P>
   And Global Gossip isn't alone. As visitors to Australia for the
Olympics will find, they may be down under, but they won't have to be out
of touch. In the past three years, Sydney -  the capital of the Australian
state of New South Wales and its most populated city, with 3.7 million
residents -  has seen an explosion of Internet cafes. As England, Israel
and other countries have, Australia has proved fertile ground for the
spread of the cafes, which are a big attraction to backpacking tourists.
</P>
<P>
   For them, e-mail is the preferred mode of communication.  It's less
expensive than calling home (although some of the cafes offer international
calling amenities) and easier than postcards.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the  35,000 customers who pop into a Global Gossip
each week are between the ages of  18 and 29, according to the site.
Sixty percent  are visitors from abroad.  Local people gravitate toward the
faxing, photocopying and scanning services, said  Dean, who compared Global
Gossip to a ``more fun'' Kinko's in that regard.     Australians with PCs
at home also stop by,  for the social experience.     ``There's atmosphere
and energy,''  Dean said.  ``People enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney  picked up e-cafe fever around 1997, when a few cafe
owners  decided to perk up business by installing a smattering of
computers.  When it soon became clear that the mouse pads were getting more
hits than the mocha, cybercafes began to be cloned in every semi-inhabited
corner of the Southern Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   A stroll around any urban neighborhood in Sydney bears out
Australia's affinity for the net.  The cafes line the streets, crammed with
young people, their eyes glued to glowing screens, fingers tapping
frantically. Many cafes stay open past midnight. And a number are located
on  the notorious Darlinghurst Road in the Kings Cross section of Sydney -
the central strip of the city's red-light district (fairly safe as
red-light districts go) and a backpacker's main stomping ground for
low-cost room and board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Australia seems kind of ahead in this area,''  said 37-year-old
Dr. Sally Harrison, from England, who is  working in a local hospital for a
year.   Her explanation for the phenomenon: Australians are ``obsessed with
the fact that they're cut off from the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Some cafes subscribe to the all-Internet, no-hoopla approach.
Sydney's Eagles Internet cafe is a ``stock, standard Internet cafe that
offers peace and quiet,'' according to its manager, Micheal O'Grady.  ``We
don't crowd our room out with lots of people, and only have a maximum of 12
people at once.  Plenty of space and nothing to interrupt them.  It keeps
them coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Competition, however, has made many cafe operators less spartan
about services offered, resulting in creative price arrangements for jaded
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Global Gossip offers patrons a stamp for each half hour they
spend online; those who collect five stamps  receive a free half-hour.
Other cybercafes lure visitors in to check their e-mail, offering the first
two minutes free.
</P>
<P>
   The more experimental cafe owners have traveled beyond the
Internet in their quest for distinction.
</P>
<P>
   The 300-seat Fountain Cafe, on the edge of Kings Cross, offers
multitaskers access to one of 40 terminals in the downstairs cybercafe,
food and beer in the restaurant (the menu includes the ``Aussie burger with
chips and soft drink and 1 hour on the Net'' for about $6 and  salon
services next door at the cafe's high-tech beauty salon.
</P>
<P>
   Rosalind Turner, 43, an Australian freelance journalist,  isn't
online at home, so she uses the Fountain's computers for the Olympic
stories she is working on.  The cafe has ``lots of  Swedish accents, and
lots of Irish and pommy accents,'' she noted. (``Pommy'' is Australians'
slang for the many Britons among them.) ``They know each other from the
hostels.''  She likes the casualness of the place.  ``The owner lets people
drink coffee and eat hamburgers downstairs, so he's not really worried
about greasy fingers on the keyboards.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner appreciates the array of conveniences.  ``I have a massage
every couple of weeks, I get a peel whenever I feel like it.''  After her
massage she goes next door to the cafe, logs on and checks her e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics are also getting in on the action.  The Athlete's
Village will have a cybercafe - the Surf Shack - where  the athletes can
respond to fans' e-mail as part of IBM's FanMail program. ``FanMail  is a
Web site we debuted in 1996 at the Atlanta Games,'' said Joyce Lagas, a
communications employee with  IBM's Olympic project. ``It lets people from
around the world send good luck and congratulations to the athletes.''  The
site is at www.ibm.com/fanmail.
</P>
<P>
   IBM is also opening a Surf Shack for public consumption, which
will be floating on a barge in Sydney's Darling Harbor.  People can stop by
to send e-mail to their favorite athletes, view the Olympics Web site
(www.olympics.com) and check out IBM technology that was created for the
Games.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Olympic Village Surf Shack's official opening was last
Saturday, Lagas observed that team trainers, coaches and officials had
already been dropping in for weeks to e-mail their families back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1996, the Internet was in its infancy, but still we
received over 100,000 e-mails for the athletes at the Atlanta Games,''
Lagas said.    ``Two years later, at the Nagano Games -  and winter Games
tend to be smaller, with fewer athletes -  we had 300,000 messages sent
from 126 countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Will the ultradisciplined athletes succumb to the lure of the
Internet cafe?  IBM thinks so.  True, the 3,800-square-foot Athlete's
Village Surf Shack with more than 60 computers will serve no food.  But
``they can play computer games here,''  Lagas said, ``and we also have a
giant video wall set up,'' with a feed from the events once the Games start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
