<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4204 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-WRITERS-BLOCKED-2000(     09-06 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITERS-BLOCKED-2000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY TV CRAZE KEEPS WRITERS IDLE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Terese Kelly's daily ritual: Out of bed by 7,
check industry trade papers by 8, call agent by 9.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything?'' is all she asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing'' is all she hears.
</P>
<P>
   It's another typical day for a Hollywood TV writer in the Age of
Real TV.
</P>
<P>
   One would expect a proven writer, with two situation comedies, a
drama and a Nickelodeon children's program under her belt, to be
something of a catch _ particularly in a medium whose creative
mediocrity has long been blamed on too much demand for the
available talent pool.
</P>
<P>
   But Kelly, who is 27 with an 18-month-old daughter and $1,567.35
in rent due on a tiny two-bedroom apartment, is facing unemployment
in her chosen profession for what could be a full year.
</P>
<P>
   In a company town as political and fickle as Los Angeles, you
can never assume automatic hiring, no matter what your resume. But
Kelly stands as the unseen, unheard _ and unexpected _ casualty of
the current fascination with so-called reality shows that are
largely unscripted.
</P>
<P>
   It's simple arithmetic, really. Reality shows such as
``Survivor'' and ``Big Brother'' on CBS and game shows such as
``Who Wants To Be a Millionaire'' on ABC are occupying prime
programming real estate previously rented to fictional
entertainment programs. Add the continued popularity of
newsmagazines such as ``Dateline NBC'' and ``20/20,'' and the job
opportunities for TV writers shrink even more.
</P>
<P>
   What a change from just five years ago, when good writers were
considered an endangered species, when there was an insane bidding
war for mediocre talent that allowed writer/producers with modest
hits to sign exorbitant, record-breaking deals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, veteran writers with solid credentials are enduring their
own version of ``Survivor,'' with often-dire consequences.
</P>
<P>
   For networks and studios that own the shows, it's simply a
matter of economics. A typical episode of ``Millionaire'' costs an
estimated $750,000 (unless a contestant wins $1 million), whereas
dramas like ``The Practice'' on ABC and ``Providence'' on NBC cost
around $1.2 million per episode. Firmly established sitcoms such as
``Frasier'' and ``Friends'' are nestled in even pricier
neighborhoods _ around $3 million per episode.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the downside to the game shows and reality
programming is that, unlike popular dramas and sitcoms, they are
expected to fare poorly in repeats and therefore could never be
sold in syndication.
</P>
<P>
   Still, CBS is betting that the wildly addictive ``Survivor''
will buck that trend, based on its ratings strength and the fact
that a number of viewers who watched the two-hour finale were
first-timers lured in by the media hype who will now backtrack to
see what they missed. The network will rebroadcast ``Survivor''
episodes nightly beginning Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Why viewers also may be worse off with this new look in TV
programming is also simple arithmetic. For the fall TV season, 44
sitcoms and 43 dramas will air, down from 60 sitcoms and 40 dramas
of a year ago and 64 sitcoms and 36 dramas from the year before
that. In terms of writing slots this season, that's a drop-off of
200 jobs, because one show employs up to a dozen or more writers
during the season.
</P>
<P>
   ABC's scheduling of a fourth hour of ``Millionaire'' this season
means just seven of the 23 hours of prime-time programming on that
network will be occupied by scripted entertainment shows. The rest
will be divided up among game shows, ``Monday Night Football,''
newsmagazines, movies and The Wonderful World of Disney franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it a time of concern for the creative community _ yeah, you
could say that,'' says J.J. Abrams, creator of the coming-of-age
drama ``Felicity.'' ``I can't say that I've had my colleagues
jumping out of windows or even changing careers just yet. But as a
producer of a show that is constantly on the bubble, there's less
of an opportunity to be creative for fear that if it fails, you'll
lose audience and be replaced by a reality program about nuns or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of reality shows is putting a lot of actors,
writers, producers and crews out of business in the short term,
``but it would be a long-term disaster if we find ourselves dealing
with only three comedies, four dramas and the rest reality shows,''
says veteran producer Aaron Spelling, whose latest drama serial is
``Titans'' on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would never do a reality show,'' he says. ``I mean, the day
will come when I'll probably be asked to do a reality show in a
house of prostitution _ that's how far out and silly this whole
thing has become.''
</P>
<P>
   But as silly as the reality-programming craze has become, it's
deadly serious to writers who find themselves suddenly on the
outside looking in.
</P>
<P>
   Terese Kelly and her colleagues saw the reality trend coming but
never thought it would affect established writers. For several
weeks beginning in mid-May and creeping into June, writers who make
their living working for shows such as ``Nash Bridges'' and ``JAG''
cast about for fall assignments.
</P>
<P>
   During that month or so when shows are making final decisions
about their writing staffs, scribes who've been asked back to
returning shows have the luxury of looking around for other
opportunities without desperation in their eyes. But Kelly, whose
series, ``Oh Grow Up,'' was canceled last season, didn't have a
fall-back position. MORE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ fall-back position.
</P>
<P>
   And when the phone didn't ring by mid-July, she began to panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been doing this for six years now, and never has there
been such little activity or movement,'' she says. ``My friends who
have writing jobs aren't going anywhere because they're scared to,
and those without jobs are going to the dot-coms or waiting it out
by waiting on tables. Me? I'm just depressed. It doesn't look like
it's letting up anytime soon.''
</P>
<P>
   She's right. With ``Millionaire'' still averaging 28 million
viewers per episode, and 51 million watching the final
``Survivor,'' CBS is already planning ``Survivor 2,'' and other
reality shows are in the pipeline there and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reality shows coming up on the major networks are
``The Mole,'' in which contestants complete a series of tasks while
being undermined by an infiltrator; ``The Runner,'' which follows
``fugitives'' as they attempt to avoid detection by viewers; and
``Chains of Love,'' which consists of a person chained to five
members of the opposite sex over a five-day period, with one
individual banished each day until only one remains. The WB is
preparing a reality series called ``Popstars'' and another that
will follow a group of young people planning an Internet
publication. Even VH1 is getting in on the act, with production
under way on ``Bands on the Run.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that jobs in the short term are being
diminished,'' says Peter Roth, president of Warner Bros., which
produces shows like ``ER'' and ``The West Wing.'' ``But I just
can't see the cream of the crop ever going away.''
</P>
<P>
   Roth thinks the current situation will end up being good for the
writers who survive _ and, more important, for viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it should force us to work harder, to do better,
to make something fresh and interesting for people to watch. My
theory all along has been that reality programming is succeeding
because the audience is simply sick and tired of being asked to
choose between one piece of junk that's only slightly different
from another piece of junk.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, but writers say networks are so fixated on reality
programming that they simply no longer have an appetite for
anything within the more traditional genres. Judd Apatow, a writer
and executive producer of NBC's canceled ``Freaks and Geeks,'' said
his series didn't stand a chance in this atmosphere and that a new
show of his, ``Happy Together,'' was flat-out rejected by NBC
without even a pilot episode being ordered.
</P>
<P>
   Series projects produced by established writer/producers like
Yvette Lee Bowser and Ralph Farguhar (''Moesha, The Parkers'') were
also shut out of the fall campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were real estate, we'd say it's a seller's market,''
says Cecil Gerald, an unemployed comedy writer who has worked on
``Amen, Martin'' and ``The Wayans Bros.'' and who, like many of his
writing buddies, is willing to drop his salary to land a job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, I'm single, I've got a roommate. But many of my friends
are selling their souls to work because they have mortgage payments
and car payments and children,'' says Gerald, who says he has
enough savings to wait out a season. ``It's depressing and kind of
scary to know that (shows) are basically sitting back selecting.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there's an upside to this seller's market, it's that
shows are being more selective.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that our staff has never been more capable,''
says Steven Bochco, who has overhauled his medical drama, ``City of
Angels,'' in front of and behind the camera. The series is getting
a last-chance shot on CBS this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Bochco says fewer job openings have forced talented, proven
writers who are capable of creating their own shows to remain on
writing staffs, thereby making them much stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are those who think this is much ado about
nothing. Dick Wolf, creator of ``Law &AMP; Order,'' told TV critics
assembled for the winter press tour in January that ``Everything's
cyclical. Sixteen years ago, comedy was dead, and along came (Bill)
Cosby. Game shows were dead, and now they're No. 1. But the reality
is that episodic series television has been a mainstay for 50 years
and will remain so.''
</P>
<P>
   While waiting for the pendulum to swing back their way, many
writers are turning to cable. HBO, TNT, Showtime, Lifetime and
other cable networks are offering more original dramas and sitcoms.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, who has worked strictly for network shows, has instructed
her agent to look at anything. ``The Food Network. Disney. I don't
care at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Some industry watchers see the possibility of writers moving
from network shows to generally lesser-paid cable shows as a blow
that networks can absorb now but that will hurt later. ``When this
trend is over, a large number of the good writers will have already
made the leap to cable and could conceivably be tied up there,''
says Jorge Reyes, a former staffer on ``New York Undercover,'' who
is now a writer for Showtime's ``Resurrection Blvd.''
</P>
<P>
   ``All writers need is a taste of the freedom cable provides, and
they may not come back. If you think network stuff is bad now, wait
until they have to rely on second- and third-tier writers. When
considering the criticism of how bad a lot of the shows are
already, man, I shudder at the thought.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1748EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
