<P>
   CLINTON-UN _ NEW YORK _ President Clinton today delivers his
last big speech before a major gathering of his peers here at the
Millennium Summit. Developing. (Deans, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 5 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire in (i)
International and (w) Washington categories.
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH _ Nearly a week after being battered by tidal waves,
35,000 displaced residents of an island in Bangladesh are still
waiting for aid to pour in. Zubair Hussain, a software engineer in
Atlanta who is helping with the relief efforts there, believes no
help is forthcoming; Bangladesh's annual call for humanitarian aid
has made donor countries indifferent to its plight. (Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   OBASANJO _ Nigerian President Obasanjo plans a dialogue with
Nigerians abroad in Atlanta this weekend. (Melvin, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES _ WASHINGTON _ The latest in the Gore-Bush debate on
debates. What's behind the postures, and how they're playing with
the pundits and the voters. Also, the rationale for the commission
debates and a look at how much debates shape the race. (Shepard,
Cox News Service). 28.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving on the New York Times wire in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   BAXTER-BUSH _ Although some of his other recent miscues are
getting most of the attention, George Bush has allowed the terms of
the presidential debate to be defined in ways that are playing to
the traditional strength of his opponent's party. (Baxter, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WEATHER-LATIN _ From offices in Atlanta, the weather is
broadcast all over Latin America, using on-air personalities hired
from those countries. We take a look at the Weather Channel/Latin
America, at the challenges it has faced in getting people in Latin
America used to relying on forecasts, and the community of
Hispanics and Brazilians who are pioneering this effort. (Melvin,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution) W/PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   LESBIAN-MARRIAGE _ Two lesbians from Houston who have tried
unsuccessfully to marry in their hometown will get a marriage
license in San Antonio today despite a Texas law prohibiting
same-sex marriages. How did they get the county clerk to agree? One
of the women used to be a man. And according to a recent lower
court ruling, marriages between folks who were born of opposite
sexes are legal. The couple say they are using their marriage, in
part, to show they think the earlier court ruling _ which
invalidated a marriage of a woman who was surgically changed from a
man _ was absurd. We look at the social ramifications of this
unusual Texas marriage. (Kurtz, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ In a sign of trouble ahead in
end-of-session negotiations between congressional leaders and
President Clinton, House Republicans led by Conference Chairman
J.C. Watts, R-Okla., declined to support an end-of-session
compromise offered by Speaker Dennis Hastert to pair a minimum wage
increase sought by Clinton with tax cuts sought by Republicans.
(Mollison, Cox News Service). 14.
</P>
<P>
   WWII-MEMORIAL _ WASHINGTON _ Opponents of the proposed World War
II Memorial gained an influential ally Wednesday when the Advisory
Council on Historic Preservation, an independent federal agency
that advises the president and Congress, called the memorial's
design inappropriate for its proposed place on the national Mall.
(Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Atlanta, National, U.S. Government
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
