   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   LODIGAN _ Lodgian Chief Executive Robert Coles tells a financial
publication that he is ``cautiously optimistic'' that a sale of the
company will be completed in a couple of months. But William Yung,
the company's largest shareholders, said it's just a ruse to run
the stock price up. What Cole really needs to do, says Yung, is to
resign. (Poole, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   IRS - The Internal Revenue Service as part of its efforts to
streamline the agency and make it more consumer friendly is
breaking its operations into four operating divisions. The
650-person Wage and Investment division, which handles individual
tax returns for single and married filers, will be headquartered in
Atlanta. (Peralte, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   IXL _ IXL and its competitors are all experiencing a stock price
slide as their market dries up. The venture capital and IPO stream
for their potential dot-com clients has been cut off, so those
customers are dormant. The big clients, that make up 80 percent of
IXL's business, are taking a wait and see attitude. IXL says it
will lay off people to cut costs and ride out the storm, but
analysts say that will come back to bite them in the bottom
because, ``iXL's most valuable assets walk out the door at 5 p.m.
every day.'' (Brister, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   AIRFARES _An American Express business travel cost survey
predicts continued increases in airfares, hotel rates and car
rental rates next year, although all in the single digits. High
demand for service, coupled with fuel price inflation, will drive
rate increases. The survey comes as oil prices near decade highs,
which could affect airfares. (Fonti, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   SHAW _ Shaw Industries, Inc. said that Warren Buffet's Berkshire
Hathaway, Inc. has offered to purchase between 80.1% and 86% of the
outstandimg shares of the company. Shaw Industries would continue
to be operated under its current management with the corporate
headquarters remaining in Dalton, Georgia. (Bond, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
