<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4220 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-SCHOOLS-GAYS-HNS &LR;      09-06 0489
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-GAYS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SCHOOL YEAR BRINGS INCREASE IN GAY RIGHTS GROUPS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CAROL NESS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an effort to combat homophobia in classrooms
and hallways, students in Northern California schools are
organizing alliances of homosexual and straight teens.
</P>
<P>
   There are about 125 schools with such clubs at the outset of
this year, up from 40 two years ago, said Carolyn Laub, founder of
the Gay-Straight Alliance Network of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, there are an estimated 700 such organizations.
</P>
<P>
   While schools in San Francisco have had services for gay
students for a decade, the presence of gay-straight alliances has
spawned opposition and controversy in conservative areas. In Orange
County, outside Los Angeles, students sued for the right of an
alliance to meet on a public school campus. After initial
opposition, the Orange County Unified School District accepted the
organization as a school group.
</P>
<P>
   School districts have been successfully sued for failing to
protect students perceived to be gay, and a new state law outlaws
discrimination based on sexual orientation or gender identity in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the GSA Network's first-ever summer training
camp drew two dozen students from Northern California and the
Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Laub, at 26, was the resident adult, but she made sure the
students ran their own show.
</P>
<P>
   Among them was George Loomis, former honor roll student and
class president at Golden West High in Visalia, who embodies the
need for gay-straight alliances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was forced out of school because of my sexuality,'' said
Loomis, 18, who lives in Fresno and is organizing a GSA network in
the Central Valley.
</P>
<P>
   He has filed a claim against the Visalia Unified School
District, and said his senior year was a living hell. He said he
was intimidated and that the teachers and administrators were
little help.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually he had to take a graduate equivalency test instead of
graduating with his class.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to try to prevent this from happening to other kids,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laub said it often takes hard facts to get administrators to
acknowledge what gay students live with daily. Her own surveys in
four East Bay high schools revealed that half to three-quarters of
the students hear derogatory comments about homosexuals and
lesbians daily.
</P>
<P>
   At Bishop O'Dowd School, which is one of only five Oakland
schools with a gay-straight alliance, 60 percent of the boys and 30
percent of girls said they hear slurs often at school, and 73
percent of the students said they seldom or never hear teachers
intervene when such remarks are made.
</P>
<P>
   ``A GSA can help decrease it, but we need teacher trainings and
we need students to get educated,'' Laub said. ``We can make it not
PC to say, but we still have to make deeper changes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1755EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
