<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4224 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-WWII-MEMORIAL07-COX     09-06 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WWII-MEMORIAL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ADVISORY PANEL SAYS WWII MEMORIAL WRONG FOR NATIONAL MALL
 &HT;    450&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Opponents of the proposed World War II Memorial
gained an ally Wednesday as the Advisory Council on Historic
Preservation deemed the design inappropriate for its planned place
between the Lincoln Memorial and Washington Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial, ``as now proposed, has serious and unresolved
adverse effects on the preeminent historic character of the
National Mall,'' the council wrote in a letter to Interior
Secretary Bruce Babbitt.
</P>
<P>
   The council, an independent federal agency that advises the
president and Congress, listed specific objections:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``The Memorial's overall scale and complexity create a tension
with the transcendent symbolic significance and fundamental
simplicity of the National Mall.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The ``visual screen'' of its 56 pillars ``violate the open
feeling of the Mall.''
</P>
<P>
   _ The memorial's lighting would alter the dusk and night views
of the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The Council has only an advisory role, however, and no power to
halt the project, which has the blessing of President Clinton and
Congress as well as several other review boards. Ground-breaking is
scheduled for Veterans Day in November, with dedication planned for
Memorial Day in 2003.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, the project must win the approval of the U.S.
Commission on Fine Arts, the National Capital Planning Commission
and the Interior secretary.
</P>
<P>
   The Commission on Fine Arts unanimously approved the memorial in
July. The National Capital Planning Commission, which has already
given its preliminary approval, has scheduled a final vote on Sept.
21. Then Babbitt will formally act.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going before the National Capital Planning Commission
with confidence that we have the backing of America for this
project,'' said Mike Conley, a spokesman for the World War II
Memorial. ``This really has been a grassroots campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents countered that the preservation council has validated
their claims that the memorial would mar the majestic open space
between two of the nation's most historic and hallowed memorials.
</P>
<P>
   The council is ``the first entity to break the lockstep of
approval'' for this ``gargantuan obstruction,'' said Rep. Eleanor
Holmes Norton, the non-voting congressional delegate for the
District of Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   She demanded that Babbitt ``act on his commitment'' that the
World War II Memorial result in ``no unacceptable impact to the
historic properties'' nearby.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball is in Secretary Babbitt's court,'' said Norton. ``I
expect him to do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Conley said he expects Babbitt to consider the recommendation
and to formally respond. However, he noted that the disapproval
represents ``a split decision'' in that the D.C. Historic
Preservation Review Board endorsed the site and design of the
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say World War II was the defining event of the 20th
century, and that a prominent spot on the National Mall is
appropriate for honoring what Tom Brokaw has termed ``the greatest
generation'' of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Led by former Sen. Bob Dole, R-Kan., and Tom Hanks, the star of
``Saving Private Ryan,'' organizers are raising $100 million from
private contributors to build the memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Fredrich St. Florian, the memorial features two
semi-circles of 56 stone pillars with bronze wreaths, representing
the number of U.S. states and territories during the war. The
pillars surround a 7.4-acre sunken plaza and fountains in what is
now the Rainbow Pool.
</P>
<P>
   St. Florian says his original concept has been altered so that
the vista between Lincoln Memorial and Washington Monument was not
obstructed.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that World War II ended 55 years ago and its veterans are
dying at a rate of 1,000 a day, supporters are pressing to get the
project begun and completed. There are already fewer than 6 million
survivors of the 16 million American men and women who served in
uniform during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents say they believe a World War II Memorial is warranted,
but not the proposed memorial at the proposed site.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial is not a ``done deal,'' said Judy Feldman, co-chair
of the National Coalition to Save Our Mall. ``Now is the time to
stop the World War II Memorial process and begin anew.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton said she believes President Clinton was ``bamboozled''
into supporting the project. She said Clinton wrongly ``assumed he
had all the facts'' when he expressed his approval.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web, www.wwiimemorial.com, www.savethemall.org
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
