A4229 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-INTERNET-FBI-HNS &LR;      09-06 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-FBI-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     SENATOR WARNS THAT FBI'S CARNIVORE COULD SLOW INTERNET GROWTH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the powerful
committee that oversees the FBI, warned Wednesday that the agency's
new computer program to police the Internet threatens to slow the
growth of e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail-sniffing system, known as Carnivore, allows agents to
sift messages to and from a targeted suspect out of the full stream
of data flowing on an Internet service provider (ISP) such as
America Online.
</P>
<P>
   ``Individuals who use the Internet for personal communications,
purchases, and hobbies are justifiably reluctant to allow an
Orwellian Big Brother to monitor which sites they visit or what
messages they send through cyberspace,'' said Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee, spoke at a
hearing by the panel on the Carnivore program, which has been
operating since early 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The senator added that concerns about privacy remain ``one of
main impediments'' to consumers using the Internet commercially.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., the committee's ranking minority
member, questioned the value of FBI assurances that agents sifting
through all e-mail traffic are looking only at messages to and from
criminal suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Such assurances are ``cold comfort to all other Internet users
who are not the subject of any court-ordered surveillance but
nonetheless are having their Internet messages automatically
screened by the Carnivore system,'' Leahy said.
</P>
<P>
   Once installed, Carnivore can monitor all e-mail on an ISP, from
people's lists of mail sent and received to the actual content of
the communications.
</P>
<P>
   The system differs from traditional wiretaps. In those cases,
the FBI first must get a court order to monitor the conversations
on a specific telephone. Then agents contact the phone company,
which installs the tap for that phone. When the investigation ends,
the phone company disconnects the wiretap.
</P>
<P>
   At no point in the investigation are law enforcement officials
able to monitor any conversations other than those on the one
phone.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Carnivore system, the FBI also gets a court order to
use the agency's software to tap into the lines of an ISP. Unlike a
traditional wiretap that gives the FBI access to only one phone,
Carnivore has access to every message being sent along the ISP's
system. In addition, the ISP has no control over or knowledge of
what the FBI was monitoring.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Justice Department and FBI officials defended the
system, saying they are not seeking new capabilities in the online
world but are simply trying to preserve their ability to monitor
criminal activity. They said that capability is being eroded by
growing use of new technologies such as encryption, cell phones and
wireless message devices.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a criminal uses e-mail to send a kidnapping demand, to
buy and sell illegal drugs or to distribute child pornography, law
enforcement needs to know to whom he is sending the messages and
from whom he receives them,'' said Kevin V. DiGregory, a deputy
assistant attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   But James X. Dempsey, an attorney at the Center for Democracy
and Technology, a Washington-based Internet watchdog group, said
that only recently have consumers become aware of how much
sensitive information about their lives is transmitted and stored
electronically.
</P>
<P>
   ``As most people sense with growing unease, everywhere we go on
the Internet we leave digital fingerprints, which can be tracked by
marketers and government agencies alike,'' Dempsey said. ``That
knowledge has made many people question what they should do online
and what they should do in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   He warned that unless these consumer fears are addressed, more
and more people will curtail their use of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Donald M. Kerr, an assistant director of the FBI, said the
public has ``nothing to fear'' with the Carnivore system. In fact,
he said, consumers should feel ``more safe'' on the Internet
because of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carnivore helps protect Internet users from cyber-criminals
who would otherwise be much more difficult to track down and
prosecute,'' he said. ``Without proper policing, these criminals
could prey on Internet users.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
