<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0199 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-ANGLO-AMERICAN-ROMANC     09-06 1683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANGLO-AMERICAN-ROMANCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    FINDING MR. RIGHT WITH A BRITISH ACCENT QL
</HEADLINE>
 QL  By HELEN KIRWAN-TAYLOR QC 
 &HT;    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service QC 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON - Ever since Madonna landed the hunky British director Guy
Ritchie and declared Britain her second home, the English tabloids have
been full of self-congratulatory prose. It's their metaphorical way of
kicking sand in the face of the single, commitment-minded American male,
who according to Time  magazine, is practically as rare a sighting as the
American osprey.
</P>
<P>
   Anglo-American romances are hardly news. Britain has long been home
for American women. From turn-of-the-century American heiresses like Jennie
Jerome (Lady Randolph Churchill, mother of Winston) and Consuelo Vanderbilt
(married off to the Ninth  Duke of Marlborough) to the late Linda
McCartney, Jerry Hall and now Candace Bushnell, American women have long
been irresistible to English men.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like them,'' Albert, Prince of Wales, said once, adding: ``They
are livelier, better educated and less hampered by etiquette. They are not
as squeamish as their English sisters and they are better able to take care
of   themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Albert, who in 1901 became King Edward VII, chose a Dane for his own
bride, but by the end of the Edwardian era, well over 100 Anglo-American
alliances had been concluded, and his grandson famously gave up the throne
for an American from Baltimore. In those days it was often a
straightforward business deal: He had class, she had cash.
</P>
<P>
   Today, I think the British male represents something that has gone
missing from his American counterpart: chivalry. Speaking as an expat
married to an Englishman, I've observed that my husband, Charlie, picks up
the tab for any single woman who joins us in a restaurant. He gets up when
my mother walks into the room and he still writes thank you notes. He also
has something else lost amongst my compatriots: mystery. Britain is now as
self-obsessed as America, but fortunately the tendency to bare it all (in
public and elsewhere) has yet to afflict the male population.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Americans and British are attracted to each other because
opposites attract,'' said Alfred Munkenbeck, an American architect living
in London with his Irish-born wife, Paula Reed, an editor at Conde Nast
Traveler.  In America, you can afford to be an extrovert. ``There's this
sense of space: you can always move somewhere else if you screw up,''  he
said. ``The British have this exaggerated politeness, very much like the
Japanese, because it's a tiny island. Everyone's terrified of sticking out.
Americans think: `How can they be so reserved?'''
</P>
<P>
   Hence, many American women find the British male to be the ultimate
challenge. ``I think American women are like sniffer dogs trying to pin
them down,'' said Cherie Phillips, an American consultant for  Sotheby's
married to a Scottish real estate executive. ``There are layers and layers
of gray to wade through.''
    For Stephanie Cabot, an American literary agent, it was her English
husband's subtlety that attracted her. ``The Englishman's approach is just
not fully fronted like ours,''  she said. ``It's layered, but what you get
out of it is nuance and subtext.''
</P>
<P>
   Where I live in Notting Hill, Anglo-American alliances are
practically as numerous as the Mercedes station wagons parked outside.
Geordie Grieg, the editor of The Tatler, who is  married to a Texan, and
Peter Soros (George Soros' nephew), who is married to the aristocratic
British writer Flora Fraser, live within 200 feet of each other. Monty
Python's John Cleese and his American psychotherapist wife, Alice Faye,
live nearby, as does Tricia Guild,  the founder of Designers Guild, and her
American restaurateur husband. The list goes on and on: Martin Amis and
his wife, the New York real-estate heiress and writer Isabel Fonseca, and
Charles and Kay Saatchi of art and advertising fame. Then, there are the
American model-makes-good stories such as that of Lili Maltese, married to
the party-loving aristocrat Henry Dent-Brocklehurst, Liz Hurley's great
friend.
</P>
<P>
   Once attached or married to a Briton, Americans seem to cut through
most of the social and professional barricades, sometimes reinventing
themselves on the way (just as the British all seem to have titles in
America, all Americans seem to have trust funds over here).
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, a fair share of Americans pretending to be
English (Madonna has been accused of affecting a slightly British accent
since she hooked up with Guy Ritchie). Annie Wentworth-Stanley, a popular
hostess, prided herself on being ``Jo Average from Connecticut'' when she
met her husband, Adrian, in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really scared, because everyone in the U.S. said the English
are stuffy chauvinists that think the women's place is in the home,'' she
said. ``My upbringing taught me to be independent and get on with my own
abilities.  In fact, I think Adrian was attracted to me because I hadn't
dropped out of a secretarial course or cooking school like so many of the
upper class English girls. I was earning more than he was when we were
dating.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, an independent American woman  can put British guys on the
defensive.  ``American women are either terrifyingly intrusive and
intense,'' said Nick Horley, 38, a single British dot-comer. ``Or they're
lifeless corporate lackeys who think we have no work ethic because we only
work 60 hours a week.''
</P>
<P>
   American men can be just as off-putting, he added, recalling an evening
out when a New York banker suddenly joined the dot-comer and his pals,
without being asked. It's that golden retriever, all-American bonhomie
that gets a Londoner's hackles up. ``A Brit would never have done that,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The American expat's life with a Londoner - though it can be initially
difficult and lonely - is often fantastically successful.  Americans may
have a reputation for overheating their houses and terrorizing members of
the service sector, but they get things done the British can only dream of.
They get   their children into plum schools, their names appear on
fashionable charity committees, and they own some of best real estate in
London.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hayes, whose company builds race cars for the Grand Prix, moved
his wife, Hilary, from New York to Britain and plunked her in the deepest
of the Oxfordshire countryside - ``the sticks,'' as she puts it (heaven to
the English). When a leading real estate agent couldn't find them a house,
``Hilary picked up the phone and called the estate agent,'' her husband
recalled. ``She said, `Do you have a memory on your phone?' He said yes.
She said `Every morning I want you to press my number when you have coffee.
I don't want you to tell me what's on the market; I want you to tell me
what's going to be on the market.' It was the same story with the builders.
Hilary would explain  exactly what a real closet looks like and how they
should build it. They  didn't know whether to laugh or cry.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Candace Bushnell will soon find out, life over here is not
one endless round of  parties. True acceptance may take 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Cindy and I first got together, she said, `You're not going to
believe the anti-Americanism in England,''' said  Anthony Holden, a writer
married to Cindy Blake, an American. ``I said, `Don't be ridiculous.'  But
it's true; even in the most  liberal households of Hampstead you hear this
cultural snobbism that can be as bad as anti-Semitism. They'll be trashing
American television and novels, and Cindy will be sitting right there.''
</P>
<P>
   Britons are resentful of American intrusion in their culture, language,
television and food products, said Robert Worcester, the director of MORI,
Britain's leading polling agency. ``They feel we are de-Briticizing Great
Britain and mongrelizing British life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Friends'' and ``Frasier,'' for example: the British either love
them or hate them. ``Sex and the City,'' which  most of the British men
don't get - they find the women sexually terrifying -  is pure nostalgia
for us ex-single New Yorkers because life here couldn't be more different.
Instead of the sunny, fun-filled Hamptons, we have cold, wet weekends of
standing by your man in the depths of Sussex as he shoots - and misses -
poor, defenseless pheasants  (women are invited to accompany men on one
``drive'').  British twentysomethings may hang out at the Pharmacy every
night, but the thirtysomethings I know stay home, giving the odd dinner
party with four weeks' notice. My  Manolos mostly gather dust in the
closet: dressing to kill is not done here.   Showing off in any way is
frowned upon in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   So, what's the upside?
</P>
<P>
   For one, the British men - at least the ones I know -  tend to be
faithful; they have a real sense of duty.  Fourteen years of same-sex
public schooling prevents them from learning too much about the opposite
sex; as a result, they treat it with cautious respect. Neil Mendoza, a
co-founder of Forward Publishing, who is  married to Emilia Mendoza, an
American designer, said: ``We're so awkward and shy, but Americans don't
know that. English   women do, of course. Americans imbue us with a false
sense of confidence.   The truth is concealed until it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Adorable as the British male may be, he's almost impossible to meet
here, though personal ads are slowly catching on. Even The Financial Times,
that bastion of serious British journalism, now has a lonely-hearts column
(the main attribute that the British male seems to be looking for is GSOH:
Good Sense of Humor). But most of the Anglo-American relationships I know
started in New York (including Bushnell's; she met Stephen Morris at Rao's,
the East Harlem restaurant). My husband, along with a dozen other young
Oxford graduates, first went to New York on the Morgan Guaranty training
program and came home  years later (as did many of his friends) with an
American fiancee. So, maybe Mr. Big is - as my rear view mirror says -
closer than he appears. He might live right next door.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1804EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
