<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-ROUNDUP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE'S ECONOMIC PLAN DRAWS FIRE FROM BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Democrat Al Gore, taking a page from Bill Clinton's successful
1992 campaign, laid out a detailed blueprint Wednesday for ``a new
prosperity'' that promises 10 million new high tech jobs, expanded
home ownership, wider college attendance and a 33 percent boost in
family income over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, speaking in Cleveland, mimicked the cadence of former
President George Bush's 1988 anti-tax pledge to ``read my lips'' in
an appeal for Americans to ``read my plan'' for the details.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican George W. Bush's campaign scoffed at Gore's
191-page federal economic plan, dubbing it a hollow ``press
release'' that would ``bust the budget'' and force the $1.9
trillion-a-year federal government back to red ink spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush summed up Gore's plan in his own words. ``It says `Send all
your money to Washington, and let me spend it for you,'' Bush said,
adding: ``And he can. Let me tell you, that man knows how to spend
money.''
</P>
<P>
   The presidential rivals' post-Labor Day battle over how to spend
the federal government's projected 10-year, $4.6 trillion budget
surplus came amid new disagreements over the timing and format of
the traditional campaign debates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who trails in the latest national poll, pressed his
challenge for Gore to join him for a joint hour-long campaign
appearance moderated by NBC News' Tim Russert next Tuesday. Bush
said he was ``showing up'' at the network studio in Washington,
D.C., whether Gore appeared or not.
</P>
<P>
   But NBC spokeswoman Barbara Levin threw cold water on that idea,
saying the network would not provide Bush a prime time platform
without Gore's participation.``We offered a debate, not an
appearance,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign, citing Gore's agreement in principle to joint
appearances with the GOP nominee during earlier appearances on
interview programs hosted by Russert and CNN's Larry King, seized
upon the debate stalemate to launch a television ad.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't trust Al Gore on debates, why should we trust him
on anything?'' the ad declared. The Bush campaign said the ads were
rotated into an ongoing series of campaign ads appearing in
battleground states.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has agreed to take part in the three 90-minute presidential
campaign debates planned by the bipartisan commission that has
hosted debates since 1988. Bush has agreed to take part in one of
the three debates sponsored by the commission, and challenged Gore
to meet him for the two less formal encounters on television
interview programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to play games to try to substitute a talk show
for the national bipartisan commission debates,'' Gore declared as
he rejected Bush's latest challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Gore leads Bush 49 percent to 39 percent, according to the
latest nationwide survey, a poll of registered voters for Newsweek
magazine that was conducted after the Democratic convention and
published Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In other campaign developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ Gore made gains on Bush in the state-by-state battle for the
270 electoral votes needed to win the White House, according to the
latest state-by-state surveys tracked by the National Journal's
political newsletter Hotline. The overview compiled Wednesday
showed Bush leading Gore in electoral votes, 279 to 221 with 38
electoral votes unassigned. Bush led Gore last week, 314 to 163
with 61 electoral votes unassigned.
</P>
<P>
   __Gore rebounded from an 11 percentage point deficit in early
July to edge ahead of Bush in the bellwether state of Missouri,
according to a survey published by the Kansas City Star. Gore led
Bush, 45 percent to 41 percent in a Mason-Dixon survey of likely
voters that had a margin of error of 4 percentage points. Missouri
has gone for the winner in every presidential election since 1960.
</P>
<P>
   __ Gore's campaign eagerly awaited the hard-won endorsement of
leaders of the 1.5-million member Teamsters union, which had balked
because of Gore's support for free trade. Gore aides said they
expected to get the endorsement Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, Gore said he was detailing his economic proposals
in excruciating detail so that American voters wouldn't have to
``read the tea leaves or read between the lines'' to know what a
Democratic administration ``would mean to families.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign manifesto, entitled ``Prosperity for America's
Families,'' outlined steps to pay off the nation's $5.6 trillion
public debt by 2012; target tax breaks to create 10 million new
high tech jobs; expand home ownership to 70 percent of American
families; hike family incomes by one-third over 10 years; and
provide tax breaks to encourage savings.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, continuing to claim the banner of a fiscal conservative,
called as well for a $300 billion ``rainy day'' reserve fund set
aside for emergencies from the projected $4.6 trillion federal
budget surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan wasn't built on the cross-your-fingers economics that
says we can give more to the people who already have the most and
then just hope the benefits trickle down to the middle-class,''
Gore told his Cleveland audience.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's detailed campaign document recalled a successful tactic
of the Clinton-Gore campaign in 1992 when the Democrats' 232-page
compendium of campaign promises, ``Putting People First,'' helped
Democrats retake the White House for the first time since 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign spokesman Dan Bartlett dismissed Gore's economic
plan, saying it could overspend projected federal revenues by as
much as $906 billion. The Congressional Budget Office projects a
$4.6 trillion federal budget surplus over the next 10 years, with
Republicans and Democrats alike promising to set aside $2.4
trillion of that amount to bolster Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's 200-page budget is written in red ink,'' Bartlett
contended, adding that Gore's package of ``targeted'' tax breaks
was so arcane that it will ``force families to hire lawyers and
accountants to determine whether they are one of the lucky few.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign touted the Texas governor's across-the-board
tax cut and competing federal budget blueprint by offering the
endorsement of six Nobel laureates and 294 other economists in a
full page newspaper ad published in editions of USA Today
distributed in St. Louis, three cities in Ohio, two cities in
Pennsylvania, Los Angeles and across Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The ad said that the Bush tax cut and spending plan was ``better
for working families and continued prosperity,'' adding that Bush's
plan to bolster Social Security, pay down the national debt,
provide $1.3 trillion in tax cuts and $475 billion in new spending
would ``create more economic growth and greater opportunities for
all Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush told a rally in Wilkes-Barre, Pa., that ``my plan has been
endorsed by Nobel prize winners; his plan has been endorsed by Bill
Clinton.``
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIOINAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GOP vice presidential candidate Dick Cheney, campaigning in
Wilmington, Del., told John and Sherry Lierenz that the Bush-Cheney
tax plan would save their three-person family $1,200 a year in
federal taxes compared to a $100 saving offered by Gore's plan.
Cheney said the GOP proposal would provide tax breaks for
stay-at-home mothers.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic vice presidential running mate Joseph Lieberman,
a senator from Connecticut, tried to counter the GOP proposal by
telling an audience at Southwest Missouri State University that
Bush's budget plan would spend so much of the federal budget
surplus that it could encourage resumption of deficit spending _ a
step that could be ``a crushing blow for the financial markets and
cause tremors around the globe.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Wire services contributed to this report.
</P>
