<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4253 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS07-COX     09-06 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By Mandi Albright, A. Scott Walton and Yolanda Rodriguez
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  COUNTRY
</P>
<P>
   ``Dev'lish Mary''
</P>
<P>
   Hot Club of Cowtown.Hightone.16 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   Hailing from Austin, the aptly named Hot Club of Cowtown keeps
on cranking out fine country music that simultaneously defies yet
draws upon tradition. ``Dev'lish Mary,'' the trio's third release,
mixes the usual _ western swing and traditional ballads _ with
styles rarely heard on country albums. ``Tchavolo Swing,'' heavy
with minor chords, sounds like a foot-stomper that the late Bob
Wills might have dreamed up during a Middle Eastern hootenanny.
Vocalist/violinist Elana Fremerman's background in classical and
world music is evident throughout ``Dev'lish Mary,'' but she stays
true to her Kansas roots, twanging it up in all the right spots.
And it doesn't hurt having premier Americana producer Lloyd Maines
at the helm, either. Hot Club of Cowtown's progressive
traditionalism flies in the face of modern Nashville's
cookie-cutter country, unabashedly embracing the past while boldly
setting new standards for alternative country's future.
</P>
<P>
   _Mandi Albright
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B :
</P>
<P>
   More on Hot Club of Cowtown: http: www.hightone.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``A Song for George Lewis''
</P>
<P>
   Michael White. Basin Street Records. 13 Tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The smile that clarinetist Michael White flashes on the cover of
this tribute album makes him appear at once mischievous, apologetic
and hopeful. It also invites you to come and explore White's
decidedly Dixieland jazz stylings. As a bandleader and arranger,
White's like a trustworthy friend leading you into terrain that's
both strange and familiar. Perhaps you've never heard the peppy
``Louisian-i-a'' before, but you'll surely imagine Ol' Louis doing
it . . . and better. But that tinny tune _ along with others
performed by White and his many accompanists (''Bugle Boy March,''
``What a Friend We Have in Jesus'') _ just attests to their
reverence for good songs, categories be damned. White's clarinet
captivates, as do the banjos and spoons and trombones, keys and
snare drums. The track in homage to the legend who first inspired
White to lick his chops is sentimental, but not sappy. And it
segues sweetly into the sassy ``St. Phillip Street Breakdown.''
Though produced by Grammy award winner Jerry Brock, everything
about this release _ and our most romantic images of New Orleans
jazzmen _ shrieks, ``Don't quit your day job!'' (In White's case,
that's as a professor at Xavier University.) At the same time, it
summons visions of a funeral parade for some Dixieland devotee who
died trying.
</P>
<P>
   _Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Michael White, Basin Street Records:
michaelw(at)basinstreetrecords.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  LATIN POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Voy A Enamorarte''
</P>
<P>
   Gisselle. BMG U.S. Latin. 11 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   There are several good songs on Gisselle's latest CD, including
the pounding opener, ``Te Voy Amar.'' This is the sixth outing for
the Puerto Rican merengue singer and the first to emphasize
ballads, which she handles very well, although the lyrics
themselves are not all that special. During the 1990s Gisselle, 30,
gained stardom with her strong vocals and fast-moving merengues. A
few songs on the new release, including ``Dime Luna'' and ``Que No
Diera,'' have cool tinges of gypsy rock, making them standouts. The
ballad ``Jurame'' is the best in the set. But the merengues don't
really distinguish themselves from what is already out there. They
are more like candy _ fun at first bite but not long-lasting.
</P>
<P>
   _Yolanda Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B :
</P>
<P>
   More on Gisselle: www.gisselle.com/
</P>
<P>
   More on BMG : www.bmgentertainment.com/
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
