<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0209 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4255 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-VIDEO-RINGEL07-COX     09-06 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-RINGEL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crisp to crazy, nurses' image runs the gamut
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Renee Zellweger's ``Nurse Betty'' isn't really a nurse, and she
doesn't play one on TV (well, not at first, but that's another
story). But she spends a lot of time in a pert-looking, nurselike
uniform, which set me thinking about the image of nurses in movies.
Mostly, it's leering soft-porn stuff like ``Student Nurses'' or
else anonymous angels in white who crisply fill in as moving
background in hospital movies. But there are some memorable nurses
who do more than empty bedpans. Here are a few to check out.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Farewell to Arms'': It may look a little creaky, having
been made in 1932, and it certainly wasn't Ernest Hemingway's
favorite, since the ambiguous ending changes the fate of one of the
major characters. Still, this adaptation of Hemingway's tragic love
story about an American ambulance driver (Gary Cooper) and a
British nurse (Helen Hayes) during World War I has an undeniable
romantic power. And it's twice as good (at least) and half as long
as the lush '50s remake starring Rock Hudson and Jennifer Jones.
The movie snagged four Oscar nominations (including best picture)
but won only two, for sound recording and cinematography. An
interesting casting footnote: The screenplay was originally written
with Fredric March and Claudette Colbert in mind.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``One Flew Over the Cuckoo's Nest'': From the saintly to the
monstrous ... Louise Fletcher's Big Nurse, aka Nurse Ratched, ruled
Jack Nicholson's psychiatric ward like the Florence Nightingale
from Hell. And she won a best actress Oscar for her efforts
(memorably accepting in sign language as a tribute to her deaf
parents). Nurse Ratched may have been a juicy role, but it wasn't
one that was easy to cast. Reportedly, everyone from Anne Bancroft
to Angela Lansbury turned it down. Then along came the little-known
Fletcher. In his memoir, director Milos Forman writes that when
Fletcher came for her interview, she was sweet and polite, with an
engaging smile. ``She was all wrong for Nurse Ratched, but there
was something about her. I asked her to read with me, and suddenly,
beneath the velvety exterior, I discovered a toughness and will
power that seemed tailored for the role.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``MASH'': The long-running TV series is so indelible that
sometimes it's easy to forget that those crazy cutups first
appeared in Robert Altman's hugely successful late-'60s comedy.
Donald Sutherland and Elliott Gould are the surgeons operating just
behind the front lines during the Korean War, though their antiwar
attitude and anti-establishment quips are far more redolent of the
then-raging Vietnam War (or at least as it was being fought over on
college campuses across the country). Their head nurse, Maj.
Margaret ``Hot Lips'' Houlihan, is played by Sally Kellerman, who
made her sexy as hell but also something of a pro-authority pain in
the butt. Kellerman later said that she had reservations when she
first discussed the role with her director. She told him, ``I don't
want to do this one-level, cold, rotten woman standing in the
background.'' He replied, ``This is just an outline and maybe a lot
of stuff can happen.'' It did _ enough to give Kellerman, a former
B-movie actress, a brief shot at the big time.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Sister Kenny'': This little-known film, based on the life of
an Australian nurse who battled for the treatment of infantile
paralysis, was a labor of love for star Rosalind Russell. Not only
did she spend time going to polio wards with the real sister
(that's British for nurse), but she battled for six years to get
the movie made. As she recalls in her autobiography, ``Crippled
children didn't sound like box office to the movie magnates.'' But
she persevered, and while the magnates were right _ the movie was a
commercial flop _ Russell got a Golden Globe award and an Oscar
nomination for her trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
