<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-SUNDAY07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A Stone-cold take on pro football
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Oliver Stone takes on pro football's dark side _ pills, booze,
prostitutes, shady back-office deals _ and almost fumbles. The
jarring game visuals come at you nonstop. All hard hits and harder
cheerleader bodies. Al Pacino plays the coach of the fictional
Miami Sharks and argues constantly with young team co-owner Cameron
Diaz. Jamie Foxx plays a rising quarterback and emerges the best
actor in the large cast. (The video is a Special Edition Director's
Cut, a version of the film re-cut by Stone, with a running time
shorter than the theatrical release.)
</P>
<P>
   `Any Given Sunday'
</P>
<P>
   Rated R / Our critic's grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : More on ``Any Given Sunday'' :
anygivensunday.warnerbros
</P>
<P>
   .com/
</P>
<P>
   More links to ``Any Given Sunday'':
www.ravecentral.com/anygivsun.html
</P>
<P>
   OTHER NEW RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``A Summer's Tale'' (unrated) _ Eric Rohmer's sunny ode to
youth and idealized love follows a young man (Melvil Poupaud)
during his monthlong holiday in Brittany. While waiting for a
girlfriend who may or may not show up, he's tempted by a local
flirt and finds his friendship with a
</P>
<P>
   waitress bordering on something more serious. Rohmer turns the
young man's burden of opportunity into something wistfully
bittersweet; we know whom the young man should choose, which makes
the movie's ending both melancholy and victorious. Grade: A -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``American Psycho'' (R and unrated versions) _ Director Mary
Harron (``I Shot Andy Warhol'') has taken Bret Easton Ellis'
controversial book about a Wall Street serial killer and created a
visually chilly but often very funny satire of American greed. It's
a critique of '80s me-first narcissism, embodied by an antihero (a
well-chiseled Christian Bale) whose refined taste in clothing and
health-care products is matched by his extensive repertoire as a
killer. Too bad it stumbles in the end. Grade: B -
</P>
<P>
   _Steve Murray
</P>
<P>
   O N T H E W E B : For upcoming video release dates:
www.comingsoon.net/videos.htm
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino and Steve Murray write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
