A4258 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKNOTES07-COX     09-06 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKNOTES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia writers gaining a hall of fame
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Georgia is the home of many famous writers, but until now there
has been no official recognition for the state's literary sons and
daughters.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Georgia Libraries has corrected that oversight
with the formation of the Georgia Writers Hall of Fame. This week,
the organization announced that 12 Georgians _ including Flannery
O'Connor, the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. and Margaret Mitchell _
will be inaugural inductees.
</P>
<P>
   Others honored include Erskine Caldwell (``Tobacco Road''), Joel
Chandler Harris (``Uncle Remus, His Songs and His Sayings: Folklore
of the Old Plantation''), James Dickey (``Buckdancer's Choice,''
``Deliverance''), John Oliver Killens (``Youngblood''), Carson
McCullers (``The Heart Is a Lonely Hunter''), Lillian Smith
(``Strange Fruit''), Augustus Baldwin Longstreet (``Georgia
Scenes''), Sidney Lanier (``Song of the Chattahoochee'') and W.E.B.
Du Bois (``The Souls of Black Folk'').
</P>
<P>
   The authors will be inducted this year. Two additional writers
will be nominated annually. Georgians can cast their votes for
nominations for living or deceased writers by clicking on
www.libs.uga.edu/gawriters or by calling Skip Hulett at
706-542-7123. The Georgia Writers Hall of Fame is housed at the
University of Georgia's Hargrett Rare Books and Manuscripts Library
in Athens, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  More lists: The New York Times is tinkering with its
best-seller list again. Barely a month after introducing its
children's list (presumably to bump the ``Harry Potter'' novels off
the adult list), the Times
</P>
<P>
   has divided the children's best sellers into three categories _
picture books, chapter books and paperbacks _ which will be
published in rotation. What this means is that ``Harry Potter'' is
nowhere to be found on Sunday's list. Instead, the top three
children's picture books are ``Wemberly Worried'' by Kevin Henkes,
``Oh, the Places You'll Go!'' by Dr. Seuss and ``How Do Dinosaurs
Say Good Night'' by Jane Yolen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Music and memories: Singer Melissa Etheridge has signed a deal
with Villard Books to publish her memoir, ``The Truth Is ...'' next
summer. The book, which will focus on her life as an artist and
mother, also will include lyrics to her songs as well as other
writings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Writing `The Truth Is ...' has forced me to look deep inside
myself and visit my past in ways I've never really done before,''
Etheridge says. ``It may be a harder road, and others may not agree
with what you have to say (but) the truth is always better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lit films: Anthony Hopkins has agreed to star in the film
version of Stephen King's ``Hearts in Atlantis.'' ... James Ellroy,
whose novel ``L.A. Confidential'' was made into a successful film,
will see another of his books on the big screen soon. Robert
Richardson, the cinematographer for ``Snow Falling on Cedars,''
will make his directorial debut with Ellroy's ``White Jazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
