<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Sept. 7, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Residents of the Northeast will awaken Thursday to another cool
morning as high pressure moves off the East Coast. It will turn
slightly warmer in the afternoon than in recent days, however, as
breezes from the southwest direct milder air north.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, a decaying front will continue slipping south across
the southern Gulf Coast States accompanied by many showers and
thunderstorms. Some of the showers will produce brief bursts of
heavy rain. Cooler air will arrive over much of Texas, bringing an
end to the record-setting heat.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and isolated thunderstorms will develop along a cold
front crossing the northern Plains. Afternoon thunderstorms will
develop in the central and southern Rockies along the tail of the
same front. Elsewhere a strong area of low pressure will roll into
the Pacific Northwest, marked by gusty winds and showers.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FADING HEAT WAVE
</P>
<P>
   Most major weather changes in the middle latitudes arrive from
the west driven by jet stream winds. But the great southern heat
wave of 2000 is ending from the east. Last week, cooler air spread
over the Carolinas and Georgia as a weak disturbance drifted very
slowly west from the Atlantic surrounded by clouds and showers. On
Wednesday, the 100-degree heat was quashed as far west as Texas
when the circulation around an expansive high-pressure zone near
the Great Lakes sent cooler air spilling southwest from Canada.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1818EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
