</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONG-KONG-POLITICS-510&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIVERSITY OFFICIALS RESIGN IN DISPUTE OVER POLITICS AND ACADEMIC
FREEDOMS 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG _ Two top officials at Hong Kong University resigned
on Wednesday after an investigation found that they and an adviser
to the territory's chief executive, Tung Chee-hwa, had pressured a
prominent pollster not to publish surveys critical of Tung.
</P>
<P>
   The vice-chancellor, Cheng Yiu-chung, and his deputy, Wong
Siu-lung, are the first casualties of a dispute that has riveted
this city for most of the summer, becoming a referendum on whether
Hong Kong's government has sought to stifle academic freedom since
the former British colony reverted to Chinese sovereignty in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The two men said they rejected the findings of the
investigation, which had been ordered by the university after the
pollster, Robert Chung, made the allegations in July. But they said
they would step down to avoid further damage to the institution.
</P>
<P>
   The report also implicated Tung's senior special adviser, Andrew
Lo. He refused to step down, saying he had not sought to intimidate
Chung. Lo has been stoutly defended by his boss, Tung.
</P>
<P>
   But with a drumbeat of discontent from students, academics and
opposition leaders here, analysts said Lo's future looked perilous.
Tung, a former shipping tycoon whose popularity has been battered
by the contretemps, may be forced to jettison one of his most
trusted advisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is blood in the water,'' said Albert Cheng, a radio host
whose talk show has been flooded with angry calls about the affair.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has injected a combustible element into Hong Kong's
legislative elections, to be held Sunday. In the territory's first
post-colonial ballot, in 1998, voters were driven by fears that
China would curtail Hong Kong's freedoms. This time around,
analysts say, people are likely to signal their dissatisfaction
with their own Beijing-appointed leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``The scandal damages the credibility and image of the local
government, especially Mr. Tung and his advisers,'' said Tsang
Yok-sing, the chairman of the main pro-Beijing party, the
Democratic Alliance for the Betterment of Hong Kong. ``We are seen
as close to Mr. Tung, so we will suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Tsang predicted that his party would lose at least one of the 24
seats in the Legislative Council, which are chosen through direct
elections. The other 36 seats are filled by an election committee
and indirect means that are designed to favor pro-business and
pro-Beijing interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hong Kong voters are not electing a government,'' said Martin
Lee, the chairman of the Democratic Party. ``They are electing
legislators, who are always going to be in opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   For all the complaints about Hong Kong's stunted political
system, the polling dispute is fresh evidence that people here
guard their liberties zealously. Chung's allegation _ that the
university had threatened to ``dry up'' his funding if he did not
stop conducting polls on the popularity of Tung _ prompted a
blizzard of criticism and news coverage.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Hong Kong University appointed an independent panel, headed by a
former High Court judge, to investigate the allegations. After 11
days of hearings, broadcast live on television, the panel last week
issued a damning report.
</P>
<P>
   It said that after a meeting between the vice-chancellor and
Tung's aide, the deputy vice-chancellor delivered a message to
Chung ``which was calculated to inhibit his right to academic
freedom.'' The panel described Tung's adviser, Lo, as a ``poor and
untruthful witness'' who gave a ``sanitized'' account of his role
to avoid the appearance of stifling academic freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The panel found no evidence that Lo had been ordered by Tung to
stop the polls. Tung declined to testify. But Chung and many others
here believe that the chief executive signaled his displeasure with
the surveys _ leading Lo to take matters into his own hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the issues in Hong Kong after the handover has been the
lack of transparency or accountability,'' said Michael DeGolyer,
head of the Hong Kong Transition Project, which measures public
attitudes in post-colonial Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   For that reason, DeGolyer said the very public airing of the
dispute would have a salutary effect. Given Hong Kong's awkward
political situation as a semi-democratic oasis in a communist
country, he said, people here should be on a hair-trigger for any
potential threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the United States, if an adviser to the governor told a
university president, `why are you doing this?' it would be
conversation,'' said Ying Chan, director of the journalism and
media studies center at Hong Kong University. ``But this is a city
with a fear of political interference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
