<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-     09-06 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WTIMOR-U.N.-KILLINGS-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KILLINGS OF U.N. WORKERS IN TIMOR MARS OPENING OF MILLENNIUM SUMMIT
MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ An armed mob stormed into a U.N. refugee office
in West Timor Wednesday, demolishing the office and beating to
death three unarmed U.N. workers, including an American, and
touching off repercussions of outrage at the Millennium Summit
meeting of world leaders here.
</P>
<P>
   The 149 assembled leaders included Indonesia's president,
Abdurrahman Wahid, who, embarrassed by the failure of his army and
police to prevent the rampage on the troubled island, said the
attack was the work of supporters of a militia leader who was
killed on Tuesday under mysterious circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid promised to send two military battalions to reassert
control in West Timor. But his words did not placate the fury at
the United Nations, which has seen 193 of its peacekeepers and
civilian workers killed in the line of duty since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council was preparing to discuss the attack, and
Secretary-General Kofi Annan moved a meeting with Wahid that had
been planned for later this week to Wednesday. Confronting Wahid
face-to-face, Annan condemned the incident and called the security
situation in West Timor unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tragedy underlines once again the dangers faced by
unarmed humanitarian workers serving the United Nations in conflict
or post-conflict situations,'' Annan earlier told the gathering of
world leaders in a scheduled address at the opening of the summit
meeting. ``The Security Council and I, myself, have repeatedly
expressed concern about the safety of United Nations personnel in
the field, both military and civilian.''
</P>
<P>
   Annan asked the assembled leaders to join him in observing a
minute of silence to honor ``those brave colleagues who have lost
their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The dead workers were identified as Carlos Caseras of the United
States, Samson Aregahegn of Ethiopia and Pero Simundza of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   According to the U.N. high commissioner for refugees, Sadako
Ogata, the refugee operation in Atambua was attacked after the
death of the militia leader. Though his death had no apparent
connection to the U.N. refugee effort, more than 1,000 supporters
brandishing automatic weapons looted and trashed the refugee
office, killed the three workers, burned vehicles and stole
equipment, including radios that the office relied upon to keep in
touch with other U.N. activities on the island.
</P>
<P>
   By evening, more than 40 employees of the U.N. refugee agency
and other international workers in Atambua had been evacuated by
helicopter to Dili, the capital of East Timor, under orders from
Ogata. Other U.N. workers were reported to still be hiding from the
mob. Fred Eckhard, the spokesman for the secretary-general,
declined to give further details, saying it might put their lives
at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Ogata called the attack the worst security incident her office
had witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   She said that she had brought up the attack during what she
called ``a kind of an encounter'' here with Wahid. She told
reporters that he had expressed feelings of mourning for the slain
workers and had said that one of the two battalions he dispatched
would arrive shortly in West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But Ogata pointedly said after their meeting: ``I would like to
insist that the president of Indonesia implement security measures.
Words are not enough anymore. I want facts.''
</P>
<P>
   Ogata said the rest of the refugee workers in West Timor would
be evacuated on Thursday and would not return until their full
security was assured. ``It is an evacuation, not a withdrawal,''
she said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The mayhem in Atambua mirrored the security problems encountered
by refugee workers in many places throughout the world, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a day of mourning for myself and the families'' of the
three murdered workers in West Timor, she said. ``I hope this
tragedy will open the eyes of the world leaders here, and if
changes take place, perhaps we will say it happened on the right
day.''
</P>
<P>
   The island of Timor was wracked by violence last year when
militiamen attacked residents of East Timor who had voted for
independence from Indonesia, killing some of them, razing homes and
sending nearly 300,000 fleeing for their safety to the western part
of the island. Nearly 170,000 East Timorese refugees have since
returned home, but up to 125,000 remain in West Timor, where
militia members have continued to prey upon them despite frequent
appeals from the United Nations and others for the Indonesian
government to intervene.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
