<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR WEDNESDAY, SEPT. 6 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: These corrections appeared in The New York Times on
Wednesday, Sept. 6. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-SCOUTS-GAYS-NYT (moved Monday, Aug. 28)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, August 28
about a falloff in support for the Boy Scouts because of their
exclusion of gays misstated two cities' reactions to the ban.
Chicago no longer lets the Boy Scouts use parks, city buildings and
schools without charge. The public schools of San Francisco no
longer sponsor Scout recruitment drives or other programs during
school hours. The Scouts are not barred from using parks, schools
and other sites.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the timing of those restrictions.
They began before the Supreme Court upheld the ban in June, not
afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The article also cited one city erroneously among those that bar
the Scouts from their facilities. Although one San Jose elementary
school district, Alum Rock Union, does not permit recruiting or
other Scout programs during school hours, the ban is attributed to
demands on instructional time, not to the Scouts' policy.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the number of United Way
organizations that have stopped raising funds for the Scouts. It is
about a dozen, not dozens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the article misstated the Roman Catholic Church's
stance on the ordination of gays. Ordination requires a promise to
live a celibate life. While the church condemns homosexual
activity, it does not have a policy against ordaining gay men.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CONGRESS-RETURN-NYT (moved Monday, Sept. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
4 about each party's legislative goals for Congress this fall
misspelled the surname of an official at the Heritage Foundation, a
conservative research institution, who said he thought the
Democrats were working more closely with their presidential
candidate than were the Republicans with theirs. The official is
Marshall Wittmann, not Wittman.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PODESTA-BROTHERS-NYT (moved Monday, Sept. 4)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Monday, September
4 about a Washington lobbying company, Podesta.com, in which two
partners have brothers in high positions in the Clinton White
House, referred incorrectly to Heather Barbour's connection with
the company. She is no longer there, having left at the end of July
for a job in California. And she is not a daughter (or other
relative) of Haley Barbour, former chairman of the Republican
Party.
</P>
</TEXT>
