<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4270 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS &LR;      09-06 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MILITARY WEAKNESS IS AN OLD CAMPAIGN PHANTOM
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When a presidential candidate finds his issues
aren't selling with the electorate, his ace in the hole is usually
to warn that the policies supported by the other party would weaken
national security.
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and Democrats have used that red flag
successfully in the past.
</P>
<P>
   John F. Kennedy hit pay dirt in the 1960 campaign when he
accused the Eisenhower-Nixon administration of allowing a missile
gap to develop at the height of the Cold War with the Soviet Union.
After Kennedy was elected, his advisers acknowledged that the
charge had no basis in reality.
</P>
<P>
   Lyndon B. Johnson attacked his GOP opponent, Sen. Barry
Goldwater of Arizona, in 1964 as trigger happy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whose finger do you want on the (nuclear) button?'' Johnson
would ask the crowds at political rallies. Johnson further
demonized Goldwater by accusing him of ``wanting to lob one in the
men's room of the Kremlin.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Johnson also charged that Goldwater wanted to send
American boys to fight when Asian boys should be doing the job.
Imagine that. Johnson, of course, later became hopelessly mired in
the Vietnam War, so much so that he feared he could not win
reelection in 1968 and withdrew from the race.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan pulled out all the stops in his 1980 challenge to
President Jimmy Carter by charging there was a ``window of
vulnerability'' in the nation's defense as a result of Carter's
cutbacks in the various weapons programs.
</P>
<P>
   Now comes the Republican ticket of Texas Gov. George W. Bush and
former defense secretary Dick Cheney with an attack on the Clinton
administration's defense policies.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, who was Pentagon chief under President George Bush,
contends the Clinton administration has undermined the military's
state of readiness with low pay, recruiting shortages, inadequate
training, and unreliable weapons. Cheney also claims morale is low
among the troops and that they are spread too thinly around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the draw down of U.S. forces began with the end of the
Cold War when Cheney was running the Defense Department.
</P>
<P>
   During his years at the Pentagon, Cheney created a blueprint for
the United States to be able to fight two wars simultaneously,
presumably against North Korea in the Pacific and in the Persian
Gulf. But out of office, he criticized President Clinton's
intervention in Haiti and other places but did not say when or
where he thought the United States should be involved militarily.
</P>
<P>
   But Cheney can't have it both ways. The United States cannot
simultaneously be the sole superpower of the world and leader of
nations and, at the same time, retreat from the world's
troublespots, especially when they involve genocide, as was the
case in Bosnia and Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore, backed up by Defense Secretary William
Cohen, a Republican, rejected harsh criticism along the same line
from GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush, who claimed the
U.S. has two Army divisions unprepared for combat.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bush and Gore are promising to increase their defense
budgets by billions if they are elected. That's par for the course.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, President Clinton has decided that the Pentagon hasn't
demonstrated that a new missile defense system is workable and he
is passing on the decision to his successor whether to go ahead
with construction of a missile shield.
</P>
<P>
   Changing world conditions require a constant U.S. reassessment
of the goals of so-called ``rogue states,'' now designated in less
menacing diplomatic jargon as `states of concern.'' The world is
changing and now rapprochement with even North Korea does not
appear too far-fetched.
</P>
<P>
   One voice of reason is Gen. George Joulwan, former head of
NATO's Supreme Allied Command, who said in an interview that what
is needed is ``clarity'' regarding the future role of the U.S.
armed forces in the 21st century. On that score, he said they must
be more versatile, flexible and mobile to be prepared for rapid
deployment.
</P>
<P>
   But more importantly, ``We have to talk more about conflict
resolution, how we work with the United Nations, what is the role
of a leader,'' meaning the United States, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   While at NATO, Joulwan arranged ``partnerships for peace''
relationships with 44 countries, including Russia, linking them to
the Atlantic Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   He boils down the military readiness issue to this hypothetical
question to Bush and Cheney: ``Ready to do what?''
</P>
<P>
   And I repeat my favorite question to presidents when, over the
years, they have thumped for bigger Pentagon budgets in peacetime:
``Who's the enemy?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
