</P>
<P>
   UN-CLINTON (New York) _ President Clinton, taking advantage of
an unprecedented gathering of world leaders at a UN summit, makes
an impassioned plea for Mideast peace, saying the time for an
agreement is ``fleeting and about to pass.'' By John Donnelly. 1200
words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS (p) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-ISSUES (Washington) _ With Al Gore putting out an
economic tome and George W. Bush detailing a big Medicare overhaul
-- all within two days of Labor Day -- this is shaping up as a
campaign of issues, big ideas, and sharp ideological differences.
By Mary Leonard. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-GORE (Cleveland) _ Al Gore spells out the nuances and
underpinnings of his economic plan. By Glen Johnson. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BUSH (Indianapolis) _ George W. Bush launches a
multi-pronged attack on Al Gore amid confidence the debate gambit
is playing to Bush's advantage. By Anne E. Kornblut.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SAFETY (Undated) _ To prevent school violence, teachers
and principals should be on the lookout for students who are
fascinated by bloodshed, unusually heartbroken over a failed
relationship or who look up to destructive figures such as Satan or
Hitler, FBI says. By Scott Greenberger. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   ALLERGY-SEASON (Undated) _ We hear to hear it every year: This
fall and spring will be one of the worst for allergy sufferers. But
this year will really, really be one of the worst, thanks to the
damp, cool summer that ruined many vacations but fostered
tall-growing ragweed plants. By Richard Saltus. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MP3-RULING (Undated) _ Universal Music Group wins a stunning
ruling in federal court when a judge says MP3.com must pay $25,000
per CD that it made available via the Internet. The judge said the
penalty, which could reach $250 million, was a warning to other
Internet companies about violating copyright laws. By Stephanie
Stoughton. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   CITIGROUP-AFC (Undated) _ Seeking to stabilize earnings and
expand its global presence in the consumer finance arena, financial
services giant Citigroup will buy the lending company Associates
First Capital Corp. for about $31.1 billion in stock. AFC is the
country's biggest consumer-finance company, adding to Citigroup's
already huge presence in consumer lending/credit cards. By Scott
Nelson. 700 words.
</P>
