</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BNP PARIBAS PROFIT RISES
</P>
<P>
   The French banking group BNP Paribas, buoyed by its asset
management and retail banking business outside France, said
first-half operating income rose 24 percent, to 2.81 billion euros,
or $2.5 billion, from a pro forma 2.27 billion euros a year
earlier. The report combined first-half results for the first time
since the takeover of Paribas by Banque Nationale de Paris a year
ago. The combined bank's chairman, Michel Pebereau, sought to
counter reports of high-level defections from the Paribas
investment banking arm, saying that integration of the banks was
proceeding satisfactorily ``despite the inherent difficulties
associated with such a merger.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EUROCLEAR ACQUISITIONS
</P>
<P>
   Euroclear, the world's largest securities clearing and
settlement company, has agreed to acquire 51 percent of the
settlement agencies for the Brussels and Amsterdam stock exchanges
as it streamlines its activities in anticipation of the merger of
the Paris, Amsterdam and Brussels Exchanges on Sept. 22. Terms were
not disclosed. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   COATS VIYELLA TO CUT JOBS
</P>
<P>
   The Coats Viyella Group PLC, Britain's biggest textile maker,
with brands that include Van Heusen and Jaeger, said it would sell
off clothing and other divisions and cut about 1,900 jobs, dealing
a blow to the ailing British textile industry. The move follows a
decision by Marks &AMP; Spencer PLC, the largest British clothing
retailer and Coats Viyella's biggest customer, to trim inventories
as its business slumps. Coats Viyella said it would focus on its
global threads business.
</P>
<P>
   FRENCH BANK SHARES FALL
</P>
<P>
   Shares in Credit Commercial de France fell almost 15 percent
after HSBC Holdings, the London-based banking group that acquired
control of Credit Commercial in April, said it would acquire the
1.4 percent of Credit Commercial shares it did not yet own for 150
euros ($135) a share. Credit Commercial said its net profit rose 30
percent in the first half, to 296.4 million euros ($266.7 million).
Yet the news of HSBC's bid, intended to withdraw Credit Commercial
shares from the bourse, caused the share price to drop 14.9
percent, to 151.1 euros. &QL;
</P>
