<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MOYERS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PBS SERIES EXPLORES CHANGING ATTITUDES ABOUT THE END OF LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MIKE McDANIEL 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
As a rule, we choose not to dwell on death, as if thinking or
talking about it might alter karma, betray faith or speed up our
own demise. But on those moments when we entertain the idea of the
inevitable, most of us reach the same conclusion: We don't want to
hurt.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death be not painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest change in our attitudes toward death and dying has
come in the last few years in our own desire to have a good
death,'' said Bill Moyers, talking about his upcoming documentary
miniseries.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was born, before World War II and before penicillin,
the median age of death was 52, and death usually came very
swiftly,'' said the 66-year-old journalist. ``Today, the median age
of death is 76, and death comes very slowly, as the result,
usually, of chronic, progressive disease.''
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers _ whom Moyers calls ``the biggest pig going through
the stomach of the American python'' _ have only lately begun
waking up to the fact that not only does death lie in wait, but
also an unhappy death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is, 80 percent of us will die in a hospital or some
other institution outside of the home,'' Moyers said, and many of
those will die a ``slow and tortuous'' death.
</P>
<P>
   But what we would prefer, if asked, is ``a good death,''
painless and at home, surrounded by people we love.
</P>
<P>
   These circumstances sparked Moyers and his wife, Judith Davidson
Moyers, to make ``On Our Own Terms: Moyers on Dying'' (8-9:30 p.m.
CDT Sunday-Wednesday, PBS). The documentary miniseries takes the
stand that the time has come to change how we die in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be free of pain,'' Bill Moyers said. ``We want some
control over the circumstances, and we want emotional and spiritual
support.''
</P>
<P>
   The Moyerses, along with producers Elena Mannes and Gail
Pellett, traveled to hospitals, hospices and nursing homes across
the country _ from Florida to Oregon _ to document the stories of
doctors, nurses, hospice workers, families of the dying and the
dying themselves. Their work was edited down into a remarkably
compelling, six-hour series, divided into four 90-minute parts.
</P>
<P>
   Achieving a ``good death'' can be complicated. A major
impediment is the caregiver. Doctors have been trained that death
is failure, so they use heroic measures and the latest medical
technology to save and prolong lives _ often without considering
the quality of the lives being saved.
</P>
<P>
   But as the series points out, a third option _ palliative care,
which emphasizes comfort over care _ is slowly becoming more
available. The series also explores the issue of physician-assisted
suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Viewers, beware: ``On Our Own Terms'' confronts death head-on.
From time to time, we see dead people. And many of the people
interviewed for the series have subsequently died. But before their
final exits, they provide a noble and lasting service in
contributing their personal stories to this series.
</P>
<P>
   For example, there's Dr. Bill Bartholome, a Kansas City
pediatrician with cancer of the esophagus. Given six months to
live, Bartholome chose quality over quantity of life. Instead of
operations and aggressive treatments for his terminal disease, he
went home and surrounded himself with family, choosing to live in
what he called ``the light of death.''
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone in this series forgoes curative treatment. In
Miami, Dr. Pat Caralis confronts a population made up of Cubans,
Haitians, African-Americans, Asians and Jews, all of whom have
cultural differences with regards to death.
</P>
<P>
   At Mount Sinai Medical Center in New York, Dr. Diane Meier
specializes in palliative care _ care emphasizing pain management
and comfort. Despite nine years of post-college medical training,
``I did not have a single lecture in pain management _ not one,''
she says. Her work has taught her that many of her colleagues don't
acknowledge pain as a relative symptom.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisiana, we meet veterinarian Jim Witcher, who is suffering
the progressive paralysis of Lou Gehrig's disease. His sad and
terrifying story is coupled (in Part 3 of the series) with that of
Kitty Rayl, an Oregon woman suffering from terminal cancer. The
difference between the two: Kitty lives in a state that allows
physician-assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   At the Balm of Gilead Project in Birmingham, Ala., Dr. Amos
Bailey oversees a program attempting to bring hospice and
palliative care to the working poor and the uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The video testimony of these and others make ``On Our Own
Terms'' extraordinary television, intimate and powerful. The series
is being packaged with a three-part, 30-minute series, ``With Eyes
Open.'' There will also be an hourlong local follow-up show at 9:30
p.m. Wednesday. And there's an extensive online component at
www.pbs.org/onourownterms.
</P>
<P>
   The Moyers' message is that change in the way we perceive and
handle death is upon us, and that it's up to us _ individually and
collectively, through personal intervention, public discourse and
change in public policy _ to be aware of our choices and to make
informed decisions so that when it is our turn, we can go out on
our own terms.
</P>
<P>
   It is a dutiful assignment, expertly realized.
</P>
<P>
   XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
