<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER NEWS WATCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 &HT;     
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LARGE LCD MONITOR BUILT FOR WORK, NOT FUN
</P>
<P>
   There is one major drawback to conventional cathode ray tube
monitors: As the screen size expands so does the plastic box out
back. Flatter liquid crystal displays, which take up less desk
space, eliminate that problem.
</P>
<P>
   NEC-Mitsubishi Electronics Displays will soon begin shipping an
LCD monitor that, at 21.3 inches, approaches the size of the
largest, conventional monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Al Giazzon, vice president for marketing at NEC-Mitsubishi,
acknowledged that there were larger flat-panel displays based on
plasma display technology. But he added that although their
width-to-height display, like a movie screen's ratio of about
16-to-9, may be fine for watching the latest DVD films, it falls
short when it comes time to work again.
</P>
<P>
   That is because word processors and other software often use a
display format that works better with the 4-to-3 width to height
ratio that is the current standard for monitors. The NEC MultiSync
LCD2110 maintains the 4-to-3 ratio, which allows a more useful
viewing area, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, space-starved users may face another shortage:
Money. The LCD2110 sells for a staggering $7,999.
</P>
<P>
   Until the price drops, he said he expected the largest group of
buyers would be stock and commodity traders, whose thirst for
screen space is apparently unquenchable. It is quite common,
Giazzon said, for a single trader to sit in front of three or four
screens.
</P>
<P>
   NEW HIGH TECHNOLOGY ALLOWS NORMAL LANGUAGE
</P>
<P>
   Searching within Web sites is often just as frustrating as
searching the whole Web. Dead ends and unrelated links are common.
But a new technology that is being unveiled this week on the Public
Broadcasting Service's Web site hopes to change that.
</P>
<P>
   The new search technology is among the first to do a linguistic
analysis of a searcher's query instead of simply relying on
matching keywords with words in a document. ``You can now ask
questions the way you normally do, using your own words,'' said
Bruno Henry, chief executive of LexiQuest, the company that
developed the search technology.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Henry said, in the past when people typed something
like, ``I want to find information on myths in American culture,''
they were unlikely to get useful search results. The words of their
query were too vague and had multiple meanings. But with the new
technology, Henry said, that query would be read by software
trained to look for the context of the sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Johnston, senior director of technology for PBS.org, said
expected the new technology would help to uncover ``a wealth of
content that is not uncovered by the typical user.'' And it will
solve another big problem too: It will forgive misspellings of a
keyword favorite: ``Antiques Roadshow.''
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT DEVICE SHOWS GAMERS JUST WHO'S TALKING THE TALK
</P>
<P>
   For online gamers, the ability to speak through the Internet to
other players while playing has obvious advantages. But it also has
the potential for trouble. ``If you're in the middle of a combat
game and you're strategizing with your team mate, it's important
not to let your opponents hear that,'' said Isabella Carniato,
Microsoft's Game Voice marketing manager.
</P>
<P>
   However, making those Internet voice connections and then
keeping track of who is hearing what can sometimes become as
complicated as determining the next step in destroying the enemy in
some cyber battle.
</P>
<P>
   While studying architecture and political science at the
University of Waterloo in Ontario, Carniato developed and marketed
one of the earliest pieces of software that allowed gamers to speak
as well as play over the Net. But now that Microsoft has taken over
Carniato's company that produced Battlefield Communicator and put
her on its payroll, she is now proposing that the next big thing
for gamers who chat is a piece of hardware.
</P>
<P>
   The main problem with software for managing voice connections is
invisibility, Carniato said. Most games don't make it practical to
show the on-screen displays of voice management software during
play. Given that, it becomes easy for players to quickly lose track
of exactly who's listening at any given moment.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft SideWinder Game Voice is a chunk of black plastic
that resembles an oversize hockey puck. When plugged in through a
computer's USB port, it acts something like an old-fashioned
telephone switchboard. Eight buttons on top of the device light up
to show live connections and allow users to quickly alter the
pattern of the hookups.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to several pieces of chat software, the device,
which costs $54.95, comes packaged with a headset microphone.
Because of that, Microsoft has also included voice recognition
software that allows users to operate most games with voice as well
as keyboard commands.
</P>
<P>
   But Carniato acknowledged that there are many situations where
pecking away at a keyboard will still be more convenient. ``You
would never say `shoot' or other commands that are right under your
fingers,'' she said. ``If you're just shooting until you run out of
rounds, it doesn't make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   THE VCR THAT PLAYS MOVIES BUT REJECTS JELLY SANDWICHES
</P>
<P>
   A videocassette recorder and a child can be a hazardous
combination _ for the VCR. The tape slot has been known to attract
foreign objects, including the occasional peanut butter and jelly
sandwich. Sony Electronics has introduced a new machine with a tape
slot that can be locked to keep wayward objects out.
</P>
<P>
   The new model, called the MovieTime and priced at $99, also has
a timer so that parents can limit the amount of tape viewing at one
sitting. For children who can't stand dead air, the machine
displays animation while a tape is being fast-forwarded or rewound.
One other parent-friendly feature: The ``Eject'' button locks so
even if Junior is sick of seeing that old Barney tape, he can't opt
out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1832EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0224 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4278 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CONTRAPTION-GAME-     09-06 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CONTRAPTION-GAME-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTRAPTIONS' HARDEST PUZZLE: HOW TO STOP 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER OLAFSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a week immersed in ``Return of the Incredible Machine:
Contraptions,'' I found strange thoughts bubbling up in my head.
</P>
<P>
   After I noticed that I had left my computer on all night, I
wondered, fleetingly, if I could rig up a boxing glove on a spring
to hit the off button at an appointed hour. When I inadvertently
disabled an electrical socket in the bedroom and couldn't
immediately figure out how to turn it on again, it flickered
through my mind that if that had happened in the game, I would have
been able to restore power with a laser that matched the color of
the dead socket's faceplate.
</P>
<P>
   And when one of the cats solemnly presented me with its latest
catch from the backyard, it occurred to me in passing that the poor
mouse would have had a better chance reaching safety with the help
of some explosives.
</P>
<P>
   So absorbing is this puzzle game, the first new ``Incredible
Machine'' game in five years, that ruminations inspired by its more
than 250 graphical conundrums have been intruding regularly upon
the real world. I don't mind. It is a tribute to the game's homey
appeal and its challenge, as well as a signal that this celebrated
series has lost none of its ability to charm and infuriate.
</P>
<P>
   Like its five predecessors, ``Contraptions'' is inspired by the
ramshackle inventions of Rube Goldberg, a cartoonist, sculptor and
author who died in 1970 and is best known for his parodies of
mankind's attempts to build ever-more-elaborate mousetraps.
</P>
<P>
   In the game, you assemble makeshift machines from objects
ordinary (flashlights and magnifying glasses) and fantastic
(anti-gravity pads) to achieve mundane results. (A mouse reaches
its hole. A candle is lighted. Fireworks are launched.) These
ostensibly labor-saving devices are peculiarly labor intensive.
Balls drop to turn power on and off, start toasters and balance
teeter-totters. Lasers power electrical sockets and light candles.
A cat frightens a mouse, which runs in its cage on a wheel that
turns a fan belt, which sets another mechanism in motion. The
shortest distance between two points is never a straight line.
</P>
<P>
   In one puzzle, for instance, I was assigned to bop an animated
baboon on the head with a steel ball. This contraption kicked into
action when a ball, different from the one that would hit the
baboon, dropped onto a springy platform and started bouncing, going
higher each time. It finally caromed off an angled corner and hit a
pair of shears. The shears snapped closed, cutting a cord that
suspended a leaky can of paint above a detonator. The explosion
that resulted when the falling can pressed the detonator's plunger
blew out the bottom of a nearby bin, which freed a little boy
inside. He walked down a ramp and onto a teeter-totter, pushing one
side down onto the handle of an air pump. The blast of air set in
motion a pinwheel, a fan belt connected to the pinwheel, a
treadmill at the other end of the fan belt and a steel ball that
had been resting on the treadmill. The ball zipped off to the
right, where it clunked the innocent monkey.
</P>
<P>
   The baboon rubbed its head, not hurt in any serious way, and the
puzzle was complete. I'd meant to take a break here, but I started
the next puzzle instead. It was only a click away. Once you've
started playing ``Contraptions,'' it's awfully hard to stop. Since
you can use the included construction kit to create your own
puzzles and can import new ones created by other players, the game
needn't end.
</P>
<P>
   This particular puzzle was rated by the game as of medium
difficulty and seemed relatively easy. But as you progress through
the game, you increasingly find that the toolkit allotted to a
particular task appears to be a tool or two short. That's usually a
clue that one piece has to perform more than one function,
sometimes a function unrelated to its obvious purpose. For example,
on one level I found that pipe segments that accelerate whatever
passes through them were more effectively used when they were piled
up as steps so a ball could bounce down them. In that way, the
puzzles extend into the supplies you are given to solve a problem.
</P>
<P>
   And as they say in advertising, positioning is everything. You
not only have to select the correct tools to complete the gadget on
the screen, but you must also tweak their orientation or settings.
For example, you can adjust the clock on the egg timer for
situations that require time delays. And you must often put objects
in precisely the right spots to achieve the necessary end. Once you
hit the Start button to set the contraption in motion, you can't
intercede further.
</P>
<P>
   The creators, much to their credit, have not rendered
``Contraptions'' in three dimensions, as often happens with updates
of older games. An ``Incredible Machine'' reinvented as an
environment might raise the conceptual questions that ``Incredible
Machine'' as a game never raises. (Mine is not to question why;
mine is simply to enjoy myself.) The graphics are more detailed
than in previous games, but the game remains distinctly low tech
and straightforward. The familiarity of the household objects in
the toolkit, the small scale (each puzzle is confined to a single
screen) and the on-screen hints leave the impression of
manageability.
</P>
<P>
   But their execution is quite another matter. ``Contraptions''
can be utterly maddening. I must have spent hours staring into the
screen to figure out why a balloon steadfastly refused to float
through a hole I'd created with a rocket. That reverie was broken
only when the real world intruded upon the game world _ hot, heavy
breath on my thigh and a steady, long-lashed gaze from the largest
of my dogs told me that it was time for their dinner. I left the
game and made my way downstairs to the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   But on the way, I confess, I wondered how I could deliver food
into their dishes without leaving my chair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Return of the Incredible Machine: Contraptions,'' published by
Sierra for Windows 95, 98 and 2000 and MacOS 8.5.1; $29.95; for all
ages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
