<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BUSINESS NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.07.00
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   B2B numbers should quadruple by 2004
</P>
<P>
   Christmas in July: 42 million shop on the Web
</P>
<P>
   Dutch bank offers online savings _ at 6.5%
</P>
<P>
   Webvan wants to deliver more customer loyalty
</P>
<P>
   Bank of America offers wireless services
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-TO-BIZ BOOM: The number of companies doing business with
each other online should quadruple by 2004, according to a new
report from the Boston Consulting Group. The study predicts that
business-to-business e-commerce will hit $4.8 trillion in four
years, up from an estimated $1.2 trillion this year. Online
purchasing will account for 40 percent of transactions, according
to the study. About 11 percent of purchases will involve online
price negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   CHRISTMAS IN JULY: Nearly 52 million visitors shopped online in
July, accounting for 42 percent of the Internet audience, according
to the Nielsen/Netratings July global Internet index. Last month,
Amazon topped the charts with 13.9 million users. One in 10 surfers
visited the eBay site, totaling 11.5 million people. LookSmart came
in just shy of that with 11.4 million visitors. Also in July, the
number of people with Internet access grew 4.5 percent over June
figures, rising to 216 million in July from 207 million.
</P>
<P>
   GO DUTCH: You can now open an online savings account with Dutch
banking and insurance group ING Group of the Netherlands. The
savings account, which offers an interest rate of 6.5 percent, is
ING Direct's first online venture in the United States. ING Direct
is also active in Canada, Spain, Australia and France. ING plans to
launch the online bank next in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   home.ingdirect.com
</P>
<P>
   WEBVAN WANTS MORE: Customer loyalty, not surprisingly, is a
concern for Webvan Group Inc. ``Customers shop with us probably not
quite as frequently as we would like,'' said Chief Executive George
Shaheen in a CNBC interview Wednesday, a day after the Foster City,
Calif., company announced buying HomeGrocer.com Inc. for about 138
million Webvan shares. Shaheen also said he doesn't see room for
other major mergers among online grocers, but does anticipate
``e-tailers hooking up with bricks-and-mortar retailers just to
stay viable.''
</P>
<P>
   WIRELESS BANKING: Bank of America will offer wireless services
for its 2.4 million online banking customers, rolling out the
features over the next 18 months. First up are private banking
customers in Dallas, Baltimore, and Washington D.C. In its first
stage, customers will be able to access account and investment
information, and transfer funds between accounts on most wireless
devices, including cellular phones using the Sprint PCS, AT&AMP;T and
Verizon wireless networks, and Palm V platform. The company plans
to expand its wireless services to include all brokerage services.
Bank of America is averaging 125,000 new online customers per
month.
</P>
