<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4288 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-CULT-PRODUCTS-ART     09-06 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-CULT-PRODUCTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPANY WEB SITES NOT JUST FOR BUSINESS, SOME ARE ALSO FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)  
 By MICHAEL POLLAK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Work and play have a wonderful way of merging on the Internet.
Take the prosaic corporate site. There is probably not much you can
do to liven up, say, North American Veeblefetzer: product pictures,
locations, corporate staff, how to order, shareholder information,
Our Founder, and so on.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are corporate sites that beg to be enjoyed, the
cyberspace equivalent of the time-traveling DeLorean in ``Back to
the Future.'' One essential element is a corporate history that
goes beyond nuts and bolts and shows an appreciation, nay, respect,
for the product's special place in modern culture, even if it
wasn't exactly what the company intended. Here are several that
meet that standard.
</P>
<P>
   Frank J. Zamboni &AMP; Co. of Paramount, Calif. (www.zamboni.com),
now in its 51st year, acknowledges the skating fans who have grown
to love its efficient, boxy ice-resurfacing machines, which have a
top speed of 9 mph, according to the trivia page. Oh, yes, a trivia
page. Also, an online Pro Shop offering shirts, jackets, coin banks
and _ this is truly inspired _ a pewter Zamboni Monopoly token.
</P>
<P>
   The Zamboni Story takes the reader back to the Iceland skating
rink in Paramount, built in 1939 by Zamboni and his brother,
Lawrence. It is still operating, the site notes. ``In fact, it's
not unusual to see Zambonis driving down the neighborhood streets
on their way to be tested at Iceland,'' the site says, suggesting
yet another Southern California tourist attraction. There are
pictures of early machines and the immortal No. 1, the Model A of
1949, which has been restored. Zamboni No. 2 caught the eye of
Sonja Henie, who bought it for her traveling ice show in 1950, and
immortality was on its way.
</P>
<P>
   The Makin' Ice page has a schematic showing how a Zamboni works.
There are snapshots showing Zambonis with Snoopy, at the Boston
Garden, at the Winter Olympics, in Japan and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   If you had to pick a single site devoted to the American fad, it
would be hard to top the Wham-O Inc. page (www.wham-o.com). Founded
in California by Arthur Melin and Richard Knerr, the company was
named for the sound made by its slingshot, and for a while in the
1950s and '60s, it was the Microsoft of novelty producers.
Frisbees. Hula Hoops. Superballs. Do-It-Yourself $119 fallout
shelters. Chubby Checker Limbo sets.
</P>
<P>
   Wham-O's history page is a hoot. When Melin traveled to Africa
in the 1960s, it says, he encountered a fish that laid its eggs in
the mud during the dry season; when the rains came, the eggs
hatched. The Web site says: ``Ah-ha, thought Melin. Sell chunks of
mud, add water, and voila, instant aquarium. Millions of dollars of
orders for Instant Fish were taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, the fish brought back to America wouldn't mate,
so no fish eggs, no mud and the end of a great idea.''
</P>
<P>
   Frisbee has its own historical time line, starting in the 1920s,
when Yale students were throwing pie tins from Frisbie Pie Co. of
Bridgeport, Conn. There is a link to an article in Scientific
American magazine on the aerodynamics of the Frisbee.
</P>
<P>
   A private tribute site honoring the Superball, and not
affiliated with Wham-O, is www.superballs.com. It includes an
extensive history and even reprints the 1966 patent by the
inventor, a chemist named Norman H. Stingley.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the story of chewing gum, on the site of William
Wrigley Jr. Co. of Chicago (www.wrigley.com). The history starts
off with the ancient Greeks and the mastic tree; North American
Indians and spruce gum; and chicle, from the latex juice of the
sapodilla tree. There is some corporate back-patting involving the
psychological satisfaction of chewing, but we do learn that Wrigley
originally offered his gum as premiums for boxes of baking soda and
that his first two gum brands were Lotta and Vassar. A page notes
that the farmland required to grow mint for Wrigley totals 53
square miles.
</P>
<P>
   Moving from underneath the school desk to its top, Binney &AMP;
Smith's Crayola site (www.crayola.com) is user- , parent- and
teacher-friendly. In addition to the usual corporate information
and helpful hints (stain removal is one of them), there is an
online tour of the Crayola Factory museum in Easton, Pa., and a
wide array of craft and entertainment projects. An online feature
lets children print out their own cards and posters to color.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0229 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4289 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-NURSEBETTY-REVIE     09-06 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-NURSEBETTY-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``NURSE BETTY'' IS PROOF THAT ``FARGO'' STILL EXERTS INFLUENCE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   For several of the artists involved, ``Nurse Betty'' is a film
of firsts. It features star Morgan Freeman's first on-screen kiss,
for one thing. And for director Neil LaBute, whose two previous
dialogue- and idea-driven movies betrayed his origins as a
playwright, it is his first film with gunfire, physical violence
and extensive scenes set outdoors with moving cameras, automobiles
and the rest.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first movie LaBute has made that he didn't also write.
(Another first, it is the work of two never-before-produced
screenwriters.)
</P>
<P>
   For the audience, ``Nurse Betty'' isn't quite so singular an
experience.
</P>
<P>
   In its commingling of violence, drama and mordant, offbeat
humor, it recalls ``Fargo,'' the Coen brothers movie of 1996. The
success of that film and ``To Die For'' in 1995 sparked a small
revival of dark comedies, including ``The Opposite of Sex,''
``Happiness,'' ``Home Fries'' and ``Very Bad Things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nurse Betty'' is proof that ``Fargo'' still is exerting a
not-altogether-unwelcome influence.
</P>
<P>
   Still, LaBute is less sure with this sort of material than are
the Coen brothers.
</P>
<P>
   This is understandable. ``Nurse Betty'' is a bigger movie than
he is used to making, with more moving parts. The budget is about
800 times the $25,000 LaBute spent on ``In the Company of Men,''
his first movie. (``Your Friends and Neighbors'' cost $4 million.)
</P>
<P>
   Both of his previous films drew upon the work of other plays,
most notably Restoration comedies and the early work of David
Mamet, and they bear strong similarities to the plays that LaBute
has written for the stage. LaBute's voice as a writer and filmmaker
came through in undiluted form in those movies. The violence in
those movies was all psychological.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview last year, he said he'd continue to make ``Neil
LaBute movies,'' but he will alternate them with films like this
one that stretch him and broaden his film vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Nurse Betty'' is any indication, these slightly more
commercial movies won't be mere digressions or artistic sellouts;
they'll be worth the wait, even if they aren't as distinctive or as
sure-footed as his more challenging personal projects.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Fargo,'' ``Nurse Betty'' is set, at least initially, in a
small Midwestern town of simple folk, and the action grows out of
men of dubious intelligence doing wrong and getting sucked in over
their heads in trouble. Both movies veer swiftly and easily between
gentle character-based humor and violence so unexpected and grisly
that we might not know quite how we're supposed to react.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Nurse Betty,'' at least, the violent jolt serves a purpose
beyond merely shocking the audience. Renee Zellweger as the title
character witnesses a gruesome murder. It is so horrific that she
not only blocks it from her mind, she temporarily enters a fantasy
world. She is a waitress when the movie begins, not a nurse. But
she starts to believe she is a character in her favorite soap
opera, ``A Reason to Love.''
</P>
<P>
   She sets out for Los Angeles, seeking the love of her life, Dr.
David Ravell (Greg Kinnear), not realizing that the man she seeks
is but an actor playing a role and that the TV hospital where he
practices doesn't exist. Nor does she realize that Freeman and
Chris Rock, the hit men whose dirty work sent her over the edge,
are on her tail.
</P>
<P>
   LaBute has toned down some of the later violence that was in his
shooting script, perhaps choosing to focus more on the development
of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman plays a hit man on the verge of retirement, a
thoughtful, well-read professional who takes pride in his work.
This was to be his last job, but the impetuousness of his partner
has caused complications.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as the two drive cross-country in search of Betty, he finds
himself falling in love with the woman he imagines her to be.
</P>
<P>
   Rock's character, it turns out, is as big a fan of ``A Reason to
Love'' as she is. But for the longest time, neither man realizes
how the TV show figures into their case. They think Betty is a
tough-as-nails ``femme fatale'' who is fleeing with valuable cargo
they were hired to retrieve.
</P>
<P>
   As a stand-up comedian, Rock can be smart and provocative, but
he's no actor. Time and again, he gives funny readings to lines
that, nevertheless, do not work precisely because funny readings
are all they are. There's sometimes a lag of maybe half a second
between his utterances (or, more accurately, his yelling of his
lines) and our comprehension. An actor could've made the readings
funny and expressive at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Zellweger is one of those actresses we sometimes wonder about.
Her performance as a Hasidic Jew in ``A Price Above Rubies'' was
unconvincing enough that it made her work in ``Jerry Maguire'' seem
like possibly a fluke. She's been good since then, but sometimes it
has appeared she's been hired mainly because she's so adorable when
she crinkles her eyes and pouts.
</P>
<P>
   She's adorable in ``Nurse Betty,'' too, but the adorableness and
all of her mannerisms are employed in the creation of a character
here _ they're not just disembodied traits. We like her. We care
about what happens to her.
</P>
<P>
   God looks after children and fools. In Los Angeles, Betty gets a
job, a place to stay and a friend to look after her, and then she
tracks down Dr. Ravell. Ravell, or the actor who plays him, is as
taken with her as we are.
</P>
<P>
   Before it is all over, the movie changes tone dramatically at
least once more; again the shift is unsettling. LaBute wants to
unsettle us, but at the same time the movie's denouement isn't laid
out as clearly as it ought to be. This raises questions about the
sureness of the director's hand.
</P>
<P>
   Just how much of that unsettledness we're feeling is the result
of artistic choice and how much of it is LaBute accidently striking
the wrong key?
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, it shouldn't matter. The movie is the movie,
accidents and all. And LaBute strikes enough of the right keys to
make you curious about the dramatic television series he says he's
working on for ABC and his upcoming film adaptation of the novel
``Possession,'' set in Victorian England. &QL; 
``Nurse Betty'' &QL; 
Starring: Renee Zellweger, Morgan Freeman, Chris Rock, Greg
Kinnear &QL; 
Director: Neil LaBute &QL; 
Screenwriters: John C. Richards and James Flamberg &QL; 
Rating: R for strong violence, pervasive language and a scene of
sexuality &QL; 
Grade: B &QL; 
XXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
