<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0230 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4290 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DIGITAL-IMAGING-N     09-06 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DIGITAL-IMAGING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW TECHNOLOGY IMPROVES DIGITAL IMAGING BY ADDRESSING LIGHT
LEVELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By ANNE EISENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The megapixel race has been the whole game in digital cameras
for the past two years, as the cameras have gone from 1 megapixel
or less to sharper, clearer images of nearly 4 megapixels.
</P>
<P>
   That's all about resolution. But another crucial aspect of
capturing a high-quality image has lagged far behind, and that is
dynamic range, the gradations of light and dark a digital camera
can capture so that details are not washed out by light or
concealed by shadows.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a new technology promises to increase the dynamic range
substantially, not just for digital still and video cameras, but
for virtually any imaging system, including those based on X-rays
and infrared radiation.
</P>
<P>
   The technology is significant not only for its promise to banish
underexposed or overexposed snapshots. It also has implications for
Web cameras, video surveillance, robotics, medical imaging and any
other system that uses images for measurements. Such systems, for
example, let doctors track changes in the size, color and shape of
lesions in the intestinal tract or let vehicle control systems
maintain proper distance between vehicles on the highways.
</P>
<P>
   The technology, a combination of software and hardware
modifications developed in the past two years by researchers led by
Shree Nayar, a professor of computer science at Columbia University
and head of the university's Computer Vision Laboratory. Nayar's
technology, which experts in the field say is simple but powerful,
increases the richness of detail a digital camera can provide.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Nayar demonstrated that when a digital camera that
measured about 8 bits or 256 levels of brightness at each pixel was
retrofitted with this technology, the 8-bit sensor extracted up to
12 bits of brightness value, thus increasing the dynamic range to
4,098 levels of brightness. By modifying a standard digital camera
with his technology Nayar has made it work in a far higher dynamic
range.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is important work that makes the task of image analysis
easier,'' said Berthold K.P. Horn, an expert in robot vision and a
professor of electrical engineering and computer science at the
Massachusetts Institute of Technology. ``It gives more accurate
data, and it is data that exists throughout the image, not washed
out in some areas.''
</P>
<P>
   With the new method, there is a small loss of resolution,
particularly in the very bright or very dark areas, but, Horn said,
``you have some image there, where before you had it totally
lost.''
</P>
<P>
   A description of the basic system was presented at the IEEE
Conference on Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition. Tomoo
Mitsunaga, a Sony scientist who is visiting at Columbia, is
co-author of the paper with Nayar. Further work extending the
algorithms and applying them in color photography was done by Nayar
and Srinivasa Narasimhan, a graduate student at Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   The Columbia University team's innovations are quite different
from traditional software that can, for instance, enhance parts of
an image by brightening it slightly. For such systems to work, the
initial information on the image must already exist. But, Nayar
said, ``Areas that are too saturated or too dark inherently lack
information. No amount of post-processing can recreate scene
details that were never captured to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Nayar's solution to over- or undersaturated areas of light has
two parts: hardware and software. In conventional digital camera
chips, all the pixels collect light equally. Nayar's hardware
solution, by contrast, involves changing the amount of light
received at each pixel, using, for instance, a mask that varies the
exposure of neighboring pixels.
</P>
<P>
   The differing exposures are repeated over the entire array of
pixels, in effect, building multiple exposures into a single image.
After Nayar's image is collected and stored, special software
reconstructs an image with a wide range of brightness variations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key insight here is that even if one pixel is saturated,
it's likely a nearby pixel will still be producing meaningful
brightness,'' Nayar said, just as another pixel might have zero
brightness because of low exposure, but a nearby one have some data
on brightness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This solution is a clever idea,'' said Pietro Perone, a
professor of electrical engineering at the California Institute of
Technology and a specialist in computational vision. Perone said
there was some photon loss in retrofitting the camera, as the mask
in front of the sensor was, like sunglasses, darkening the light.
An ideal system, one designed from scratch, he said, would have
different-size pixels to avoid wasting photons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market will choose between retrofitted standard sensors
and some photon loss, or new sensors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The real world has enormous fluctuations in brightness that have
long posed problems for scientists working with computer images.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nayar's system provides a natural, simple solution to a
serious historical problem,'' said Jitendra Malik, professor of
computer science at the University of California in Berkeley, and a
specialist in computer vision. ``The problem of saturated light
outdoors is obvious, but even indoors, with light streaming in the
windows you sacrifice either the bright or the dark regions. This
technology recovers the information in those regions.''
</P>
<P>
   Computer vision, or machine vision, as it is also called, is
expected to have many outdoor uses, like car-mounted cameras that
use image data to maintain a fixed distance from another vehicle,
eliminating the brake-tapping of present versions of cruise
control.
</P>
<P>
   The new technology also promises help in medical applications.
Takeo Kanade, a professor and head of the robotics institute at
Carnegie Mellon University who has experience with laproscopic
techniques where a tiny camera is inserted in the body, explained
the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The camera doesn't have sufficient dynamic range for the
bright shiny portions that tend to be saturated with light, and for
the darker fields which can't be seen,'' Kanade said. Today,
laproscopic images of lesions are visually analyzed by doctors.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future,'' Kanade said, the computer will look to
measure the size, shape, and color of the lesion, but right now the
camera is not good enough as a measurement device.''
</P>
<P>
   Nayar is the holder of a number of patents in computer vision,
and is the inventor of the Omnicamera, a 360 degree camera that
allows internet or television viewers to see images in all
directions simultaneously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
