<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Sept. 7 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   TIRE-RECALL (Washington) _ Faced with growing evidence that
Bridgestone/Firestone and possibly Ford Motor Co. knew about tire
problems for years and did nothing, Republican and Democratic
members of Congress began hearings on the issue Wednesday by
calling for more money for safety regulators and stiffer penalties
for violators. By Keith Bradsher and Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT31,32.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CLINTON (United Nations) _ President Clinton on Wednesday
told the largest gathering of world leaders in history that the
United Nations must reconfigure itself to deal with a world in
which there are ``fewer wars between nations, but more wars within
them.'' With the energy of a man who sees his moment on the world
stage quickly slipping away, he immediately used the Millennium
Summit meeting here to take a last stab at many of the issues that
have defied resolution during his presidency. He tried to fend off
a proposal from Russian president Vladimir Putin that would lead to
a demilitarization of outer space _ an effort by Putin to put an
end to American talk of a national missile defense _ and met with
the Palestinian leader, Yasser Arafat, and Israeli Prime Minister
Ehud Barak in one last effort to rescue the Middle East peace
process. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT16,17,20,22,23,24.
</P>
<P>
   NY-BRICK-KILLING (New York) _ The owner of a Queens Chinese
restaurant who was bludgeoned to death during a delivery last
weekend was killed by one of five teen-agers who intended to steal
the food, law enforcement authorities said Wednesday. The
teen-agers called in an order to the restaurant and lured the
victim to an abandoned home, the police said. The teenagers grabbed
the food from the owner, who often made deliveries himself, and
then one of them hit him on the head with a brick and killed him,
the authorities said. By David Barstow and Sarah Kershaw.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MAFIA-ARRESTS (New York) _ The Manhattan district attorney
Wednesday charged 38 union officials, contractors and reputed
mobsters with bribery, bid-rigging or other racketeering schemes
that siphoned millions of dollars from public and private building
projects throughout the city over the last two years. By William K.
Rashbaum.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-ECON (Cleveland) _ Vice President Al Gore on Wednesday
offered his economic vision for the future, a vision that hinges on
optimistic fiscal forecasts that, if they held, would produce many
of the results that he described as his goals. By Katharine Q.
Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT1,2,3.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Washington) _ An update on the Bush campaign.
Byline TK.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-INDIANS-CANNIBALS (Undated) _ Scientists have found what
they say is the first direct evidence of cannibalism among
prehistoric Indians in the American Southwest, belying the image of
these people as steadfastly peaceful farmers and perhaps reigniting
controversy over whether ancestral Indians ever made a practice of
eating human flesh. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
