<HEADER>
A4293 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BELGIUM-ROYALS-2TA     09-06 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BELGIUM-ROYALS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGIUM'S `COOL' ROYAL COUPLE COMING TO NEW YORK TO PROMOTE THEIR
COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS NOTE: The complete text of the New York Times interview with
Prince Philippe and Princess Mathilde of Belgium is available from
The New York Times on the Web: www.nytimes.com) 
 By GLENN COLLINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The royals are coming.
</P>
<P>
   No, no, not the poor old British crown prince, still
overshadowed by the tragic legacy of Diana, Princess of Wales. Nor
any of his relatives, like that fellow who flies the helicopter and
his former lady who does the weight-loss thing.
</P>
<P>
   No, New York is getting the other ones, the fabulously cool new
royals: the handsome Crown Prince Philippe of Belgium and his
ravishing Princess Mathilde, the fairy-tale couple that have
monopolized magazine covers and glossy photo spreads throughout
Europe. Their nuptials on Dec. 4 were trumpeted as the last royal
wedding of the millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Their mission is nothing less than to take New York City by
storm, winning hearts, minds, media and, more important, market
share.
</P>
<P>
   And so, on Saturday, just when New York is once again a
Millennium Summit-free zone, the prince and princess will kick off
their whirlwind five-day visit. A plane full of European reporters
and news crews will arrive at Kennedy International Airport with
the royal delegation to cover the tour, which includes stops at the
United Nations, the World Trade Center, the Metropolitan Museum of
Art and even a supermarket.
</P>
<P>
   The joint visit is unprecedented, given the traditional
protectiveness of the royal household. And the great to-do over the
arrival is even more unusual given that the royals hail from the
tiny, distant nation of Belgium, which to many New Yorkers is
simply the country the waffles come from.
</P>
<P>
   But that stubbornly self-deprecating nation of 10 million people
by the North Sea, in an area scarcely larger than New Jersey, has
enjoyed an extraordinary visibility in New York City of late. The
effusion of Belgianophilia includes eateries like Markt, Petite
Abeille and Le Pain Quotidien, proliferating in a restaurant
district in Manhattan that some call Little Belgium. Not to mention
the explosion of interest in Belgian beers, chocolates,
double-fried potatoes and deconstructivist fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all this, ``Belgium is a well-kept secret that deserves
to be better known by many more Americans,'' the prince said in the
couple's first joint written interview.
</P>
<P>
   Ingeborg Kristoffersen, the Belgian consul general in New York,
said the royal visit ``is a way to bring attention to the variety
and quality of things Belgian.''
</P>
<P>
   One indication of the importance of the visit was the interview
with the prince and princess, which ``is quite extraordinary,''
said Philippe Gyhsens, a royal-watching reporter for Belgium's
largest newspaper, Hetlaatste Nieuws, in Brussels. ``Journalists
are not allowed to ask questions of the prince or princess.''
</P>
<P>
   But the symbolic visit of the future monarch of Belgium is
decidedly serious in a nation where the constitutional monarchy
``is the only institution holding the country together,'' said Luc
Sante, the Belgian-born writer who is a visiting professor at Bard
College. He referred to the disparate, oft-fussing population of
Dutch-speaking Flemings and French-speaking Walloons.
</P>
<P>
   The ``working visit,'' as the prince termed it, is also a
long-sought validation for American importers of Belgian products,
who traversed a desert of indifference for decades before the
current Belgian boom. The advent of the royals is nothing less than
``a culmination, coming at a very fortuitous time,'' said Don
Fineberg, co-founder of Vanberg &AMP; DeWulf of Cooperstown, an
importer of Belgian specialty beers.
</P>
<P>
   But are they attractive enough to bring off a Belgian conquest?
Well, though he drives a Carrera 911 Porsche, studied at Oxford and
Stanford Universities, leads trade missions and flies F-16s, Prince
Philippe, the 40-year-old heir to the Belgian throne, does have his
Prince Charles-ish aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Belgians had nearly given up on the prince, a perennial
bachelor, until he stunned the nation by announcing the royal
wedding from out of the blue _ after a secret three-year courtship
_ last fall. He is reported to be reticent, even, well, ``dull,''
as Ghysens, the royal-watcher, put it.
</P>
<P>
   It is a reputation that ``I hope is unjustified,'' said the
prince, adding: ``I am not the best judge in this matter. You
should ask my wife.'' The princess did not touch on this point in
her interview.
</P>
<P>
   Princess Mathilde, a friendly, radiant 27-year-old, has been
dubbed the ``Queen of Hearts'' by the French magazine Paris-Match.
She resembles the model Claudia Schiffer and traces her
aristocratic lineage back to the 13th century. She is destined to
become the 170-year-old country's first Belgian-born queen (royal
predecessors have come from France, Italy, Spain and Sweden). So
far, she can do no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally we have a gorgeous princess, and some glitter and
glamour,'' Ghysens said. ``Now we finally have an international
visiting card.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Surprising in a nation known for its reserve, she was greeted
with a chant of ``Mathilde, Mathilde, Mathilde'' from thousands of
Belgians during the wedding. ``It was a very private moment for the
prince and me, and we were glad that we could share it with the
Belgian people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mathilde d'Udekem d'Acoz started her own speech-therapy practice
at the age of 22 in Brussels. She is currently working toward a
degree in psychology. Despite the royal fish bowl, the princess
said, ``I intend to continue my studies, as I am doing my finals
next year.'' But she acknowledged, ``As you can imagine, it will be
very difficult for me to work as a speech therapist as I did
before.''
</P>
<P>
   For the princess, who once lived in Washington for three months,
the return to America is welcome because ``I really enjoyed my stay
here,'' she said. When asked if she found it difficult to define
the role of princess in the year 2000, she agreed that the role was
challenging, but said that ``my support of my husband is of utmost
importance to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The high point of her activities is likely to be an
attention-focusing visit to Abraham House, a seven-year-old halfway
home in the South Bronx founded and run by Sister Simone Ponnet, a
Belgian nun who works as a chaplain at Rikers Island.
</P>
<P>
   The prince and princess _ who are to be addressed
``monseigneur'' and ``madame,'' don't you know _ will attend 17
major events from Saturday until their departure on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The giddy whirl _ graced on occasion by Prime Minister Guy
Verhofstadt of Belgium _ will range from a glittering dinner
fund-raiser for the Belgian-American Chamber of Commerce at the
Metropolitan Club to yes, a supermarket promotion: the royals will
swoop down on the D'Agostino supermarket at 23rd Street and Eighth
Avenue to kick off a celebration of Belgian products at 24
D'Agostino stores.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a Wall Street power breakfast (followed, of
course, by the ringing of the bell by the prince to launch trading
on the New York Stock Exchange). There will be global trade
seminars and presentations for business leaders at the World Trade
Center to sell the idea that Belgium is about biotechnology as well
as mussels and frites.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably the royals will, by example, quash the base rumors
that Belgian beer makers are disappointed that they don't publicly
drink more of the national brew. ``I want to reassure you that both
Princess Mathilde and myself are fond of Belgian beer,'' said the
prince, ``and we drink it often.''
</P>
<P>
   Belgian living in New York will also be received at Markt, the
Belgian bistro on 14th Street and Ninth Avenue. Young Belgian
artists, academics and entrepreneurs will be feted at Le Pain
Quotidien in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the advent of the royals in New York is viewed by
some expatriates as fair Belgian retribution. ``Celebrities, the
modern kings, have become one of America's most important export
products,'' said Tom Ronse, an artist who is one of the
metropolitan area's 8,000 Belgians.
</P>
<P>
   It is no exaggeration to say that the European press gushed,
swooned and curtsied at the couple's picture-perfect December
wedding, attended by some 45,000 Belgians and, literally, the
crowned heads of Europe. A half-dozen Belgian television outlets
offered as much as 15 hours of live coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Because they are Belgians, afterward some grumbled at the $1
million of taxpayers' money spent on the wedding for appointments
that included a 1,000-person security detail, a host of motorcycle
police and an F-16 fighter fly-by of the palace.
</P>
<P>
   But so great was the swell of national optimism that
commentators said the ``Mathilde Factor'' helped to distract
attention from a series of national scandals that questioned
Belgians' faith in the country's policies, its judiciary and its
political system, ranging from a dioxin food scare to a notorious
pedophile-and-murder case bungled by Belgian detectives.
</P>
<P>
   It also caused consternation in the royal household, European
journalists said, because Prince Philippe, not unlike Prince
Charles, was being upstaged by his glamorous bride.
</P>
<P>
   Annually Belgian taxpayers spend more than $8 million to support
their monarchy, only a 10th of what the British annually pay for
their royals. If the queen in England, as head of the Commonwealth
and the Church of England, has more designated power, in Belgium
the king appoints the new government and assumes a crucial unifying
function.
</P>
<P>
   ``If one of the royals were to favor the Flemish or the French,
chaos would break out,'' said Sante, the Belgian writer who
immigrated to the United States at 5 and described his life in
``The Factory of Facts'' (Pantheon Books, 1998).
</P>
<P>
   But the prince said there was ``a new spirit in the country,''
an improvement ``in the relations between the Flemish and the
Walloons.''
</P>
<P>
   That new spirit could have something to do with Princess
Mathilde, who is, herself, a balanced ticket. The ancestors of the
princess come from Flemish-speaking Flanders to the north, but she
grew up in French-speaking Wallonia to the south, and lived in
bilingual Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, the princess is trying to tone down
``Mathildemania.'' ``Maybe I will not be able to fulfill all
expectations,'' she said humbly, ``but I will surely do my
utmost.''
</P>
<P>
   The prince's fortitude and his bride's charisma may soon be put
to the test: King Albert II, Philippe's 66-year-old father, who had
already undergone painful back surgery, had quadruple bypass heart
surgery in April, giving rise to speculation that he will soon step
down from the throne.
</P>
<P>
   So, will America fall prey to rampant Belgianism? Some
expatriates are amused at the very presumption. ``Why is there this
incredible fascination with royalty?'' asked Jacqueline Goossens,
who lives in Stapleton, Staten Island, and files weekly reports on
life in the city for two Belgian publications, De Morgen and Knack.
``I am flabbergasted that modern people in this day and age are
interested in them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
