<HEADER>
A4298 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-BELLSOUTH0907-COX     09-06 0439
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELLSOUTH0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BellSouth promotes Harris to lead consumer services unit
 &HT;    By Michael E. Kanell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - BellSouth has promoted Isaiah Harris Jr. to president
of its consumer services unit, replacing Sue McLaughlin, who has
resigned effective Sept. 15.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who has been vice president for finances, will take
responsibility for an 8,500-person group that is the core of the
$26 billion-a-year company.
</P>
<P>
   With 14.5 million customers, the unit handles local phone and
customer service in nine states. On that turf, BellSouth still has
dominance, but is facing increasing competition during a time of
technology change in which the Internet is ever-more important.
</P>
<P>
   The company also announced that Pat Shannon, the company's
principal accounting officer, will take on Harris' former duties.
However, no one will step into Harris' job title as vice president
for finances.
</P>
<P>
   Harris praised the management team assembled by McLaughlin.
``The challenges will be steep, but they are not insurmountable,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris came to BellSouth from SuperValu, a wholesaler and
retailer of food, and before that worked for 13 years with Peat
Marwick Main &AMP; Co. While at Peat Marwick, he played eight seasons
of professional football as a wide receiver with the St. Louis
Cardinals and New Orleans Saints.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement from the company, McLaughlin left ``to
pursue other directions.'' McLaughlin, who was traveling and
unavailable for comment, was among the top-ranking female
executives at BellSouth. Harris is among the highest ranking blacks
at BellSouth.
</P>
<P>
   McLaughlin came to BellSouth less than three years ago from
Kodak as part of BellSouth's efforts to pump up its marketing
efforts for the new age of competition. During her tenure,
BellSouth continued its streak of victories in the annual
competition among local phone companies judged by consulting
company J.D. Power &AMP; Associates. But after four straight
first-place finishes, BellSouth this year placed fifth, just behind
Bell Atlantic. The winner was Southern New England Telephone. In
general, customer satisfaction has declined, said J.D. Power in the
August 8 announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a goal to win that,'' Harris said. ``There is no
reason in my mind why we cannot. I think it's a matter of focus. I
think it's a matter of resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, who had previously reported to chief financial officer
Ron Dykes, will now report to Richard A. Anderson, president of
BellSouth Customer Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
