<HEADER>
A4299 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-OPPORTUNISTS-REV     09-06 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-OPPORTUNISTS-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``THE OPPORTUNISTS'' IS QUIETLY PLEASING IN ITS OWN, MODEST WAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LOUIS B. PARKS 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
Christopher Walken and the film ``The Opportunists'' are a perfect
match.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walken reigns as master of the minimalist performance _ this is
a compliment _ and ``The Opportunists,'' as written and directed by
Myles Connell, avoids excess and size at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   That may well leave viewers, arriving for a crime caper,
surprised to realize they've stumbled into a mild, modest, almost
arty character study. They'll be even more surprised, however, when
the ending of this movie proves to be a lot different than the
first 75 minutes indicated.
</P>
<P>
   Walken plays Victor Kelly, who lives in a modest Brooklyn house
with his daughter. Before we learn Victor's past, Connell carefully
reveals him as a guy who lovingly cares for an elderly aunt. He
also cares for an old Buick Riviera _ it turns out he is repairing
it for a police acquaintance to earn a few extra bucks.
</P>
<P>
   Victor lives with a local bar owner, Sally (Cyndi Lauper), who's
fond of him in a quiet, unextravagant way.
</P>
<P>
   A young Irish relative, Michael (Peter MacDonald), shows up at
the door, eager to meet his American cousins. Victor's never heard
of Michael, but when his daughter says the youth's story checks
out, Victor puts him up until Michael can find a job.
</P>
<P>
   This mellow character development goes on so long we are lulled
into surprise when something happens to the Riviera.
</P>
<P>
   Victor, struggling to pay rent and other debts, needed that
money. Now Victor is susceptible when Michael and a local man
(Donal Logue of ``The Tao of Steve'') come to him, deferentially
but insistently, with the idea for a crime. Victor was a
safecracker before a stretch in prison made him famous in his
neighborhood, ended his marriage and made him vow to go straight.
</P>
<P>
   Connell has already established that we are not in for a
happy-go-lucky crime caper in which the hero merrily pulls off a
slick job amid exciting chases and adventures. Now the sober tone
threatens to turn gloomy. The prospect of a triumphant outcome for
Victor and associates seems remote, especially since Michael is not
who he pretends to be.
</P>
<P>
   The format may be classic film noir _ the imperfect but
basically likable protagonist unwillingly trapped into a crime,
with the web of fate tightening toward almost certain doom. But
Connell, showing admirable patience and restraint in his feature
film debut, does not play it that way.
</P>
<P>
   The film ignores traditional crime film beats and homages,
treating all the characters as ordinary people and avoiding
dramatic music or suspense scenes, even in the heist. When a
potentially melodramatic situation arises, Connelly deftly
sidesteps into something much more likely (and, some will feel,
more mundane).
</P>
<P>
   That does not prepare us for the ending. Played in the same
minimalist tone, it nevertheless takes the film in a completely
unexpected direction. Frankly, Connell employs considerable pixie
dust to do this, but by maintaining the same understated pace and
feel, he pulls it off with surprising dexterity.
</P>
<P>
   The film's resolution is satisfying and does not seem overly
dishonest. Saying more would be, well, criminal.
</P>
<P>
   Walken, bless him, never works to make Victor charming or cool,
but has us pulling for him, anyway. The film and his performance
are flawlessly wedded: They understand each other perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   The movie is hardly a must-see, and ``Mission: Impossible'' fans
would probably rather watch paint dry, but it's sneakily involving
and quietly pleasing in its own, modest way. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The Opportunists'' &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; Starring: Christopher Walken, Peter McDonald, Cyndi Lauper, Donal
Logue &QL; 
Screenwriter and director: Myles Connell &QL; 
Not rated, but has occasional strong language. &QL; 
Running time: 89 min. &QL; 
Grade: C+ &QL; 
X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4300 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-UGLY-TECH-2NDTAKE     09-06 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-UGLY-TECH-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: phone towers. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Property values play a big role, too. The Dunn Foundation, in
its research on utility lines, has found that real estate prices
increase in places where lines have been buried. Kreines has seen
real estate values drop when cell phone towers have been installed
nearby. In one case in Ho Ho Kus, N.J., he said, a tax assessor
determined that the aggregated value of property near a cell phone
tower would drop as much as $660,000.
</P>
<P>
   Telecommunications companies say they are trying to balance two
opposing desires: Cellular customers want clearer calls, and
property owners want unobstructed views. But the companies say they
try to be sensitive to aesthetics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the best we can to keep our facilities from looking
unsightly,'' said Tracey Kennedy, a spokeswoman for Verizon, which
provides wireless and conventional telephone service. ``The last
thing you want,'' she said, ``are your constituents to be up in
arms about their surroundings.''
</P>
<P>
   Some communities have found that companies are responsive to
their requests. Several have asked cell phone companies to install
cell sites on top of light poles or on buildings where they are
less noticeable. And camouflaging is becoming more popular for the
sites. Some cell phone companies have made cell phone towers look
like pine trees, and in Arizona and California, cell sites that
look like giant saguaro cactuses rise 35 feet above the desert.
</P>
<P>
   When compromises cannot be reached, battles erupt. Search the
Internet for ``cell phone towers,'' and you will find dozens of Web
sites that have been posted by people protesting the erection of
towers that block their views.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, wireless companies have sued municipalities for
the right to go forward with their plans. In others, local
governments have sued to prevent construction. Kreines lists about
15 cases on his Web site (www.planwireless.com).
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, most cell-site lawsuits were won by the
telecommunications companies. But some observers say that is
changing as municipalities realize that they can place limits on
construction and still stay within the law.
</P>
<P>
   For example, in a case last year against Albemarle County in
Virginia, the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals ruled in favor of
the county. The county's board of supervisors had denied an
application filed by 360(degree)Communications, a company that
wanted to install a 100-foot tower on a ridge called Dudley
Mountain. The company sued, but the appeals court ruled that the
denial of that single tower did not have the effect of prohibiting
the provision of wireless services. The county board, for example,
might someday permit other towers or poles in other places.
</P>
<P>
   Getting rid of ugly utility lines may be a tougher fight. Cities
and property owners are usually expected to cover the costs of
taking down the wires and burying them, a practice known as
``undergrounding.'' The cost to communities can run from $500,000
to $3 million per mile, said Dan Weaver, an urban planner who
coordinates a San Francisco campaign to bury utility wires.
</P>
<P>
   Technical challenges contribute to the high costs, said Dave
Gordon, a manager for American Electric Power. Construction crews,
for example, must avoid things like water and sewer lines when they
excavate. And while underground wires are protected from falling
trees or high winds, Gordon said, they are often harder and more
expensive to repair when something does go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But many cities and towns argue that the benefits of putting
wires underground outweigh the disadvantages. Planners show
photographs of cities in the early 20th century, when a haphazard
sprawl of telephone and electrical cables crisscrossed every
street. In new suburban developments, most developers do not even
consider installing above-ground lines.
</P>
<P>
   At least nine states have granted municipalities the authority
to create special districts that could tax residents to cover those
costs, according to the Dunn Foundation. In California, for
example, a surcharge is added to utility bills to pay for burying
wires in areas where landowners are also willing to pay for land
surveys, connection fees, new street lighting and the cost of
administering the special districts. Those services, Weaver said,
can cost residents as much as $7,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   But those who oppose unsightly towers and overhead wires say
that is not enough. The California plan does not work, Weaver said,
because the areas that have the most overhead wires are usually
populated by residents on low or fixed incomes, who are generally
unable to afford to pay to bury the wires.
</P>
<P>
   ``More and more people are getting upset because undergrounding
just never happens,'' Weaver said. The joke in San Francisco, he
added, is that some areas are on a ``300-year undergrounding
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Weaver is researching new ways to pay for putting wires
underground. One possibility, he said, is to charge a fee to those
buying and selling property in areas where wires are still hanging
overhead. That is no different, he said, from the fees that are
typically included in the cost of houses in new developments where
wires are buried.
</P>
<P>
   Other options, Youngken said, include trying to hide the lines
above ground.
</P>
<P>
   As he continued his recent drive through the suburbs of Rhode
Island, he described some of those efforts. Some cash-strapped
towns have managed to move the wires to alleys or have requested
heavy-duty wire that can be strung through tree branches. At the
very least, he said, communities should require utility companies
to get rid of unnecessary poles.
</P>
<P>
   As Youngken talked, he passed a sign for Newport, R.I., which
recently put some of its utility lines underground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now look,'' he said, pointing at the scenery whizzing by. The
poles suddenly disappeared, and nothing but grassy lawns sloped
down to a tranquil waterfront on the left side of the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a difference,'' he said. ``Isn't it amazing?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1851EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
