<SLUG> BC-CITIGROUP-AFC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITIGROUP BUYS TEXAS LENDING COMPANY FOR $31.1 BILLION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT BERNARD NELSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Citigroup Inc. turned its voracious appetite on Associates First
Capital Corp. Wednesday, gobbling up the Texas-based lending
company in a deal valued at $31.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Citigroup is already the largest credit card lender in the
world, the largest bank holding company in the United States, and a
leader in brokerage and insurance services.
</P>
<P>
   AFC is no slouch, either. With revenues of $7.1 billion in the
first half of the year, it is the biggest publicly traded American
company focused on loaning money to consumers. It is also the
fifth-largest consumer-lending firm in Japan, and has 700,000
customers in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citigroup needs to do acquisitions like this if it wants to
keep growing at a 15 percent clip,'' said Dick Bove, an analyst who
covers both companies for Raymond James &AMP; Associates in St.
Petersburg, Fla. ``Plus, it gets a big boost internationally and
widens its lead as the biggest card lender in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   AFC was spun off from Ford Motor Co. in 1998. If the deal is
approved, it will join a stable of businesses that includes
Citibank, Salomon Smith Barney, and Travelers Property Casualty.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for AFC shareholders to receive 0.7334 shares of
Citigroup stock for each AFC share they own. All told, AFC
investors will get $42.49 per share _ a 52 percent premium over
Tuesday's closing price.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, AFC shares skyrocketed on the news, gaining $10.63
to close at $38.63. Citigroup shares, meanwhile, fell $2.56 to
close at $55. In both cases, trading volume was far heavier than
normal.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call, Citigroup chief executive Sanford Weill
said the move would pay off in the long term for his company's
investors, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The acquisition) increases the percent of our income that is
recurring and predictable, ignites what we want to do
internationally in our consumer franchise, and at the same time
adds 10 cents to earnings,'' Weill said.
</P>
<P>
   Weill said Citigroup will take a charge against earnings of $600
million to $700 million to pay for the AFC purchase. The move, he
said also would yield more benefits when the economic-induced boom
on Wall Street starts to slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumer finance has done better in recessionary periods over
the past 25 years,'' he said. ``It happens to be something all of
us up here know something about.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement Wednesday, Citigroup and AFC said the agreement
would be consumated using the controversial pooling-of-interests
method of accounting. That way, Citigroup doesn't have to subtract
the so-called merger premium _ the amount above AFC's book value
that it paid _ from earnings in future quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board has proposed a rule
change that would make pooling of interests accounting illegal
starting next year. Instead, the bean-counting organization wants
corporations to use purchase accounting and take a charge on their
reported earnings as the premium value declines.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of such details, buying consumer finance companies
whose stocks are trading cheaply and combining them with other
businesses has been Weill's strategy for three decades. He built
Travelers Group _ the insurer, brokerage, and consumer finance
conglomerate that merged with Citicorp in 1998 _ that way.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of 1999, Citigroup shares have gained 136
percent, trouncing money-center banks such as Chase Manhattan Corp.
and topping some securities firms including Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   ``Citi has taken the tack that bigger is better, and so far it
has proven to be right: Earnings have consistently been
increasing,'' said Daniel Bandi, a money manager at National City
Investment Management, whose fund has about 500,000 Citigroup
shares.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Wire service information was used to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
