<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMYPICKS-MOVIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT WILL WIN _ AND WHAT SHOULD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So it's not the Oscars. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or the Grammys. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Or even the MTV Movie Awards, for that matter. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the standard line these days is that the Emmys _ the
52nd version of which airs Sunday on ABC _ may be of questionable
value and status. But, hey, we love it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So we'll fearlessly handicap the major categories, from best
actor in a drama to best actress in a comedy.
</P>
<P>
   First up: Outstanding TV movie
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``Annie,'' ABC; ``If These Walls Could Talk 2,'' HBO;
``Introducing Dorothy Dandridge,'' HBO; ``Oprah Winfrey Presents:
Tuesdays With Morrie,'' ABC; ``RKO 281,'' HBO
</P>
<P>
   The Buzz: HBO is Tiger Woods in this category, winning seven
years running without even breaking a sweat, and the networks are
simply sick to death of it. ABC is placing substantial bets on
``Tuesdays With Morrie,'' which makes sense, considering that there
are at least a half-dozen other movies that could've adequately
replaced the musical ``Annie'' on this slate. (We can start with
``Freedom Song,'' a dignified telling of what happened when the
civil rights movement came to a small Southern town.) ``Introducing
Dorothy Dandridge,'' a sentimental look at the tragic life of the
late film actress, won a Golden Globe for its star, Halle Berry.
But that's pretty much what you'd expect from the voting foreign
press corps, which wanted to see Berry sashay up to the podium.
``If These Walls Could Talk 2,'' which explored the lesbian
experience in America, is the longest of shots in the category.
</P>
<P>
   What will win: ``RKO 281,'' the docudrama about the making of
``Citizen Kane.'' It offered a fresh, smart spin on a movie that
many Emmy voters probably consider the best ever.
</P>
<P>
   What should win: ``RKO 281.'' Because it offered a fresh, smart
spin on a movie that continues to fascinate.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding miniseries
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: ``Arabian Nights,'' ABC; ``The Beach Boys: An American
Family,'' ABC; ``The Corner,'' HBO; ``Jesus,'' CBS; ``P.T.
Barnum,'' A&AMP;E.
</P>
<P>
   The Buzz: ``The Corner,'' a gritty look into drug use, is too
dark and too much of a downer. Voters were probably so surprised
that ``Jesus'' wasn't badly botched like most other network
biblical undertakings that it appeared better than it actually was.
``Arabian Nights'' has that Emmy flavor _ big, expensive, colorful.
The dark horse here is ``P.T. Barnum.''
</P>
<P>
   What will win: ``Arabian Nights.''
</P>
<P>
   What should win: ``The Corner.'' Well-crafted, well written,
well executed, painfully honest. An important portrayal that could
have easily passed as a documentary or docudrama. That it depicted
a real-life neighborhood only strengthens its cause. Losing will
certainly add to the travesty, since the lead actors, Khandi
Alexander and T.K. Carter, whose performances were the best of the
year on TV, weren't even nominated.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
