<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMYPICKS-SUPPORTINGACTRESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL WIN _ AND WHO SHOULD
</HEADLINE>
  (for use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Supporting players rarely get the attention they deserve, so
we're proud to sing their praises. Which isn't to say that everyone
nominated for an Emmy in the supporting category this year deserves
the attention. We provide a scorecard:
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding supporting actress _ comedy
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Jennifer Aniston, ``Friends,'' NBC; Kim Cattrall,
``Sex and the City,'' HBO; Lisa Kudrow, ``Friends,'' NBC; Megan
Mullally, ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' NBC; Doris Roberts, ``Everybody Loves
Raymond,'' NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The Buzz: Where's Courteney Cox Arquette? ``Friends' '' most
appealing performer this past year didn't make the cut in what
would have been an intriguing race if she had. Aniston and Kudrow
were worthy, at different times in different years, but not this
past season. Roberts also isn't generating much buzz: She's a
consistent joy on ``Raymond,'' but she's overshadowed by an
ensemble that delivers humor with honesty and clarity.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Cattrall, who has become quite the scene stealer
in the hot ``Sex and the City.'' She's also a TV veteran who has
finally found material that suits her.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Mullally, whose pseudo-ditzy voice turns her
lines into glorious melodies with the power to sting. Give the
woman credit for making us care about a character who, let's face
it, is obnoxious, self-centered and has few redeeming qualities to
speak of, except, of course, being absolutely hilarious.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding supporting actress _ drama
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Stockard Channing, ``The West Wing,'' NBC; Tyne Daly,
``Judging Amy,'' CBS; Allison Janney, ``The West Wing,'' NBC; Nancy
Marchand, ``The Sopranos,'' HBO; Holland Taylor, ``The Practice,''
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   The Buzz: Marchand, who died earlier this year, is being talked
about in sentimental terms, which is making her competitors sweat.
As for the rest of the field, you can toss a coin and not feel
cheated. Daly and Janney are both strong but are representing
first-year series. Channing was seen little but had an impact every
time she showed up. Taylor, who surprised _ and upset _ most
everyone last year by winning this category as a guest star who
qualified as a regular, is being viewed as the dark horse. That
shows how strong this field is.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Marchand, with Emmy bowing to a sentimental vote
that, for a change, won't make us cry bloody murder.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Daly, whose acting style often reminds me of
James Earl Jones' in terms of making every scene noticeable with
impressive oracular pronouncements. While her mother-hen gruffness
can be off-putting, Daly does this sort of thing so charmingly that
you don't mind that she's driving everyone around her batty.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
