<HEADER>
A4308 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-EMMYPICKS-SUPPORTINGA     09-06 0513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EMMYPICKS-SUPPORTINGACTOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHO WILL WIN _ AND WHO SHOULD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Supporting players on TV have a tendency to steal the spotlight
from their more staid, traditionally appealing leading men, and
this year is no different. From belligerent fathers to belligerent
mobsters, the supporting categories are full of actors who know how
to get noticed.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding supporting actor _ comedy
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Peter Boyle, ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS; Brad
Garrett, ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' CBS; Sean Hayes, ``Will &AMP;
Grace,'' NBC; Peter MacNicol, ``Ally McBeal,'' Fox; David Hyde
Pierce, ``Frasier,'' NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The Buzz: Pierce is still able to convey wit, humor and pathos
with merely a roll of the eyes, and his multiple Emmy wins prove
his popularity with voters. His chief competition comes from
Garrett and Boyle from the popular ``Raymond,'' but the two
co-stars are seen more as ensemble stalwarts than as budding stars.
Hayes is a zany motormouth in a hot show, and MacNicol is a zany
motormouth in a terrible show, so the race is shaping up to be
between Pierce and Hayes.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Pierce, because Emmy voters don't have a
compelling reason not to go with the tried-and-true.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Hayes. He combines physical comedy, impeccable
timing and solid acting into a performance that's so high-energy
it's sometimes unnerving. But while Hayes is criticized for being
almost a caricature, it's his uninhibited exuberance that makes his
Jack a true original. He manages to create memorable comic moments
with each entrance and exit.
</P>
<P>
   Outstanding supporting actor _ drama
</P>
<P>
   Nominees: Michael Badalucco, ``The Practice,'' ABC; Dominic
Chianese, ``The Sopranos,'' HBO; Steve Harris, ``The Practice,''
ABC; Richard Schiff, ``The West Wing,'' NBC; John Spencer, ``The
West Wing,'' NBC.
</P>
<P>
   The Buzz: None of the actors has momentum going in, partly
because most of the nominees are new. One thing seems almost a
certainty: Badalucco, who surprised everyone last year by walking
away with the honor, can forget about repeating the trip to the
podium. He had a fine season on ``The Practice,'' but series
creator David E. Kelley is falling out of favor with voters. Harris
is in the mix this time around, but he'll suffer the same handicap,
despite managing to make viewers care about a character who only
has two emotions: angry and really, really angry. And Schiff and
Spencer are well-liked _ and ``The West Wing'' is garnering the
same enthusiasm that ``Ally McBeal'' did during its first season _
but the show is largely viewed as an ensemble piece in which no one
voice stands out.
</P>
<P>
   Who will win: Chianese, almost by default.
</P>
<P>
   Who should win: Chianese, because he makes his mobster's faults
so human. Much of last season, his Uncle Junior was under house
arrest _ getting him hooked on ``The Bold &AMP; The Beautiful'' was a
nice touch.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
