<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4310 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-OLDWEST07-COX     09-06 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLDWEST07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Keeping the West on the silver screen
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DRIFTWOOD, Texas _ Banks are being robbed, horses stampeded and
Jesse James is mounting the gallows _ in several takes _ near this
tiny Central Texas town south of Dripping Springs.
</P>
<P>
   As magical as film-making is, the creation of one of the
country's largest Western movie sets is just as fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   Where cows grazed on the Newberry family ranch in June, three
Western towns rise from the parched pastures. In about six weeks,
crews erected 42 structures _ facades, newly constructed buildings,
a borrowed Post Office and butcher shop. On any given day, they
change a few signs, move a building or replace plastic stone siding
with rough sawn wood and the movie set becomes another town.
</P>
<P>
   To really dress it up for an untitled Jesse James film,
designers use the four B's of Western sets _ boxes, barrels, bags
and benches.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many movie sets, this one in Hays County may hang around
longer than the film reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our personal goal, to have a town here for filming in
the United States,'' said Janis Weinheimer, who manages the ranch
with her husband, Kim. In 1991, the Weinheimers introduced music
videos, still shoots and films as a way to increase ranch revenue.
Today, some 40 projects later, Austin-wood contributes as much to
the ranch's bottom line as cattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a way to stay in ranching,'' said Kim Weinheimer. ``It
gets harder every year.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1,650 acre ranch, which traces its roots to a land grant for
Alamo commander William B. Travis, has been depicted as everything
from Africa to Vietnam (at night) to Mississippi. And that was
before the erection of the Western movie set.
</P>
<P>
   The Weinheimers, the Newberry family and Morgan Creek
Productions, the makers of the movie about Jesse James, are
negotiating plans to leave the set intact. The City of Austin and
State of Texas are weighing in, saying a Western set would be a
magnet for more movie production.
</P>
<P>
   ``I very much would like to see it remain there,'' said Austin
City Council Member Will Wynn. ``I plan to lead the city effort to
research the role the city can play in this.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has disclosed details of what public assistance,
if any, would be required to maintain, protect and promote the
movie set.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Copeland, the director of the Governor's Office of Music,
Film, Television and Multimedia Industries, has endorsed making the
set permanent. Ric Luber, executive director of the Austin
Convention and Visitors Bureau, said it could be worth millions to
the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's as if someone would drop a factory in the middle of
Texas, for all the business it would generate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   So far this year there has been $135 million in movie production
in Austin, Luber estimated. Of that, about half stays in the local
economy, primarily from 600 Austin-based technicians who make their
livings in the movies.
</P>
<P>
   Cary White and John Frick are examples of Austinites behind the
camera. White is the production designer and Frick the art director
for the Jesse James movie. They've worked together on the
``Lonesome Dove'' mini-series and several movies.
</P>
<P>
   Their jobs, White jokes, is to litter the country with as many
forts, ranch houses, saloons and dry good stores as they can.
</P>
<P>
   The Driftwood movie set, if left to stand, would not be unique
to Texas. The set used for Willie Nelson's ``Red-Headed Stranger''
remains on the singer's property near Spicewood. Near Fort Davis is
the set for a mini-series called ``Dead Man's Walk.'' The
storefronts of ``Lonesome Dove'' still stand near Del Rio and the
fort from the epic ``Alamo'' looms near Bracketville, Copeland
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Driftwood set has one significant advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the zone,'' said Janis Weinheimer, speaking like a
Hollywood veteran who understands film grosses and union scale. In
movie parlance, in the zone means the set is within 30 miles of a
major city. That means lower overhead in less per diem, mileage and
other union perks.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, ranching side-by-side with couple of hundred members
of a film crew can take patience _ on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   It's a bit odd to see speed bumps on a dirt road and signs that
read: ``Mandatory 10 MPH This Means You!'' The cattle like to drop
into the Jesse James homestead and chew on the film crew's wiring.
And when the commotion of gunfights, stampedes and bank robberies
become too much for ranch residents, Kim Weinheimer said,
``Sometimes you go out to talk to the cows.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
