<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0249 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4315 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-UN-0907-COX     09-06 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON OPENS UN SUMMIT WITH CHARGE TO 'REWRITE HISTORY', HOST
OF BILATERAL MEETINGS
 &HT;    With CLINTON-MIDEAST-0907.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ President Clinton used the largest gathering of
international leaders in history Wednesday to spar with his global
counterparts on issues ranging from nuclear arms control and human
rights to Third World poverty and the quest for Mideast peace.
</P>
<P>
   Taking a final formal bow as senior statesman on the global
stage, Clinton delivered a brief but wide-ranging valedictory
address to nearly 160 world leaders attending the United Nations
Millennium Summit, challenging the institution to embrace the
challenges of an uncertain world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The leaders assembled here can rewrite human history in the
new millennium,'' Clinton said, speaking for his eighth and final
time as president to open the annual U.N. General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we must believe the simple things,'' he implored, ''that
everywhere, in every land, people in every station matter. Everyone
counts.''
</P>
<P>
   Shattering the optimism of the moment, though, tragedy struck
the organization just hours before Wednesday's proceedings began,
when militiamen attacked U.N. offices in the tense island enclave
of East Timor, killing three U.N. workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I much regret to have to open our proceedings on a somber
note,'' said U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
   He asked leaders and diplomats to stand and observe a minute of
silence in the memory of those killed: Carlos Caseras of the United
States; Samson Aregahegn of Ethiopia; and Pero Simundza of Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This tragedy underlines once again the dangers faced by
unarmed humanitarian workers serving the United Nations in conflict
or post- conflict situations,'' Annan said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton looked out from the U.N. podium onto a sea of faces
mirroring the diversity of the group and the era it serves, as
long-term U.S. foes such as Cuba's bearded dictator, Fidel Castro,
in a dark business suit, and Iranian President Mohammad Khatami, in
a long flowing black robe and wire-rimmed glasses, silently
listened to the remarks.
</P>
<P>
   In an unscheduled surprise, Khatami rose to address the assembly
_ he had been slated to speak several hours later _ as Clinton sat
in the chamber shortly after his own speech.
</P>
<P>
   With Secretary of State Madeleine Albright seated to his left,
Clinton listened as the voice of a female interpreter crackled
through a dingy plastic earpiece, as Khatami warned against the
dangers of ``a few power-holders'' exerting undue influence over
global affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nations can no longer be excluded or marginalized on
political, cultural and economic pretexts,'' Khatami said in a
lecture that appeared largely tailored to target the United States
and its major allies. ``No double standards, national or
international, can ever be accepted in
</P>
<P>
   the contemporary world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, for his part, slammed the military junta that rules the
Southeast Asian nation of Burma, demanding the release from house
arrest of democratically-elected leader Aung San Suu Kyi and
calling her ``a brave and popular leader.''
</P>
<P>
   And, with Indonesia's President Abdurrahman Wahid looking on,
Clinton pressed the government in Jakarta to rein in elements of
the Indonesian military that have assisted paramilitary groups in
violence against pro-independence forces in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was deeply saddened to learn of the brutal murder of the
three U.N. relief workers there by the militia,'' Clinton said. ``I
urge the Indonesian authorities to put a stop to these abuses.''
</P>
<P>
   A U.N. operation is administering East Timor, which voted last
year for independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid, who was steadied by two aides as he left the U.N. General
Assembly Hall after morning speeches, issued his own statement,
expressing ``deep regret'' over the incident, and ordered an
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the assembly hall for his opulent quarters at a
Manhattan luxury hotel, Clinton careened through a day of intensive
face-to-face diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   He met from morning until deep into the night with one leader
after the next, including Russian President Vladimir Putin, Israeli
Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian Authority President
Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin squared off over the future of a U.S. missile
defense system, with Putin insisting that such a weapon could upset
the strategic balance of power and perhaps even spark a global
nuclear arms race.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders agreed, however, to conduct a joint assessment
of the threat a national missile defense (NMD) system would be
designed to defend against: the risk that a rogue state or
terrorist group might try to attack a major power with a long-range
missile tipped with nuclear, chemical or biological weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton announced last Friday that he would not deploy such a
system, but the administration made clear Wednesday that the issue
would remain on the White House desk once Clinton's successor takes
office in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NMD issue is not off the table, it's not solved,'' Deputy
Secretary of State Strobe Talbott told reporters here. ``There is
going to have to be, over time, a change in the way that, not just
the United States, but other countries, too, pursue ...
anti-missile defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Putin, though, used his own U.N. address to attack the plan as
part of an effort to turn outer space into a battlefield. He called
for a U.N.-sponsored conference to prevent what he called ``the
militarization of outer space,'' and offered to host such a
gathering in Moscow next spring, if the U.N. adopts the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The NMD system under U.S. development combines powerful radars
and rockets to try to knock down incoming missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Putin signed a Joint Statement on Strategic
Stability Cooperation, building on earlier documents the two inked
in Moscow in June and in Okinawa, Japan, in July.
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
