<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4344 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-06 1124
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO WORLD LEADERS: IT'S TIME TO END CONFLICTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Standing before the largest ever gathering of
world leaders, President Clinton Wednesday made a plea to his
audience to end conflicts around the globe, including a pointed
reminder to the Israeli prime minister and the Palestinian
president that the moment to end their history of enmity was
``fleeting and about to pass.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is not a moment to lose,'' Clinton said directly to
Israel's Ehud Barak and the Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, Clinton plunged into separate talks with Barak and
Arafat only nine blocks from the United Nations headquarters, but
US officials were careful to play down expectations, saying the
likely outcome would be more discussions and not a hasty return to
the presidential Camp David compound at week's end.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago the Israeli-Palestinian talks ended with no deal
at the Maryland retreat, but the two sides had engaged in
unprecedented discussions on the core issues that divide them,
including the future of the holy city of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   But as Clinton, UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and others
called on leaders to find ways of compromise to defuse flareups,
Russian President Vladimir Putin Wednesday unleashed an arrow at
what many world leaders perceive as the dangerous US consideration
of a missile defense system.
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton last week postponed a decision on missile defense
to allow his successor to make the choice, Putin, without
specifically mentioning the US idea, said that militarization of
space was ``particularly alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   Noting that Soviet cosmonaut Yuri Gagarin became the first man
in space on April 12, 1961, he suggested holding an international
conference next year in Russia on the 40th anniversary on the uses
of space.
</P>
<P>
   And heaping more derision on the United States was North Korea,
which denounced the superpower as a ``rogue state'' _ turning a
phrase often employed by Washington against it. North Korea, which
boycotted the meeting, claimed the US government was responsible
for allegedly ordering a search of members of the delegation as
they switched planes in Germany. American Airlines apologized for
the search and said no US government agency took part.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day meeting of kings, monarchs, presidents, prime
ministers and other dignitaries from 189 nations opened a half-hour
late due to the hobnobbing of dignitaries. And then came speeches
from 63 leaders, with the unlikeliest of bookends, Clinton kicking
off the summit and Cuban President Fidel Castro closing it
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Annan strove to inspire world leaders to think beyond their
national concerns for the good of all people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problems seem huge,'' he said, listing poverty, the AIDS
epidemic, wars and environmental degradation. ``But in today's
world, given the technology and the resources around, we have the
means to tackle them. If we have the will, we can deal with them.''
</P>
<P>
   While Clinton also packed a paragraph with broad themes _ he
particularly mentioned the need to fight malaria, tuberculosis and
AIDS, which cause a quarter of all deaths in the world; the need to
stimulate the development of affordable drugs and vaccines; and the
need to make peace more profitable than conflict by shutting down
diamond and drug industries from Angola to Colombia _ the issue of
peace dominated his thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, he noted, wars have claimed the lives of
more than 5 million people around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The toll was underscored Wednesday with the news of three UN aid
workers killed in West Timor. The assembly began with a moment of
silence in their memory.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, in his eighth and final address to the world body as US
president, said it was about time that the United Nations build a
peacekeeping force that was better armed and could deploy quickly
to the world's troublespots.
</P>
<P>
   As his daughter Chelsea looked on, Clinton also turned
reflective, and drew upon his experiences around the world in
trying to settle conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have learned anything in these last eight years, it is,
whether we like it or not, we are growing more interdependent. We
must look for more solutions in which all sides can claim a measure
of victory and move away from choices in which someone is required
to accept complete defeat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He continued, ``That will require us to develop greater
sensitivity to our diverse political, cultural and religious
claims. But it will require us to develop even greater respect for
our common humanity.''
</P>
<P>
   The remarks could be read as universal, pertinent to any
conflict, but they were made with the Israeli-Palestinian peace
talks in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``To those who have supported the right of Israel to live in
security and peace, to those who have championed the Palestinian
cause these many years, let me say to all of you: They need your
support now more than ever to take the hard risks for peace. They
have the chance to do it. But like all life's chances, it is
fleeting and about to pass,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barak and Arafat, in public comments, both seemed to hold firm
to their positions, offering little hope for a breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in his speech before the summit, said Israel already had
shown it was ready to compromise for peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It remains to be seen whether our counterparts (the
Palestinians and Syria) are also capable of rising to the magnitude
of the hour,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Jerusalem ``the eternal capital of Israel,'' Barak said
a peace deal would also reflect Muslim and Christian links with the
city.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of Arafat, he said, the two were ``at the Rubicon,
and neither of us can cross it alone. ...The opportunity for peace
in the Middle East is now at hand and must not be missed.''
</P>
<P>
   But Arafat told reporters, ``I am sure I will not be flexible
with the holy places because the holy places are not only
Palestinian. It's Palestinian, Arab, Christian and Muslim holy
places, and everybody has to respect it.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian legislators are scheduled to meet over the weekend
to discuss whether to unilaterally declare a state on Sept. 13 _
the end date of the Oslo peace process _ or to postpone it until
later in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Palestinians' decision, Barak said UN members
could help the process by opposing any unilateral measures.
Listening, through a set of headphones, was Arafat, whose face
masked his thoughts. Although Clinton met Arafat Wednesday night
after talks with Barak, the Israeli and Palestinian leaders were
not scheduled to meet over the three days in New York.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
