<SLUG> BC-FLEET-SHARES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEET INVESTMENT UNIT ROBERTSON STEPHENS SEEKS IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BETH HEALY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Top executives of Robertson Stephens are trying to
persuade their parent, FleetBoston Financial Corp., to sell shares
of the investment banking group to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Such a move would give Robertson attractive stock and options
incentives for employees, people close to the companies said. And
it would give Fleet large potential stock gains on a valuable
property.
</P>
<P>
   There is no imminent plan to take Robertson public, Fleet
sources said. But the Boston-based banking giant is said to be
mulling an IPO of a minority slice of the group, with Fleet keeping
a controlling interest.
</P>
<P>
   A Fleet spokesman declined to comment on the potential IPO. News
of the negotiations first appeared in Wednesday's San Francisco
Chronicle. Robertson Stephens is holding an Internet conference
this week in San Francisco, where it is headquartered.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said a partial IPO of Robertson _ known for taking
Internet and other high-tech companies public _ would make sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something you have to give consideration to,'' said Tom
Theurkauf, a senior vice president at Keefe, Bruyette &AMP; Woods in
New York. ``The brokerage stocks are on fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping key talent is crucial to the investment banking
business, Theurkauf said. ``While Fleet's stock is attractive, I
think if you had a security that was a pure play on the investment
bank, that would be a very attractive employee retention option.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleet shares are trading at a price-to-earnings multiple of 13,
while top investment banks are trading above 20. While Fleet shares
have risen 21 percent since January, the jump followed a deep lull
for financial stocks. From 12 months ago, Fleet shares are up just
6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fleet became Robertson's parent with its merger with BankBoston
Corp. nearly a year ago. BankBoston bought the investment bank in
1998 for $800 million, a price many believed was high at the time.
It was nearly 50 percent more than BankAmerica Corp. had paid for
the firm a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Robertson employees want a stock that reflects the
recent boom of their business, rather than a bank stock. Fleet has
earned nearly $250 million on Robertson's activities.
</P>
<P>
   The investment banking group ranked sixth in the nation for fees
earned on deals in the first quarter, at $72 million, according to
Thomson Financial Securities Data. But it fell to 13th in the
second quarter, as the Nasdaq market tanked, earning about $10
million.
</P>
<P>
   If the IPO market has been rocky for investment bankers in
recent months, however, the stock market has been generous to them.
Huge deals such as Credit Suisse Group's recent agreement to buy
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc. have fueled investor interest in
Wall Street firms.
</P>
</TEXT>
