<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV10-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     CLINTON STEPS UP EFFORT ON HIS LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sept. 10)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ While Al Gore and George W. Bush zoom from state to
state in search of votes, Bill Clinton blithely circumnavigates the
globe doing his own thing in his own way.
</P>
<P>
   With less than five months left in his presidency, Clinton has
intensified efforts to leave his mark on world and national
affairs. At 54,he is not yet ready for retirement or a final moment
in the spotlight of history.
</P>
<P>
   The recent record of his activities confirms that fact.
</P>
<P>
   One day he was in Africa promoting democracy and fighting the
AIDS epidemic, and the next day he was in Egypt conferring with its
leader, Hosni Mubarak, about peace in the Middle East. Then he was
off to Colombia to pledge more U.S. financial aid for the war on
drugs. From there, he dashed to Syracuse, N.Y., to bolster Hillary
Rodham Clinton's senatorial campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she can have an enormously beneficial impact for New
York all around the country and all around the world,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His next major stop was the United Nations to participate in the
Millennium Summit, a gathering of about 160 presidents, prime
ministers, kings and generals. There he met with Israel's Ehud
Barak and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat in a last-ditch effort
to bring the longtime foes together in peace.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. session also afforded him the opportunity to confer
with Russia's Vladimir Putin and China's Jiang Zemin.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is prepared to do all he can to win the presidency for
Gore, but he has no intention of yielding his office and its many
perquisites before the moment _ noon on Jan. 20 _ decreed by the
Constitution for his successor to take over.
</P>
<P>
   The fascinating aspect of Clinton's peripatetic efforts to leave
behind a record of achievement is that, for all his troubles and
scandals, he remains the most formidable figure in American
political life.
</P>
<P>
   That is true not just because he still bears the title
``president of the United States'' or because he can go where he
wants, when he wants on a Boeing 747 furnished by the federal
government. It is true because of his own talents and perseverance.
</P>
<P>
   That is the tragedy of the Clinton presidency. He is so
intelligent, so personable, so well motivated in most domestic and
foreign policy matters, but he was so unable to control his private
deportment. With his retentive mind and his vast knowledge, Clinton
undoubtedly is one of the most perceptive presidents of all time.
</P>
<P>
   As a communicator, he is almost as good as Ronald Reagan, who
entered the White House after decades as a movie and television
performer.
</P>
<P>
   It has been difficult for many Democrats to defend Clinton,
given his bad personal behavior. But he has put a new face on the
nation's oldest political party by taking a middle course on some
issues _ economic growth, welfare reform and crime reduction. Part
of the crime drop results from his program to add more than 100,000
officers to local police forces.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is prone to give his administration the lion's share of
credit for the surge in the economy, the balanced budget and the
surplus. The truth is that credit must be shared with Federal
Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan and with business, labor and
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But it all happened on Clinton watch. Therefore, he is entitled
to great credit.
</P>
<P>
   Ideologically, Clinton is less overtly liberal than George
McGovern, whose presidential bid he supported as an anti-Vietnam
War activist in 1972, or Michael Dukakis, whose name he placed in
nomination at the 1988 Democratic convention.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton might have achieved more as president had his party not
lost control of both houses of Congress in 1994 and had he not lost
a year of achievement because of his misconduct with Monica
Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Some presidential observers tend to lump him with Richard Nixon,
who was immobilized by the 1972 Watergate scandal and forced to
resign. It is true that a strong strain of deviousness ran through
both men and that they both lied to the American people.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon, in an illegal invocation of presidential power,
sought to obstruct justice by using the CIA and FBI to cover up
criminal acts. His administration's crimes and dirty tricks sent a
host of government officials to prison, and Nixon himself was named
as an ``unindicted co-conspirator.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did lie under oath about his relationship with Lewinsky,
but he did not seek to use government agencies to obstruct justice.
Despite his acquittal in the Senate's in the impeachment trial, he
remains in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   Independent Counsel Robert Ray, the successor to Kenneth Starr,
has impaneled a new grand jury to decide whether the president
should be indicted on criminal charges once he leaves the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   As long as he lives, Clinton's character defects will be fair
game for biographers and political critics. His actions will make
colorful reading and television viewing for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   In his memorable farewell speech to the Democratic National
Convention in Los Angeles last month, Clinton defended and extolled
the record of his presidency. Then as delegates cheered and wept,
he dramatically declared: ``The best is yet to be _ if we make the
right choices ... the future of our country is in your hands. You
must think hard, feel deeply and choose wisely.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, keep putting people first. Keep building those
bridges. And don't stop thinking about tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   If Nixon was a human phoenix, rising from the ashes of defeat,
Clinton is even more so because he never let scandal and adversity
rob him of the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   (Robert E. Thompson can be reached at 202-298-6920.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
