<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SAFETY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI REPORT OFFERS VIOLENT-STUDENT WARNING SIGNALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT S. GREENBERGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teachers and principals should be wary of students who make
threats and are fascinated by bloodshed, who seem unusually
heartbroken over a breakup or who admire destructive figures such
as Satan or Hitler, according to an FBI report on school violence
released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The School Shooter: A Threat Assessment Perspective'' lists 28
personal traits that may indicate if a student who has threatened
to commit a violent act is serious about carrying it out. The
36-page report, which is based on two years of research, also
details school and family conditions that can breed violent
behavior in children.
</P>
<P>
   The chief author of the study emphasizes that it should be used
to evaluate the seriousness of threats, not all students.
</P>
<P>
   But critics say that many of the identified traits could apply
to almost any teenager. They also worry that the report could lead
principals and teachers to overreact at a time when school violence
is actually on the decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the feeling that they're responding to public pressure
and media coverage that has made the public feel that this is a
greater danger than it is,'' said Vincent Schiraldi of the Justice
Policy Institute, a Washington research group that focuses on
juvenile justice issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this gets used inappropriately, it's not a stretch to
imagine school principals coming up with lists of the ten most
dangerous kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In compiling the report, the FBI examined 14 school shootings
across the country and four cases in which police thwarted an
incident after ``significant preparations'' had been made.
Researchers interviewed the offenders, witnesses, and people who
knew the students and their families. They also analyzed crime
scene photographs and videos.
</P>
<P>
   Besides a fascination with bloodshed, romantic difficulties and
negative role models, the researchers found that many of the
shooters had trouble controlling their anger, were prejudiced
against minorities, or were alienated from their peers.
</P>
<P>
   Other potentially problematic personality traits, according to
the study, included ``a lack of empathy,'' an ``exaggerated sense
of entitlement'' and an ``attitude of superiority.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers found that many of the shooters' families did
not impose discipline, and that the perpetrators had unsupervised
access to television, the Internet and weapons. The families also
lacked intimacy or closeness.
</P>
<P>
   In reviewing the schools which had become crime scenes, the FBI
found that many of them had an ``inflexible culture'' that was
insensitive to the needs of newer students and staff. There often
was a pecking order among students, and a sense that discipline was
meted out unfairly.
</P>
<P>
   The study also ranks threats in terms of their seriousness,
emphasizing that those that are specific and plausible are the ones
that should be heeded.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the factors match those outlined in a Massachusetts
school violence report produced by the Governor's Advisory Council
on Youth Violence. Gov. Paul Cellucci launched the panel in 1998 _
before Columbine but after a spate of less deadly school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Everett, Mass. Superintendent Frederick F. Foresteire, a member
of that council, says the fact that none of the school shootings
has taken place in the Commonwealth is ``not luck.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's being on top of the issue and hearing students, listening
to students,'' Foresteire said. ``I don't care if it's academic
difficulties, the difficulties in their homes, or difficulties with
their peers. If they've got a shoulder to lean on, they'll get
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Massachusetts experience also illustrates the potential
for overreaction.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, for example, a 15-year-old Leominster special-needs
student was expelled for drawing a picture of his school surrounded
by explosives. That same month, the Boston public schools
overturned the suspension of a student who wrote a horror story
that featured a student seemingly taking a chainsaw to his English
teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Special Agent Mary Ellen O'Toole, the chief author of the study,
stresses that it should be used to assess the seriousness of a
threat, not to isolate difficult or troubled children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you never made threat in school, this framework model
should not be used as far as you're concerned,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But some fear that teachers and principals won't get that
message.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's useful information from a clinical point of view, but to
repesent this as a tool for schools is problematic,'' said Nancy
Mullin-Rindler, who heads the Project on Teasing and Bullying at
Wellesley College. She also advised the state on its new
anti-bullying initiative, which recently issued its first set of
grants to six elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although they carefully stress that this isn't a profile. the
fact is you're going to have schools that are going to latch onto
this and say, `this is what we're going to do.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
