<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4354 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-ATL-OBASANJO07-COX     09-06 0526
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-OBASANJO07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nigerian president, emigres plan talks here
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _In the last years of the 20th century, as Nigeria
suffered under years of repression, misrule and outright
governmental theft, many of the country's best-educated
professionals fled the country.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Nigerian President Olusegun Obasanjo, who was
elected last year, will visit Atlanta to try to convince those
professionals things back home have changed.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he will solicit their advice and ask for their help
in rebuilding the country, either with their talents or their
money, Joe Keshi, Nigeria's consul general in Atlanta, said
Wednesday. The country needs the services of the Nigerian doctors
and professors living in the diaspora, and it needs investment as
well, Keshi said.
</P>
<P>
   By rights, Nigeria should be prosperous. With 123 million
people, the west African nation, which is about twice the size of
California, is Africa's most populous. The country is rich in oil,
pumping 2 million barrels of crude out of the Niger Delta region
every day.
</P>
<P>
   But 16 years of military government left the country
impoverished, its infrastructure in disrepair, its government
institutions corrupt and its ethnic and religious groups vying for
power. From 1993 until his death in 1998, dictator Sani Abacha is
believed to have diverted several billion dollars into his personal
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Since his inauguration in May 1999, Obasanjo has been consulting
groups inside Nigeria on how to rebuild the country, Keshi said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president does not want to exclude Nigerians in the
diaspora,'' Keshi said.
</P>
<P>
   Nor, apparently, do Nigerians in the diaspora want to be
excluded. The consulate originally planned for 500 people. Now
organizers expect two or three times that many to attend, and they
are concerned about logistical problems if people show up Saturday
without advance registration.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8,000 Nigerians live in metro Atlanta, Keshi said. But
the conference will be attended by Nigerian professionals from
across the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Obasanjo's willingness to seek advice has impressed even some
critics. Femi Shotomide King, president of the Vanguard for
Democracy and Justice, a group of Atlanta-area Nigerian activists,
has criticized corruption in government, the ineffectiveness of
national police and Obasanjo's refusal to call a national
conference on the country's future.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, King praised the president for soliciting the
opinions of Nigerians in the United States. King said his biggest
fear is that the conference will prove to be a lot of talk with no
results.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Obasanjo is a very good man,'' King said. ``He has a
good intention. He has a vision. But I hope the people surrounding
him in the government can actualize the vision and bring it to
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   The conference will convene at noon Friday at the Georgia
International Convention Center at 1902 Sullivan Road in College
Park. Obasanjo will join the conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
