A4355 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-COLLEGE-MEDICINE07-CO     09-06 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-MEDICINE07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There won't be a quiz later, but please note these tips
 &HT;    By Leigh-Ann Jackson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the middle of the night and you have a laundry list of
uncomfy symptoms that leave you with just enough energy to moan and
curse your fate. A few weeks ago, you could have trudged down the
hallway to your parents' room, groaned out a pitiful ``Mommy!'' and
gotten the Florence Nightingale treatment with items pulled from a
well-stocked medicine cabinet. But now, you're staring bleary-eyed
at your wilted reflection in the dorm's community bathroom mirror.
Although packing for your freshman year of college took
approximately two weeks (allowing time for you to smuggle away your
parents' smaller appliances and replace that perfect pair of
first-day-of-school boots with a really perfect pair), the
nonessentials managed to crowd out the true necessities.
</P>
<P>
   It stands to reason that semesters filled with sleepless nights,
course-related stress and abysmal eating habits will call for some
first aid. Instead of dragging that lifeless body to the pharmacy
in the throes of yuckiness and grabbing the first over-the-counter
drug in sight, be prepared ahead of time. Tina Dooley, assistant
chief pharmacist at UT's Health Services Pharmacy, runs down a few
items you won't regret stock-piling.
</P>
<P>
   There are myriad reasons that your body succumbs to head colds _
lack of sleep, stress, poor diet, etc. _ and odds are the average
student's touch-and-go lifestyle will eventually carry him/her
through all of them. There's no (good) excuse for missing class if
you use the right medication.
</P>
<P>
   Robitussin DM is a cough suppressant that loosens and relieves
chest congestion without causing drowsiness.
</P>
<P>
   Seven-layer burritos, nachos and cinnamon twists do not a
balanced meal make. Because your knowledge of this fact will remain
on your brain's back-burner for many semesters to come, supplement
your junk-filled diet with a daily dose of multivitamins.
</P>
<P>
   _Contrary to popular collegiate belief, the back of your
roomie's hand is not an accurate gauge for fevers. Instead, opt for
a quick and easy portable oral thermometer.
</P>
<P>
   _Tex-Mex dining has the potential to go very wrong, very
quickly, especially for Northerners who don't know a serrano from a
bell. For immediate relief of heartburn and acid indigestion
there's Maalox.If you just couldn't say no to those extra dollops
of guacamole and queso, try a longer-lasting formula like Zantac 75
(it can be taken up to 60 minutes before the onslaught of onions
and ancho).
</P>
<P>
   _Non-Texan-- may have never driven as much in their lives as
they will in the next four years of Lone Star living. Impromptu car
trips to away games, spring break haunts and roommates' hometowns
may leave you somewhat queasy, so try Dramamine, or any other
tablets with dimenhydrinate, to prevent or treat motion sickness.
</P>
<P>
   _Blaring stereos to the left of you, shouting matches to the
right and mind-boggling equations staring up at you. Faced with
such adversity, there's no way to avoid a pulsing headache, but you
can cure it with Aleve, which Dooley recommends for its overall
versatility _ it relieves headaches, muscle pains, menstrual pains
and reduces fever and swelling, as well.
</P>
<P>
   _Never had to wrestle with bothersome seasonal allergies before?
Welcome to Austin, where no one seems immune. For your garden
variety symptoms (pun surely not intended), go with a sinus and
nasal decongestant like Tavist D. Because it's an antihistamine, it
may cause drowsiness and shouldn't be mixed with alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   _In case you had to learn the hard way that you need to wear
flip-flops in the dorm showers, Lamisil AT (with terbinafine
hydrochloride cream 1 percent) offers a prescription-strength cure
for athlete's foot and other minor foot foibles.
</P>
<P>
   _You may pride yourself on a consistently clean bill of health,
but never underestimate the awesome power of your own clumsiness.
Keep a first aid kit handy, complete with antiseptic wipes for
cleansing minor wounds, burn cream, sterile nonstick pads, adhesive
bandages, pain relievers, gauze and antibiotic ointment.
</P>
<P>
   _For the not-so-happy-camper who's been felled by plagues of
mosquitoes or poisonous foliage, there's hydrocortisone cream 1
percent (that's the maximum strength) to treat not only insect
bites and poison ivy/oak/sumac, but rashes caused by soaps,
cosmetics, detergents, etc.
</P>
<P>
   _Now it's clear that you shouldn't have ventured
south-of-the-border thinking that water warning was an old wives'
tale. Immodium A-D (containing Loperamide HCl) is a relatively
on-the-spot anti-diarrheal caplet.
</P>
<P>
   NOTE: Of course, if symptoms persist or if you think your health
woes indicate a more serious problem, you should consult your
physician.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
