<HEADLINE>
TELEVISION'S BIG NIGHT OUT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use on or after Sept. 8, 2000, by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
(Eds: 2 fact boxes below) 
By VALERIA KUKLENSKI 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hard-core Emmys fans may want to park a TV next to their computers
to take advantage of all the extras packaged on www.abc.com.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours before the telecast, users can check out arrivals,
including all the dirt on designers and jewelers, as well as
profiles of all the nominees. Come showtime, the Web site will
offer a fly-on-the-wall Emmy cam showing backstage activities in
the production trailers, press rooms and even dressing rooms.
</P>
<P>
   To watch the video stream and related games and trivia contests
in sync with the West Coast airing, look for the West Coast link.
Of course, if you're itching to know who won before the show is
over here, you can get all the answers from the East Coast link.
</P>
<P>
   That high-tech song and dance might help bring in more viewers.
Last year's show attracted only 17 million viewers, making it the
lowest-rated in nearly 10 years. (For comparison's sake, 51 million
viewers watched the ``Survivor'' conclusion and 46 million tuned
into last March's Academy Awards telethon.)
</P>
<P>
   By the way, don't wait until 11:01 p.m. to turn on the Emmys
telecast if you're expecting to catch the last big categories _
best comedy and drama series _ because this show honors its
three-hour time limit.
</P>
<P>
   Executive producer Don Mischer, an Emmy Awards veteran, said,
``It's not that we pride ourselves on (ending on time) _ we are
given no choice. We are told by the networks that carry the Emmys
that they want the show off the air right on time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And in the six years that I've done it, I think one year I
went over 18 seconds. That's part off the fun of doing live
television. We can't control a whole lot of this show. We don't
know who wins, we don't know what they're going to say. We have to
be real careful as we go through the three hours of live television
to make adjustments to get the show off on time.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward that end, Mischer will be hanging out backstage with
Emmys host Garry Shandling, keeping one eye on the script and the
other on his precision watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk about where we are, should we do this, add this,
should we write something about what just happened that we might
make a joke with,'' he said, praising Shandling's ability to think
on his feet and adapt to what's going on.
</P>
<P>
   There's no theme per se, but Mischer said the writers are
cranking up the comedy a few notches from years past. We wait with
bated laughtracks.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The show: ``Countdown to the Emmys.'' &QL; 
What: The red-carpet arrivals of TV's biggest stars at the Shrine
Auditorium. &QL; 
Where: ABC. &QL; 
When: 7 p.m. (tape delayed). &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The show: ``52nd Annual Prime-time Emmy Awards.'' &QL; 
What: Academy of Television Arts and Sciences hands out winged
statuettes in 27 categories to TV's best and brightest. &QL; 
Where: ABC. &QL; 
When: 8 p.m. (tape delayed). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
