</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SEASON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESSAY: ALL SINGING, ALL DANCING, ALL SURPRISING 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELVIS MITCHELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   This fall will be a season of radical departures, with an
astonishing number of musicals from directors new to the genre and
an action film from a director who made his name with finely tuned
pictures based in the comedy of manners.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch would seem to be revivifying: many of the films have
a restorative vigor. ``Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon'' is a period
Hong Kong action film from Ang Lee, whose best-known movies _ ``Eat
Drink Man Woman,'' ``Sense and Sensibility,'' ``The Ice Storm'' _
have pinpointed, with refined comic feeling, the disruptive and
sometimes microscopic bumps in social interactions that lead to
discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's silken restraint is evident in ``Crouching Tiger,'' an
elegant, literally high-flying epic whose blade-swinging heroes
soar around on the wire rigs that are now a hoary tradition in Hong
Kong action movies. Lee's patience as a storyteller gives the film
a relaxed urbanity new to the genre; he has such deep-down
confidence in his cast _ Chow Yun Fat, Michelle Yeoh and Zhang Ziyi
_ and in his filmmaking skills that nothing feels rushed. It's a
gift he applies to a type of material he's never attempted before;
the graft takes.
</P>
<P>
   There's more genre-bending going on in the spate of musicals
arriving this fall, from the established directors Joel and Ethan
Coen (``O Brother, Where Art Thou?''), Lars von Trier (``Dancer in
the Dark''), Wong Kar-wai (``In the Mood for Love'') and Baz
Luhrmann (``Moulin Rouge'') and from the first-time feature film
director Stephen Daldry (``Billy Elliott''). Movie musicals were
presumed dead, both by audiences old enough to have grown up with
them and by younger viewers born into MTV, who had sought them out
as a source _ of either inspiration or pillage, depending on your
point of view _ for the music video. In their way, music videos
have kept the form's romantic impulse alive (while it looked as
though movie studios would never make another). And some filmmaking
techniques _ which started off as experimental but lapsed quickly
into cliche from overuse _ have taken these MTV and BET
mini-musicals into altogether different territory.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that in the films I've seen, directors are
using music to personalize their pictures. There's honest sentiment
in them, rather than the respectful entombment that has made the
occasional attempt to revive the form (in limp pictures like
``Evita'') such a letdown. Even a film that isn't, strictly
speaking, a musical, Cameron Crowe's ``Almost Famous,'' uses the
rock and pop of the early 1970s for its ability to voice feelings
and, eventually, heal wounds. (``Almost Famous'' is such a personal
statement for Crowe that its opening credits are scrawled in his
handwriting.)
</P>
<P>
   The Coen brothers, who have often made music a part of their
films, have gone into full-scale delirium with ``O Brother,'' a
lovely and assaultive pastiche that quotes from almost every
memorable movie ever made and whose musical interludes are employed
for their ability to soothe. Wong has woven music so deftly into
the textures of ``In the Mood for Love'' that the songs are on a
par with the images in the film's portrayal of heartsick desire;
``Love'' is all mood and music, a dream from a director who's
temperamentally unable to think in narrative terms. And he's free
of the kind of moist corniness that lies at the heart of all
traditional musicals _ a quality the Coens embrace and comment on
in ``Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   The one element these musicals share is that they're all period
pieces. ``Brother'' is set in the 1930s, and uses a digital
desaturation process that drains so much color from the film that
it's virtually black and white for a good portion of the running
time; ``Love'' is set in the early 1960s, as is von Trier's
``Dancer in the Dark.'' Even ``Billy Elliott'' (which was
originally called ``Dancer''), the story of a young boy in a mining
town who takes to ballet as a means of escape, is set in the past,
albeit in the more recent past. Its 1980s period is appropriate for
the what-a-feeling ``Flashdance'' plot turns _ even its climax
recalls ``Flashdance.''
</P>
<P>
   So while it looks as though musicals are in the midst of a
resurgence, it may still be true that directors haven't found a way
to use the form's conventions in a contemporary setting. (``Dancer
in the Dark'' and ``Moulin Rouge'' use new songs, but they can
still be said to be dependent on the past _ even if the warm
feeling on which they rely is merely nostalgie de la boue.)
Directors are taking advantage of the distance the musical form
imposes, rather than solving the problem that prevents musicals
from being a viable means of conveying contemporary concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the ubiquity of the music video, which has turned
the show-stopper into a regular part of everyday life. Musicals
evoke a specific kind of joy, and nothing is as mesmerizing as
being drawn into a masterfully staged song-and-dance number on the
big screen: music videos have diminished that pleasure a bit by
miniaturizing it and making it commonplace. Directors whose
instincts are best suited for musicals are often filmmakers with an
eye for using space and creating tension in a confined area.
Directors as varied as the Wachowski brothers and John Woo have
those instincts _ and Woo has expressed an interest in the form,
which he should be allowed to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   That ability shows up also in ``Crouching Tiger,'' a picture
that has the range and radiance of a musical; maybe Lee should
think about turning himself in that direction next.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
