u a BC-ALLERGY-SEASON-BOS &LR;      09-06 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALLERGY-SEASON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POTENT ALLERGY SEASON JUST A SNEEZE AWAY, EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost every fall the start of ragweed allergy season brings so
much misery so swiftly that sufferers believe it's the worst year
ever.
</P>
<P>
   So far, allergy experts say, the ragweed pollen count isn't
setting records. But, they note, the rainy summer nourished
outsized ragweed plants that are spewing millions of pollen grains
into the breezes that can spread ragweed as far as 400 miles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of severe patients today,'' Dr. Julian
Melamed, an allergist in Chelmsford, Mass., said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just saw a kid who was totally miserable, whose symptoms
were so severe'' that he was prescribed potent cortisone pills.
``I've seen half a dozen patients like this today,'' said Melamed.
</P>
<P>
   He added that some patients are suffering needlessly because
they didn't start their medications _ particularly steroid nose
sprays, which take days or weeks to work _ early enough in the
season.
</P>
<P>
   People who suffer from seasonal allergies or ``hay fever''
triggered by ragweed and other weeds start to react around August
15 each year. The warmer and dryer the weather, the more misery the
pollen inflicts, until the first frost nips the ragweed into
submission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine has been bad for the past two weeks,'' said Paul
Pressman, an architect who lives near Boston. ``I don't like to
take pills, but I've been resorting to my Claritin now.''
Otherwise, he said, ``my sneezing is annoying to people around
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides fall, there are two other allergy seasons. In summer,
grass pollens trigger sneezing from May to mid-July, and in spring
it's pollen from trees that begins the allergy year in January.
</P>
<P>
   The same moisture that disappointed so many vacationers in the
Northeast was a two-edged sword for ragweed allergies. Ragweed is
the most allergenic, or allergy-causing, plant in the country, and
its green-beaded shoots are found almost everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   On one hand, the summer rains have sent ragweed plants shooting
up, said Melamed. ``The plants are really exceptionally big this
year,'' he said. Melamed is among scores of allergists who
voluntarily monitor pollen counts for the National Allergy Bureau
of the American Academy of allergy and Immunology.
</P>
<P>
   But while the plants may have flourished, the damp weather also
may have been keeping the airborne pollen from reaching the peaks
seen last year, said Dr. Martin Ostro, an attending physician in
allergy and immunology at Massachusetts General Hospital. But it's
early in the season, he cautions: ``If we get some Indian summer we
could really be in trouble,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 3.8 million school and work days combined are lost
each year because of allergic rhinitis, or hay fever, according to
the AAAI. The academy says 80 percent of people with bad seasonal
allergies have sleep problems that can lead to fatigue and
absenteeism.
</P>
<P>
   Allergies are the result of an overreaction by the body's immune
system to substances that aren't harmful. The cause isn't known,
but the tendency is inherited. This year, as in any year, some
people are being affected for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 10 percent of our patients say they haven't been
bothered before, or had only mild problems,'' said Ostro. It
doesn't mean the season is a particularly severe one. People often
begin to suffer allergies two or three years after they've moved to
a region and have become sensitized to the local pollen.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding pollen is the first line of defense for seasonal
allergies. That means keeping windows closed at night and using air
conditioners, which can be equipped with filters to keep pollen
out. People should watch pollen forecasts and try to do their
jogging or lawn-mowing when counts are expected to be low, staying
inside at other times.
</P>
<P>
   Over-the-counter drugs like Benadryl can quench sneezing and
itchy eyes but often cause drowsiness. Most people with bad
allergies are taking the new antihistamines like Allegra, Claritin
and Zyrtek that don't impair alertness, say the allergy doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Steroid nose sprays taken before the allergy season starts can
keep symptoms at bay. But some people find they cause too much
stinging in the nose and occasionally suffer from nosebleeds.
</P>
<P>
   Itching and burning eyes aren't always helped by systemic
antihistamines. Now there is a big crop of antihistamine eye drops
that go right to the source of trouble. They are sold by
prescription under names like Patanol, Alomide and Zadator.
</P>
<P>
   Even with these new remedies, the old desensitizing ``allergy
shots'' are still the most effective treatment for some people. But
they have to be given once a week for a long period of time and
tend to be expensive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1937EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
