<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4364 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-FILM-WATCHER-REVIEW-H     09-06 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-WATCHER-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIAL KILLER IN ``THE WATCHER' IS ALL TOO FAMILIAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. Houston Chronicle 
 
``The Watcher'' is both mundane and strange _ mundane for being yet
another serial-killer flick, and strange because this modest movie
has a major star.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like it or not, Keanu Reeves is such a star. Hits such as ``The
Matrix'' and ``Speed'' have pushed his fee to $15 million per
picture.
</P>
<P>
   The catch is that he became pals with Joe Charbanic, having
bonded while playing street hockey. As a favor to the novice
director, Reeves signed to play a small part in his film for union
scale.
</P>
<P>
   It seems he also wanted to play a villain for a change _ at
least for a few days. But when Charbanic beefed up the part of
Reeves' serial killer, the actor was stuck.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves was miffed enough to have his name buried in ``The
Watcher's'' credits and his appearance downplayed in its marketing.
</P>
<P>
   For artistic reasons alone, you can't blame him. ``The Watcher''
is a numbingly familiar exercise in fear, disgorging regular doses
of grisly violence buoyed by precious little plot and pitifully
thin character development.
</P>
<P>
   Why does Reeves kill blameless young women? The film never
bothers to go there. Rather, it plays up a symbiotic link between
the killer and an FBI guy (James Spader) on his case.
</P>
<P>
   When first seen, Spader is so burned out that he's fled his job
in Los Angeles to settle in Chicago. There he pops pills, seeks
therapy and stares at the ceiling of his bleak apartment.
</P>
<P>
   But Reeves follows, starting a new string of murders by sending
Spader photos of his targets scant hours before an attack. A
reluctant Spader then shifts back into gear, leading Chicago's
police in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Splashing women's photos on TV doesn't help much _ not in this
city, which differs from the Chicago of ``Return to Me.'' In that
romantic comedy, Chicago was a place of neighborhoods, friends,
families _ connections. In ``The Watcher,'' it's a city of anomie _
of isolation amid multitudes _ where no one knows you and no one
cares.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're all stacked on top of each other, but we don't really
notice each other'' goes the lament. Yet any police failures seem
more a function of bad luck than community indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Spader is suitably tense, intense, haunted and haggard, though
his suffering loses its sting when he galvanizes from despairing
loner to well-tailored top cop.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves uses his usual dispassion (or is that flat acting?) to
good effect as the coldhearted killer. But this also makes him
flavorless, apart from a twisted pleasure in dancing with victims.
Whoa _ what character development!
</P>
<P>
   Marisa Tomei also appears, continuing her post-Oscar slump since
1992's ``My Cousin Vinnie.'' She's the one with the bit part: an
emotionally fragile psychiatrist who's merely a victim in waiting.
</P>
<P>
   As a music-video veteran, Charbanic directs predictably,
emphasizing flashy but incoherent visuals. Often changing film
stocks and speeds, he deliberately distorts images until they
collide in a stylistic junk heap. He also scores the movie with a
jarring mix of inappropriate pop songs and corny orchestrations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his flourishes are so cliched they're an inadvertent
joke. Point-of-view shots with labored breathing seem like outtakes
from ``Scary Movie.''
</P>
<P>
   The story is also standard-issue, for all its showboating about
Reeves and Spader ``needing'' each other. ``You're like a brother
to me,'' Reeves proclaims. ``We define each other.''
</P>
<P>
   A defiant Spader sets him straight, pointing out that serial
killers are common, and Reeves' crimes are just another ``job.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, serial killings aren't at all common, despite their
maddening overuse in movies. If Spader's character has reason to be
burned out by them, then so do filmgoers everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
``The Watcher'' &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Starring: James Spader, Marisa Tomei, Keanu Reeves &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Director: Joe Charbanic &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Screenwriters: David Elliot and Clay Ayers &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Now showing: at area theaters &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Rating: R for violence and language &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Running time: 95 min. &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Grade: C-  &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL; 
$$$
</P>
</TEXT>
