<SLUG> BC-OLYSHARIF0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Abdur-Rahim happy about playing on Olympic team
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - This is the summer that life changed for Shareef
Abdur-Rahim.
</P>
<P>
   He was selected to the Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   He got married.
</P>
<P>
   What more could he want?
</P>
<P>
   ``A gold medal,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Well, that's coming, too.
</P>
<P>
   And once the USA Men's basketball team conquers the world in the
Sydney Olympics, Abdur-Rahim should shed his reputation as ``the
best player in the NBA nobody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, unless the Marietta native hits the Georgia lottery,
he's probably used up his good fortune for now. And that's just
fine by him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is enough, for sure,'' Abdur-Rahim said. ``It's a great
honor (to be on the Olympic team), and probably an honor I don't
fully understand right now and maybe won't until my career is over
something I'll look back on and tell my kids and, hopefully, my
grandkids about. It's going to be a big-time experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdur-Rahim, 23, is replacing Grant Hill. Now with the Orlando
Magic, Hill vacillated about accepting a spot because he was
getting married and the training would interfere with his plans. He
eventually backed out because of an ankle injury.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Lakers' Kobe Bryant declined an invitation for
the squad because he was getting married and did not want to
interrupt his plans. When USA Basketball summoned Abdur-Rahim, he
had no problem accepting.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics had been a childhood ambition. And he was marrying
Delisha Hodges on Aug. 6, which was enough time experience the
nuptials, enjoy a honeymoon and still have time to relax before the
start of training in Hawaii. So, Adbur-Rahim never hesitated in
jumping at the selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know that I was in heavy contention to be named
on the team, and I found out kind of all of a sudden,'' Abdur-Rahim
said. ``I was out playing and got a call, and it was very exciting.
As far as me getting married, I think I (had) enough time to spend
at that time with my wife before we had to leave. I think it is
more of a situation where she is very excited for me. and I
probably would have had to fuss and fight with her not to go. She's
excited. I'm excited. She understands how much something like this
means to me, so for both of us and my family, it is a no-brainer.''
</P>
<P>
   For the selection committee, Abdur-Rahim was a no-brainer for
the team. At 6 feet 9, the silky-smooth former Wheeler High star
can play all three frontline positions, which was significant.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Thorn, chairman of USA Basketball Men's Senior National
Team, said: ``He is one of the bright young stars in our league. He
fits right in with the other players that we have, and we're very
interested in having players who can play multiple positions, we're
very interested in having very flexible players, and he fits right
in with that. He can play three or four.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He can exploit smaller players by posting up and can use his
quickness to beat bigger players with his driving ability,'' Thorn
said. ``We now have a versatile, well-rounded team, and we are at
least three deep at every position, which is very important and is
insurance against injury. . . .I'm very excited about Shareef's
skill and talent level, but I also feel he is a great fit for this
team.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdur-Rahim's accomplishments in the NBA 20.3 points, 10.1
rebounds last year have gone widely unnoticed because he plays in
relative obscurity in Vancouver. The worldwide attention of the
Olympics could take Abdur-Rahim's fame to another level. Right?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure,'' he said. ``I'm not even really that concerned
with that and haven't been throughout my career. This is really not
something that you can get caught up with yourself and what it can
do for me. I'm just looking forward to going in and fitting in with
the guys and doing the best that we can do with the country and try
and bring home the gold.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Abdur-Rahim looks forward to the position of being on a
team favored to win. ``Yeah, without a doubt,'' he said. ``It's
been a while, three or four years, since I've been part of
something that was expected to win and win big, so that will be
exciting. I think everything (that happens) will be something I'll
try to remember, and I'll just try and soak it all up.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the whole thing remains somewhat overwhelming for
Abdur-Rahim.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, I just keep saying it's an accomplishment. This is an
honor. Anytime you're honored for anything, it's flattering. I've
been on teams that aren't winning, and I guess a true All-Star is
one that is able to help his team win, and until our team gets to
that point, I kind of understand. I think this is much more of an
accomplishment than any All-Star selection could be.''
</P>
<P>
   And it's outstanding recognition for a franchise that exists
north of the border and has not reached the playoffs in its five
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is big-time for our organization,'' Abdur-Rahim
said. ``We're an organization that doesn't get a lot of exposure,
and then, just for our fans, it gives our fans something to be
proud about and to cheer about. I think it is big time for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
