<HEADER>
A4370 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-EURO-FALLS-BOS &LR;      09-06 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-FALLS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EURO SUFFERS IN RETREAT TO DOLLARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The value of the battered euro plunged further against the
dollar Wednesday, as investors fled the recently minted currency of
a unified Europe to bet on a smooth-sailing US economy.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's decline, analysts said, was spurred by Wednesday's
report that US workers' productivity in the second quarter rose
even faster than estimated earlier. It was yet another sign of low
inflation and strong growth in the US economy, which has acted like
a giant vacuum, sucking in assets from around the globe and
boosting the dollar, at the expense of other currencies.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the euro's decline, Patrick Smith, portfolio manager
for the Pioneer Europe and Pioneer World Equity funds in Boston,
said, ``It's more dollar strength going on out there than it is
euro weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro, which has lost 30 percent of its value against the
dollar over the past year, sustained its biggest decline ever
Wednesday. It tumbled 2.3 percent, to a value of about 87 US cents.
A year ago, the euro was trading at about $1.05.
</P>
<P>
   European markets were down slightly Wednesday, though losses
were contained at under 1 percent of the three major index's value.
London's FTSE 100 index fell 57.8, to 6694.70, while on Germany's
stock market, the DAX declined 62.05, to 7333.02. France's bourse
saw a 59.97-point decline in its 40-stock index, to 6796.79.
</P>
<P>
   Such an exaggerated imbalance between the US dollar and the euro
may present an opportunity for investors with stamina to jump into
Europe, where economies are strengthening, even as its unified
currency softens, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Surging oil prices and inflation in Europe are dangers for
investors, though _ perhaps more so than in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The euro's skid this week began, traders said, after German
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder was quoted on Monday as saying, ``I
don't want to be long,'' or own a lot of euros. But Schroeder also
noted that the euro's decline was welcomed by European exporters. A
weak euro makes their goods less expensive overseas.
</P>
<P>
   A strong US dollar is one of the spillover effects of raising
interest rates _ a policy pursued by the Federal Reserve since June
1999.
</P>
<P>
   US bonds have attracted overseas investors, too, rallying in
recent months on growing confidence that the economy is slowing and
that the Fed is nearly at the end of its cycle of rate increases.
The central bank raised its benchmark rate to a nine-year high of
6.5 percent in May, but has not changed rates since then.
</P>
<P>
   The productivity figures may also encourage investment in US
securities if it means the Fed has achieved its goal of a ``soft
landing'' for the economy, with low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flows are going into the dollar,'' said Patrick Laub, chief
trader at Landesbank Hessen-Thueringen in Frankfurt, Germany. ``As
long as we have these capital flows, the euro will suffer.''
</P>
<P>
   The euro, a single regional currency introduced in stages in
Europe, has been battered almost nonstop since its January 1999
debut, losing 25 percent to date. After a brief run-up in May and
June, the currency slid again.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, European stock markets have had a respectable year,
nonetheless.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Henry, vice president of T. Rowe Price International in
Baltimore, noted that many markets in Europe, on a
domestic-currency basis, are actually outperforming US stock
markets. When US investors translate their euro-purchased stocks
into costly US dollars, however, the returns deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality for investors is dollar returns,'' Henry said.
</P>
<P>
   He and other money managers said they are optimistic about
Europe's future, though. Because the euro has fallen so much,
traders said, it has fallen below reasonable levels and will
inevitably snap back.
</P>
<P>
   A weak euro ``presents _ for those people with a little bit of
nerve and a little bit of vision to look out a few years _ an
excellent opportunity to shift assets out of dollars and into
euros,'' said Pioneer's Smith.
</P>
<P>
   And with Europe's economies improving, ``You're going to
eventually find Europe in the same sweet spot that the US is in
now,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
