<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CIRCUITS QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By J.D. BIERSDORFER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Is there any difference between a DSL line and a cable-modem
connection for high-speed Internet access?
</P>
<P>
   A. The two types of connections have several things in common,
like speeds much faster than a regular dial-up modem can offer and
the ability to be on all the time. And they usually download files
much faster than they upload them. But a cable connection and an
asynchronous digital subscriber line (commonly referred to as DSL)
differ in how they link you to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   A cable-modem setup uses the same type of wire that brings cable
television programming into your house. In general, cable
downloading speeds average 1 million bits per second, about 20
times as fast as a 56 kilobits-per-second modem (and can be even
faster). Cable is a shared line, though, and one reason the speeds
may vary is that when a lot of people are using that cable
connection, downloading speeds drop for everyone. One place to find
more information on cable modems is the Cable Modem Information
Network (www.cable-modem.net).
</P>
<P>
   A DSL connection is made through a phone line instead of a
shared cable, so speeds are more consistent. Some places advertise
a maximum of 1.54 megabits for downloading speed, but most
lower-priced DSL services for the home user offer downloading
speeds of 256 to 640 kilobits per second, or up to 11 times as fast
as a 56K modem. DSL technology can maximize the potential of your
phone line for transmitting data because it is possible to use the
same line for phone calls and DSL service. For more information
about DSL, visit www.adsl.com. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The response time from when I type a letter and when it
appears on the screen seems very slow on my new computer. Is there
anything I can do to fix that?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Check the cord connecting your keyboard to the computer and
make sure that everything is plugged in tightly. (If you have a
cordless keyboard, make sure that you are not farther away than the
manufacturer recommends.) Slow response time is often caused by
insufficient RAM or processor speed for the task at hand. A program
that you may have open in the background but are not using may be
taking up some of your processor's attention and causing the lag
you see between keys and screen. You might try closing all programs
except the one you are working in and see if the keyboard response
time improves.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases when a computer's memory and processor resources
are low, USB keyboards have been known to cause small delays in the
keyboard response time. Increasing your system resources by closing
programs might help in this situation as well.
</P>
<P>
   A full hard drive or temporary-file directory can also slow
things down, but if the computer is new, you may want to check with
the manufacturer's technical support department, especially if the
machine is still under warranty or you have free access to the
telephone help line.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have already used up all the USB ports on my computer, but
I want to add a USB scanner. Is there an easy way to do this?
</P>
<P>
   A. If you have used up your USB ports, you can purchase a hub
that lets you add more. It is a small device that plugs into one of
your computer's USB ports and offers you multiple slots to plug in
other USB peripherals.
</P>
<P>
   You can get hubs with three, four, seven or even more ports. You
can also link the hubs together to create more outlets for USB
equipment. Hubs are available in ``powered'' and ``nonpowered''
models. The powered hubs have their own electrical supply and
typically offer better performance because the hubs do not have to
rely solely on the power that runs through the USB cables, as the
nonpowered hubs do.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
