<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4377 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BAXTER-BUSH07-COX     09-06 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAXTER-BUSH07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New politics of surplus are tricky territory
 &HT;    By Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Before they begin falling to the winds of autumn, let's pause
for a moment to admire the majestic march of zeros that heralds the
onset of the fall presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   This week, while Al Gore, the Democrat, was laying out his
blueprint for what to do with a projected $4.6 trillion surplus,
George W. Bush, the Republican, was explaining his $198 billion
plan to add prescription drug coverage and other improvements to
Medicare. So many million-, billion- and trillion-dollar proposals
are being floated this fall, it's hard for the candidates, much
less the voters, to keep track of all the zeros going by.
</P>
<P>
   This remains a happy economy, when neither party is tempted to
preach hard times. It is also tricky ground for Bush, at least in
this phase of the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``My party has often pointed out the limits and flaws of the
Great Society,'' Bush said Tuesday. ``But there were successes as
well, and Medicare is one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely there are many Republican beneficiaries of
Medicare who would argue much with Bush's remark, but it
underscores the delicate task Bush must execute in reaching beyond
his conservative, anti-spending base to compete with Gore for a
broader spectrum of middle-class voters.
</P>
<P>
   There are significant differences in the two candidates'
proposals. Gore's prescription drug plan would cost $253 billion
compared to Bush's $158 billion, over 10 years. Bush's proposal
would rely more on free-market options. In some cases, the
Republican proposal is more generous to lower-income recipients
than Gore's plan, although the Democrats charge he can't pay for it
and deliver a major tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   But the politics of surplus are such that the differences
generally get expressed as a matter of degree. Spending has been
stamped on the public consciousness, with the energetic assistance
of the Republicans, as an essentially Democratic exercise. That
doesn't invalidate Bush's more modest proposals, but it makes it
easier for the Democrats to raise doubts about the Republican's
real commitment to spending the money Bush talks about.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulties of playing in this particular territory made
the media distractions of the week doubly unfortunate for the Bush
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   When Bill Clinton got caught on mike, it usually smacked of an
elaborate setup. Bush's unguarded remark to running mate Dick
Cheney this week revealed no such guile.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters will embrace this as a token of their
candidate's much-advertised genuineness, but it is the precise
difference between the two politicians.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign moved aggressively on the other distraction,
putting up an ad claiming Gore is backing down from his commitment
to appear on two TV interview show debates. Gore has said he would
appear on these debates if Bush agrees to three formal debates run
by the bipartisan Presidential Commission on Debates, while Bush
wants only one commission debate.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving aside the hair-splitting, it's hard to see what
advantage Bush gains by protracting this argument. There is a
reasonable argument that Bush ought to sign on to as many debates
as possible, decreasing the impact of any gaffe and deflating
Gore's claim he's trying to duck him.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, it's to Bush's advantage to settle the debate
question as quickly as possible, and maneuver his message back into
familiar territory.
</P>
<P>
   (salinity) O N T H E W E B : Political news and commentary:
coxnews.com/2000
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
