<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0277 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4378 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-GORE-BUDGET-HNS &LR;      09-06 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Gore unveils detailed long-range economic plan
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By BENNETT ROTH
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Hoping to dazzle voters with 191 pages of budget
figures and analysis, Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore
Wednesday unveiled a long-range economic plan that he pledged would
eliminate the national debt, reduce poverty, increase family
savings and add jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In an address at Cleveland State University, Gore outlined a
comprehensive 10-year plan for use of the projected budget surplus
that contained little that is new, but compiled and repackaged many
of the ideas he has rolled out during the course of his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing this because I don't want you to have to read the
tea leaves, or read between the lines of a press release or
position paper to know what the Gore-Lieberman administration would
mean for families,'' said Gore.
</P>
<P>
   And in a play on George W. Bush's father's broken pledge of
``read my lips _ no new taxes','' Gore told a supportive audience,
``Instead you can just read my plan _ a detailed economic plan that
spells out line by line, how we can make prosperity work for
America's families.''
</P>
<P>
   In conjunction with the address, the candidate released a
191-page glossy paperback filled with numbers, graphs and a listing
of 10 economic goals for a Gore administration that mixes
conservative fiscal policy with populist programs.
</P>
<P>
   The goals include eliminating the debt by 2012, raising family
income by one third and cutting the earning gap between men and
women by half, bringing down the poverty rate by 10 percent, and
creating 10 million high-tech jobs.
</P>
<P>
   The document, titled ``Prosperity for America's Families,'' was
reminiscent of Bill Clinton's ``Putting People First'' _ a catalog
of initiatives published during the president's 1992 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore book also served to underscore a message the candidate
has pushed since the Democratic National Convention _ that he puts
forth detailed proposals while Bush offers slogans and
generalities. The Gore campaign posted the blueprint on his Web
site, www.algore.com.
</P>
<P>
   Bush struck back, telling about 1,000 supporters at a campaign
rally in Indianapolis that he could summarize Gore's plan: ``It
says keep sending all of your money to Washington, and I'll be glad
to spend it for you.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett dubbed Gore's book a ``200-page
press release'' and said it included spending that would bust the
federal budget.
</P>
<P>
   But in his address, Gore suggested that his plan was more
fiscally responsible than Bush's, arguing that the governor would
be unable to pay down the debt because of the high cost of his $1.3
trillion tax cut proposal, coupled with a range of new spending.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested his opponent was relying on the same faulty
economic assumptions that guided the Reagan and Bush
administrations during the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``My plan wasn't built on the cross-your-fingers economics that
says we can give more to the people who have the most _ and then
just hope the benefits trickle down to the middle class,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But in one concession to his Republican opponent, Gore embraced
the projections by the Congressional Budget Office, which has
estimated that the budget surplus during the next 10 years would be
$300 million larger than the Clinton administration has calculated.
Gore had earlier criticized the Texas governor for relying on
overly rosy budget projections.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore said he would not use extra surplus money as Bush has
proposed to give out bigger tax cuts and pay the transition costs
of letting people invest a portion of their Social Security taxes
in the private market.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Democratic contender said he would deposit the
extra $300 million in a reserve fund to be used for emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our national government should do what so many families have
done for years _ set aside some money for a rainy day to be
absolutely certain that we never spend money we don't have,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to his budget document, Gore would divvy up the $4.5
billion in projected surplus in this way:
</P>
<P>
   Slightly more than $1.5 billion would be allotted to a variety
of new spending programs and a $500 billion tax cut. The remaining
$3 billion would be used to pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has conceded that his plan would not eliminate
the debt until 2016 in part because of the high cost of phasing in
the Bush Social Security plan.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's economic blueprint immediately drew fire from Bush
and other Republicans who claimed that the Democrat was
underestimating the costs of his programs and exaggerating the
impact of the governor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore's spending program and `rainy day' fund overspend the
surplus by $906 billion, leaving Social Security and Medicare high
and dry,'' said Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the Bush campaign took out a half-page USA Today
ad, which touted the endorsement of the governor's proposals by a
list of academics, business people and others who worked at
conservative think tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Republican majority on the Senate Budget
Committee issued an analysis of the Gore's budget plan that claimed
that his programs would exceed the projected surplus by $27 billion
to $900 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides countered that the Republicans had dramatically
overestimated the price tag of a number of Gore programs, including
a tax credit to encourage people to save for retirement and a
college tuition tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   To help sell his economic plan, Gore brought along Robert Rubin,
a former Clinton administration Treasury secretary and Wall Street
executive. In his introductory remarks, Rubin called Gore's
blueprint, ``the most detailed economic plan offered by any
presidential candidate in my memory.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Vice President Gore was the center of all major economic
decisions of this administration,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   In a jab at Bush's plan, Rubin said, ``Fiscal discipline is not
easy. Tax cuts are a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
