<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4380 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-GRAPHICS-CARDS-NY     09-06 1214
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-GRAPHICS-CARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW GRAPHICS CARD TECHNOLOGY TRANSFORMS PC GAMING TO CINEMATIC
EXPERIENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By MICHAEL MARRIOTT  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, the only home computer users who cared about
seeing high-quality images on their monitors were hard-core gamers.
</P>
<P>
   But in the last few years, that circle has expanded to include
people who watch DVD movies on their computers or edit digital
photographs or videos on the weekends. And yes, some of them may
even be tempted to play the occasional game of Quake III.
</P>
<P>
   All that focuses more attention on a generally overlooked
computer component: the graphics card.
</P>
<P>
   For years, home and office computers worked quite nicely without
graphics cards. The electronic components that helped the computer
render routine, two-dimensional images were built into the main
circuit board. But as the demand for more powerful computer
graphics increased (first brought on by the heavy graphics demands
of the early Windows operating system), the circuitry designed to
produce graphics, especially 3-D images, evolved into powerful,
separate circuit boards that plug into computers' motherboards.
</P>
<P>
   Those boards _ also called video boards, graphics accelerator
cards and game boards _ are a collection of components for
processing graphics quickly, a process known as acceleration. Each
graphics card has its own microprocessor and packs megabytes of its
own memory, arranged on a board the size of a graham cracker.
</P>
<P>
   Practically overnight a confusing crop of graphics cards has
sprung up, each promising great enhancements for what can actually
be seen on computer monitors.
</P>
<P>
   For home computer users with gaming aspirations, almost any card
that comes with 64 megabytes of memory and can handle OpenGL,
DirectX and Glide _ all video game standards _ will fit the bill.
For the average consumer who just wants to play a few modest
computer games, a low-end graphics card with 2 MB to 8 MB of memory
will work fine. Even the built-in graphics cards, the kind likely
to be found in a budget computer, are adequate.
</P>
<P>
   Graphics cards come in two types: PCI (Peripheral Component
Interconnect) and AGP (Accelerated or Advanced Graphics Port).
These abbreviations refer to the expansion slot the cards occupy on
computer motherboards. The AGP slot, found on almost all computers
made in the last several years, is better suited for a graphics
card.
</P>
<P>
   I looked at three highly rated, high-performance graphics cards,
each made to work in an AGP slot and all for PCs: the Voodoo5 5500
AGP by 3dfx, the Radeon 64-MB DDR by ATI and the 3D Prophet II GTS
64 MB by Hercules, a division of Guillemot. Each card has 64
megabytes of memory, important for delivering high resolutions for
larger monitors (19 inch and up). Each is supposed to deliver high
levels of color and 3-D acceleration, a must for demanding games.
</P>
<P>
   Each card was a marvel of engineering. But the Voodoo5 5500 was,
pound for pound, the, uh, heaviest. The board, with its outsize
length (just over 9.5 inches) and two on-board cooling fans, has
macho appeal. And get this: the card needs so much juice that it
plugs into the computer's main power supply. Most cards draw all
the electricity they need from the slot that connects them to the
motherboard.
</P>
<P>
   Once it was snapped into place and its software installed
(itself a snap), the Voodoo5 came to life and instantly produced
noticeable improvements on my 19-inch display. Taking advantage of
this card's 2-D accelerator, DVD movies appeared to have more
depth, color, detail and vibrancy. But it was under game conditions
where the Voodoo5 5500 showed its true colors. Revving up its 3-D
accelerator capabilities, the Voodoo5 called upon its processing
muscle to render game environments, equipment and characters
smoothly and rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The company that makes the Voodoo5 says that its technology is
capable of drawing 667 megapixels every second. (The faster the
pixels are drawn, the better the image resolution.) The card, which
costs $299, also did a good job of reducing the number of jagged
edges you often see when running computer games with inadequate
graphics cards.
</P>
<P>
   But after several days of use, I noticed that the Voodoo5 raised
the temperature of my motherboard, sometimes making it so hot that
I had to shut my computer down for a few minutes. Especially good
computer case ventilation is a must for this monster card.
</P>
<P>
   The Radeon, which costs $399, was also simple to install and
began working right away. It was particularly impressive handling
DVD movies and images, eliminating the need for a separate MPEG-2
decoder card, which many DVD-ROM makers require or include. With
the Radeon alone, DVD movies could be played full-screen with good
color depth and resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Radeon also played 3-D computer games well, with resolutions
as high as 2,048 by 1,536 pixels, the same as the Voodoo5. But the
Radeon's images were not as clean as those rendered by the Voodoo5.
It draws only 366 megapixels per second but compensates in other
ways.
</P>
<P>
   The Radeon does offer some handy pluses: a TV Out port for
sending computer-generated images over included cables to a
television set (preferably one with a large screen) and
video-capture capability to store images seen on television.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the third card, the 3-D Prophet II, which was the
hands-down winner in practically all the categories and in a few
that only it offered.
</P>
<P>
   For all of its optimized processing might and 64 MB of on-board
memory, the Prophet II is surprisingly unassuming in size. It fits
easily into its AGP slot, but installation was a bit of a task,
requiring the complete removal of any software from previous
graphics cards (at least a three-step process).
</P>
<P>
   Once it was in and its software was installed, the Prophet
started showing off. Its makers say the card will deliver 800
megapixels a second.
</P>
<P>
   The Prophet easily handles very high 2-D and 3-D resolutions, up
to 2,048 by 1,536 pixels. DVD movies looked especially clear and
detailed when played through this card. The Prophet also has a TV
Out port and something the other cards don't: a DVI _ Digital
Visual Interface &UR;  &LR; _ enabling newer digital monitors to be plugged
right into this card. The Voodoo5 and Radeon are not set up to
handle digital monitors.
</P>
<P>
   The Prophet easily handled the most demanding video games,
making Quake III look downright cinematic. Textures, lighting and
shading were all superior, and the card's rendering of 3-D
environments was at least as clean as Voodoo5's.
</P>
<P>
   But there is a downside to the Prophet _ its price. At $420,
this card is one of the most expensive consumer cards on the
market. That cost might be especially hard to justify if you are
not concerned about seeing your computer games played on a digital
flat-screen monitor or if you're not interested in using an LCD
projector to stun colleagues with the most visually dazzling
PowerPoint presentation they are likely to see. For less money, the
Voodoo5 is a better buy.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not a serious gamer and do not mind good VCR-type
quality images on your computer's DVD, stick with your old
eight-megabyte graphics card, which probably came with the wonder
PC you bought a few years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
