<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4383 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-SPORTS-SEXISM-GO     09-06 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-SPORTS-SEXISM-GOODRIDGE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN TENNIS, A GENDER WAR ISN'T EQUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, Sept. 7, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By FRANCIE KRAKER GOODRIDGE    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANN ARBOR, Mich. _ I'm glad to see that in the face of John
McEnroe's petulant insistence that not only he but ``any good male
college player'' could beat them, Venus and Serena Williams have
responded with both dignity and humor. Laughter is an especially
appropriate answer to McEnroe's childish display of wounded egoism,
but there are serious issues here, too.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing seems all too familiar. In 1973, I found myself
denigrated, along with three Soviet athletes, the track star
Lyudmila Bragina and the Press sisters, in the maunderings of
George Gilder in his book ``Sexual Suicide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mss. Bragina and Kraker and the Press sisters enter the
athletic realm on male terms,'' he wrote. ``While often performing
impressive feats _ for women _ and sometimes defeating a few lesser
male competitors, they cannot fulfill the Olympian ideal of sport.
In fact, when intruding on the male athletic arena, women may serve
only to detract from its symbolic and ritual content and thus its
value in male socialization.'' I read the chapter in a bookstore
and laughed, astounded at such nonsense.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, the distance runner Steve Prefontaine scoffed
at the world record set in the women's indoor mile by Francie
Larrieu, saying, ``I can run six 4:29 miles in a row.'' Soon
afterward, I wrote in The New York Times that comparisons of the
relative performances of men and women are pointless. Now I find
myself making the same obvious point again.
</P>
<P>
   Billie Jean King has been quoted as saying that a new version of
her 1973 match with Bobby Riggs, with McEnroe playing against one
of the Williamses, would be ``great.'' Much as I admire King, she
is wrong. It was not great to pit women against men 25 years ago,
when girls and women were battling to take the first steps toward
equal opportunity in sports, and it would not be great now, when we
still have far to go.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics revealed under federal law show a clear remaining
gap. Most large intercollegiate athletic programs are still not in
compliance with Title IX, the civil rights law requiring parallel
athletic opportunities for women and men in educational
institutions that accept federal aid. And when a school drops a
men's sport as a means of equalizing sports offerings, blame is
often assigned to the law and to women, rather than to the
administrators who take this cheap and damaging way out.
</P>
<P>
   We all know that in most sports, competing against men would not
give women equal opportunity. Even in events like the New York City
Marathon, where thousands of men and women run together, they have
separate championships. And no matter what rivalries between the
genders unfold on the city's streets during those hours, women and
men undoubtedly care more at the end of the day about how well they
did against their own sex, because it is the most valid comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Why, then, does John McEnroe feel compelled to denigrate women's
performances, apparently somehow resenting that women were given
credit and admired?
</P>
<P>
   I am glad the Williams sisters have indicated no interest in
being drawn into some trumped-up, media-hyped new battle of the
sexes. By dismissing the idea, they do what is right for themselves
and for other girls and women. Why let the threatened male ego
create a circus and intrude yet again on our own competition?
</P>
<P>
   (Francie Kraker Goodridge, a track and field coach, was on the
U.S. Olympics track teams in 1968 and 1972.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
