<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4384 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-OPED-BUSH-MEDICARE-EP     09-06 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-BUSH-MEDICARE-EPSTEIN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW APPROACH TO MEDICARE IS NEEDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for Thursday, Sept. 7, and thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's OPED news service. For more information
about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _ or becoming a
client of the OPED news service _ contact one of the New York Times
Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the text.)  
 By RICHARD A. EPSTEIN    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The health care debate has heated up in earnest with
George W. Bush's detailed proposal to overhaul Medicare. On this
issue, Bush seeks to meld the best of the open market with what he
terms the nation's ``moral obligation'' to secure the health needs
of the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   His plan rejects Al Gore's flawed strategy of shoring up the
existing Medicare system and expanding it to include prescription
drugs. In its stead, Bush hopes that private insurers would compete
to supply senior citizens with an expansive package of medical
benefits for a fee underwritten in part by the federal government.
But the elderly could also stick with the basic Medicare program.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, this plan won't induce many insurers to offer
expanded health care packages. Bush may lure customers; but he
won't attract any insurer that speaks to its actuaries first.
Offering individuals insurance options may work in settings where
they do not already know their medical condition. But this approach
can't work for populations that have intimate knowledge of their
own health profiles.
</P>
<P>
   Suppose the government offers to pay a private health plan
$5,000 toward coverage of any enrollee that signs up for its
souped-up health plan. Older seniors with chronic illnesses, for
example, will surely flock to the plan, even with a required
copayment; but healthier and younger seniors are much more likely
to stick with Medicare, because they won't want to pay for the
extra coverage. What insurance carrier will cover high-risk
patients for premiums calibrated to some group average by the
federal government? Bush's proposal will not wean the elderly from
government programs. It will only reaffirm the status quo.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposal, on the other hand, could easily make things
worse. He seeks to tap into the common sentiment that health care
is a special good that markets cannot be trusted to properly
supply. But the gloomy economist reminds us that two constraints
still apply.
</P>
<P>
   First, any system of uniform prices shelters companies that can
only supply health care services at high cost.
</P>
<P>
   Second, increased health care subsidies lead to increased health
care consumption _ to be paid for by someone else, with no ceiling
to limit costs. This pattern of consumption goes a long way to
explaining the looming Medicare deficits.
</P>
<P>
   The seeds for Medicare's long-term woes were sown by its very
passage in 1965. The program subsidizes the elderly as a class at
the expense of the general taxpayer. And it imposes little
financial burden on recipients when they receive medical services.
To slow down consumer demand while keeping prices under control,
Medicare has instead adopted countless strategems, including
monitoring hospitals and doctors, imposing delays on services and
raising taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's program will do nothing to relieve these pressures. Far
from it, his prescription drug plan (more generous and hence more
flawed than Bush's) will surely increase the overall cost of
running Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to think of a sensible way out of this hole. It is
intolerable to force millions of people to pay for medical benefits
that they long thought they enjoyed as a right.
</P>
<P>
   But at the very least, both parties should stop serving up
endless plates of goodies. Instead, before the next economic
downturn hits, the next president should forthrightly work to trim
coverage and increase the out-of-pocket amount people contribute in
Medicare copayments. Both political parties should try to reduce
the costs of getting new drugs to market. Either we sober up today,
or we reap the whirlwind tomorrow, no matter who wins the next
election.
</P>
<P>
   (Richard A. Epstein, a law professor at the University of
Chicago, is author of ``Mortal Peril: Our Inalienable Right to
Health Care?'')
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on OPED
articles and other features.
</P>
<P>
   NONSUBSCRIBERS: To publish a `separate-buy' feature article, it
must be purchased. Please contact one of these sales
representatives:
</P>
<P>
   --U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at
1-732-390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   --Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   --Latin America: ANA PENA in New York, 212-499-3333; fax,
212-499-3382.
</P>
