<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4385 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-INDIANS-CANNIBALS     09-06 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-INDIANS-CANNIBALS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STRONG EVIDENCE OF CANNIBALISM BY PREHISTORIC INDIANS IS REPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Southwest)  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOHN NOBLE WILFORD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scientists have found what they say is the first direct evidence
of cannibalism among prehistoric Indians in the American Southwest,
belying the image of these people as steadfastly peaceful farmers
and perhaps reigniting a smoldering controversy over whether
ancestral Indians ever made it a practice to eat human flesh.
</P>
<P>
   At the site of an ancient Anasazi settlement near Mesa Verde in
southwestern Colorado, archaeologists came upon butchered human
bones and stone cutting tools stained with human blood. A ceramic
cooking pot held residues of human tissues. But the most telling
evidence was found in human feces: biochemical tests revealed clear
traces of digested human muscle protein in the dried coprolite, or
preserved prehistoric feces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analysis of the coprolite and associated remains at last
provides definitive evidence for sporadic cannibalism in the
Southwest,'' Dr. Brian R. Billman, an archaeologist at the
University of North Carolina, said Wednesday in an announcement of
the discovery.
</P>
<P>
   The biochemist who conducted the tests, Dr. Richard A. Marlar of
the University of Colorado School of Medicine in Denver, said the
only way this particular human protein, myoglobin, would be present
in the feces was if the person had eaten human flesh. The tests and
other research were repeated many times over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt we had to be absolutely sure on such a sensitive and
controversial issue,'' Marlar said in an interview. ``I have no
doubt about this data.''
</P>
<P>
   The research team described and interpreted the findings in a
report being published in Thursday's issue of the journal Nature.
In an accompanying commentary, Dr. Jared M. Diamond, an
anthropologist at the University of California at Los Angeles,
called the research ``compelling evidence'' of the practice of
cannibalism by some ancestral Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Donald Grayson, an anthropologist at the University of
Washington who specializes in prehistoric people in the American
West, said in an interview that he was not surprised by the
findings. ``I was already convinced by the evidence of butchering
marks and bones from archaeological sites,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Archaeologists think that cannibalism among people in the
American Southwest occurred between the years 900 and 1150, but was
fairly rare. Then, for about 50 years, during a severe drought, the
evidence suggests that there was an outbreak of cannibalism.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Diamond described this ``customary cannibalism'' as the
consumption of human flesh, from either deceased relatives or slain
enemies, as a non-emergency practice and not just something a group
may resort to in the face of starvation, as the Donner Party of
American pioneers did in 1846.
</P>
<P>
   The mounting evidence was described by Dr. Christy Turner II, an
anthropologist at Arizona State University in Tempe, in his book,
``Man Corn: Cannibalism and Violence in the Prehistoric American
Southwest,'' published last year by the University of Utah Press.
Turner is on an expedition to Siberia and could not be reached for
comment on the new findings.
</P>
<P>
   But the evidence is still disputed by some anthropologists and
especially by modern American Indians, offended at the perceived
insults to their ancestors. Archaeologists who reported suspected
cannibalism said they were sometimes accused of contributing to
racism and genocide. Some early European colonists used stories of
Indian cannibalism as justification for their conquests of the
land.
</P>
<P>
   The debate intensified after Dr. William Arens, an
anthropologist at the State University of New York at Stony Brook,
argued in an influential book, ``The Man-Eating Myth,'' that there
have been no reliable, firsthand accounts of cannibalism. So he
doubted the very existence of the practice, except perhaps when
people are facing death by starvation.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to reach Arens for comment were unsuccessful. But in a
1998 article in The New Yorker magazine, he was quoted as having
apparently changed his mind. Asked about Turner's research, Arens
said that cannibalism is a ``possible interpretation, even a good
intepretation.''
</P>
<P>
   All previous evidence of occasional Indian cannibalism, though
increasingly persuasive, was still circumstantial. Finding the
human feces in an abandoned kiva, or pit house, in Colorado opened
the way to gathering direct evidence.
</P>
<P>
   When archaeological sites in the foothills of Sleeping Ute
Mountain were about to be destroyed by newly irrigated agricultural
fields, the Ute tribe called in Soil Systems Inc., a private
archaeological excavation company in Phoenix. Dr. Billman, who
worked for the company then, led the investigation of a community
of 70 to 125 people that existed there between the years 1130 and
1150.
</P>
<P>
   It was a time of severe drought, one of the worst the American
West in the last 2,000 years. The Anasazis' descendants are today's
Indian tribes such as the Hopi and Zuni, who have never practiced
cannibalism and object to archaeologists' inferences of cannibalism
by their prehistoric ancestors.
</P>
<P>
   Many Anasazi settlements, including Chaco Canyon in New Mexico,
failed and were abandoned in the drought. Billman said the small
Colorado site he studied was abandoned suddenly. No one had time to
remove tools, grinding stones and other valuable materials. The
piles of human bones showed that at least 35 adults and children
were butchered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the entire community was extinguished in a single
episode of violence and terroristic cannibalism during a period of
social chaos brought on by the drought,'' Billman said.
</P>
<P>
   The raiders may have considered the people intruders on their
own withered farming land and had to be driven away. After killing,
cooking and eating seven people in one dwelling, one of the raiders
squatted over the cold ashes of the hearth and defecated, a parting
sign of contempt.
</P>
<P>
   When Billman told this story at an archaeological meeting,
Marlar, an amateur archaeologist as well as biochemist, offered to
try to develop a technique for testing the feces for any traces of
human tissues. Biochemical assay techniques have been used before
to identify animal meat residues in cooking pots at archaeological
sites. Tests of the coprolite showed that the person had eaten
almost nothing but meat in the last 18 hours or so. And the
presence of the human myoglobin, the journal Nature said, was
``incontrovertible evidence of cannibalism.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Nature report, Markar, Billman and their colleagues
concluded, ``With the presentation of the first direct evidence of
cannibalism in the American Southwest in the prehistoric era, we
hope that the debate will shift from the question of whether or not
cannibalism occurred to questions concerning the social context,
causes and consequences of these events.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
