<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SAYS GORE'S PROMISES WOULD WIPE OUT THE SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT14 and NYT15 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS, Ind. _ Gov. George W. Bush opened a new line of
attack against his Democratic rival Wednesday, accusing Vice
President Al Gore of making so many promises in this campaign that
he would eat through the entire $4.6 trillion federal surplus
projected for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Bush chose the economy and fiscal policy as his targets on the
same day that Gore unveiled an ambitious and detailed economic
blueprint that called for the creation of a $300 billion rainy day
fund to be set aside for emergencies, like if the economy slows
down.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign took out a full page advertisement in USA
Today quoting six Nobel laureates and nearly 300 other economists
praising Bush's approach to fiscal policy. The Texas governor also
seized on an analysis released by Republicans on the Senate Budget
Committee, who said the vice president's programs could cost more
than $900 billion more than he has estimated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want America to add up all the promises my opponent has
made,'' Bush told a crowd at an airport rally in Scranton, Pa.,
early Wednesday morning. ``All the promises over the course of this
campaign. He has the easy style of campaigning. Go to one community
and make a promise here, go to another community. When you add it
all up he's spent the entire surplus on bigger government. He won't
admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor stood before a large blowup poster of the USA
Today ad and used it to contrast his economic plan with Gore's.
``My plan has been endorsed by these Nobel prize winners and
leading economists,'' Bush said. ``His plan has been endorsed by
Bill Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's charges were a mirror image of the Gore campaign's
assertions that it is the Republican nominee who is threatening the
surplus with his spending programs and his proposal to enact a $1.3
trillion tax cut over 10 years. When Bush unveiled a $198 billion
plan on Tuesday to change the Medicare system, Gore said, ``There
is no money to pay for it if you give away all of the surplus in
the form of a giant tax cut for the wealthy.''
</P>
<P>
   At every campaign rally, Bush is now featuring blue-collar
families who he says would receive large reductions under his tax
cut plan, but who would receive little to nothing from Gore's
proposals for smaller, more targeted tax cuts for such expenses as
college education or home health care. ``We trust you with your
money,'' Bush told crowds Wednesday as he promoted his tax cut in
Pennsylvania, Wisconsin and Indiana. ``We trust you to make
decisions with your lives. We don't trust bureaucrats in
Washington, D.C. We don't believe in planners and deciders making
decisions on behalf of America.''
</P>
<P>
   At another airport rally here he appropriated Gore's theme of
helping ``working families'' and thundered, ``Guess which plan is
on the side of the working people? It's our plan. It's our plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's turn to economic themes Wednesday was echoed by his
running mate, Dick Cheney, who, campaigning before a chamber of
commerce in Wilmington, Del., said that he believed the economic
policies of President Reagan should get a strong measure of credit
for the booming economy of the last eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Answering a question from a member of the audience, Cheney
compared Bush's tax cut proposal to Reagan's own income tax cuts of
two decades ago, saying that it was ``exactly what we did to get
this prosperity begun in the first place, back in the early '80s
under President Reagan.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, speaking to reporters, Cheney said the boom was created
by 20 years of strong leadership by the Federal Reserve, reductions
in military spending after the Cold War and the tax policies of
Reagan and even those of President George Bush. ``My analysis would
be a 20-year look at the economy and policy, not just the last
eight years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Still later in the day, an aide said Cheney wanted to clarify
that he also gave a measure of credit to President Clinton for
``reluctantly signing'' fiscal measures approved by the Republican
Congress,
</P>
<P>
   The argument over surpluses and deficits is a muddy one because
accounts of how much each candidate will spend depends on estimates
and projections.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Republican analysis found, for example, that Gore's
proposals would overshoot the available surplus by as little as $27
billion over 10 years if the costs of Gore's spending plans are
assumed to be at the low end of credible estimates.
</P>
<P>
   If the costs of the spending plans are assumed to be at the high
end of estimates, Gore's budget would be in the red by as much as
$906 billion over 10 years, the report said. For example, the
report noted that Gore says his plan to increase retirement savings
would cost $200 billion over 10 years, while other estimates put
the cost at as much as $750 billion. The Gore campaign dismissed
the report as partisan.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign says that the governor's own budget plan
leaves a $265 billion surplus. But John Cogan, an economics adviser
to Bush, acknowledged Wednesday as he was briefing reporters on
Gore's spending that the Bush figures did not account for the costs
of deploying a missile defense system, but only for research and
development. Bush has called for a far more robust system than the
one that Clinton had been contemplating at a cost of $60 billion.
Cogan argued that Bush could make other savings in military
spending to offset the costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
