<SLUG> BC-AIRFARES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business airfares expected to increase
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Business travelers can expect to dig deeper into their pockets
to pay for their airline tickets next year, a survey by American
Express's travel service unit says.
</P>
<P>
   Robust demand for travel and soaring jet fuel prices will push
business airfares up to 5 percent higher next year. That increase
is slightly less than the annual 6 percent jump business tickets
have averaged in the past two years, which followed a period in
which fares were fairly flat.
</P>
<P>
   In the second quarter of this year, the ``typical business
fare'' nationwide was an average of $778 roundtrip. That fare,
based on an average of the lowest fully refundable coach fare in
selected markets, will rise to $817 next year, American Express
predicts. Other factors in the airline industry could influence how
much travelers pay. In fact, United Airlines has pledged not to
raise fares for two years if it is allowed to merge with US
Airways. The exception, United has said, is if fuel prices _ now
near record levels _ continue climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ''The thing that's going to control this is the big promise
United made during the merger,'' said David Stempler, president of
the Air Travelers Association, a travel advocacy group. ''If they
hold the line, it's going to be very difficult to raise fares.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, airlines have boosted business fares 7 percent since
January, with several of the increases tied to the rising cost of
jet fuel, the airlines' second-highest expense after labor. Fuel
could push prices even higher: On Wednesday, crude oil rose to
$34.90 a barrel, the highest since the Gulf War in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines won't be the only companies charging business travelers
more next year. American Express sees hotel rates climbing 6
percent and rental car rates up 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
