<SLUG> BC-IXL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IXL walks fine line, analyst warns
 &HT;    By Kathy Brister
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Atlanta-based iXL Enterprises Inc.'s stock, battered in recent
days by an earnings warning and the loss of a key executive,
continued its decline Wednesday, closing at $6.94, down 6 cents.
</P>
<P>
   IXL this week announced cost-cutting measures, including
layoffs, meant to bolster the stock. But job cuts could hurt the
company by bruising employee morale, analysts warned.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies in the same category as iXL _ those that develop
online strategies, Web sites and Internet applications for other
firms _ also have seen a slowdown in business and a sag in stock
prices.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Executive Bert Ellis said Tuesday iXL would begin trimming
``anything that isn't productive to the company,'' including
employees. IXL wouldn't elaborate. The company employs 3,000
worldwide and 800 locally.
</P>
<P>
   BB&AMP;T Capital Markets analyst Thomas Neuhaus gave iXL's planned
layoffs mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``(IXL's) hired a lot of people anticipating greater demand.
Cutting that excess is a positive,'' Neuhaus said.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is how the job cuts could affect employee morale, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``With iXL, all it has to sell is its people,'' he said. ``IXL's
assets walk out the door every day at 5 p.m.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Malever, chief executive officer of Atlanta-based
recruiting firm Lanta Technology Group, said he's seen an
increasing number of iXL resumes. He said morale drops as stock
dips, and that employees start looking for other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   But iXL employees are talented, and the company name adds weight
to resumes, Malever said. He expects most will be absorbed easily
into Atlanta's booming economy.
</P>
<P>
   Neuhaus said iXL must build declining revenue and attract new,
large clients to stand alongside customers like Virgin-Atlantic and
General Electric, which has a 9 percent stake in iXL.
</P>
<P>
   It's worrisome the company hasn't announced a large contract in
about three months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 20 percent of iXL's revenue comes from start-up
e-commerce firms, yet its troubles are rooted in their growing
pains, Neuhaus said. He said ``the funding environment for dot-coms
went from being extremely robust to almost drying up completely''
after the Nasdaq's spring nose dive.
</P>
<P>
   If the downward spiral had stopped there, iXL probably could
have held tight.
</P>
<P>
   But, less concerned about a competitive threat from fast-moving
start-ups, big firms slowed online plans and stopped snapping up
iXL's services.
</P>
<P>
   Neuhaus predicted a market shakeout but said IXL has the
strength to survive such an evolution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
