<HEADLINE>
FOR LOVERS OF LATIN BEATS, WEB SITES PROLIFERATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(Eds.: Please note that tilde in parentheses has been used in the
12th graf instead of the actual tilde character, which is
non-transmittable to some newspaper systems.) 
 By DEBRA A. KLEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Ricky Martin swiveled his hips at the 1999 Grammys, he set
off a tide of Latin pop record sales in this country.
</P>
<P>
   A year and a half later, on the eve of the first Latin Grammys,
a new group of Internet entrepreneurs is trying to ride that tide
by offering Latin music Web sites that include crash courses in the
different rhythms of mambo, bomba and merengue, and also sell the
latest salsa and rock en Espanol CDs.
</P>
<P>
   And while many Spanish-language music sites originate from
Brazil and Mexico, these upstarts from the United States are in
English to attract a new audience: bilingual Hispanic-Americans as
well as fans who do not speak Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   Francisco de la Torre founded Eritmo.com (www2.eritmo.com) one
year ago to fill a void on the Net. Latin music styles vary from
country to country, de la Torre reasoned, so Eritmo.com (``ritmo''
means rhythm in Spanish) customizes news and information with
separate pages and headlines from Puerto Rico, Mexico, Brazil,
Argentina, Venezuela and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Eritmo.com publishes limited concert reviews, news and opinion
articles, and music rankings by country. It also has chats, puzzles
and games. Its Supermall sells CDs by top-of-the-charts Latin
performers and links users to a site to make their own CDs.
</P>
<P>
   If Eritmo.com feels like the sterile but stocked neighborhood
superstore, the LaMusica.com site (www.lamusica.com) is a fan's
basement, crammed with colorful photos and video interviews with
the stars of the Latin pop, salsa, merengue and Tejano scenes. What
LaMusica.com does best is to give access to small concerts and
corner top performers in interesting places. When visited recently,
the site had an interview with Son by Four in Central Park and one
with Marc Anthony, holding forth from a bed (fully clothed). The
site includes timely reviews of festivals sponsored by radio
stations and of rare concert appearances, and links to Latin music
radio shows featuring styles like freestyle and Latin jazz.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish word ``descarga'' means ``to unload,'' but it also
refers to a type of musical jam session. In that spirit,
Descarga.com (www.descarga.com) is an amalgam of opinion,
instruction and sales. Critical essays that assume familiarity with
major figures in Latin music, and rare recordings and percussion
instruments, like afuches and timbales, for sale make the site seem
like a Greenwich Village music shop on the Web. The glossary is
basic but useful for those encountering decades of Latin music for
the first time. The catalog includes hard-to-find recordings like
Israel (Cachao) Lopez's Cuban jam sessions and Afro-Cuban Santeria
vocal and drum music.
</P>
<P>
   Two-year-old LA'Ritmo.com (www.laritmo.com) offers Top 25 charts
in several Latin music genres, as well as the Tu Ritmo collection
of digital sound clips, a handy sampling tool that gives beginners
who cannot decipher Spanish labels a place to start looking for
Latin CDs. The Latino Wired news link chugs with the latest
industry music news and is updated daily; the extensive archives of
reviews, charts and interviews go back two years.
</P>
<P>
   Dgolpe.com (www.dgolpe.com) offers a vast English-, Spanish- and
Portuguese-language digital catalog for downloading, and though the
six-month-old site's name is a pun on the Spanish word for coup,
Dgolpe.com insists that all of its MP3 downloads are legal.
</P>
<P>
   Ritmoteca.com (www.ritmoteca.com), which made its debut in
December, has a Latin catalog on its site, which is decorated with
a deep red border, maracas and bongos. Artists' pages offer brief
biographies and discographies to help users select CDs.
</P>
<P>
   A Latino lifestyle site, Latino.com (www.latino.com), available
in Spanish and English, has an extensive music section, with news
articles on things like hip-hop and salsa, and video links to Latin
artists, but its best item is a map. The clickable, color-coded
guide describes and matches Latin musical genres to their countries
of origin.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   There are dozens of fan pages for specific artists and
categories, as well as specialized sites with narrow city and club
guides. Salsaweb.com (www.salsaweb.com) is a bright site with a few
salsa headliner tour schedules, a listing of dance events around
the world and an eclectic collection of features on topics like
Japanese salsa and dance floor etiquette. The Latin Jazz Network
(www.latinjazznet.com) compiles reviews, profiles and in-depth
interviews with musicians, and links users to a calendar of jazz
festivals and other events, as well as to Latin jazz radio stations
online.
</P>
<P>
   For a primer on the backbone of Latin music, the spare but
colorful Latin Rhythms site (www.cam.org/(Tilde)raybiss/rhythms)
pulses with clickable musical staffs and congas with brief
explanatory paragraphs for each pattern of beats. Latin American
Musical Styles (havana.iwsp.com/radio/lamusic) illustrates its
regional glossary of Latin genres, from aguinaldos (Venezuela) to
zouks (French Caribbean), with clickable snippets from popular
recordings of each.
</P>
<P>
   Visually oriented fans can click on a handful of Latin artists'
streaming videos on AllLatinMusictv.com (www.alllatinmusictv.com),
including one from the legendary Celia Cruz and a video of Enrique
Iglesias performing an English cover of Yaz's ``Only You.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1952EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
