<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4390 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-BUSH-DEBATE-HNS &LR;      09-06 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-DEBATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Bush tells swing-state voters the debate flap is a test of
Gore's character
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By R.G. RATCLIFFE
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCRANTON, Pa. _ With a new taunt and television commercial,
Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush sought to convince
swing-state voters Wednesday that the debate over where and when to
debate is a test of character for Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's get it on, Mr. Gore,'' Bush said on NBC's ``Today
Show.''
</P>
<P>
   The taunt was meant to prompt Gore into facing off with Bush
next Tuesday on a special edition of ``Meet the Press'' with Tim
Russert. Bush noted that Gore previously said he would debate Bush
on the show as part of his ``any time, anywhere'' challenge.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore, on ABC's ``Good Morning America,'' said Bush is trying
to avoid debating on what likely would be highly watched events
sponsored by the Commission on Presidential Debates. Gore has said
he would consider the NBC and CNN forums only if Bush agrees to the
commission's debates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to play games to try to substitute a talk show
for the national bipartisan commission on debates,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission has sponsored presidential debates since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Bush on Sunday announced he would debate Gore on ``Meet the
Press'' next week and then the CNN ``Larry King Live'' show next
month. Bush also agreed to participate in late October in one
commission-sponsored debate, rejecting two others.
</P>
<P>
   ABC and CBS officials have said their networks will not carry
debates sponsored by another network, and NBC officials said
Wednesday they will not give Bush an open forum if Gore does not
agree to debate.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he is going to Washington on Tuesday no matter what.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't given up on the fact that we'll debate on NBC next
Tuesday night with Mr. Russert,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign argues that Bush is choosing the path of least
viewership. King's highest rated audience was 11 million when Gore
debated Ross Perot over the North American Free Trade Agreement.
Meet the Press averages 3.6 million views, the Gore campaign has
said.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the commission sponsored presidential debates in
1992 drew 90 million viewers and in 1996, 41 million.
</P>
<P>
   When ``Today Show'' host Matt Lauer asked Bush if he was trying
to avoid large audiences, the Texas governor replied, ``Not at all.
I want as many people watching me debate Al Gore as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has refused to negotiate with the debate commission since
making his proposal on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In a new television commercial that is being put into the
rotation of Bush ads in 21 battleground states, the Bush campaign
says Gore's refusal to meet Bush on NBC next week shows the vice
president is untrustworthy.
</P>
<P>
   The advertisement said Bush last weekend accepted ``a record
five national debates,'' without mentioning two of those would be
between his running mate, Dick Cheney, and Gore's, Joseph
Lieberman. The commercial goes on to talk about how Gore accepted
debate offers from ``Meet the Press'' and ``Larry King Live''
earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it was politically convenient, Gore said he'd debate `any
time, anyplace, anywhere.' Now that Governor Bush has accepted,
Gore says, `unacceptable,''' the announcer says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't trust Al Gore on debates, why should we trust him
on anything?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides would not say how often the ad is running or
divulge the number of states where it is running.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
