 PERSONALS: Chelsea Clinton's Special Pal 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file.) &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR; By LEAH GARCHIK &QC;  &LR; 
 &UR; c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle &LR;  &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &UR; Jeremy Kane &LR;  wouldn't talk with the New York Daily News about it,
but White House sources quoted in that newspaper Wednesday, Sept.
6, said that the Stanford University senior and &UR; Chelsea Clinton &LR; ,
19, are an item.
</P>
<P>
   Kane, who is from Los Gatos, Calif., had a White House job this
summer interning in the speechwriting department. He was a member
of the Clinton entourage at the Democratic National Convention,
after having spent New Year's Eve with Chelsea and attending church
in San Francisco with her last spring.
</P>
<P>
   Kane will be back at Stanford for his last year, but Chelsea,
taking the semester off to help her mother campaign, won't be there
this fall.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; PICKING UP GEORGE W.'S PEARLS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   There was much joking at the White House on Tuesday, Sept. 5,
about  &UR; George W. Bush &LR; 's widely heard ``aside'' to  &UR; Dick Cheney &LR;  on
Monday, when he called New York Times reporter &UR; Adam Clymer &LR;  a
``major league'' body part two letters away from an asp pole.
</P>
<P>
   White House National Security Council spokesman  &UR; P.J. Crowley &LR; 
began a briefing with ``Welcome to the James S. Brady Briefing Room
at your media-friendly Clinton-Gore White House, where seldom is
heard a disparaging word, particular when the mike is on.'' Later
in the day, White House Chief of Staff  &UR; John Podesta  &LR; told
reporters at Rose Garden ceremonies, ``We like all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Salon.com referred to previous reports of George W. using
colorful language, particularly in a 1988 conversation with the
Hartford Courant. ``When you're not talking about politics, what do
you and your father talk about?'' he was asked. A small cat, he
said, but his answer was in the form of one word.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Washington Post asked several people who know
Clymer for their opinions. ``He's a big teddy bear,'' said Health
and Human Services Secretary  &UR; Donna Shalala &LR; . ``It's actually a
charge that any good reporter should take pride in,'' said  &UR; Tony &LR; 
 &UR; Blankley &LR; , who used to be  &UR; Newt Gingrich &LR; 's press secretary. ``I
think Adam personally is a lovely fellow, but professionally he's
tough as nails.'' Said White House Press Secretary  &UR; Joe Lockhart &LR; ,
``Anybody who gets to George Bush that quickly is a friend of
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S.  &UR; Ed Brayer &LR;  saw the sticker on a bumper in Diamond Heights:
``If God wanted us to vote this year, he would have created
candidates.'' And  &UR; Bob Lacey &LR;  applauds the ladies' cookie cook-off,
which will allow the ``nation to have something to toss,'' he says,
when campaign rhetoric gets hot.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; TAKE IT TO HEART &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ A plaintiff in a Los Angeles case was allowed to present in
court an 11-minute skit including Irish dance and music, reports
California Lawyer. Defense attorney  &UR; David Stewart &LR;  complained,
``This is a lawsuit, not an episode of `Ally McBeal.' ''
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Rosie Sorenson &LR;  was perusing her Healthwise Handbook from
Kaiser Permanente when she came to the advice on home treatment for
warts. ``To get rid of your warts,'' it said, ``it helps to believe
in the treatment. If something works for you, stick with it.''
She's wondering if eye of newt is a covered benefit.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``The all-time classic `Andy Griffith Show' with Andy, Barney, &LR; 
 &UR; Opie, Aunt Beecq and all the Mayberry gang is the basis for a &LR; 
 &UR; brand new Bible study (class) that is coming to First Church of &LR; 
 &UR; God in Napa.'' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Item in the Worship section of the Napa, Calif., Valley
Register, clipped for Personals by  &UR; Andy Demsky &LR; .
</P>
