<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4395 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-ESPORTS0907-COX     09-06 0720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESPORTS0907-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   SPORTS NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.07.00
</P>
<P>
   Horse racing supports anti-Net gambling bill
</P>
<P>
   Major leagues get new address
</P>
<P>
   NFL, Snowball take kids 'Under the Helmet'
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME ONLINE: All stories and urls on this page are one
click away on ajc.com/enews
</P>
<P>
   POST TIME: In Congress' final month, leaders of the U.S. racing
business are waiting for U.S. House leadership to decide the fate
of the Internet Gambling Prohibition Act. While the bill's name
suggests those in the industry may hope for its failure, the
reverse is true because it includes language clarifying legality of
what racing has done for years _ simulcasting, telephone betting
and other interstate activity _ in a gray area of the law. Its
opponents include anti-gambling groups who complain there are too
many exemptions; state lotteries and Native American gambling
interests that want to operate online; and people opposed to any
Internet regulation. Under the bill's language, an interstate bet
is legal if it is legal in the state where it is received.
</P>
<P>
   NEW BALLGAME: Major League Baseball acquired a new Internet
domain name, mlb.com, from Morgan, Lewis &AMP; Bockius LLP, the law
firm that had used it since 1994. The firm, the fourth largest in
the U.S., agreed to transfer its domain name to baseball last
month. Terms weren't disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   www.mlb.com
</P>
<P>
   SNOW STORM: The NFL and Snowball.com Inc. will team for the next
two years on a site aimed at attracting younger people to pro
football. When it launches this month, the site will feature
content linked with the television show ``Under the Helmet,'' which
airs on Fox network on Saturday mornings, and aims to give NFL fans
insight into the lives of players on and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   www.nfluth.com
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH ENGINE: 09.07.00
</P>
<P>
   SITES
</P>
<P>
   Evert, Collins analyze U.S. Open
</P>
<P>
   Tennis experts Chris Evert and Bud Collins are breaking down the
remaining players at the U.S. Open Tennis Championships for
MSNBCSports.com. Evert examines remaining players in the women's
singles draw, while Collins analyzes the men.
</P>
<P>
   www.msnbc.com/news/tennisfront.asp
</P>
<P>
   Dogs' Stroud goes world wide
</P>
<P>
   Fans of Georgia defensive tackle Marcus Stroud can now keep up
with the senior All-America candidate by logging on to the
Internet. Stroud created a website as a class project and
maintained it ``just for fun.'' It was discovered recently by web
surfers and has had more than 200 visitors. ``I don't have the
slightest idea how it got out,'' Stroud said. ``I think it was on
Dawgvent or something like that. It's been fun.'' _ Chip Towers
</P>
<P>
   www.arches.uga.edu/(tilde)mlove
</P>
<P>
   Pelicans in the playoffs online
</P>
<P>
   Listen as the Myrtle Beach Pelicans _ the Atlanta Braves' team
in the Class A Carolina League _ go for the Mills Cup Championship.
Go to the team's Web page and follow the link to broadcast.com. The
best-of-five series is scheduled to begin tonight at 7. Christian
Parra, a league-best 17-4, will start for Myrtle Beach, which led
the minors with a 2.51 team ERA. _ Guy Curtright
</P>
