 &HT;    NEWS ABOUT THE NET: 09.07.00
 &HT;    By John Druckenmiller
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Cartoon Network 's ``Toonami'' gets interactive with
``Intruder''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Is a David Allan Coe comeback a good thing for anyone but him?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Justice is blind as is ``victim'' of ``Whiplash'' frivolous
suit awards
</P>
<P>
   ``INTRUDER'' ALERT: Cartoon Network isn't happy simply taking
over your kids' afternoons with its popular on-air ``Toonami''
programming block. Now they want your kids to get hooked online as
well. The network and its Web site have created ``The Intruder,''
starring Tom, ``Toonami's'' computer-generated host. Every day at 5
p.m., Sept. 18-22, ``The Intruder'' will follow Tom for a few
minutes, as he battles an alien aboard his ship. On the Web site,
you'll get online-only information, including 3-D diagrams of the
ship, in sync with the TV action. Also planned: a three-part
Internet comic and a five-part ``Intruder'' interactive game. To
play, you'll need the special code revealed during ``Intruder''
episodes.
</P>
<P>
   www.cartoonnetwork.com
</P>
<P>
   SONGS OF WOE: After years out of the spotlight, outlaw country
singer-songwriter David Allan Coe is cool again, thanks to an
opening slot on Kid Rock's current tour and a shout-out on the
rapper's hit single ''American Bad A--.'' But The New York Times
reports that Coe's decision to re-release two widely bootlegged
early-'80s albums _ originally sold through biker magazines while
Coe was riding with a motorcycle gang, and generally considered to
be ''among the most racist, misogynist, homophobic and obscene
songs recorded by a popular songwriter'' _ has many fans wondering
how Rock, ''who has collaborated with black rappers and has made a
living through appropriating their music, can be touring with a
songwriter responsible for blatantly anti-black material.'' Coe is
selling the albums through his so-so Web site,
officialdavidallancoe.com, as a single-CD set, for $45, although he
refuses to put his name on the disc or its packaging.
</P>
<P>
   LEGAL MISSTEP: No lifelines, please, but answer the following:
Which of these actual lawsuits is more trivial? A) A blind man sued
by a woman because he stepped on her foot, or B) a suit filed by
college student who fell from his dorm window while ``mooning''
friends? These cases were included in an Internet poll of
outrageous suits conducted by Michigan Lawsuit Abuse Watch, which
intends to use the Whiplash Awards for America's most frivolous
lawsuits in much the same way the Golden Fleece tackles government
waste. Overall, 2,100 online voters chose a Florida woman for the
dubious distinction of suing a school for guide-dogs after a blind
man who was using one of the dogs stepped on her foot. No Georgia
cases were among the finalists.
</P>
<P>
   www.mlaw.org
</P>
