<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAYBERRY-VS-NYC07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bar brouhaha begs question: New York _ or Mayberry?
 &HT;    Should we try to mimic New York _ or Mayberry?
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Well, we all know what John Rocker's answer would be.
</P>
<P>
   The question? Actually, it was more of a challenge that Atlanta
city Councilman Michael Bond issued Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta has to decide,'' Bond said during a tense council
meeting and vote on bar closing times, ``whether it's going to be
New York City or Mayberry, because it can't be both.''
</P>
<P>
   Coming on the heels of a TV commercial in which Jacksonville's
mayor slams Atlanta as hell with HOV lanes, this latest, largely
self-induced, civic identity crisis naturally set tongues wagging.
</P>
<P>
   And not just in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   First, Gotham weighed in on the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would advise all cities to strive to be like New York
City,'' Curt Ritter, chief spokesman for New York Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani, said with a slight ``you should be so lucky'' lilt to his
voice. ``As the safest large city in America, we are certainly the
cultural capital of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Goober's hometown was heard from.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Atlanta should retain some of its Southern charm,''
advised Ann Vaughn, director of the Visitors Center in Mount Airy,
N.C., which native son Andy Griffith lovingly re-created as the
fictional Mayberry on his long-running TV show. ``Atlanta or New
York, they're wonderful to visit, but it really does make you
appreciate your small-town roots.''
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, bars can stay open until 4 a.m., which some here
link to a recent rise in violent crime in Buckhead and other parts
of the city. Meanwhile, in Mayberry, er, Mount Airy, you can't even
buy liquor by the drink, and most restaurants close by 9 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Yet New York City bars close anywhere between midnight and 4
a.m., Ritter says, and the city is ``safer than ever.'' So safe _
he couldn't resist adding from the city whose Mets and Yankees are
the Braves' biggest rivals _ that ``as we approach the playoff
season, New York City's baseball teams would be safer in the Bronx
or Queens than they would be in Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Atlanta City Council: Go Goober.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 1958EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0296 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4399 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FILM-HENRY-JAMES-$ADV     09-06 1062
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HENRY-JAMES-$ADV10-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S HARD ADAPTING HENRY JAMES. STILL, THEY KEEP TRYING .
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By LISA ZEIDNER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ladies with lacy parasols, twilit mansions with topiary mazes:
There's no huge mystery about why filmmakers would be attracted to
Henry James novels. Adapting James is a more dignified undertaking
than filming ``Lethal Weapon IV''; Henry James shot-puts us into
the land of Art, of substance and gravitas. Besides, there are only
so many Jane Austen novels.
</P>
<P>
   We've thus seen, in quick succession, Jane Campion's ``Portrait
of a Lady'' (1996), Agnieszka Holland's ``Washington Square''
(1997) and Iain Softley's ``Wings of the Dove'' (1998) _ as if
there were an antitrust suit to bust up the Merchant-Ivory monopoly
on James, which has produced ``The Europeans'' (1979), ``The
Bostonians'' (1984) and, coming on Nov. 3, ``The Golden Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to the appearance of a mini-boom, filmmakers have
in fact been steadily filming James for over a half-century. Since
1947, at least 30 James novels and stories have been brought to big
and small screen, mostly to give sundry ``it'' girls a chance to
dress up. ``The Heiress,'' William Wyler's 1949 version of
``Washington Square,'' stars Olivia de Havilland, and Peter
Bogdanovich bathes Cybill Shepherd in golden light in ``Daisy
Miller'' (1974). ``The Innocents'' (1961), based on ``The Turn of
the Screw,'' stars Deborah Kerr; John Frankenheimer directed Ingrid
Bergman in the same vehicle, for television, in 1959. Ten
adaptations of ``The Turn of the Screw'' feature evil children
torturing their governesses _ which means, of course, that without
Henry James there would be no ``Omen IV: The Awakening.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the respectful good will of these efforts, most of the
films lose James in the translation. Either they aim for stately _
and become deadly dull, or they trump the drama with swelling
scores and shouting matches more appropriate for a daytime soap.
What no filmmaker has yet found is a way to capture James' gently
acid tone. The last decade's adjective of the moment, ``edgy,''
might have been invented for the novelist's dark, layered ironies.
But to understand his tone, we must understand his culture. Making
sense of James' characters requires sharing assumptions about money
and manners that simply don't compute for a contemporary audience.
The films therefore resort to screaming clues through a megaphone _
and thus sacrifice subtlety in stories that pretty much depend on
subtlety.
</P>
<P>
   They're costume dramas, so let's start with the costumes.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Golden Bowl,'' James' novel about a nasty love
quadrangle, Maggie sits at home, pretending to read. Really she
awaits her husband, who, Maggie suspects, is having an affair with
her best friend, Charlotte, who, it so happens, is also her
father's wife. But Maggie will not make a scene. She waits quietly,
in a brand-new dress. She does not even indulge in the luxury of
pacing. Would Charlotte like the dress? Probably not, although the
hyper-polite Charlotte would never say so.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the challenge of translating this one crucial scene to
the screen. In the new film, directed by James Ivory, Maggie
forgoes dignity and hurls herself dolefully on the floor in front
of the fire. When hubby finally returns, he compliments the frock.
``You like it?'' Maggie says. ``I wore it tonight for dinner _ for
you. But you had dined.'' Point taken: She's on to him. But how to
reveal Maggie's thoughts about Charlotte without Charlotte's
appearing on the scene, without even a word of dialogue?
</P>
<P>
   That is the almost wholly internal drama of ``The Golden Bowl,''
and it could not be less cinematic. The risk of trying to film such
scenes, of course, is that you reduce the novels to fancy-dress
balls _ and let's face it, a contemporary audience can barely tell
a tasteful gown from a tacky one. Unfortunate, since there's no
doubt that James takes the clothes seriously, as does Isabel
Archer, the heroine of ``The Portrait of a Lady,'' when she
proclaims: ``I've a great respect for things! One's self _ for
other people _ is one's expression of one's self; and one's house,
one's furniture, one's garments, the books one reads, the company
one keeps _ these are all expressive.''
</P>
<P>
   To make sure we can read the signs of ``Washington Square'' _
James' consideration of gold-digging _ Agnieszka Holland dresses up
Jennifer Jason Leigh for the ball so that she looks like an
upholstered sofa bought at a yard sale. Plus she can't dance and
trips a lot. She's such a hopeless plain Jane that we know her
father's right: Her suitor can only be after her money. But if
that's too obvious, where's the suspense? In the film, what you see
is what you get. In the novel, you're not sure what you're seeing
or getting; James thus forces readers to reconsider their
suppositions about marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Austen's young women don't have to choose love or money.
They generally get both. Not so in James, whose marrying maidens
get betrayals, intrigues and disappointments. In a way, ``The
Portrait of a Lady'' seems ripe for contemporary retelling. But in
updating the characters, Jane Campion loses the story's sense and
center.
</P>
<P>
   Campion wants to portray Isabel as a feminist free spirit. So
while the other damsels at the ball in ``The Portrait of a Lady''
faint, presumably from the corsets, Nicole Kidman struts about with
her burnished hair wild and aswirl, utterly indifferent to her
clothes, her eyes red-rimmed. Yet Isabel is supposed to be the
ultimate social creature, so charming she needs no dowry. If she's
going to spend all her time crying or almost-crying, oblivious to
everyone, why should so many suitors ardently want her?
</P>
<P>
   Why Isabel chooses Gilbert Osmond (John Malkovich), a bald boor
in the slimiest of smoking jackets, is unclear too, although
Campion throws in a little fantasy sequence of a menage a trois to
suggest that it has something to do with sexuality. (``Director's
Cut: The Playboy Mansion Footage''?) Campion actually has Osmond
strike Isabel, something the King of Decorousness never even comes
close to doing in the novel. As a portrait of a marriage, the film
is less Henry James than ``The Ike and Tina Story.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Not that you can blame directors for wanting to offer us
something to watch. In ``Washington Square,'' Holland has her
heroine chase her ex-beau's carriage, in pouring rain, and fall
sobbing in the mud. (In the novel, stiff upper lip prevails.) Here,
in the book, is how Isabel realizes that her husband and his old
friend Serena Merle are, as James would say, ``familiarly
associated'': She sees them talking near the fire. But Madame Merle
stands while Osmond remains seated. James doesn't need to alert his
readers to what such rudeness means in a gentleman: ``The thing
made an image, lasting only a moment, like a flicker of light.''
Try that on for size for a film's big Act Two reversal. Jane
Campion gives up on making the discovery vibrant; she just has
someone tell Isabel flat out. But once you excise the psychological
unfolding, what do you have? Just another fool for love, with
period accents.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail Merchant and James Ivory don't generally make these kinds
of blunders. Say what you will about filmmakers so tasteful they
have their own coffee-table book (``Merchant Ivory's English
Landscape: Rooms, Views, and Anglo-Saxon Attitudes''), after 45
films they can help an actress wear a bustle without looking like a
buffoon. The camera caresses the country estates. You can feel both
the seduction of the moneyed life and its concurrent risk of
hollowness. Moreover, the filmmakers have feelings about
expatriates' belonging and longing, those critical Jamesian themes.
</P>
<P>
   If you need to see how far Merchant and Ivory have advanced the
look and feel of the cinematic James, revisit the 1969 BBC
production of ``The Portrait of a Lady,'' a studio piece of the old
school. The light, the clothes, the wainscoting: Everything looks
brown. The point of the story is muddy as well. And the blather!
It's enough to make you want to hurl yourself face down in the mud.
Merchant and Ivory's longtime screenwriter, Ruth Prawer Jhabvala,
mercifully strips down the dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But Merchant and Ivory may be growing tired of the ``tasteful''
label. No more English reserve for them; ``The Golden Bowl'' goes
all Italian, rococo and operatic. More sweeping vistas, more gilded
interiors, a drunken bacchanal reminiscent of a Victorian ``Animal
House,'' molto sobbing, even (duck!) that bonus passionate smack to
the face. Surprising, since this is the quietest of James' novels _
a book about secrecy and decoding in which hardly anyone says
anything to anyone about anything. But perhaps for that very
reason, the script shifts the focus from the cuckolded parties to
the adulterers. (At least they're doing something.)
</P>
<P>
   To help us see the dangers of wealth, Maggie's father, the
American millionaire Adam Verver (Nick Nolte), is made not a
homebody but Citizen Kane-ish in his isolation, hoarding his
goodies while his young bride (Uma Thurman) plays solitaire in the
drafty mansion. (In today's movies, being able to afford a
governess, no less a wing of an estate for her, makes a character
highly suspect and ripe for satanic takeover. But James liked
money. Maybe we have to wait for the ``Clueless''-style update, in
which Adam Verver is an Internet billionaire building a pleasure
palace in Seattle, to understand that.)
</P>
<P>
   To Ivory's credit, it's a briskly paced two-hour film. You'd
need a six-part mini-series to be true to the novel. Actually,
there  &UR; is  &LR; a six-part mini-series of ``The Golden Bowl'' (BBC,
1972). Made before the ``Brideshead Revisited'' revolution in
British television, it's long-winded, the casting off. Still, a
mini-series could allow you to dwell on each unnerving revelation,
and to do tight reaction shots without looking pretentious. Time to
crack out Michael Gambon, Jeremy Irons, Helen Mirren, Ian Holm, the
entire cast of ``Pride and Prejudice.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of the actors and actresses do get recycled from
one period film and television show to another. Kate Beckinsale,
from the A&AMP;E ``Emma,'' appears as Maggie in ``The Golden Bowl'';
her husband, Amerigo, is Jeremy Northam, who plays Emma's suitor
Knightley in the feature film version of ``Emma.'' Not that these
actors aren't capable; but it does triple the ``Wait, didn't I
already see this period movie?'' double take.
</P>
<P>
   James gives actors eerily little to do. Actors must be
expressive with the least possible wailing or ground-pounding _
often through nothing more than a hesitation or a veiled glance.
They can't just hammer on one note, either. Each performance must
be deep and protean. Because the vehicles are by necessity so
quiet, with James the directing is paramount. The director must
provide a controlling voice and make sense of all the conflicting
clues.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the film that best manages such Jamesian complexity is
Iain Softley's ``Wings of the Dove.'' The costume-drama queen
Helena Bonham Carter, her bare shoulders aglow against Venetian
stucco, wears gowns of sapphire blue so rich you understand why she
would sell her soul in order to be able to afford them. Softley
generally admits only one color per scene _ a bright red taxi, that
deep and luscious blue _ while the rest of the world recedes into
gritty gray. Each frame of this film is so visually charged that
you could watch it without the sound and still be bombarded by
signals of posture, personality, reaction, interaction. Softley
updates the novel from 1902 to 1910, a period of social transition
and uncertainty. It's not James' period, but at least it's a
period.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't hurt that Linus Roache is as beautiful to look at as
the very different women (one worldly, one virginal) vying for his
attention. And he's new. When the American heiress spies Roache's
character for the first time from a balcony, hers is not the only
breath taken away. Glamorous and brooding, alternately shy and sly:
He's the perfect Jamesian boy-toy.The movie's climactic nude scene
captures the bleakness of the novel, in which the characters
``attempted to bury in the dark blindness of each other's arms the
knowledge of each other that they couldn't undo.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``The Wings of the Dove'' may be the most menacing James
novel, even it is often quite funny. We're still waiting for a
James movie with a sense of humor. ``I, Claudius,'' ``The Young
Catherine'': Once more, it's television, as opposed to film, that
seems to have managed a way to season period gravity with irony.
(Hot tip to development folk: Still awaiting adaptation is James'
seriocomic gem ``What Maisie Knew,'' a child's-eye view of an ugly
divorce.)
</P>
<P>
   One final plea to James adaptors of the future. Please lose the
madcap accents. Being an American abroad does not require you to
speak like Scarlett O'Hara. Nor do you need to speak really, really
loudly, as Kathy Bates does in ``Titanic,'' to show how crass you
are. In ``The Golden Bowl,'' both Anjelica Huston and Nick Nolte
sport intermittent Texas or Carolina twangs. Only the English
actress Kate Beckinsale manages an appropriate American accent.
</P>
<P>
   But then, this is why we like English actors in our period
pieces. They can do accents because they mostly understand the
notion of class, and Americans mostly don't. Which is why James
didn't deign to live on our shores _ and why translating his
byzantine class consciousness into film terms is close to
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
