<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE LITTLE THINGS THAT COUNT
</HEADLINE>
  Attention to details makes for a savvy wardrobe 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DeWITT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Webster defines accessories as ``optional equipment,'' but he
obviously wasn't talking about fashion accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Try telling any fashion student those big gold hoops or slinky
shoulder dusters that are all the rage are optional equipment and,
well, they might grind their stiletto heel into your foot.
</P>
<P>
   Less emotional, but equally savvy, was the fictional sleuth
Sherlock Holmes, who observed that ``little things are infinitely
the most important.'' Although he probably wasn't talking about
which fashion accessories had the most elan (shoes, handbags,
jewels, hats or sunglasses), our trench-coated British gumshoe knew
the goods of good taste.
</P>
<P>
   Having accessories _ and the correct ones for each season _ is
so important that entire books are devoted to the details. For
instance, in ``Chic Simple Clothes'' (Alfred A. Knopf; $25) by Kim
Johnson Gross and Jeff Stone, there's a roundup of accessory
advice, but fashion maven Diana Vreeland leads with, ``First, I'd
put money into shoes.''
</P>
<P>
   And in ``Best Dressed'' (Clarkson Potter; $25), author Suzy
Gershman tells us that ``one hot accessory can make your ensemble
sing.'' She chats about the importance of an Hermes scarf, a pair
of real Chanel earrings and a pashmina stole, but then she gets to
the core of the accessory story: ``Forget (about the adage) you are
what you eat. In public, you are your handbag.''
</P>
<P>
   With advice like that, arm candy is turning into the most
important accessory of the season. Art in a bag is now big
business, with traditional companies often getting upstaged by
young new designers such as Lily Yudis. Her handmade retro-design
evening bags sporting the Lily Scott label have been spotted all
over Hollywood hanging on the arms of celebs such as Kirsten Dunst
and Jeri Ryan. Indeed, there are so many new designers in the purse
trade _ including Sharon Stone, who has a limited-edition
collection with Louis Vuitton to raise money for the American
Foundation for AIDS Research _ that the once-hot Kate Spade is
becoming lost in the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   While purse shopping, don't rule out those ladylike bags by
established designers from Hermes to Christian Dior that link you
to !ital!old money, last forever and get you better restaurant
service. For more accessory instruction, rent a video of ``The
Talented Mr. Ripley'' and ``Evita,'' or buy a copy of ``French
Style'' (Express; $20) by Veronique Vienne, who advises readers on
how to carry a purse with panache by holding it tenderly and close
to your body as part of your outfit.
</P>
<P>
   While you're studying up on purses and such, make sure you match
the right accessories to the right look. You won't increase your
hipster quotient with '70s-inspired python print pants and a Lady
Di bag by Christian Dior. Instead, swing a chain-strapped baguette
style over your shoulder, tie on a lariat necklace (hotter than
``Sex and the City's'' name necklace) and add a pair of hoop
earrings. Then ground the look with boots, adding bonus points for
choosing red over black.
</P>
<P>
   For those classy '40s tweed suits that everybody's talking
about, you'll need pearls _ ropes and ropes of them a la Coco
Chanel. Plus a pile of gold jewelry (silver is looking tarnished
this year) on your wrists, and some peek-a-boo (open-toed) or
pointy-toed spectator pumps.
</P>
<P>
   For either of the season's freshest looks, rethink hosiery.
Naked legs and toe rings that required expertise with fake tanning
lotions are all passe in the first fall of Y2K. What's new again
are sheer black stockings, opaque tights in colors and prints,
small-scale (not the Halloween witch variety) fishnets and even
preppy plaid socks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, here in L.A., you'll need some new shades.
</P>
<P>
   As with the two directions of clothing _ ladylike and disco
queen _ there are two major shade trends. For traditional
trappings, think of small, refined glasses with narrow frames such
as Chanel's new style with interlocking gold C's, or go for big,
bold black plastic frames with equally status-focused logos on the
sides. In regard to the latter, eyewear designer Alain Mikli says,
``They create an allure of mystery. Jackie O would have approved.''
</P>
<P>
   Too hip for designer shades, but tired of retro cat's-eye
frames? Start focusing on another '70s fad _ the oversize, rimless
aviator in Crayola colors. And just for fun, add a little crystal
heart or star in the corner of one of the lenses like fashion
designer Kenneth Cole, who recently opened a boutique in Santa
Monica.
</P>
<P>
   And stay tuned.
</P>
<P>
   As the weather cools down (and you know it will), retailers will
be tempting you with fur scarves to tuck inside black leather
jackets. It's a look that should make last year's pashmina stole
look as dated as those crystal bead bracelets you just had to have
last summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
