<HEADLINE>
FOO FIGHTERS STEPPED UP FOR LETTERMAN
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: On David Letterman's comeback show after his heart surgery,
what musical group canceled a tour date to perform for him? Also,
what song did they play? _ U.C., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: At Letterman's request, the Foo Fighters showed up Feb. 21 to
perform ``Everlong'' from their second album, ``The Colour and the
Shape.''
</P>
<P>
   When introducing the song, Letterman said that it was ``my
favorite band playing my favorite song.'' He also held the group's
CD cover upside down, which he often does for bands that he likes.
</P>
<P>
   Windows users can see the performance on ``Nothing Left to
Lose,'' the Foo Fighters' current CD, which includes a multimedia
``ECD'' with several of the band's videos.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I'm trying to find a song I used to hear on jukeboxes when I
walked through the Fort Worth Stockyards in 1944. The only line I
remember is ``they took the stars out of heaven when they took you
from me.'' Can you help? _ J.G.S., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: That song is ``They Took the Stars Out of Heaven,'' recorded
by Floyd Tillman and the Texas Playboys.
</P>
<P>
   It is included on the 1994 three-album collection, ``From the
Vaults: Decca Country'' which also features ``The Eyes of Texas''
by Milton Brown and his Brownies, ``Cool Water'' by Sons of the
Pioneers and ``Walking the Floor Over You'' by Ernest Tubb.
</P>
<P>
   The album is still in print. If you can't find it at a local
store, you can order it for $38.97 from People's Tour by calling
(877) 362-8019 or visiting the Web site www.peoplestour.com.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a new marketing idea for the Joe Boxer Company. Where
can I write to the president? _ C.J., Arlington
</P>
<P>
   A: Send your letter to Chief Underpants Officer Nicholas Graham,
Joe Boxer Corp. World Headquarters, 1265 Folsom St., San Francisco,
CA 94103.
</P>
<P>
   That title is official, by the way. Graham, 40, began the
company in 1985 while working as a rock musician in San Francisco,
creating novelty ties and X-rated underwear. Today, Joe Boxer
products appear in more than 4,000 U.S. stores and have yearly
sales of more than $100 million. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL;   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
