<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4418 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-WEAThER-LATIN0907-COX     09-06 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEAThER-LATIN0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Live, from Marietta, it's weather for Latin America
 &HT;    By Don Melvin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Helena de Moura has just come off the air near the end
of a 10-hour shift of broadcasting the weather. As she makes her
way toward her desk she passes Vanessa Miranda, a fellow Brazilian
weather presenter, applying makeup in preparation for her own
appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Soon afterward, Ricardo Nogueira, an on-air meteorologist,
arrives. He is carrying, as always, a carved gourd called a
``cuia''filled with something that looks, to North American eyes, a
bit like silage or something a cow might chew.
</P>
<P>
   But it's ``chimarrao,'' a tea common to southern Brazil, where
Nogueira grew up. He pours water into the leaf-filled ``cuia,''
lets it steep, then drinks the tea through a spoon-slash-straw that
has a strainer on the bottom to keep the leaves from being sipped
into his mouth. ``Chimarrao,'' Nogueira explains happily, has a
much higher caffeine content than coffee.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by so many things Brazilian, it seems de Moura might
as well be back home.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Marietta, not Brazil, and de Moura works at the
Weather Channel Latin America, or TWCLA, as employees call it, a
sister company to the original Weather Channel. Both are owned by
Virginia-based Landmark Communications.
</P>
<P>
   The original Weather Channel _ a 24-hour all-weather cable
television channel that was launched, to some skepticism, 17 years
ago _ is by now familiar to many people in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin American version was launched three years ago, aimed
at the vast Spanish-speaking world between the tip of South America
and the Mexico-Texas border. That programming is now seen in 20
countries.
</P>
<P>
   And two years ago, a Portuguese language edition was started to
serve Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Those ventures have been propelled by about 70 employees, drawn
from diverse countries, working together at TWCLA's offices in
Marietta. The group, which includes people from Brazil, Colombia,
Mexico, Argentina, Cuba and Chile, has melded into a kind of
miniature Latin American society.
</P>
<P>
   The Latin American weather channel is doing very well, says
Eduardo Ruiz, its president. But in the beginning, the project
faced serious challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's very little education on meteorology in Latin
America,'' Ruiz says.
</P>
<P>
   Schoolchildren rarely come home discussing the difference
between cirrus clouds and cumulonimbus ones. Farmers have not
traditionally watched weather forecasts and made decisions
accordingly. City dwellers have not been in the habit of turning on
the TV in the morning to see whether to carry umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   When TWCLA began, 90 percent of the programming was weather
forecasts and data and 10 percent was educational features, Ruiz
says. Now the split is closer to 50-50, he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest obstacle is that we're trying to develop a new
habit in consumers,'' he says. ``We're doing it, little by
little.''
</P>
<P>
   An important ingredient in gaining acceptance, he says, is to
have Latin Americans on the air.
</P>
<P>
   So it was that last month, when serious flooding hit
northeastern Brazil, residents of the area were able to watch de
Moura telling them what was likely to happen next.
</P>
<P>
   The programming they watched from Marietta had an even more
local flavor than they might have gotten out of Rio de Janeiro. De
Moura is from Recife, a coastal city in northeastern Brazil, the
area affected by the floods. Much as a Southern drawl might be a
hindrance for someone seeking on-air TV work in the United States,
de Moura says her regional accent would probably preclude her from
getting a television job in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   But here it's an advantage, says Eduardo Mack, program manager
of the Weather Channel/Brazil, and a native of Rio.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want this to be a truly Brazilian network,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   TWCLA's employees may have fused into a little Latin American
society, but language is a significant issue in a company where, by
Mack's count, five different ones are spoken. Employees in these
Marietta offices, he says, speak English, Spanish, Portuguese and
two hybrids _ Spanglish and Portunol.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of room for miscommunication,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Many employees are hired directly from their native countries,
like Luis Carrera, who was a television meteorologist in Chile
until he got an improbable phone call asking whether he'd like a
job in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   But de Moura, 33, a graduate of the University of Georgia, has
lived in the metro area for many years. She worked off and on for
five years at CNN as an assignment editor and producer and wrote
for the Reuters news serviced before Mack called asking if she'd
like an on-air job.
</P>
<P>
   She had to begin an intensive study of weather, a topic about
which she had scant prior knowledge. While she consults the
meteorologists who analyze the information collected at hundreds of
sites in Brazil, she doesn't read a script on the air. She ad libs.
She has to know her stuff.
</P>
<P>
   TWCLA has, at the moment, only one satellite feed. In Brazil,
computers interrupt the feed and show local weather graphics as a
five-minute Spanish segment airs in the rest of Latin America. Then
viewers in the Spanish-speaking countries watch graphics while de
Moura, or another Brazilian personality, presents 2 1/2 minutes of
weather in Portuguese.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for growth in Latin America is enormous, says
Ruiz, and the company is also seeking ways to tap into the growing
Spanish-speaking market in the United States. TWCLA is available in
the United States through DirecTV Para Todos, which offers
Spanish-language programming via satellite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our forecast is clear and we have good weather ahead of us,''
Ruiz says.
</P>
<P>
   The forecast for de Moura looks good, too. Several Brazilian
newspapers have written about her. She receives e-mails from
Brazil, though often they are from long-lost cousins saying things
like, ``You need to do something about your hair.''
</P>
<P>
   She's learning more about Brazil and its topography than she
ever knew when she lived there. And she is becoming friends with
people from different parts of that vast country _ Brazil is larger
than the continental United States _ and learning more about
Brazil's many different cultures than she knew when shelived in
Recife.
</P>
<P>
   And, after 16 years in Georgia, she feels that, on Interstate
North Parkway in Marietta, she has in a way finally returned home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find a camaraderie here,'' she says, ``that I had longed
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
