<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4424 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-WAY-OF-GUN-REVIEW-LAD     09-06 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAY-OF-GUN-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOOT-'EM-UP GOES TOO FAR
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
-Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christopher McQuarrie, the Oscar-winning screenwriter of ``The
Usual Suspects,'' proves he knows how to handle cameras, actors and
violent action with his directing debut, ``The Way of the Gun.''
Care has evidently been lavished on the film's every line
(McQuarrie also wrote the script), composition, performance and
bullet squib.
</P>
<P>
   Why so much talent was spent on a project as distasteful as this
one is another matter. McQuarrie has stated that he wanted to
subvert Hollywood's standard, simplistic moralism with this film.
Rather than stack the deck against bad guys in order to justify
their extended punishment, he figured making all of his characters
ethically repugnant in one way or another would challenge audience
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   Like this is anything new. Hitchcock began experimenting with
viewer sympathies back in the '20s, and a hundred or so
post-Tarantino crime films _ ``Suspects'' included _ have made a
fetish out of the practice for the last half a decade.
</P>
<P>
   McQuarrie comes up with some interesting variations on the
notion here, no question (an unmourned innocent bystander left
lying after a parking lot shootout, for example). But he also goes
so far with it, culminating in an astonishingly brutal, extended
climax that has to rank as one of the great audience endurance
tests of all time, that his smarter ideas will likely be
bloodwashed from most filmgoers' memories.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is the old kidnapping-gone-wrong ploy _ but, boy, what
a messy one this is. Two not-so-bright criminal drifters, Parker (a
beefed-up, brooded-over Ryan Phillippe) and Longbaugh
(``Suspects''' Benicio Del Toro, inscrutably cooler than ever),
cook up a cockeyed plan to ransom a surrogate mother (Juliette
Lewis). (The last names of the characters were inspired by the
real-life monickers of Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid.) Little
do these two know that the young woman's wealthy womb-renters are
deeply involved with the mob.
</P>
<P>
   As Parker, Longbaugh and Lewis' verging-on-delivery Robin scoot
around the desert Southwest and across the Mexican border, several
factions of enforcers, each with their own agendas, dog their tail.
Will the humiliated, untrustworthy bodyguards Jeffers and Obecks
(Taye Diggs and Nicky Katt) find the fleeing trio before veteran
bagman Joe Sarno (James Caan), who has his own conflicted
loyalties, cuts a deal? And where do the Mexican police, Robin's
overly concerned obstetrician (Dylan Kussman) and a suicidal
assassin (Geoffrey Lewis, Juliette's real-life father, in a
terrific small bit on a par with the best Sam Peckinpah and Don
Siegel criminal losers of the '70s) fit in?
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, what effect will Robin, whose motives emerge as
increasingly complex while the chase progresses, have on the deeply
buried consciences of (and bond of trust between) Parker and
Longbaugh?
</P>
<P>
   Any one of these intricate storylines would have been
fascinating to follow, had its narrative and behavioral
implications been played out fully. Instead, everything just kind
of collapses into one of the most intensely ballistic desert
shootouts ever filmed (and certainly the first one _ spoiler
warning here, for those who prefer to be surprised rather than
unnecessarily disgusted _ juxtaposed against a torturous induced
labor).
</P>
<P>
   There you have it. If this sounds at all interesting to you, you
can be assured that ``Way of the Gun'' presents it all pretty well.
The bigger concern, however, should be why you might possibly be
interested. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
-The film: ``The Way of the Gun'' (R; violence, language). &QL; 
-The stars: Ryan Phillippe, Benicio Del Toro, Juliette Lewis, James
Caan, Taye Diggs, Nicky Katt, Dylan Kussman, Geoffrey Lewis. &QL; 
-Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Christopher McQuarrie.
-Produced by Kenneth Kokin. Released by Artisan Entertainment. &QL; 
-Running time: One hour, 59 minutes &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0311 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4425 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-GORE-ECON-ASSESS-(TRI     09-06 1232
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-ECON-ASSESS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: GORE REVIVES DEBATE OVER BASIC ECONOMIC MANAGEMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (With GORE-ECON, BUSH) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In releasing a detailed economic blueprint
Wednesday, Vice President Al Gore reignited a debate with Gov.
George W. Bush about who can better apportion the projected federal
budget surplus without driving the government back into the red and
running the good economy off the rails.
</P>
<P>
   By making selective assumptions about which tax and spending
proposals to include and how to put a pricetag on them, both
presidential campaigns can produce bottom lines suggesting that
theirs is the path of fiscal prudence and their opponent's the
first step toward economic ruin.
</P>
<P>
   The money the two sides are planning is only hypothetical at
this point, and for all the numbers flying back and forth, the
issue is not really arithmetic. What matters is the clear
difference in approach to economic management and use of the
surplus between the two parties and their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush for the most part represents conservative orthodoxy, with a
heavy emphasis on tax cuts, keeping politicians from getting their
hands on too much money and relying on individuals and markets to
solve problems and strengthen the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In his view, tax cuts are a powerful way to improve the chance
that the the economy will continue to grow over the long term.
Reducing the national debt, while an important goal, is not a
singular priority.
</P>
<P>
   After spending much of the past several months campaigning as a
corporation-bashing populist fighting for working families, Gore
presented himself Wednesday as the embodiment of fiscal
responsibility, brushing aside the Bush camp's accusations that he
is a recklessly big-spending liberal.
</P>
<P>
   He emphasized his willingness to take some money out of
contention for either tax cuts or additional spending, vowing to
set aside $300 billion of the projected surplus over the next ten
years in case the economic assumptions that produce the estimates
of the coming surplus prove to be wrong. If the money materializes,
it would go to additional debt reduction; if it does not, then it
would not have been promised for any particular use and thus would
not be contributing to any new deficit.
</P>
<P>
   The 191-page document released Wednesday by Gore was written
largely by economic advisers closely associated with the Clinton
administration's emphasis on keeping the budget balanced and paying
off the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   They included former Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin, , who
colleagues said has sometimes been uncomfortable with Gore's recent
populist emphasis; Gene Sperling, the White House economic policy
adviser; Erskine Bowles, the former White House chief of staff; and
Laura Tyson, a former White House chief economist and policy
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Those advisers generally see the strong economy as Gore's best
weapon, and reducing the debt as the best way of keeping interest
rates low and stimulating the investment the economy needs to
remain the world's most competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as he presented himself as a man of economic prudence,
Gore sketched a vision of an activist government willing to take on
big problems. The document he released Wednesday sought to spell
out for voters, with considerable specificity, how Gore would seek
to harness continued prosperity on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Incomes would rise by a third, Gore promised. The poverty level
would decline from 12.7 percent to below 10 percent. College
attendance and graduation rates would increase. Income tax rates on
families making the median income would fall. The disparity between
what men and women earn would be reduced by 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore described not just the goals, but the programs and policies
he said would be necessary to achieve them, from paying off the
national debt to spending $115 billion more on education in the
next decade and establishing a new retirement savings program at a
cost of at least $200 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Whether the goals are achievable is largely a matter of how well
the economy does in coming years, a variable mostly outside the
control of any president.
</P>
<P>
   The current business expansion is already the longest the nation
has ever enjoyed. Should the combination of healthy growth, low
unemployment and higher productivity continue for another eight
years _ by no means a certainty, even if the president, Congress
and the Federal Reserve make all the right choices _ many if not
all of Gore's goals could be within reach.
</P>
<P>
   Should the economy hit the rocks, they could come back to haunt
a President Gore.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The entire exercise was striking for the degree of detail it
involved.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years ago, Bill Clinton offered an economic policy agenda
entitled ``Putting People First.'' It was praised if nothing else
for being detailed and concrete about his plans and priorities. In
its original form, it was a few dozen pages long, an airy pamphlet
alongside Gore's chart-laden presentation.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush has not pulled his proposals together in a comprehensive
document. But his campaign put out a detailed accounting of his tax
and spending plans Wednesday, right down to his proposed spending
increase for aid to historically black colleges and universities
($900 million over ten years).
</P>
<P>
   Bush counterpunched hard, citing support for his approach from
conservative Nobel prize-winning economists like Milton Friedman,
and asserting that Gore's long list of initiatives would blow a
hole in the budget.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore's camp is happy to have the campaign fought over
economic management issues, seeing that as ground on which Gore is
both comfortable and right.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear how much credit voters will give to the vice
president for the current prosperity _ whether, as is traditionally
the case, the good times will lead voters to think hard before
throwing the incumbent party out of the White House.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Gore left little doubt about how he wants to put prosperity to
work, but some of his more ambitious goals were vaguely defined.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would seek to create 10 million new ``high-tech,
high-skill'' jobs during the next decade. But he did not define how
those jobs would differ from other jobs, or how much better paying
they would presumably be than flipping hamburgers. And his
prescription for creating them encompassed such broad initiatives
as improving education and training and continuing to open new
foreign markets to American goods and services.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would work to raise family incomes by one-third over
10 years, largely by fostering continued improvement in the growth
rate of productivity, the basic measure of economic efficiency. As
productivity increases, wages and profits can rise without setting
off inflation, and much of the economy's recent strength can be
traced to productivity improvements.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no simple recipe for nurturing productivity.
Productivity dropped sharply in the early 1970s for reasons that
economists still do not fully understand, and has only rebounded in
the past few years. The spread of computers and other information
technology has obviously played a role, but no one knows for sure
how long the improvement will last.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
