<SLUG> BC-IRS0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    IRS restructuring to bring new division to Atlanta
 &HT;    By Peralte C. Paul
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Get ready for a kinder, gentler IRS. Yes, that IRS.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the federal agency's 1998 restructuring to take
consumer confusion out of tax collection, the IRS set up four
operating divisions to specialize in a particular tax area.
</P>
<P>
   The wage and investment operating division, charged with
handling individual taxpayer returns, will be based in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The wage and investment division will begin operations Oct. 1 in
the Peachtree Summit Building downtown, said John Dalrymple, the
division's commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   The unit will hire several hundred employees and will be
operational by May 2001, he said. The agency already has hired 100
people to staff the division.
</P>
<P>
   The division will handle $380 billion of the $1.8 trillion in
taxes the IRS collects each year.
</P>
<P>
   The three other divisions, based in Washington for now, will
handle returns for mid- and large-sized businesses, tax exempt
organizations and government entities, and small
business/self-employed operators.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the old system, which was geographically based with 33
districts nationwide, the new approach is meant to make the IRS
more customer-friendly, Dalrymple said.
</P>
<P>
   Local tax preparers and certified public accountants said the
IRS' step toward specialization is a logical move. ``The tax code
is so broad and so complicated, they need to break it down into
smaller segments,'' said Ken Weatherwax, owner of Weatherwax &AMP;
Associates, a tax public accounting firm in Norcross.
</P>
<P>
   The restructuring will make it easier for taxpayers to navigate
the agency, said one former IRS agent. ``It's easier, yes, but the
people who want to cheat are getting away with murder,'' said
Lawrence L. Denney, an IRS agent for eight years before starting
his Atlanta-based public accounting firm in 1983. The IRS has been
lax on filing levies and seizures on evaders since the Tax Reform
Act of 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a wonderful time for people who don't want to pay
taxes,'' he said, adding about 20 percent of Americans don't file
or pay taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
