<HEADER>
A4429 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS &LR;      09-06 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-SHUTTLE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Russia scurries to find government funds for space station
 &HT;    Lightning strike interrupts NASA's preparations for Atlantis
launch
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By MARK CARREAU
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. _ Russia's space agency is once again
scraping for the scarce government funds it needs to keep the
international space station supplied with fuel and the other
supplies next year, a top official said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   More funding will be needed soon if Russia's contractors are to
finish the work on rockets that will be needed to boost a
half-dozen Progress cargo and two Soyuz crew capsules to the slowly
developing orbital outpost during 2001, according to Mikhail
Sinelshikov, chief of piloted programs for the Russian Aviation and
Space Agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ugly process actually,'' said Sinelshikov, who is
at NASA's Kennedy Space Center this week for the launching of the
U.S. shuttle Atlantis on a supply mission to the station. ``It's a
very difficult, cumbersome, unpleasant process of dealing with the
ministry of finance and actually forcefully getting the money.''
</P>
<P>
   Sinelshikov was hopeful the prime minister, Parliament and
finance ministry can free up the Russian equivalent of $54 million
by the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Russia successfully launched the station's Zvezda
module, a 43-foot-long compartment that equipped the station with
living and working quarters for three. The addition will make it
possible for astronauts and cosmonauts to begin a decade-long
occupancy of the outpost in early November.
</P>
<P>
   Stalled more than two years by Russian economic problems, the
Zvezda module represents the first of that country's major
contributions to an unprecedented assembly effort involving 16
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's other major contribution is a steady supply of Progress
and Soyuz capsules. The Progress will furnish the fuel that is
necessary to keep the outpost circling the Earth at a safe
altitude. The Soyuz capsules will park at the station for six
months at a time, serving as lifeboats for residents of the
outpost, a means of returning quickly to Earth in an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians offered assurances they will have no difficulty
launching a Soyuz with the station's first resident crew, American
Bill Shepherd and cosmonauts Yuri Gidzenko and Sergei Krikalev on
Oct. 30 nor the three Progress capsules pledged for the remainder
of this year.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 rockets are in various stages of assembly at RSC
Energia, the Russian agency's spacecraft contractor, plenty of
hardware to meet the station's future Soyuz and Progress needs if
only the funds arrive to finish the work.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to make sure we are on our way next year,'' said
Sinelshikov. ``We need to do some important work right now to be
sure we will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   As the project's managing partner, NASA is planning three
shuttle station supply and assembly missions this year and six in
2001, a pace that will greatly enhance the size and capability of
the new station.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. space agency is closely monitoring Russian
spacecraft production and developing options to make up for lapses
in the Progress missions where it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russians are very financially strapped. They don't have as
much money as they and I would like them to have,'' said Tommy
Holloway, NASA's space station program manager. ``They are very
resourceful. We will watch and wait.''
</P>
<P>
   One option is to dedicate the Progress craft that are available
to fuel transport. The food, spare parts, clothing and other dry
cargo would instead be delivered aboard U.S. shuttles, said Bob
Cabana, NASA's manager of international operations for the station.
</P>
<P>
   XXXXX
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's
efforts to prepare Atlantis for a Friday liftoff were interrupted
for several hours by a lightning strike on the shuttle's coastal
launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis was undamaged by the strike. The shuttle was shielded
by an elaborate protection system that includes a 100-foot tall
lightning rod that rises above the launch pad and a network of
conductive cabling that grounded the surge.
</P>
<P>
   After the strike late Tuesday, engineers examined launch pad
sensors and reviewed a record of electrical activity aboard
Atlantis before concluding the shuttle was unharmed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't see anything that concerns us at all,'' said Dave
King, NASA's shuttle launch director.
</P>
<P>
   However, the recovery activities placed ground crews several
hours behind schedule on Wednesday as they readied the shuttle's
electrical power generation system for an 11-day flight. Atlantis
is scheduled to blast off at at 7:45 a.m. CDT, Friday.
</P>
<P>
   King said that all countdown activities would be back on
schedule by early Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   After docking with the station, the shuttle crew plans to unload
about 5,000 pounds of equipment, some carried into orbit by
Atlantis and some already awaiting the astronauts in a Progress
capsule that linked with the outpost in early August.
</P>
<P>
   The cargo includes equipment that recycles breathing air, a
toilet and exercise gear. The fliers will prepare the systems for
the arrival of Shepherd's crew.
</P>
<P>
   xxxx END OF STORY xxxxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
