<HEADER>
A4431 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-OHAIR07-COX     09-06 0638
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OHAIR07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Prosecutors may indict Waters in O'Hair case
 &HT;    By Andrea Ball
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Five years after atheist leader Madalyn O'Hair
and two relatives vanished in a suspected kidnapping and murder
plot, federal prosecutors are going after the man they say
masterminded everything _ David Roland Waters.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office plans to seek an indictment against
Waters, 53, in the 1995 disappearance of O'Hair, her son Jon Garth
Murray and granddaughter Robin Murray-O'Hair, whom she adopted as
her daughter. The case could be presented to the grand jury within
the next month.
</P>
<P>
   Sources involved in the investigation refused to speak publicly
about Waters, who is serving a 60-year prison sentence. But several
said plans to pursue Waters are motivated by two factors: fear that
Waters could be released from prison and a rapidly approaching
deadline for the statute of limitations.
</P>
<P>
   If indicted, Waters would be the second man charged in the
O'Hair family's disappearance. Last month, alleged accomplice Gary
Paul Karr was sentenced to life in prison after a jury convicted
him of crimes including extortion and transporting stolen goods. He
was acquitted of a kidnapping charge.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have not rushed to indict Waters because he is
already in state prison. The Illinois native, who pleaded guilty in
1995 to stealing $54,000 from O'Hair's atheist organization, is
serving 60 years for violating his probation in that theft. He also
must serve a separate eight-year federal sentence on unrelated gun
charges.
</P>
<P>
   But Waters' time in prison could be shorter than expected.
</P>
<P>
   As new projections show Texas prisons could be filled to
capacity in one year, parole officials are considering policy
changes that could allow more nonviolent offenders to be released.
Although convicted in other states of murder and assault, Waters
has no violent offense on his Texas criminal record.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators worry that Waters, eligible for parole in 2006,
could be released early to serve his federal time, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not he would be paroled that early would be up to
the parole board, but their record shows that criminals of this
nature are rarely being given parole before their scheduled release
date,'' said Larry Todd, spokesman for the Texas Department of
Criminal Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Garrett, chairman of the Texas Board of Pardons and
Paroles, said that he did not know whether Waters would be a likely
candidate for parole but that Waters would be considered like
anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be irresponsible of me to speculate on the outcome of
a particular person's parole without knowing the facts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another motivating factor in the potential indictment is time.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have until October _ when the five-year statute of
limitations expires _ to file charges in the O'Hair family's
disappearance that don't carry the death penalty, such as
kidnapping and transporting stolen property. After that, federal
prosecutors have only one basic option: murder charges.
</P>
<P>
   Without bodies, eyewitnesses or strong physical evidence,
prosecutors acknowledge murder charges would be hard to prove.
</P>
<P>
   But the kidnapping charge is another story. Jurors in the Karr
case resoundingly agreed that, had Waters been on trial, they would
have convicted him on all counts. Jury foreman Hector Rodriguez
said he expected a new jury would come to the same conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the very strong evidence in the case was about Mr.
Waters,'' Rodriguez said. ``The prosecution portrayed him as an
evil man capable of these sorts of things. ... I couldn't imagine
that any reasonable juror could move to acquit him based on that
evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
