<HEADER>
A4432 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UT-SICKOUT07-COX     09-06 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UT-SICKOUT07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    UT 'sick out' pretty anemic, observers say
 &HT;    By Ben Wear and Sharon Jayson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The burnt-orange flu at the University of Texas
Wednesday was more like a case of the hiccups.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the thousands of absent staff employees predicted by
the University Staff Association, which organized what is supposed
to be a three-day work stoppage, participation appeared to be in
the dozens or low hundreds. The group put the number higher, saying
that based on visits to some campus offices and extrapolations
1,300 and 1,800 of UT-Austin's 7,900 classified staff workers
stayed home.
</P>
<P>
   Wherever the actual figure lies, campus officials said the
missing employees failed to even partially disrupt operations.
Aside from a noon protest attended by perhaps 300 students and
employees and some classes held outdoors in support of the sickout,
Wednesday looked like business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the association, which has organized events since
1997 to protest salary and other issues, said they hoped for more
employees to stay home. The association's president, Peg Kramer,
had estimated that up to 7,000 would call in sick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to escalate things,'' Kramer said. ``The focus
should be on the fact that the university hasn't addressed one
issue on the list of 17 demands. And that university employees are
so afraid of their employer that they're afraid to participate in a
job action.''
</P>
<P>
   Average pay for support staff at UT has increased 21 percent in
three years. But it still lags behind other Austin salaries, and
insurance changes this spring increased premiums for most
employees. University President Larry Faulkner said he will
continue to make raising staff pay a priority and that answers to
other issues are in the works. UT has already announced it will
create a staff advisory council, with members elected by classified
staff workers. And Faulkner said he will announce a new, more
arms-length grievance procedure for staff members ``pretty soon.''
</P>
<P>
   As for those who participated in the sickout, Faulkner said
punishment, if any, will be up to supervisors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not going to be any witch-hunt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While UT officials did not have comprehensive numbers on
absentees, they did have some indications there was little
participation. Physical Plant _ the section of UT whose 1,000 or so
workers keep the campus buildings clean and machinery humming _ had
eight absences on the day shift, said Kyle Cavanaugh, UT's
associate vice president for human resources. That number, however,
stood to grow, he said, as night-time shifts begin. He said four of
several hundred Food and Housing employees were missing.
</P>
<P>
   Student Financial Services, with about 55 staff members, was at
100 percent on Wednesday, said Director Larry Burt. At the
University's Health Services Department, medical director Dr.
Theresa Spaldingsaid three people of about 160 called in ill. Ten
to 12 of the College of Liberal Arts' 287 staff employees were out,
Cavanaugh said. And at the School of Social Work, where Kramer
works as a graduate adviser, nine of 13 staff employees were at
work. Kramer was among the missing. .
</P>
<P>
   It was a normal Wednesday at the Perry-Castaneda Library, said
Robert Clontz, a part-time staffer who works at the circulation
desk. ``I haven't heard much talk within the library about joining
the walkout,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among students, few were well-versed on UT staff complaints or
the sickout But some, such as junior Janis Gorton, wore ``Students
Support Staff'' stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I signed the petition and we've talked about it in class,''
she said. ``I don't know if it's the best way, but I think maybe
right now it's the best action because the university isn't really
listening to what they're saying.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
