<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0319 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4436 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-JOAN-OSBORNE-MUSIC-$A     09-06 1523
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOAN-OSBORNE-MUSIC-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH A NEW RELEASE, A RELUCTANT MAKEOVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
(Karen Schoemer is senior editor for music for Us Weekly.) 
 By KAREN SCHOEMER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The woman who greets you in front of a Manhattan soul food joint
is not someone you would recognize. She is tall and imposing,
beautiful but remote. She wears slender black stretch capris and a
chic blue three-quarter-sleeve gingham shirt with matching
decorative eyeshades. Her posture is so perfect she could balance
books on her head; her cheeks have a spa-fresh glow. Demure honey
ringlets frame her face. She tells you that this home-cooking place
is a bit crowded and noisy for her liking; she would prefer the
upscale French boite across the street. She glides into a booth,
tucks her Bebe shopping bag under the table, orders a cappuccino _
no food today; she is staying slim for some forthcoming television
appearances _ and fixes you with a humorless, rather unhelpful
stare. You feel perplexed, a little thrown off. You look over her
shoulder, half expecting a wild-haired, grinning, explosive,
bluejeans-clad hippie babe to leap out from behind a pillar and
rescue you. You're not sure what to say to this creature. How
about: Nice to meet you _ now where's Joan Osborne?
</P>
<P>
   The music business has a long tradition of making over its
female artists, whether it's the Supremes in finishing school or
just the latest battery of stylists dispatched to a video shoot.
What's odd about Osborne's situation is that she seems to have
forced this transformation upon herself, and she's not entirely
comfortable with it. Is that a designer shirt? you can't help
asking. ``Well, yes, it's Agnes B.,'' she answers with a slight
squirm. ``I have a weird relationship to the whole celebrity
glamour thing, so I'm wary of saying that I bought a designer
shirt. I don't like that musicians have become mannequins for
designers, and that everything people wear gets reported on in the
media, and people don't have their own style anymore. But I did buy
it; they didn't give it to me. I mean, I like nice things, and I
don't have to buy my clothes at Goodwill anymore. It's nice to be
able to go into a store and pick out something beautiful and wear
it and like it. I don't think there's anything wrong with that.''
Then she allows herself a wee extra measure of defensiveness.
``It's not like it's Versace or anything,'' she grumbles.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne, 37, has a strong motivation for remaking herself. On
September 12 she releases ``Righteous Love,'' her first album in
five years and the long-delayed follow-up to her Grammy-nominated
major-label debut, ``Relish.'' What's on the line? Only her future
as a recording artist and her ability to continue making a living
at the thing she loves, music. Five years ago, Osborne, along with
Sheryl Crow and Sarah McLachlan, helped set a new standard for
strong, self-sufficient female singer-songwriters in the pop
marketplace. Osborne was the most unconventional of the three:
Raised in Kentucky, with a gutsy stage presence nurtured in New
York City dives and a voice that teetered between angelic ecstasy
and sexual abandon, she expressed an affinity for the blues that
had rarely been heard in a white girl since Janis Joplin.
``Relish'' was the success story of the year. By early 1996 she had
been nominated for seven Grammy Awards; the album crept into
Billboard's top 10, and the single ``One of Us,'' a quirky musing
on God, hit No. 4. Rolling Stone put her on the cover, and
Entertainment Weekly dubbed her ``Saint Joan.'' Her natural image
was a huge part of the appeal: Her kinky hair, lack of makeup and
exuberant smile suggested that a woman could be herself, look like
herself and still win the love of millions.
</P>
<P>
   But behind the scenes, problems were brewing. By the time of the
Grammys _ and by the way, she left empty-handed _ Osborne was
already starting to psych herself out. Wrestling with the notion of
a follow-up, she embarked on a compulsive spree of collaborations
with different producers, including David Lowery of the band
Cracker; Aaron Comess of the Spin Doctors; the hip-hop producer
Mike Mangini, and T-Bone Burnett, who had coaxed hits out of the
Wallflowers and Counting Crows. Most of the sessions were
fruitless. She even dallied once again with Rick Chertoff, who had
produced ``Relish'' and signed her to Mercury Records. But she was
uneasy about giving Chertoff too much control. For all the
accolades, she was dissatisfied with ``Relish.'' ``I think I have a
lot more in me than what's on there,'' she told Spin magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Her restlessness went beyond the recording studio. She traveled
to India to perform at a benefit for the Dalai Lama and studied
vocal technique with the qawwali singer Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan.
Finally, after three years of searching, she hit a groove with the
producer Mitchell Froom (his credits include albums with Suzanne
Vega and Elvis Costello). And then out of nowhere she became the
victim of a music-industry drive-by. Mercury's parent company,
Polygram, was bought by Seagram and merged with Universal. Late in
1999, her album still unfinished, Osborne was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   She says she tried not to take it personally. ``My first
reaction was: Wow! That's a bad business decision. If I were a
business person, I would not choose to drop me.'' She decided to
continue work on the album using her own money. ``It became a
little scary when I realized that if I couldn't get another deal, I
was going to lose my house,'' she says matter-of-factly. She did
get another deal, curiously enough, with Interscope, a label within
the Universal fold. ``It was a risk,'' Osborne says now. ``But I
think it would have been a greater risk for me not to do it. I
didn't have anything to fall back on. It's not like I could start
making a living at Wall Street the next day. I just thought, well,
this is one of those moments that you read about in people's
stories, when they're up against a wall and they have to take a
chance and believe in themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Righteous Love'' is ready to be heard, but Osborne's struggles
probably aren't over. The pop world is a completely different place
now than it was five years ago. Studio-sculptured, choreographed
and scripted idols like Britney Spears and Christina Aguilera have
become the new female role models. The momentum of Lilith Fair has
expired for a more up-to-date example of gung-ho female
togetherness _ check out ``The Powerpuff Girls.'' Osborne, who
lives in Manhattan, insists she's not starting from scratch. ``As
fickle as audiences or the media can be, I still walk around the
streets of New York and strangers ask me, `When is your new record
coming out?''' she says. ``That will happen a couple of times a
day. So I do have a feeling like they're still out there. I don't
know how many people are out there, but there's somebody that still
wants to hear more.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet she realizes that she is under pressure, even if it's
self-inflicted, to conform to a less forgiving and indulgent set of
music-business rules. ``I know the word artist has been adulterated
in the context of the music business, but I still believe in what
that means for myself,'' she says. ``So to keep functioning within
a system where it doesn't really matter if you're an artist or not
_ you just have to sell records and whatever sells is acceptable
and legitimate _ well, that can be difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   With ``Righteous Love,'' Osborne is trying to have it both ways:
She wants to express raw passion and sexual heat but do it in a
restrained enough way to be digestible by a wide audience. She
needs to deliver a product that will make a healthy return on her
label's investment, or risk losing the financial backing that
allows her to work at a broad mainstream level; yet she also needs
to satisfy a core audience that looks to her for music of lasting
substance. It's a lot to accomplish. ``Righteous Love'' has some
glorious moments: The title track shimmies and sways like a
beefed-up version of early '60s Brill Building soul, and ``Poisoned
Apples (Hallelujah)'' equals the best moments on ``Relish'' for its
conflation of the sexual and the spiritual. Her cover of Bob
Dylan's ``To Make You Feel My Love'' is so sublime, you are tricked
into thinking it's one of the best songs he ever wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Osborne herself admits that at times she has been too distracted
by other aspects of the business to focus on the goal at hand.
``I'm jealous of people like Neil Young who came of age in the '60s
and '70s, when it wasn't part of your job to pose for a million
magazine pictures and look like a model,'' she says. `` 'Cause I
don't, and it's hard to try. I think my music has suffered because
of the time I have to put into other things. I often struggle with
the thought that here I am spending an hour at the gym because I
have to look a certain way, because otherwise I won't be palatable
to an audience. When in reality I would rather be learning to play
the guitar better or spending more time writing. It is a
compromise; it is a balancing act.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0320 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TX-FOODSTAMPS07-COX     09-06 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TX-FOODSTAMPS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas food stamp rolls drop by 40 percent since 1996
 &HT;    By Gaiutra Bahadur
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Cynthia Ali, a working mother of five from the
Lincoln Gardens section of East Austin, almost applied for food
stamps last May.
</P>
<P>
   Then she found out she would need to take time off from her job
as a kitchen manager to get pay stubs from a former boss and to
ferry her kids to the local Texas Works office to be fingerprinted
and photographed.
</P>
<P>
   The eligibility interview would last about 90 minutes, if it
kept pace with the statewide average.
</P>
<P>
   Every hour would cost Ali $9.46 in wages. It would take seven
hours to consume the average food stamp benefit of $71 per person
per month. That would not be enough to feed Ali's weeks-old
granddaughter Enfamil baby formula for the full month. And in one
to three months, she'd have to take time off again to be
recertified because of a 1995 state law designed to fight fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to go through that,'' Ali said. ``I just
said, ``Forget about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly a million fewer Texans receive food stamps today than in
1996, the year that Congress overhauled welfare. The 41 percent
drop _ slightly more than the nationwide decline of 33 percent _ is
due partly because of lower unemployment rates and a strong
economy.
</P>
<P>
   But food banks report a steady demand for their services, and
anti-hunger advocates say many people have left the rolls because
of a complex and burdensome application process. The government
estimates that 37 percent of people eligible for food stamps aren't
getting them.
</P>
<P>
   A recent study by America's Second Harvest, a hunger relief
group based in Chicago, showed that food stamp applications in 29
states and the District of Columbia are 10 to 36 pages long. The
average application is 12 pages long. And in all states except
North Carolina, the applications require a 9th to 12th grade
reading level.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, called ``The Red Tape Divide,'' some
states ask food stamp applicants about income from baby-sitting,
panhandling, bingo and blood donations. Some demand garage sale
receipts. And others ask about assets in the form of burial plots,
tools and livestock.
</P>
<P>
   In Texas, the form spans four pages _ longer than applications
for a federal firearms permit, the federal school lunch program or
a school bus driver's license. According to America's Second
Harvest, the Texas application requires a 12th grade reading level
and asks three questions that the group says are not necessary to
determine eligibility:
</P>
<P>
   -- The value of a house or land.
</P>
<P>
   -- The value of life insurance and/or pensions.
</P>
<P>
   -- The value of gifts or loans from charities, friends or
relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Traylor, a spokesman for the Department of Human Services,
said Texas uses a single form to determine eligibility for food
stamps, Medicaid and Temporary Assistance to Needy Families. That
means some questions not specifically relevant to food stamp
eligibility might be asked, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Traylor also said details about payments on a home could help,
not hinder, an applicant for food stamps; that gifts and loans,
depending on the size and circumstances, could count as assets; and
that questions about life insurance, while not required by the
federal government, ``provide clues to unreportable income.''
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Public Policy Priorities, an Austin-based
research institute that focuses on poverty and its impact, worked
with advocates, legislative aides and case workers from the
Department of Human Services to design a new application to be
tested in five cities, including Houston, Pampa, Mission and Del
Rio. The pilot will begin as soon as the agency receives approval
from the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   The experimental application is four pages longer than the
current one, but its language is simpler and its tone is more
helpful. It has breakout boxes with ``Important Information for
Immigrants'' and separate sections in Spanish. Its text is larger
and easier on the eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Celia Hagert, a nutritional policy expert with the center, said
the new application would be a step in the right direction but more
needs to be done to reduce the ``burden on working families, who
need to take time off from work to apply.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocacy groups suggest extended office hours, limiting
face-to-face interviews for recertification to once a year and
allowing food stamp enrollees to recertify by phone or mail in the
interim. They also support more training for case workers to cut
down on confusion about who is eligible for food stamps or other
assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Hagert said some of the $27 billion in federal money Texas
received from Sept. 1998 to Aug. 31, 1999 _ as a result of its
success in reducing welfare fraud _ should be used for outreach to
Texans eligible for food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Traylor said the state's decline in food stamp rolls outpaced
the country's decline partly because of Texas' large share of
immigrants. In 1996, Congress made many immigrants ineligible for
benefits.
</P>
<P>
   About 935,000 legal immigrants, or about 5 percent of the
caseload, lost their food stamp eligibility.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Public Policy Priorities estimates that about 12
percent of the decline in Texas over the last four years can be
attributed to this change in federal policy.
</P>
<P>
   You may contact Gaiutra Bahadur at gbahadur(at)statesman.com or
445-3631.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
