<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ABORIGINES-1130(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUSTRALIA'S `STOLEN GENERATION' TRIES TO HEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SYDNEY, Australia _ Valerie Murphy stood in the alley behind her
modest house on the tattered fringe of downtown, smoking nervously,
looking away as if to keep tears from coming into her eyes. Even
now, four decades later, she said she could hardly speak of the
time when her life had been stolen.
</P>
<P>
   At 53, she is part of what is known here as the ``stolen
generation,'' one of perhaps 100,000 Aboriginal children, most of
them light skinned, who were taken from their parents between 1910
and 1970 and placed into training homes to be assimilated into the
dominant white culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like thinking about it,'' Murphy said, producing a
photograph of herself, uncertainty and fear on her face, with other
girls at the Cootamundra Training Home for Girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was 5 or 6 when they took me. Eleven years I was there. When
you did something wrong, they put you in a room like a box. I would
bang and bang to get out of that box. When I was 14, the police
flogged me. They have taken my life away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Summer Olympics, which begin Sept. 15, will showcase
Sydney's famous Opera House, its arresting harbor vistas and its
fabulous swimmers. The Games will also focus attention on the
plight of the Aborigines, Australia's indigenous minority who
originally inhabited the continent 50,000 years ago but were
marginalized over the past two centuries by European settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The treatment of the Aboriginals, who make up about 400,000 of
Australia's 19 million people, has a bleak resonance with the
struggles of American Indians and blacks in the United States.
Indigenous people were not allowed to vote until 1962 in Australia
and were not counted in the national census until 1967. Life
expectancy is 18 years shorter for Aboriginals, average incomes are
one-third lower and the unemployment rate _ 34 percent _ is nearly
five times the national average.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with alcohol, drugs, suicide, domestic violence and
high birth rates are severe. A quarter of the Aboriginals age 55 or
over have never been to school. Aborigines account for half of the
young people incarcerated in the juvenile justice system.
</P>
<P>
   The Australian government will spend $1.5 billion on Aboriginal
programs this year, addressing disadvantages in health, education,
employment and housing. In May, more than 200,000 people marched
through Sydney in support of racial equality. But contentious
debate persists on how to achieve reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   Only last week, after a number of reprimands, the conservative
government of Prime Minister John Howard announced that it would no
longer cooperate with the United Nations' attempt to investigate
Australia's human rights practices.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently concerned about the government's vulnerability to
demands for compensation, Howard has declined to formally apologize
to the Aborigines. He has also opposed a civil rights treaty for
Aborigines. Opinion polls indicate that most Australians support
Howard in opposition to special treatment for indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both the prime minister and I have expressed our personal
feelings of deep sorrow in relation to the injustices suffered by
indigenous Australians as a result of the practices of past
generations,'' said Sen. John Herron, the minister for Aboriginal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   But the government does not support a formal apology, Herron
said, because it ``could imply that present generations are in some
way responsible and accountable for the actions of earlier
generations, actions that were sanctioned by the laws of the time,
and that were believed to be in the best interests of the children
concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   Aborigines have sharply criticized Herron for suggesting that
perhaps only 10 percent of Aboriginal children were taken from
their families and for calling the term ``stolen generation''
rhetorical.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say we were not stolen,'' Murphy said outside her home in
the Redfern section of Sydney. ``It made me cry, it hurt so much.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was not seeking financial reparation from the
government, only an apology for past wrongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, it would be helpful,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Australia's most celebrated Aborigine, Cathy Freeman, the world
champion in the 400-meter sprint and an Olympic gold medal
favorite, called the federal government insensitive in July and
revealed that her grandmother had been taken from her parents and
did not know her own birthday or her precise age.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an endemic problem ignored by most Australians, and
there seems to be compassion fatigue for acknowledging the
problem,'' said Sen. Aden Ridgeway, the only Aboriginal member of
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the Aborigines will be made visible during the
Olympics in both celebration and protest. Juan Antonio Samaranch,
president of the International Olympic Committee, plans to mention
the Aborigines in his remarks during opening ceremonies. The
boomerang, an Aboriginal hunting tool, has been incorporated into
the official Olympic logo.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers will allow the red, black and yellow Aboriginal flag
_ depicting the earth, the skin of the indigenous people and the
sun _ to be flown at Olympic stadiums. Freeman and others will also
be welcomed to carry the flag during victory laps.
</P>
<P>
   In Victoria Park, just outside Sydney's central business
district, televisions will be hooked up so that protesters
occupying 40 or so tents at the so-called Aboriginal Tent Embassy
can watch Freeman run. A fire ritual is performed each day at the
encampment as branches from gum trees are placed on smoking logs in
a gesture of peace and healing. Oral histories will be presented at
Aboriginal forums in the park during the Games, and a rally is
planned for the day the Games open.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want the world to know that this country is at war with its
indigenous people,'' said Isabell Coe, the advocate who started the
tent embassy in July.
</P>
<P>
   Another group is planning to form a human chain along the road
outside the Sydney airport to make Olympic visitors aware of the
despairing condition of Australia's indigenous people. Trevor
Close, an Aboriginal activist, said he planned to camp with some
protesters near the Olympic Stadium and might resort to violent
clashes if the police interfere.
</P>
<P>
   The Aborigines were nomadic hunter-gatherers still using stone
tools when European settlers, primarily British convicts, arrived
in 1788. Their encounter with white migration proved ruinous to the
Aborigines' way of life. Many were massacred, others died of
diseases to which they were not immune and survivors were placed in
missions run by churches and the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are being treated like aliens in our own country,'' Coe
said. ``The only place we are winning is the number of prisoners.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
