<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-ABORIGINES-NYT     09-06 0395
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-ABORIGINES-NYT </SLUG>
 
SYDNEY, Australia: of prisoners.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still, Aboriginals have managed to produce notable achievements
in recent years on the national and world stage. Nova
Perris-Kneebone became the first Aborigine to win a gold medal as
part of Australia's field hockey team at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics.
Freeman is a two-time world champion and Olympic silver medalist in
the 400 meters. The Aboriginal writer Kim Scott won a share of
Australia's top fiction prize this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, two members of the so-called stolen
generation had their claims for reparation dismissed last month in
a federal test case.
</P>
<P>
   The urban despair of Sydney's Aborigines is apparent in Murphy's
blighted neighborhood, known as ``the block,'' a failed land-grant
experiment for indigenous people. It is a rat- and drug-infested
collection of graffiti-scarred houses where heroin addicts inject
themselves 50 yards from a playground where children frolic on
swings.
</P>
<P>
   Ridgeway, the Aboriginal senator, said the sense of fatalism can
be overcome only by self-determination, including the recognition
of traditional laws, diversionary programs instead of mandatory
prison sentencing and restoring the role of Aboriginal elders
within communities. But the current government is concerned that
the creation of two sets of laws would diminish the sense of
Australia as a single nation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are talking about a disciplinary code that is breached
and the penalty enacted might be a spear in the thigh, by today's
values that would be something broadly unacceptable,'' said Philip
Ruddock, the minister of immigration and multicultural affairs.
</P>
<P>
   The infant mortality rate among Aboriginals, once 20 times the
national average, has decreased to three times the national
average. While only a handful of Aborigines once went to college,
there are now 8,000 college graduates, ministry statistics show.
</P>
<P>
   But a much more comprehensive effort needs to be taken, Ridgeway
contended, or the cycle of poverty and despair will only perpetuate
itself under the current welfare state.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most a young Aboriginal person can expect to achieve is to
work for the dole scheme, and he essentially reaches that at 16, 17
or 18,'' Ridgeway said. ``There is nothing beyond that.
Incarceration becomes a badge of honor, a right of passage into
adulthood.''
</P>
</TEXT>
