s e BC-DEVIL-FILM-2TAKES-$AD     09-06 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEVIL-FILM-2TAKES-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENOUGH ABOUT ANGELS: THE DEVIL GETS HIS DUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By JAMIE MALANOWSKI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Angels have been gracing pop culture fairly ostentatiously these
last several years _ ``Touched by an Angel,'' ``City of Angels,''
``Angels in the Outfield,'' ``Angels in America,'' John Travolta
spectacularly spreading his wings in ``Michael,'' the elevation of
``It's a Wonderful Life'' to a basic text of American civilization.
But lately, and almost unnoticed in the seraphic swell, the Devil
has been getting his due.
</P>
<P>
   Date the current surge to 1997, when Al Pacino was so
charismatically diabolical in ``The Devil's Advocate.'' Since then,
the Devil has been a featured player in three television series,
``G&AMP;E,'' ``Brimstone'' and ``God, the Devil and Bob''; had a big
part last year in the Arnold Schwarzenegger Christmas movie ``End
of Days''; prominently appeared in the Johnny Depp vehicle ``The
Ninth Gate''; was the prime mover of the plot of the Kim Basinger
movie ``Bless the Child'' this summer; and had the key supporting
part _ the best part, really, and one in which he showed a
surprising comic touch and a long-hidden singing voice _ in ``South
Park: Bigger, Longer, Uncut,'' last summer's animation hit.
</P>
<P>
   I know what you're thinking: With as many people in Hollywood
headed for hell as the religious right seems to think, why such an
uneven output? All three television series tanked. The big ``Ninth
Gate'' reunion of Roman Polanski and the Devil turned out to be
less a reimagining of ``Rosemary's Baby'' than leftovers on the
order of ``The Odd Couple II.'' And ``End of Days,'' dramatically
speaking, fell short of apocalyptic. But the Devil must have an
awfully good agent: This fall will have no fewer than five movies
featuring Old Nick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedazzled,'' a remake of the Peter Cook-Dudley Moore classic,
stars Brendan Fraser as a nerdy young man who, in exchange for the
fulfillment of seven wishes, surrenders his soul to a very
seductive Devil played by Elizabeth Hurley. ``Little Nicky'' is a
comedy in which the casting seems half the attraction: Adam Sandler
as Satan's good son, Harvey Keitel as Satan and Rodney Dangerfield
as Satan's father. In ``Lost Souls,'' a thriller, Winona Ryder
plays a devout schoolteacher who becomes aware of a Satanic
conspiracy against a New York journalist (like, only one?). ``Simon
Magus,'' a British film by Ben Hopkins set in 19th-century Europe,
is about a young man seemingly possessed by the Devil (Ian Holm,
who, making sure that all his bases are covered in the afterlife,
played a Satan-fighting priest in ``Bless the Child''). And the
granddaddy of them all, ``The Exorcist,'' will be rereleased with
additional material never shown before _ perhaps scenes where the
poor girl stops spewing pea soup and moves on to beef barley and
chicken with stars. Not to give anything short shrift, hovering
somewhere in straight-to-videoland is ``G-Men From Hell,'' in which
the Devil is portrayed by Robert Goulet.
</P>
<P>
   While this does seem to be an especially verdant crop full of
stellar performers, devil movies have always been with us. A search
of the Internet Movie Database (imdb.com), in a highly unofficial
but still usefully suggestive count, yields 290 movies about the
Devil, starting with Georges Melies' ``Le Cabinet de
Mephistopheles,'' which was made in 1897; but more than half the
films have been made since 1980. Among the more provocative items
on the list: ``Inflation'' (1942), in which the Devil, in response
to a telephone call from Adolf Hitler, begins wrecking the American
economy by encouraging people to cash in their war bonds, to hoard
and to spend too much money (no doubt an impressionable Alan
Greenspan attended repeated showings); ``Santa Claus'' (1959), in
which Santa has to battle Satan's minions before delivering his
Christmas Eve rewards; ``Satan's Cheerleaders'' (1977), in which
the members of a high school cheerleading squad turn out to be _ as
many have long suspected _ ringleaders of a Satanic cult;
``Fertilize the Blaspheming Bombshell'' (1990), in which a comely
lass is menaced by Satan worshipers en route from New York to Las
Vegas, and ``Girlfriend from Hell'' (1990), in which the Devil,
fleeing one of God's agents, hides in the body of a young woman on
a blind date. Perhaps this is based on a true story.
</P>
<P>
   Although we missed these films, we've seen plenty of others.
Some general themes emerge.
</P>
<P>
   1. HOLLYWOOD CAN'T AGREE ON WHAT THE DEVIL CAN DO. Moviemakers
are pretty consistent about the Devil's being the source of all
evil in the world, but there's a range of opinion on other matters,
beginning with whether he's the Devil at all. Sometimes the
character we see is clearly Satan ( Pacino in ``The Devil's
Advocate,'' the Beast in ``Rosemary's Baby''); sometimes he is the
Devil in human form (Gabriel Byrne in ``End of Days''), and
sometimes he's the Devil's son (Sam Neill in the ``Omen'' sequels).
Sometimes, for whatever reason, the Devil is more reclusive, and we
meet his emissary or servant (Rufus Sewell in ``Bless the Child'').
Sometimes it's not clear whom we're seeing. Emmanuelle Seigner may
be the Devil in ``The Ninth Gate,'' but the whole movie is about
how complicated it is to summon the Devil, and she's been hanging
around the whole picture. In ``Damn Yankees,'' is Ray Walston the
Devil, or just his field representative in Washington, D.C.? And
why isn't his office on K Street?
</P>
<P>
   Other questions remain. Sometimes the Devil can be thwarted by
faith _ in ``The Evil'' (1978), when the psychologist played by
Richard Crenna uses a crucifix to stab Victor Buono, playing Satan
as a grouchy neighbor who won't give back your baseball, it stymies
Satan long enough for Crenna to escape. Rediscovering faith helps
Schwarzenegger thwart the devil in ``End of Days.'' But they're
stars. Faith is fairly useless to secondary characters, like the
elderly priest in ``The Omen'' whose function in the movie is to
warn a skeptical Gregory Peck that he really shouldn't be worrying
about getting his son into a good prep school, and then to die
gruesomely. Sometimes faith has nothing to do with it: In
``Crossroads'' (1983), the hero's classical-music training enables
him to win a blues-guitar showdown and beat the Devil.
</P>
<P>
   There are other discrepancies. Usually the Devil has
extraordinary demonic powers. But at other times he seems weaker,
resorting to agents _ a dog in ``The Omen,'' street kids in ``Bless
the Child'' _ to wreak havoc. Occasionally he goes to great lengths
to avoid suspicion: In ``The Omen,'' he kills a character by
causing him to be decapitated by a runaway cart _ nothing a veteran
police officer hasn't seen before; in ``Bless the Child,'' the
Devil proves as inept as a Bond villain _ instead of just offing
Kim Basinger, he tries to kill her by causing her to drive off a
bridge, and she gets away. All this is very confusing. Is the Devil
who causes a lighting bolt to break a shaft off a church and then
sends it ripping through the air to pierce a cleric in ``The Omen''
the same Devil who relies on sweaty spells, deal-making and the
drug-dispensing ministrations of Ruth Gordon just to get a young
woman pregnant in ``Rosemary's Baby''? Can the Devil who blows up
restaurants on a whim in ``End of Days'' be the same fussy
businessman who patiently waits for Mickey Rourke to track down
Johnny Favorite in ``Angel Heart''? Why does Pacino's Devil let his
minions spend so much time shredding documents to thwart a
government investigation if he's perfectly capable, as he
demonstrates, of just killing the investigator?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe he is _ the big source book is hardly consistent.
Professor Elaine Pagels, the Harrington Speare Professor of
Religion at Princeton University, points out in her book ``The
Origin of Satan'' that the first few times Satan appears in the Old
Testament, he's just a servant of God sent to obstruct human
activity _ on God's orders. Gradually, Satan's role evolves. He
prods God to test Job; later, Satan is blamed for pushing King
David into an unpopular tax plan. Only in Isaiah do we finally get
the 411 about the rebellion of the angels who sought to elevate
themselves above God. And in the New Testament, Jesus arrives to
redeem the world from Satan, who aims to stop him. In the first
gospels, Satan tempts Jesus personally; in the last gospel, Jesus
is tempted by people. If the Bible isn't consistent about what the
Devil does, how can we expect Hollywood to be?
</P>
<P>
   2. THE DEVIL IS CURIOUSLY ENCUMBERED BY RULES, BOUNDARIES,
BUREAUCRACY. In ``The Evil,'' he is stuck in the basement of an
old, spooky house, and would never get out without the help of some
well-meaning social workers (secular humanists!) who move in. In
``The Ninth Gate,'' Satan can be summoned only with secret
incantations recited in the right order _ placing the film at odds
with all the movies in which he roams around at will. In ``End of
Days,'' Satan has to assume human form, and impregnate a certain
woman by a certain date to establish his realm; he may be the
Prince of Darkness, but punctuality counts. In ``Crossroads,'' a
blues singer signs his soul away on paper. In ``Damn Yankees,'' the
contract has an escape clause. In ``Angel Heart,'' all the Devil
wants is the soul he was promised. Maybe one day we'll get an
Arthur Miller version, Satan Loman, his feet aching, wearily
pushing his temptations on an inattentive world.
</P>
<P>
   3. IT DOESN'T PAY TO WORK FOR THE DEVIL. Although the Devil
seems to have cast a kindly glance at the old folks who served him
in ``Rosemary's Baby,'' elsewhere he is literally the Boss From
Hell. In ``Omen III,'' ``Angel Heart'' and ``The Devil's
Advocate,'' useful, loyal retainers are crisply eliminated the
moment they cause Satan any trouble. In ``Damn Yankees,'' when his
assistant, Lola, gets too sweet on her intended victim, the Devil
makes her ugly. When you go to work for the Devil, think in terms
of immediate payoffs; his pension plan is weak.
</P>
<P>
   4. THE DEVIL IS ALWAYS PUTTING CHILDREN FIRST. A surprisingly
large number of movies have to do with Satan's wanting to be a
father. Obviously, there's ``Rosemary's Baby.'' But ``The Omen'' is
about the Devil's son, ``End of Days'' about the Devil wanting to
sire a son, and ``The Devil's Advocate'' about Satan wanting his
son to sire a son. You can't really say that ``The Witches of
Eastwick'' is about the Devil's wanting to sire a son, but in the
end, he winds up with three. ``Little Nicky,'' clearly, is going to
fall somewhere in this tradition. Also clearly, these plot lines
are a reaction to the story of Jesus, the Son of God. But the
impulse isn't the same: Jesus comes to redeem humanity by his
death, a sacrifice no son of Satan is being asked to make. Why does
Satan need an heir? Is he going somewhere? Does he have expansion
plans? Who's going to mentor the kid? And if he spends his
apprenticeship drinking, taking drugs and chasing women, doesn't
that constitute learning the business?
</P>
<P>
   5. EVERYBODY LIKES TO PLAY VILLAINS. Jesus has been played by
Max Von Sydow, Jeffrey Hunter and Willem Dafoe. But look who has
played the devil: Pacino, Jack Nicholson, Robert De Niro, George C.
Scott, Billy Crystal, Claude Rains, Donald Pleasence, Sam Neill,
Vincent Price, Terrence Stamp and Mickey Rooney. That's a lot of
awardware on hell's mantelpiece.
</P>
<P>
   6. IT'S HARD TO BE TEMPTING. Devils in the movies generally come
in two forms: Destroyers and tempters. The destroyers are fairly
easy to place _ you just have to be bad. It's harder to be the
tempter _ for the scene to work, Satan really has to be persuasive.
You can see how hard it is in last year's miniseries ``Jesus,'' in
which Jeroen Krabbe, a capable actor, had to persuade Jesus to
renounce his mission. Krabbe was about as convincing as a car
dealer; far better at the art of closing are Nicholson and Pacino.
In ``Eastwick,'' Nicholson's Devil plays on each woman's
vulnerability, teasing out her small resentments and places of
self-pity to bring her along. In ``The Devil's Advocate,'' Pacino
goes one better: He actively encourages the Keanu Reeves character
to do the right thing, knowing that he has so cleverly stacked the
deck that Reeves will reject the virtuous alternative. In the end,
he still overplays his hand, and Reeves thwarts him by killing
himself _ which seems to be the method of choice for thwarting the
Devil (see Schwarzenegger in ``End of Days'' and Jason Miller in
``The Exorcist'').
</P>
<P>
   But surely these are only temporary setbacks. That's the thing
about the Devil _ he's always practicing.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
