<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4444 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-FRANCE-DANCE-$ADV10-N     09-06 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANCE-DANCE-$ADV10-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW MOVES FROM A LAND BEYOND CATEGORY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Diversity, thy name is individuality. That may well
be the message of ``France Moves,'' a major festival of French
contemporary dance that will spread some 10 experimental troupes in
New York from April 24 to May 6.
</P>
<P>
   Final programs (including film screenings and panel discussions)
still have to be worked out. But the choreographers chosen by
Yorgos Loukos, the artistic director of the Lyon Opera Ballet and
of the new showcase, include Maguy Marin and Angelin Preljocaj,
both well known from previous appearances here; Jose Montalvo and
the hip-hop collective Kafig, both part of the New Europe Festival
last year; and Fred Bendongue, seen at the American Dance Festival
this summer and earlier at 651, the black arts center associated
with the Brooklyn Academy of Music.
</P>
<P>
   Making their U.S. debut will be Philippe Decoufle, a mixed-media
wizard who choreographed the ceremonies for the 1992 Winter
Olympics, complete with bungee jumpers; Joseph Nadj, who favors
Kafkaesque images; Dominique Boivin, whose solos suggest a gentle
clown; and Boris Charmatz, whose mix of brain and brawn has made
him French experimental dance's young golden boy.
</P>
<P>
   It seems only yesterday that Marin was part of the historic
debut in 1983 by five young French companies at the American Dance
Festival in Durham, N.C. _ a series of performances that revealed a
nascent modern-dance boom in a country once dominated by ballet.
</P>
<P>
   Although sent over as a group by Association Francaise d'Action
Artistique, the cultural arm of the French foreign ministry (which
is also behind ``France Moves''), the choreographers in 1983 were
unanimous on one point: They were making their U.S. debut not as
representatives of France but as themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, to place the French in a category is to do so at one's
peril. Certainly the choreographers who have emerged since 1980
have not lacked separate signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Preljocaj's work is even distinctive enough to have attracted
the ire of an American presidential candidate. Typical of his
exploration of instinct and gesture, his mesmerizing
``Annonciation'' depicted a tender encounter between the Virgin
Mary and an angel portrayed by an androgynous woman. Patrick J.
Buchanan did not see this female duet at the Joyce Theater in 1997,
but denounced it nonetheless in his syndicated column as an assault
on religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The French government, for its part, rewarded Preljocaj that
year with the Legion of Honor. Perhaps it knew more about how
religious ecstasy has been depicted in the history of art. After
all, it was a Frenchman, Charles de Brosse, who had this to say in
1739 about Bernini's famous sculpture of an angel hovering over St.
Teresa's contracted body: ``If this is divine love, I know all
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not surprising that the inspiration for experimental
choreographers in France often comes from art, literature and film.
These reference points come from a major part of their culture.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the three generations of companies that will appear
in Manhattan theaters (the Joyce, the New Victory, St. Mark's
Church, the Kitchen and Florence Gould Hall), Brooklyn (the Academy
of Music) and the Bronx (Hostos College) next spring will show a
shift in focus since Marin, the group's senior choreographer, came
to notice in the late 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   For all their individuality, the 1983 choreographers had common
themes. ``May B,'' Marin's poignant tribute to Samuel Beckett, was
typical of a shared concern with the human condition. The 1983
choreographers ( Marin, Karine Saporta, Dominique Bagouet, Caroline
Marcade, Joelle Bouvier and Regis Obadia) were not alike. But most
had a sensibility aligned with existentialist and absurdist
theater. More often than not, their dancers failed to make
connections, fell repeatedly and were hemmed in by darkness or
closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Alienation is not entirely absent from ``France Moves.'' Nadj,
an ethnic Hungarian from Yugoslavia (think Monica Seles), will
present ``Les Veilleurs,'' inspired by Kafka, with a cast of
Hungarian-trained actors and French dancers. Expect his
hallucinatory brand of relentless nightmares. Preljocaj's new
``Paysage Apres la Bataille'' draws upon the aesthetics of Joseph
Conrad and Marcel Duchamp, a contrast that already sets up a
picture of tension between instinct and intellect.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the choreographers opt for lighter, more playful
imagery. But beneath the entertaining surface, there is a change
from a pondering of the absurd to a concern with new reality and a
celebration of cross-cultural differences.
</P>
<P>
   Modern dance in France is visibly reacting to a change in
politics and in society. France is now a multicultural country,
with an immigrant population that is the target of extreme
right-wing propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   The new theme of most choreographers today is reconciliation
within diversity. Montalvo and his co-choreographer, Dominique
Hervieu, have recruited dancers from Guadeloupe to Africa to preach
an antixenophobic message in their high-tech blend of video and
live images. Their hip-hop virtuosos, as in other troupes, are
often of North African and sub-Saharan African descent. Kafig uses
the break-dance idiom with ultimate sophistication. Bendongue
worked for many years with a hip-hop troupe. ``D'une Rive a
l'Autre,'' his new piece, is concerned with identity in a
multiracial world.
</P>
<P>
   That politics impinge directly on choreographers was obvious in
1995 when Preljocaj rejected a post at an arts center in protest
against a victory by the extreme right in nearby Toulon. Marin, who
will present a new trio, ``Pour Ainsi Dire,'' has chosen to work in
a tough immigrant suburb of Lyon.
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the choreographers are children of foreign
political exiles, it is hard to think of them as anything but
French. By extension, Decoufle, Boivin and Preljocaj have studied
in France and New York with Americans including Alwin Nikolais,
Merce Cunningham, Viola Farber, Carolyn Carlson and Douglas Dunn.
Yet their choreography does not have the formal look of American
experimental dance.
</P>
<P>
   Rooted in different experiences, these choreographers could be
compared to the painters of the School of Paris between the two
world wars: their origins are varied, and France has allowed them
to be themselves.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
