<HEADER>
A4445 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-TEXAS-SURPLUS-HNS &LR;      09-06 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SURPLUS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Texas comptroller announces budget surplus amid criticism
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By KATHY WALT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas ended its fiscal year with $1.45 billion
in the bank, $45 million more than had been expected in July,
Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The state closed its books on the fiscal year Aug. 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our Texas economy is strong, personal income is $8 billion
higher than projected and the gross state product is $25 billion
higher than projected,'' said Rylander, a Republican who has been
accused by some Democrats of ``cooking the books'' to bolster Gov.
George W. Bush's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   State Sen. Mario Gallegos, D-Houston, however, cautioned that
it's too soon to say whether the surplus will be enough to cover
cost overruns in some programs and growing demands on state money.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of things that we need to take take a look
at,'' Gallegos said, citing $610 million in cost overruns in the
state Medicaid program for the first six months of the fiscal year
and a $90 million shortfall in what the state had expected to
collect as part of its settlement with the tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   He said Rylander's announcement is akin to an individual
announcing he has ``$100 in his pocket but $200 in bills to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That don't fly until we get a true answer on how (many) bills
Texas has to pay,'' he added. ``Then the comptroller can give a
true'' accounting.
</P>
<P>
   It was Gallegos who accused Rylander of manipulating her revenue
forecasts in an effort to undermine Democratic presidential
candidate Al Gore's criticisms of Bush's spending philosophies.
Gore accused the governor of pushing tax breaks for the wealthy at
the expense of health insurance programs for children.
</P>
<P>
   While the surplus is not as large as it has been in the past
couple of years, Rylander has insisted it will more than cover
Medicaid's needs.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts are predicting that lawmakers will face a tougher time
working out a budget in the 2001 session. Not only are there cost
overruns in Medicaid, but there are also new budgetary pressures to
build more prisons and bail out health insurance programs for
retired teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to her good news about the overall surplus, Rylander
said Wednesday that she had doubled the amount of money going to
the state's so-called ``rainy day'' fund.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is a savings account created by legislators during the
1980s in the midst of a recession that forced budget cuts and huge
tax bills.
</P>
<P>
   In July, Rylander had estimated $43 million would go into that
fund, but additional natural gas severance tax collections
increased the amount to $103 million, she said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
