<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4449 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-SEUSSICAL-THEATER-ART     09-06 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEUSSICAL-THEATER-ART-$ADV10-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LONG ROAD FROM WHOVILLE TO BROADWAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, Sept. 10) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By PETER MARKS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the Broadway of right now, the notion seemed
irresistible: an original musical out of the pages of Dr. Seuss
that would turn Horton the Elephant and the Cat in the Hat into
theater animals.
</P>
<P>
   But one look at the characters onstage in Boston and the
creators of ``Seussical'' knew the show had identity problems.
Catherine Zuber's costumes for the eagerly anticipated production,
based on the work of one of the world's most popular children's
writers, were simply too stylized, too whimsical _ too, of all
things, Seussian.
</P>
<P>
   It was not that Zuber, a highly regarded designer in her own
right, had failed her aesthetic mandate. It was just that the
producers, authors and director of the $8.5 million production, a
show blessed with some of the best pre-Broadway buzz in years, were
worried. If taste-setting early audiences sensed too much fluff and
preciousness, would the musical be categorized _ and marginalized _
as kids' stuff?
</P>
<P>
   ``We had beautiful costumes individually, but as soon as we put
more than half a dozen out there it became such a feast for the
eyes that we lost focus on the people and the storytelling,'' said
Gary Gunas, who is producing ``Seussical'' along with such Broadway
and Hollywood powerhouses as SFX Theatrical Group, Barry and Fran
Weissler and Universal Studios. ``Catherine and the rest of us just
sort of stared up there and said, `OK, we've gone astray.'''
</P>
<P>
   So, mere days before performances were to begin late last month
for the show's Boston tryout, Zuber and her designs were out.
William Ivey Long was brought in to replace her, with the idea of
dressing the Seuss characters more realistically. Such
substitutions are not unheard of in a show's trial-and-error phase
out of town. But the last-minute turmoil was more than a struggle
over how Dr. Seuss' exotic creations should look. It reflected the
serious artistic and commercial conflicts arising ever more
frequently these days as Broadway becomes more preoccupied with the
needs of an age group that in the past it rarely catered to _
children _ while holding on for dear life to the adult audience
that has sustained it.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, George Bernard Shaw or Thornton Wilder served
as the inspiration for a season's major Broadway musical. Today,
that role has shifted to the likes of Disney cartoon animators _
and the creator of ``Green Eggs and Ham.'' From the New Amsterdam
Theater on 42nd Street, where ``The Lion King'' reigns as the
biggest Broadway hit in years, to the Royal National Theater in
London, where ``Honk!,'' a show based on ``The Ugly Duckling,''
snared the Olivier Award for best musical this year, it is the
fantasy world of the youngest theatergoers that has captured the
imagination of the conceptualizers and bankrollers of lavish
entertainments.
</P>
<P>
   The evolution can be traced through shows like ``Cats.'' When it
began life on Broadway 18 years ago, it was touted as an innovative
grown-up musical. But over the years, the marketing seemed to
shift. Where once the show's dominant image was of that lithe
dancer framed by a pair of cat's eyes, the television commercials
became filled with the images of children having their faces
painted to resemble the characters onstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was a child in the suburbs of New York, the big event
was to go to the theater and see the thing that all the adults were
excited about,'' said Leonard Marcus, a children's book historian
and critic. ``I went to see `My Fair Lady' and `The Music Man' and
`Bye Bye Birdie': That's a reflection of how child-adult
relationships were in those days. These days, there's a lot more
interest in what the child wants to do. Doing things for the
child's sake.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Seussical,'' scheduled to open Nov. 9 at the Richard Rodgers
Theater, was clearly created with the hope of tapping into the
changing demographics of Broadway, a shift mainly brought about by
three factors: The culture's obsession with youth, a nostalgia
craze among baby boomers with children and an appetite for pricier
family entertainment fueled by the robust economy.
</P>
<P>
   But in engaging such known Broadway quantities as the lyricist
Lynn Ahrens, the composer Stephen Flaherty and the director Frank
Galati, all of ``Ragtime'' fame, along with the choreographer
Kathleen Marshall (``Kiss Me, Kate''), the producers of
``Seussical'' found themselves faced with a difficult question:
Could an ambitious show that tells the story of an elephant who
hatches an egg and a microscopic boy who lives on a speck of dust
and a homely bird who just wants to be loved add up to something
that grown-ups would buy tickets to, even if they didn't have
children?
</P>
<P>
   Barry Weissler, a co-producer of ``Chicago'' and ``Annie Get
Your Gun,'' joined the production team with his wife after he saw a
workshop version last summer in Toronto that witnesses report had
many a hard-bitten producing type in tears. Weissler said the
success or failure of ``Seussical'' at overcoming preconceptions of
how adult a show about Seuss could possibly be might be the
ultimate test of its theatrical power.
</P>
<P>
   The magic numbers, say the producers of ``Seussical,'' are 7 and
77. That is the age range they are seeking to attract; indeed, it
is the range they believe they have to draw to approach the success
of the show that radically changed perceptions of children's
musical theater, ``The Lion King.'' With its heart-stopping masks
and visual effects, overseen by the avant-garde theater director
Julie Taymor, on whom the Walt Disney Co. took a chance, ``The Lion
King'' demonstrated that a big, commercial family show could have
artistic aspirations: That it could be more than a cartoon with
Equity actors cast as dessert plates (Disney's ``Beauty and the
Beast'') or the kind of clunky spectacle doomed to be made sport of
by critics (Frank Wildhorn's ``Jekyll and Hyde'').
</P>
<P>
   The powers behind ``Seussical'' believe that some of its
strengths _ a melodic Ahrens-Flaherty score; an emotional
narrative; a potential star in Kevin Chamberlin (a Tony nominee
last season for his role in ``Dirty Blonde''), who plays the
hapless Horton _ make it a worthy example of old-style Broadway
values, and thus perhaps an even likelier candidate than ``The Lion
King'' for crossover appeal. Though Taymor's production received
generally glowing notices, some critics, like Ben Brantley of The
New York Times, pointed to the show's weaker elements _ for
example, a book that seemed undramatic and characters that were
essentially opaque.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, ``Seussical'' strives to be unlike ``The Lion King''
everywhere but at the box office. ``We are a different animal,''
Weissler said, the pun unintentional. ``Julie Taymor is a genius at
what she does with masks and costumes. But that's the opposite of
what we're doing. That's why the costumes had to go. Because they
weren't allowing us to be the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks ago, in a fourth-floor studio at 890 Broadway,
rehearsal central for musical theater in New York, Galati and
Marshall watched as the company ran through the ensemble number
``Here on Who.'' Whoville is an important destination in the nearly
sung-through ``Seussical.'' The inhabitants of ``the tiniest planet
in the sky'' are beset by war and environmental disaster: Some of
the books by Dr. Seuss, aka Theodor Geisel, are virtual parables of
modern human perils. But the most affecting problem facing the Whos
is that no one knows they are alive.
</P>
<P>
   When the number was over, Galati seemed pleased. ``There's no
sense of cartoon,'' he told the company, and he meant it as a
compliment. ``It's absolutely real and specific. Just as long as it
stays that way, the arc of the number will work.''
</P>
<P>
   That adult sensibility is intended to inform every movement. For
example, when the denizens of Who, hoping that Horton will protect
their little planet, end their serenade of him with ``We're tiny
little people/ Saying thanks in advance,'' Marshall devised a
tip-o'-the-hat gesture on ``thanks in advance'' that is an homage
to Broadway choruses of the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any good theater, the theme reveals itself,'' she said.
``The universality comes from the specifics.''
</P>
<P>
   The interwoven tales of ``Seussical'' amount to a musical
convention of Seuss characters, presided over by the Cat in the Hat
(played by David Shiner, half the mime team of ``Fool Moon,'' in
his first professional speaking role). It is Horton alone, as the
famous story goes, who hears the Whos, and in particular one of the
littlest Whos, a boy named JoJo Andrew Keenan-Bolger and Anthony
Blair Hall alternate in the role) with a vivid imagination and a
feeling of being all alone in the universe.
</P>
<P>
   It becomes Horton's humanitarian (elephantarian?) mission to
have their innocent voices heard in the brutally cynical Jungle of
Nool, where Horton himself is an outcast, a lonely figure of fun.
He too has his blind spots, though; he is oblivious to the
attentions of Gertrude McFuzz (Janine LaManna), a sorry-looking
bird with only one pathetic tail feather.
</P>
<P>
   With its deep investment in the rhyming nonsense of Seussian
language _ ``Think a Trip on a Ship/ To the Vipper of Vipp/ Or to
Solla Sollew,'' the cast sings in the opening, ``Oh, the Thinks You
Can Think!'' _ the musical is a manifesto on the liberation of the
mind. It is also about the dignity of individual expression, the
struggle to be noticed _ and accepted _ for who you are.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really been Lynn's and my vision of Dr. Seuss,'' said
Flaherty, who has been writing musicals with Ahrens for nearly 20
years. In addition to ``Ragtime,'' their Broadway collaborations
include ``My Favorite Year'' and ``Once on This Island.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stephen forced me to read the books,'' Ahrens added. ``The
little Whos are like Earth: We're adrift, looking to save
ourselves. We tried to be truthful to the innocent anarchy in the
books. There is a deep concern in them for the planet, for human
beings and how we should behave toward one another, and it plays
out in all this zany stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   The songwriting team was recruited for the project by Livent,
the Canadian theatrical production house founded by Garth
Drabinsky, which produced ``Ragtime'' and obtained the rights to
the Seuss anthology from Geisel's widow, Audrey. Following
Drabinsky's dismissal after questions about Livent's bookkeeping
practices, the shepherding of ``Seussical'' became the
responsibility of SFX, the entertainment giant that had acquired
Livent. Signing on as co-producers were Universal _ which is
bringing out a big-screen version of ``How the Grinch Stole
Christmas starring Jim Carrey, scheduled to open the week after
``Seussical'' _ and the Weisslers.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Eric Idle, a member of the Monty Python comedy team,
was to write the book, but he dropped out well before last summer's
Toronto workshop, the event that kicked ``Seussical'' into high
gear. Even Audrey Geisel was there. ``I was completely
captivated,'' Geisel said in a recent interview. ``And if I had to
be narrowed to one single word about the production it would have
to be `seamless.''' Though she had been wooed ``many, many times''
for the rights to musicalize her husband's works, she said, what
persuaded her to yield on this occasion was the run-the-gamut
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one had ever hit on that bouquet of all the characters, and
said `I want to take all of them,''' she continued. ``And before,
none of it was enchanting enough that I wanted to give the critters
up.''
</P>
<P>
   From that successful workshop, many actors were retained for
Broadway. None are household names, but the most troubling loss was
that of Andrea Martin, who won a Tony Award for ``My Favorite
Year'' and was to play the Cat in the Hat, until she decided, the
producers said, that she could not be away from her family in
California for the length of a Broadway run. It was then that the
producers approached Shiner, whose skills as a clown with a mean
streak were thought to encompass just the sort of danger required
for the major-domo-like role of the Cat.
</P>
<P>
   Even more dangerously, though, the Cat in the Hat is ubiquitous
in ``Seussical,'' assuming various personalities, commenting on the
action and, gulp, singing his heart out. And Shiner has absolutely
no professional experience in a musical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never sung a note onstage in my life,'' he said. In fact,
the thought of singing for the cast, let alone an audience,
terrified him. ``I just kept getting in a room and singing and
singing and singing until I started feeling comfortable with it,''
Shiner added. ``I started taking voice lessons, learning ways to
deepen my voice and to relax, and I slowly discovered that my voice
wasn't that bad.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, Shiner has become the embodiment of the show's
attempt to defy expectations, the clown who is not just for
children in a musical that is not meant just for them, either.
</P>
<P>
   What he and everyone else associated with ``Seussical'' are
banking on is Dr. Seuss' uncommon common touch. ``The essence of
this piece is very universal and it connects in a deeply emotional
way,'' Shiner said. ``Horton and JoJo sing of being alone in the
universe, of the notion that `I have wings and I can fly.' There is
a part of everyone that feels alone _ and the feeling we all have
of something in us that is much, much deeper, that feeling that we
can fly.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
