<SLUG> BC-WILLIAM-MORRIS-RESIGN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM MORRIS' ROBERT GOTTLIEB DEPARTS AGENCY _ WITH CLIENTS IN
TOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Robert Gottlieb, one of the most powerful agents in
book publishing, resigned as head of the William Morris agency's
New York literary group to start his own agency and multimedia
management company, a blow to the venerable William Morris agency's
presence in the book business.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb's jump is also a sign of the strains on agents'
traditional roles as more agents and managers seek to participate
in lucrative deals to produce their clients work for other media,
like film and television. In fact, by opening the possibility of
producing projects based on his clients work, Gottlieb is
apparently reversing his own recent disparaging statements that
such managers were ``neither fish nor fowl,'' creating a potential
conflict of interest by representing authors to negotiate some
contracts while sitting across the table from their clients to sign
deals for other media.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb, 46, began his career at William Morris 24 years ago in
the mail room and now represents a roster of blockbuster writers
including Dean Koontz, Deepak Chopra, Elizabeth George, Catherine
Coulter and Janet Evanovich. In recent months, Gottlieb clashed
with James Wiatt, the former vice chairman of International
Creative Management who took over last year as president and
co-chief executive of William Morris, but both sides said Wednesday
that Gottlieb's departure was unrelated to their personal
relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb's move had been in the works for at least eight months
according to people involved, and his new company, Trident Media
Group, has already furnished and occupied its office on Madison
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``For some time, I have been planning on starting an agency that
is not simply devoted to selling rights or selling authors
manuscripts, but really is a business founded on an understanding
the world of intellectual property rights, branding and managing
across a variety of platforms,'' Gottlieb said.
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb said that his new company will represent clients in
film, television, Internet and museum exhibition deals as well as
books. The new firm will receive a commission on some deals it
negotiates, but may participate as producer and partner on other
deals, he said. ``That is part of the entrepreneurial
proposition,'' he said, ``There are no closed doors, no borders.''
Gottlieb said that his clients would be represented by outside
lawyers or agents when they negotiated deals with his firm.
</P>
<P>
   After his longtime client Tom Clancy recently dropped William
Morris in favor of Mike Ovitz's new talent management firm,
Gottlieb criticized Ovitz for blurring the lines between agent and
manager or producer. ``I think this is different,'' Gottlieb said.
``I am going to embrace agents, managers and laywers. I have no
intention of taking clients away from agents.''
</P>
<P>
   Gottlieb will take with him an assistant, an agent and a
recently departed agent from William Morris, and, he said, his list
of more than 40 clients had agreed to follow him.
</P>
<P>
   His resignation leaves a substantial vacuum in the William
Morris agency's literary group. The firm will retain commissions
from all of the contracts Gottlieb negotiated while at the firm,
some of which extend for several books yet to be written. But his
departure leaves William Morris without another agent of Gottlieb's
stature. Among its biggest agents are Owen Laster, head of its
worldwide literary group, and Joni Evans, former publisher of
Random House's adult trade division, who joined William Morris
seven years ago but has not established a client list nearly
comparable to Gottlieb's.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Gottlieb ``is a big bump,'' said Laster, 61, who once
employed Gottlieb as his assistant. ``We will have to do some
rebuilding, I can't deny that.''
</P>
<P>
   Among its best-selling authors remaining are Judy Blume, Susan
Isaacs and Peggy Noonan, Laster said.
</P>
<P>
   William Morris, one of the largest talent agencies, retains
operations in extensive film, music and television businesses.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
