<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4452 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-UGA-SCAROLINA-COX     09-06 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UGA-SCAROLINA-COX0907 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Carolinians returning for battle with Gamecocks
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Georgia defensive tackle Richard Seymour grew up
in Gadsden, S.C., about 15 miles from the University of South
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Seymour was a Clemson fan, he attended several South
Carolina football games. But Seymour quit making the short trips to
Columbia during his senior season at Lower Richland High School.
</P>
<P>
   ``South Carolina stopped recruiting me,'' Seymour said.
``Georgia, Clemson and Tennessee were recruiting me, but South
Carolina stopped. They didn't recruit a lot of good players.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina coach Lou Holtz probably wishes the Gamecocks'
previous coaching staff had kept Seymour at home. In Georgia's SEC
opener at South Carolina on Saturday, Seymour will be one of three
Bulldog starters returning to their native state.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia guard Kevin Breedlove and receiver Durrell Robinson also
left South Carolina when they signed with the Bulldogs two years
ago. A fourth South Carolina native, tight end Ben Watson from Rock
Hill, transferred from Duke to Georgia this year.
</P>
<P>
   Breedlove, from Daniel High School in Clemson, started 12 games
at right guard for Georgia last season and was named a freshman
All-American. Robinson sat out last season as a
</P>
<P>
   partial-qualifier, but the first catch of his career was for a
touchdown Saturday against Georgia Southern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know what it is,'' said Robinson, from Byrnes
High School in Lyman. ``A lot of playersa go somewhere else. I
guess they just want to leave home.''
</P>
<P>
   Seymour didn't have much of a choice, according to his high
school coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``During his senior season, South Carolina didn't come into the
building,'' Lower Richland High coach David Moore said. ``It
probably would have been a 10-minute drive to see him play. The
story from South Carolina was that they thought he was too slow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had told Georgia's coaches that it was going to be between
them and South Carolina, because that's where I thought his dad
wanted him to go,'' Moore said. ``But South Carolina didn't even
invite him over for a senior visit. I think sometimes they took it
for granted that they were going to get the in-state kids.''
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's futility on the field _ the Gamecocks broke the
nation's longest losing streak at 21 games with a victory last week
_ certainly didn't help its recruiting efforts. Under Brad Scott,
the Gamecocks lost their final 10 games in 1998. Scott was fired
that season, and Holtz was lured out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Holtz, who won a national championship at Notre Dame in
1988, could persuade Breedlove or Robinson to play for the
Gamecocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Holtz tried to convince me to come there, but I'd
already made up my mind,'' Robinson said. ``I already knew that I
was going to Georgia or Tennessee. I wanted to get away from
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of those recruiting wars, the Georgia-South Carolina
series has become one of the better rivalries in the SEC. The
Gamecocks have 14 players from Georgia, including starting kicker
Reid Bethea (Dublin), defensive end Kalimba Edwards (East Point),
guard Phillip Jones (Snellville) and linebacker Shannon Wadley
(Swainsboro).
</P>
<P>
   Holtz, in his second season at South Carolina, concedes that his
program has lost most head-to-head battles with the Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that until you beat Georgia and Tennessee, you
aren't going to get the athletes that keep matriculating to those
schools,'' Holtz said. ``And you're not going to beat those schools
until you keep those athletes in-state.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gamecocks have managed to keep a handful of the top recruits
from South Carolina. Defensive end John Abraham, selected in the
first round of April's NFL Draft, was a native of Timmonsville.
Current Gamecocks running back Derek Watson, from Williamston, was
recruited by Georgia, Clemson and Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   But until the Gamecocks keep players like Breedlove, Robinson
and Seymour at home, Holtz says, it will be difficult to catch the
Bulldogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's all said and done,'' Seymour said, ``I want to tell
my kids that I beat South Carolina four years in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
