<HEADER>
A4454 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MOTOROLA-PROMOTIONS07     09-06 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTOROLA-PROMOTIONS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motorola promotes two in the semiconductor division
 &HT;    By John Pletz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Motorola Inc. looked inside to two company
veterans Wednesday to lead its semiconductor business, which is
headquartered in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Shlapak, 56, who was the No. 2 executive in Motorola's chip
business, replaces Hector Ruiz, who left in January to become
president of rival Advanced Micro Devices, as division president.
Bill Walker, 57, the longtime head of Motorola's worldwide
chip-manufacturing operations, becomes general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Interim president Fred Tucker returns to Motorola's Schaumburg,
Ill., headquarters as deputy to the chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Both Shlapak and Walker are described as hard-driving,
blunt-talking executives who face an organization that is
struggling somewhat to define itself and its future.
</P>
<P>
   Shlapak, an electrical engineer who joined the company in 1970
in Canada, is known for speaking his mind in a loud, clear voice.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will be able to hear us all the way out to Loop 360'' from
Motorola's Oak Hill campus near Hwy. 290 and William Cannon Drive,
Shlapak joked.
</P>
<P>
   But he predicted that he and Walker, who joined the company in
1968 and oversaw 38 factories in nine countries in his previous
job, will get along well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bill will run the operations on a day-to-day basis,'' Shlapak
said.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's semiconductor business _ which creates chips for
everything from Apple Computer Inc.'s G4 desktop to General Motors
Corp.'s automobiles _ has about one-third of its workers in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   Although the semiconductor division accounted for about 22
percent of the parent company's $33.1 billion in revenue last year,
it went through two painful restructurings during Ruiz's three-year
tenure. The business was downsized with layoffs and buyouts to
about 33,000 from 50,000 workers worldwide, and some parts were
sold.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola remains the No. 1 maker of microcontrollers, more
commonly known as embedded chips. But while the semiconductor
industry has enjoyed a boom recently, Motorola hasn't ``quite kept
up with the industry,'' said Fred Zieber, an analyst who follows
the industry for Pathfinder Research in San Jose.
</P>
<P>
   Motorola's chip revenue was up 27 percent last year, compared to
44 percent for the industry overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not grown as fast as the industry has recently, but we
have improved our profit position from quarter to quarter,''
Shlapak said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Many have questioned whether Motorola might someday sell its
semiconductor business. Chris Galvin, Motorola's chief executive,
said earlier this year that semiconductors remain central to the
company's overall strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is this question on the outside of where they're
going,'' Zieber said. ``The fact that those kinds of questions come
up are indicative of the fact that people are having a hard time
getting their arms around what Motorola is or isn't.''
</P>
<P>
   It's taken a toll on the work force as well. Motorola has lost
some valuable talent to competitors recently in a very tight labor
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is going after everyone in terms of talent,'' said
Kim Butler, a recruiting executive with Greywolf Consulting.
``Motorola has had some real difficulties in that arena. They're
very much vulnerable on the talent side.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Matas, an analyst with IC Insights in Scottsdale, Ariz.,
said another challenge for Motorola is that growth in demand for
chips in cellular phones is expected to drop from historic rates of
about 60 percent annually during the last five years to 20 to 30
percent this year and the next.
</P>
<P>
   The new management team acknowledged the challenges that lay
ahead Wednesday. But Shlapak said both he and Walker have been
around the industry and the company a long time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of scars on our backs,'' he said. ``We know what
it takes to win. If we have to shake it up, we will shake it up. We
want results, and we know what we want.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go out there and set an expectation and hold people
accountable,'' Walker added. ``We have the knowhow ... to get the
job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler doesn't dispute the notion: ``You look up hardball in the
dictionary, and there is a picture of Bill Walker.''
</P>
<P>
   Statesman staff writer Kirk Ladendorf contributed to this story.
You may contact John Pletz at jpletz(at)statesman.com or 445-3601.
</P>
<P>
   Hector Ruiz
</P>
<P>
   Bill Walker
</P>
