<HEADER>
A4456 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT &LR;      09-06 0803
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-REDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REDS TOP METS AS BENITEZ'S BEST IS NOT GOOD ENOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI _ Armando Benitez throws heat. Every hitter knows it,
and every hitter has to expect it. When the New York Mets' closer
came into the game with the bases loaded and one out in the eighth
inning Wednesday, protecting a one-run lead, he had to throw the
fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a real tough situation coming in with the bases loaded
and one out,'' Benitez said. ``You have to come in with your best
pitch. You don't want to throw a couple of pitches and make a
mistake. He looked for the pitch he wanted. He had to look for my
best pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Benitez tried to throw his fastball outside. But it came in high
over the middle of the plate, and Benito Santiago belted it over
the fence in left-center field for a grand slam, the crushing blow
in an 11-8 comeback victory for the Cincinnati Reds at Cinergy
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Benitez, who had allowed one earned run in his previous 31
outings, was philosophical. ``Sometimes we're human, no?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the human frailties are showing up at the same time on the
roster. The Mets limped home having lost 5 of 6 games on a road
trip that began Sept. 1, a date that has heralded doom for the team
three years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   They missed the playoffs by losing their last five games in
1998. They dropped seven in a row late last season before returning
from the brink of elimination. Now this. The Mets are taking
comfort in the standings: Before Wednesday night's game in Atlanta
between the Braves and the Diamondbacks, the Mets had a 4 1/2 game
lead over Arizona in the National League wild-card race and trailed
Atlanta by a game and a half in the National League East.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the guys will shake it off fine,'' said Mets manager
Bobby Valentine. ``We've got plenty of games left to play, and
we're still sitting OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby J. Jones, who started Wednesday's game and could not get
an out in the third, agreed. ``The good thing is we've still got a
good lead in the wild card, and we're right there in reach of the
Braves,'' Jones said. ``Sure, it's a disappointing road trip, and
every team has streaks like this. But we were right in all these
games.''
</P>
<P>
   In a way, that made this trip harder to take. Matt Franco hit a
three-run homer in the first inning and Todd Pratt homered in the
second, but Jones could not hold a 5-2 lead. Bobby M. Jones
relieved with four one-hit, shutout innings after the Reds tied the
game, 5-5, but the Mets led by 8-5 before the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a slow game, a bad start for both teams, but we had
the opportunity to put them away, and we let up,'' said Lenny
Harris, who started at first base. ``We didn't put them away like
we're supposed to, like we did last month when we were putting
teams away. We just have to get that fire back, and hopefully we'll
get it down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   After Bobby M. Jones' outstanding effort, in which he changed
speeds effectively with a sinking, turnover fastball he had never
thrown with confidence before, Dennis Cook pitched a scoreless
seventh. Turk Wendell came on in the eighth and got one out, but he
allowed two singles and Valentine called for John Franco.
</P>
<P>
   Franco missed two weeks with a sore pectoral muscle before
returning on Tuesday, and he felt no discomfort Wednesday. He said
he had good pop on his fastball and a better change-up, but he
missed his spots and the Reds took advantage. Sean Casey and Dmitri
Young singled, cutting the Mets' lead to 8-7 and bringing in
Benitez.
</P>
<P>
   When Benitez allowed the slam, Franco was charged with three
earned runs, the first he has given up since June 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy's been automatic all year,'' Franco said of Benitez.
``He comes in and gives up a home run _ big deal. It's a big deal
we lost, yeah, but he's been so automatic all year. He made a
mistake. It's not going to be the first time. It's not going to be
the last time.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, so many Mets are making mistakes in unison. Even
in the Mets' lone victory on this trip, they did not hit much. Todd
Zeile's game-winning homer in the 10th on Tuesday followed five
hitless innings, and the Mets managed just six hits Wednesday.
Since whacking Arizona's Randy Johnson in a 13-3 victory on Aug.
25, the Mets are hitting .193.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets do not play Thursday, and on Friday they open a
six-game homestand against Philadelphia and Milwaukee. Some players
said the off day is a good thing. ``The day off is going to be very
important,'' Alfonzo said. Others are not sure.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to hurt watching baseball tomorrow,'' said Pratt,
who said he may check out the game between the Braves and the
Diamondbacks, ``knowing we had a bad road trip and not being able
to do anything until Friday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
