<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4458 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SEAGRAMS-MP3-MUSIC-(T     09-06 1130
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAGRAMS-MP3-MUSIC-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. JUDGE RULES AGAINST MP3.COM, SAYING COPYRIGHT INFRINGEMENT
`WILLFUL' 
</HEADLINE>
   By AMY HARMON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ruling that the online music startup MP3.com had
willfully infringed the copyrights of Universal Music Group, a
federal judge on Wednesday ordered the company to pay potentially
crippling damages in one of the first cases to test the legal
boundaries of digital music distribution.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Jed S. Rakoff in Manhattan said MP3.com must
pay $25,000 for each of the Universal compact disks included in its
My.Mp3.com service, which let users listen to music from any
computer connected to the Internet after indicating that they
possessed the CD or had purchased it through an online vendor
associated with the company.
</P>
<P>
   The number was less than the $45,000 per-CD that Universal's
lawyers had requested, but an MP3.com lawyer had argued that
anything more than a $500 per-CD penalty would be a virtual ``death
sentence'' for the company.
</P>
<P>
   The number of CDs copied is in dispute. But depending on how
many copyrights MP3.com is found to have infringed, total damages
could reach as high as $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they have to pay numbers near that it would be
devastating,'' said Heath Terry, an analyst at Credit Suisse First
Boston. ``But now we go into more negotiations and an appeal.
Basically it stretches out the timeline on all of this, so instead
of being able to come to a resolution they're plunged into more
litigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Another phase of the trial in November will determine the number
of CDs involved. Universal has said between 5,000 and 10,000
copyrights are at issue. MP3.com's lawyers have set the number at
4,740, but said they plan to challenge the eligibility of virtually
all of Universal's copyright registrations.
</P>
<P>
   With about $300 million in cash, some of which has been
earmarked to settle with the four other major record companies
originally involved in the lawsuit, analysts said MP3.com should be
able to stay afloat if it managed to keep the damages payment in
the $100 million range. The other companies _ Sony Music, Time
Warner, the EMI Group and Bertelsmann AG _ did not reveal the
settlement amounts, but analysts estimated that MP3.com settled for
$20 million with each company. A group of music publishers have
also filed suit against the company.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The trial has been closely watched by many companies seeking to
stake a claim in the potentially lucrative arena of Internet music
distribution, including Napster, the online music trading service
that is facing its own lawsuit brought by the major record labels.
In July, a federal judge ordered Napster to stop helping computer
users trade copyrighted music over the Internet. The ruling was
later stayed pending appeal.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In determining the level of damages, Rakoff said he chose a
number considerably lower than the maximum penalty of $150,000 per
infringement because Universal had not specified how it lost money
because of MP3.com's actions, even though it could have done so. He
also said MP3.com had acted more responsibly than other Internet
startups.
</P>
<P>
   But the judge said he balanced that against the need to deter
other Internet companies from copyright infringement.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some companies operating in the area of the Internet may have
a misconception that, because their technology is somewhat novel,
they are somehow immune from the ordinary applications of laws of
the United States, including copyright law,'' Rakoff said. ``They
need to understand that the law's domain knows no such limits.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of MP3.com fell in after-hours trading. MP3.com shares
last traded at $5-7/8 on the Instinet electronic trading system,
down $2 from where it last traded before being halted, pending the
ruling announcement, at around 2 p.m. on the Nasdaq Stock Market.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Robertson, MP3.com's chief executive, said the company
would appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built technology that lets people listen to their own CD
collections,'' Robertson told reporters in Rakoff's courtroom
Wednesday afternoon. ``We think the law needs to accommodate
consumers' need to listen to their own CD collections online in a
digital form.''
</P>
<P>
   The law currently allows consumers to be able to store their
music online and listen to it anywhere after those individuals copy
their own CDs in a somewhat onerous process known as ``ripping,''
and upload them to a virtual storage locker provided by companies
like Myplay, an MP3.com rival.
</P>
<P>
   To make its My.MP3.com service easier to use, MP3.com did not
require users to load their own music into an on-line locker.
Rather, a user had merely to insert a CD into the CD-ROM drive of a
computer and log into MP3.com's Web site, at which point MP3.com
would automatically put a copy of the music into the person's
virtual locker. A user could also purchase a CD from an on-line
retailer and listen to it immediately once MP3.com had confirmed
the transaction.
</P>
<P>
   The company suspended the service after Rakoff ruled in April
that it had violated the copyrights of the major record labels by
compiling a database of about 80,000 CDs.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com hoped to attract advertisers with the service and
eventually charge a subscription fee. The company argued that the
service was legal under the ``fair use'' doctrine of copyright law.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   After MP3.com settled with the other four companies, Universal,
a unit of the Seagram Co. and the largest of the five major
companies, remained as a plaintiff.
</P>
<P>
   A Universal spokesman said Wednesday that the company would have
no comment because of the pending litigation. Cary Sherman, general
counsel of the Recording Industry Association of America, a trade
group representing the major labels, said in a statement that the
group was pleased with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``This should send a message that there are consequences when a
business recklessly disregards the copyright law,'' Sherman said.
</P>
<P>
   In an appeal, MP3.com will no doubt have to address Rakoff's
initial determination that its fair use defense was, as he
reiterated yesterday ``without any merit.'' In his ruling on
willfulness, the judge said that the notion that My.Mp3.com simply
enabled consumers to more easily store their own CDs was ``little
more than a sham'' because the consumers CDs were never actually
stored with MP3.com.
</P>
<P>
   ``While they camouflaged the critical differences with
broad-brush appeals to `consumer rights,' they were in fact never
in any doubt that this purported justification for their otherwise
obvious copyright infringement rested on a doubtful factual
premise,'' the judge said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
