A4461 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-EU-TRADE-WAR-NYT &LR;      09-06 0690
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EU-TRADE-WAR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND EUROPEANS RAISING THE STAKES IN TRADE IMPASSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELIZABETH OLSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GENEVA _ The European Union and the United States are holding
fast in several trade disputes, their continued standoff
threatening a more punishing confrontation between the two trading
blocs, the world's biggest.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union has rejected the United States' attempt to
overhaul a tax benefit that saves American companies millions of
dollars a year. The move comes at a time when Washington is drawing
up a list of more than $300 million in tariffs on European goods,
mainly food, after the Europeans refused to alter their
restrictions on banana imports and on hormone-treated beef.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a panel of the World Trade Organization,
which is based here, ruled that the United States must change a law
that allowed companies _ including General Motors, Microsoft and
Boeing _ to avoid paying taxes on some overseas sales by channeling
them through offshore subsidiaries. Under the trade organization's
rules, the United States has until Oct. 1 to revise the law, which
the panel called an illegal export subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter made public late last week, the European Union's
trade commissioner, Pascal Lamy, said that American changes still
retain export subsidies in violation of WTO rules, and allow the
subsidies to be continued beyond the October deadline. ``The only
way for a U.S.-based manufacturer to benefit from the new regime is
by exporting,'' said a European Union summary of the letter to
Stuart Eizenstat, the American deputy secretary of the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   An attempt in May to reach a compromise failed, and Eizenstat
warned in July that ``a major trade war'' could follow.
</P>
<P>
   The new system for offshore sales was approved by the House Ways
and Means Committee late in July, and awaits approval by the House
and Senate. Clinton administration officials have indicated they
intend to press for congressional approval of the modified law.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Aug. 31 letter was not made public, Lamy is said to
have indicated that the only change in the U.S. tax breaks scheme
was eliminating the requirement that a ``paper'' company be set up
offshore. About 5,000 such offshore tax havens exist, mostly based
in the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the EU says it is willing to continue negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is one month before the Oct. 1 deadline, and we believe
there is still time for a solution,'' said Herve Jouanjean, a
commission official.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of a compromise, the EU is expected to seek WTO
permission to impose retaliatory sanctions on U.S. exports in
amounts that dwarf previous trade spats. Such sanctions are meant
to be based on the amount of harm suffered in the international
marketplace. Using that measure, the Europeans are likely to ask
for compensation of 100 percent tariffs on $4 billion in American
goods export to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   If Congress passes the proposed reform legislation before Oct.
1, trade experts said it was likely that the European Union would
have to file a new challenge to the law. A ruling, which is
delivered by a three-judge panel, could take months.
</P>
<P>
   In the dispute over bananas and beef, the Clinton administration
is preparing a list of European products that would be subject to
tariffs. Britain has been lobbying the administration to exempt
Scottish cashmere from the list.
</P>
<P>
   The European Union's initial effort to reform its banana import
regime, which gave preferential treatment to former European
colonies, was rebuffed by the United States as insufficient.
Brussels now is trying to get agreement internally and with its
banana exporting partners on a new alternative. The 15-country
trading bloc and the United States also remain at odds over how to
replace the European ban on hormone-treated beef, which was struck
down at the WTO. Currently, the European Union is banning one
hormone and temporarily excluding four others while scientific
studies are under way to evaluate their effect on human health. The
United States maintains that the growth-inducing hormones are safe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
