<HEADER>
A4463 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TOBACCO-SUITS-NYT &LR;      09-06 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUITS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO TOBACCO COMPANIES ANGLING FOR SETTLEMENT IN ALL CLAIMS BY
SMOKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARRY MEIER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two of the nation's major cigarette companies have been engaged
in preliminary talks with plaintiffs' lawyers in recent months as
part of a bid to reach a nationwide settlement of all smokers'
claims against the tobacco industry, said lawyers involved with the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the two companies involved, the Lorillard Tobacco
Co. and the Liggett Group, either declined to comment or did not
return phone calls. Lawyers and others, who spoke on the condition
of anonymity, cautioned that the talks were preliminary, and other
cigarette makers said they had no intention of settling cases.
</P>
<P>
   The disclosure of the talks came as a federal judge in Brooklyn,
N.Y., issued an order Wednesday that could provide a mechanism for
reaching a global settlement of claims by smokers. The judge, Jack
Weinstein of U.S. District Court, told the parties to come to court
on Monday to consider a suggestion by plaintiffs' lawyers to spin
off claims for punitive damages against cigarette makers into a
nationwide class-action lawsuit, with separate trials for claims
for compensatory damages. Such a division would be unique.
</P>
<P>
   Punitive damages are those intended to punish a defendant for
its conduct. Plaintiffs' lawyers, in pressing for a separate
punitive damages class-action suit, are apparently seeking to play
on the tobacco companies' biggest concern.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, a state court jury in Florida issued a
stunning $144.8 billion punitive award to members of a class-action
lawsuit brought on behalf of all Florida residents who had been
made sick by smoking.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies have appealed the Florida verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, Weinstein, who is viewed as a judicial
activist, made a bid to create such a class action for all claims
but the tobacco companies rejected his suggestions. Spokesmen for
the nation's three biggest cigarette companies _ the Philip Morris
Cos., J.R. Reynolds Tobacco and the Brown &AMP; Williamson Tobacco Co.
_ also criticized the latest plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no intention whatsoever of settling these lawsuits,
and we are not discussing settlement with plaintiffs' attorneys or
anyone else,''said Mark Smith, a spokesman for Brown &AMP; Williamson
Tobacco.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, tobacco companies agreed to pay $246 billion to
settle a series of lawsuits brought by state attorneys general. But
that settlement did not foreclose claims by individual smokers, as
in the Florida case.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Liggett Group, the smallest of the cigarette
manufacturers, did not return two telephone calls Wednesday. But
Liggett, which broke ranks with the other companies during the
attorneys general litigation, has previously sought settlements of
litigation against it.
</P>
<P>
   The apparent interest of Lorillard Tobacco, a unit of the Loews
Corp., in settlement talks, however, comes as a surprise. Steve
Watson, a spokesman for Lorillard, said it was not company practice
to comment with regard to litigation or potential ligation.
</P>
<P>
   Given recent decisions by the U.S. Supreme Court, several legal
experts have questioned whether a nationwide settlement of all
current and future smoking claims could withstand constitutional
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Coffee, a law professor at Columbia University, said
Weinstein appointed him several months ago as adviser to help
determine ways that a national settlement could survive such
appeals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2058EDT &QL; 
