<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4470 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG     09-06 0407
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS TO START SANS STUMPEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Kings will begin training
camp Friday without top-line center Jozef Stumpel, a restricted
free agent who is holding out while seeking a new contract with the
club.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel, 28, earned $1.75 million last year when he scored 58
points in 57 games. But he also missed more than two months with a
groin injury that required surgery and was out for three more weeks
with an injured left knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't expect him and it is difficult to say when he'll be
in,'' Kings general manager Dave Taylor said Wednesday. ``It's
unfortunate because he is our first-line center and an important
member of the team. We need a healthy (Stumpel) this year and
training camp only helps that.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor, who last month avoided salary arbitration by reaching
agreements with centers Bryan Smolinski and Ian Laperriere, also
must address the contract status of captain Rob Blake, who will
become an unrestricted free agent at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Blake already has arrived at camp, which will be held
through the first week of October at the Kings' new training
facility. Like Mattias Norstrom, who skipped camp last year before
getting a three-year deal, Stumpel is without a contract and using
his absence as leverage.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Stumpel was the Kings' best player with club
highs in assists (59) and points (79). But he missed 43 games
during the next two seasons. When he played last year, he excelled,
leading the club with 41 assists and tying Luc Robitaille for a
team-high plus-23 rating.
</P>
<P>
   Stumpel had seven game-winning goals, including three in
overtime. During a six-game stretch from Jan. 31 to Feb. 14, he had
five goals and eight assists. The Kings went 5-1.
</P>
<P>
   __ Notes: Although camp does not begin until Friday, most of the
team skated Wednesday. Beginning at 7 a.m. today, the players will
undergo physicals. They also will attend meetings in the afternoon
with coach Andy Murray. . . . Forward Pavel Rosa, one of the more
popular members of the organization after scoring two goals in his
first NHL game (Dec. 17, 1998), will not be back this season. Rosa,
who spent most of last season at minor-league Long Beach, rejected
a contract offer from the club this summer and is expected to play
in Europe.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
