<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4472 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PAGAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT     09-06 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAGAN-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PAGAN BABIES': SAMPLING THE LOWLIFE FOOD CHAIN WITH ELMORE
LEONARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Publication notes are at end of review.) 
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a move more apt to inspire compassion than readers'
confidence, Elmore Leonard begins his latest novel with the grim
aftermath of genocidal massacre in Rwanda. Five years earlier, 47
of the Rev. Terry Dunn's parishioners were murdered in church, and
he still lives with the memory. Dunn also lives with an
interestingly eclectic attitude toward his spiritual duties. When a
Tutsi man confesses homicidal anger toward the Hutu who killed his
family, the priest offers practical advice. `` `Walk up to the
guy,' Terry said, `and hit him in the mouth as hard as you can,
with a rock. You'll feel better.'''
</P>
<P>
   As he describes Terry's quiet, haunted life in Africa, Leonard
remains noticeably out of his element (though not nearly as far out
as when he tried working rock lyrics into ``Be Cool,'' his shaky
1999 foray into the music business). Then, 50 pages into the story,
the happily inevitable begins to happen. Circumstances force Terry
to leave Rwanda in a hurry, and he returns to what is terra firma
for this author: a Detroit filled with delusional schemers and
fabulously inept hoods. The pieces of this crime tale begin falling
into place so handily that Leonard might as well have hung a
``Virtuoso at Work'' shingle on his door.
</P>
<P>
   Terry has a brother, Fran, who knows a woman named Debbie Dewey,
who has ambitions as a stand-up comic. Debbie has been honing her
act in a women's medium-security prison, a hard place to get
laughs. The centerpiece of her act is an account of the event that
landed her behind bars. ``True story,'' Debbie tells her audience.
``I was visiting my mom in Florida and happened to run into my
ex-husband ... with a Buick Riviera.'' Pause for effect. ``It was a
rental, but it did the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Two salient things about Debbie: Terry, who raised eyebrows by
living in not-so-priestly closeness with his Rwandan housekeeper,
will be secular enough to like her style, and what she passes off
as the true story of her automotive mishap is baloney.
</P>
<P>
   The car was a Ford Escort, but she thinks Riviera sounds
classier. The ex-husband was really an ex-boyfriend, but she
changed that detail for the same reason. She didn't mention that he
conned her out of money by posing in a yachting cap and borrowing
funds for imaginary nautical supplies. She didn't hit him hard
enough, because Randy Agley (ne Aglioni) is still around. Randy is
a restaurateur who has hair like Michael Landon's, keeps a
photograph of Soupy Sales over his desk and went through a brief
phase of fashioning himself after Pierce Brosnan. Now his style
inspiration is the mob.
</P>
<P>
   When Terry meets Debbie, and when he finds himself having to
settle an old score about cigarette-smuggling charges from his
unholy days, ``Pagan Babies'' hits its cool, sustainable stride.
Leonard returns to the lean fluidity of his best work as he begins
demonstrating how a proposed Little Orphans of Rwanda Fund may just
spin off dividends for Terry and various other characters.
</P>
<P>
   The book's title, less enlightened, comes from Terry's school
days, when ``there'd be a jar in the classroom and a sign that said
FOR THE PAGAN BABIES, and we'd put change in it left from our lunch
money.'' Fund-raising methods may have changed, but the scam
artistry displayed by Leonard's latest crowd of miscreants is
timeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pagan Babies'' takes Terry seriously as a man of conscience,
despite his wily way of navigating hoodlum-infested waters and his
impressive dissembling. Thus, partly paralyzed by virtue, he
remains a neutral hero, but the book that he anchors does not lack
local color.
</P>
<P>
   As it moves entertainingly up the gangland food chain,
escalating from tax-free cigarettes to mob hits and a scam to
extort damages from Randy's restaurant, the story trots out an
irresistible array of lowlifes. Randy, in particular, is a
character actor's dream, what with the debonair manner of an ersatz
yachtsman, the pretensions of a professional host and the
paper-thin civility of a mob frontman.
</P>
<P>
   Told that he has to subsidize mob-controlled prostitutes at his
restaurant for an exorbitant fee, Randy wearily raises no-win
questions about the fairness of the deal. ``What you're telling
me,'' he tells a mob intermediary, ``the girls could all quit and
become stockbrokers, you still get your eight'' thousand ``a
week.''
</P>
<P>
   The book is at its devilish best in a scene that has Randy
interrogating Mutt, a potential hired killer who doesn't seem to
know any tricks of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to catch him someplace having his supper,'' says the
would-be assassin.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't mean here,'' Randy hastily replies.
</P>
<P>
   No, Mutt is imagining one of those mom-and-pop Italian
restaurants that are required for gangland assassinations in
movies. (``In the movies they're always sending to Detroit for a
hit man, like they're sitting around waiting for calls,'' Terry
remarks. ``Guy picks up the phone, `Hit man, can I help you?''')
</P>
<P>
   But Randy thinks it might be better to drive past and pop the
victim. ``You do have a car?'' he asks Mutt. No, but Mutt has a
pickup with a battery that often needs jump-starting. ``Or you
could steal a car, just for the job,'' suggests Randy. ``I
understand that's often the way it's done. You know, in case
someone gets the license number.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, maybe. But then Mutt would need to worry about finding a
parking place. Maybe a buddy could drive him, but he doesn't have
any friends. Nor does he, unlike many more highly skilled hit men,
have a gun.
</P>
<P>
   When the terms of the shooting are worked out, Mutt has one last
question: ``But now which person was it again?''
</P>
<P>
   It will spoil none of the story's cunning, and probably surprise
no one, to learn that Terry Dunn, a k a ``the priest,'' is the
intended target. Or that Mutt, in the manner of Leonard's most
memorable small-time operators, has a practical streak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess it's OK,'' he decides. ``I'm a Baptist.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PAGAN BABIES'
</P>
<P>
   By Elmore Leonard
</P>
<P>
   263 Pages. Delacorte Press. $24.95
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
