<HEADER>
A4475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-R-U.N.-RWANDA-ART-NYT     09-06 0789
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-U.N.-RWANDA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RWANDA'S PRESIDENT CALLS FOR MORE U.N. EXPERTISE TO HELP COUNTRY
REBUILD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating to add art note)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT8,9 were sent on Sept. 5 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Less than two weeks after experts told the
United Nations that it needed an in-house policy center to work on
areas of tension before they turn into international crises,
President Paul Kagame of Rwanda came along Tuesday with a case in
point.
</P>
<P>
   More than six years after a frenzy of ethnic killing tore his
small African country apart, armed militia and former soldiers
thought to be guilty of some of the killings are still roaming free
in neighboring Congo. A plan to deal with them should have been
worked out long ago by U.N. officials drawing on their experience
and collective skills, Kagame said in an interview. To him, they
are the reason there is a war in Congo.
</P>
<P>
   In New York for a meeting of world leaders, Kagame said that
until the Hutu responsible for killing Tutsi and their moderate
Hutu allies are disarmed and resettled somewhere in peace, Rwandan
troops will stay in Congo. The presence of foreign troops _ from
Rwanda, Uganda, Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia _ is also a major
impediment to dispatching a U.N. peacekeeping operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. has enough resources and expertise _ and even
experience from other situations _ to come up with a proposal,''
Kagame said. Breaking the cycle of blame and counter-blame between
Rwanda and the Congolese government would mean separating fewer
than 10,000 Rwandans who, he said, are mixed with troops from Congo
and its allies, particularly Zimbabwe and Angola.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many ways of dealing with the problem,'' he said.
``One is working together to see that these people don't get
support from other governments. Then you can move farther and
identify where they are. Let's put them into camps and disarm them.
Let's repatriate them to Rwanda or take them elsewhere. I don't see
why the U.N. can fail to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep coming to us and asking us what we feel they should
do, but this is simply escaping the problem, trying to run away
from the problem. They come a hundred times asking the same
questions. I think they'd better get serious and do what they're
supposed to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of exiles have returned voluntarily, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Call my bluff,'' he said to those who say that Rwanda really
has designs on territory in eastern Congo. With the former Rwandan
soldiers and militias out of Congo, he said, his troops will come
home.
</P>
<P>
   Kagame said the costly business of keeping Rwandan troops in
Congo to seal the border burdens the reconstruction of Rwanda, a
country of about 7.5 million people.
</P>
<P>
   He said that Rwanda, like Cambodia, will suffer for a long time
from the loss of much of its middle class in the killings. The
events of 1994 left up to 800,000 Rwandans dead and led several
months later to the overthrow of a Hutu-led government by Tutsi-led
rebels whom Kagame commanded. He has been the central power figure
in Rwanda ever since, although he did not assume the presidency
until this year after a split in his party led to the resignation
of his predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   The middle-class professionals lost to Rwanda came from both
ethnic groups. Kagame said that in addition to those who were
killed, many of the 120,000 Rwandans charged in the attacks and
still in jail are also middle class: priests, civil servants, local
political leaders and sometimes teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Kagame, who has tempered the fury he first expressed at the
failure of the United Nations and its leading members, including
the United States and France, to prevent or end the massacres, now
focuses his criticism on what he sees as an international failure
to recognize that a country so profoundly wounded cannot be treated
like just any place.
</P>
<P>
   ``My country has to be treated as a special case,'' he said, and
he intends to make this a theme of his speech this week to world
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   He said Rwanda still has a long way to go toward reconciliation
and the rebuilding of government institutions that can withstand
ethnic tensions. Agriculture, education and health services are
only beginning to be restored.
</P>
<P>
   But he rejected suggestions that the Hutu majority and Tutsi
minority will never be reconciled.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been nothing in the past to demonstrate that they
can't live together,'' he said, ``but I do see a solution in the
better political management of the situation _ better political,
economic and social management of the country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
