<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVE CAMPO'S REACTION TOO MEEK, TOO WEAK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know the Dave Campo story.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter 1 was such a nice read:
</P>
<P>
   Hard-working, very competent football guy busts his butt all
those seasons, advances through the staff ranks, and then is
rewarded by the benevolent team owner with the head coaching job.
</P>
<P>
   There is initial doubt, locally and nationally, over Campo being
able to ``handle'' the many nonfootball variables that come with
the Valley Ranch territory (i.e., the Jerry factor). But through
the spring and summer, all you had to do was deal with Campo
personally, and he'd win you over. Sincerity and honesty were
prevalent. Eventually, no doubter was left unturned.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, then came Chapter 2, where the season-opening
Sunday story line switched quickly from nice to nasty:
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a dark and stormy night.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it was 109 degrees under cloudless afternoon skies
when a hard rain of fire scorched the Texas Stadium fake earth. I
didn't research it, but it may have been the worst head-coaching
debut, all things considered, in the history of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   Campo's players turned into heartless, prideless mutants. They
disgraced the new coach and themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Media-wise, Campo probably got off a little light in the
retelling of Sunday's thing. Why? Read Chapter 1 again. Blame it
also on patriotism. America would be a better place if the Campos
of our world were a success. The jock kingdom needs more good guys
and less rodents. In other words, we play favorites in the media.
You got a problem with that? Then e-mail this:
</P>
<P>
   As bad as the Philly flop turned out, Campo deserves, of course,
not to be judged on one game. And he won't be. Not here anyway.
</P>
<P>
   But I'm also not so sure the football failure has been the worst
moment of Campo's week. How he handled himself from the minute that
game was over has certainly been watched closely. And judged
closely.
</P>
<P>
   To borrow a favorite Campo lead-in line when answering media
questions:
</P>
<P>
   To-be-honest-with-you ...
</P>
<P>
   Dave, you are coming across as weak.
</P>
<P>
   Those who desire to label Campo as ``Jerry's puppet'' have been
given ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal:
</P>
<P>
   Campo walked into a jam-packed media conference some 25 minutes
after Sunday's game, climbed to the podium, and started off with,
``Fellows, this is gonna be brief.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. Now, do some Jimmy theater. Give us one minute, with
the minicams rolling, of livid anger, then storm off the podium,
and out of the room. Take no questions. Take the blame (which Campo
did) and promise to correct the sins (which Campo did), but don't
give us (the media) the time of day after that.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Campo wasn't brief, and he wasn't mad enough. He spent
at least 20 minutes patiently giving good answers to hard
questions, which was certainly helpful. But it's every man for
himself in this bottomless pit. Campo needs to watch out for No. 1.
His players had already quit on him. The media won't be far behind.
</P>
<P>
   That was a too-docile beginning for Campo. The expected and
necessary explosion never happened.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was also another postgame scene that didn't seem to
fit the situation. On Monday, Campo spoke of being proud of how his
locker-room comments to the players the day before were limited. He
said he didn't have to say all that much because several veteran
players took the lead in scolding the troops.
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Just another opinion from the outside, but Campo should
have storm-trooped that locker room, shut up any player who wanted
to say anything, and then delivered a come-to-Jesus speech that
would have peeled paint off the walls. Name names, and dog-cuss
everybody, including immediate family members of every offensive
and defensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, Dave, but that seems weak that you didn't personally
deliver the hell-fire sermon of your life to the same players who
had just left your coaching debut for dead out there on Jerry's
fake grass.
</P>
<P>
   Move it ahead then to Tuesday, the head coach's media-conference
day at Valley Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Another potential credibility problem exists because of the
dazed state of quarterback Troy Aikman. Maybe you've noticed _
credibility has never been a strong point out there in Irving.
</P>
<P>
   But here's the skinny:
</P>
<P>
   Aikman suffered a medically diagnosed concussion on Sunday, the
eighth, 12th, 20th, 25th _ who knows the truth by now _ of his
career.
</P>
<P>
   I repeat. This is a concussion. The doctors said so. And
yesterday, the proper decision was finally made to sit Aikman for
Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   But, somehow, the smokescreen of ``inner-ear infection'' had
been introduced this week to explain Aikman's condition. Jerry,
that's you, isn't it?
</P>
<P>
   The implication here was someone at Valley Ranch wanted Aikman
back on the field in Tempe, regardless of a brain bruise. And, by
the way, Aikman did have an inner-ear infection last week, and
there was a medical question over his continuing headaches this
week being related to that, or the concussion.
</P>
<P>
   For credibility purposes, however, Campo should have stayed 10
miles away from ``inner-ear infection'' mumbo-jumbo. Instead, he
brings it up on his own Tuesday, traps himself into that no-escape
alley, and overall, it sounded Jerry-puppet-like.
</P>
<P>
   Campo is better than that and smarter than that. He has enough
football problems. He definitely needs no additional perception
negatives.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2108EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0353 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4477 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX     09-06 1747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIP NEW COACH HAS TEXAS TECH HUMMING HAPPY TUNE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The musical mess has abated at Texas Tech, giving way to a
spirit of compromise that seems to have struck a chord of
contentment in all parties.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Leach, the Red Raiders' first-year football coach with a
laundry list of push-the-envelope ideas to motivate his team, will
continue to inspire his team during practice with piped-in music of
his players' choosing. And the Tech band will continue working to
adapt instrumental versions of the tunes into their game-day
repertoire, as evidenced by the debut of two movie themes _
``Jaws'' and ``Mission: Impossible'' _ in last week's 38-16 rout of
Utah State.
</P>
<P>
   More selections may be in the offing for Saturday's 6 p.m. game
against North Texas, with ``Start Me Up'' by the Rolling Stones on
the short list of possibilities. Leach isn't sure, and much will
depend on how quickly the band can learn a tune like
``Headhunters'' to serenade the kickoff coverage squad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're headed in the right direction. The instrumentals
the band converted are pretty neat,'' said Leach, who must have
established some type of Big 12 coach's record by discussing theme
music for 10 minutes during his weekly conference call with media
members.
</P>
<P>
   For the uninitiated, Leach is Mr. Motivation. He has assistant
coaches dub inspirational clips from movies into videotapes the
players study. He concocted a ``Super Games'' competition during
spring drills, pitting players against one another in offbeat
sports like water polo to build camaraderie. But his master stroke
as a motivator might have come in preseason drills, when he
assigned each special-teams unit at Tech a theme song.
</P>
<P>
   Players practice to the music in daily drills. Leach sought a
game-day carryover, but his plan hit a snag in the Aug. 26 season
opener. Fans objected to hearing canned music from Metallica and
rapper Warren G, prompting the decision to have the Tech band
handle all music _ including theme song adaptations _ during games
at Jones SBC Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The rap song, in particular, drew the ire of Tech fans because
its lyrics contain the word ``damn.''
</P>
<P>
   Leach's response?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's actually a pretty clean rap song,'' Leach said. ``I read
the Bible a lot and it says `damn' in there, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it does. But not in the same context, a fact that is not
lost on the youngest man (39) in charge of a Big 12 football
program.
</P>
<P>
   As the new coach on the block, Leach is not willing to push the
envelope past the point of tolerability for West Texas residents.
So the canned music, rap or otherwise, is shelved on game days in
favor of heaping helpings of the Goin' Band from Raiderland. But
the boom box plays on at Tech workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll still do it in practice, regardless,'' Leach said. ``Our
players like it. It fires them up. Just because their tastes are
different \Rthan fans' musical preferences\S, that doesn't mean we
should cut someone off. If we can get to a happy medium on both
sides, it's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're there. Some of those hard rock songs the band
plays gives them a new dimension, and it sounds great.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the varied musical tastes, there's one sound Tech fans
long to hear Saturday: the chime of victory bells from the East
Tower of the administration building after a game against North
Texas in Lubbock. The Red Raiders have not heard those since 1985,
a stretch that encompasses three Mean Green visits (1999, 1997,
1988) and three Tech coaching changes.
</P>
<P>
   If Leach can ring those bells, it will provide the sweetest
music sounded during his short tenure in Lubbock.
Quarterback mystery continues for 'Horns
Applewhite or Simms? Simms or Applewhite?
</P>
<P>
   No matter how you phrase it, that is the question that plagues
men's souls in Austin, where the sixth-ranked Longhorns will open
the season Saturday against Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be known, it hardly matters if Chris Simms or Major
Applewhite takes the opening snap against the Ragin' Cajuns (0-1),
a 451/2-point underdog coming off a 21-14 home loss to Sam Houston
State, a Division I-AA school.
</P>
<P>
   Both will play and both should thrive in a mismatch so glaring
it would make Kansas State coach Bill Snyder blush. With the
Longhorns committed to evaluating two quarterbacks and developing
young wide receivers, the biggest challenge for Texas coach Mack
Brown will be knowing when to pull back on the passing game before
critics begin drawing comparisons to former Houston coach John
Jenkins, master of the 10-touchdown victory margin.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has been guarded in his pregame comments. He won't
publicly identify a starter until game day. He refers to Applewhite
and Simms as ``co-starters.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brown might have tipped his hand, in terms of his grand plan
for the quarterback position, when he likened it to Texas' tailback
search last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, it took us three or four weeks last year to figure
out our tailback situation,'' Brown said. ``It may take some time
to figure this thing out. It's hard to figure it out in two-a-days
because you don't hit quarterbacks. So you don't know how they're
going to respond in a ballgame. We've got to look at who's going to
be the best starter on Saturday. We've got to look at who comes off
the bench the best. We've got to look at the best chemistry for our
team.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Saturday's game is another dress rehearsal for
the quarterbacks before a more permanent decision is made. Logic
suggests that could come as soon as Sept. 16 against Stanford or as
late as Oct. 7 against Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, it's more important to note how well Simms and
Applewhite perform under fire rather than when they take their
snaps.
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:QUICK HITS
\Nsubheds:Opening in style Texas and Oklahoma State will be the
final Big 12 schools to open their seasons Saturday, with the
sixth-ranked Longhorns seeking to extend a league record. Texas has
had more success in season debuts than any Big 12 school, with a
career mark of 87-17-3. A victory over Louisiana-Lafayette would be
No. 88 for the Longhorns, eight more than any conference rival.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma reached the 80-victory plateau in openers last week in
a 55-14 rout of UT-El Paso. Behind the Sooners are Nebraska (76),
Iowa State (76) and Missouri (70). \Nsubheds:Bracing for Big Red
Through the years, few schools have played more high-profile games
in the regular season than Nebraska or Notre Dame. But the
Cornhuskers haven't played in South Bend, Ind., since 1947. That
will change Saturday, when No. 1 Nebraska (1-0) meets No. 23 Notre
Dame (1-0) in a contest that is creating numbers problems for the
participants. And we're not talking about national rankings.
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska officials estimate 30,000 fans will travel to the game,
even though the Big Red contingent is allotted only 4,000 of 80,232
seats in Notre Dame Stadium. To assist with the overflow, a
Nebraska alumni association has rented a nearby golf course to give
unsuccessful ticket buyers a place to congregate.
</P>
<P>
   From the Irish side of the equation, the pregame buzz is
significant enough that Notre Dame officials might move their
Friday pep rally from the basketball arena to the football stadium
to accommodate an estimated gathering between 30,000 and 40,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably never been associated with a game quite like
this so early in the season,'' Nebraska coach Frank Solich said.
``This one has been brought up almost constantly ... for as long as
I can remember. We're happy it's here, so we can finally play it.''
\Nsubheds:Picking up the pace Texas Tech coach Mike Leach said he
has been pleased with his offense's progress since opening the
season with a lethargic 24-3 victory over New Mexico on Aug. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Tech (2-0) rebounded last week to pound Utah State, 38-16, with
quarterback Kliff Kingsbury throwing for 450 yards and wide
receiver Carlos Francis grabbing seven passes for 234 yards and a
touchdown. Other players, said Leach, have shown signs of
approaching breakout status in practices. He cited wide receiver
Tim Baker, who grabbed 22 passes in a recent workout, as an
example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I try to gauge things by asking, `Did we get a week's worth
better than our last game?,' '' Leach said. ``We did that, and then
some. I think we've got to be pretty satisfied with how many plays
we're making, at this point.''
