<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-RECEIVER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWERFUL RECEIVER GIVES TEXAS A&AMP;M BIG-PLAY OPTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ A hard-nosed grandmother raised and
nurtured Robert Ferguson during his formative years.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the strongest person in the world I know,'' Ferguson
said. ``She don't take no stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps that explains why Texas A&AMP;M's big-play receiver appears
as tough as a $2.99 breakfast steak served at a highway truck stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``She gave me that mentality,'' Ferguson said. ``That's where I
get it from.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson's faint voice defies his 6-foot-2, 220-pound frame, but
don't mistake that sedate personality for weakness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two words come to my mind with Robert,'' said Aggies offensive
coordinator Steve Kragthorpe, who recruited the junior-college
All-American. ``No. 1, he's a great competitor. No. 2, he's a
warrior. He'll play hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson played in pain throughout the Aggies' 24-10 loss
Saturday to Notre Dame. The 20-year-old transfer from Tyler Junior
College suffered a painful shin bruise during the Aggies' first
offensive series and also required an IV at halftime, Kragthorpe
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He won't come out of a game,'' Kragthorpe said. ``To get him
out of a game, you'd have to put him on a cart, strap him down and
put him in a straitjacket.''
</P>
<P>
   That might be the best manner to defend Ferguson, who riddled
the Irish secondary for a game-high five receptions worth 79 yards
and drew two pass-interference penalties worth another 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson beat Notre Dame's Ron Israel on a deep post pattern in
the second quarter, but the Irish defender denied the big play by
grabbing the receiver's arms and settling for a 15-yard penalty.
Irish cornerback Cedric Jefferson utilized a move from the World
Wrestling Federation to mug Ferguson in the end zone to prevent a
third-quarter reception.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of those plays are touchdowns if they don't do it,''
quarterback Mark Farris said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope that's not something I have to get used to,'' Ferguson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Defenders might be forced to rely on such tactics against
Ferguson, who combines size, speed, strength and athletic ability.
Ferguson once ran 40 yards in 4.36 seconds at Tyler Junior College,
and he bench-presses 400 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he walks into a room, he looks like a linebacker,''
Kragthorpe said, ``but he plays wide receiver.''
</P>
<P>
   That presents matchup problems for many of college football's
smurf-sized defensive backs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of them are 5-9 and 5-10, and that presents a lot of
problems for defensive backs,'' Farris said. ``Whether you line him
up in the slot or outside, he's going to be so much bigger than
most of them. You don't find many receivers with his size and
speed. You might find some big guys like that, but they can't run
like he does.''
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies appear to have a special player, and Farris sensed it
as soon as he met him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could tell he was something different,'' Farris said.
``He's going to be a big weapon for us.''
Robert Ferguson file
</P>
<P>
   Position: Wide receiver
</P>
<P>
   Class: Junior
</P>
<P>
   Height: 6-foot-2
</P>
<P>
   Weight: 220 pounds
</P>
<P>
   College career: Had big first game with Aggies, catching five
passes for 79 yards last week against Notre Dame. ... Played at
Tyler Junior College a year ago, where he caught 36 passes. ...
Originally signed with A&AMP;M out of Houston Spring Woods High School.
... Also outstanding long jumper and basketball player in high
school.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
