<HEADLINE>
TIME-SHARE BACKS BOOST SMU ATTACK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TRACEY MYERS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ SMU is spreading its wings in the backfield, as Jason
Pipkins and Kris Briggs are sharing time at running back.
</P>
<P>
   Briggs led the team in rushing with 522 yards last season,
despite never starting a game. He was a projected starter before
this season, but a nagging hip injury and the emergence of Pipkins,
who didn't carry the ball in 1999, has given coach Mike Cavan a
dual attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was ever a case of a young man who worked himself
above his capabilities, it's Jason Pipkins,'' Cavan said. ``Briggs
has been out a lot, so I think you'll see both of those guys. With
Briggs, it's probably best for him because his hip is not going to
get any better.''
</P>
<P>
   Pipkins and Briggs had comparable outputs in the Mustangs' 31-17
opening-season victory Saturday against Kansas. Pipkins rushed 18
times for 74 yards, and Briggs had 20 carries for 71 yards and a
touchdown. Briggs said he was disappointed with the decision at
first, but has settled into his role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an I thing, it's a team thing,'' Briggs said. ``We
don't look at each other as competition. We both work hard because
it's going to take both of us to depend on each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The duo will see a different defense Saturday when the Mustangs
travel to UT-El Paso for their Western Athletic Conference opener.
The Miners use an eight-man defensive front that likes to blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're anything like last year, maybe we can catch them on
a good day and the running game will be wide open,'' Briggs said.
``If we set up correctly, hopefully \Rwe'll\S catch them blitzing
the wrong side.'' \Nsubheds:Positive feelings Mike Cavan and the
Mustangs are still living off the positive vibes from their
season-opening victory in the new Gerald J. Ford Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was maybe the most important in a long time as
far as a victory, and I still felt that way a day or two after it
was over,'' Cavan said. ``But we don't want \Rthat excitement\S
just to be at the opening ceremonies of Ford Stadium. We want that
every week. That's the kind of atmosphere we want to have.''
\Nsubheds:O'Neill questionable Tight end Steve O'Neill sprained his
left ankle toward the end of the Jayhawks' game, and is
questionable for the UTEP game. O'Neill did not practice Monday or
Tuesday. \Nsubheds:Focusing on UTEP tight end The Mustangs' primary
concern could be UTEP tight end Brian Natkin. The nation's leading
returning tight end in receptions (59) and touchdowns (4) could be
a candidate for the John Mackey Award, given to the nation's top
tight end. Last season, Natkin caught five passes for 60 yards and
a touchdown in UTEP's 42-28 victory against SMU.
</P>
<P>
   Cavan is mainly looking for containment with Natkin.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great players, they're going to do what they do and you
hope they don't go crazy,'' Cavan said. ``We have to be conscious
of him. We have to know what he likes to do, where he catches the
ball and, hopefully, have someone there.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
