<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TRAINING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS GLAD TO BE BACK ON THE JOB
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Rangers haven't seen the right side of .500
since mid-June. Playoff talk died not too long after.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys, meanwhile, not only lost their season opener in
pathetic fashion Sunday but lost their star receiver and their
quarterback as well.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the sporting landscape here in North Texas hasn't been too
pretty lately. But we interrupt your regularly scheduled depressing
sports news to tell you that hope is on the horizon.
</P>
<P>
   It's time for hockey again. Really, the Stars are back at Dr
Pepper StarCenter. They have a meeting tonight and physicals Friday
before flying to Vail, Colo., to begin training camp Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike last season, when the Stars wearily dragged their
Stanley Cup-winning behinds into camp, captain Derian Hatcher said
guys are eager to get back this time around.
</P>
<P>
   Losing a Cup does a lot for one's enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a different feeling, definitely different,'' Hatcher
said. ``I think there is a lot of guys with still a pretty sour
taste in their mouth, and when you have that, you can't wait to get
back and try to get it out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars were so close to winning their second Stanley Cup
championship they could almost taste it when they hit the ice June
10 for Game 6 of the Stanley Cup Finals against the New Jersey
Devils.
</P>
<P>
   A game, a couple of overtimes and a Jason Arnott goal later, it
was over.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars had come up two victories short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it does go away,'' Stars winger Mike Keane said.
``Every day something comes up. The newspaper has so-and-so taking
the Cup to so-and-so, and you can't help it. You start thinking
about the what-ifs. What if we don't lose three in a row at home? I
don't think there is a day that you don't think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the taste Hatcher was talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The players can't get rid of it. They can't ignore it. They,
instead, come to camp looking to replace it.
</P>
<P>
   Stars coach Ken Hitchcock didn't have to talk to anyone. He
could see the change as players began to trickle in from their
summer vacations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got a lot of guys hungry and in shape and ready to compete
for work,'' Hitchcock said. ``I'm not talking about people who want
to make the team. I'm talking of guys who are going to be on the
team who want more ice time and a bigger bite of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Take winger Grant Marshall for instance. For a number of reasons
_ injury, lack of production _ he found himself on the outside
looking in for a good portion of last season. He left at the end of
last season out of shape and quickly falling out of favor.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall returned with 13 fewer pounds of fat clinging to his
body and talk of playing gritty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to bring that full style of game, of grind it out,
creating space, bring the energy and work as hard as I can, like I
did two years ago when I was healthy,'' Marshall said. ``I can
fight. I like fighting. I don't mind it, but I want to bring that
total package. Consistency is the biggest thing I have to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Stars are ready to go.
</P>
<P>
   And just in the nick of time.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
