<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFT RACETRACK WALLS' A HARD BARRIER TO RESOLVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rumors from Darlington Raceway last weekend about a possible
boycott by NASCAR Winston Cup drivers at the star-crossed New
Hampshire International Speedway have begun to dissipate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll go to New Hampshire and race like we always have,''
reigning Cup champion Dale Jarrett said Tuesday in reference to the
New Hampshire 300 weekend Sept. 15-17. ``The thing I was hoping for
was either for them \Rowners Bob and Gary Bahre\S or someone in
NASCAR would get us a barrier. But it's not a necessity. It's not a
situation where anybody is looking at not going.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the renewed concern expressed by some of NASCAR's
highest-profile drivers about the Turn 3 concrete wall at NHIS _
site of the separate crashes that killed Adam Petty and Kenny Irwin
Jr. this season _ is unprecedented in the sport's recent feel-good
era. Jarrett, Jeff Gordon and Rusty Wallace all went on the record
at Darlington for installation of some sort of energy-dissipating,
``soft-wall'' technology at NHIS. Now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that most every driver in this garage area will be
totally blown away ... if we go back to New Hampshire and those
walls aren't lined,'' Wallace said Saturday, the day after current
points leader Bobby Labonte crashed in Turn 3 at Darlington when
the throttle on his car hung at approximately 180 mph. It is widely
believed, but unsubstantiated, that hung throttles caused the
crashes in practice that killed the 19-year-old Petty on May 11 and
the 30-year-old Irwin on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Echoing the pointed comments made by Jeff Burton before the
Brickyard 400 at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway last month, Gordon
said he would be ``disappointed'' if no changes were made at NHIS
for this race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not put some extra protection out there when it's a
racetrack that all of us agree we want something to be on the walls
there, that can absorb some more impact?'' Gordon said. The
three-time Cup champion predicted ``a lot of backlash'' for Mike
Helton, NASCAR's senior vice president and chief operating officer,
and Gary Nelson, Winston Cup Series director, if no changes were
made.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the ``soft-wall'' issue has the potential to pit
the drivers against NASCAR's hierarchy in the eyes of the fans. And
because the drivers rate as genuine American heroes to the fans _
how many Mike Helton or Gary Nelson T-shirts do you have in your
collection? _ these well-intentioned men could be in for a rougher
ride than they deserve.
</P>
<P>
   Helton and Nelson steadfastly have maintained that nothing is
inherently wrong with the design of the 1.058-mile oval in Loudon,
N.H. Furthermore, both have pointed out that no material has been
developed to lessen the impact created when a 3,400-pound Cup car
crashes into a concrete wall at speed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The buzzword these days is `soft walls,' '' Nelson said during
a recent interview. ``We don't want the solution to create other
problems that may be worse. We found on road courses that a big
stack of tires or block of foam is great where the car leaves the
track. The problem we have on ovals is the racetrack goes right up
against the concrete. In that \Rinstance\S, there's a lot of
contact with a wall at a slight angle. That slight angle ... if the
wall gives at all, it will grab the car and literally suck it into
the wall and stop suddenly.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton said the sanctioning body remains open to any reasonable
solution.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of different test tracks and a lot of different
barriers in this country for a lot of different things, from
overlapping galvanized metal to cables inside tubing and
water-filled and sand-filled,'' Helton said. ``I mean, it's
incredible the different types of barriers being used. The dilemma
is finding one that's better than concrete in motorsports.''
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with the Brickyard 400, Cup cars have been equipped
with a mandatory throttle stop and ignition kill switch on the
steering wheel, a switch Labonte said he did not have time to click
before his crash Friday. NASCAR also is studying a device being
developed by Roush Racing engineers that would shut off the
ignition and engine if a driver applies the brakes when the
throttle sticks.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett indicated Tuesday the majority of drivers understand the
effort being expended by NASCAR on this issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just snap your fingers and have hung throttles go
away, and you just can't snap your fingers and have a barrier,''
Jarrett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an ongoing work in progress that we're very serious
about,'' Helton said, ``in spite of what some people believe.''
SPOTLIGHT ON...
Tracy's CART title chase gets an honest boost
Paul Tracy discovered Sunday that teammate Dario Franchitti truly
is a man of his word. Because he is, Tracy held on to win the
Vancouver Molson Indy and reestablished himself as a title
contender in the CART FedEx Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Team owner Barry Green and the two Team Kool Green drivers
agreed that whichever held the lead after the last pit stop on the
1.781-mile temporary street course would stay in front. Franchitti
was in the lead when the teammates pitted on Lap 53 of the
90-lapper under caution.
</P>
<P>
   But the Scotsman stalled his Honda-Reynard while attempting to
exit his pit box, allowing Tracy to drive around and into the lead.
Franchitti did pressure Tracy when the race went green on Lap 60,
but kept up his end of the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   ``A team's got to work together, and that's what our biggest
strength is,'' said Tracy, who scored the 18th victory of his
Championship Auto Racing Teams career. ``Dario and I work together
and work hard and concentrate on being fair with each other. Yeah,
we've had our accidents, but that hasn't caused any
self-destruction in the team. We're honest with each other.
Sometimes it's not that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Tracy scored his third victory of the season, and second in as
many races, by 0.384 seconds. Tracy began the day sixth in points,
25 behind Michael Andretti. But Tracy's victory and Andretti's
last-lap drop to 12th because of a mechanical problem moved the
Canadian to within six points (126-120) heading into the Honda
Grand Prix at Laguna Seca Raceway in Monterey, Calif., this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   CART's top five drivers are separated by 11 points. Adrian
Fernandez of Patrick Racing is third with 117 points, followed by
Gil de Ferran of Marlboro Team Penske with 116 and Roberto Moreno,
also of Patrick, fifth with 115.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy, who has won races at four of the five tracks remaining on
the schedule, believes that Andretti still presents his toughest
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been there, done it, won championships and knows he can
win anywhere on a given day,'' Tracy said of Andretti, the 1991
series champion. ``He's got the most experience of anybody, so he's
going to be the toughest guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Tracy also is convinced this is his best shot at earning his
first CART championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know this is a good situation,'' said Tracy, who won at
Laguna Seca in 1993 and 1994, the latter when he led all 84 laps en
route to victory. ``I led the championship for seven or eight races
\Rthis season\S and would have liked to have checked out. Now we're
not focusing on the championship so much. I think maybe that was a
big part of our problem in the middle of the season. All we were
worried about was points, points, points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're going to go out and race as hard as we can and
wherever we end up at the end of the year is what's going to
happen. It's worked the last two races. Hopefully, it will work the
last five.''
PIT STOPS Meyer lines up buyers Texas Motorplex owner Billy Meyer
continues to shop his drag-racing facility in Ennis.
</P>
<P>
   Elon Werner, Motorplex general manager, said he expects Meyer to
use the O'Reilly Fall Nationals on Oct. 19-22 as a ``showcase'' for
three prospective owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if Billy's the owner in 2001,'' Werner said.
``He's talking to three people that are really serious about it.
They're fans of the sport and have the financial means to buy the
track. Billy wants to sell it to someone who will be a real good
caretaker. He's put 30 years into NHRA drag racing and wants to
make sure those years won't be wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Meyer decided to sell the track he opened in 1986 after National
Hot Rod Association officials pulled the Motorplex's spring
national event from the 2001 schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Ticket information for the race is available by calling (972)
878-2641 or at www.texasmotorplex.com. Waiting on Mikey CART
superstar Michael Andretti, the series' winningest active driver
and current points leader, is expected to make an announcement
about his future after the Honda Grand Prix at Laguna Seca Raceway
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Speculation is that Andretti, who has driven for Newman/Haas
Racing a total of 10 years in two stints, will leave the team to
become part of a new group affiliated with Barry Green's two-car
Team Kool Green. Andretti and his father, Mario, are expected to
have ownership in the team, allowing Michael to compete in the
Championship Auto Racing Teams FedEx Championship Series and the
rival Indy Racing League's Indianapolis 500.
</P>
<P>
   Mario Andretti won his only Indy 500 in 1969. Michael, 37, last
competed at the Indianapolis Motor Speedway in 1995, the year
before the series split. Monza chicane under fire Changes in the
legendary Monza circuit for the Italian Grand Prix have prompted a
forecast of doom for the start of the Formula One race Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The new-look Rettifilio chicane in Turn 1 is much tighter than
in previous years and bordered by asphalt as opposed to gravel.
Because of the narrowness of the chicane, a number of drivers fear
there will be an accident heading into Turn 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to see the braking points to the corner, and so
many people are cutting the chicane because of that,'' David
Coulthard of McLaren-Mercedes said after testing the layout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a 100 percent chance of an accident at the start,''
Jordan driver Jarno Trulli said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be carnage at the start,'' Arrows racer Pedro
de la Rosa said. ``I just hope I'm not part of it.'' Last laps
Buddy Lazier, the Indy Racing Northern Light Series points leader,
is scheduled to join two other teams in a test at Texas Motor
Speedway on Monday. The season-ending Excite 500 is scheduled at
the 1.5-mile quadoval Oct. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The late Greg Moore's No. 99 officially was retired by the CART
FedEx and Dayton Indy Lights series at the Vancouver Molson Indy on
Sunday. Moore, a 24-year-old resident of the Vancouver, British
Columbia, suburb of Maple Ridge, was killed in a crash during the
CART season-finale at the California Speedway last November.
</P>
<P>
   Rusty Wallace is the runaway leader in Winston Cup poles this
season with eight, five more than runner-up Dale Jarrett. The most
Bud Pole Awards won by a driver in a single season during NASCAR's
``modern era'' (since 1972) is 14 by Cale Yarborough during the
31-race 1980 season.
</P>
<P>
   Native Texan Bobby Labonte's 111-point lead over runner-up Dale
Jarrett ties the largest margin of the season and is equal to the
difference between a first and 31st-place finish.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Evernham, former three-time Winston Cup champion crew chief,
returns to the series as owner of the No. 19 Motorola Evernham
Motorsports Ford Taurus team at Richmond International Raceway on
Saturday night. The Chevrolet Monte Carlo 400 is the first of three
Cup starts scheduled for Casey Atwood this season.
