<HEADER>
A4482 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TORONTO-FILM-FEST-900     09-06 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-FILM-FEST-900&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BACK FROM THE BEACH AND BOUND FOR TORONTO 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The beach chairs are back in the garage, the
children have returned to the custody of their teachers, summer's
hot breath has taken on the faint scent of autumn and, once again,
the publicists are returning to Ontario.
</P>
<P>
   It can mean only one thing: The summer movie season is finally,
blessedly over, and it's time for the Toronto International Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   This year marks the 25th annual gathering of filmmakers, actors,
agents, producers, publicists and the ladies and gentlemen of the
entertainment press, an event that not only has grown into one of
the world's most important film markets but also has become the
prime launching pad for the fall and holiday season's Oscar bait.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year ``American Beauty'' and ``The Cider House
Rules'' were fighting it out for the top Oscars, Kevin Spacey from
``Beauty'' was vying with Denzel Washington from ``The Hurricane''
for best actor, and Hilary Swank of ``Boys Don't Cry'' was carting
off practically every acting award in Hollywood, including the
Oscar. Every one of those films got its first big exposure at last
year's Toronto festival.
</P>
<P>
   While this year's gathering will include some special events
geared to the 25th anniversary _ including the festival's first
filmmaker tribute since 1984, honoring the director Stephen Frears
_ the festival will largely look as it has in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a funny way, we didn't want the anniversary to impact on
the festival,'' said Piers Handling, director of the festival for
the last seven years. ``We wanted some special events, but we
didn't want them to take over because, obviously, the festival is
on a roll.''
</P>
<P>
   There were 1,832 films submitted to this year's festival,
compared with 1,585 last year. ``And that doesn't include the films
we're seeing on screening trips,'' Handling said. ``In the end, 329
made the cut, including 178 world or North American premieres, from
56 countries, 253 of them feature-length films. Last year, we had
254, so it's basically the same size festival as last year.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night's opening gala, which is traditionally reserved
for a film from a Canadian director, will be Denys Arcand's
``Stardom,'' about a small-town girl's sudden rise in the modeling
world, with an ensemble cast including Dan Aykroyd and Frank
Langella. The closing night film, on Sept. 16, will be Michael
Kalesniko's ``How to Kill Your Neighbor's Dog,'' a comedy with
Kenneth Branagh and Robin Wright Penn as a struggling playwright
and his baby-obsessed wife.
</P>
<P>
   There will be plenty in between. The writer and director Cameron
Crowe will unveil ``Almost Famous,'' his first film since ``Jerry
Maguire'' in 1996, based on his own adventures as a teen-age
Rolling Stone reporter. Robert De Niro and Cuba Gooding Jr. will
star in ``Men of Honor,'' a big-studio adventure about the first
black Navy Seal. Richard Gere will headline ``Dr. T and the
Women,'' from the director Robert Altman.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Glazer, a first-time director, will offer ``Sexy
Beast,'' starring Ben Kingsley as a veteran crook. The director
Terence Davies has an adaptation of Edith Wharton's ``House of
Mirth,'' and the director Ang Lee, returning to China, offers
``Crouching Tiger, Hidden Dragon,'' a martial-arts fantasy that was
a hit at the Cannes Film Festival earlier this year. Tom Tykwer,
the director of the 1998 festival's biggest surprise, ``Run Lola
Run,'' returns with ``The Princess and the Warrior,'' about a
psychiatric nurse (Franka Potente, star of ``Lola'') whose life is
saved by a small-time crook.
</P>
<P>
   As for performances, the publicists are already fanning the
Oscar buzz as vigorously as they can. Among those drawing the most
prefestival attention were Joan Allen, playing a United States
senator with a sex secret in her past in Rod Lurie's ``The
Contender,'' and Willem Dafoe in ``Shadow of the Vampire,'' playing
a fictional version of Max Shreck, the actor who starred in F.W.
Murnau's classic vampire film, ``Nosferatu.'' And, no doubt, a crop
of sleepers will emerge from the public screenings held at packed
cinemas all over downtown Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 19th Toronto festival in a row,'' said Amir Malin,
chairman of Artisan Entertainment. ``I love Toronto as a town. I
love the Toronto audiences, who have a great affinity for films,
both ones that are artistically oriented and ones that are more
commercially oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto festival has always served at least two functions _
a place where distributors can unveil releases before an
appreciative audience (as well as the largest annual concentration
of North American entertainment journalists) and a market where
producers and directors can try to interest distributors in buying
the rights to their films.
</P>
<P>
   ``Toronto has always been the best launching pad for a movie of
any festival in the world,'' said Tom Bernard, co-president of Sony
Pictures Classics, which has seven films in Toronto this year.
``It's like a big press junket that the newspapers have paid for
themselves. So we can bring in our talent, screen our movies with
very favorable audiences and make the talent available for
newspapers all over North America. The Sundance festival is more of
an industry audience. The New York festival is much more, well,
they're patrons of the arts, not your mainstream filmgoer. But the
Toronto audience is real moviegoers. They get every nuance, and
they love movies.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If the festival has changed in recent years, as many believe,
perhaps it has become more important as a launching site and
somewhat less important as a film market.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has less to do with the festival than with the ebbs and
flows of the movie business,'' Malin said. ``I can remember going
into Toronto and having five or six different films that everyone
would be bidding on. Now there is less and less product that is
available in a festival context, because there is a tendency when
there is a good project around for one of us to pre-buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees. Tom Ortenberg and Mark Urman, co-presidents
of Lions Gate Films, said they had continued to have success
picking up films in Toronto in recent years (``The Big Kahuna''
last year, ``The Red Violin'' the year before) and hoped to buy
more this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always go there with an eye toward obtaining important
titles for our lineup,'' Urman said. ``I think there are certainly
a number of prospective acquisitions there this year, including
many that will be seen for the very first time by anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   If there has been a shift in the festival, Ortenberg said, it
has been to keep getting bigger _ not just in the number of films,
but in their scope and in the swirl of events that surround the
screenings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's always represented such an interesting blend of
the biggest of Hollywood and the most obscure of international
films and everything in between,'' he said. ``Most of the other
festivals have an imported audience, but here you have a major
metropolis that just gives itself over to the festival in a way
that is really unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   Urman described it this way: ``With the New York Film Festival,
if you veer two blocks away from Lincoln Center, you don't even
know it's going on. But when you get off the plane in Toronto,
you're bombarded. You can't escape it; it's omnipresent.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
