<SLUG> BC-SERKIN-MUSIC-$ADV10-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER SERKIN MIXES THE NEW WITH THE NEARLY NEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, September 10)  
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Peter Serkin has never been an ordinary virtuoso. His deep
concern with the music of living composers has brought him to work
more than most solo pianists in collaborative contexts (his modest
demeanor has surely helped here) and encouraged him to be
unconventional in his programming. He is more likely to be found
playing the piano part in Schoenberg's ``Pierrot Lunaire'' than
that in a Rachmaninoff concerto, and any recital of his will
probably include at least one contemporary piece.
</P>
<P>
   So he has all the qualities Judith Arron, the executive and
artistic director of Carnegie Hall until her death in 1998, was
looking for when she set about inviting a few musicians to imagine
coherent sequences of concerts that they and others would give at
the hall around the time of the new millennium. Last season
Maurizio Pollini, Pierre Boulez and Daniel Barenboim presented
their extensive Perspectives series; now (along with second seasons
of Perspectives from Pollini and Barenboim) comes Serkin's turn, in
a more compact group of concerts to take place in March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking recently at his summer home near Tanglewood in the
Berkshire Hills of Massachusetts, Serkin, 53 and a son of the
revered pianist Rudolf Serkin, recalled how Arron had worded her
invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``She spoke about making music,'' he said. ``When I hear that
phrase I immediately think of composers first, and so I decided I
would have some very new music, with older music around that. At
first the series was going to be much larger. As it's turned out,
there are just four concerts, and in all of them the repertory
begins in the 20th century. That was something that just happened,
but I'm very pleased about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerts, utterly characteristic of Serkin's musical
interests, include late works by Stravinsky, a little Schoenberg
and Webern, and pieces by Stefan Wolpe and Toru Takemitsu to bring
the story forward to music by five living composers: Charles
Wuorinen, Peter Lieberson, Oliver Knussen, Alexander Goehr and
George Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charles Wuorinen once said to me that a program ought to
include a work by an old master, a work by a 20th-century master, a
work by an older living composer and a work by a young composer,''
Serkin said. ``I've just left out the first category, though I
would also have liked to include pieces by younger composers than I
have.''
</P>
<P>
   The music by younger composers was one casualty of the
curtailment of the series for financial reasons. Another was
Olivier Messiaen, the most conspicuous absentee among recent
composers with whom Serkin has been most closely associated. He
wanted at one stage to include a big Messiaen piece: probably
``From the Canyons to the Stars,'' which he played this summer at
the Lincoln Center Festival. But finally, there was no room.
</P>
<P>
   Any limitation, though, is more than balanced by the opportunity
to hear the selected composers in depth. Wuorinen is represented in
three of the four programs, by an orchestral piece, a chamber
composition (his Horn Trio) and a set of songs (to words by James
Fenton, the librettist of his forthcoming work for the New York
City Opera). Knussen, Goehr and Lieberson all appear in two
programs each.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to let the audience get familiarized with these
composers,'' Serkin said. ``I hoped people would come and hear one
new piece, and be intrigued, and want to hear more. Then the older
music fits around the newer, in a way. Stravinsky connects with
Charles Wuorinen. Schoenberg and Webern were very important to
Alexander Goehr.''
</P>
<P>
   All four concerts will feature the London Sinfonietta, conducted
by Knussen, a longtime friend and colleague of Serkin's. The first
two programs will occupy the main auditorium at Carnegie Hall and
will each include an orchestral piece by Takemitsu and a pair of
late Stravinsky works.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember going to the first New York performances of some of
the late Stravinsky pieces, with him conducting,'' Serkin said, ``
`Threni' in particular. The climaxes and the energy in the rhythm
were unforgettable. But still the music hasn't caught on with the
public somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   These performances should help. Knussen is a marvelous
Stravinsky performer, and in ``Movements'' he will be joined by
Serkin at the piano, as in a forthcoming Deutsche Grammophon
recording. Also to be heard are the Variations, the compact
biblical fable ``The Flood'' and ``Requiem Canticles.''
</P>
<P>
   All four of these works date from Stravinsky's last creative
decade, before he became too ill to compose, at the end of the
1960s. All are brilliant examples of the composer's capacity to
learn from much younger composers _ Boulez, Krzysztof Penderecki _
and still remain, in every fizzing measure, himself. ``Movements''
is a compressed piano concerto bursting with life and invention.
``Requiem Canticles,'' Stravinsky's last major work, is an open
stare into the eyes of death.
</P>
<P>
   The danger might be that these supreme pieces, which seem to
become ever more crucial as time goes on, would shrivel any other
music of the last 50 years placed near them. But Serkin appears to
have guarded against that in his judicious choices. The two
Stravinsky-centered programs will include, besides their delicate
Takemitsu works, highly colorful pieces by Knussen (``The Way to
Castle Yonder''), Wuorinen (his recent ``Symphony Seven'') and
Lieberson (``Red Garuda''). Here, too, will come the taste of
Schoenberg: his graphic ``Accompaniment to a Film Scene.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Red Garuda,'' in which a giant bird of Hindu and Buddhist
legend is portrayed with flexing metal feathers and a sonorous
beating of wings, is the second of Lieberson's two piano concertos
and something like the eighth work he has written for Serkin, who
played it last season at its Boston Symphony premiere and then at
the Tanglewood Festival this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like it very much,'' he said. ``Of course, it's entirely
different from the first concerto, which was so wonderfully
unreasonable. This one is free of frivolous extra decoration, very
straightforward, with well-chosen notes.'' Yet the piece is also
brilliant and clear, and in those ways not so distant from another
picture of a mythic avian, Stravinsky's ``Firebird.''
</P>
<P>
   The other two concerts will take place in Weill Recital Hall,
and here newly commissioned pieces _ by Goehr and, again, Lieberson
_ will be presented. Both are piano quintets, which Serkin will
play with the Orion String Quartet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The piano quintet is, I think, a wonderful medium but not much
used these days,'' he said. ``Alexander Goehr's piece is already
written. It's a big work, in three movements, lasting half an hour,
and it's extremely clear, lean. It has a lightness that's very rare
in the piano quintet. I asked him if I could have it a year ahead,
because I wanted to get to know it thoroughly. For me that means,
first of all, getting to know the whole piece, approaching it as if
I were a composer or a conductor studying it. After that I start to
learn my part. Right now I'm looking forward to working on it with
the quartet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, there are also times when you have to work more
quickly. I remember one time when I was in Tokyo with Oliver
Knussen, and he was writing `Prayer Bell Sketch' for me, faxing it
a few measures at a time from his hotel to mine. The ending I got
only on the morning of the performance. So that was kind of fun, an
adventure. But whether I have a long time to prepare or a little
doesn't really matter. The quality of the work is much more
important, and I'm just glad these composers can write these pieces
at all.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
 &QL; 
</P>
<P>
   Serkin's enthusiasm for his chosen composers is so evident in
how he speaks _ just as it is in how he performs _ that the obvious
question is whether he has ever composed music himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I've tried to put notes and rhythms on paper,'' he said.
``When I was young, I composed quite a bit. My father was very
critical. He told me how Schoenberg had said you couldn't compose
until you knew all the Haydn quartets. So I got to know all the
Haydn quartets. But my love is for music. I love to listen to
music, and did from an early age. And at that time I was already
studying the piano seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   So when did he decide he was going to be a concert pianist?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's happened yet,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile the listening goes on. ``Nowadays I often listen to
the radio,'' Serkin said. ``I like the unexpected. I enjoy
listening to recordings of new music, and I've been listening to
some older recordings of Otto Klemperer: recordings from the Kroll
Opera in 1927, when he has the music on fire. I always loved
Klemperer particularly. I heard him rehearse and perform. Just
observing him provided great lessons in music.''
</P>
<P>
   Other musicians he remembers with special intensity include the
violinist Alexander Schneider, the flutist Marcel Moyse, the
pianist Mieczyslaw Horszowski and the cellist and conductor Pablo
Casals, all of whom he heard in his father's company at the
Marlboro Music Festival in Vermont.
</P>
<P>
   Relationships with composers he has made for himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``With Toru Takemitsu I had a close friendship,'' he said.
``When I played a piece for him, he didn't make a lot of comments.
He seemed curious about what the possibilities might be from a
performer's point of view. He was very open-minded. Sometimes he
would just sit at the piano and play pop songs, including some with
his own texts, but always with that gracefulness of his. I'd got
interested in the music of his that was a lot more wild _ pieces
like `Arc,' for piano and orchestra _ but then I started to
appreciate the sweetness of his later music, the things that were
so fastidiously and beautifully realized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stefan Wolpe I met at a party after one of Stravinsky's
concerts. What he said was very poetic, but he was already ill. I
never played for him, though I did play for Irma Wolpe, his second
wife, who had some of his manuscripts, often with a lot more
indications than there are in the published scores.''
</P>
<P>
   A fair amount of Wolpe has come out on record lately, but in the
concert hall his music is as rare as late Stravinsky. The reasons
are similar: the unfamiliarity of the music to performers, and
therefore the amount of rehearsal time required. But the vividness
locked up in this music is similar, too.
</P>
<P>
   Serkin recalled coaching a group at Tanglewood in Wolpe's
``Piece in Two Parts.'' ``We rehearsed for 75 hours,'' he said,
``and then the piece became electric.''
</P>
<P>
   In his recitals and solo recordings, Serkin has been a great
exponent of both Wolpe and Takemitsu, but in these concerts he will
be in his favorite role of listener, hearing Knussen conduct
Takemitsu's ``Green'' and ``How Slow the Wind,'' and hearing the
Orion String Quartet and the London Sinfonietta play some of
Wolpe's caustic, fantastical chamber pieces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think it so important that I play all the time,'' he
said. ``And I didn't have any specific plan in assembling the
programs. I'm not really conceptual. I just tried to think of works
that will sound well together.''(BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
