<HEADLINE>
INVESTORS BAIL OUT OF TECHNOLOGY AND SEMICONDUCTORS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT D. HERSHEY Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Investors bailed out of semiconductor stocks again
Wednesday, driving the Nasdaq composite index, which rallied 11.7
percent last month, to its second consecutive decline and its
biggest since late July.
</P>
<P>
   This time, the main instigator of the technology fall appeared
to be Micron Technology, which slumped $9.50, to $68.75, on the New
York Stock Exchange, after its rating was cut by Donaldson, Lufkin
&AMP; Jenrette. Intel played a similar role on Tuesday and fell an
additional $3.55 Wednesday, to $65.50, on the Nasdaq.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stocks are being downgraded, making people nervous, worried
about'' price-to-earnings ratios, said Mayer Offman, the chief
trading officer at Carlin Equities. ``They're in sell mode,'' he
added, predicting this would persist for a few more days before the
market rebounded.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq lost 129.84 points, or 3.13 percent, to 4,013.34,
finishing at the session's low for the second consecutive day,
suggesting to some that more selling remained to be done. The index
also slipped back into negative territory for the year, down 1.38
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other markets fared better, largely because strength in a
handful of financial stocks and in oil shares partly offset
weakness in technology and in drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 14.83 points, or
about 1 percent, to 1,492.25. Advancing issues, however, outpaced
declining ones by a sizable margin, 286 to 194.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average, meanwhile, rode another big
gain in J.P. Morgan to an advance of 50.03 points, or 0.44 percent,
to 11,310.64. Morgan jumped $7.81, to $167.75, accounting for
nearly all of the Dow's rise, on speculation that it is to be
acquired by Deutsche Bank.
</P>
<P>
   But semiconductors and their ilk grabbed much of the attention
as the Philadelphia Semiconductor Index dropped 5.71 percent,
cutting its gain so far this year to just above 50 percent. Among
the other big losers were Applied Micro Circuits, down $10.77, to
$179.05; PMC-Sierra down $16.58, to $217.05; and Xilinx down $7.13,
to $81.94.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what to make of Nasdaq,'' said Donna Van Vlack,
head trader at Brandywine Asset Management. ``Is this backing and
filling or the beginning or real decay?''
</P>
<P>
   This week's decline of 220.99 points was the severest since a
July 26-28 swoon of 366.57 points that preceded the August rally.
Wednesday's volume swelled to 1.76 billion shares from 1.60 billion
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Associates First Capital was the other major financial standout
Wednesday, leaping $10.50, to $38.50, on word that Citigroup was
buying it for $31.1 billion in stock. Citigroup fell $3.02, to
$54.92.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, H.J. Heinz fell $1.75, to $35.44, after the company
warned that profits in the current quarter would fall short of
expectations.
</P>
<P>
   With prescription coverage increasingly a focus of election
debate, drug stocks sank further, with Merck, downgraded by Banc of
America Securities on Tuesday, down $2.19, to $65.888, and Eli
Lilly, Bristol-Myers and American Home Products all down $2 or
more.
</P>
<P>
   On the New York Stock Exchange there were 1,620 stocks that rose
compared with 1,255 that fell, with 167 stocks making new 52-week
highs and 32 making new lows. Volume climbed about 20 percent from
Tuesday's pace to a more normal 998 million shares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
