<HEADLINE>
LA SCALA BIDS ADDIO TO A FAVORITE HAUNT OF CATCALLS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ELISABETTA POVOLEDO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ These days the real drama at La Scala in Milan is taking
place in the auditorium and not onstage. When the season starts up
again with Puccini's ``Boheme'' on Tuesday, the 200 standing-room
places of the first and second galleries will no longer be
occupied. This is tragic news for its habitual dwellers, the feared
and respected ``loggionisti,'' the ardent opera buffs who sit or
stand in the galleries and are said to dictate the failure or
success of a performer, a conductor or even an opera at the
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Last week administrators at La Scala announced that having
people stand in the two galleries did not conform to fire
regulations, and so standing-room tickets, which cost about $5,
would no longer be sold. They had been so prized that people stood
in line for hours for them. Administrators did promise that the
galleries would be restructured to conform to fire regulations as
part of the theater's general overhaul, which is expected to begin
at the end of next year. Until then, opera lovers will have to pay
$12 to $150 (what tickets usually sell for) and just sit tight.
</P>
<P>
   La Scala was built in 1776 by Empress Maria Theresa of Austria
to replace an earlier building that had burned down. Nearly all of
the world's greatest opera singers have performed there over the
years, and many great operas have had their world premieres there,
including Verdi's ``Nabucco,'' ``Falstaff'' and ``Otello'' and
Bellini's ``Norma.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike a flop on Broadway, failure at La Scala does not
necessarily mean the disappearance of a work. The world premiere of
Puccini's ``Madama Butterfly'' at La Scala in 1904, for example,
was a disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the lapses in judgment, many agree that the power to
make or break the reputation of performers, conductors and operas
comes from the loggionisti, who greeted the decision to cut the
standing-room places with dismay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is very unpleasant because we will lose a traditionally
passionate public that truly loves opera, lives for opera and will
line up for tickets for hours, making huge sacrifices just to see a
performance,'' said Giuseppe Castagnetti, president of Gli Amici
del Loggione, a group of 2,000 opera aficionados who occupy most of
the seats in the balconies. ``A theater is more than just its
conductors and the works that are presented in it, but also its
public.''
</P>
<P>
   At La Scala the public usually means the loggionisti. He said
that the opera house's decision was even more serious coming just
before the start of its millennium season, which will feature 11
works by Verdi, starting with ``Il Trovatore'' on Dec. 7 and for
which tickets will be even more in demand than usual.
</P>
<P>
   The loggionisti, whose legendary fanaticism has more than once
been compared to that of Italy's soccer fans, recoil at being
considered a claque of people who for money or free tickets or
simply out of passion band together to applaud or deride a
performance.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, they pride themselves on their familiarity with libretti
and scores, and part of the mandate of Gli Amici del Loggione is to
hold regular conferences and two or three-day workshops before
every new La Scala offering. Such intimate knowledge of the music
tends to breed contempt of less-than-perfect performances. Some say
that Luciano Pavarotti has refused to sing again at La Scala since
he was booed in 1992 by the loggionisti during his first
performance of Verdi's ``Don Carlo.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago the American soprano Renee Fleming was booed
repeatedly when she sang the lead in a summer production of
Donizetti's ``Lucrezia Borgia.'' Even emerging singers are not
spared. ``For a young singer, performing in front of the
loggionisti is like coming into hell,'' said a La Scala employee
who asked not be named. ``Knowing there are people who can destroy
you listening in the gallery _ well, for the singers it feels a lot
like going to the front in the middle of a battle.''
</P>
<P>
   The loggionisti defend their right to speak out (or make
catcalls).
</P>
<P>
   One 30-year veteran of La Scala who was more than once the
target of the loggione's disapproval said she was nonetheless sorry
to see the standing-room places go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the loggionisti because I have received the warmest
demonstrations of approval from them,'' said the mezzo-soprano
Fiorenza Cossotto, who made her singing debut at La Scala in
Poulenc's ``Dialogues des Carmelites'' in 1957. ``At the same time
no one wants to be reprimanded or reproved, it makes an artist very
nervous,'' she said. Cossotti said she had been contested ``even
when I didn't deserve it but I had to put up with it.'' Castagnetti
put it this way: ``You either have more amorphous theaters where
the public does not participate, like the Met, where I have heard
some horrible performances without the public saying anything, or
you have La Scala, which prides itself in being competent.''
</P>
<P>
   Though today one is more likely to hear someone on the street
singing Janet Jackson's latest song than a Verdi aria (as was
common in the second half of the 19th century), Italians are still
proud of their rich opera heritage.
</P>
<P>
   The imminent demise of the standing-room clique made the front
pages of many Italian newspapers and prompted earnest editorials.
In the Rome-based paper Il Messaggero, the journalist Rita Sala
made a passionate appeal to La Scala's music director, Riccardo
Muti.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maestro Muti, do something,'' she pleaded. ``The Mediterranean
blood of Apulia and Naples that flows in your veins may have been
tempered by northern discipline, but it will certainly not accept
that the loggionisti be left outside the door. Protest, Maestro.''
</P>
</TEXT>
