<HEADLINE>
NEW GABRIEL CD ISN'T BAD, BUT ISN'T ALL HIS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By DAVE FERMAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Come! Gather the children and light the fires! Shut off the TV
and order a pizza! It's ... ohmigosh ... a ``new Peter Gabriel
CD!''
</P>
<P>
   Whoo and, naturally, hoo! Let the parades begin!
</P>
<P>
   Only, um, it's not.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after Gabriel's last studio CD _ the rather limp
``Us'' _ and 14 years since the landmark ``So,'' the wily former
lead singer of Genesis and hypertalented solo ``artiste'' has
released a soundtrack. Of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Only, it only has his name and the CD's title, ``OVO,'' on the
spine. And to confuse things even more, although it's readily
available in the stores, it comes only as a high-priced ($30.30 at
Borders bookstore) import.
</P>
<P>
   And to confuse things even more, those who plunk down that $30
or so _ which comes to about 50 cents per minute _ will find that
our Peter sings lead on only a few tracks, the majority of the
singing being done (softly and/or slowly) by the Cocteau Twins'
Elizabeth Fraser, Woodstock hero Richie Havens, Paul Buchanan and
Irishman Iarla O' Lionaird, of Afro Celt Sound System. Gabriel _ or
PG as he's known in the credits _ busies himself on everything from
guitar to synthesizers to string arrangements to piano.
</P>
<P>
   Got all that? OK, then. Penned by Gabriel, ``OVO'' (the name of
an industrial empire) is a soundtrack to a ``visual and musical
experience'' put on by London's Millennium Dome, the liner notes
say. It tells the story of one family moving from past to present
to future, and trying to fuse nature and technology along the way.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it works onstage, but the rather thin, vague story line
doesn't work. The upside is, this is not a bad CD, as long as
you're not expecting another ``Big Time'' or ``Sledgehammer,''
'cause believe me, you ain't gonna get 'em.
</P>
<P>
   What you do get is a mix of ambient, techno, Celtic (including a
genuine good ol' reel) a touch or three of Gabriel's own personal
brand of gospel, tons of different percussion instruments, violins,
synthesizers galore, and a rousing, 10-minute
let's-make-the-world-better finale, ``Make Tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   The CD has a fistful of interesting songs, from ``The Time of
the Turning (Reprise)/The Weaver's Reel'' to the soft ``Father,
Son'' (Gabriel on lead vocals) to ``Downside-Up,'' to that finale.
And on the whole, ``OVO'' will please many who are adventurous
listeners, with some ACCS and other world-beat/Celtic artists (and
plenty of Gabriel CDs) in their collections. Those wanting ``So
Part II'' need to hunker down and wait. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Ferman covers pop music for the Star-Telegram. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
.MDBU/ nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
