<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-BOXOFFICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BOX OFFICE LACKED BUZZ 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ In the end, the summer movie season was neither as
lucrative as it looked at its onset nor as disastrous as it
appeared at its midpoint, but what exactly was it?
</P>
<P>
   In raw numbers, the movie season that ran from Memorial Day to
Labor Day, traditionally Hollywood's most lucrative period,
generated $2.7 billion at the box office, about $200 million less
than last year's record. Eleven of the films released earned more
than $100 million each, and one or two others may eventually
surpass that mark.
</P>
<P>
   Not so bad, on the face of it, but there were some disquieting
details beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   While overall box office looked fairly strong, even in
comparison with last year's sizzling pace, that was partly because
of an increase in ticket prices. In fact, attendance at movies was
down significantly, by 9 to 15 percent, depending on what the
National Association of Theater Owners concludes was the summer's
average ticket price, said Paul Dergarabedian, chairman of
Exhibitor Relations, a Los Angeles company that monitors box office
performance.
</P>
<P>
   While there were just as many $100 million movies this summer as
last, there was only one $200 million movie (``M:I-2,'' the
season's biggest hit at $214 million), compared with three last
summer (``Star Wars: Episode 1 _ The Phantom Menace,'' ``Austin
Powers: The Spy Who Shagged Me'' and ``The Sixth Sense''). At the
same time, many movies that opened strongly this summer quickly
fell off.
</P>
<P>
   Most disturbing to many in the movie business was that people
just weren't talking about movies this summer. Last year, the
hottest topics of conversation and magazine covers were the new
``Star Wars'' prequel and the surprise success of ``The Sixth
Sense'' and ``The Blair Witch Project.'' This year, no movie seemed
to generate that kind of buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's attention was on other things,'' Dergarabedian said.
``Last summer, to be included in the discussion you had to go see
`Blair Witch' or ``Sixth Sense.' This year, you had to watch
`Survivor' on television to be part of what everyone was talking
about. There was nothing on the order of a cultural phenomenon,
which is what you need to keep attendance from falling flat or
dipping. General malaise sort of overtook the summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, some said, was that the summer of 1999 was
such an unusual one, kicked off by a frenzy over the ``Star Wars''
film and then powered by one major hit after another. It was
unfair, they said, to expect a subsequent summer to live up to
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summer of '99 was an extraordinary summer, and I think
that to use it as a benchmark is difficult,'' said Robert G.
Friedman, vice chairman of the Paramount Motion Picture Group.
``You need to look over the last three years and, when you do, that
tells you that the summer of 2000 was a very good summer, equal to
or even better than '97 and '98.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said he was not overly concerned about the attendance
drop. ``Our business is movie-driven,'' he said. ``It's not as
though people have gone to other forms of entertainment. It's not
as though we've lost them as future moviegoers. They've just
responded to the product that's been offered to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the summer movie season begins on Memorial Day,
but the trend in recent years has been to release big-budget,
summer-oriented films earlier and earlier. This year, for instance,
Ridley Scott's ``Gladiator,'' the summer's second-biggest hit at
$184 million, opened the first weekend in May, followed by Disney's
``Dinosaur'' ($136 million) in mid-May. Then came a record-breaking
Memorial Day weekend led by ``M:I-2'' and, shortly after, the
surprise success of Martin Lawrence's ``Big Momma's House'' ($116
million).
</P>
<P>
   After that, moviegoers seemed to get pickier, and it was not
until after a monthlong slump that the box office revived over the
Independence Day weekend, thanks in part to Wolfgang Peterson's
``Perfect Storm'' (at $178 million, the summer's third-biggest
hit). Other hits followed, like ``Scary Movie,'' a $19 million
spoof of teen-age slasher films that has earned nearly $150
million, and more expected successes like ``Nutty Professor 2: The
Klumps'' ($115 million) and ``X-Men'' ($153 million).
</P>
<P>
   By August, however, ticket sales had cooled again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom sort of fell out,'' Dergarabedian said. ``We ended
up the summer with 10 out of 15 weekends performing more poorly
than the same weekends last summer, and you just can't recover from
that.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem was that, except perhaps for ``Scary Movie,'' the
summer produced nothing like the kind of sleeper success enjoyed by
``Sixth Sense.'' Outside of a few films, notably Robert Zemeckis'
``What Lies Beneath'' (which has earned $137 million and is still
attracting audiences) and Clint Eastwood's ``Space Cowboys,'' the
summer releases did not seem to hold on at the box office week
after week, indicating that people were not telling friends to go
see them.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly disquieting to studios and theater owners is that
no movie coming out of the summer seems likely to run strongly into
September, as ``Sixth Sense'' did last year. With the Olympics
about to begin and few major releases in the immediate offing,
there are fears that it will not be until after the World Series
and the presidential election _ until November, that is, and the
release of the big holiday films _ that the box office will
recharge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's been a good summer, though obviously not a great
summer,'' said Jim Tharp, head of distribution for DreamWorks. ``I
think it always goes back to the movies. Now, we have more
theaters, more conveniently located, more up-to-date and nicer to
be in, so that would seem to indicate you'd get more attendance.
But we didn't. So the issue has to be the movies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
