<SLUG> BC-MP3-RULING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS MP3 . COM BROKE COPYRIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A federal judge in New York ruled Wednesday that MP3.com had
willfully infringed the copyrights of the Universal Music Group by
making its CDs available for play over the Internet and ordered the
online music site to pay damages that could total $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   In a much anticipated decision, US District Judge Jed S. Rakoff
said he wanted to send a strong warning to online music
distributors who ``may have a misconception that, because their
technology is somewhat novel, they are somehow immune from the
ordinary applications of laws of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to understand that the law's domain knows no such
limits,'' the judge added.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff set damages at $25,000 for each CD of Universal Music
Group, the world's biggest record company, it made available on the
site. The exact number of disks involved and the total award will
be decided during a hearing in November.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com, based in San Diego, said it would appeal the ruling.
The company had argued that it could be forced out business if
damages exceeded $500 per CD. Trading of MP3.com shares was halted
at $7.88.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff's ruling was another victory in the Old Economy's
campaign against the Internet community's attempts to redefine
intellectual property. Corporations that make music and movies
continue to wage war against new technologies that allow widespread
sharing of their content.
</P>
<P>
   In July, a federal judge in San Francisco issued an order that
could have shut down Napster Inc.'s music-sampling service. The
injunction is on hold pending an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent victories, the recording industry hasn't
shown signs of letting up the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Scour Inc., for example, was recently sued by both the Recording
Industry Association of America and the Motion Picture Association
of America. Backed by Hollywood agent Michael Ovitz, Scour hopes to
bring free music, movies, and pictures to the Internet public. But
the lawsuit is making potential investors nervous, said analyst
Eric Scheirer of Forrester Research.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can chalk that up to the chilling effect,'' Scheirer said.
``The content industry is still in the driver's seat _ even on the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Scheirer and other industry observers say they were surprised by
the tenor of Wednesday's ruling and concerned about its impact on
start-ups that want to change the way consumers buy and listen to
music.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Lemley, a professor of intellectual property law at the
University of California at Berkeley's law school, said the
recording industry has spent too much time in court and needs to
find its own way of distributing digital music.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't just make digital music go away by suing everyone
who's involved in it,'' Lemley said. ``The demand is too great.''
</P>
<P>
   In April Rakoff decided that MP3.com had infringed the
copyrights owned by Universal, a unit of Seagram Co. Ltd., and four
other big record labels. MP3.com settled with all but Universal,
taking a $150 million charge related to the lawsuits in its second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Attorneys for Universal had urged Rakoff to award Universal as
much as $450 million, claiming MP3.com had duplicated as many as
10,000 of the firm's CDs. MP3.com says the number is closer to
4,700.
</P>
<P>
   An attorney for MP3.com said earlier this week that a huge
penalty would be a ``death sentence'' to the company. But the
judge, who wanted to sent a strong message to the Internet
community, warned that the fine could start at $118 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential for huge profits in the rapidly expanding world
of the Internet is the lure that tempted an otherwise generally
responsible company like MP3.com to break the law,'' Rakoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone believes MP3.com will be flattened by a huge fine.
Jon Zittrain, a cyberlaw professor at Harvard Law School, noted
that the company raised $344 million in an initial public offering
in July of 1999. Wednesday, MP3.com had a market capitalization of
$584 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't necessarily break the bank,'' Zittrain said. ``But
you lose momentum. . . . At best, it's a rollercoaster ride for
them that increases the pressure of accommodation (with the record
industry) of some kind.''
</P>
<P>
   The recording industry cheered Rakoff's ruling. ``This should
send a message that there are consequences when a business
recklessly disregards the copyright law,'' said Cary Sherman,
general counsel for the Recording Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Howard King, an attorney who represents Metallica in the music
group's battle against Napster, said the decision also bodes well
for his clients.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another judge enforcing the copyright laws,'' King said.
``No matter what the technology, our laws still respect the rights
of copyright owners.''
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com has said it will appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that everyone should have the right to listen to
the music they purchase, even if it's on the Internet,'' said
Michael Robertson, chairman and chief executive officer of MP3.com.
``While we respect the court, we disagree with the court's decision
and we look forward to taking our case to the Court of Appeals.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Wire service material was used to prepare this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
