<HEADER>
A4506 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-PET-HEALTH-SPAS-ART-2     09-06 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PET-HEALTH-SPAS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW PHYSICAL THERAPY CENTERS CATER TO 4-LEGGED CLIENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Va., Colo.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JULIE V. IOVINE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rocco arrived at Bonnie's K9 Swim Center in Manhattan
prancing with excitement, a bandana knotted around his thick furry
neck and metal wheels strapped to his withered hind legs. A
10-year-old German shepherd, Rocco had lymphoma last summer,
followed by a ruptured disk requiring emergency surgery the week
before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Lenny Addamo, Rocco's owner, lowered the 90-pound dog into the
waiting arms of Jodi Richard, who was submerged to her shoulders in
87-degree water and ready to right Rocco as he started to roll and
submerge. The pool's surface, lightly dusted with dog hair, boiled
around Rocco's flailing front paws as Richard, the owner of
Bonnie's K9, a new physical therapy center for dogs, held onto his
hips.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, physical therapy was mainly for people. Pets,
even when valued as guardians and companions, received limited
medical care and were often euthanized when they were deemed too
old, too infirm or too expensive to treat. Today, as pets become
more prized, and a booming economy creates more discretionary
income, pet care might include a $400 customized weight-loss
program at a health spa.
</P>
<P>
   While the yellow pages bulge with listings for fancy poodle
parlors, the latest pet spas are beginning to offer the same
therapies available to humans _ from electro-stimulation to
underwater treadmills. With fees kept low to attract all comers (an
average $15 an hour for massage or swim therapy), these new therapy
centers are only beginning to meet the demand of pet owners eager
not only to indulge but also to save their animals.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the new breed of pet spa is Bonnie's K9, which opened
last month in Chelsea and offers swim therapy, massage and
acupuncture as well as homemade organic dog food. Richard invested
about $500,000 (with contributions from her husband, Dwight
Merriman, co-founder of DoubleClick, an Internet advertising firm)
to open the 2,000-square-foot center. It is named after their
German shepherd, which they rescued from a puppy mill. Bonnie had
been caged for the first years of her life for breeding and, as a
result, is paralyzed in her hind legs.
</P>
<P>
   Richard, who is earning a veterinarian technician degree (the
equivalent of a nursing degree), has two full-time employees and
works most nights until 8. One evening last week, as she handed her
panting client a natural dog biscuit, and ate one too, she said,
``Some people think I'm crazy to be doing this,'' but ``it's
extremely rewarding.''
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians refer their clients to Richard, who treats dogs
suffering from hip dysplasia, degenerative spinal disorders, cancer
and other diseases resulting from dogs living longer than in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were overwhelmed when we found out that Rocco was probably
never going to walk again,'' said Dr. Dina Addamo, a resident
doctor at Mount Sinai in Manhattan who had to work extra night
shifts to help pay over $10,000 for Rocco's cancer treatments.
``We'd do practically anything. He deserves it,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Operating on a much larger scale, on farmland 50 miles east of
Pittsburgh, is the Baden-Baden of New Age pet spas, the sprawling
Cozy Inn Pet Resort and Spa. Here, one afternoon last week, workers
led a 1-year-old black Labrador runt named Zoey in for a
therapeutic swim session. Unable to stand because of a congenital
affliction caused by overbreeding, Zoey is shaky as a newborn foal.
But once in the pool, she takes off like the swimmer she's supposed
to be. Afterward an attendant wraps Zoey in a clean towel and
returns her to a cage with a private door flap leading into the
yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one time you took a dog with problems out and shot it,''
said Carol Boerio-Croft, the founder of Cozy Inn. ``Now dogs have a
much better lifestyle. They're not disposable anymore; they're part
of the household.''
</P>
<P>
   Boerio-Croft, whose husband, Dr. Henry L. Croft Jr., is a
veterinarian, was among the first to sense a growth industry in the
making. Fourteen years ago she created a boarding facility for pets
and offered luxury amenities like facial massages and off-leash
nature walks. Three years ago, she added the Mozart wing, a
step-down facility for postsurgical and geriatric dogs named after
her terrier mutt, which died of cancer. The $2 million complex is
steeped in pet-theme memorabilia, from plaster dog statues on the
lawn to ``101 Dalmatian'' clocks. There are two indoor pools: one
is shaped like a bone; the other is a whirlpool with the shape of a
dog paw.
</P>
<P>
   Business is brisk, with about 250 dogs on the grounds every day.
Rates average $16 a day, generating enough income to allow the
Crofts and an investor to underwrite a $3 million center in
Pittsburgh, which is to open this winter. They say they hope it
will serve as a prototype for a pet-care chain offering everything
from vacation centers to education and spa treatments.
</P>
<P>
   In Annandale, Va., Stan Marks, a real estate broker, was
inspired to build a rehabilitation clinic for small animals after
he was unable to find the care he wanted for his 14-year old German
shepherd, who died four months ago from degenerative bone disease.
The Royal Treatment center, which is opening in six months, will
offer conditioning and weight-loss programs, hydrotherapy and
range-of-motion exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``People today are willing to go any distance for their pets,''
said Marks, who spent over $5,000 on hip replacements for his dog.
``I'm the perfect example. And there are a lot of `me's' out
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Although physical therapy has been used on thoroughbred
racehorses and greyhounds for at least 20 years, it is new to the
world of pets. Determined to improve and prolong the lives of their
animals, the aging Me Generation has become the Me and My
Four-Legged Companion Generation.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are demanding these services,'' said Marks, who is
already planning to open a second center next year in suburban
Washington. ``It's a whole new area of veterinary medicine, and it
can't move fast enough to meet the demand.''
</P>
<P>
   A survey last year of 1,200 pet owners by the American Animal
Hospital Association found that pet owners were more likely to take
their animals to the veterinarian on a regular basis than they were
to see a doctor themselves. (Eighty-four percent of the respondents
called themselves Mom or Dad when talking to their pets.)
</P>
<P>
   The urge to devote special care, from expensive prepared foods
to lifesaving surgery, focuses more on dogs than on cats, perhaps
because cats live longer (16 years on average). Large dogs are
considered old when they are 8. Modern medicine and an insistent
clientele, has stretched that natural limit.
</P>
<P>
   Shelly and Jack Galati of Riverdale, N.Y., have a 15{-year-old
Labrador named Sydney that has been undergoing acupuncture for
three years. When Sydney recently started falling on slippery
floors, they started looking for additional treatments. ``We know
she's old, and we don't expect her to get better,'' Galati said.
``We just want to keep her as she is.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Veterinarians are traditionally accustomed more to emergency
medical care (``Help! My dog ate the remote control!'') than to
prevention and wellness care. The American Veterinary Medical
Association has been cautious in embracing treatments like
acupuncture and physical therapy, although it agrees that there is
anecdotal evidence supporting their benefits. The veterinarians who
recommend physical therapies say that animals tend to respond to
treatment better than humans because they don't resist their
exercise regimes and they have a higher threshold of pain, making
it possible to rebuild muscular tissue more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the newness of the business, there are no degree
programs or licensing requirements for pet physical therapists.
``It's a bit of a problem,'' said Dr. Robert B. Parker, head of the
surgery department at the Animal Medical Center, a highly regarded
animal hospital in Manhattan. ``It involves a lot of issues on the
front lines of what should be done by a licensed veterinarian and
what a lay person should do.''
</P>
<P>
   The insurance industry, which has been curbing reimbursements
for physical therapy for humans, has inadvertently supplied a
talent pool. Two years ago, the American Physical Therapist
Association started helping members explore animal physical therapy
``in part because insurance is not reimbursing people for continued
physical therapy,'' said Cheryl Riegger-Krugh, who runs the
organization's special interest group on animal physical therapy.
She explained that while people without insurance coverage tend to
drop out of treatment, people with pets pay for it with their own
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Boerio-Croft, the owner of Cozy Inn, has gone the limit herself.
She spent $85,000 to fly her Irish wolfhound to Colorado for a bone
marrow transplant with limited results. ``I bought him 8 months,''
she said, ``And I was happy to get it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2131EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0376 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4508 &Cx1f; tad-z
b i BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-0907-     09-06 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-MIDEAST-0907-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN: writes thru to update with Barak, Arafat meetings
 &HT;    CLINTON REVIVES PEACE TALKS IN MEETINGS WITH ARAFAT, BARAK
 &HT;    With CLINTON-UN-0907.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Fanning the embers of the smoldering Mideast peace
process, President Clinton huddled Wednesday night with Israeli and
Palestinian leaders, reviving negotiations that collapsed in July.
</P>
<P>
   With Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak and Palestinian Authority
President Yasser Arafat engaged once again in diplomacy, White
House spokesman Joseph Lockhart said a Sept. 13 deadline for
agreement was likely to be missed. The danger of a breakdown over
that date, however, appears to have abated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that both sides, and the United States included, are
focused on getting an agreement and finding a way to bridge the
differences,'' Lockhart said, ``and are not particularly focused on
a calender date in next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart made clear that the meetings produced no breakthroughs
_ none had been expected _ and he said the leaders had scheduled no
further meetings, though he didn't rule out additional talks as
early as Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process has not broken down,'' Lockhart said. ``It's
ongoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's meetings were Clinton's first with Arafat and Barak
since his efforts to press them toward a peace accord collapsed in
July at the Camp David presidential retreat in western Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   There, two weeks of summitry fell apart over the issue of
Jerusalem, a city holy to Christians, Jews and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Clinton warned that time was slipping away on
the prospects for a near-term Mideast peace accord. Barak is in a
precarious political position at home and could face a
parliamentary vote as early as the end of October on whether to
dissolve his government.
</P>
<P>
   In a bid for urgency, Clinton appealed for global backing for
his efforts to craft a peace treaty acceptable to Barak, Arafat and
their respective peoples.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need your support now, more than ever, to take the hard
risks for peace,'' Clinton said in remarks to the United Nations
General Assembly, the body's annual conference of international
leaders. ``They have the chance to do it. But, like all life's
chances, it is fleeting and about to pass. There is not a moment to
lose.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, Clinton met for an hour with Barak in a
Manhattan luxury hotel. Following that, Clinton met for an hour and
40 minutes with Arafat, Lockhart told reporters traveling with the
president.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Clinton met into the evening with Jordan's King
Abdullah then, separately, with Crown Prince Abdallah of Saudi
Arabia, to discuss ways the Arab world might support the peace
process and to hear their ideas on a possible path forward.
</P>
<P>
   In their Wednesday meetings, Clinton and the two Mideast leaders
_ Arafat and Barak _ discussed new possibilities for bridging their
gaps over the future of disputed portions of Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president and the two leaders went through a number of
ideas,'' Lockhart said, though declining to be specific.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has demanded full sovereignty over East Jerusalem, the
center of Palestinian social, cultural and economic life.
</P>
<P>
   The territory, though, which Israel seized in the 1967
Arab-Israeli war, contains sites holy to all three major religions
and holds deep historic meaning to Israelis and Palestinians alike.
</P>
<P>
   Barak offered Arafat partial sovereignty over the disputed land,
but Arafat rejected that formulation.
</P>
<P>
   In their own U.N. remarks on Wednesday, Arafat and Barak sent
mixed signals.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat hinted, for instance, that he was willing to drop his
threat to declare Palestinian statehood on Sept. 13, so long as he
sees a chance for progress on the diplomatic front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of our friends and brothers consider that reaching a
final settlement requires allowing an additional chance for these
efforts to succeed,'' Arafat said, adding that he would take up
that prospect at a meeting of the Palestinian Central Council this
weekend in Gaza.
</P>
<P>
   In the same speech, though, Arafat blasted Israel, casting the
Jewish state as the villain in the oft-tortured peace process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are confronting Israeli attempts at the Judaization of
Jerusalem,'' said Arafat, ``land confiscation, the building of
illegal Israeli settlements, the siege imposed upon Bethlehem, and
the lack of honest and accurate implementation of the agreements
signed by Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat went on to characterize Jerusalem as ``the cradle of
Christ and the site of Prophet Mohammed's ascension to heaven,''
leaving out the city's even longer history as the center of Judaism
and accusing Israel of attempts at ``monopolizing'' the ancient
city.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, for his part, stressed the 3,000-year history of Judaism
in Jerusalem, quoting Old Testament scripture, even as he called
upon Arafat to embrace compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerusalem, the eternal capital of Israel, now calls for a
peace of honor, of courage and of brotherhood,'' said Barak.
</P>
<P>
   ``We recognize that Jerusalem is also sacred to Muslims and
Christians the world over and cherished by our Palestinian
neighbors,'' he said. ``A true peace will reflect all these bonds.
Jerusalem will remain united and open to all who love her.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Deans' E-mail address is: bobdeans(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
