<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4510 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-LIST-MAGAZINE-ART-2TA     09-06 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIST-MAGAZINE-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE CONDENSED INTO A LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: 2nd take is a 1270-word Q&AMP;A-style interview with the
founders of List magazine.) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Reading the telephone book used to be a joke until
List magazine, also exclusively a collection of lists, appeared in
June. Four thousand copies later (at $15 a pop), the new magazine's
last laugh is the next item on the editors' list: Issue 2 arrives
in October. The white pages, at least, are free.
</P>
<P>
   Detractors and admirers _ along with List's creative directors,
Lisa Ano, 28, and Serge Becker, 39, who are designers by background
_ like to think of List as a kind of literary Armageddon: the
arguments of the traditional magazine piece stripped to a corrosive
litany of disinterested facts. It might be a perfect model for the
new popular magazine: you can't do anything but skim it.
</P>
<P>
   In 40 lists, List/01 includes topics that are better listed than
explained (supermodel day rates), topics explained by their listing
(international illiteracy rates) and topics explained in a list
(death row inmates' last meals: John Wayne Gacy ate four courses of
fried foods, with fresh strawberries for dessert).
</P>
<P>
   Ano and Becker create List at Can Resources, an architecture and
design company, where they work with Derek Sanders, 39, an
architect, on projects like the new Standard hotel in Los Angeles.
Ano, a graphic designer, previously assisted Tibor Kalman at M&AMP;Co.
</P>
<P>
   Becker, a restaurant and club entrepreneur _ List is his idea _
is a list maker from way back, as in guest lists and A-lists. He
helped create MK, Bowery Bar and Joe's Pub. With a resume that
lopes like a velvet rope, Becker understands the power of
exclusivity, from the FBI's 10 Most Wanted list to Tina Brown's
``Talk Magazine Launch'' Liberty Island party list: he published
both in List.
</P>
<P>
   Visited at its Chinatown offices, two flights above a sewing
shop, List previewed its next proudly engineered controversy _
List/02 _ an advertorial vehicle created instead as
``edvertisements.''
</P>
<P>
   The magazine will portray 12 personalities, like Bryce P.
Wilson, a music producer, and Lizzie Grubman, a publicist, in
visual lists or trademark litanies based on the brand-name products
they consume, excerpted from responses to a 138-item questionnaire
on items from art to underwear. Makers of the products listed will
be invited, the editors said, to sponsor the magazine by paying a
$3,500 fee for a more adlike depiction of the product. It is either
a bold sales call or a sly social comment. Becker, unsurprisingly,
said it was both _ a Trojan horse with viewing balconies. List/02
has to pay its way, or it's history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We Are All Lucky,'' a vertical list of Chinese characters left
by the last tenant, was the only sign on List's door.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Q: Name two things you used to do that you don't do anymore.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: Smoke cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: Smoke cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: Ever?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: Oh _ steal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: Oh! Me, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: Me, too!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: That's No. 1. Thank you. That was a major issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: Shoplifting _ big teen-age sport.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: Good consumers at an early age _ we had an eye.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why lists?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: It seemed pure. Very much of the moment. We have less
time right now. They're really easy to kind of glance at. What
about a magazine that condenses everything down to lists? You pick
it up, you check out one or two, you put it down. You pick it up
again. It dispenses with the articles concept.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did you come up with the lists?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: Calls, calls, calls.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: First, we made a list. (Laughter all around.) Blacklist,
wish list, A-list, to-do list. Then wordplays, like socialist,
capitalist. The idea was that it could be a very collaborative
magazine. You can't ask everybody to contribute an article, but you
can ask a lot of people to contribute a list. Lists can be very
boring, but then, a really good list is a really great snapshot
that really captures the moment. A little bit like the cover. (
Becker's 1-year-old daughter, Georgia, is pictured in the arms of
her mother, Jodie Patterson-Becker: the first item on their family
list.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is a magazine of lists with a paying readership a good or a
bad thing?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: I read The New Yorker. List doesn't replace a really
great researched long-form article. There's not that many great
ones written anyway. There's so much fluff in magazines. This is
cool information that's actually useful.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has an architectural office come to publish a magazine?
Is List really a design magazine?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: I studied communication design in Switzerland. My career
at that point was supposed to be advertising. I hated it. I came
here, got into nightclubs, started designing them.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why nightclubs?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: New York was the city of Studio 54. Clubs were a vital
part of the culture. It's changed. The moment has passed. The
people drawn from the creative world to clubs are focusing on
fields like the Internet. I started designing other places and got
into architecture. Derek and I worked together on the Mercer Hotel.
As you get older, you don't want to be in nightclubs anymore. I had
to create a day job for myself.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Design's such a trendy subject right now, from hotels to Web
sites. Is it is generation's new club scene?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: There's a glut almost.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: Design is fashion now. It spreads really fast, because
there's so much media that translate these ideas. From the time
it's a germ until it's some mass product in everybody's house,
everybody's mind, that time lag is so short. These things move like
viruses through the culture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: We're talking about something as simple as the radius
curve that you started to see.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: It started in furniture. Then it went into graphics. One
minute it's in Wallpaper _ the next minute it's at Urban
Outfitters. The next minute . . .
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: Centro-fly.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: I think our conversations are a little anti-design
sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: It's not just dealing with the form and the shapes of
things anymore. List is about pure content, and a lot of the design
work that we do is really a little bit like production design,
about scripting _ an environment idea that fits a particular
purpose, then creating a set for it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: The attempt is to get a little bit of longevity out of
design _ in creating a place that moves you. You go there, to feel
that. It's not a radius curve that you get tired of.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: We're going through such a transformation of our
information culture _ all these new technologies. They always bring
too much to you. When you first get a cell phone, you're constantly
on the stupid phone. Gradually, you realize, hey _ I can turn this
off. It's the same way with design now: how much design do we
really need? I like the new Jasper Morrison low-pad chair. Do I
need it? Is it exciting? Is it what I want to do with my life?
Absolutely, no.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: We're still in the infatuation phase with the technology.
You take like Frank Gehry, infatuated with creating shape with it.
It's still new. I think you'll get past that, into something more
content-driven.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's next then?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: Design becomes less dogmatic, less one style ruling all
and more niche, niche, niche. More people doing their own thing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do most of us, after 50 years of commercial television,
international advertising strategies and global brands, really have
our own identities to draw upon? Or will individual design just be
an assembly of prefabricated parts? A shoplifter's list?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: It's the theme of our next issue.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: How we construct personalities as consumers _ all the
consumer choices that people make.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: From clothes to water.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: The car they drive, the toothpaste they use. We tried to
look at our own lives: what we use, how we make decisions. Do you
ever ask yourself that?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: All the time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: All the time! (Laughter all around.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: When you look at the magazine, you'll think, ``Where are
the ads?'' The magazine is the ad. We won't have a single page of
real advertising, but companies will pay for our endorsement, when
we show their product, in a personality's profile.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: That doesn't seem particularly provocative, or new. Michael
Jordan wears Nikes _ we know that.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: But Jordan is paid to wear Nikes. The value of our
endorsement is different: it's true. Real people are saying they
really use the product. That's at least as valuable as an ad, to an
advertiser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it still possible to be in love?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: Yes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: Definitely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is anyone at the table in love?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: I am.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: No.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Name two people you admire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: Muhammad Ali and Rem Koolhaas.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: I have to say Rem. It's the first thing that came to my
mind. He doesn't make value judgments. He deals with a lot of what
we've been talking about. He embraces these changes that are
coming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: OK, that's one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: I'm totally blank. I can only think of my mother right
now.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: I'm trying to think of a person that I find inspiring, in
terms of helping people get past these doubts, all these daunting
changes that are constantly assaulting us, that can inspire you to
say, ``No it's not getting worse, it's getting better,'' and have
trust in that. I met Nelson Mandela, when he got out of jail and
came to New York. He had dinner at TriBeCa Grill. I was totally
blown away by his example, but then, I look at his country. Maybe
it isn't enough, the idea that one person can do it all.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is globalization a good or a bad thing?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: It's not good or bad _ it's just happening.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: We're becoming members of, not ethnic tribes, but
cultural tribes, that have their equivalent all around the globe.
When we travel, we travel within that world. You have your
equivalent of the scene that you have here in L.A. When you go to
London, you have your connectors that bring you into the same
world.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: Isn't that just portable consumer choices?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: It's a support network. I'm sure there are people that
arrive at great wisdom by not interacting at all.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM.)
</P>
<P>
   Q: What one thing would you change if you could change anything?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: I'd slow the world down _ just the pace that everything's
progressing at. That's the one thing that's anxiety ridden in me.
If I slowed it down, somehow, inside me, it would calm a lot of
stuff.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LISA: I want to be in love.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SERGE: Yeah?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   DEREK: Yeah.
</P>
</TEXT>
