<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRIT-U.S.-COUPLED-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX AND THE SITTING ROOM ON TWO CONTINENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER MASON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ ``I just hope I don't pick up a fake English accent,''
Candace Bushnell said, reaching for a glass of Champagne proffered
by a dapper butler on hand one evening to serve her and some 25
British and American guests cocktails and blinis laden with caviar.
The setting: Cranley Lodge, the London pied-a-terre of her English
boyfriend, Stephen Morris, where Bushnell now makes herself at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Like the main character in ``Single Process,'' a novella in her
new book, ``Four Blondes'' (Atlantic Monthly Press), Bushnell
appears to have found love at last with a suave gent after years of
exasperation with the dating game in New York. Since the couple
began cavorting romantically 15 months ago, Bushnell has been
sharing his home in London. Morris, a venture capitalist with a
taste for the high life, spends three months a year in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``London's like New York _ there's a lot of funny, fun girls
here,'' Bushnell said. One of them is Imogen Edwards-Jones, a
columnist for The Times of London. With a flourish, Edwards-Jones
entered Cranley Lodge clutching a copy of her own new book, ``My
Canape Hell.'' (``It's about a girl on a downward spiral in
celebrity hell London,'' she said.) The two women embraced with
theatrical effusiveness. For all the withering precision with which
she chronicles the glittering lives of semicelebrities, social
aspirants and moneyed folk, Bushnell, 41, appears to relish being
part of the world she makes seem so harrowing.
</P>
<P>
   Cranley Lodge, despite the grand name, is a tiny two-bedroom
house built in 1860 as a painting studio for an earl's wife.
Essentially a country cottage in Chelsea, in the middle of London,
the house is concealed behind a high brick wall that barely
diminishes the roar of passing double-decker buses.
</P>
<P>
   Morris appeared at the party in a conservative blue suit and tie
that looked incongruous in the silvery stage set designed for him
by Nicholas Haslam, the society decorator. ``I told Nicky I wanted
it to be like a Roman villa, then I pretty much left it to him,''
Morris said. Haslam gave him trompe l'oeil stone walls, plump sofas
and shimmering curtains. ``It's the stuff photographers' umbrellas
are made out of,'' Haslam said. ``It keeps in the heat in winter,
and it's terribly chic.''
</P>
<P>
   During the party _ where the eccentric assortment of guests
included Paul McKenna, a celebrity hypnotist; a bevy of rail-thin
blondes; and raffish bankers chuckling about plans to hit a
lap-dance joint later _ Haslam carried on decorating. With casual
aplomb, he whipped a small tube of gold paint out of his pocket and
proceeded to daub a scuffed fluted column.
</P>
<P>
   Although Haslam sought her opinion, Bushnell had limited input.
She doesn't do decor (even though her parents took her antiquing
almost every Sunday of her childhood, she said) but she makes an
effort to be spectacularly decorative. Bushnell greeted the guests
in a mohair micro-miniskirt with sequins, and glittery knee-high
boots by Jimmy Choo, enthusiastically inhaling Marlboro Lights and
shaking a professionally coiffed golden mane.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly for a chronicler of sexual mores in ``Four Blondes''
and her first book, ``Sex and the City,'' she invariably writes
next to the bed. ``So the only thing I asked for was a little tiny
desk in the bedroom, because that's where I work,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After years of struggling as a freelance writer for women's
magazines _ her career began improbably at Ladies' Home Journal and
Good Housekeeping _ she gained recognition five years ago as the
sex columnist for The New York Observer; lucrative book, television
and film contracts followed.
</P>
<P>
   She now flies business class and relishes shopping sprees (but
not in London. ``You find yourself buying a little pair of sweat
pants and it's like $200,'' she said). And she gives imaginative
gifts. For Christmas, she commissioned a painting from Lady Theresa
Chipman _ a painter who is the sister of the Duke of Rutland, as
well as the former lead singer in a rock band. Chipman is also an
ex-New York nightclubbing pal of Bushnell. The subject of the
painting? Morris. The painting is displayed in the Chelsea living
room.
</P>
<P>
   She seems tickled that her travels in the fast lane in New York
and London, including her nighttime peregrinations and even her sex
life, have become the subject of gossip columns on both sides of
the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an author is really the lowest level of celebrity,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but she has raised it to a high art with a series of
titillating publicity pictures that feature her seemingly infinite
legs and generous portions of honey-toned flesh. Currently, she is
working on a movie script for Universal Studios based on
``Platinum,'' the third novella in ``Four Blondes,'' about an
insecure American girl married to a European prince whose life _
and Cinderella fantasy _ starts to fall apart when she becomes
convinced that her husband is cheating on her.
</P>
<P>
   Bushnell says that Universal executives have been urging her to
make some characters seem more mature, sincere and to have them
exude noble intent. ``I was trying to do it, but I got stuck,''
Bushnell admitted. ``Then I realized, I don't do noble. I do
shallow and superficial.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, she may find material lacking in London, which she
distinguishes from New York as a place where one might actually be
happily married and not have to be constantly in search of
excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not a big deal, being married here,'' Bushnell
marveled. ``It's not this horrifying thing that it is for men in
New York. Here, they don't have the attitude of the old ball and
chain. If you're married, it doesn't mean you're home every night
with your spouse. There's less of that `Oh-my-God-he's out,
what-is-he-doing?' syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinner parties at home in London are the preferred form of
socializing. ``It's not like New York, where you feel like going
out is your second job,'' she said. ``Here, it feels like people go
out not necessarily to have their photograph taken, but to see
their friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that she has given up on New York. Three of the four stories
in her new book are set in Manhattan. She divides her time between
New York, London and a rented house in Kent, Conn. In Manhattan,
she and a girlfriend, Anne Fell, share an Upper East Side apartment
just a few blocks north of the town house Morris, 35, uses when he
is in town. She shares the Connecticut house with Sara Colleton, a
film producer who also lives in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally, I think it's healthier to live with other
people,'' Bushnell said. ``If I am working alone in the country, I
feel like I'm going crazy after a few days.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Morris' business activities frequently take him to
Australia and all over Europe, Bushnell explained, the couple try
to schedule weekends together in Connecticut or flying visits to
London.
</P>
<P>
   ``English guys are fun,'' Bushnell said. ``They're more relaxed
and less afraid of being themselves and being vulnerable. Most of
the English men I know are willing to poke fun at themselves _ it's
less of a macho culture. You don't meet guys here who go to the gym
every day. Men here just don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, she noted: ``In England, character counts for a lot.
You don't have to look like a model to get a guy.'' (Looking like
one herself, she would have to admit that it helps.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about being entertaining and being a good egg,'' she
said. ``Englishmen are entertaining _ they're characters. They can
be flawed and make mistakes and it's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Does she include her new boyfriend in that description? ``I
don't feel that comfortable talking about it much,'' she said. ``He
is terrific. I would say he would fit that model.''
</P>
<P>
   Englishmen are no more likely to discuss their feelings than the
American variety, she observed. ``But unlike New York, this is not
a psychoanalyzed culture,'' she said. ``That idea of English
restraint, which sounds horrifying to Americans, is actually a good
thing, like this culture of manners and being polite. The truth is
that manners and politeness can get you through the rough patches
of a relationship. If you act like nothing happened, sometimes it's
better.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2139EDT &QL; 
