<HEADER>
A4516 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON-COLUMN &LR;      09-06 1376
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-SFCHRON-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MURDER ACCUSATIONS SHROUD INDUSTRY STANDARD'S LATIN AMERICA TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FOST  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here's a story you won't read in the Industry
Standard.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tale of how the hot Internet magazine nearly nailed a
deal to acquire or enter a partnership with a new Latin American
monthly.
</P>
<P>
   And it's also a tale of how talks with the new magazine faltered
_ just as the Standard received a background check that tied one of
the new publication's execs to an old murder accusation in
Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   The accusation was probably spurious, and Standard CEO John
Battelle says it had nothing to do with the deal getting killed.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Standard weighing a potential public stock
offering, a well-placed source at the Standard asserts, ``We feel
at this stage of our life cycle, we need to be whiter than white.
We concluded we would step away from it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Standard premiered in San Francisco in 1998 and quickly
became a must-read for workers in the burgeoning Internet economy.
While it has dipped its toes into Europe and Asia, it has not
established a presence in Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, earlier this year, a team of young journalists had
started Punto-com _ the name is Spanish for dot-com _ as a
magazine, Web site and conference business. In the words of a
Punto-com publicist's pitch, ``think of the Industry Standard and
Red Herring ... focused on the Internet economy in Latin America.''
</P>
<P>
   Although executives from the Standard spent months talking to
Punto-com leaders to try to hammer out some sort of joint venture,
with the courtship extending to meetings in Florida and Spain,
numerous factors conspired to squash the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies disagreed over issues such as what to call the
new venture and whether it would be an acquisition or a
partnership. Battelle also said the Standard's board of directors
balked because Punto-com was launched as a ``pan-regional play,''
covering several countries simultaneously, while the Standard
prefers to move into one country at a time.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Standard's board of directors apparently didn't
even know about the explosive background check when they informally
gave the deal a thumbs-down. Two directors, speaking confidentially
and through a spokesperson, expressed surprise at the report; two
others did not return repeated phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Standard executives didn't necessarily believe the murder
accusation when they did find out, the source said. ``Maybe we were
being too conservative,'' the source said. ``No one at Punto-com
was ever charged with any crime. ... Friends of people at Punto-com
were involved in this incident, and that was enough for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The background check, described by Standard executives as part
of their routine ``due diligence,'' unexpectedly turned up
8-year-old allegations that tied Punto-com's founder and chairman,
Isaac Lee, to a shooting death at a Bogota apartment building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mataron a un hombre bueno,'' screamed the headline in the
now-defunct tabloid La Prensa on Aug. 23, 1992. Translation: They
killed a good man.
</P>
<P>
   The article told of a doorman who was killed by police four
months earlier. It alleged that Lee was working in security for a
Cabinet minister at the time and was helping someone in the
building stockpile weapons. The article included assertions that
Lee was part of an Israeli conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, who was 20 at the time, vehemently denies any involvement
in the killing of the doorman.
</P>
<P>
   He was not at the building at the time of the incident, and
neither Lee nor his friends or colleagues were ever charged with
any crimes. Lee said the article was an attempt to smear the
Cabinet minister he was working for.
</P>
<P>
   Lee contends that the doorman was drunk and shooting at the
police at the time, and that investigations exonerated even the
police officers who pulled the trigger.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and others in the Colombian press maintain that the
journalist who wrote the story accusing Lee has a controversial and
checkered history in Colombia. A Chronicle correspondent
interviewed the journalist, who stands by his story.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the assertions on either side of the story are difficult
to substantiate. It's probably impossible to thoroughly prove or
disprove allegations of an 8-year-old murder in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
   But Lee did not have a chance to present his case to the
Standard. Executives there never told him what their investigators
turned up until I started making inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   Lee gave me a long list of people who could speak to his
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   People like Miguel Silva, the CEO of Publicaciones Semana when
Lee _ as editor in chief of Semana magazine, Colombia's leading
newsweekly _ was one of his employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The editor in chief of Semana has an armored car, he has
bodyguards, he has a driver, and he usually takes very good care in
how or where he moves. It's a very risky job,'' Silva said. ``Every
journalist in Colombia has a risky job. This is a tough place to
write tough stories.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee never shied from publishing hard-hitting controversial
material, whether about narco-traffickers, leftist guerrillas,
right-wing paramilitaries or the government.
</P>
<P>
   Lee was ``one of most aggressive and leading investigative
journalists,'' said Doug Farah, a reporter for the Washington Post,
who covered Colombia for 10 years and is now based in Africa. ``He
wasn't an investigative journalist himself, but he headed
publications that turned folks loose to do investigations on
drug-trafficking paramilitaries and other things.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People I really trusted, really trusted Isaac,'' Farah said.
``That was why I worked with him. People who I knew and who could
have had me killed easily and didn't, trusted him.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee rose to prominence at a very young age. He was only 26 when
he was named editor of Semana; he's only 29, at the helm of
Punto-com, a company that's raised $4 million from investors such
as Citicorp Venture Capital and Bank of America. He's got 45
employees already, is trying to raise more than $10 million more
and played host to a glittering launch party last month featuring
author Tom Wolfe and Economist editor Bill Emmot.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's ascendance is ``a fascinating story in Colombian
journalism,'' Silva said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's father was 3 when his family spirited him out of Poland
during the Holocaust. They landed in Colombia, which has only a
small Jewish community, and the family thrived.
</P>
<P>
   His father grew up to run a successful construction supply
business, selling pipes and flooring to the builders of Bogota. Lee
grew up in affluence, but to his father's disappointment, he did
not want to go into his family's business.
</P>
<P>
   He went to work for a Cabinet minister at age 20, handling
everything from errands to political duties to security work.
</P>
<P>
   After the fateful article appeared, however, Lee decided to
become a journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, the best revenge is success,'' he said. ``The way
to show people they were doing things wrong is to do them right. I
discovered how powerful the media was, and I wanted to do it
right.''
</P>
<P>
   In any event, Lee believed that he had put the allegations
behind him after rising to prominence in Colombian journalism
circles.
</P>
<P>
   But then he became an Internet entrepreneur. And the old rumor
surfaced just as his new venture began to take off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel really bad that instead of talking about Punto-com _
the effort we have done, the team we have put together _ instead
I'm having to answer a false rumor that was way, way behind me,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a journalist, you and I know, to dismiss a false rumor is
the hardest thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee said the rumor's resurrection is only stiffening his resolve
to move forward. Punto-com is trying to raise more money this month
and is also seeking partnerships with other U.S. companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know who is behind this, but it did not work in the
past, and it will not work this time,'' Lee vowed. ``Punto-com will
be a success.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kirk Semple, a Chronicle Foreign Service reporter in Bogota,
contributed to this report. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Media Bytes appears every Thursday in The Chronicle. Send buzz,
dirt, tips and comments to dfost(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
