<HEADER>
A4518 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MACQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON-COLUMN     09-06 1809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MACQ&AMP;A-SFCHRON-COLUMN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SON'S MAC AND DAD'S PC CAN BE ONE HAPPY FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRY NORR  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: I want to network my blue-and-white Power Mac G3 to my dad's
PC, but I don't have any idea what to do. We would also like to
share DSL. How can I do this? Is there a book or a Web site out
there that could help me?
</P>
<P>
   A: MacWindows, a site dedicated to peaceful coexistence between
its two namesakes, has an online tutorial on cross-platform
networking (www.macwindows.com/netbasic.html), but it's probably
more complicated than you need, so I'll offer my own advice.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has three levels: getting the two computers
physically connected, enabling them to share files and other
resources, and giving them both access to your DSL line.
Conceptually, each level requires its own solution, though some
products include solutions for several parts of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   -- Making the connection. The first challenge is the easiest. If
your family won't object to having a cable between the two
machines, wired Ethernet is the cheapest solution. It's built into
your Mac, and if your dad's PC is already connected to a DSL line,
it probably already has a network adapter (sometimes known as a
NIC, for network interface card) installed in one of its PCI or ISA
slots. If you don't have DSL yet, the installer who comes to hook
it up will almost certainly offer you a network card as part of the
setup process.
</P>
<P>
   Then just get an ordinary Ethernet hub (they start at around
$30), and connect the Mac, the PC and your DSL device to it with
standard twisted-pair Ethernet cabling, which you should be able to
find at any computer or electronics store. Make sure to get
Category 5 cables, but these days most network cables fit that
description.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't want new wires running around your home and both
machines are near phone jacks, Farallon Communications offers
HomeLINE kits that connect Macs and PCs through existing home phone
wiring (www.farallon.com/products/homeline/index.html). Yes, you
can use the phone for voice calls while you're online. A kit with a
single PCI card lists for $65, while an external USB adapter is
$98, and you can get two-packs at a discount.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sharing files. Either HomeLINE or Ethernet solves the first
part of the problem. Sharing files is a bit more complicated. You
can give your dad access to HTML pages on your Mac just by turning
on the Mac OS's built-in Web Sharing feature, via the control panel
of the same name, and selecting a folder to share.
</P>
<P>
   If, however, you want to give him more-complete access to your
Mac, and you want the same on his PC, you will need to buy some
third-party software. Traditionally, the main choices have been
Miramar Systems' $199 PC MacLAN
(www.miramarsys.com/products/pcm.htm) and Thursby Software Systems'
$149 Dave (www.thursby.com/products/dave.htm).
</P>
<P>
   I have Dave installed at home, but I used to use PC MacLAN, and
both have worked well for me. (The former, installed on a PC, adds
support for AppleTalk networking to Windows; the latter, installed
on the Mac side, in effect adds Windows networking technology to
the Mac.) With either one, your dad's PC will show up in your
Chooser, and your Mac in his Network Neighborhood, and you will
have access to each other's drives and, with some limitations,
printers.
</P>
<P>
   The only problem is that both products are a bit complicated to
configure and a little pricey for many home users. Fortunately, the
folks at Thursby Software have recognized that, and they are in the
final stages of testing a cross-platform networking product that
makes progress on both fronts. It's called MacSOHO, and it is
scheduled to ship by the end of this month at $99, which means some
outlets are likely to discount it to around $80.
</P>
<P>
   Based on my experience with a beta version, it is hard to
imagine anything simpler _ you don't have to worry about the
technicalities of Internet configuration at all. Just run the
installer on your Mac, answer a few quick questions in an Assistant
application and you're sharing files.
</P>
<P>
   -- Sharing Internet access. That leaves the third level, sharing
access to your DSL line and thus the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The simplest solution to that problem is to get separate, static
IP addresses for each machine from your Internet service provider;
that way, you don't have to install any additional software on
either the Mac or the PC. The downside is that most ISPs charge
extra for additional IP numbers; some offer them only with their
business-oriented service plans, which usually cost a lot more than
consumer plans. With Pac Bell DSL, for example, you would have to
pay $40 more a month to get five IP addresses, even though you
actually need only a couple.
</P>
<P>
   The alternative is hardware or software that lets multiple
machines share a single Internet account; both kinds of products
typically also include a firewall, to protect your mininetwork
against intrusion, and other features.
</P>
<P>
   The software route is a little less expensive, but it has a
definite downside _ the machine hosting the sharing software has to
be running or else the other computer can't get online. My advice
is to use hardware instead, in the form of a product generally
known as an Internet access router.
</P>
<P>
   These devices cost hundreds of dollars when I bought mine, one
called the SonicWall from Sonic Systems (www.sonicsys.com), several
years ago. But prices have dropped sharply _ some first-rate
models, such as the LinkSys EtherFast Cable/DSL Router I recently
tried out (www.linksys.com/products/product.asp?prid20&AMP;grid5), cost
as little as $150, if you shop carefully.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of these devices are listed and evaluated by Mac users
who have tried them (www.macintouch.com/accessrouters.html).
Specific features vary, of course, but nearly all of them include
two technologies, known as NAT (network address translation) and
DHCP (dynamic host configuration protocol), that make it easy for
multiple computers to share a single Internet account.
</P>
<P>
   Their firewall features also provide a strong protection from
hacker attacks _ an important consideration for anyone with DSL or
a cable modem. The devices themselves are typically small (not much
bigger than a modem), silent and fairly easy to set up _ there's
inevitably a bit of configuration involved, so you will need to
look at the instructions, but you don't need to be a networking
expert. In most cases, you can do it all with a Web browser running
on either the Mac or the PC.
</P>
<P>
   And once you have one of these devices set up, it should just
run indefinitely with no further intervention required.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of MACQA907 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  If you can't afford a hardware router, there are several
relatively inexpensive software-only solutions. In fact, if your
dad's PC has Windows 98 Second Edition, a built-in feature called
Internet Access Sharing will do the trick. Microsoft even provides
instructions for getting a Mac online through a PC with this
feature set up _ see
support.microsoft.com/support/kb/articles/Q230/5/85.ASP?LNEN-US&AMP;SD
gn&AMP;FR0. Windows Millennium Edition, the consumer version Microsoft
</P>
<P>
   plans to release next week, has a similar feature.
</P>
<P>
   If your dad doesn't have Windows 98 Second Edition or ME there's
a slew of low-cost PC-sharing utilities with names like WinGate and
WinProxy. As far as I know, they all support Mac clients.
</P>
<P>
   If you would prefer to run the access-sharing software on your
Mac, the two main contenders are Sustainable Software's IPNetRouter
(www.sustworks.com/site/prodiprouteroverview.html) and Vicomsoft's
SurfDoubler (www.vicomsoft.com/surfdoubler/surf.main.html).
IPNetRouter, which is priced at $89 or $44.50 for students and
academic organization, is more powerful and versatile; SurfDoubler
is more limited but priced at only $29 for two machines. (It's
included in Farallon's HomeLINE kits).
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WARNING OF THE MONTH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Mac OS 9's Multiple Users feature can be a real convenience in
households and offices where several people share the same Mac. It
enables users, administrators or parents to create up to 40
customized desktop environments _ just log in and you get your own
settings, preferences and favorites. The feature also makes it
possible to limit each user's access to applications and to other
users' documents.
</P>
<P>
   But if you are serious about keeping any or all of your files
away from children, co-workers or anyone else, don't count on
Multiple Users' access controls to do the job, because any slightly
savvy 12-year-old can figure out how to bypass them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Apple recently posted step-by-step instruction on how
to do so in its online Tech Info Library. The note was listed as
``RESTRICTED: Apple Internal and Support Providers Only _ Not for
General Public Release,'' but for at least several days it was
easily accessible to anyone with a browser, and its availability
was noted on several Mac Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR; TIP OF THE MONTH
</P>
<P>
   Tired of wrestling with the hockey-puck mouse that came with
your iMac or USB-equipped Power Mac? There are numerous third-party
alternatives available, not to mention clip-on shells that give the
awful Apple mouse a more-manageable shape.
</P>
<P>
   But you won't find a better mouse than the Apple Pro Mouse, the
sleek, buttonless (or all-button) optical design the company
introduced in July. It's now available, at least from Apple's
online store, as an upgrade for any USB Mac. At $59 it's not
exactly cheap, but it may make your time on the Mac a lot more
pleasant and productive.
</P>
<P>
   While you're at it, you may want to consider ordering Apple's
new Pro Keyboard, which also costs $59. It's a huge improvement
over Apple's previous model, offering full-size navigation and
function keys and a nice solid feel, yet retaining a relatively
compact size.
</P>
<P>
   Just a couple of warnings: In addition to USB, it requires Mac
OS 9.0.4, and four of its keys _ new ones for volume up, volume
down, mute and media eject _ work only with the latest Macs. Apple
says they won't be functional on older models until a software
upgrade scheduled for early 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Alternatively, Microsoft also makes USB keyboards, and though
they are marketed mainly for Windows PCs, the company now
officially supports two of them _ the Microsoft Natural Keyboard
Pro and Internet Keyboard Pro _ on the Mac. Not surprisingly, they
are not as spiffy as Apple's, but I have found them comfortable and
convenient. You might not find Mac software in the box, or at least
not the latest version, but Microsoft just posted a new release at
www.microsoft.com/products/hardware/keyboard/download/mac/macdownl
oad.htm.  &QL; Mac Q&AMP;A runs the first Thursday of each month. Send
questions to Henry Norr at  &LR; mac &LR; sfchronicle.com.  &LR; Please specify
what Mac model and what version of the Mac OS you're using.
</P>
</TEXT>
