<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4519 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SALINGER-REVIEW     09-06 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SALINGER-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALINGER PROVES ELUSIVE, EVEN TO HIS DAUGHTER 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KIPEN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (set ital)Why are all our heroes so imperfect? ...
</P>
<P>
   William Faulkner, drunk and depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Dorothy Parker, mean, drunk and depressed.
</P>
<P>
   And that guy, ``Seven Years in Tibet''? Turned out to be a
Nazi.(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   _ Jill Sobule, ``Heroes'' &QR;
</P>
<P>
   For those of us to whom J.D. Salinger was ever a hero, his
daughter's book adds another unwelcome verse to Jill Sobule's great
new pop song. That guy, ``The Catcher in the Rye''? Turned out to
be a misogynist, a crackpot and such a perfectionist that he'll
occasionally drink the same beverage twice.
</P>
<P>
   This we needed to know? Margaret A. ``Peggy'' Salinger seems to
think so. ``Dream Catcher'' tells the story of her life as
firstborn daughter to postwar America's most widely read author of
ambitious fiction _ a man who retreated to a mountain home in New
Hampshire in the '50s and whose sole available output since 1965
consists of legal filings to protect his privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dream Catcher'' is really two books in one: a very short, at
times acute critical biography of Peggy's father and an overlong,
provisionally uplifting account of her own life, culminating in
marriage, the birth of her now kindergarten-age son and
long-awaited professional satisfaction as a hospital chaplain.
Curious readers naturally will wish the dimensions of these two
books could be reversed, but that was out of the author's control.
</P>
<P>
   J.D. Salinger, as presented here, comes to seem almost as
reclusive to his daughter as he's been to his admirers. From well
before Peggy's birth in the mid-'50s until well past his withdrawal
from publishing, Salinger has apparently put in terribly long hours
at his work _ which he never discussed, at least with his family.
Peggy's parents divorced when she was in her teens and, although
geographically still close, she saw even less of him than before.
When a few years ago her father suggested that she abort her child
in the sixth month of an arduous pregnancy, communication dried up
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Hardly ideal conditions for a tell-all. Presumably for legal
reasons, Peggy can't even quote from Salinger's letters (some to
Hemingway) that she finds at the Library of Congress. Although her
writing has flashes of insightful wit and wordplay, it falls to
Salinger's invalid sister to deliver the most durable summation of
``Sonny's'' character:
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't take any criticism. I'm just sorry I'll be dead and
won't see that book he's been working on all these years. Not
publishing all these years. What a crazy business. It's because he
can't stand any criticism. He sure doles it out, though. I love
him, my brother and I were the best of friends growing up, you
know, but I have to admit that he's a bastard.''
</P>
<P>
   What made Salinger, now in his 80s, such a bastard to every
family member cited except his son and, one hopes, his third wife,
with whom he still lives up that same mountain road? Peggy doesn't
know or pretend to, though she brings to bear (perhaps too much)
research on anti-Semitism in prewar America, coupled with some
fairly astute readings of the still largely uncollected short
stories that grew out of Salinger's traumatic experiences in World
War II.
</P>
<P>
   Bastard or no, tidings of another book from Salinger will get
pulses racing among his ever-growing legion of fans, to say nothing
of booksellers everywhere. This is as it should be, even if his
last published novella, ``Hapworth 16, 1924,'' portended an
increasingly fanatical preoccupation with his fictional Glass
family and can't hold a candle to either ``The Catcher in the Rye''
or the underestimated ``Franny and Zooey.'' (``Hapworth'' came out
in a 1965 issue of the New Yorker and has never seen print in book
form, though tiny Orchises Press _ not for the first time _ claims
that an edition is forthcoming, this time in November.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Dream Catcher'' fans our hopes further with word that Salinger
has left instructions for the posthumous publication of at least
some post-1965 work.
</P>
<P>
   The question won't go away _ why (set ital)are(end ital) all our
heroes so imperfect? Bitter as she gets, Peggy knows the answer:
because they're human. To her credit, she remembers good times,
too, the wonderful bedtime stories from a great and _ why do so
many people forget this about Salinger? _ often very funny
storyteller.
</P>
<P>
   And why did Peggy write ``Dream Catcher''? She claims she wrote
it to answer her son's eventual questions about where his family
came from, but that doesn't explain why she felt compelled to
publish it while her father is still alive. It wouldn't have
compromised the book's meager but undeniable worth _ as a piece of
mildly informative insider literary criticism, or as a
better-written-than-most recovery memoir _ to admit that her son's
college fund may benefit along with his emotional well-being.
</P>
<P>
   How people feel about ``Dream Catcher'' may ultimately depend on
how they feel about biographical criticism in general. Is the
writing really all that matters? Or can correlations between a
writer and his work sometimes help us understand how, writers or
not, who we are becomes what we do? Those of us who believe the
latter can finish ``Dream Catcher'' without needing a shower _
though at times, while reading all the interminable notes Peggy's
classmates passed her in junior high, a nap may prove tempting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
