<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4520 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-SEGA-SFCHRON &LR;      09-06 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEGA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEGA HOPES THE NET CAN KEEP IT FROM FALLING 
</HEADLINE>
   By KELLY ZITO  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ If Sega were a character in one of its own video
games, it would be swinging across a bottomless crevasse clinging
to a thin rope.
</P>
<P>
   The rope in this case is the 16-foot telephone cable that comes
with the company's flagship Dreamcast console. The crevasse is the
uncertain future the company faces as it tries to outmaneuver a
horde of formidable competitors with an online service that
launches today.
</P>
<P>
   Sega, the once-dominant maker of the video-game consoles that
hook into television sets, is hoping to jump start sales of the
Dreamcast and take the lead in the fledgling online gaming industry
with the premiere of SegaNet.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of Internet service provider and online gaming
hub, SegaNet is the first time a consolemaker has allowed users to
face off against fellow gamers from across the country _ rather
than across the living room. While gamers have been able to play
over the Web using personal computers for years, no game console
has capitalized on the phenomenon, though most in the industry say
online games are key to the industry's future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet can change this business as it has banking and
retailing, but so far it hasn't,'' said Peter Moore, president of
San Francisco's Sega of America. ``This is a watershed moment in
the industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Using Dreamcast's built-in modem and the phone cable, users can
log on to SegaNet for 50 free hours of football, mainly, since NFL
2K1 is one of the two online games available now (Sega says about
30 Web-ready titles will premiere in the next several months). If
consumers sign up for the $22-a-month ISP for 18 months, they
receive a free Dreamcast (now at $150, down from $200) and keyboard
for typing smack with their buddies.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a great opportunity here to set the standard for
online gaming,'' said Gartner Group senior analyst P.J. McNealy.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, there is one major snafu already, he says _
AOL's proprietary technology prevents the company's 23 million
subscribers from logging onto SegaNet directly. However, Sega says
consumers can call a toll-free number and service representatives
will give them a special number to bypass AOL and tap directly into
SegaNet _ also for free. Sega said it is working with AOL to
rectify the situation.
</P>
<P>
   However, a glitch of that magnitude doesn't bode well for the
troubled Sega. In the past several months, Dreamcast sales have
cooled. In addition, independent video gamemakers seem to be
focusing more on on Sony's PlayStation 2 _ the highly anticipated
follow-up to the ubiquitous PlayStation _ as well as new machines
from Microsoft and Nintendo.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Sega is trying to dig itself out of a deep hole it
dug for itself in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Early that year, the company was enjoying a 50 percent market
share in the video-game console market and had a 1,400 head count
at its American headquarters in San Francisco. Then it launched
Saturn. Difficult to develop games for and backed by a weak
marketing campaign, Saturn was a major flop. Sega's market share
plummeted to less than 1 percent and the company reduced its
workforce in San Francisco to about 100. Sony entered the market
later that year with PlayStation, snatched market share from Sega
and Nintendo and hasn't looked back.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts say Sega's Dreamcast rebate and free SegaNet
access smack of desperation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they go this aggressive and give away a lot of consoles and
SegaNet and people don't buy the software, then they've failed _
and that could represent a terminal failure for Sega,'' said Andy
Eddy, editor at GameWeek magazine.
</P>
<P>
   But Sega says it is simply trying to draw a starker contrast
between Dreamcast and the competition. Dreamcast supports dial-up _
or narrowband _ Internet access, while Sony and Microsoft will
support only broadband connections. What's more, at $150, Dreamcast
costs half as much as PlayStation 2, which is due out Oct. 26.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of our demise is a little premature,'' Sega's Moore
told the crowd at a recent game industry conference in Napa.
</P>
<P>
   PlayStation ``will be wildly successful, but unless they back it
up with software, the shine wears off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Critics contend that Sony has an unimpressive lineup of games
for PlayStation 2's premiere; and Sony officials conceded recently
that ``some of the launch titles in Japan didn't reinvent the
wheel.'' In addition, there are no online games ready for release
when PlayStation 2 goes on sale.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sony is arguably one of the best-known brands when it
comes to home electronics gadgets. And, the PlayStation 2 has a DVD
player _ considered a major selling point for consumers on the
fence _ and the support of all of the biggest video-game publishers
in the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really Sony's game to lose,'' said David Herschman,
executive vice president for sales and marketing at Flipside.com,
an online gaming division of software giant Havas Interactive.
</P>
<P>
   If Sega sells 5 million Dreamcasts in the United States by the
spring (2.1 million units have been sold since Dreamcast's Sept. 9,
1999, launch), the company says it can rest assured that game
publishers will continue to pump out titles for the console. Sega
says its strength has always been its innovative titles, like
Seaman, the virtual pet man-fish that slings snappy comebacks at
players through voice recognition software.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, Sega hopes to use certain titles, such as NFL 2K1,
to establish online leagues and formal competitions where Gap or
Nike pay sponsor fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes a network like ABC, NBC or CBS,'' Moore said.
``It's not that different from people playing fantasy football, but
they get to be the players.''
</P>
<P>
   If Sega falls short of that ``critical mass'' figure, the
assumption is that developers may shift resources to other
platforms. But Sega officials in San Francisco say the firm will
remain financially solvent, largely because CSK Corp., the Japanese
information services company that owns 20 percent of Sega, has
recently invested $1 billion in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Others aren't so sure Sega will weather this storm _ even though
the online component could give the console and company a nice bump
in revenues. The resurrection of the ``Sega Scream'' ad campaign
could help, and Dreamcasts will make several appearances tonight
during the MTV Video Music Awards.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how much marketing muscle Sega throws behind
Dreamcast, the console market is strictly a three-horse race,
according to many industry insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you count Xbox, Sony, Nintendo and Sega, that's four,''
said Jay Cohen, director of Ubi Soft, a San Francisco game
publisher. ``Someone's going to take a hit. I don't know who it's
going to be, but it will be interesting to see in a year.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Kelly Zito at kzito(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
