<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4521 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GAYMEDIA-SFCHRON &LR;      09-06 1414
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAYMEDIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANETOUT EXPANDS UNIVERSE WITH DEAL FOR MAGAZINES 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAN FOST  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ &LR;   &LR; It's getting to be a familiar story in the
business world: the Internet upstart buying its offline
predecessors. Think EBay buying Butterfield &AMP; Butterfield or AOL
purchasing Time Warner.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it's happening in the market serving gays and lesbians,
it's causing some debate about the pros and cons of media
consolidation.
</P>
<P>
   On the one hand, the San Francisco Web firm PlanetOut's pending
acquisition of the company that publishes the Advocate and Out
magazines has sparked criticism. The fear is that PlanetOut may be
able to exercise too much control over what a noisy and diverse
community has to say.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, even PlanetOut's rivals say they're
encouraged by the deal for what it symbolizes: the continued growth
of gay-oriented businesses into a force to be reckoned with.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the maturing of a marketplace where gay and lesbian
business _ five, 10 and 15 years ago _ was very much in the
closet,'' said Lowell Selvin, chief executive of Gay.com. ``Today,
those businesses have stepped out of the closet. They're looking at
ways to grow, not just as community organizations but as true
businesses: acquire capital, expand reach, consolidate. It's part
of a natural progression.''
</P>
<P>
   For PlanetOut, the progression marks a phenomenal growth. The
company started out as the pioneering Digital Queers Web site,
which promoted an online gay community. Then it foundered amid
internal turmoil as an investment bank pulled its funding in a
dispute over serving the transgender community. Today, it has
emerged as a leading venture-backed player on the national gay
media scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal from day one has been to become the leading provider
of information, goods, services, media and entertainment,'' said
Megan Smith, PlanetOut's chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's no surprise that a gay-oriented dot-com would
swallow up its old media predecessors. Smith said 70 percent of
subscribers to the Advocate and Out magazines get it them plain
wrappers, choosing not to be identified as gay. ``That will always
physically stop and limit distribution,'' said Susan Schuman,
PlanetOut's chief operating officer.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet, such barriers don't exist, as people can surf
the Web freely in the privacy of their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's quite exciting that somebody in the Deep South could find
through Google.com stuff about gay people and become connected,''
said comedian and writer Kate Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Web privacy is also no guarantee: Many companies can
tell an awful lot about the people who visit their Web site.
</P>
<P>
   That's the downside of what Clinton describes as a switch from a
movement to market.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sentiment many echo as they mull the combination of
PlanetOut and Liberation Publications, the parent of the Advocate
and Out. (The $30 million merger was announced in March, but has
not yet closed. PlanetOut says that the deal was announced early in
the process and that negotiations are proceeding without any
apparent trouble.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Consolidation in the gay media world will prove a much
stronger business model for PlanetOut,'' said Steven Petrow, a
former editor at Time Interactive who will moderate a panel
discussion on media convergence at the National Lesbian and Gay
Journalists Association convention, which begins today in San
Francisco. ``Without a diversified `empire,' it's very difficult
for a company like PlanetOut to reach profitability.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On the other hand, consolidation has its downside as well,''
added Petrow, now a Web consultant. ``For writers, especially in
the gay press, it means there are fewer entities to work for, and
the larger an entity becomes, the greater its leverage is against
its writers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also anxiety in the gay community that this
consolidation will mean less diversity of points of view in the gay
press overall as PlanetOut continues on its shopping spree.''
</P>
<P>
   The concerns stem partly from the speed of the consolidation: In
February, the Advocate said it was buying Out, and then the
PlanetOut deal was announced only one month later.
</P>
<P>
   PlanetOut and the magazines insist they will not stifle
different viewpoints.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you start to have it all become one point of view or one
voice, it's not going to work,'' said Judy Wieder, editor in chief
of the Advocate. ``People are going to be bored with it. You need
variety. You need many different people.''
</P>
<P>
   PlanetOut executives say that even with the clout of
consolidation, the newly merged company would be a far cry from a
media monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   ``A monopoly comes when you have access to the entire market,
and have 90 percent of that market,'' said Schuman, PlanetOut's
chief operating officer. Smith, the CEO, points out that PlanetOut
reaches 1.5 million people per month, out of an estimated 16
million to 20 million gay and lesbian Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Out is the largest gay magazine, with a monthly circulation of
about 100,000. The Advocate is the second largest, with a
twice-monthly circulation of 93,000.
</P>
<P>
   Smith talks in ambitious terms. She notes that gays and lesbians
spend $450 billion a year, which has helped PlanetOut earn
sponsorships and ads from companies such as IBM, Procter &AMP; Gamble
and Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   PlanetOut raised $3 million in 1996 and another $16.4 million
last year, and now has 80 employees in its new Harrison Street
headquarters. Smith says the company continues to view an initial
public offering as an option, which would be a historic first for a
gay-oriented company.
</P>
<P>
   That sort of growth and ambition fills some in the gay media
with a vicarious pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I started, it was a fledgling business sector,'' said
Heather Findlay, editor in chief of Girlfriends magazine, published
in San Francisco. ``Now it's starting to behave as if it's not
marginal any more ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly there's an enormous amount of money in a gay media
company. I hope they take some that money and use it to expand the
quality of journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   Findlay is particularly concerned that lesbian issues are often
overshadowed by gay men's issues. ``Lesbians had the back seat of
the bus when it came to attention to our issues,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But Schuman said PlanetOut is sensitive to those concerns, and
40 percent of PlanetOut's users are women.
</P>
<P>
   Other issues with PlanetOut have been more contentious.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Ian Cummings, a former Advocate reporter who is now
publisher of XY, a national magazine for young gay men, was
embroiled in a dispute with PlanetOut earlier this summer over
censorship. PlanetOut had a deal to post XY's content, but yanked a
controversial story in which Cummings charged that big clothing
advertisers boycott XY for anti-gay reasons. Cummings said he was
told the story was pulled because it was ``potentially libelous ...
not appropriate ... (and of) questionable writing quality.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummings wouldn't talk about the incident. PlanetOut and XY have
reached an agreement in which XY has regained the rights to publish
its own content on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But Cummings did say he was worried by consolidation of the gay
media.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole function of the gay press was, one, to accomplish
social and cultural and political change and, two, to enable people
to meet and have sex and form relationships,'' he said. ``That was
the whole purpose. Now it's changed to deliver market share to
corporations.''
</P>
<P>
   Schuman, at PlanetOut, said that PlanetOut does cover political
and social aspects of the gay community but that it also emphasizes
opening up economic issues. She also would not talk about the
specific incident with XY.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the growth of the Advocate tells the gay media story
in a nutshell.
</P>
<P>
   Wieder, the Advocate's editor, said the magazine was founded as
a mimeographed sheet in Los Angeles in 1967, two years before the
infamous Stonewall incident, which is seen as the birth of the
gay-rights movement. It has grown more polished and professional
today, with 31 employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``A couple of years ago, we couldn't have sent a journalist to
cover a terrible murder in West Virginia,'' as she did last month,
she said. ``We didn't have the money to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the Advocate to be as newsy looking as Time magazine.
Time has a lot of little photos, and they cost a lot of money.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Dan Fost at dfost(at)sfchronicle.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
