<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4526 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-SHAW0907-COX     09-06 0504
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAW0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Shaw seeks buyout to Buffett
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA -Shaw Industries has offered to sell most of its North
Georgia family carpet dynasty to billionaire Warren Buffett's
holding company for as much as $2.07 billion in cash.
</P>
<P>
   Berkshire Hathaway Inc. said Wednesday it has agreed to buy
between 80.1 percent and 86 percent of the carpet maker's 126.6
million outstanding shares. The remaining stock would be held by
Shaw Industries management and their families.
</P>
<P>
   The surprise deal values Shaw Industries at $19 a share, a 56
percent premium to its price of $12.19 before trading was halted on
Wednesday. Shaw Industries shares shot up $6.44, or 53 percent, to
$18.63 on news of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Top management at Shaw Industries will stay in charge at the
company's headquarters in Dalton, said Julius Shaw, executive vice
president of investor relations and son of Bud Shaw, chairman
emeritus. Brothers Robert Shaw, chairman and chief executive, and
Bud Shaw own about 11 percent of the company. President Julian Saul
owns about 9 percent. All together, the extended families own about
a third of the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the arrangement, Berkshire Hathaway would favor having
Bob and Julian stay in management for at least a couple of years,''
Julius Shaw said. The Shaw brothers grew up in North Georgia's
carpet industry, which now supplies 80 percent of the nation's
carpets, and took over the family rug dyeing business in the late
'50s. Shaw Industries employs 30,000 people, about two-thirds of
them in Georgia, and runs more than 50 mills in five states.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts and investors called the deal a classic Buffett
acquisition. With a portfolio spanning gems, shoes, candy and more,
Buffett is known for buying undervalued businesses with strong
management teams and letting them remain fairly autonomous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Warren Buffett is the best value investor that ever walked the
Earth,'' said textile analyst Kay Norwood of Wachovia Securities.
``He looks for value and Shaw certainly represents that.'' The
world's largest carpet maker, Shaw Industries earned $60 million in
the second quarter on about $1.06 billion in revenue. The company
operates 53 plants in five states.
</P>
<P>
   Like other housing suppliers, Shaw Industries has profited from
the boom in residential construction and remodeling in recent
years. But the carpet industry has started to cool with the
economy. Costs of raw materials have gone up, taking a bite out of
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed acquisition needs approval from Shaw Industries'
board of directors. Robert Shaw and Saul, who have approved the
deal, would each keep his 5 percent stake in Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The remaining shares not bought by Berkshire Hathaway would be
held by other Shaw management and members of the Shaw and Saul
families, who would have the option of selling them to the Omaha,
Neb.-based company beginning in March 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
