<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0397 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4536 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TA     09-06 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEADING REPUBLICANS FEAR BUSH DRIVE IS SPUTTERING AS GORE GATHERS
STEAM 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT45 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE and FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Prominent Republicans around the country, including
several who advise Gov. George W. Bush, say they are worried that
his candidacy has floundered in recent weeks, allowing Vice
President Al Gore to build on his velocity from the Democratic
convention in a way they never expected.
</P>
<P>
   While none of these Republicans expressed panic and all said
that Bush could reverse the trend, they acknowledged puzzlement,
frustration and even some distress about the strides that Gore has
made, a degree of progress that they said went beyond an inevitable
tightening in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt about it: There's real worry about the
general state of things,'' said William Bennett, the former
education secretary, who has advised Bush from time to time.
``There's nervousness that was not there before.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews over the past several days, leading Republicans on
Capitol Hill, at state capitals and even at the Bush headquarters
in Austin, Texas, raised concerns beyond poll numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Many of them expressed unease about the way Bush has handled
himself, saying that over the last two and a half weeks there have
been too many instances when he seemed either defensive, bumbling,
weary, detached or peevish.
</P>
<P>
   And there have been too many missteps, several Republicans said.
For starters, they cited Bush's refusal to go along with the debate
schedule proposed by the bipartisan Commission on Presidential
Debates, saying his reluctance had made him look timid and was
diverting attention from issues that he would be better off
discussing.
</P>
<P>
   Others said he was letting Gore drag him into the bogs of a
policy debate, where the vice president is at his best. Still
others said that Bush's choice of Dick Cheney as a running mate had
produced scant excitement on the campaign trail but significant
damage in the news media, manifest in weeks of questions about the
financial details of Cheney's retirement from Halliburton, an
energy services company where he served as chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   And several Republican officials said they had serious
reservations about the party's tongue-in-cheek TV commercial
broadcast last week that challenged Gore's truthfulness and
political consistency.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, chairman of the House Budget
Committee, said the campaign was too preoccupied with trying to
make everyone happy and was not delivering a clear message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest mistake we can make is to try to be all things to
all people,'' he said. ``We have to be very aggressive and not
engage in any reticence about our philosophy or our positions.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, dismissed the
worries about the state of the governor's candidacy, which was so
dominant for most of the year. ``Everybody wants to win in a
landslide,'' he said. ``Landslides are rare. We've always known and
said this was going to be a close race.''
</P>
<P>
   In the eyes of some Republicans, Bush successfully began the
process of correcting his campaign this week. On Tuesday, he moved
aggressively to neutralize Gore's advantage on the critical issue
of health care by releasing his own plan to give prescription drug
benefits to the elderly. And Bush has been engaging Gore much more
forcefully in his comments and oratory.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said the combined e1}ect of Gore's surge and
Bush's stumbles had made Gore, for perhaps the first time in the
2000 presidential race, the front-runner.
</P>
<P>
   Many said they were unnerved by voter surveys showing that Gore
_ who for months lagged in the polls _ had pulled even or ahead of
Bush nationally and in some important states like Florida,
Pennsylvania and Missouri, where campaign officials have long
predicted probable victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody expected a bounce, but not nearly as much as this,''
said Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., referring to Gore. And he said that
it had significantly altered the mood of Republicans in his state,
a crucial battleground.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a lot of chatter at the grass-roots level about how
they're scared of these new numbers,'' he said. ``This has shocked
the system from what looked like a slam dunk.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania, a Republican who has campaigned
with Bush in his state, another battleground, for the last three
days, said: ``I'm at a loss to explain the rather significant
change in the polling numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ridge said he was confident Bush would recover, he said,
``We've got to go a little bit more on the offensive.'' He added of
Gore, ``This guy's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, in the nearly three weeks since the end of the
Democratic convention, Gore has been constantly on the offensive,
first declaring himself as the candidate of the little guy and
portraying Bush and Cheney as beholden to big oil and
pharmaceutical companies and then relentlessly attacking Bush over
tax policy and health care.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Gore has managed to use the favorable attention
he received during the convention, particularly the much publicized
kiss he planted on his wife, Tipper, before his acceptance speech,
to give life and personality to his image, which had been stiff and
uninteresting.
</P>
<P>
   A Republican official closely involved in the Bush campaign said
that the Texas governor's aides had readjusted their expectations
for a spate of new polls that will be released over the next few
days.
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two weeks ago, the official said, Bush's aides
were forecasting that these polls would show the race in a dead
heat. But these aides were now predicting that Gore would have, on
average, a 3-to-5-point percent advantage.
</P>
<P>
   An adviser to the Bush campaign in Washington said: ``After the
convention, I thought it was going to be difficult for Gore to come
out better than tied. Today, I think anybody forced to wager on the
race would have to bet on Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An official of the Republican National Committee, said, ``You're
always on the defensive when your lead evaporates.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interviews, Republicans of all ideological stripes were
hardly unified in dispensing advice for Bush, or in gauging the
health of his candidacy. Several Republicans said that Bush was
merely being buffeted by cyclical forces, which might change
several times again before Election Day. Others said that Bush's
position on debates made at least as much sense to voters as
Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   But some concerns about Bush's campaign were mentioned time and
again.
</P>
<P>
   For example, several Republicans said Bush still needed to be
more aggressive in explaining his proposal for a tax cut of $1.3
trillion over 10 years, more than double the size of Gore's.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get very worried about that kind of a tax cut with the
speculative nature of the surplus,'' said Sen. Arlen Specter of
Pennsylvania. ``That, I think, has to be spelled out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge said he was heartened that Bush has begun to cite real
families to explain his tax cut _ but that he could do more. ``You
talk about tax cuts in the abstract,'' he said, ``and people's eyes
glaze over.''
</P>
<P>
   Specter and other Republicans said it was a mistake for the Bush
campaign to sign off on a Republican Party commercial that poked
fun at Gore for appearing at a Buddhist temple fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's wise to do a tongue in cheek,'' Specter
said. ``It's got to be treated very seriously and in a factual way
with no apologies _ but not tongue in cheek.''
</P>
<P>
   Some people close to the campaign even said that officials at
the Republican National Committee warned that the commercial was
inappropriate because it moved the discourse away from issues.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney was also cited by many Republicans as a disappointing
choice of a running mate for Bush, especially compared to Sen.
Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, who has helped energize the
Democratic ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can recover, but he's not gotten off the dime,'' Upton, the
congressman from Michigan, said of Cheney. ``The focus, rather than
on his solid record of achievement, particularly as the secretary
of defense, and then in the private sector, has been totally
eclipsed by personal finances.''
</P>
<P>
   Bennett put it this way: ``The Lieberman pick looks pretty
solid. He's a happy camper out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Imploring Bush to campaign harder, he added, ``They could put
more on their schedule. Gore's certainly been very energetic.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans also said that despite his proposal for debates
this week, Bush was unwise to make an issue out of the format for
his televised encounters with Gore. ``He is proposing debates that
will arguably reach fewer people,'' said a Bush adviser. ``You
can't sell a Chevy and say it's a Cadillac.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, several Republicans said, Bush has at times failed
to muster the sunny geniality and bravado that have always been his
strongest suits.
</P>
<P>
   He has fumbled with his mathematical figures and his words. In
an interview late last week, at a time when he might be expected to
be as pumped up by the gathering frenzy as ever, Bush instead grew
prematurely reflective and slightly teary as he mulled over what he
said was the greatness of American democracy.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference on Sunday, as he showed snippets of
videotape to support his charge that Gore was backing out of an
agreement to debate anytime and anywhere, he tapped his foot and
occasionally pursed his lips.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Bush, who prizes himself on discipline, was caught
making a vulgar utterance about a reporter into a microphone. While
many political analysts said that the incident would cause no major
damage, others said it could feed into perceptions of Bush as
insufficiently experienced or mature for the task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still a relative rookie at the national level,'' said
Bruce Buchanan, a government professor at the University of Texas
in Austin, ``and that's showing right now.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the concerns, some Republicans said that while they were
sobered by the situation, they were not scared.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a period right before and during the Republican
convention where it looked like Bush would sail away with this,''
said Sen. Peter Fitzgerald of Illinois. ``We've all come back to
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Joe Scarborough of Florida said, ``The campaign actually
started yesterday in earnest. If Bush was going to have a problem,
he picked the right time to have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Paxon, a former House member who is an adviser to the
campaign, said Republicans who expected Bush to be ahead now were
guilty of ``Alice in Wonderland'' thinking. ``I believe that it's
going to be a tight race to the finish,'' he said. ``But I am as
confident of victory as I was six month ago. George W. Bush is
going to be the next president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2200EDT &QL; 
