<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0401 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-BLAIR-WIFE-NYT     09-06 0978
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-BLAIR-WIFE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPPOSITION POUNCES AS BLAIR'S WIFE SPEAKS OUT ON HUMAN RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo, NYT44, is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SARAH LYALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cherie Booth, the wife of the British prime minister, strode
purposefully into a thicket of unflattering headlines last month
when she wrote a newspaper article praising Britain's Human Rights
Act, a central element of her husband's legislative program and the
basis for much of her work as a high-powered international lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, she demonstrated that even the Tories' efforts to
compare her to Hillary Clinton and Lady Macbeth _ in the same
breath, and not as a compliment _ had not dissuaded her from
pursuing what has become an unprecedented, and increasingly public,
role. At a forum sponsored by New York University, she joined a
panel of lawyers from Britain and the United States in a spirited
debate on human rights, here and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Booth, as she is known professionally, was discussing the
revolution taking place in English courts as the country prepares
to adopt the European Convention on Human Rights into domestic law,
effectively giving Britons their first bill of rights ever. But she
was breaking new ground by discussing anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   No Prime Minister's spouse _ including Sir Denis Thatcher,
Margaret Thatcher's discreet and sporting husband _ has ever opened
his or her mouth in public before in anything but the most
innocuous way.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Major, John Major's wife, was best known for her expertise
on the opera. Denis Thatcher, who tended to walk demurely behind
his wife, once observed that ``she runs the country; I run the
family.''
</P>
<P>
   Byron Shafer, the Andrew Mellon professor of American government
at Oxford University said, ``Before Cherie Blair, in some sense the
role model for the prime minister's spouse would have been someone
like Lady Bird Johnson. They could have public causes _ saving
species and beautifying highways _ things that no one could
criticize.''
</P>
<P>
   But Booth, who until recently has deliberately stayed out of
politics and who never speaks to reporters, has taken on a much
more explosive cause: human rights. In an article in the Daily
Telegraph co-written with one of her law partners, Rabinder Singh,
she said that the Human Rights Act, which takes effect on Oct. 2,
would ``bring rights home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Human Rights Act forms an integral part of the
government's program of Constitutional reform, which has the aim of
modernizing Britain to make it a strong a confident democracy in
the 21st century,'' she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But the article provoked an outpouring of sniping from
conservative-minded Britons who believe that the new law will
produce a deluge of lawsuits and upend many of England's traditions
by setting individual rights _ of gays, criminal suspects and the
like _ above the rights of the state.
</P>
<P>
   John Bercow, a home affairs spokesman for the Conservative Party
and a man known for his pungent metaphors, was dispatched to lead
the party's attack. Accusing Booth of suffering from ``Hillary
syndrome,'' Bercow said that ``people in Britain will not put up
with anyone who thinks she can be an unaccountable cross between
first lady and Lady Macbeth.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving Lady Macbeth out of it, Booth has gone further than
Hillary Clinton in pursuing her own career, even as her husband
pursues his. Sometimes the two courses seem almost contradictory.
As a lawyer specializing in employment law, she is often called on
to challenge laws enacted by the government or decisions made by
public authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a sense, hers is the more radical departure,'' Shafer of
Oxford said. ``She's said, `I'm having a life of my own, and it's a
public life, and it's going to go on.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the attack seemed to backfire, as even some
Conservatives bristled at Bercow's insinuation that perhaps Booth
should not have a job at all. Even so, said Ann McElvoy, a
columnist for The Independent in London, Booth put herself in a
newly vulnerable position by inserting herself so publicly into
such an explosive issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cherie is a very political person,'' McElvoy said. ``Where
there's perhaps a bit of a conflict is that she was very
deliberately using Blairite language to describe what the human
rights law will achieve. It's very hard, as Hillary Clinton found
out, to go back into the shadows once you've come out.''
</P>
<P>
   But Booth, who temporarily slipped out of the conference
Wednesday, colleagues said, to breast-feed her baby, has proved
remarkably unperturbed by the fuss.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is very tough, Cherie,'' said Nick Martin, chief executive
of Matrix, the human-rights-minded law firm set up in a blaze of
publicity by Booth and an number of other high-profile lawyers last
spring. ``She wants to get on with it and do her job. Her only
worry would be that her partners would feel that it distracted from
Matrix's work.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tories also picked on Booth when it emerged that she had
held legal meetings with clients in the Blair family apartment
above No. 11 Downing Street.
</P>
<P>
   ''The taxpayer pays for Downing Street as a place to live and
work for the prime minister,'' sniffed John Redwood, a top-ranking
Conservative. ``A member of the prime minister's family should not
be using No. 10 or No. 11 for business purposes. It's as simple as
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But Booth _ who spoke recently during a case involving parental
leave about the ``culture of discrimination'' forcing women ``to
struggle with the balance of work and family life'' _ was on
maternity leave at the time, a Downing Street spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Downing Street is Mrs. Blair's home,'' the spokesman said.
``As a mother with a small baby, it is not unreasonable for her to
work from home.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2207EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
