<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4542 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-UNIVERSAL-MP3-LADN     09-06 0582
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNIVERSAL-MP3-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL MP3 RULING QUASH INNOVATION?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JESSE HIESTAND 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If the $118 &UR;  &LR; million verdict against MP3.com buys
Universal Music Group and the music industry anything, it's time --
time to find their way online, analysts said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Upstaged by upstarts like the free song-swapping service Napster
and music downloader MP3.com, the five major labels have fumbled
for the right formula to sell their tunes over the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Now with MP3.com reeling from a potentially fatal blow, the
industry has a chance to take make a stronger presence in this
emerging field, industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to keep everyone else on the sidelines as far as
creating legitimate ways of getting music online,'' said Heath
Terry of Credit Suisse First Boston's office in San Francisco.
``MP3.com was by and far the most copyright-conscious service on
the Internet and they got hit with what could be a $250 million
verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   The amount of damages will depend on how many of Universal's
compact discs MP3.com put online for people to listen to if they
could prove they already owned a copy.
</P>
<P>
   While estimates vary on how many discs MP3.com was found to have
willfully infringed upon, each will draw $25,000 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego-based Web company has already also set aside $150
million to cover legal expenses and the settlements it reached with
the other four major labels before trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way they're going to survive if Universal collects
$250 million,'' said David Bench, an analyst with Arnhold &AMP; S.
Bleichroeder in New York. ``How they will survive is if they cut a
deal with Universal before that. This definitely gives Universal
more leverage in terms of negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts largely said MP3.com blundered in not getting the
labels' permission to post the albums on its controversial
``MyMP3.com'' service.
</P>
<P>
   The industry has shown even less tolerance for Napster, where
people can freely download Top 10 hits, obscure tracks, even whole
albums before they are released. The five major labels banded
together to get Napster shut down in July, but it remains online
pending an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But for all its opposition to these services, the record
industry has not offered any other means of getting music that the
public has embraced. Insiders said the main stumbling block was
preserving copyright, which the rulings in these two cases appear
to bolster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's all about slamming the brakes on any innovation
out there so they can figure this out first,'' Terry said.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Napster and MP3.com cases were also closely watched
because they had broad implications for Internet content.
</P>
<P>
   ``This definitely set a precedence for copyright issues in
general, whether it's music or videos,'' Bench said. ``It shows you
don't step on the toes of the big companies.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, MP3.com will continue to serve as one of the leading
sites for thousands of aspiring musicians who post their songs and
press kits, hoping to gain exposure, Bench said.
</P>
<P>
   One such musician, Brett White, said he doubts MP3.com will fold
even if the staggering damages are enforced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still going to be a warehouse of unknown music and it
doesn't take much money to maintain that server space,'' said
White, 34, of Hollywood. ``But it will probably shut down the ways
they're trying to be innovative.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
