<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-SCENE-NYT &LR;      09-06 0687
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMIT WATCHING: WHO WAS THAT MAN IN THE SUIT? 
</HEADLINE>
   By EDWARD WONG and ELISA GOOTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The television cameras and reporters raced across the
marble lobby of the Waldorf-Astoria and swarmed around the Chinese
man in a dark suit. Was he a high-ranking party official? Perhaps
President Jiang Zemin himself?
</P>
<P>
   Hardly. It was William Chiu, chairman of the American Fujian
Association of Commerce and Industry. He had just left a meeting
with President Jiang. On Tuesday morning, more than 300 Chinese
American community leaders, businessmen and scholars gathered at
the hotel to hobnob with the leader of the world's most populous
country. About a third were from the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   ``The meeting was just great,'' said Chiu, an insurance agent
who lives in the Long Island community of Setauket. ``It's like
we're in the same family.''
</P>
<P>
   There were even Taiwanese Americans at the meeting, but they
never raised the issue of Taiwan independence because the meeting
was ``a family talk,'' Chiu said.
</P>
<P>
   The insurance agent was among a crowd that welcomed Jiang
earlier this week when he flew in. But a cadre of pro-Tibet
protesters had also shown up, something that Chiu would rather
forget.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want their freedom, but they should give us our freedom
too,'' he said. ``Don't bother us, don't interrupt us.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Jiang was in town for the rest of the week, would Chiu be
meeting with him again?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's very busy,'' the insurance agent said. ``There
are 1.2 billion people in China. He has a lot of work to do.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Room Service Stampede  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   With more than 30 heads of state on the premises, the
Waldorf-Astoria finds itself this week having to provide literally
world-class service in ways it has never done before. Where
gastronomic matters are concerned, such an undertaking would bring
stomachaches to many a chef.
</P>
<P>
   Not so at the Waldorf, said Christophe Le Chatton, director of
food and beverage operations. The hotel has doubled the number of
cooks on duty, and quadrupled the number of room service waiters.
</P>
<P>
   ``To coordinate how to make them happy is important,'' Le
Chatton said of the world leaders. ``They're all equally important
in their own mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The requests are as varied as the languages heard these days in
the hotel lobby. There is, for instance, the state leader who
insists on drinking papaya juice. World affairs being what they
are, Le Chatton remained discreet about that dignitary's identity.
``I  &UR; never &LR;  give out names,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the delegates who asked the hotel to fetch Thai
food from a local restaurant, and those who brought their own
chefs. (China and India, for instance.) Space in the kitchen was
cleared away, woks were provided. But the chefs brought with them
their own knives, strictly for use in the kitchen, not in plenary
sessions or backroom conferences. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In New York to Talk Trash  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Most dignitaries converged on the city to ponder things like
world poverty and globalization, but a few arrived with humble
concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Rwanda's health minister, Dr. Ezechias Rwabuhihi, found time to
to talk about garbage trucks, landfills and sewage treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like New Yorkers have a lot of expertise in these
matters,'' said Isidore Munyiakazi, an official at the Rwandan
mission to the United Nations, who accompanied Rwabuhihi on his
visit Tuesday to the Sanitation Department's Worth Street
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   If New York can cope with its trash, Rwanda should be able to
handle the waste generated by its growing population, Munyiakazi
reasoned. ``People leave their garbage outside, then the city tries
to collect it. But we don't have enough cars, we don't have enough
personnel and we don't have enough landfills,'' Munyiakazi said.
</P>
<P>
   Chief William Jelley, who heads the agency's Bureau of Cleaning
and Collection, briefed the minister, who seemed to have trouble
finding the office, said Peter C. Fenty, a Sanitation Department
spokesman. ``I guess they ran into Gramercy Park, which can be a
surprise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
