A4549 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DASIBI-VENTURE-LADN     09-06 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DASIBI-VENTURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DASIBI LANDS CHINA DEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLENDALE _ Dasibi Environmental entered the realm of giants
Wednesday, inking a joint venture to build air quality measurement
equipment in China.
</P>
<P>
   Dasibi's deal with Shenyang Dongyu is worth an estimated $200
million in sales as the two companies supply 680 cities in China
with the equipment. To the officials present at a signing ceremony
Wednesday, it's also a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to be big to do business in China,'' said Mary
Delmege, western regional director of the U.S. Department of
Commerce. ``There's a large perception that the big international
trade deals are only for big companies.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement marks the culmination of six years of negotiations
between Dasibi, which employs 55 people, and Dongyu, which was
drawn to the American company by the relationship it had with trade
officials in the Chinese government. In April 1999, Dasibi launched
a 25-city air quality monitoring project in connection with China's
environmental protection agency.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for Dongyu, based in the city of Shenyang, to
build Dasibi monitoring equipment and distribute among client
cities. Dasibi said air pollution in major Chinese cities rivals or
even exceeds that of Los Angeles. The purchase is indicative of
that government's attempt to update its monitoring capabilities,
said Dasibi Project Engineer Eric Lai.
</P>
<P>
   ``The air quality is getting worse so the government wants to do
whatever we do,'' Lai said.
</P>
<P>
   Albert Gosselin, president and chief executive officer of
Dasibi's parent Pollution Research and Control Corp., said it will
provide the lion's share of his company's business for at least
five years. Given that China has imported $3 billion in pollution
control equipment, the magnitude of the relationship hasn't yet
been realized, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good-sized market no matter how you multiply it,'' said
Gosselin, who jokingly calls his company a ``Fortune 5 million''
firm, a riff on Fortune magazine's Fortune 500 listing of the
United States' biggest companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dasibi has a very good (technology),'' said Dongyu Chairman
and President Zhuang Yuyang at the ceremony. ``If the (technology)
can find a market, everything is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
