<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4551 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-OLY-SWIM-DOCTOR-HNS &LR;      09-06 2157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWIM-DOCTOR-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Olympic `swim doctor' comes under scrutiny
</P>
<P>
   By DANNY ROBBINS
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ An Austin nutritionist who describes himself as a
Ph.D. in nutritional counseling and has been advising U.S. Olympic
swimmers Dara Torres and Jenny Thompson on the use of dietary
supplements received his doctorate from a school that offers its
courses through the mail and is unaccredited, leading some to
question whether he should be working with Olympic athletes in such
a sensitive area.
</P>
<P>
   Glen R. Luepnitz, who has been labeled an ``expert'' on dietary
supplements by U.S. women's swim coach Richard Quick and is due to
work with U.S. swimmers at the Olympics in Sydney, received his
doctorate from LaSalle University in Mandeville, La., an
institution that was widely known as a so-called ``diploma mill''
at the time of his enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   Records show Luepnitz enrolled in the LaSalle program in April
1995 and was awarded a doctorate in nutrition counseling two years
later after completing eight courses _ all by mail _ and a
``doctoral project.'' He had previously received a bachelor's
degree in education from the University of Texas in 1981.
</P>
<P>
   LaSalle has never been accredited by a recognized accrediting
agency and four years ago was enmeshed in a federal investigation
focusing on the school's founder, Thomas Kirk, and its parent
organization, the World Christian Church.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1996, the LaSalle offices were raided by agents from a
joint task force of the FBI, the U.S. Postal Inspection Service and
the Internal Revenue Service. Kirk subsequently pleaded guilty to
one count of conspiring to commit wire fraud, credit-card fraud and
tax evasion. He is now serving a five-year prison sentence at the
federal correctional complex in Beaumont.
</P>
<P>
   The government contended that thousands of students were handled
by a faculty of less than 10, most of whom lacked traditional
academic degrees, and that the accrediting agency listed by the
school was in fact a fictitious entity created by Kirk consisting
of nothing more than a mailing address and an answering service.
</P>
<P>
   The school was reorganized in July 1997 when it came under the
control of a nonprofit corporation, LaSalle Education Corp., and
its name was recently changed to Orion College. As part of the
restructuring, the school stopped offering doctorate degrees.
</P>
<P>
   John Bear, author of Bear's Guide to Earning Degrees
Nontraditionally, said a degree awarded by LaSalle before mid-1997
should be viewed as a ``time bomb'' on any resume, particularly
that of someone in a health-related field.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're in a borderline health area, as nutrition is, it's
especially dangerous to go out there as a doctor (with a LaSalle
Ph.D.),'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Luepnitz, 41, provides nutritional counseling for cancer
patients as well as athletes. He works out of an office at Lone
Star Oncology, a clinic set up by Austin physician John Costanzi,
and claims affiliation with several other health-care
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Since May, he has served as an unpaid adviser on matters
relating to diet and dietary supplements for Torres, Thompson and
other swimmers who train at Stanford University, a role he assumed
after coming to the attention of Quick, the women's swim coach at
Stanford and a former coach at the University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Luepnitz worked with Quick's swimmers at the Olympic trials last
month in Indianapolis and is due to continue in that position at
the Olympics in Sydney, where Quick will serve as head coach of the
U.S. women's team.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, 33, is expected to be one of the Games' biggest stories.
She has qualified for the Olympics in three individual events and a
relay, a remarkable achievement in light of the fact she returned
to competitive swimming last summer after a seven-year layoff. When
she swims in Sydney, she will become the first U.S. swimmer to make
four Olympic appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, 27, has qualified to compete in three events. A third
Quick-trained swimmer _ Stanford senior Misty Hyman _ has qualified
in one.
</P>
<P>
   Luepnitz defended his doctorate, saying it is comparable to
those awarded in a more traditional fashion. He said his work
included a thesis that ran between 300 and 400 typewritten pages
(with another 150 pages of charts) and was on the subject of
``developing wellness programs for long-term health.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he elected to obtain a doctorate from LaSalle because he
was trying to continue his education while working and raising a
family and because he wanted to be involved with a school
accredited by a church-related organization. He said it was his
understanding the school had been ``set up by monks'' and
accredited by a ``theological-type'' organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what their practices were with other students or
what their practices were in general, how they handled other
things,'' he said. ``But for me, it was an extremely positive
experience. It allowed me to accomplish something in my life that
otherwise I wouldn't have been able to accomplish.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has made Quick and others associated with the U.S.
Olympic swim team aware of the nature of his academic record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about it,'' Luepnitz said. ``They asked me in
the past where I went to school, and I tried to give them all the
information I possibly can, because it's better to give them the
information and then that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   An attempt to contact Quick through USA Swimming, the governing
body for swimming in the United States, was unsuccessful. The U.S.
swim team left Sunday for Brisbane, Australia, where it will train
prior to the start of the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Luepnitz as ``Dr. Luepnitz,'' Quick talked
extensively about the nutritionist at the Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   Quick said he was concerned by the furor over home-run king Mark
McGwire's use of the supplement androstenedione and wanted input
from someone who could help athletes deal with questions regarding
it and other supplements. He said he was in Austin in the spring
visiting his daughter, learned of Luepnitz's work, and decided to
seek the nutritionist's help.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an expert in that field,'' Quick said, ``so I wanted
an expert in that field working with my athletes. I didn't want
them relying on the sales person in the local nutritional store.''
</P>
<P>
   Quick said he had created a foundation to raise funds so
Luepnitz and other support personnel involved with the Stanford
swimmers could go to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   Torres, speaking to reporters on a conference call before the
trials, cited Luepnitz as a critical factor in the success she and
other swimmers training with Quick had experienced. She said
Luepnitz had given the Stanford swimmers a legal way to keep up
with those using performance-enhancing drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather not get into detail about what we're doing, because
you can't give away all your secrets,'' she said, ``but he's really
helped the team a lot in trying to get us to where the cheaters are
without cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   The success of Torres and Thompson at the trials led other
Olympic swimmers and their coaches to seek out Luepnitz for advice.
Luepnitz said last week he had drawn blood from 40 Olympic swimmers
to analyze their nutritional needs and that he is working with all
members of the Olympic team, both men and women, ``in one way of
another.''
</P>
<P>
   Luepnitz identifies himself as Glen R. Luepnitz, Ph.D., on his
resume and business cards. His e-mail address includes the
designation ``drnutrition.'' His resume states that he holds a
doctorate in nutritional counseling from LaSalle University but
makes no mention of the school's location, method of operation or
accreditation.
</P>
<P>
   Luepnitz provided his resume to the Chronicle during an
interview in his office Aug. 29. Three days later, after the
Chronicle had made inquiries regarding his background, he contacted
the newspaper and faxed transcripts showing he had obtained an
undergraduate degree from UT and a doctorate from LaSalle
University in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The LaSalle transcript shows he received a doctorate in
nutrition counseling by completing 30 hours of course work in two
years. He received 24 credit hours for passing eight courses and
another six hours for completing a ``doctoral project.''
</P>
<P>
   The doctorate program completed by Luepnitz differs markedly
from those offered at conventional colleges and universities, where
earning a Ph.D. typically requires about 90 hours of course and
research credit at the graduate level, the first 30 or so hours
leading to a master's degree. A legitimate doctorate program
generally takes a minimum of four years to complete.
</P>
<P>
   Claire Given, LaSalle's director of marketing, said all courses
offered by the school at the time it was operated by Kirk and the
World Christian Church consisted entirely of reading a book and
writing a paper. She said the school also routinely awarded course
credit based on the previous job experience of students.
</P>
<P>
   Considering the school's direction at the time, she said, its
course credit was subject to inconsistencies in faculty
credentials, grading practices and prerequisite standards.
</P>
<P>
   An FBI affidavit filed in federal court shortly after agents
raided the LaSalle offices said the school employed five people in
1996 to grade the papers of 6,293 students. The affidavit quoted a
former LaSalle employee as saying standards were so lax that papers
were sometimes graded based on weight and length instead of
content.
</P>
<P>
   According to Bear, who has provided expert testimony regarding
phony schools as well as written about them, even if Luepnitz had
the best of intentions in enrolling in the LaSalle program, he
would not have received anything resembling a legitimate doctorate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can say with absolute certainty there's no way a LaSalle
doctorate from that era can represent real academic work,'' Bear
said, ``no matter what was going on in his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Students who received LaSalle degrees prior to the school's
reorganization in mid-1997 have been given the option of turning in
their diplomas and receiving refunds, but few have taken that step.
Some have been prosecuted for using LaSalle doctorates to obtain
teaching and other doctorate-level positions.
</P>
<P>
   Bear said many individuals with LaSalle doctorates slip through
the cracks because employers and others believe the degrees were
awarded by La Salle University in Philadelphia, a well-known and
respected institution.
</P>
<P>
   Luepnitz's academic credentials are significant because he is
involved with Olympic athletes in an area that has generated
considerable debate.
</P>
<P>
   Physicians involved in sports medicine often warn that dietary
supplements, which are largely unregulated, offer few benefits and
numerous risks. They cite inconsistent manufacturing, poor labeling
and other factors in explaining why supplements should be avoided
for health reasons as well as the possibility of unknowingly
ingesting a banned substance.
</P>
<P>
   ``There isn't much you can know about these, because they
haven't been studied,'' said Edward R. Laskowski, a physician who
serves as co-director of the Sports Medicine Center at the Mayo
Clinic in Rochester, Minn. ``And what we do know about some
potential ill effects and the downside of taking a substance you
don't know the purity of, it seems like playing Russian roulette.
You can get away with it for a while, but maybe you won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care how many degrees you have, if you don't know the
long-term effects, you should be wary. A supplement like creatine,
we don't know what this stuff may do to a guy who's been taking it
10 years, starting at age 15. It's like tobacco. It may take awhile
for the effects to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Bryan W. Smith, team physician for the University
of North Carolina athletic program and chairman of the NCAA's
competitive safeguards committee, most of the positive drug tests
involving college athletes can be tied to substances found in
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   ``It truly is one of those things where I don't know if anybody
can feel safe in saying, `I take this, and I take it in this
quantity,''' he said. ``Most of these things, frankly, for the
majority of individuals are probably OK. But we really don't know
the answer. If you're on the opposite side of the fence, and you
have a bad outcome (positive drug test), well, you're a
statistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Luepnitz said he agrees with the notion that using supplements
comes with risk but doesn't believe they should be avoided
altogether. He said he has developed detailed information about
various brands and vendors and uses it in counseling Torres,
Thompson and the other swimmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before they take anything, we talk about what brand it is,
where they bought it, whether it's any good or not, the whole
works,'' Luepnitz said. ``It's a lot of pressure. It's a lot of
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
