<P>
   (NYT48) UNDATED -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT -- Before
the introduction of gypsum wallboard, interior walls were finished
with plaster. Wallboard is essentially a flat sheet of plaster
sandwiched between sheets of special paper. Unlike plaster,
wallboard is fastened to the studs in a dry state and for this
reason it is frequently called drywall. It is also sometimes called
Sheetrock. (Ed Lipinski/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT47) CHICAGO -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- OBIT-SIMPSON -- John
Alexander Simpson, a nuclear physicist and astrophysicist whose
instruments have been sending data back from space for nearly 40
years, died on Aug. 31 in Chicago. He was 83 and lived in the Hyde
Park neighborhood of Chicago. The cause was complications after
open heart surgery. Dr. Simpson, who went from helping develop the
atomic bomb to exploring cosmic rays at the University of Chicago.
(The New York Times/University of Chicago)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT46) CHICAGO -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- OBIT-MUSSO -- George Musso,
a Hall of Fame lineman and captain of the Chicago Bears before and
during World War II, died Tuesday in Edwardsville, Ill. He was 90.
Musso was probably the only player who once lined up against two
future presidents. In 1929, he played against Eureka College's
175-pound guard, Ronald Reagan. In the 1935 College All-Star Game,
he opposed the Michigan center, Gerald Ford. (The New York
Times/The Chicago Bears)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT45) SCRANTON, Pa. -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- BUSH-CAMPAIGN --
Prominent Republicans around the country, including several who
advise Gov. George W. Bush, say they are worried that his candidacy
has floundered in recent weeks, allowing Vice President Al Gore to
build on his velocity from the Democratic convention in a way that
they never expected. George and Laura Bush, surrounded by staff,
board their campaign plane in Scranton enroute to Milwaukee,
Wednesday morning. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT44) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- U.N.-BLAIR-WIFE -- Cherie
Booth, right, the wife of the British prime minister, at a forum
sponsored by New York University, Wednesday. Booth joined a panel
of lawyers from Britain and the United States in a spirited debate
on human rights, here and abroad. Miss Booth, as she is known
professionally, discussed the revolution taking place in English
courts as the country prepares to adopt the European Convention on
Human Rights into domestic law, effectively giving Britons their
first bill of rights ever. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
