<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTON-EARNINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOOD NEWS DOESN`T BUOY LITTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Litton Industries announced Wednesday that it beat
analysts' fourth-quarter estimates but was punished on Wall Street
anyway by forward-looking investors.
</P>
<P>
   The military shipbuilder pared down its earnings estimate for
the first quarter of the new fiscal year and watched its stock
value drop 24 percent. Analysts said increasingly skittish
investors have their doubts about the rebound Litton predicted in
succeeding quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``What wound up happening was, essentially, that their
(first-quarter) earnings will be 10 (percent) to 20 percent below
last year but they will hit earnings targets in Q2, 3 and 4,'' said
Thomas Meagher of BB&AMP;T Capital Markets. ``There was some healthy
skepticism about their that.''
</P>
<P>
   Litton considers 2001 a rebuilding year. Though it earned $1.52
per share in the fourth quarter and beat Wall Street estimates of
$1.49 per share, it anticipated that earnings would be 10 percent
to 20 percent less in the first quarter of the 2001 fiscal year
than a year entire fiscal year, it forecast earnings growth of only
zero to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The company attributed that to a ``changing product mix'' in its
shipbuilding operations, adding more new projects with high
front-end costs as opposed to ongoing projects that improve cash
flow.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of our efforts are focused on building a foundation to
accelerate growth in sales earnings and cash flow,'' said Litton
Chairman and Chief Executive Officer Michael R. Brown in a
Wednesday morning conference call to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Litton shares fell 81.25 cents to close at $41.25 on heavy
volume of 2.23 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is just unavailing of any shortcomings these
days,'' said Meagher.
</P>
<P>
   XXX
</P>
</TEXT>
