   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- Sept. 6, 2000 -- PET-HEALTH-SPAS -- Ten
years ago, physical therapy was mainly for people. Pets, even when
valued as guardians and companions, received limited medical care
and were often euthanized when they were deemed too old, too infirm
or too expensive to treat. Today, as pets become more prized, and a
booming economy creates more discretionary income, pets are being
offered the same therapies available to humans,. Jodi Richard with
Her Nibs, a German short-haired pointer, in the pool at Bonnie's K9
Swim Center in Manhattan. Her Nibs is receiving therapy for a
ruptured disk and dislocated hip. (Rebecca Cooney/The New York
Times) LITE
