<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4559 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-USOPENMAIN0907-COX     09-06 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-USOPENMAIN0907-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Power isn't everything for Hewitt
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Lleyton Hewitt is heir to what was expected to be
Andre Agassi's easy quarter of the draw, but those who think the
flashy Australian teenager is the lesser player should give it some
thought.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt defeated Arnaud Clement, the man who blitzed Agassi in
straight sets in the second round, 6-2, 6-4, 6-3 Wednesday to
become the first man to qualify for the semifinals of the U.S.
Open.
</P>
<P>
   The ninth-seeded Hewitt, who calls himself ``Rock'' because he's
inspired by the Rocky movies, has won four titles this year, tied
for first on the ATP Tour. He's lost only one set here in five
matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I got in the top 10, I think I really started to
believe that I should be there,'' said Hewitt, the youngest top-10
player. ``I want to cement my spot in the top 10 among these guys.
This is just another step in my career.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, at 19 years, 4 months, is the youngest men's
semifinalist here since Pete Sampras in 1990. That was the year
Sampras first won it.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Hewitt became the youngest winner at the
Queen's grass court tournament since Boris Becker when he beat
Sampras in the final.
</P>
<P>
   At 5-foot-11, 148 pounds, Hewitt is one of the tour's quickest
and most spirited players, and he showed Clement a good stick from
the service line, hitting a career-high 18 aces, including eight in
his first four service games.
</P>
<P>
   One of the questions in Hewitt's game has been whether he could
hurt his opponents with more than just his speed and steady
groundstrokes. Hewitt didn't have to do much more than that against
Clement, who wasn't sharp in his first quarterfinal at a Grand
Slam.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't make any mistakes, just put the ball on the court,
and me, I made lots of mistakes,'' Clement said. ``That's it. He
can play better than today.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt, supported by a vocal group of flag-waving Australian
fans known as the Fanatics, faces the winner of Wednesday's late
match between Pete Sampras and Richard Krajicek.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously I'm going to have a few nerves the morning of the
match and that,'' Hewitt said. ``But I like being out there trying
to put on a show for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The final two men's quarters _ Todd Martin vs. Thomas Johansson
and No. 6 Marat Safin vs. No. 14 Nicolas Kiefer _ will be today.
The semifinals begin at 11 a.m. Saturday, and the men's final will
be at 4 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
