<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, SEPT. 7 
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: These corrections appeared in The New York Times on
Thursday, Sept. 7. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.) 
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CHENEY-STOCKS-NYT (moved Friday, September 1)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, September
1 about the finances of Dick Cheney, the Republican candidate for
vice president, misstated his reason for having rejected $89,500 in
honorariums from 1992 to 1999 and having directed them to charity.
The action was voluntary, not required.
</P>
<P>
   The article also misstated the relationship of Cheney's wife,
Lynne, to the board of Union Pacific Resources. She was a board
member until the company was taken over this year by the Anadarko
Petroleum Corp., an independent oil and gas exploration company.
She is not now a member.
</P>
<P>
   BC-AOL-TIME-WARNER-NYT (moved Tuesday, September 5)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, September
5 about the government's review of the pending merger between Time
Warner and America Online referred to a proposed deal between Time
Warner and the EMI Group. Time Warner has agreed to merge its music
business into a joint venture with EMI; it does not plan to acquire
EMI.
</P>
<P>
   BC-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-NYT (moved Sunday, September 3)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, September
3 about sports Web sites that sell merchandise misstated the date
for the reopening of ESPN.com's online store. It is mid-September,
not mid-December.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
