<HEADER>
A4570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      09-06 0689
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: BOMBING INQUEST OPENS
</P>
<P>
   An inquest into the 1998 car bombing in Omagh that killed 29
people and injured more than 300 opened with witnesses calling on
members of the Real IRA _ the dissident Republican group that took
responsibility for the act but said it was a mistake _ to come
forward and ``clear their consciences.'' Police say they know who
the bombers are but do not have enough evidence to bring them to
trial. The inquest is expected to last four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: EASTERNERS PARDONED
</P>
<P>
   Two former members of the East German Politburo, Guenter
Schabowski and Guenther Kleiber, who were jailed in December for
their role in East Germany's shoot-to-kill policy at the Berlin
Wall were pardoned by Mayor Eberhard Diepgen of Berlin. Justice
officials said they would be freed on Oct. 2, after serving less
than a third of their three-year sentences. They said the pardon
was a symbolic gesture to help rehabilitate those who had
apologized for their role in the East German state.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: HUNGER STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen Marxist guerrillas who were convicted on terrorism
charges related to the attack on an army barracks in 1989 went on
their second hunger strike this year demanding a court appeal in
their case. The attack by the tiny All for the Fatherland band on
the La Tablada base outside Buenos Aires left 39 dead. The rebels
say there were only trying to halt a coup, a claim disputed by most
historians and political analysts.
</P>
<P>
   CHILE: CONSCRIPTION TO END
</P>
<P>
   President Ricardo Lagos announced that the armed forces will
phase out the draft and become a voluntary force by the year 2005,
in a move that potentially will impact the lives of 27,000 young
people every year. The high command supports the new policy as a
way to modernize the military.
</P>
<P>
   ECUADOR AND UNITED STATES: INDIANS' SUIT AGAINST TEXACO
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge rejected a motion filed by lawyers for Ecuadoran
Indians requesting that he withdraw from handling their
seven-year-old lawsuit against Texaco Inc. The suit accuses Texaco
of polluted the Indians' Amazon lands. The lawyers said the judge,
Jed S. Rakoff of Manhattan, had attended an expenses-paid seminar
in 1998 at which a former chairman of Texaco spoke. They said this
gave the appearance of a conflict of interest, enough to require
him to withdraw. Rakoff confirmed he had attended the seminar but
said the lawsuit was never discussed.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   GAZA: PALESTINIAN PROTEST
</P>
<P>
   Hamas, the leading Islamic fundamentalist group in the
Palestinian entity, and Islamic Holy War, a smaller group, will
boycott this weekend's meeting of the Palestinian Central Council.
The two organizations' spokesmen said they expected the council to
defer declaration of a Palestinian state and endorse a continuation
of the peace effort, which they reject.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   AFGHANISTAN: TALIBAN GAINS
</P>
<P>
   After fierce fighting, the ruling Taliban militia have captured
the critical northeastern city of Taloqan, an opposition
stronghold. Taloqan has changed hands several times during the long
civil war. If the Taliban can hold on, it will have a significant
victory over the forces of Ahmad Shah Massoud. The opposition now
controls only a neighboring province and small pockets in a few
other northern provinces.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: HOSTAGE TALKS BREAK DOWN
</P>
<P>
   Talks with the criminal Veerappan, who has been holding movie
star Rajkumar captive for five weeks, have broken down. R.R. Gopal,
emissary between the two sides, said the bandit is sticking to his
demands for the release of dozens of his jailed comrades-something
state authorities have been willing to do but the courts have
forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   KASHMIR: LETHAL DECADE
</P>
<P>
   The latest official death toll in a decade of violence is
33,854, according to a police document reported by Agence
France-Presse. This includes 19,781 civilians, 11,757 militants and
2,316 security forces. Separatists claim the numbers understate the
carnage by at least half.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
