<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      09-06 0574
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
  
BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR(a) 
 &HT;    A FLAWED FATHER'S PERFECT SON(a) 
 &HT;    (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)(a) 
 &HT;    By E. J. MONTINI(a) 
 &HT;    c.2000 The Arizona Republic(a) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (PHOENIX) - It took guts to pick up the telephone and dial. The
phone number is at the bottom of the newspaper column, inviting
people - almost daring them - to call. But he had to figure the guy
on the other end of the line is most likely what George W. Bush
would call a ``major league (expletive).''
</P>
<P>
   Still, he called.
</P>
<P>
   The column was about his father, and it troubled him. He's 19
years old, trying to get through a very tough college and having to
deal with the fact that his dad is locked up in a federal
penitentiary. Now along comes this writer saying things about his
old man he just can't accept or go along with.
</P>
<P>
   He loves and admires his dad. He always has, even during the
many years his father lived a lie, calling himself Gary Tredway and
pretending he wasn't a fugitive named Howard Mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   The writer doesn't admire Mechanic much. At least he doesn't
admire the fact that Mechanic chose to run.
</P>
<P>
   It was a tough time. Mechanic had been tried and convicted of
tossing a cherry bomb during a student demonstration in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   The evidence against him was shaky at best, and the sentence he
received, five years in prison, was outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he'd made choices based on his convictions. He'd assumed
risks. And when the time came to pay the consequences, he ran,
changing his name and living a fiction.
</P>
<P>
   Five years in federal prison seems like a terrible price to pay
for your convictions. Then again, it seems a lot easier than the 5
1/2 years the future Sen. John McCain spent in North Vietnam's
Hanoi Hilton for the way he exercised (beginitalic)his
(enditalic)convictions.
</P>
<P>
   A man and woman at Washington University in St. Louis put up
their house to bail Mechanic out of jail. He left them holding the
bag.
</P>
<P>
   He says he was young and foolish, only 22. But nothing changed
by the time he turned 32 or 42. Nothing changed until he was
exposed by a reporter at 50, and even then, he didn't want to come
forward with the truth.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's in prison, and there are a lot of people trying to get
him a presidential commutation. They call him a persecuted man and
even a martyr. But he's not. A martyr doesn't run.
</P>
<P>
   Mechanic is only a man serving too much time for too little
crime. Among American prisoners, this hardly makes him unique.
</P>
<P>
   These are the kinds of things the writer said about the
19-year-old's father. The young man could have let them pass,
ignored them, but he didn't.
</P>
<P>
   He called. It's not always wise to telephone a newspaper writer.
A string of quotes from the son of a high-profile newsmaker is
fairly irresistible to a major league expletive like me.
</P>
<P>
   You won't read any here, through.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a flawed father with a son of my own. I figure Howard
Mechanic worries, as we all do, that our flaws will define our
children's future.
</P>
<P>
   They won't with Mechanic's son, about whom his parents should be
very proud.
</P>
<P>
   He is articulate and passionate. He speaks with confidence and
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't about what Howard Mechanic's son said, however, but
about what he did.
</P>
<P>
   He was confronted with a difficult and intimidating situation,
and he stood his ground. He didn't run.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Reach Montini at ed.montini(a)arizonarepublic.com or (602)
444-8978
</P>
</TEXT>
