<HEADLINE>
THIS GAME PERSONAL FOR MANNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When UCLA sophomore cornerback Ricky Manning takes
the field Saturday against hometown Fresno State, he'll be carrying
more than the responsibility of being a game captain. He'll be
carrying a chip on his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Manning, a three-year star in baseball and football at Fresno
Edison, believes he's been denigrated by Fresno State coach Pat
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know coach Hill feels some animosity toward me,'' Manning
said. ``He'll say stuff and downtalk my skills. I don't know if he
doesn't like me or what. I'm ready for this game.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this has left Hill dumbfounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It amazes me that he'd say that,'' said Hill, who says he's
known Manning for five years. ``If that's the way he feels, I feel
bad about that. I've never gotten into a (war of words) about Ricky
Manning. I'm not going to brownnose him, but I think he's a great
player. He's a humble kid. I've got nothing but good things to say
about him as a player and a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning concedes that Hill has never said anything to him
personally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hear things, rumors,'' said Manning, who is close to
about a half-dozen Bulldogs, including former high school teammates
Atnaf Harris, Tierre Sams and Deandre Gilbert. ``He probably says
it to get his players going. I know he wants to beat me. If I make
a play, they're going to come right back at me.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning, one of the best players to come out of Fresno in years,
told Hill early in the recruiting process that he was going to
leave town for college. ``Very rarely will a kid be that honest,''
Hill said. ``We knew we had no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   On signing day, Manning's decision to attend UCLA dominated the
front pages of Fresno-area papers. Hill remarked the next day that
it would be nice if some of the local kids who stayed home were
given more publicity. His comments caused a flap with Manning's
high school coach, Ray Reyes, and Hill called both Manning and
Reyes to apologize for any misunderstanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a lot of pub. They blew me up in high school,'' Manning
said. ``Maybe he didn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Manning made a critical play in UCLA's 35-21
victory over the Bulldogs. With the Bruins leading 17-7, Fresno
State was driving for a touchdown in the final minute of the first
half. But Manning intercepted a pass and returned it 83 yards to
the Fresno State 11-yard line with 12 seconds left in the half.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins kicked a field goal on the final play of the half.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people wanted me to say (bad) things about him last
year, but I never got caught up in that,'' Hill said. ``Why he'd
say that I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Faster feet: On his interception last season, Manning was run
down by Harris, his former high school teammate. In fact, Manning,
a quarterback at Edison, used to throw to Harris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him now I'm not 4.6 (in the 40-yard dash), I'm 4.4,''
Manning said. ``He won't catch me now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
