<SLUG> BC-COACH-LAWSUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JURY SIDES WITH FIRED SOUTHWEST BAPTIST COACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A jury on Wednesday agreed with a former
coach that Southwest Baptist University fired her because she sued
the school, claiming sex discrimination and unequal treatment of
women's teams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a happy day, but also a sad day,'' Anne Julian said after
the jury announced its verdict in U.S. District Court in Kansas
City.
</P>
<P>
   After hugs from her attorney and friends and family, Julian said
she is glad a jury sided with her. But she also has been deeply
wounded during the past two years, she said, because people she
thought respected her now question her integrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. (Pat) Taylor (university president) asked me if I wanted
to hurt SBU. I didn't. I want to help SBU,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Retaliation was the only charge the jury considered, because
Julian's claims of sex discrimination were dismissed by U.S.
District Judge Fernando Gaitan.
</P>
<P>
   Julian graduated from Southwest Baptist, a small school in
Bolivar, Mo., in 1990. She was hired in 1996 to coach volleyball
and softball. In 1997 she filed a complaint with the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission, claiming she was paid less than
male coaches and was given fewer resources than coaches of male
teams.
</P>
<P>
   She coached softball until 1998. In 1998 she also filed suit for
sex discrimination. She was fired in May 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Kirksey, the university's attorney, said he was shocked by
the jurors' decision because they had heard school administrators
say they fired Julian because she mistreated her players by not
feeding them when they lost on road trips. They also said she acted
unprofessionally by discussing her lawsuit with her players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' Kirksey said. ``Would we make the same
decision again (to fire her)? Yes. We chose to fight rather than
lie down. We made the best choice. We stood up for the students.''
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded Julian $1,800 in lost wages for the three
months it took her to find a job after she was fired. The jury also
directed the university to pay her $75,000 for her emotional
anguish.
</P>
<P>
   Julian coaches and teaches at a Kentucky high school.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Kilkenny, a juror from Kansas City, said the testimony
showed the university had ``nitpicked'' at Julian's performance
after she filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   In her first year of coaching, Julian was lauded on campus for
vastly improving the volleyball and softball teams. She received a
job evaluation of ``exceeds some expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   In later seasons, after she complained to the EEOC, the
university questioned her about potential NCAA violations, refusing
to allow athletes to tape their ankles, and making her players go
without food.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe that someone could go from being so good to
so bad in such a short period of time,'' Kilkenny said.
</P>
<P>
   Julian's attorney, Denise Henning, said the lawsuit has prompted
Southwest Baptist to improve conditions in women's athletics. She
hopes the verdict will prompt even more improvements.
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked the jury for fair play, and that's what they gave
us,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
