<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Retrieving the Tradition and Renewing Evangelicalism'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By D.H. Williams &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eerdmans, $16) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, a blurb for a Six Flags roller coaster went something
like this: ``The only way out is backward.'' D.H. Williams'
prescription for what he sees as an amnesiac conservative
Protestantism is strikingly similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tradition is not something evangelicals can take or leave,''
he writes in ``Retrieving the Tradition and Renewing
Evangelicalism.'' ``To make any claim for orthodox Christianity
means that the evangelical faith must go beyond itself to the
formative eras of that faith, apostolic and patristic.''
</P>
<P>
   Them's fightin' words among people to whom terms such as
``tradition'' and ``creed'' are cause for caution, if not flat-out
opposition. But Williams makes a strong case for reconsidering the
repudiation of practically everything that went on between A.D. 100
and 1500, although his book is certainly no valentine to the
Vatican.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retrieving the Tradition'' challenges stereotypes of not just
the post-apostolic church but the Reformation as well. It's a good
starting point for some welcome thinking. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shirley Caesar &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``You Can Make It'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word Entertainment/Epic Records &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now well into her 60s _ although her most recent bio doesn't say
just how well _ and showing no signs of slowing down, Shirley
Caesar rolls on like a force of nature.
</P>
<P>
   If you saw her recent show at Bass Performance Hall in Fort
Worth, you know what I mean: On that night, Caesar hollered and
cooed her ageless gospel and her ageless message of salvation,
giving a bravura performance that a woman half her age might have
envied for its immediacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You Can Make It'' is her 35th CD since going solo in 1967 with
``I'll Go.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, it sounds like it: There are a number of songs that
are cookie-cutter slices of traditional gospel that never go beyond
the average; one of the weakest is ``Lift Him Up,'' which is
basically Caesar and her background singers shouting ``Lift him
up!'' and ``Praise his name!'' over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the time, though, ``You'' is a powerful testament to
Caesar's 50-plus years as a performer. The CD features her working
with a variety of performers and choirs, including gospel superstar
Bobby Jones &AMP; The Nashville Super Choir Cast and the Mount Calvary
Word of Faith Choir. And, of course, horn sections and the organ
are often deployed to deliver extra punch.
</P>
<P>
   Caesar works her magic with all of them, whether she's doing an
up-tempo song such as ``What Joy'' (a duet with Jones) or a ballad
such as the title song. ``You Can Make It'' is classic Caesar: It
starts quietly, with just piano and her voice, and then builds to a
powerful, stately climax with the help of Jones and his crew.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, ``You Can Make It'' is a worthy addition to Caesar's
legacy, if not her best work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Dave Ferman &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
