<SLUG> BC-GAYNEWS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 GAY NEWS COVERAGE NOT GOOD, JOURNALISTS SAY  &HT;     By DAN FOST  
 c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Gay journalists have made great strides over the
years but still have a long way to go, according to a survey by the
University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The survey results were scheduled to be released Thursday at the
National Lesbian and Gay Journalists Association conference in San
Francisco, where an estimated 500 attendees will gather at the
Argent Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the gay and lesbian journalists surveyed find the
mainstream news organizations that they work for don't do a good
job of covering issues of importance to the gay community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Journalism these days is more concerned with high drama,
conflict and entertainment value,'' said Leroy Aarons, the study's
co-author and director of the Program for the Study of Sexual
Orientation Issues in the News at USC's Annenberg School for
Communication. ``We're seeing the hot-button stories get a lot of
attention, perhaps at the expense of ongoing day-to-day local
coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   But Aarons is encouraged that today's debate is about the
quality of coverage. Ten years ago, major news organizations did
not cover gay issues as substantially.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a substantial explosion of news about gay and
lesbian issues,'' said Aarons.
</P>
<P>
   Much of that, Aarons said, is owed to gay journalists feeling
able to advocate for their stories in newsrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heterosexual journalists looked to their right and left, and
people who they respected for years came into focus as gays and
lesbians,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It helped that gay stories became important in everyday American
life, from the AIDS epidemic to civil rights pushes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story is still a major story in our society today, perhaps
even more than before,'' Aarons said. ``You see the way its
injected itself into presidential politics, family issues,
adoption, gay marriage and so on.''
</P>
<P>
   The NLGJA did not release specific numbers in the survey,
holding those until Thursday's news conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
