<HEADLINE>
CAMPO GIVES THUMBS UP TO CUNNINGHAM'S WORKOUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys coach Dave Campo said Wednesday he
couldn't have been more pleased with what he saw from quarterback
Randall Cunningham in practice.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham, who will replace the injured Troy Aikman against the
Arizona Cardinals on Sunday, took all of the repetitions with the
first-team offense. He also showed no ill effects from the sprained
right thumb he suffered against the Philadelphia Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he had a good practice,'' Campo said. ``He was very
upbeat. I felt good about the way he handled himself today. This
guy is excited about jumping out there and playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Campo didn't envision Cunningham playing this soon, he
said the Cowboys signed the two-time MVP quarterback in the
off-season because they wanted someone to win games for them if
Aikman were unable to play.
</P>
<P>
   Campo said the Cowboys have started to add some wrinkles in the
offense to take advantage of Cunningham's scrambling ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we will see what Randall will do under these
circumstances,'' Campo said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys also are preparing for a possible loss of Cunningham
to an injury. Rookie Clint Stoerner took snaps as the backup
quarterback. He will be promoted from the practice squad to the
active roster this week and serve as Cunningham's understudy
against the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Also taking snaps from center Wednesday was running back Emmitt
Smith, who has been tabbed as the team's emergency quarterback in
the event that Cunningham and Stoerner are injured.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who needs 8 rushing yards to reach 14,000 for his career,
could be a couple of ankle sprains away from throwing the first
pass of his NFL career. \Nsubheds:No sympathy from Cardinals The
injuries to receiver Joey Galloway and quarterback Troy Aikman are
making headlines in Dallas. However, the Cowboys won't get any
sympathy from the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona opened the season with nine players on the injured
reserve list, including star receiver Rob Moore and expected
contributors such as defensive tackles Rashod Swinger and Jerry
Drake, and cornerbacks J.J. McCleskey and Coby Rhinehart.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals also are waiting for defensive end Andre Wadsworth
and linebacker Zack Walz to return from off-season knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Things got worse in the season opener against the New York
Giants when starting offensive tackle L.J. Shelton sprained his
left knee. He is out indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the worse things that can happen to a team,''
Cardinals quarterback Jake Plummer said of the injuries. ``We don't
feel much remorse'' for the Cowboys. \Nsubheds:He said it Cowboys
running back Emmitt Smith on the difference between quarterbacks
Randall Cunningham and Troy Aikman: ``Obviously, his skin color . .
. and he's more mobile, too.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly Cowboys cornerback
Dwayne Goodrich returned to practice for the first time since
suffering a strained hamstring Aug. 5.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys cornerback Charlie Williams, out since the beginning of
training camp because of knee surgery and a staph infection,
practiced on a limited basis.
</P>
<P>
   News on whether Erik Williams is fined by the NFL could come
from the league office today. Williams was ejected in the fourth
quarter of Sunday's game after punching an Eagles player.
nn
</P>
