</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-SPACE-SHUTTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAUNCHING OF SHUTTLE WILL BEGIN PUSH TO COMPLETE SPACE OUTPOST 
</HEADLINE>
  By WARREN E. LEARY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The space shuttle Atlantis is set to head for the
International Space Station on Friday, beginning an intense push to
finish the long-delayed orbital research outpost.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlantis and its seven-member crew are to blast off at 8:45
a.m. EDT on Friday, beginning an 11-day mission to outfit the
growing station for the arrival of its first permanent residents in
November. The flight begins a surge of 15 station-related missions
by American and Russian rockets over the coming year that will
greatly increase the station's size and functions.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the National Aeronautics and Space Administration
said Wednesday that no major problems stood in the way of the
Atlantis' launch, although there were some concerns about weather.
U.S. Air Force forecasters said there was a 60 percent chance that
weather would not interfere, but coastal showers and low clouds
around the Kennedy Space Center in Florida could pose problems,
particularly with the mission's unusually small launch window.
</P>
<P>
   Shuttle managers are giving the shuttle only a 2 1/2-minute
period to lift off starting at 8:45 a.m., about half the time
usually allotted for missions to the space station. A 2-to-3-hour
launch window is common to other shuttle missions.
</P>
<P>
   By launching when the shuttle's ground position is aligned
perfectly with the space station's orbit, officials can, they said,
save fuel normally used to steer the rising shuttle at its moving
target. Having more fuel will make it easier for the shuttle to
deal with any unexpected thrust shortfalls in its three main
engines, they say. It also makes it more likely that the spacecraft
could return to an American landing strip if engine problems
develop, instead of going to one of the emergency sites in Spain or
North Africa.
</P>
<P>
   NASA officials say the upcoming flurry of flights, after more
than two years of delays in constructing the station, will be one
of the most intense periods of human space flight ever.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dittemore, NASA's shuttle program manager, said that until
the Russian service module Zvezda docked with the station on July
26, ``we were in a holding pattern.'' Zvezda, containing the living
quarters and control room for the station during its early
construction stages, arrived two years behind schedule because of
Russian financial problems and booster rocket difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``This mission begins a series of station-assembly flights
aboard the shuttle during the next year that will be as complex as
anything NASA has ever done, including landing a man on the moon,''
Dittemore said.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis' mission of hauling equipment and supplies to the
station, and getting the living quarters ready for occupancy by the
first station crew of three, will be followed in October by a
flight by the shuttle Discovery to haul up the first segment of a
scaffolding-like truss on which other segments will be built.
Endeavour is to go up in November with the first segment of
American solar power panels, after the arrival of a Russian Soyuz
ship carrying the first crew.
</P>
<P>
   Eight shuttle flights are scheduled for 2001, starting with
delivery of the American science laboratory Destiny. The last time
NASA flew eight shuttles in one year was 1997, and an all-time
record of nine went up in 1985, the year before the Challenger
explosion, which resulted in cutting back the ambitious shuttle
program.
</P>
<P>
   Because of studies raising safety concerns about launching so
many flights, NASA last year reversed years of workforce reductions
and began hiring hundreds of new people, particularly safety
engineers. And space shuttle contractors have added hundreds more
to help with the accelerated flight rate.
</P>
<P>
   Atlantis' crew of five American and two Russian astronauts will
start this renewed activity by unloading 2 tons of supplies and
equipment it is carrying, and another 1,300 pounds of material from
an unmanned Russian Progress cargo ship which docked with the
station last month. The crew will outfit Zvezda, which was launched
virtually empty of equipment, with food, clothing, exercise
equipment, computers, medical kits, food warmers, gas masks, fire
extinguishers and other necessities. The astronauts also will
install the station's first toilet, a Russian model similar to one
used aboard the Mir space station.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle, commanded by Col. Terrence Wilcutt of the Marines
on his fourth trip into space, and piloted by Cmdr. Scott D. Altman
of the Navy on his second shuttle flight, will dock with the
station on the third day of the mission. The crew will wait almost
two days before entering the station, first conducting a critical
space walk to connect segments of the outpost electronically.
</P>
<P>
   An American astronaut, Edward T. Lu, and a Russian counterpart,
Yuri I. Malenchenko, are to spend 6 1/2 hours scaling the
140-foot-tall station secured to the Atlantis' cargo bay. The
astronauts, climbing 110-feet up the structure, will connect nine
communications and power cables on the most distant spacewalk ever
from a shuttle. Afterward, the crew, including the Americans
Richard A. Mastracchio and Daniel C. Burbank and the Russian Boris
V. Morukov, will enter the station and transfer the supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The shuttle is to return to the Kennedy Space Center on Sept.
19.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
