<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-DEATHS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    Executive apologizes in tire deaths
 &HT;    Senate, House hold hearings
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By JENNIFER HOYT
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The CEO of Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. apologized
Wednesday and accepted blame for his company's role in dozens of
fatal crashes linked to faulty tires.
</P>
<P>
   The apology came during tense Senate and House hearings in which
Firestone, Ford Motor Co. and federal safety regulators were
blasted for not sounding the alarm quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   Citing evidence that the two companies had received complaints
from around the world over the past decade, lawmakers challenged
claims by Firestone and Ford officials that they were unaware that
tires were defective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me alarm bells were ringing, but that the people
in a position to do something weren't listening,'' said Sen.
Richard Shelby, R-Ala.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the National Highway Transportation Safety
Administration began investigating accidents in which Firestone
tires suddenly lost their tread or suffered blowouts.
</P>
<P>
   The problem tires, many of them on Ford's popular Explorer, have
been blamed for 88 deaths and at least 250 injuries in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   At back to back Senate and House hearings Wednesday, Firestone
CEO Masatoshi Ono said he was appearing ``to apologize to you, the
American people and especially to the families who have lost loved
ones in these terrible rollover accidents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ono, who rarely appears in public, told lawmakers he had ``come
to accept full and personal responsibility on behalf of
Bridgestone/Firestone for the events that led to this hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Nasser, president and CEO of Ford, denied his company
was responsible. ``We know this is a Firestone issue, not a Ford
issue,'' he testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``My one main regret is that we did not ask Firestone the right
questions sooner,'' Nasser said. ``We did everything we possibly
could to replace bad tires with good tires as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, The Associated Press cited documents indicating
that Bridgestone/Firestone officials were aware of safety problems
years before its Aug. 9 recall of 6.5 million tires.
</P>
<P>
   The documents also indicate that the ATX II tires included in
the recall account for more than half the injury and property
damage claims Firestone received from 1997 to 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The confidential documents contradict claims by Ford and
Firestone that no analysis was done on the tires until July and
August, according to the AP.
</P>
<P>
   The tires Firestone has recalled are the P235/75R15-size ATX and
ATX II models, as well as similarly sized Wilderness AT tires. Most
of the tires were made at its plant in Decatur, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   The recall by Firestone was issued a year after a similar effort
to replace faulty tires in Saudi Arabia and 16 other countries.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, NHTSA issued a warning about the safety of an
additional 1.4 million tires. Firestone insists there is no reason
to expand the recall to include those tires.
</P>
<P>
   About the same time. Venezuela's consumer protection agency has
recommended that Ford and Firestone be held criminally responsible
for 46 deaths in that country.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen President Joan Claybrook told the Senate
transportation subcommittee that Firestone and Ford had covered up
tire safety problems for almost 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question that the companies knew they had a problem
and they kept it a secret,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Crigger, Bridgestone/Firestone's executive vice president
of business planning, said the company believed tires had failed
because of outside influences such as punctures and not because of
a defect in the tire design.
</P>
<P>
   ``In reviewing the cases, no, there was nothing to indicate
there was a tire defect,'' Crigger said. A pattern did not become
apparent until this, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Under heated questioning from lawmakers, NHTSA Administrator Sue
Bailey said Ford had no obligation to tell her agency about its
effort to replace suspect tires outside the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ford would have been required to notify NHTSA of such an
action if it had occurred in the United States, but our regulations
do not apply to actions taken outside the United States,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   From 1991 to 1999, Firestone produced 47 million of the tires
now under investigation. NHTSA received only 46 complaints about
those tires during that time, Bailey said, explaining it was not a
large enough number to trigger an inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``In view of the large number of tires that had been produced,
the variety of possible causes of tire failure and the fact that
all types of tires can fail in use, the reports that we received
did not indicate a problem that would warrant opening a defect
investigation regarding these tires,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That changed, she said, after KHOU-TV in Houston broadcast a
report about safety problems with Firestone tires.
</P>
<P>
   By Aug. 1, the agency had received 193 complaints, and that
number has since risen to 1,400. On Aug. 4, NHTSA recommended a
recall, which Firestone announced on Aug. 9.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone's Ono said he still does not know what
caused the tire problems but the company is investigating. ``You
have my word that we will continue until we find the cause,'' Ono
said.
</P>
<P>
   xxx END OF STORY xxx
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
