<SLUG> BC-RIVER-DEBATE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE DEBATES BOND'S PLAN TO PROTECT BARGE TRAFFIC ON THE
MISSOURI 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN MURPHY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate on Wednesday night debated whether the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers should be able to change the flow of
the Missouri River to protect three types of endangered birds and
fish.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Kit Bond, a Missouri Republican, is trying to keep the
corps from having that option. Under the proposal, the corps could
release extra water at a South Dakota dam at least once every third
spring to improve wildlife habitat downstream.
</P>
<P>
   Bond said that releasing more water could flood farm fields and
hamper barge traffic in Missouri and other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a risky scheme that we cannot afford to gamble on,'' Bond
said. Missouri saw in 1993 and 1995 the devastating effects floods
can have on farms and cities, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Conservation groups say higher river levels could enhance
habitats for the pallid sturgeon, a bottom-dwelling fish, and two
endangered birds _ the interior least tern and the piping plover.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Fish and Wildlife recommended the higher
levels to improve chances for the species' survival, but Bond said
the Missouri Department of Natural Resources and other groups
disagreed that the plan would help.
</P>
<P>
   Bond wants to withhold funding that would allow the Corps of
Engineers to revise its manual, in effect since 1960, so that river
flow could be altered. A Senate vote is expected today.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, a South Dakota Democrat who is the Senate
minority leader, wants the Bond language removed from the
legislation to finance the corps.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle argued in favor of allowing the flow to be changed,
saying it would give the corps flexibility to adapt to wildlife,
agricultural and recreational needs.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the corps' manual too heavily favors barge operators,
Daschle said. Barges, he said, account for only 0.3 percent of
transportation of farm products.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the tip of the tail wagging the tail and the dog
itself,'' Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Bond replied that barge traffic was important for farmers
because it provided competition for rail shippers and helped keep
prices down.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle also said concern about flooding was unfounded because
extra water would not be released if flooding seemed likely. But
Bond said that in the 11 days it takes for water to get from South
Dakota to St. Louis, heavy rain could fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one mistake is all it takes to introduce a
government-controlled flood,'' Bond said. He said that Missouri
Gov. Mel Carnahan, a Democrat, also opposed letting the corps
release more water upstream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2319EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
