u f BC-EURO-MARKETPLACE-NYT &LR;      09-06 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EURO-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: RISE IN RATES NOT STEMMING EURO'S SLIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Higher interest rates don't seem to be helping.
</P>
<P>
   The euro, born amid optimism some 20 months ago, suffered the
worst day of its young life Wednesday, as it lost 2.3 percent of
its value against the dollar, settling at 87.01 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The European currency also hit a record low against the Japanese
yen as it briefly traded below 92 yen.
</P>
<P>
   It was just over a week ago, on Aug. 31, that the European
Central Bank raised interest rates for the sixth time in a year.
The central bank then expressed concern over the ``protracted
depreciation'' of the euro, which is down 26.5 percent against the
dollar since Jan. 4, 1999, the first business day for the euro _
the currency of 11 European countries.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has long since come to seem quite cheap by many
measures, like purchasing power parity, but that has not helped the
currency to rally. Nor have higher interest rates helped.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that higher interest rates help to bring in money
to an economy, but while that may be true in some circumstances, it
is not helping now.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the story is that the United States has also been
raising interest rates as well, but the other part of the story is
that it is not debt investments that now drive investment flows. It
is the equity investments, both through stock purchases and direct
foreign investments, that have driven the dollar up and the euro
down.
</P>
<P>
   It is in that environment that the dollar has performed well
despite a high and growing current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
   That deficit, largely driven by the trade deficit, must be
financed by foreigners willingly reinvesting the money in
dollar-denominated assets. So far they have been more than willing
to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Given that current reality, the best course if Europe wants to
support its common currency would seem to be to make itself more
attractive for equity investors, and to some extent it has done so.
European growth is at its highest levels in a decade, albeit still
below growth in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am very impressed by European corporate restructuring,''
said Nicholas P. Sargen, global market strategist for J.P. Morgan's
private clients. He compared the restructuring to that embarked
upon by many United States companies in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Germany is overhauling its tax structure in a way
that is widely viewed as attractive to foreign investment and is
likely to be imitated by other European countries.
</P>
<P>
   But none of that has been enough to make European investments
seem more attractive than American ones, and raising interest rates
may hurt if it threatens to slow growth and thereby make equity
investments less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are tightening because your currency is weak, and your
real economy and markets are also weak, it is not going to work,''
Robert Barbera, the chief economist of Hoenig Securities, said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The euro has not been helped by the fact that while it is one
currency, it has 11 governments. There have been efforts to get
those 11 governments to show solidarity in defense of the currency,
but in fact some Europeans like a weak currency. European exports
are booming, in part because of the falling euro, and that eases
pressures for structural reforms to European economies that are
strongly resisted by European unions, among others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The current euro-dollar rate is more of a reason to be happy
than concerned,'' said Gerhard Schroeder, the German chancellor, in
a speech on Monday that helped to provoke the latest decline.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's German economic data showed some of the results of
the weak euro. Unemployment fell to its lowest level in five years,
although it still remains at 9.5 percent of the work force, in part
because of strong factory orders from abroad. ``The export orders
were very strong,'' noted John McCarthy, director of foreign
exchange at ING-Barings Capital Markets.
</P>
<P>
   But McCarthy said there was nonetheless a wave of selling of the
euro from Americans after it became clear that the currency was
moving decisively below 89 cents, the area where it bottomed in May
before rallying back above 96 cents in June. The currency had ended
Tuesday's trading at 89.06 cents.
</P>
<P>
   When the euro was introduced, there were widespread predictions
it would be a strong currency, continuing the historic role of the
German mark.
</P>
<P>
   But the current level of the euro is equivalent to a value of
2.24 marks to the dollar _ the highest level for the dollar since
1986, when the dollar was falling from historically overvalued
levels.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, interest-rate-denominated investments were much
more important in driving currency flows, and U.S. interest rates
had fallen sharply. In addition, the U.S. economy was slowing.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, the euro's weakness may end only when U.S.
investments come to seem less attractive, either because U.S.
markets are falling rapidly or because the U.S. economy appears to
be in danger of a recession. Neither possibility seems very likely
to investors at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
