<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-CAMPAIGN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIEBERMAN VISITS KANSAS CITY, SPRINGFIELD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE and SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A blue-jeaned Joseph Lieberman wandered amid
newly assembled motorcycles Wednesday before rolling out parts of a
Democratic economic plan that he said would keep Americans on the
road to prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   The Connecticut senator's second day of campaigning through
Missouri took him in the early morning to the Harley-Davidson plant
near Kansas City International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this works as we hope and believe it will, maybe someday
the names `Gore' and `Lieberman' will enjoy as much respect as the
names `Harley' and `Davidson,' &UR; '' he told workers.
</P>
<P>
   He later moved on to Springfield and the campus of Southwest
Missouri State University, where he read a speech echoing Vice
President Al Gore's economic address Wednesday in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' plan calls for paying off the national debt by
2012, prohibiting lawmakers from spending Social Security and
Medicare funds on other needs and raising the average family's
income by one-third over the next decade, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman talked of how the proposal includes the creation of
tax-free 501(j) accounts that workers could use to cover the cost
of training and new tax credits for companies that retrain workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as the last eight years have been, if we work
together, the next eight can be even better,'' the
vice-presidential nominee said.
</P>
<P>
   Before his talk, the senator toured the state-of-the-art plant
in faded denims and steel-toed boots. He admired the sleek
motorcycles and sat aboard a 1200 custom Sportster.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a beautiful operation,'' he told about three dozen
workers who assembled to hear the candidate. ``I told my wife this
morning...where I was going,'' he said. ``She got nervous, because
now she figures I'm going to want to buy a bike.''
</P>
<P>
   And something else caught his attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``This group of workers has the strongest handshakes that I've
met in one place in America.''
</P>
<P>
   His appearance drew different responses from workers.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Hines, who works in the paint department and who plans to
vote for Texas Gov. George W. Bush, said Lieberman's comments on
Medicare troubled him. ``He just started throwing numbers out. I
wanted to hear the plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Reiley, a production technician, had a different reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he answered the questions real well,'' said Reiley,
depicting Lieberman as sincere and down to earth. And he
appreciated Lieberman's attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a Harley look to him,'' Reiley said. ``But there wasn't
a lot of leather.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit came one day after a new poll commissioned by The
Kansas City Star showed Gore leading Bush in Missouri by 45 percent
to 41 percent. The GOP nominee had led by 11 points in an early
July survey.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman said he was eager to visit Springfield. ``We're going
to go everywhere in Missouri,'' he said in an interview with The
Star. ``We think we've got a program...that should appeal across
the board.''
</P>
<P>
   Once in the Republican stronghold, Lieberman read his economic
speech to an appreciative but restrained audience of more than 300
people on the Southwest Missouri State campus. There, he pushed the
Democratic ticket's proposal for focused tax cuts for retirement
savings and spending on college and job training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a moment in time to make real what two centuries of
Americans could only dream about: to empower every American, to
lift up every citizen,'' Lieberman said. ``Let our descendants look
back to this time and place and say, `We were up to the
challenge.' &UR; ''
</P>
<P>
   He depicted the 10-point Gore plan as a more fair way of using
the federal budget surplus than that proposed by the GOP ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush looks at the surplus and wants to give most of
it away in one fell swoop,'' Lieberman said, arguing that most of
the Republicans' tax cuts help the rich. ``We shouldn't used our
hard-earned prosperity to give the most to those who need it least,
and the least to those who need it most.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman used about a fourth of his talk to bash Bush's
proposals. He even ad-libbed a line to say that low interest rates
have saved Americans more money on their home and car loans than
they could expect to reap from Bush's tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Clipping through the Democrats' ambitious set of promises, he
pledged significant tax breaks for the middle class for expenses
such as sending a child to college or caring for an elderly parent.
And he continually added assurances:``We can do it...You better
believe we can change the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman did little to tailor his speech to either Springfield
or Missouri, other than to add to his prepared remarks ``at
universities like this'' when referring to education. The roughly
three hours he spent in Springfield after his speech were occupied
not in meeting Missouri voters or even raising money but conducting
satellite interviews with TV networks about the Gore plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mel Carnahan, a candidate for the U.S. Senate, appeared
with Lieberman. Carnahan, adopting much of the tone sounded by
Lieberman, said the deficit reduction under the Clinton
administration may not be the focus of grateful kitchen table
conversation, but it is responsible for America's widespread
prosperity. And he attacked Bush's ideas as ``flawed plans that
give most of the (tax) relief to the elites.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's speech of about 40 minutes, he later told local
party officials, was by far his longest of the campaign. And
although he drew occasional applause, it was clear he was reading
nearly every word and his audience responded in similarly
restrained fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the most exciting speech I've seen in my life,''
said Andrea Margel, a Southwest Missouri State student from St.
Charles, Mo. ``But it sounded like he was trying to be responsible
with the money.''
</P>
</TEXT>
