<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-09-06 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4723 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-STORM-SURVIVORS-HNS &LR;      09-06 1123
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STORM-SURVIVORS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    EDS: Macdonald is CQ
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    `ALL HELL BROKE LOOSE'
 &HT;    104-year-old tells how she survived 1900 hurricane
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By KEVIN MORAN
 &HT;    c. 2000 Houston Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lorraine Hofeller was only 4 years old when she lived through
the Great Storm that devastated Galveston in 1900.
</P>
<P>
   Now 104, she still fears hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been scared all my life'' of threatening weather, she
confided Wednesday from the southwest Houston retirement center
where she recently moved.
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 8, 1900, she and her family _ parents Ben and Belle
Isaacs and brother Mortimer, 10 _ lived in a frame house at 2012
Broadway in Galveston.
</P>
<P>
   The house, built with its first floor about 10 feet above
ground, stood in the highest part of the city, about 8 feet above
sea level.
</P>
<P>
   On the morning of the storm, she and her mother visited a
neighbor a block over.
</P>
<P>
   When rains started about noon, Hofeller recalls, her mother
decided it was best to head home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't even take an umbrella,'' she said. ``Instead of
going around the block, we went the back way through the alley.
When we got home, it really started to rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, a grocery broker, came home for lunch, and her
brother brought in the family pet, a fox terrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought the dog in, and then all hell broke loose,'' she
said Wednesday, recalling that the family sat in the dining room in
the middle of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat on my mother's lap all night, it seems to me,'' she
said. ``My mother was so scared, and my father was scared, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The house withstood the storm.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the family discovered the second-floor ceilings
were sagging from water that had leaked through where shingles were
blown from the roof.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father took his walking cane and punched a hole through it,
and all the water came down, and it scared me to death,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   After the storm, the little girl, her mother and her brother
took a wagon to Dickinson and then caught a train to Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But soon they returned and were part of the effort to rebuild
Galveston, which had suffered more than 6,000 deaths and saw nearly
4,000 homes destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1913 she graduated from Ball High School, after beating four
boys to be elected senior class president. She notes that was in
the days when women didn't have the right to vote.
</P>
<P>
   She married Sigmar Hofeller in 1919, and in 1934 they moved to
Houston, where he sold insurance. They reared two daughters, Elaine
Kuper, now 77, and Marion Levi, 75, both Houston residents.
</P>
<P>
   Sigmar died in the mid-1960s, after 45 years of marriage. The
family now includes four grandchildren and six great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, as Hofeller told her story, Kuper and a
granddaughter, Houston school trustee Laurie Bricker, 51, were
there to hear it.
</P>
<P>
   The Great Storm lore of many families is preserved in written or
oral accounts collected from survivors who have since died.
</P>
<P>
   Houstonian Margaret Ray tells one such story. Because her
grandmother fainted in front of just the right house, Ray's mother
survived the storm.
</P>
<P>
   As a child in the 1920s, Ray, now 80, heard the tale many times
from her mother, Grace Fine Stenzel, who was 11 when the storm
struck.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Stenzel died in 1979, but Ray put the story of Alice
Atkins Fine's fortuitous faint in writing.
</P>
<P>
   Alice Fine, who had been ill, was alone with her children,
Grace, Enos, Edith and Mary, when they discovered water in their
front yard on the morning of the storm. Fine's husband, Joseph, was
out of town.
</P>
<P>
   Records show that the family lived at 722 Church Street.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's grandmother decided to move her children to higher ground
_ a good thing because the area where they lived was wiped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were walking through the water when, all of a sudden, my
grandmother fainted,'' Ray said. ``Fortunately, they happened to be
in front of a two-story house where a man was looking out of a
window at the storm and saw her faint. He rushed out and brought
the whole family into his house.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was so strong that it had blown part of their clothes
right off their backs,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   As the storm tore the city apart, water drove everyone to the
second level, but the house and those inside survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother said she never knew the name of the man who took them
in,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's family lore isn't all so pleasant. ``When the tin roofs
flew through the air, Mother said, they sometimes beheaded horses
that were struggling in the water,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   Her grandmother also told of looters who went to work
immediately after the storm, taking jewelry from bodies, even
cutting off fingers to get rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mother said the authorities announced that if anyone were
caught looting, they would be made to dig their own grave and would
be shot on the spot,'' Ray said.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly wiping out Galveston, the storm swept toward
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   In League City, Alison Adams, his wife, Nora, and their five
children lived in the caretaker's cottage at a cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Leatie Adams, born Aug. 28, 1900, was too young to remember the
storm. But she left a letter before she died, relating what her
parents and oldest brother, Grover, told her.
</P>
<P>
   Her family was huddled on a feather bed and her father held a
kerosene lamp when the roof blew off.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mattress went sailing out and landed on a small peach tree
on the bank of Clear Creek, which was by now a raging torrent,''
Leatie Adams wrote. ``We were all still on the mattress, and Papa
still had the lamp in his hand.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleo Robinson, 79, Grover's daughter and a retired Houston
schoolteacher, said: ``Dad always remembered that his daddy tied
his wife and the five children to trees with bedsheets, and that is
the way they survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was so remarkable that five children, including
the baby, were all saved,'' said Robinson, who lives in Hillcrest
Village near Alvin.
</P>
<P>
   Some survivors' tales include humor.
</P>
<P>
   Galvestonian Linda Macdonald's grandfather, Clarence LaCoume,
was 6 when the storm struck. Until his death at 88, LaCoume told
her the family's survival tale, describing winds ``like a thousand
demons screaming in the night.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, she smiles when she recalls another of his memories. Of
French descent, his father operated a Galveston bakery.
</P>
<P>
   Venturing outside the morning after the storm, family members
found a barrel of unspoiled wine in the bakery doorway.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather told me,'' Macdonald said, ``that his father
turned to him and said: `See, son? Don't ever forget that, even in
times like these, the good Lord remembers the needs of a
Frenchman.'''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
