<SLUG> BC-PROPRANE-PRICES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONFERENCE TO ADDRESS CONCERNS ABOUT PRICE AND DELIVERY OF
PROPANE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The fifth annual Rural Energy Conference is
set to open Sunday in Kansas City amid concerns about the price and
delivery of propane, the heating fuel for much of small-town and
rural America.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, which will continue through Tuesday, comes as
wholesale propane prices have risen about 60 percent from a year
ago. Consumers could spend $200 to $300 more to heat their homes
with propane this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Propane customers have been waiting for a break in prices this
summer but, unlike past summers, it hasn't happened. Now the
industry worries that consumers will continue to delay filling
their tanks until the last minute. That could swamp the fleets of
trucks owned by propane companies to deliver the propane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing some real concerns out there,'' said Pat Westhoff,
program director of the Food and Agriculture Policy Research
Institute at the University of Missouri-Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Propane prices already have begun to affect farmers who use
propane to dry grain. Some crops are being left longer in the field
in the hope they will become drier naturally, Westhoff said.
</P>
<P>
   Most experts say there are sufficient supplies of propane for
the coming winter. Instead, questions are being raised about the
distribution network that gets the fuel to the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is getting it out to the marketplace,'' said Bard
Black, a consultant at Propane Resources, an energy consulting
company in Mission that is sponsoring the energy conference.
</P>
<P>
   The concerns may not become reality, but propane companies and
their trade associations are urging consumers to fill their propane
tanks as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   The next few weeks are considered crucial. ``We need to be
moving on this now,'' said Daniel Myers, executive vice president
of the National Propane Gas Association.
</P>
<P>
   The association is telling consumers they shouldn't delay the
purchase because of a possible decline in propane prices. While
predictions about future prices are difficult to make, the
association says any price relief is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Ferrellgas LP in Liberty, the largest propane retailer in the
United States, is taking a proactive approach before any problems
develop, said Pam Blase, a company spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   She said customers were being urged to talk to their propane
representative about filling their tanks. One program available to
help budget the cost is a level-payment plan.
</P>
<P>
   Propane is a byproduct of crude oil and natural gas, which have
risen in price. Natural gas, a popular heating fuel in the Midwest,
is also expected to cost consumers an extra $200 to $300 to heat
their homes this winter.
</P>
<P>
   But propane customers are among the first to get sticker shock.
</P>
<P>
   Propane customers have to buy the fuel and store it for future
use. A typical storage tank for residential use holds 250 gallons
of propane that at today's retail prices can cost up to $300 and
more to fill. Over the winter, the tank may need to be refilled
three times.
</P>
<P>
   The Rural Energy Conference, which will be held at the Hyatt
Regency Crown Center hotel, expects to attract 250 persons. Besides
general sessions about rural energy, there will be workshops on
several issues, including propane prices and the infrastructure to
deliver the fuel. For more information, go to www.ruralenergy.com
or call (913) 262-1545.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-06-00 2328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000906.0450 </DOCNO>
